INSERT INTO `pef_docs` (`id`, `name`, `pef_docs_id`, `order_no`, `auto_expand_children`, `process_content`, `body`, `icon`, `hidden`, `docs_set`, `docs_subset`, `notes`, `dibuid`) VALUES
    (1, 'dibForm', 4, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The primary dropin used for stored data-entry. Components such as \'textfield\' and \'checkbox\' can be added to the form and linked to the fields of the container\'s table. Use the Field List in the Designer to drag-and-drop fields to the Item Tree which will auotmatically link the items to their table fields.</p><p>Forms can be child-containers on other containers, eg other dibForm or dibContainer containers. Use ~navdocs(Filters)~ to establish links between data to show only related records. The navigation buttons on the child form will automatically inherrit the filter set on the container component containing it; ie the navigation buttons will cycle only through the filtered records. See &#34;Parent\'s Users&#34; (containerParentsUsers) on test_company_form as an example. Filters can be changed programmatically using the ItemHandler.</p><p>The dibForm dropin makes use of the following fields in the pef_container table (Pg1, Pg2 and Pg3 in the Designer):</p><p>~docstable(pef_container,$name$caption$pef_display_dropin_id$window_state$window_mode$model$table$crud_store_controller$extra_table_join$invert_item_perm$order_by$configs$auto_refresh$min_button$max_button$close_button$)~</p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, '', 'doc1-dib'),
    (2, 'dibGrid', 4, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The dibGrid dropin is used to display and filter data in rows and columns. The container\'s model field is used to specify the type of data-source.Â </p><p><b>Note, Â </b>more documentation available under the models provided: <b>~navdocs(dibGrid - Table, Table)~</b> and <b>~navdocs(dibGrid - Sql, Sql)~</b>Â (a Pivot Table model is being developed).</p><p>See the grids on ~nav(dibexContainerDropins, Container Dropin Examples)~ as practical examples.</p><h3>Features</h3><p>showSearch=true in pef_container_settings will keep the search open permanently.</p><p><span id="selectionBoundary_1513929153687_4334641248781437" class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span>gridMultiselect=false (also set the pef_dropin_id to dibGrid\'s dropin id) in pef_container_settings will allow only the last clicked row to be selected by the user.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc2-dib'),
    (3, 'Dropins', 28, 90, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc3-dib'),
    (4, 'Container Dropins', 42, 10, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc4-dib'),
    (5, 'Module Dropins', 42, 20, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc5-dib'),
    (6, 'dibEmail', 5, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><b>(NOTE:: Note, the user-interface is not available for Angular yet ... )</b></p><p>The <strong>dibMail</strong> dropin adds email client like functionality to Dropinbase and also allows for more powerfull capabilities.</p><p><strong>dibMail</strong>Â is primarily split into two halves, Send and Fetch, encapsulated by the DSendMail and DFetchMail classes respectivley.(found under dropins/dibmail/components/)</p><ul><li>dib_email_account Â  Â  Â -contains information and settins for each email account</li><li>dib_email_action Â  Â  Â  Â  -used to set actions or scripts to run at various stages of the fetching or sending emails</li><li>dib_email_attach Â  Â  Â  Â  -links attachments, that are stored locally on the server, to the emails they are attached to</li><li>dib_email_in Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â -is populated with all the emails retrieved from email accounts</li><li>dib_email_individual Â Â </li><li>dib_email_out Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â -is populated with all the messages and drafts that have or will be sent from the dibMail dropin</li></ul><p><strong>Fetching Mail</strong></p><p>In order to fetch mail, there needs to be at least 1 email account record in the dib_email_account that has a receive_method set</p><p>Some email providers like gmail require the recieve method(imap or pop) to be activated and may require additional unblocking</p><p>Please check with your email provider for the correct account settings to use.</p><p>Fetching mail can be done in one of two ways, through the <em>fetch</em> function in <strong>TasksController</strong>(to be linked up to a button in dropinbase, or directly with the <em>fetchPop3</em> in <strong>DFetchMail</strong>.</p><p>To use the <em>fetch</em> function, one should place a setting on the correlating button with the name &#34;Fetch Mail Criteria&#34;, the value of which should be the where clause equivalent to a sql statement(used to filter for specific email accounts). If this setting is not added to the button, <em>fetch</em>Â will retrieve email from every account, with a recieve method listed, in dib_email_account. For example &#34;from_address=\'johndoe@neverdie.ever\'&#34;</p><p>If one desires direct usage of <em>fetchPop3,</em>Â then one would pass it the where clause equvalent, as mentioned above.</p><p>Either of these functions(<em>fetch</em>Â being a \'wrapper\' for the <em>fetchPop3</em>Â function) will then populate the dib_email_in and dib_email_attach tables upon each email sucessfully retrieved from the email server. All attachments are downloaded to the /projectFolder/files/tmp/ Â directory (this excludes attachments included via url).</p><p>Using dibMail\'s <em>dib_emil_in_grid</em> container is reccomended as it provides a simple graphical manner with which the user can interact with. this container can be customised, or one can design ones own solution.</p><p>To get a more in-depth look at code functionality, please view the <strong>DFetchMail</strong>Â subtopic.</p><p>Â </p><p><strong>Sending Mail</strong></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc6-dib'),
    (9, 'Introduction', NULL, 15, 1, 'eleutheria', '', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc9-dib'),
    (10, 'Build My Apps', NULL, 40, 1, 'eleutheria', '<p>This tutorial will step you through creating applications based on relational databases, and then subsequently re-building the entire application or applying changes to your applications based on changes in the underlying database. Note, for more info about what happens under the hood, see ~navdocs(Technical Look at Creating Applications)~.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc10-dib'),
    (11, 'Dropinbase Features', 9, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><strong>General</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Instant cutting-edge applications - Given an existing backend database, generate a fully functional, modern, customized application in less than 5 minutes. Generation is based on an analysis of relationships, indexes, fields and data in relational databases.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Highly customizable - You can build nearly &ldquo;anything&rdquo;.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Easy to use - Changing applications is quick and easy using drag-and-drop. The system regenerates any associated code.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Robust - Generated code is production ready.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Facilitates programmers - The system is designed to assist developers who need to customize applications to very specific requirements. New programmers can be productive within a day.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Flexible and Extendable - Reusable server- and client-side components and modules can be added. *** We aim to implement an online store with free and paid components and modules, which developers can contribute to.&nbsp;</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Import data - Import tables and data from databases, as well as .csv/.txt/fixed length text/.xlsx/.xls files (version 3.1). Automatically build new containers (pages) in the process.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Mashups - Integrate more than one database in a single application &ndash; using the same permission system. Tables can be on physically separate servers facilitating scaling of systems.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Database independent - The system is compatible with multiple database engines. More will be added on an ongoing basis</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Advanced user interface features implementing Angular Material - a modern and thoroughly researched look-and-feel. See below for more detail.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Browser independent - User-interfaces are fully compatible with modern browsers, tablets and smart phones.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>More Features</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Add and configure databases, tables, fields, grids, forms, reports, exports, menus, server- and client-side events, filters, permissions, etc. with powerful design tools.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Filtered data views - Create dependent relationships between data views using filters (eg master-child forms).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Audit trails - Optional Audit trails track Views, Updates, Deletes and Inserts of all users.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Flexible multi-factor authentication.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Sending &amp; receiving emails &amp; SMS.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Export to .pdf, .xlsx, .xls, .csv.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Customize application themes.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Embed other websites inside the system. Embed the system, or any part of it, in another website.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Flexible permissions and business rules - Permissions for viewing, creating, updating and deleting can be set for tables, records (using criteria) and fields (also using criteria). &nbsp;<br>Permissions can also be set on forms, menus, popup tips and events. Permissions are based on user groups, where a user can belong to many groups and a group can have many users. <br>Eg only users of group A can see records of table B where criteria C applies and not update field D or E in this table if criteria F applies for old values and G for new values using page H, and delete a record from this table only if criteria I applies etc.).</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Validation rules &ndash; data can be restricted according to type and size.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Dashboards &ndash; using icons, queries, charts, etc.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Integrated navigation &ndash; the system automatically configures links between related entities.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Grid filters &ndash; Users can filter and sort table and report data using flexible criteria.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Data capturing &ndash; Inline editing in grids, functions to duplicate and find-and-replace data.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Tools &ndash; Various tools for developers, crafted to maximize productivity when building applications</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Variable data sources - Fields and grids can be based on SQL statements, constants and coded functions.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Email - Send info &amp; reports via email from the system.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Automated Unit Testing - record all API calls with their correct responses, and run these tests after any changes that are made.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Charts, maps etc from open-source and paid third party vendors.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Calendars &ndash; Weekly &amp; monthly calendar views of data.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Tablets &amp; Mobiles - Responsive layouts.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Of Interest to Developers</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Re-usable modules &amp; UI components.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Container (page), Item, and table events. Server- and client-side.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>A layered design and separation between databases, api and user-interface allows us to swap out technology and keep in step with the future at each level.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Override system code &ndash; Override core PHP modules(dropins) with your own custom code.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Requires &gt;= PHP 5.4, and &gt;= Apache 2.4, or Nginx.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>We strive to stay with the latest version of Angular - normally updated every 6 months. This is a huge advantage for developers since we go through the tedious process of ensuring everything works exactly the same after any upgrade.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Database engine independent. Currently supports MySQL/MariaDb/AuroraDb as primary Dropinbase database. In addition, PostgreSQL, SQL Server and Sqlite may be used for secondary (client) databases. Nothing stops developers from creating a dropin for other database engines. Integration with other useful data systems eg NoSQL and LDAP is planned.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc11-dib'),
    (16, 'Technology and Requirements', 105, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>A working Dropinbase installation requires the following to be in place:</p>\n<h3>Dropinbase Setup</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Dropinbase database</strong>: hosts the app design in a MySQL-compatible database engine, eg MySQL / MariaDb / Aurora / etc.&nbsp;<br>It stores the design of the application. Use a copy of it for each application (preferred), or use one copy for multiple applications.</li>\n<li><strong>Secondary databases</strong>: hosts user data. Strictly optional since Dropinbase will work without.<br>Can be in SQLite / PostgreSQL / SQL Server / MySQL compatible.</li>\n<li><strong><strong>Dropinbase PHP Client</strong><span style="font-weight: 400;">: application-specific settings in PHP files, styling files, and your own custom code. <br>The Dropinbase PHP Client interfaces with (consumes) the Dropinbase Core Framework.</span></strong><strong><br style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Obtain from&nbsp;</span><a style="font-weight: 400;" href="https://github.com/Dropinbase/dibclient" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://github.com/Dropinbase/dibclient</a><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span><br style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Location: /www/myProjectFolder.<br></span></strong>This is also where developers add their own code, and have the ability to overide /dropins in the Core Framework.<br>Note, the /index.php file contains a <code>require</code>&nbsp;statement that loads the Dropinbase Core Framework. Ensure the path is specified correctly.</li>\n<li><strong>Composer and Third Party Extensions</strong>: Dropinbase uses&nbsp;<a href="https://getcomposer.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Composer</a> for certain features, and also for installing and updating the Dropinbase Core Framework (see below).<br>It is not required to use Composer - you can manually check the Framework out with GIT, or install the files. <br>The third party extensions are not required either, but some features like sending emails and creating PDF\'s won\'t work without them (Excel exports and imports are provided by DIB).</li>\n<li><strong>Dropinbase Core Framework</strong>: the core framework<br>Install with <strong>Composer </strong>or obtain from <a href="https://github.com/Dropinbase/framework" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://github.com/Dropinbase/framework</a>.<br>Location: /www/myProjectFolder/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase.</li>\n<li><strong>Configuraton File Settings</strong>: (this is part of Dropinbase PHP Client files) various settings that tie everything together. Especially the following:<br>Database connection strings are stored in <strong>/projectFolder/configs/Conn.php</strong>.<br>The index values in <strong>Conn.php</strong> must match the <em>id</em> values of records in the <em>pef_database </em>table.<br>Also set the index values for $DBINDEX, $LOGINDB etc in the <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> file (note, this is a template file used to create the&nbsp;<strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> file which is actually used).<br>Hard-coded and generated file-paths in the <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> file must be correct.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Server Requirements</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>PHP 5.4 and above.&nbsp;See ~navdocs(PHP Settings)~.</li>\n<li>Nginx, or Apache 2.4 and above.&nbsp;See ~navdocs(Apache Settings)~</li>\n<li>Node.js &amp; NPM - necessary on development machines only.\n<ul>\n<li>Node.js will install npm which will be used to install Angular during installation of Dropinbase.</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Install Angular)~ - see the "<strong>Install Node.js &amp; NPM and optionally NVM</strong>" section.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>4Gb server space (excl database storage &amp; user files).</li>\n<li>Database system (various):\n<ul>\n<li>Dropinbase database: MySQL compatible, eg. MySQL/MariaDb/AuroraDb/SkySQL.</li>\n<li>User database(s):&nbsp; MySQL compatible/PostgreSQL/SQL Server/Sqlite.\n<ul>\n<li>Creation of a module to support any other RDBMS is about 2 days work.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>File System Permissions</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>See ~navdocs(File System Settings)~</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Client Browsers</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>JavaScript &amp; HTML 5 compatible</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Skill Requirements</h3>\n<p>Administering many of the key features of Dropinbase do not require a technically skilled person.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Armed with a valid database connection, an administrator can easily import tables and create containers, and then customize layout, modify menus, activate dropins, set permissions and create business rules, create buttons to export xlsx/csv files, etc.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Knowledge of SQL will greatly assist to customize dropdowns and build reports, although AI chatbots will increasingly assist.</p>\n<p>A developer is needed to create events that perform custom actions. We can help.</p>\n<p>If you lack the skill to build a relational SQL database for your application, here are some options:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Learn the skill:\n<ol>\n<li><a href="https://www.tutorialspoint.com/sql/index.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Tutorialspoint\'s SQL Tutorial</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://lagunita.stanford.edu/courses/DB/2014/SelfPaced/about" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Stanford University\'s Introduction to Databases</a></li>\n</ol>\nDownload a copy of eg. <a href="https://www.heidisql.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HeidiSQL</a>&nbsp;or <a href="https://dbeaver.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DBeaver</a> or the like, and dive in.&nbsp;<br>Once you have a database most of the other requirements can be met with Dropinbase.&nbsp;<br>Note, if you are building a large or critical system, it is best to involve expert system architects.</li>\n<li>If it is not your "thing", you are facing constraints, or you need a professionally designed system, contact us (details on the website) or an experienced database designer.&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc16-dib'),
    (19, 'Basic Building Blocks', 324, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>A Dropinbase application consists of various types of <b>containers </b>(or pages) that are&#160;loaded into one another.&#160;</p><p><span class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;There is always a <b>base containe</b>r&#160;</span>which is loaded first. The base container typically contains <b>items </b>like a logo, a menu, and a set of tabs which will be used to &#34;host&#34; the other containers.</p><p></p><p>The other containers may be for eg. grids and forms used to capture and display data. A form may have items like <b>fieldsets </b>used to group field items together and buttons to save and delete records.</p><p>Containers are loaded and attached to specific places in other containers as a <b>child container</b>, or via <b>port records</b>. Without going into too much detail now, the main difference is whether a container is loaded together with the container hosting them (as a child <span class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span>container), or as a result of an event, eg the click of a menu button (which triggers a port record).&#160;</p><p>Linked to containers and items are other entities such as events which may call custom server-side PHP code, or client-side JavaScript.</p><p></p><p>There is also an extensive <b>permission </b>system linked to containers, items and events which can be used to conditionally control what <b>users&#160;</b>can see and do.</p><p></p><p></p><p>Dropinbase is designed to be compatible with various types of user-interface libraries. Previously&#160;<a href="http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/4.2.2/">ExtJs&#160;4.2</a>&#160;from Sencha was implemented, but this was now replaced by the latest version of Google\'s&#160;<a href="https://angular.io/">Angular</a>&#160;with <a href="https://material.angular.io/" target="">Angular Material</a>. Both provide modern, rich and flexible client-side API\'s. Note, ExtJs and Angular implement <b>One Page Applications</b>. The code that defines individual pages is loaded once when first requested and not again until the browser window is refreshed. Pages (containers) can be hidden temporarily, but when requested again they are simply made visible from memory. For deployment purposes, the design of all containers can be bundled together in one file and compressed, which dramatically increases load time and performance.</p><h4>Example from Angular</h4><p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/portsNg.jpg"></p><h4>Example from ExtJs</h4><p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/ports.jpg"></p><h2>Code Generation and Dropinbase Tables</h2><p><span>On importing the tables of a database, Dropinbase stores meta-data defining the complete structure of the tables and their relationships. It optionally then creates records defining grid-containers, form-containers, menu items and permission records etc by populating configuration&#160;tables. Administrators customize applications by creating and making changes to the records that stores this metadata. The following screenshots illustrate the basic building blocks. They are described in more detail below.&#160;</span><br></p><h2>Containers, Items, Components &amp; Dropins</h2><p>A container\'s type (eg grid or form) is determined by its display dropin. A display dropin is basically a folder in the application with templates and code that defines the layout of items on a container, and the container\'s client-side behaviour. When a container\'s code is generated, the database entries related to that container is merged with the templates and the result is stored in a /cache folder.<br><br></p><p>As mentioned above, there are various types of containers, eg grids, forms, charts, and trees. The best introduction to them is working through&#160;~nav(dibexContainerDropins, Container Dropin Examples)~. The main properties of a container is specified in the&#160;~navdocs(Tables Reference,Containers table,pef_container)~ (pef_container), visible under the Configuration tab of the ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~. Containers can source data from either tables or SQL statements, depending on the type of dropin (eg dibForm, dibGrid, dibTree, etc) and model (eg Table, Sql, None, etc) used (<i>pef_dropin_id </i>and <i>model </i>are fields in pef_container).</p><p>A container&#160;normally has&#160;items, stored in the related ~navdocs(Tables Reference, Items table, pef_item)~ (<i>pef_item</i>), and visible under the Layout -&gt; Selected Item Details-tab of the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~. Eg a grid has columns and filter-buttons, and a form has fields and tabpanels with tabs.&#160;Each item is of a certain&#160;component&#160;type, eg a date field will use the <i>datefield</i> (ExtJs) or <i>inputDate</i> (Angular Material) components on a form. Note, Angular Material uses the same component type on both grids and forms, while ExtJs has specific component types for each, eg <i>datefield</i>&#160;for forms and <i>griddate</i>&#160;for grids.&#160;</p><p>Each component stored in the <i>pef_component</i> table is linked to a template file via the <i>name</i> and <i>pef_component_dropin_id</i> fields. The file contains the code that defines the component\'s behavior (eg the xtype in ExtJs, or component in Angular). Components can therefore be easily added or modified.&#160;</p><p>A container can also host other containers using the subcontainer-component and <i>pef_item</i>.<em>pef_child_container_id&#160;</em>field. The data displayed in child containers (eg a child-grid) can be linked to items on their parent (or other) containers via filters to facilitate a typical master-child scenario. A particular form\'s related child containers (if any) can be added by using drag-and-drop from the \'Containers/*Related Containers\' section on the Component tree in&#160;the ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~. Other containers, based on tables or queries, can be added using drag-and-drop on the Overview tab.</p><p>A container\'s type is determined by its <em>pef_display_dropin_id </em>field which links to the ~nav(dibDropinGrid,pef_dropin table)~. This table stores a list of downloadables eg container types, modules, modifiers, and special components. Examples of container dropins are&#160;dibForm, dibGrid, dibGoogleMaps, dibHighChart and dibHTMLTemplate. Container dropins have code templates for the containers\' models, views, controllers and stores. Developers can add dropins, or copy and modify the existing ones. ~nav(dibDropinGrid?filter_dropin_type=container,Click here)~&#160;to view a filtered list.&#160;</p><h2>Base Containers</h2><p>Base containers are the first containers that are loaded, and normally contain menus, logos and a place where other containers can be attached. <span>Each base container provides a different basic structure and layout for your application, which therefore implies one of the first choices the designer of a Dropinbase application needs to make.&#160;</span>Any container within Dropinbase can be a &#34;base container&#34; by creating a related record in the <i>pef_port</i> table where the <em>pef_item_id</em> field is left blank (see the next section below). Dropinbase ships with useful base containers that can be duplicated and used (tmplBase1, tmplBase2).&#160;Alternatively, create your own.</p><h2>Page Panels, Port Items &amp; Ports</h2><p><span>Port records enable containers to belong to more than one base container, or to be loaded in different places in the same base container, or to be their own base container.</span><br><br>The following explanation uses the ExtJs screenshot above. Base containers typically contain layout components such a <i>tabpanel</i> or <i>div</i> which will host the other containers that are loaded. These components are referred to in Dropinbase as&#160;<em>port items&#160;</em>and are in fact any component that can contain other panels. The default ExtJs base container for Dropinbase is named dibBase1. It has a tabpanel named pagePanelMain which contains other tabpanels used as port items to host the loaded containers. Note pagePanelMain could itself be a port item to host eg. a grid container, but since for each table (eg the Test Company table) we want to display both a grid and a form container we introduce another layer named a page panel to host the Grid and Form.</p><p>When you view the structure of a base container (eg dibBase1), you will notice the page panels contain items (eg pgExamplesExtJs), but their&#160;<em>display_on_load (Loaded)&#160;</em>field is not checked. These are the actual <em>port items</em>, that will host the containers (the forms and grids). If <em>display_on_load</em>&#160;= 0, the item&#160;will only be loaded once a container or other item that requires them is loaded. Note, since port items are often used as tabs in tabpanels, a useful property of these items is their&#160;<em>caption&#160;</em>field.</p><p>Ports are stored in the <i>pef_port</i> table and&#160;link containers to port items. Containers can have multiple port records with different port items. To load a container in a different place, simply change its port item or create a new port record with a different port item value. If a container\'s port &#160;record does not have a port item it is treated as a base container and will load directly into the browser tab/window.&#160;</p><p>Port records have a <em>port_alias </em>field which identifies which port record to use when a container is opened.&#160;Each port has a url, eg /nav/dibDesigner&#160;(note, container names are unique). By default, the URL opens the container port where the <em>port_alias </em>field is empty. If a second port record is created for a particular container its&#160;<em>port_alias</em> field must have a (unique) value to distinguish it from the first. The URL format used is then &#160;/nav/container_name/port_alias, eg /nav/dibDesigner/admin.</p><h2>Permissions &amp;&#160;Code Generation</h2><p>The records in <i>pef_login</i> define the users of the system. Usernames and passwords can be set on ~nav(dibLoginGrid)~ (use the edit icon). When a user logs in, the default URL is read from his login record and then opened.</p><p>Login records are linked to Permission Group records, which in turn are linked to other permission tables in order to define permissions for Permission Groups on containers, items, container events, item events and tooltips. The link between a login record and permission group, as well as each permission group, has a start date and expiry date. Dropinbase &#34;compiles&#34; the information in the permission tables and stores the output in special temporary permission tables which is used to create the <em>permfiles</em> (see below).&#160;</p><p>A special user is the <em>system_public </em>user. If a user is not logged into the system then Dropinbase automatically logs them in as the system_public user. The system_public user can be assigned any (or no) rights, allowing public access to containers. See ~nav(pef_perm_group)~&#160;(use the edit icon).&#160;</p><p>The combination of Permission Groups that a login is actively linked to defines a <em>permgroup.</em>&#160;Eg if a login record is linked to permission groups 1, 3 and 7 their permgroup will be x1x3x7x. ~navdocs(Permgroups,permgroup)~&#160;are used throughout the application to manage permissions.</p><p>Whenever a user of a particular permgroup issues any request (other than a file request eg. /files/xxx), the system checks the specific permgroup\'s&#160;permissions stored within permission files named <em>permfiles&#160;</em>in /projectFolder/runtime/permFiles. If these files do not yet exist, they are created. The files contain code that stores lists of containers, data-lists and events the permgroup has access to. The same applies when a container is opened - specific design and data-access (CRUD) code is generated for the permgroup&#160;for that container, should the files not already exist. Any files that are associated with permgroups will contain the name of the permgroup in the file name.</p><p>This system of generating highly customized code based on each permgroup\'s&#160;specific configurations&#160;greatly increases security, and the response time of the server. The flip side is that these files need to be deleted whenever design or permission changes are made (ie data in Dropinbase\' configuration tables change). The system automatically attempts to manage that, but in some cases they need to be manually deleted, which is easily accomplished using the top-right most icon on the Designer. Fortunately the system auto-generates required files very quickly, and not all of them need to be deleted. For more information see ~navdocs(Permgroups)~ and&#160;~navdocs(Auto-generated Files)~.</p><p>&#160;</p><p>&#160;</p><p>&#160;</p><p>&#160;</p><p>&#160;</p><p>&#160;</p>', '', 0, 'dib', NULL, '', 'doc19-dib'),
