    (23, 'Permissions and Business Rules', 28, 110, 1, 'eleutheria', '', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc23-dib'),
    (24, 'Event Permissions', 23, 60, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Permission groups can be blocked from executing Item and/or Container Events by setting the appropiate permissions.<br>(These permissions are stored in the <em>pef_perm_item_event </em>and <em>pef_perm_container_event </em>tables).</p>\n<p>By default a permission group has access to all events on a container, except if the <em>Container Events</em> or <em>Item Events</em> ticks under Container Permissions is not set. These are "global" permissions per container that can revoke access to all Container/Item Events for a permission group on a specific container.</p>\n<p>Use the "+p" button next to each Container/Item Event in the Designer to add a permission record for that event. Add records for all the Events that must NOT be blocked. Those that do not have permission records will be blocked.</p>\n<p>In other words if at least one event has a record, then all events that do not have records will be blocked.</p>\n<p>Any changes to event permissions for a particular ~navdocs(Permgroups,Perm Group)~ need to be activated before they become effective. Use for eg. the "Recreate All Active Permissions"-button on the Designer, or delete the dibCode and active permissions for the container so that it will be created again.</p>\n<p>Note, criteria for executing events can be handled by programmers in the PHP function that is called.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc24-dib'),
    (26, 'Basic Steps Tasks and Tools', 324, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The following diagram provides an overview of the processes involved with building an application.Â </p><p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/lifecycle.jpg"/></p><p>Â </p><h2>Find Help</h2><p>The recommended way to master the system is to start with the video tutorials, followed by working through the ~nav(dibDashboard, examples)~.</p><p>Other sources of help:</p><ul><li>F1-key - provides popup help for the current field (note this facility is also available for your client applications)</li><li>These documentation pages (dibDocs)</li><li>Support from the community forum</li><li>Official help from Dropinbase</li></ul><h2>Administrator Tasks &amp; Tools</h2><p>Most features of a Dropinbase application can be customized by Administrators (non-programmers) to nearly any extent, while programmers with knowledge of Angular/ExtJs, PHP and SQL can customize anything.Â </p><p>By default Administrators login with username &#34;admin&#34; and password &#34;test&#34;. The dashboard displays links to common tasks, while the menu provides access to all tools, grids and forms.Â The AdministrationÂ application is in fact not required, but simply facilitates the editing of the Dropinbase configuration tables that define applications.Â </p><p>Below is a list of tools and forms that are particularly useful for common tasks.Â </p><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Task</strong></td><td><strong>Tool(s)</strong></td><td><strong>Affected Table(s)</strong></td></tr><tr><td><b><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">Setup &amp; test database connections</span><br/>Import tables</b></td><td>&#34;Tables&#34;-tab on the Form:Â ~nav(dibDatabaseForm?record=first)~</td><td>pef_database, pef_table, pef_field, pef_table_option, pef_table_option_field, pef_table_fk, pef_fk</td></tr><tr><td><b>Configure containers (pages), items, layout, ports, events, etc</b></td><td>~nav(dibDesigner)~. This is the main tool used to customize applications. The layout of items on containers is visualized by a tree structure resembling the DOM that defines views. <br/>Customize with drag-and-drop, copy&amp;paste, editing etc. Use the duplicate button under Configuration to make copies of containers.</td><td>pef_container, pef_item,Â pef_port,Â <br/>pef_container_setting, pef_container_event, pef_container_setting, pef_perm_container,<br/>pef_item_setting, pef_item_event, pef_item_filter, pef_perm_item, pef_action</td></tr><tr><td><b>Configure Audit Trailing, Table Events and changes to records</b></td><td>~nav(dibTableGrid,Tables)~. To view audit trails see Â ~nav(dibAuditTrailGrid,Audit Trails)~. Note, by default all forms have a Audit Trail link under the Tools menu button that will filter a records\' related audit trail records.</td><td>pef_table, pef_audit_trail</td></tr><tr><td><b>SQL queries for dropdown lists and reports</b></td><td>Use the &#34;Create From SQL&#34;-button on ~nav(dibSqlGrid)~. Drag and drop queries in ~nav(dibDesigner)~\'s Overview. Note, SQL is used to query relational databases. We can strongly recommend serious developers to get a proper grip on SQL (<a href="https://www.w3schools.com/sql/sql_intro.asp" target="">Learn SQL</a>).</td><td>pef_sql, pef_container, pef_item</td></tr><tr><td><b>Events &amp; Actions</b></td><td>~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~ - use the links on the Container and Item Overview tabs to add/edit events.</td><td>pef_item_event, pef_container_event</td></tr><tr><td><b>Permissions and business rules</b></td><td>~nav(dibPermGroupGrid,Permission Groups)~</td><td>pef_perm_group,Â pef_login,Â pef_login_group<br/>pef_perm_container, pef_perm_container_event,<br/>pef_perm_item, pef_perm_item_event, pef_perm_tooltip</td></tr><tr><td><b>Generate Files</b></td><td>~nav(dibFiles)~. Generate application files for deployment to a production server.</td><td>Â </td></tr><tr><td><b>Components &amp; Dropins</b></td><td>~nav(dibDropinGrid)~ ~nav(dibComponentGrid)~. Define building blocks of applications. The component table records reference the coding templates used to construct the items used in containers. Dropin records potentially define distributable application modules, container types (eg dibTree, dibForm), modifiers (functions to aid users modify the design of containers) and reusables (collections of items that can be reused). </td><td>pef_component, pef_dropin</td></tr><tr><td><b>Share &amp; Synchronize Records</b></td><td>~nav(dibShare)~. Synchronize records with project team members (still under development).</td><td>Â </td></tr></tbody></table><h2>Customization by Programmers</h2><p>Events can be linked to ~navdocs(Item Events, items)~, ~navdocs(Container Events, containers)~, or ~navdocs(Table Events, tables)~ and both server- and client-side events are available. Many functions such as opening containers or lazy loading items or refreshing data can be accomplished without any programming. Note, server-side code can return actions for execution on the client. Interfaces are being developed that will allow code in other languages.</p><p>Code generated by Dropinbases can be manually customized and moved to folders to avoid them being overwritten again.</p><p>It is possible to further customise applications by creating or activating ~navdocs(Dropins Overview, Dropins)~ that provide functionality such as components, maps, shopping carts, exporting information to specific formats, or whole systems (eg a stock tracking system with all related reports etc). Dropins are modules that define basically any reusable part of a system and can be shared with other Dropinbase systems (coming soon... see ~nav(dibShare)~).Â <span id="selectionBoundary_1555061165654_012936730741677449" class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span></p><p>Programmers can also create and distribute Modifiers (listed in the Component tree in the Designer). Modifiers aid administrators to modify the design of containers programmatically.<br/><br/></p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, '', 'doc26-dib'),
    (27, 'Why use Dropinbase', 9, 5, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Dropinbase was designed to facilitate the rapid and agile development of advanced, real-world database driven applications, and to remove the limits imposed by No/Low-code systems in general.</p>\n<p>It is in use by small NGO\'s to large corporates, and the system is regularly penetration tested by independant testers.</p>\n<p>By learning and implementing Dropinbase you can save time, money and skill requirements, and so-doing, greatly reduce the risks involved in a project.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/mx/Documents/human-capital/01_ERP_Top10_Challenges.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">55% - 75% of ERP implementations fail</a>! So use a system that facilitates a <strong>highly </strong>agile process.</li>\n<li>Build a fully functional application based on your back-end database within minutes as a starting point.</li>\n<li>Easily and fully customize applications - users with no programming skills can accomplish most of the work.</li>\n<li>From concept to production and ongoing maintenance, Dropinbase facilitates the development process and replaces complex programming and slog work, with drag-and-drop and small configurations.</li>\n<li>Leverage from thousands of hours of coding by experts with more than 30 years of experience.</li>\n<li>Mash-up many databases in a single application.</li>\n<li>Dropinbase is adequately documented, and support *** is available when help is needed.</li>\n<li>Dropinbase is continually improved and expanded by the core team and valued contributions from our community.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For developers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Add your own reusable components and modules</li>\n<li>The client and server API\'s are relatively small, well structured and therefore easy to debug.</li>\n<li>There is very little in Dropinbase that cannot be fully customized. Experienced Angular and PHP developers can customize anything.</li>\n<li>Focus scarce developer resources on custom code. Let Dropinbase do the slog work for you.</li>\n<li>Dropinbase implementations are strongly&nbsp;structured and standardized. Developers that learn to implement Dropinbase features (eg adding a report) can immediately add value to any other Dropinbase project.</li>\n<li>Build, share and sell (coming soon) reusable code.</li>\n<li>Take part in an exciting, growing and active community - show us what you can build!</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Dropinbase is very well placed to integrate artificial intelligence. The aim is to implement AI as a very capable assistant. <br>Developers will be able to build databases and containers, and users will be able to query their data and let AI perform tasks. <br>We have started the process... watch this space :)</p>\n<p><strong>*** NOTE</strong></p>\n<p>At present there is very little paid support available, making Dropinbase practical for experienced full-stack developers, or for simpler implementations where no advanced customization is required.</p>\n<p>We trust that developers will quickly learn the system and become part of the community and paid support.</p>\n<p>We strive to keep an open ear to our community\'s needs. Although our team is still small, it is passionate and growing, so please be patient as we move forward.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc27-dib'),
    (28, 'Understanding Dropinbase', NULL, 50, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc28-dib'),
    (29, 'Processes', 324, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The following diagram and discussion provides a technical overview of how requests are processed. It is useful for programmers and to debug any issues.Â </p><p>As mentioned before, the client-side application consists of containers that are loaded as they are required. Once they are loaded, the design is kept in cache (even if closed) for re-use until the browser window is refreshed (press F5 or use the browser\'s refresh icon) or the browser cache is cleared. This ensures enhanced performance over traditional applications that load a whole page with each request. Requests can be viewed in the browser\'s Console (press F12, go to the Console, and make sure that the setting that logs all requests is active (right-click in Chrome)).Â </p><p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/processes.jpg"/></p><ul><li>There are various request types. All navigation requests are of the form http://domainname/nav/containerName?parameters, eg Â http://www.mydibapp.com/nav/dibDatabaseForm?primary_id=1.</li><li>The Dropinbase client-side (JavaScript) framework consists of a core application that directs all events and is built on top of the Angular / Â ExtJs framework. It also contains libraries of common and useful functions that are available though the API. The Angular / ExtJs framework is a rich client-side application framework that adds endless possibilities to your application\'s design (see Angular: <a href="https://material.angularjs.org/latest/" target="">https://material.angularjs.org/latest/</a> and ExtJs:Â <a href="http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/4.2.2/">http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/4.2.2/</a>)</li><li>For a navigation request, the client-side framework first issues a &#34;getPortInfo&#34; request that checks whether the container exists and whether the user has rights to it, and then returns information regarding the container\'s port and container dropin type. It then requests the template controller of the given container dropin. Once the controller is loaded, it will in turn request the model, store, view, data, etc. Each of the requests will return html/json and JavaScript that may issue further requests for components etc. All the requests can be viewed in the browser\'s Console (note certain requests like HTML templates are listed only in the Network tab). Since browsers only issue between 2 and 8 concurrent requests per domain before any further requests are issued, it is important to limit the amount of requests. For this reason most container dropins (eg. dibForm and dibGrid) are optimized to include the model, store and view in the response for the controller.Â </li><li>Submission data can be specified for certain requests, eg a data request may have a custom filter that requires parameters (such as the selected record in a grid). This submission data is specified in the <i>configs </i>fields of items and containers, and posted along with requests. For more info see ~navdocs(Submission Data)~.</li><li>When loading the framework the first time, most requests are for static files and are of the form /files/dropins/xxx or /files/xxx. Static files requests are handled entirely by the files.php script in the /dropinbase folder.</li><li>The server application uses the DibApp.php, Url.php and ControllerFactory.php classes to processes all types of requests. The DibApp.php class will automatically create the following ~navdocs(System Configuration Files)~ if they do not exist:</li><ul><li>/configs/Dib.php</li></ul><li>The parameter values declared in dropin/API controller functions determine the values in the post data, URL or the URL query string that are passed to these functions. Three special (case-sensitive) parameter names are used specifically to enable permission checking before the controller functions are called (note, declaring functions with defaults for these parameters will nullify permissions):</li><ul><li>$containerName - will force a check in the current user\'s permgroup container permission files (eg /runtime/permFiles/_Containersxx1xx.php) to determine whether the container may be accessed</li><li>$itemEventId - used for item events. Will force a check in the permgroup item event permission files (eg /runtime/permFiles/_ItemEventsxx1xx.php) to determine whether the item event may be executed.</li><li>$containerEventId -Â <span style="font-size: 12px;text-align: left;float: none;">used for container events. Will force a check in the permgroup container event permission files (eg /runtime/permFiles/_ContainerEventsxx1xx.php) to determine whether the container event may be executed.</span></li></ul><li>See ~navdocs(Executing Server Functions From the Client)~ for more details about the available parameters for each type of event, and automatic validation checking.Â </li><li>After checking permissions, the ControllerFactory class will pass the parameter values to the relevant controller function. Depending on the type of call (\'actions\', \'redirect\' or a timeout value for the queue), the function will generate a response or redirect the client to another page/container. Responses can include actions to execute on the client, data for forms or grids, client-side code that defines a new container or a command to initiate the Queue.</li><li>The system will package and json-encode the response and return it to the client for processing. The communication between client and server can be viewed in the browser\'s Developer Tools (Console and Network tabs).</li><li>For some practical examples, see ~nav(dibexEvents)~ and the associated PHP controller classes.</li></ul><p>Â </p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc29-dib'),
    (30, 'Tables Fields and Table Options', 324, 100, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The following tables are all automatically populated and maintained by using the actions under &#34;Tables&#34; on ~nav(dibDatabaseForm)~:</p><ul><li>~navdocs(Tables Reference,Tables,pef_table)~</li><li>~navdocs(Tables Reference,Table Options,pef_table_option)~</li><li>~navdocs(Tables Reference,Table Option Fields,pef_table_option_field)~</li><li>~navdocs(Tables Reference,Fields,pef_field)~</li><li>~navdocs(Tables Reference,Table Foreign Keys,pef_table_fk)~</li><li>~navdocs(Tables Reference,Foreign Keys,pef_fk)~</li></ul><p>The information in these tables are mostly used when generating code for CRUD (create, read, update, delete) actions, or when transferring whole tables between database servers. Many of the values in the Fields table are used as defaults when creating Item records.Â </p><p>The ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Tables,pef_table)~ table stores the names of the tables that have been indexed (&#34;imported&#34;) into the Dropinbase system, and a few related settings, most notably the Audit Trail settings.</p><p>The closely related ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Table Options,pef_table_option)~ andÂ ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Table Option Fields,pef_table_option_field)~ tables contain field index information, specifying for eg which combination of columns should have unique values. The Dropinbase CRUD classes will contain specific code generated to test for these unique values when records are changed or created.</p><p>TheÂ ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Fields,pef_field)~ table describes the fields belonging to each table, and, as mentioned, is used when setting default values for Items. The values are also used when creating table definitions in databases, such as when tables are transferred between Dropinbase installations.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc30-dib'),
    (31, 'Filters on Containers and Dropdowns', 28, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>By default, grids, forms and dropdown lists return all the records in their data sources (page by page). But what if you need to show only the records that relate to a certain client or product?</p>\n<p>Filters provide a way to limit the records returned to only those that satisfy certain criteria. The same grid or dropdown can be implemented in many places, each with their own filter.&nbsp;<br>By using filters, features like master-child forms and dropdowns that are dependant on one another\'s values can be facilitated.</p>\n<p>Here is an example of a typical master-child form filter that will be entered into the&nbsp;<em>filter</em> field of a subcontainer-component under Item Details.</p>\n<p>sales.product_id = :alias_parent_productId</p>\n<p>where <strong>sales.product_id</strong> refers to <em>product_id </em>field in the <em>sales </em>table, and <strong>:alias_parent_productId </strong>refers to the value of the <strong>productId</strong> item (that may be hidden, but must have an alias to include it in Client Data) on the parent container.<span id="selectionBoundary_1513182444317_0050098536215168465" class="rangySelectionBoundary"></span></p>\n<p><span class="rangySelectionBoundary">The available parameters are in Client Data and User Parameters and other Dropinbase Parameters. See the Configurations tab of this example for more info: ~nav(dibexSqlParams)~.</span></p>\n<p>Filters are SQL criteria expressions that contain parameters (eg :alias_parent_productId) and are valid in the current container or dropdown\'s underlying SQL. Any field in any table of the underlying SQL\'s from-clause can be used in expressions. To view the underlying SQL of a container, use the <strong>View SQL</strong> button under Container Details on the Designer. Note, the Extra Table Join (<em>pef_container.extra_table_join)</em> field can be used to add more tables.</p>\n<p>For more practical examples see ~navdocs(Filters, docs, Filter Examples)~.</p>\n<p><strong>How filters work:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Each filter implemented is assigned a unique name in the generated user-interface code.</li>\n<li>The read request of the filtered dropdown or container sends this unique name as a POST parameter named \'activeFilter\', along with the Client Data.</li>\n<li>The generated server crud class code accepts this specific unique filter name and appies the related filter criteria to the underlying SQL\'s where-clause. Any parameters in the filter criteria is resolved in a secure manner with PDO to prevent SQL injection.&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n<p><span style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">IMPORTANT</span>: filters <strong>should not be used</strong> to permanently block users from seeing certain records in a given data source. Malicious users can remove or change the activeFilter name or Client Data values in requests to view other records. <br>Use criteria in a SQL grid\'s underlying query, or Container Permission crtieria in order to limit users in a manner that is unaffected by client request parameters. In some cases this may mean that the Filter becomes superflous. If a user may in any case see all data retuned by a data source, implement a filter.<br><span id="selectionBoundary_1513185160074_05537938570623724" class="rangySelectionBoundary"></span></p>\n<p>Filters can be applied to subcontainers, ports with child containers, or items such as dropdowns that return lists of data. For container filters, the <strong>activeFilter </strong>parameter is set to the name of the container. For item and port item filters the <strong>activeFilter </strong>name is constructed by combining the names of the container, item and child container.</p>\n<p>There are two ways of filtering a container\'s data. The filter can be applied directly in the container\'s Filter (<em>pef_container.filter) </em>field, which is useful if the container is never a child of another container. Alternativily the container can be hosted in a subcontainer-component, and the filter applied to it in the Item\'s <em>Filter </em>(<em>pef_item</em>.<em>filter</em>) field. Note, if both are specified, then both filters are applied using an AND operator to join them.&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Scenario\'s Where Filters are Often Used:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Two (or more) dropdowns (comboboxes) where dropdown B displays a list that is filtered by a value selected in dropdown A. Add the filter to B, and add a Refresh Item Action to A that refreshes B after a value is selected. See ~nav(dibexFilterDropdown)~.</li>\n<li>A child container on a form that displays records related to the parent form\'s data (typical master-child form/grid scenario). Add the filter to the subcontainer-component on the parent form. Data displayed in subcontainer components is automatically refreshed when navigating through records in the parent form - no need for a Refresh action. Note, the child container can be nearly any type, eg form, grid, tree, chart, etc. Html/Iframe containers can also accept filters if the container is based on a table or SQL statement (<em>pef_table_id </em>or <em>pef_sql_id </em>is is filled in), though in most cases parameters and SQL inside the HTML template is used to filter the data. See ~nav(dibexContainerFilterForm)~</li>\n<li>A container that is loaded in a port item using a port. This is also the default way of implementing related records when tables are imported (see the <em>related_records </em>field in <em>pef_database </em>and <em>pef_table</em>). See ~nav(dibexContainerFilterPort)~.</li>\n<li>A "stand-alone" container that must have a permanent filter applied. Set the&nbsp;<em>filter </em>and <em>filter_syntax&nbsp;</em>fields in pef_container.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Configuration and Debugging</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Provide the criteria expressionin the F<em>ilter </em>field in <em>pef_container</em> or <em>pef_item</em>.</li>\n<li>Provide the SQL syntax of the expression, eg. <strong>mysql </strong>or <strong>mssql </strong>etc, in the <em>filter_syntax </em>field (see below definition for filter_syntax).</li>\n<li>Remember that the <strong>:alias_self_xxx</strong> and <strong>:alias_parent_xxx </strong>Client Data is submitted by default with all read requests. If additional Client Data is required by the filter criteria, specify it in the Item or Container\'s<em> Configs</em> field.</li>\n<li>In cases where the filtered item/container is dependent on the selected value of another item/container, consider adding a Refresh Item action on the latter item\'s change or grid\'s rowClick event. This will cause the target item/container to automatically refresh when the Client Data changes.</li>\n<li>Clear the generated /dibCode files for all containers that are involved.</li>\n<li>Reload the container in the browser to regenerate the view\'s code and test the filter.</li>\n<li>Check the Console (eg press F12 in Chrome) for the relevant read request. It should contain an "activeFilter" parameter and the Client Data should match parameters used in the filter.</li>\n<li>For further debugging, check error logs (if errors occur) or open the generated code in the /dibCode folder and add <strong>Log::w($sql, $params)</strong> statements where necessary to print values to the Debug Log.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Fields used for Filtering</h2>\n<p><strong>Item Table</strong></p>\n<p>~docstable(pef_item,$filter$filter_syntax$configs$)~</p>\n<p><strong>Container Table</strong></p>\n<p>~docstable(pef_container,$filter$filter_syntax$configs$)~</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc31-dib'),
    (32, 'DEvents', 324, 40, 1, 'eleutheria', '', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc32-dib'),
    (33, 'SQL and Reports', 324, 120, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The pef_sql table stores SQL SELECT queries that are used as record sources for containers or dropdown lists.</p><p>When used for dropdown lists, there are very specific rules that need to be adhered to. See ~navdocs(Dropdown Display Expressions)~ for more info.</p><p>See ~navdocs(dibGrid - SQL)~ for more info about using SQL as the record source of containers.Â </p><h3>SQL Table Fields</h3><p><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">~docstable(pef_sql)~</span></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc33-dib'),
    (34, 'Item Events', 32, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Item events make use of named listeners such as \'click\' or \'change\' that dynamically load JavaScript code or call server-side code for execution.Â </p><p>The following discussion gives a broad overview of the topic; follow the links below for more information.</p><p>An event occurs on a specified trigger (eg \'click\') and will execute one of the following types of actions:</p><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Action Type</strong></td><td><strong>Description</strong></td><td><strong>Main Fields in Item Event table</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Execute Server Functions <br/>(PHP)</td><td><ul><li>A developer\'s own code in a /dropins/DROPINNAME/controllers folder is called to process the request.</li><li>A URL must be specified in the submit_url field of the following form: /dropins/DROPINNAME/CONTROLLERNAME/FUNCTIONNAME<ul><li>eg /dropins/dibExamples/Events/btnHelloWorld_click Â  OR Â Â /dropins/setSencha/dibAdmin/dibDebug/clearDibLog Â (here a parent dropin is involved)</li><li>The file must be located at /dropins/dibExamples/controllers/EventsController.php.</li></ul></li><li>âA set of predefined parameters (eg containerName, itemEventId, ~navdocs(Submission Data, submissionData)~,Â etc are submitted with Controller actions and are available for use in server code.Â </li><li>If serverside function parameters include $containerName, $itemEventId, and/or $containerEventId, the user\'s permgroup permissions are checked before the controller function is called.</li><li>See Â ~nav(dibexEvents)~ andÂ ~navdocs(Executing Server Functions From the Client)~ for more info</li></ul></td><td>submit_url, trigger, response_type</td></tr><tr><td>Execute Client Functions <br/>(JavaScript)</td><td><ul><li>Â A developer\'s own client-side code is executed.</li><li>Â A URL must be specified in the submit_url field of the following form: Dropins.DROPINNAME.xxx[.yyy][.etc].FILENAME which will target the following file: /dropins/DROPINNAME/xxx[/yyy][/etc]/FILENAME.js<ul><li>eg Dropins.setMySet.myDropin.js.Reload</li></ul></li><li>If the dropin is a child-dropin of the setNgMaterial dropin, then the following shorter version will also work:</li><ul><li>myDropin[.xxx].Reload</li><li>The file must be located at /dropins/setNgMaterial/myDropin[/xxx]/Reload.js</li></ul><li>The class must always be defined using the full version of the url, egÂ <br/><!--StartFragment--><span style="font-size: 12px;text-align: left;float: none;">Dropins.setMySet.myDropin.js.Reload</span><br/></li><li>See Â ~nav(dibexEvents)~ andÂ ~navdocs(Executing Client Api Functions From the Client)~ for more info</li></ul></td><td>submit_url, trigger</td></tr><tr><td>Refresh Actions</td><td>Provides a convenient way to refresh the data of a given item/child container. Note, the target item must have an Alias in order for the client-side api to find it. See ~navdocs(Refresh Item Action)~, andÂ Refresh Events on ~nav(dibexEvents)~ for more info.</td><td>refresh_item_alias.<br/>Â </td></tr><tr><td>Lazy Load Action</td><td>Provides a convenient way to lazy load items into the view. See ~nav(dibexEvents)~ andÂ ~navdocs(Lazy Loading Items)~ for more info.</td><td>pef_lazy_load_parent_id,Â lazy_load_tag,<br/>lazy_load_option,Â lazy_load_activate</td></tr></tbody></table><p><br/></p><p>Note, only one action type per recordÂ will be executed reliably. To execute different action types on the same trigger (<span id="selectionBoundary_1555061108835_14182411938266104" class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span>eg \'click), create more than one record for it.</p><p>See the ~nav(dibexEvents, examples)~ for more info.Â </p><h2>Item Event Table Fields</h2><p>~docstable(pef_item_event)~</p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc34-dib'),
    (35, 'DContainer Events', 32, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>A container event occurs either on the client or server on a specified trigger (eg \'load\' or \'before create\') and can execute any of the action types below.</p><p>Dropinbase includes custom container events for each dropin type. A set of events common to most dropin types are listed in the<strong> Dropinbase Custom Events</strong> table below. Refer to the container dropin\'s documentation for specific events.Â </p><p>The Container Event table (<i>pef_container_event</i>) links triggers with the following types of actions:Â </p><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Action Type</strong></td><td><strong>Description</strong></td><td><strong>Fields in Container Event table</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Server-side Functions called from the client</td><td><ul><li>A developer\'s own code in a /dropins/DROPINNAME/controllers folder is called to process the request.</li><li>A URL must be specified in the submit_url field of the following form: /dropins/DROPINNAME/CONTROLLERNAME/FUNCTIONNAME<ul><li>eg /dropins/dibExamples/Events/btnHelloWorld_click Â  OR Â Â /dropins/setSencha/dibAdmin/dibDebug/clearDibLog Â (here a parent dropin is involved)</li><li>The file must be located at /dropins/dibExamples/controllers/EventsController.php.</li></ul></li><li>âA set of predefined parameters (eg containerName, itemEventId, ~navdocs(Submission Data, submissionData)~,Â etc are submitted with Controller actions and are available for use in server code.Â </li><li>If serverside function parameters include $containerName, $itemEventId, and/or $containerEventId, the user\'s permgroup permissions are checked before the controller function is called.</li><li>See Â ~nav(dibexEvents)~ andÂ ~navdocs(Executing Server Functions From the Client)~ for more info</li><li>Only the <b>Client-sideÂ </b>Dropinbase event triggers are available for events: SeeÂ the<strong>Â Dropinbase Custom Events</strong>Â table below.</li></ul></td><td>submit_url, trigger, response_type</td></tr><tr><td>Client-side Functions<br/></td><td><ul><li>A developer\'s own client-side code is executed.</li><li>Â A URL must be specified in the submit_url field of the following form: Dropins.DROPINNAME.xxx[.etc][.zzz].FILENAME which will target the following file: /dropins/DROPINNAME/xxx[/etc][/zzz]/FILENAME.js<ul><li>eg Dropins.setMySet.myDropin.js.Reload</li></ul></li><li>If the dropin is a child-dropin of the setNgMaterial dropin, then the following shorter version will also work:</li><ul><li>myDropin[.xxx].Reload</li><li>The file must be located at /dropins/setNgMaterial/myDropin[/xxx]/Reload.js</li></ul><li>The class must always be defined using the full version of the url, egÂ <br/>Dropins.setMySet.myDropin.js.Reload</li><li>Only the <b>Client-sideÂ </b>Dropinbase event triggers are available for events: SeeÂ the<strong>Â Dropinbase Custom Events</strong>Â table below.</li><li>See Â ~nav(dibexEvents)~ andÂ ~navdocs(Executing Client Api Functions From the Client)~ for more info.</li></ul></td><td>submit_url, trigger</td></tr><tr><td><br/>Server-side Functions called from CRUD classes on the server<br/></td><td><ul><li>A developer\'s own PHP function in the following file is called to process the request:Â Â /dropins/DROPINNAME/components/CLASSNAME.php</li><li>A corresponding URL must be specified in the <i>submit_url </i>field as follows: /dropins/DROPINNAME/CLASSNAME/FUNCTIONNAME<ul><li>eg /dropins/dibExamples/ContainerEvents/afterChange Â  OR Â /dropins/setSencha/dibAdmin/Permissions/itemList Â (here a parent dropin is involved)</li></ul></li><li>âA set of predefined PHP parametersÂ are available for use as function parameters in FUNCTIONNAME. See theÂ <strong>Dropinbase Custom Events</strong>Â table below for details.</li><li>The <b>ContainerÂ CRUD event</b> triggers are available (see<b> Dropinbase Custom Events below</b>).</li><li>You can override any message returned to the client by using theÂ DibApp::setClientMsg function in the PHP code that is called.</li><li>You can also return actions to be executed on the client by using the DibApp::$clientActions array.</li><li>See ~nav(dibexEvents)~ andÂ Â ~navdocs(Executing Server Functions From the Server)~ for more info.</li></ul></td><td>submit_url, trigger</td></tr><tr><td><p>Refresh Actions</p></td><td><ul><li>Provides a convenient way to refresh the data of a given item/child container. Note, the target must have an Alias in order for the client-side api to find it.Â See ~navdocs(Refresh Item Action)~, andÂ Refresh Events on ~nav(dibexEvents)~ for more info.<br/></li><li>Only the <b>Client-sideÂ </b>custom Dropinbase eventÂ triggers are available for events: SeeÂ the<strong>Â Dropinbase Custom Events</strong>Â table below.</li></ul></td><td>refresh_item_alias.<br/>Â </td></tr><tr><td>Lazy Load Action</td><td><ul><li>Provides a convenient way to lazy load items into the view. See ~navdocs(Lazy Loading Items)~ and ~nav(dibexLazyLoad)~Â for more info.<br/></li><li>Only the <b>Client-side</b>Â Dropinbase eventÂ triggers are available for events: SeeÂ the<strong>Â Dropinbase Custom Events</strong>Â table below.</li></ul></td><td>pef_lazy_load_parent_id,Â lazy_load_tag,<br/>lazy_load_option,Â lazy_load_activate</td></tr></tbody></table><p><br/></p><h4>Notes</h4><ul><li>Only one action type per recordÂ will be executed reliably. To execute different action types on the same trigger, create more than one record for it,or use PHP to call client-side actions.Â </li><li>When theÂ $containerName parameter is present in the PHP function parameter list and has no default, Dropinbase checks the current user\'s permissions to open the container.<br/></li></ul><h2>Container Events Table Fields</h2><p>~docstable(pef_container_event)~</p><h2>Dropinbase Custom Events</h2><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Trigger Name</strong></td><td><strong>Trigger Type</strong></td><td><strong>Notes</strong></td><td><b>Parameters Available</b></td></tr><tr><td>onInit</td><td>Client-side</td><td><p>Occurs after the container is initialized (loaded the first time), and before any data is loaded. Note some items may not yet be loaded in the view, so this event should not depend on the availability of items.<span style="background-color: transparent;">All container dropins in Dropinbase should have this event.</span></p></td><td>$containerName, $containerEventId, $submissionData, $triggerType, $containerId</td></tr><tr><td>load</td><td>Client-side</td><td>Occurs each time data is loaded into the container, after the new data has arrived.<br/>All container dropins in Dropinbase should have this event.<br/></td><td>$containerName, $containerEventId, $submissionData, $triggerType, $containerId</td></tr><tr><td>reloadContainer</td><td>Client-side</td><td>Occurs when data is loaded into the container using a crud/read request, before the new data has arrived. Does not occur when data is loaded the first time. Also occurs each time when the URL changes and a container gets focus, and on a child container when the data in the parent container is reloaded and the subcontainer has a filter. <br/>All container dropins in Dropinbase should have this event.<br/></td><td>$containerName, $containerEventId, $submissionData, $triggerType, $containerId</td></tr><tr><td>postLink</td><td>Client-side</td><td>Occurs when data is loaded into the container the first time, using a crud/read request, after the new data has arrived.<br/>All container dropins in Dropinbase should have this event.<br/></td><td>$containerName, $containerEventId, $submissionData, $triggerType, $containerId</td></tr><tr><td>before readone</td><td>CRUDÂ (Create-Read-Update-Delete. Note, container CRUD events occur in the generated PHP classes thatÂ manage data-interactions with the underlying database tables).</td><td>Occurs before the read request is issued to the database server for a single record (eg when navigating between records in a Form).</td><td>$containerName, $filterParams, $trigger</td></tr><tr><td>after readone</td><td>CRUD</td><td>Occurs after the read request is issuedÂ to the database server for a single record (eg when navigating between records in a Form).</td><td>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger, $filterParams</td></tr><tr><td>before readmany</td><td>CRUD</td><td>Occurs before the read request is issuedÂ to the database server for potentially many records (eg when refreshing or filtering a Grid).</td><td>$containerName, $filterParams, $trigger</td></tr><tr><td>afterÂ readmany</td><td>CRUD</td><td>OccursÂ after the read request is issuedÂ to the database server for potentially many records (eg when refreshing or filtering a Grid).</td><td>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger, $filterParams</td></tr><tr><td>before create</td><td>CRUD</td><td>Occurs before the create (insert) requestÂ is issuedÂ to the database server and after all validation has occurred (eg the Save button is clicked on a new record in a Form/Grid). This event is useful if you want to modify the field values somehow before creating the record.</td><td>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger</td></tr><tr><td>after create</td><td>CRUD</td><td>Occurs after the create (insert) requestÂ is issuedÂ to the database server and after the audit trail records have been created (eg the Save button is clicked on a new record in a Form/Grid).Â Note this event will not fire if there was an error with the create request.</td><td>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger</td></tr><tr><td>before update</td><td>CRUD</td><td>Occurs before the change (update) requestÂ is issuedÂ to the database server and after all validation has occurred (eg the Save button is clicked on an existing record in a Form/Grid). This event is useful if you want to modify the field values somehow before updating the record.</td><td>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger, $recordOld</td></tr><tr><td>afterÂ update</td><td>CRUD</td><td>Occurs after theÂ change (update)Â requestÂ is issuedÂ to the database server and after the audit trail records have been created (eg the Save button is clicked on an existing record in a Form/Grid). Note this event will not fire if there was an error with the change request.</td><td>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger, $recordOld, $validAttributes</td></tr><tr><td>before delete</td><td>CRUD</td><td>Occurs before the delete requestÂ is issuedÂ to the database server (eg the Delete button is clicked for an existing record in a Form/Grid).Â </td><td>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger</td></tr><tr><td>after delete</td><td>CRUD</td><td>Occurs after theÂ delete requestÂ is issuedÂ to the database server and after the audit trail records have been created (eg the Delete button is clicked on an existing record in a Form/Grid). Note this event will not fire if there was an error with the delete request.</td><td>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger</td></tr><tr><td>get defaults</td><td>CRUD</td><td>Occurs after the default values for a record has been constructed but not yet sent to the client (eg the Add button is clicked on a Form/Grid). This event is useful if you want to modify the default values before they are sent to the client.</td><td>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc35-dib'),
    (37, 'DRefresh Item Action', 32, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><span>Various components and container dropins, have a Dropinbase custom reloadContainer client-side function which can be called to refresh the information displayed in them. This can be accomplished by simply adding a client-side event in either the ~navdocs(Item Events,Item Event)~ or ~navdocs(Container Events,Container Event)~ table. The item that <i>pef_refresh_item_id</i> references Â (normally a subcontainer or dropdown component)Â must have an Alias.</span></p><p>Refresh actions are often used with Filters (on eg child-grids) that contain Submission Data that does not originate from parent containers. Eg should you have a tree or grid component where the selected record is submitted as criteria for displaying information in a form, then the tree/grid will have a Refresh action on the \'itemselect\' event trigger (a special event trigger defined by Dropinbase for this purpose) that references the Item Alias of the form. The dibDesignerItemTree container makes use of this event.</p><p>See Refresh Events on ~nav(dibexEvents)~ for more examples.</p><p>Â </p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc37-dib'),
    (38, 'DClient API Functions', 32, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The dibGlobals/js/action folders contain useful API functions that can be executed client-side.Â </p><p><b>Angular:</b> /setNgMaterial/dibGlobals/js/action<br/><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;"><b>ExtJs:</b> Â /setSencha/dibGlobals/js/<b>app</b>/action</span><br/></p><p></p><p>Also see the /js/action folders of other dropins, eg. dibForm and dibGrid.</p><p>Note, the files in the above mentioned folders can also act as examples for your own client-side functions.<br/></p><h3>Executing from PHP</h3><p>Actions are added to an array. The ClientFunctions class has convenient functions to assist (eg the addAction and addMethod functions).</p><p>The array of actions can then be sent to the client for execution either via NodeJs, Queues, validResult or invalidResult.</p><p></p><p></p><p>See ~navdocs(Executing Client Api Functions From the Server)~ for more info.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc38-dib'),
    (39, 'Developer Topics', NULL, 80, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc39-dib'),
    (40, 'Executing Server Functions From the Client', 324, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Throughout the system, urls are used to execute server-side functions. The functions are always either Dropinbase core API functions (situated in the Dropinbase/components/xxx folder) or dropin functions (situated in the /dropins/DROPINNAME/controller/ folders).</p><p></p><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Function Type</strong></td><td><strong>URL Format</strong></td><td><strong>Example</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Dropin</td><td>/dropins/DROPINNAME/CONTROLLERNAME/FUNCTIONNAME</td><td>/dropins/dibExamples/Events/btnHelloWorld_click<br/>or<br/>/dropins/setMySet/myDropin/myEvent</td></tr><tr><td>Core API</td><td>/peff/ACTIONCLASSNAME/FUNCTIONNAME</td><td>/peff/Sync/refreshTableList</td></tr></tbody></table><p></p><p>Eg http://dev.peff.net/dropins/test/Run/setFilterNone Â  - this URL will execute the function named setFilterNone in the RunController.php in the /projectFolder/dropins/test/controllers/ folder.</p><p>Function calls from the client to the server can be specified in the following places:Â </p><ul><li>~navdocs(Tables Reference,Item Events table,pef_item_event)~</li><li>~navdocs(Tables Reference,Container Events table,pef_container_event)~</li><li>in HTML, eg in the underlying HTML templates of dibHtmlTemplate containers (see ~navdocs(Executing Server Functions From the Client,Calls From within HTML,Calls From within HTML)~ below)</li></ul><p>In addition, navigation urls (eg /nav/myContainerName) can be specified in the expression field of button and menu item components.</p><p>A call to a dropin controller function causes the system to first check if the file exists under developer dropins (ie /projectFolder/dropins/...) before checking the system dropins folder (ie /dropinbase/dropins/...). This implies that one can override a system dropin by copying it to the developer dropin folder and modifying it. If it still can\'t find it, the function will fail, and an entry will be made in error.log.</p><p>See ~nav(dibexEvents)~ and the related PHP files in /dropins/dibExamples/ for examples with clarifying notes.</p><h3>Event Permissions</h3><p>If any of the following parameters are included in the controller function\'s declaration, the the user\'s permgroup permissions are checked before the controller function is called. If the search term is not found, and $LOGPERMISSUES in Dib.php=1, the details of the call is logged in the /runtime/logs/Permissions.log<br/></p><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Parameter Name</strong></td><td><strong>File Checked <i>(assuming the permgroup is x1x)</i></strong></td></tr><tr><td><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">$containerName</span><br/></td><td>/runtime/permFiles/_Containersxx1xx.php</td></tr><tr><td><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">$itemEventId</span><br/></td><td>/runtime/permFiles/_ItemEventsxx1xx.php</td></tr><tr><td><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">$containeEventId</span><br/></td><td>/runtime/permFiles/_ContainerEventsxx1xx.php</td></tr></tbody></table><p><br/>Note, b<span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">y default the </span><i style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">pef_perm_container.</span>item_events field</i><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;"> field is set to 1, meaning that the permission group that has rights to a container, also has rights to all events in the particular container, unless permissions are explicitly specified in <i>pef_perm_item_event </i>for one or more events (then only those events are permitted). The same logic applies for <i>pef_perm_container.container_events</i> and <i>pef_perm_container_events</i>.</span></p><p></p><h3>Assignment of Function Parameter Values</h3><p></p><p>The ControllerFactory class uses reflection to obtain the list of function parameters, and then loops through the list (in the order provided) to assigns values to them using the following rules:</p><p></p><ol><li>If the URL contains any extra parts, assign these parts as values in order (if they exist).Â </li><ol><li>Eg /dropins/myDropin/myFunction/extra1/extra2âÂ </li><li>\'extra1\' will be assigned to the first parameter in the list, and \'extra2\' to the second parameter.</li></ol><li>else if the parameter name (case-sensitive) in the function declaration appears as a url\'s query parameter, assign this value</li><ol><li>Eg /dropins/myDropin/myFunction/company?myParam=aaaa&amp;itemEventId=234</li><li>\'company\' will be assigned to the first parameter, \'aaaa\' will be assigned to the parameter named myParam, and 234 to itemEventId</li></ol><li>else if the parameter name in the function declaration is Â \'submissionData\' Â then obtain the value from posted data</li><ol><li>Note, all items on a container and its parent container that have aliases are automatically included in submissionData. To include additional values, see ~navdocs(Submission Data)~.</li></ol><li>else if the parameter has a default value, assign it</li><li>else log an error with details in error.log, inform the user to notify the Administrator, and stop any further execution.</li></ol><p></p><h3>Additional Rules For Successful Execution<br/></h3><ol><li>All names are case-sensitive</li><li>CONTROLLERNAME must exclude the suffix \'Controller\' (eg myClass).</li><li>The PHP class name must be CONTROLLERNAME, and the file name must end in Controller.php (eg myClassController.php).</li><li>For dropin functions, the PHP file must be in the /dropins/DROPINNAME/controllers subfolder.</li><li>None of the parameters must be called by reference. Ie the use of &amp; (eg &amp;$containerName) will cause a fatal exception).</li><li>Functions that are targeted by urls must be public and non-static, eg</li><ol><li>public function myFunction($containerName, $itemEventId, $submissionData=null) {...}</li></ol><li>If any of the public functions are called with the \'actions\' response type, Â the PHP class should extend the \'Controller\' class in order to return a response using one of the following:</li><ol><li>return $this-&gt;validResult(...)</li><li>return $this-&gt;invalidResult(...)</li></ol></ol><h3>Response Type</h3><p>The response_type field in pef_item_event and pef_container_event determines the interaction between client and server.</p><p>The following insert comes from the field reference for \'response_type\':</p><p style="font-size: 12px;">~docstable(pef_item_event,$response_type$)~Â </p><h3>Parameters</h3><p>The following parameter values are available when server-side functions are called:</p><p>(Note, for container events, $itemEventId should be replaced with $containerEventId and $itemId by $containerId and $itemAlias can be omitted).</p><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td>Parameter</td><td>Description</td></tr><tr><td>$containerName</td><td>If present it will contain the name of the container from where the event was triggered. It will also force a permission check to be done to see whether the user\'s permgroup has rights to open the container. The $containerName parameter should not have any default value, otherwise permissions will not be enforced.</td></tr><tr><td>$itemEventIdÂ (for item events only)</td><td>If present it will contain the id value of the item event that was triggered. If both $itemEventId and $containerName are present, it will also force a permission check to be done to see whether the user\'s permgroup has rights to execute the event. Note event permissions are allowed for all events on a container, or each specific event, dependant on whether rights are specifically specified or not. The $containerName and $itemEventId parameters should not have any default values, otherwise permissions will not be properly enforced.</td></tr><tr><td>$containerEventId (for container events only)</td><td>If present it will contain the id value of the container event that was triggered. IfÂ both $containerEventId and $containerName are present, it will also force a permission check to be done to see whether the user\'s permgroup has rights to execute the event. Note event permissions are allowed for all events on a container, or each specific event, dependant on whether rights are specifically specified or not. The $containerName and $containerEventId parameters should not have any default values, otherwise permissions will not be properly enforced.</td></tr><tr><td>$submissionData</td><td>A Json encoded array containing the submissionData. By default it will contain submitItemAlias_self and submitItemAlias_parent. See ~navdocs(Submission Data)~ for more info.</td></tr><tr><td>$triggerType</td><td>The type of trigger that caused the event, eg. \'click\' or \'select\' etc.</td></tr><tr><td>$itemIdÂ Â (for item events only)</td><td>The pef_item.id value of the item that triggered the event.</td></tr><tr><td>$containerId (for container events)</td><td>The pef_container.id value of the container where the event was triggered.</td></tr><tr><td>$itemAliasÂ (for item events only)</td><td>The Item Alias value (if any) of theÂ item that triggered the event (useful if distributing your application since the id value can change).</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Â </p><h3>Calls From within HTML</h3><p>~navtag(Calls From within HTML)~The dibHtmlTemplate container dropin provides a convenient way of merging data with HTML and displaying it in the application.Â </p><p>To specify events that call server-side functions in the HTML, include the following reference in the &lt;head&gt;...&lt;/head&gt; section:</p><pre>&lt;script type=&#34;text/JavaScript&#34; src=&#34;/files/dropins/setNgMaterial/dibAngular/src/js/core/shared/TemplateActions.js&#34;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre><p>The following JavaScript functions are available:</p><h4>goTo</h4><p>Used for navigation.</p><p><b>Syntax:</b> common.goTo(containerName, portAlias, changeUrl, urlQueryString)</p><p><b>Example</b>:Â </p><pre><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">&lt;a href=&#34;#&#34; onClick=&#34;common.goTo(\'dibFieldForm\', \'\', true, \'?record=first\');return false&#34;&gt;Go to the first record&lt;/a&gt;</span></pre><p><b>Notes</b>:</p><p><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;"></span></p><ul><li>use \'\' if there is no value for portAlias</li></ul><h4>startAction</h4><p>Executes a server-side function.</p><p><b>NOTE:Â </b>See ~navdocs(startAction)~ for a more detailed explanation.</p><p><b>Syntax:Â </b>common.startAction(submitUrl, containerName)Â </p><p></p><p><b>Example:</b></p><pre>~$delim~$// Get the dibuid/id values of pef_item_event record(s) into the globalArray so that they can be passed on for permission checking, eg see testAction below) ~$delim~<br/>~$delim~adddbval([*i.name, pie.dibuid*], pef_item i INNER JOIN pef_container c ON i.pef_container_id = c.id INNER JOIN pef_item_event pie ON pie.pef_item_id = i.id, c.name=\'dibtestCompanyETReport\')~$delim~<br/><span id="selectionBoundary_1498814643343_5947597114611296" class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span>&#10;&lt;a style=&#34;color:#5BB0FF&#34; href=&#34;#&#34; onClick=&#34;common.startAction(\'/dropins/dibExamples/Events/btnHelloWorld_click/dibtestCompanyETReport/~fld(testAction)~\', \'<span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">dibtestCompanyETReport\'</span>);return false;&#34;&gt;Say Hello&lt;/a&gt;<br/></pre><p><b>Notes:</b></p><p></p><ul><li>To enable permissions we used a trick ...Â </li><ul><li>Using the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ we dragged a button to the dibtestCompanyETReport container and specified the URL we wish to call, /dropins/dibExamples/Events/btnHellowWorld_click</li><li>When the permission files are created again, the _ItemEventsxx1xx.php file included our new event</li><li>We then created the <span style="font-size: 12px;text-align: left;float: none;">btnHellowWorld_clickÂ </span>controller function and included the $containerName and $itemEventId parameter values.</li><li>To pass the required $itemEventId values to the server, we first use the adddbval Eleutheria function to get it (and the dibuid values of any other item events)</li><li><b>Note, an easier method than using adddbval is to simply hard-code the dibuid value in the template.</b><br/></li></ul><li>The containerName parameter is used as a starting point to search for submissionData which affects \'self\' and \'parent\' values.</li></ul><p></p><p><br/></p><p></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc40-dib'),
