    (43, 'Material Component', 324, 55, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The library ofÂ ~nav(dibComponentGrid,Components)~ lists the different types of items that can be used to build a Dropinbase application\'s user-interface. The component settings are stored in pef_component, while the <i>pef_component_dropin_id </i>and <i>template_folder </i>fields identify where the files are stored.Â </p><p>The <em>pef_material_dropin_id </em>field distinguishes between ExtJs and Angular (Ng Material) components. Certain components can only be used with certain container dropins, eg those prefixed with \'grid\' in ExtJs can only be used in grids.Â </p><p>Depending on the component, certain fields in the Items table can be used to set properties. Components that have the same value in theÂ <em>include_fileÂ </em>field, share sets of properties in the Items table.Â The <em>pef_item.configs</em>, <em>pef_item.layout_configs</em> and <em>pef_item.expression</em> field is often used as generic fields to provide values for properties not included in pef_item fields. The easiest way to learn about components\' properties is to investigate examples. For detailed information about a component, see the relevant documentation:</p><p><strong>ExtJs:Â </strong><a href="http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/4.2.2">http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/4.2.2</a></p><p><strong>Angular (Ng Material):</strong>Â <a href="https://material.angularjs.org/latest">https://material.angularjs.org/latest</a>Â (see Demos and Directive), <a href="https://docs.angularjs.org/api">https://docs.angularjs.org/api</a></p><p><strong>Material Design:</strong>Â <a href="https://material.google.com/">https://material.google.com/</a>Â (also helpful for designing pages)</p><p><strong>Dropinbase examples:</strong>Â ~nav(dibexComponents)~</p><p>Dropinbase specific components areÂ described in more detail under the Components Reference section of the documentation.</p><p>The records in the ~nav(dibComponentGrid,Components table)~ reference files that define the components. The table can be edited to change/add components.</p><p>Most components\' names can be changed (if their related file names are changed as well) without any effect on the system. Exceptions are dockedItems and subcontainer.</p><p>Â </p><h2>Component Table Fields</h2><p>~docstable(pef_component)~</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc43-dib'),
    (45, 'Submission Data', 324, 80, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Many events that occur on the client, spawn requests to the server, which in most cases will include a parameter in the post data named submissionData. This provides a way of sending information in an associative array to the server which can be used in server-side functions.&#160;</p><p>See ~nav(dibexSubContainers)~ and ~nav(dibexEvents)~ for examples.&#160;</p><p>By default, values of all items with Aliases (the <i>item_alias </i>field = 1) on the current and parent containers are always included. Values of other items can be included on the container or item level, by using the <i>pef_container.configs</i> and<i> pef_item.configs</i> fields respectively.&#160;Note, names of items with aliases must consist of only alphanumeric characters and underscore (_) and exclude spaces.<br></p><p>To exclude an item that has an Alias from Submission Data, add \'dibIgnore\' as prefix to the item name, eg dibIgnoreBigTextField.</p><p>Practically any value from the user-interface (including hidden fields) can be submitted (developers of new components and dropins should ensure this). For grids, the values of all items with Aliases of the record that last had the focus, is submitted.&#160;</p><p>Specifying Submission Data in <i>configs</i> follows specific syntax rules (see below). The same rules apply when referencing client-interface items for other purposes, eg. specifying an item to disable, or container to refresh.</p><p>Example. The following may appear in a button\'s configs field:</p><pre><p>submitItemAlias : \'dibDatabaseForm, dibTableForm\',<br>submitCheckedItem : \'parent.containerMenuEvents\'</p></pre><p>The first line above will cause all items with Aliases on both the &#160;\'dibDatabaseForm\' and \'dibTableForm\' containers to submit their values (use a comma to separate multiple objects).<br>The second line assumes the current container is hosted inside a subcontainer where the parent container has another subcontainer with Alias \'containerMenuEvents\'. Primary key values of all checked/ticked records of the child grid in the containerMenuEvents subcontainer are submitted.</p><p>Submission Data can be specified on any item (eg buttons, dropdowns or subcontainer components) and on containers, using the <i>configs </i>fields. If specified on subcontainer<i> </i>components, the read request of the child container will include the Submission Data which can then be used in eg ~navdocs(Filters)~. Submission data specified on containers will be included in container-level events such as read requests. If specified on both a container, and the subcontainer component that contains it, then the union of both will be submitted (see ~nav(dibexSubContainers)~ and ~navdocs(Filters)~ for more info).</p><p>The values will be included in the post data of all requests originating from the item\'s events.&#160;In this case the post data for the button\'s click-event may look like this:</p><p><strong>submissionData : {&#34;submitItemAlias.self&#34;:{&#34;tester&#34;:&#34;21035&#34;},&#34;submitItemAlias.parent&#34;:{&#34;containerTree&#34;:{&#34;id&#34;:&#34;61021&#34;},&#34;containerFields&#34;:{&#34;id&#34;:&#34;61021&#34;},&#34;containerMenuEvents&#34;:{&#34;id&#34;:&#34;742&#34;}},&#34;submitItemId&#34;:&#34;29050&#34;,&#34;submitItemAlias.dibDatabaseForm&#34;:{&#34;id&#34;:12,&#34;tableRecords&#34;:null}<strong>,&#34;submitItemAlias.dibTableForm&#34;:{&#34;id&#34;:32}</strong>,&#34;submitCheckedItem.parent.containerMenuEvents&#34;:[{&#34;id&#34;:&#34;742&#34;},{&#34;id&#34;:&#34;743&#34;}]}</strong></p><p>Note the submissionData parameter in json format. It will be decoded as follows:</p><pre><p>Array(<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;[submitItemAlias.self] =&gt; Array(<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[tester] =&gt; 21035<br>&#160; &#160; )<br>&#160; &#160; [submitItemAlias.parent] =&gt; Array(<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[containerTree] = &#160;&gt; Array(<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[id] =&gt; 61021<br>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160; )<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[containerFields] =&gt; Array(<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[id] =&gt; 61021<br>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160; )<br>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160;[containerMenuEvents] =&gt; Array(<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[id] =&gt; 742<br>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160; )<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;)<br>&#160; &#160; [submitItemId] =&gt; 119768<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;[submitItemAlias.dibDatabaseForm] =&gt; Array(<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[id] =&gt; 12<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[tableRecords] =&gt;&#160;<br>&#160; &#160; )&#10;    [submitItemAlias.dibTableForm] =&gt; Array(&#10;&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[id] =&gt; 32&#10;&#160; &#160; )&#10;&#160;&#160; &#160;[submitCheckedItem.parent.containerMenuEvents] =&gt; Array(</p><p>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[0] =&gt; Array(<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[id] =&gt; 742<br>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160; )<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[1] =&gt; Array(<br>&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;&#160;&#160; &#160;[id] =&gt; 743<br>&#160; &#160; &#160; &#160; )<br>&#160; &#160; )<br>)</p></pre><p>By default, all the items with an Alias (<em>pef_item.item_alias</em>) on the current (&#34;<i>self</i>&#34;) container, as well as on the &#34;<i>parent</i>&#34; container are included. If the current container is not inside a child container component, then the parent will refer to the base container.&#160;</p><p><b>ExtJs only:</b> Another default is&#160;<i>submitItemId </i>which refers to the last user field (eg textbox, dropdowns etc. and not buttons) that had focus.&#160;</p><p>In the example above&#160;containerTree,&#160;containerFields and&#160;containerMenuEvents are all subcontainer components on the parent container. The primary key values of the current record inside each is included. An array is used to submit primary key values to allow for composite primary keys. The dibDatabaseForm container\'s two items with aliases are included as specifically requested by the button\'s configs, as well as the primary key values of the records the user has checked in the child grid inside the&#160;containerMenuEvents container component.</p><p>Note, null values are submitted as nulls and booleans as booleans (TRUE or FALSE), the rest (eg dates, all numeric values and strings) as strings.</p><p><em><strong>Developer Note:</strong></em></p><p><em>To view the URL requests, open the browser Console (F12) and refresh any page or activate eg a dropdown list. Experiment with the filter function to find a particular one. To view a more readable version of submissionData values click on the request\'s URL in the Network-tab (Chrome) and see the Request Payload section under Headers.</em></p><h2>Using Submission Data in PHP Functions</h2><p>The PHP controller function that is referenced by the event must have a parameter named $submissionData to receive the array of values. Using our example above, the individual values can be extracted as follows:</p><pre><p>$id = $submissionData[\'submitItemAlias.dibDatabaseForm\'][\'id\'];<br>$firstCheckedItemPrimaryKeyValue = $submissionData[\'submitCheckedItem.parent.containerMenuEvents\'][0][\'id\'];<br>$secondCheckedItemPrimaryKeyValue = $submissionData[\'submitCheckedItem.parent.containerMenuEvents\'][1][\'id\'];</p></pre><p>Note, loops and the <a href="http://php.net/manual/en/function.implode.php">PHP implode</a> function are useful when working with collections of values such as in&#160;submitCheckedItem.</p><p>Since we should always check for the existence of keys in an array and their associated values, the DibApp::getSubmitValue function comes in handy. It will automatically return NULL if a value is not set:</p><pre>// Testing single values&#10;// Note the abbreviations used: \'sIA.s\' means \'submitItemAlias.self\',  \'sIA.p\' means \'submitItemAlias.parent\',&#10;//    and \'sIA.\' translates to \'submitItemAlias.\'&#10;&#10;$tester = DibApp::getSubmitVal($submissionData, \'sIA.s\', \'tester\');&#10;$treeId = DibApp::getSubmitVal($submissionData, \'sIA.p\', \'containerTree\', \'id\');&#10;</pre><pre>// Testing many values. Here $missing will be NULL&#10;list($id, $tableRecords, $missing) = DibApp::getSubmitVal($submissionData, \'sIA.dibDatabaseForm\', array(\'id\', \'tableRecords\', \'missing\'));&#10;list($id, $missing) = DibApp::getSubmitVal($submissionData, \'submitCheckedItem.parent.containerMenuEvents\', 0, array(\'id\', \'missing\'));&#10;</pre><h2>Using Submission Data in Filters and dibHtmlTemplate</h2><p>Submission Data passed to CRUD classes for processing ~navdocs(Filters)~, and to the dibHtmlTemplate dropin for passing parameters to Eleutheria templates, are flattened by inserting underscores for each &#34;level&#34; in the array.</p><p>Example, the Submission Data in the array above will be available for use as:</p><pre><p>submitItemAlias_self_tester<br>submitItemAlias_parent_containerTree_id<br>submitItemAlias_parent_containerFields_id<br>submitItemAlias_parent_containerMenuEvents_id<br>submitItemId<br>submitItemAlias_dibDatabaseForm_id<br>submitItemAlias_dibDatabaseForm_tableRecords<br>submitCheckedItem_parent_containerMenuEvents_0_id<br>submitCheckedItem_parent_containerMenuEvents_1_id</p></pre><p>In Filters prefix the parameter with a colon (:), eg :submitItemAlias_self_tester &#160; and &#160; :submitCheckedItem_parent_containerMenuEvents_1_id. See ~navdocs(Filters)~ for more information.</p><p>In dibHtmlTemplate&#160;templates, the parameters are available as Eleutheria global variables. Access their contents by wrapping them with ^ characters, eg &#160;^submitItemAlias_self_tester^ &#160; and &#160;&#160;^submitCheckedItem_parent_containerMenuEvents_1_id^. Note, when used in SQL &#160;statements, it is highly recommended to make use of the Eleutheria param function to avoid SQL Injection, eg</p><pre>SELECT * FROM company WHERE id = ~fld($delim)~param(^submitItemAlias_parent_companyId^)~fld($delim)~.</pre><h2>Configuring Submission Data</h2><p>The name/first part (before the colon) defines the type of information that must be submitted, eg Item Alias values &#160;(submitItemAlias) or Checked Items (submitCheckedItem) in a grid or tree. The values part (after the colon) defines a&#160;reference to the container or child container (subcontainer component) to collect the information from, ie which grid or tree. To specify more than one container (or subcontainer), separate them with a comma within the single quotes. All the items (eg item aliases or checked items) on the <span>specified target&#160;</span>containers are submitted, never a single item\'s value. Note the single-quotes (\') surrounding the values in the examples are required. SubmissionData configs are separated with a comma.</p><p>~incldocs(incl_clientDataTable)~<br></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc45-dib'),
    (47, 'Criteria Evaluation', 28, 120, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The permission tables have Criteria fields which enables conditional permissions and business rules.<br>The criteria contained therein is&nbsp;either evaluated as part of the WHERE clause of a SQL query, or in the Dropinbase <strong>EvalCriteria </strong>class. <br>The ~navdocs(Criteria Evaluation,Criteria Evaluation Contexts,Criteria Evaluation Contexts)~ table below lists the context, how criteria is evaluated and which parameters are available.&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Criteria in the SQL WHERE Clause</h2>\n<p>The <em>Criteria </em>field in Container Permissions, and the <em>Update Criteria</em> field in Item Permissions are examples of criteria fields that allow SQL.</p>\n<p>Any valid SQL that can be included in the WHERE clause in the generated crud class can be executed, which makes this very powerful.</p>\n<p>In UPDATE and DELETE statements any field from the current container\'s table can be used in criteria (or else a nested SELECT statement can be used). In SELECT statements the specific container\'s table fields as well as the fields of the foreign tables that are referenced by foreign keys in the main table, are available.</p>\n<p>The foreign tables must however be referenced by their alias. The aliases can be viewed in the Designer under Container Details -&gt; View SQL. Alternatively, open the relevant CRUD PHP class (eg table_testForm_x1x.php) in the container\'s /dibCode folder and add a <strong>Log::w()</strong> statement where the actual UPDATE/DELETE is executed.</p>\n<p>Note to avoid potential ambiguity, it is best to always prefix fields with their table name or alias, eg test_company.id, test_company.website, &nbsp;test_user1000.name and test_user1000.email.</p>\n<p>All User and Dropinbase Parameters are available (see heading below)</p>\n<h3>Examples</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>test_company.website LIKE \'%.co.za%\' AND test_company.name &gt; \'M\' AND test_company.owner = :dibUser_username</li>\n<li>test_user.country = \'Brazil\' OR test_company1001.name &lt; \'M\' OR test_user.startDate &gt; :dibDate</li>\n<li>(test_user.country = (SELECT country FROM pef_setting WHERE default_country =1 LIMIT 1)) OR test_user.country IS NULL</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>The EvalCriteria Class</h2>\n<p>The <em>Criteria New </em>field in Container Permissions, and the <em>Read/Create/Update Criteria</em> field in Item Permissions makes use of the EvalCriteria class for the criteria evaluation.</p>\n<p>The following operators can be used in criteria: &lt; &nbsp; &lt;= &nbsp; = &nbsp; &gt; &nbsp; &gt;= &nbsp; &lt;&gt; &nbsp; !=&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;AND&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp; ( &nbsp; )&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; like&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; not like&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; is null&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; is not null&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Notes</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The like operator uses regular expressions with the PHP <strong>preg_match</strong> function. <br>There are many online tools, eg https://regex101.com. The official PHP reference is <a href="http://au2.php.net/manual/en/reference.pcre.pattern.syntax.php">here</a>.</li>\n<li>The &lt;&gt; and != &nbsp;operators both mean "is not equal to".</li>\n<li>Anything between single quotes (\') is seen as a string and is not evaluated in any way. Single quotes inside strings can be delimited with a backslash (\\), eg. \'Say \\\'got it!\\\'...\'.</li>\n<li>A colon is used to indicate a parameter name, eg :my_parameter. Since table field names containing eg spaces can be passed as parameters when evaluating permission criteria, the following syntax can also be used to delimit field names: <code>{:my field with spaces}</code>,&nbsp; eg <code>{:last name} &gt; \'M\'</code>. Using this syntax is safer since a field name can be the prefix of another field or parameter name.</li>\n<li>All User and Dropinbase Parameters (see below) are available.</li>\n<li>V<span style="font-size: 12pt;">ariable names are <span style="text-align: left; float: none;">case-sensitive</span>.</span></li>\n<li>Spaces are not always necessary unless it will cause ambiguity.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Examples</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>6 &gt; 3 AND (3&gt;4 OR (6 &gt;= 5) AND 7&lt;8)</li>\n<li>\'This is how to escape a single quote in a string \\\'hallo\\\' \' &lt; :notes</li>\n<li>\'a\'&lt;\'b\' and &nbsp;\'ef\'=\'e\'</li>\n<li>\'a\'&lt;\'b\'AND\'ef\'=\'ef\' and (5&gt;=6or(\'aa\' &lt; \'ab\'))</li>\n<li>1 = 1 and 2 &gt;= 2 AND 4 &gt; 1 AND \'aa\' != \'ab\' AND \'aa\' &lt;&gt; \'ag\'</li>\n<li>:dibDateTime &gt; \'2012-08-10 11:12:10\'</li>\n<li>:dibUser_user_type = \'admin\'&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>NOTE: in this example we assume that a field named user_type was made available in /configs/DibUserParams.php.</strong></em></li>\n<li>:firstname &gt;= \'John\' and {:lastname} &lt; \'r\'</li>\n<li>:date_joined IS NOT NULL OR {:my other field} is null</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>User and Dropinbase&nbsp;Parameters</h2>\n<p>The following special values are available as parameters and should not be enclosed with quotes:&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>:dibUser_xxx where xxx is any field in the user\'s session (see the&nbsp;<strong>/configs/DibUserParams.php</strong>&nbsp;file)</li>\n<li>:dibDateTime = current datetime on the server, eg \'2014-06-05 10:56:32\'</li>\n<li>:dibDate = current date on the server, eg \'2014-06-05\'</li>\n<li>:dibTime = current time on the server, eg \'10:56:32\'</li>\n<li>:dibIp = client\'s IP address, eg. \'196.34.234.55\'</li>\n<li>\n<div>\n<div>:dibUniqueId = cryptographic strong unique random number tied to a user session and set in Authenticator.php; never sent to the browser.\n</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\n<div>:dibSessionIdMd5 = md5(session_id())&nbsp; &nbsp;// md5 hashed PHP session id</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<!--StartFragment-->\n<h2 style="font-size: 30px;">Criteria Evaluation Contexts</h2>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Context</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Purpose</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Parameters Available and Notes</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Method</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Open Container Permissions<br><em>pef_perm_container.open_criteria</em></td>\n<td>Determines whether a container may be opened/loaded or not.</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>User and Dropinbase Parameters, eg :dibUser_perm_group</li>\n<li>More Info: ~navdocs(Container Permissions)~</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>EvalCriteria</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>Read/Update/Delete records in a Container<br><em>pef_perm_container.criteria</em></p>\n<p><em>* Note criteria_new below</em></p>\n</td>\n<td>Determines records that may be viewed, changed, or deleted in a specific container.</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>User and Dropinbase Parameters, eg :dibUser_perm_group</li>\n<li>Any criteria that can be added to the container\'s SQL SELECT statement when it is executed on the database server.</li>\n<li>More Info: ~navdocs(Container Permissions)~</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>SQL where clause</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Create and Change records in a Container&nbsp;-<em>pef_perm_container.criteria_new&nbsp;</em></td>\n<td>Determines whether the new values provided for a container\'s record is acceptable.</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>User and Dropinbase Parameters, eg :dibUser_perm_group</li>\n<li>The new values provided by the user for the container\'s table fields.</li>\n<li>Use :{...} to delimit field names with spaces or which can be the prefix of other field names or parameters, eg {:my field name} &gt; 10</li>\n<li>More Info: ~navdocs(Container Permissions)~</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>EvalCriteria</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Update (new data)/Read/Create fields linked to Items<br><em>pef_perm_item.criteria</em></td>\n<td>\n<p>Determines whether data for a specific item/field is valid when updating (new values) or creating records.</p>\n<p>Invalid values are set to NULL when data is read.</p>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>User and Dropinbase Parameters, eg :dibUser_perm_group</li>\n<li>The new values provided by the user for the container\'s table fields (<strong>update </strong>and <strong>create</strong> operations)</li>\n<li>Existing field values (<strong>read </strong>operation)</li>\n<li>Use :{...} to delimit field names with spaces or which can be the prefix of other field names or parameters, eg {:my field name} &gt; 10</li>\n<li>More Info: ~navdocs(Item Permissions)~</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>EvalCriteria</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Update fields (existing data) fields linked to Items<br><em>pef_perm_item.update_criteria</em></td>\n<td>Determines whether existing data for a specific item/field is valid when updating records.</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>User and Dropinbase Parameters, eg :dibUser_perm_group</li>\n<li>Any criteria that can be added to the container\'s SQL SELECT statement when it is executed on the database server.</li>\n<li>More Info: ~navdocs(Item Permissions)~</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>SQL Where clause</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Eleutheria templates</td>\n<td>Used in <strong>if-</strong>statements along with other functions and data to build customized reports and files.</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Parameter table (pef_param).</li>\n<li>Anything that is available within the context of the <strong>if</strong>-function</li>\n<li>Use single-quote (\') to surroud variables to avoid cases where criteria includes operators such as OR / AND / or / and</li>\n<li>Eg ~$delim~if(\'fld(name)\'&gt;M and \'fld(notes)\' = \'x or y\', true, false)~$delim~</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>EvalCriteria</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc47-dib'),
    (49, 'Adding Components', 39, 100, 0, 'eleutheria', '<div>Components are easy to add. The dependencies are as follows:</div><ul><li>Create a new record in <i>pef_component </i>(see ~navdocs(Table References, pef_component, pef_component)~ for details).</li><li>âCreate a template file with a .et.html extension for the new component, using the same name as in the <i>pef_component </i>table (without the file extension) eg myComponent.et.html.</li><ul><li>Start with a copy of an existing template that has similar functionality (see /dropins/setNgMaterial/dibGlobals/templates/includes/components).</li><li>Store the file in the dropin and subfolder indicated by the <i>pef_component_dropin_id </i>and <i>folder</i> fields.</li></ul><li>Refresh the ~nav(dibDesigner)~. The new component should be available under the chosen <i>category </i>of the component tree (alphabetically sorted).</li></ul><div><b>Notes:</b></div><p>The <i>include_file</i> field is used to include commonly used sections of attributes stored in /dibGlobals/templates/includes/sections/ for certain types of fields, eg buttons or layout components. Ensure all the attributes here apply before choosing them. If not, copy-paste the attributes you will need to the new template file.</p><p>The contents of dibConfig.et.html file should always be included, eg via another section, or directly by the new template (use the Eleutheria inclfile() function).</p><p><b>Extjs: </b>components that manage their own events, eg dropdownboxes, should not use the <i>include_file </i>field to include a file that already manages events (eg commonFieldAttributes).</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc49-dib'),
