    (54, 'startAction', 53, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The startAction JavaScript function can be used to call server-side controller functions. The example below is extracted (and slightly modified for demo purposes) from Â  /dropins/dibExamples/templates/testCompanyETReport.html. It calls the btnHelloWorld_click function in /dropins/dibExamples/controllers/EventsController.php with three parameter values (\'dibDesignerContainerHtml\', 1706, \'hello world\').</p><p><b>Example</b></p><p><b>HTML:</b></p><pre><p>&lt;html&gt;<br/>&lt;head&gt;<br/>Â  Â &lt;meta http-equiv=&#34;Content-Type&#34; content=&#34;text/html; charset=UTF-8&#34; /&gt;<br/>Â Â  &lt;title&gt;Container Design&lt;/title&gt;<br/>Â Â Â &lt;script type=&#34;text/JavaScript&#34; src=&#34;/files/dropins/setNgMaterial/dibAngular/src/js/core/shared/TemplateActions.js&#34;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</p><p>Â Â  ...</p><p>&lt;/head&gt;</p><p>&lt;body&gt;<br/>Â Â Â ...</p><p>Â  Â &lt;a style=&#34;color:#5BB0FF&#34; href=&#34;#&#34; onClick=&#34;common.startAction(\'/dropins/dibExamples/Events/btnHelloWorld_click/dibtestCompanyETReport/1706/hello%20world\');return false;&#34;&gt;My Test&lt;/a&gt;</p><p>Â  Â ...<br/>&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;</p></pre><p><strong>Comments:</strong></p><ul><li>Note the use of ;return=false; to prevent client-side exceptions.</li></ul><p><strong>PHP:</strong></p><pre><p>public function dibDesignerAddEventCont($containerName, $itemEventId, $anotherValue) {</p><p>   // $containerName =Â \'dibtestCompanyETReport\', Â  $itemEventId = 1706, Â  Â $anotherValue = \'hello world\'</p><p>}</p>&#10;</pre><h2>Security and Other Notes</h2><h3>Special Characters, Query Parameters</h3><p>We replaced the space in \'hello world\' above with its URL encoded equivalent, %20. Apart from merely being a syntax requirement (eg the use of &amp; could be interpreted by Dropinbase incorrectly as a delimiter in the query parameter list), special characters in parameter values can be unsafe and it is best to URL encode them. The ~$delim~encode(this, url, ...)~$delim~ Eleutheria function can help with this.Â </p><p>The example below assumes that our function has two additional query parameters namedÂ queryPar1 andÂ queryPar2:</p><p><strong>HTML:</strong> Â Â </p><pre>&lt;a style=&#34;color:#5BB0FF&#34; href=&#34;#&#34; onClick=&#34;common.startAction(\'/dropins/dibExamples/Events/btnHelloWorld_click/dibtestCompanyETReport/1706/~rawurlencode(hello world)~?queryPar1=~rawurlencode(fld(firstname))~&amp;queryPar2=~rawurlencode(fld(surname))~\');return false;&#34;&gt;Add Event&lt;/a&gt;</pre><p><strong>PHP:</strong></p><pre>public function dibDesignerAddEventCont($containerName, $itemEventId, $anotherValue, $queryPar1, $queryPar2)</pre><p><b>More:</b></p><ul><li>http://stackoverflow.com/questions/497908/is-a-url-allowed-to-contain-a-space</li><li>http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/appendix/notes.html#h-B.2.2<br/></li></ul><h3>Enforcing Dropinbase Permissions</h3><p>The examples above use theÂ <strong>$containerName</strong> and <strong>$itemEventId</strong> parameters which will automatically be checked against the user\'s permissions. The $itemEventId parameter can be removed if permissions is required on only the container level. If not, a dummy item event record with id 1706 pointing to the same controller function will need to be created for one of the items belonging to the dibDesignerContainerHtml containerÂ otherwise the permission check will fail. Below is an example of the actual dummy item with its dummy item event that was created in the dibDesignerContainerHtmlÂ for this purpose:</p><p><strong><!--StartFragment--><b style="font-size: 14px;">testAction(183053)</b><br/></strong></p><table border="0" cellpadding="2"><tbody><tr><td>Component:</td><td>mdButton(134)</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td>Order No:</td><td>15</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td><br/></td><td><br/></td></tr><tr></tr></tbody></table><p><b style="font-size: 13px;">EventsÂ </b><br/></p><p><b></b></p><table cellpadding="3" border="1"><tbody><tr bgcolor="#3a79b3" style="color: white;text-align: center;font-size: 13px;"><td>Id</td><td>Trigger</td><td>Url</td><td>Refresh Alias</td><td>Response Type</td><td>Order#</td><td>Permgroups</td><td>LL Parent</td><td>LL Tag</td><td>LL Option</td><td>LL Activate</td><td>Template</td></tr><tr id="trrow" style="font-size: 12px;"><td>1706</td><td>click</td><td>/dropins/dibExamples/Events/btnHelloWorld_click</td><td></td><td>actions</td><td></td><td>x1x</td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr></tbody></table><p style="font-size: 13px;"><br/></p><p></p><h3>Validating parameter values</h3><p>Since hackers can pass malicious values, it is recommended to validate vulnerable parameters.</p><p><b>ExampleÂ </b></p><pre>if ($containerId != (string)(int)$containerId)<br/>    return $this-&gt;invalidResult(\'Error in request. Please contact the System Administrator.\');<br/>&#10;$sql = &#34;SELECT pef_table_id FROM pef_container WHERE id = <strong>$containerId</strong>&#34;; // NOTE use PDO parameters instead for string variables!&#10;</pre><h2>Getting Rid of the Hardcoded itemEventId</h2><p>In the examples above, 1706 was hardcoded for the itemEventId. When distributing your applications, you have no control over what primarkey value will be given to the item event record, which means the permission check will fail.Â </p><p>The easy solution is to generate a dibuid value for the item event record (use ~nav(dibShare)~ to generate values) and use this instead. The dibuid values are globally unique. Remember to recreate permission files in order to pick up the new value.</p><p>If your end-users will have access to the Dropinbase records that define the event, another solution is to use Eleutheria to lookup this value at runtime. The ~$delim~adddbval(...)~$delim~ function adds name-value pairs from a database query to the Eleutheria global array. These values can be accessed using the fld(...) function.Â </p><p>See the <b>HTML EVENTS</b>-tab on ~nav(dibexEvents)~, and the associated .html template for more info.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc54-dib'),
    (55, 'ajaxRequest', 53, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><b><i>ExtJs only... Angular version coming soon.</i></b></p><p>This function calls a server-side function which responds with TRUE or FALSE and responseData. If TRUE, then funcX(responseData) is called, where funcX is any JavaScript function and responseData is the data that is returned by the server-side function. If FALSE then another functionÂ is called in the same way.</p><p>ajaxRequest(urlString, paramsArray, JavaScriptFunctionOnTrue(responseData),Â JavaScriptFunctionOnFalse(responseData));</p><p>ExampleÂ </p><p>Ã¢â¬â¹&lt;a style=&#34;color:#5BB0FF&#34; href=&#34;#&#34; onClick=&#34;ajaxRequest(\'/dropins/test/Run/testAjaxRequest\', { \'par1\':5, \'par2\':\'hello world\'}, function (responseData) { updatemydataintemplate(responseData) }, function (responseData) { showerrormessage() } );&#34;&gt;Test Ajax Function&lt;/a&gt;</p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc55-dib'),
