    (58, 'Security', 28, 130, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>In a client-server application the main assets that need protection is the source code, the user accounts, the data and/or files that are kept on the server, and the ability of users to access that information.</p>\n<p>Security involves creating multiple defensive layers. Malicious activities, ranging from data theft to system sabotage, can take many forms (like the infamous case of a cleaner walking away with a company\'s server). Developing effective security measures requires not only adding the right layers of protection at every potential entry point but also gaining extensive experience in recognizing and mitigating risks.</p>\n<p>This discussion primarily focuses on implementing these security principles for Dropinbase applications. Applications that are publicly accessible, or where security or stable functioning is paramount (even behind firewalls), should involve a security expert. Further resources and links are available at the end of this article.</p>\n<p>The security of the Dropinbase core framework is an ongoing priority for the core team. We also periodically engage respected independent penetration testers to evaluate the framework. If you encounter any security issues within the core, we urge you to report them promptly by emailing&nbsp;<a href="mailto:security@dropinbase.com" target="_new">security@dropinbase.com</a>. To protect the wider community, refrain from publicly disclosing any security issues. We promise to address any concerns as soon as possible.</p>\n<p>Before deploying an application to production, consider the following checklist. Remember, this is not a comprehensive list, as each system has its own unique requirements. Again, for critical sites, it is crucial to involve developers who have a deep understanding of security considerations.</p>\n<h4>Usage Disclaimer</h4>\n<p>Please be aware that Dropinbase software is provided "AS IS," and using it is solely at your own risk - view the Licensing Agreement for more info. If you\'re not prepared to accept the inherent risks and responsibilities, we advise against using the software.</p>\n<h2>Security Checklist for Servers with Sensitive Data/Files</h2>\n<h3>Protocol</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Use HTTPS with TLS/SSL certificates to encrypt all communication on your site between client and server.</li>\n<li>This is especially important for sites that are available publicly and that allow users to login to access protected data. Unencrypted communication is wide open to hackers.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Webserver</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Run tests at&nbsp;<a href="https://observatory.mozilla.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://observatory.mozilla.org/</a></li>\n<li>Configure CSP rules that allows traffic over HTTPS only, and only from secure sites.</li>\n<li>Configure limits on the payload size of client requests to assist with preventing denial-of-service (DoS) attacks caused by extremely large requests.</li>\n<li>Set HTTP headers to enhance security against clickjacking, MIME-type sniffing, cross-site scripting and other security attacks.\n<ul>\n<li>X-Frame-Options</li>\n<li>X-Content-Type-Options</li>\n<li>X-XSS-Protection</li>\n<li>Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS)</li>\n<li>Referrer-Policy</li>\n<li>Permissions-Policy</li>\n<li>X-Permitted-Cross-Domain-Policies</li>\n<li>Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy (COOP)</li>\n<li>Clear-Site-Data</li>\n<li>Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy (COEP)</li>\n<li>Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy (CORP)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Disable any webserver modules that are not needed for your web server\'s functionality to minimize potential attack vectors.</li>\n<li>Adjust KeepAlive and Timeout settings to balance performance and security, helping mitigate slowloris-type attacks.</li>\n<li>Ensure that .php files are the only executable files that Apache can execute on the server.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>.htaccess</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>The /<strong>.htaccess</strong> file is used to redirect certain requests to certain PHP files, and block other requests.</li>\n<li>Since Dropinbase installations do not require&nbsp;<strong>.htaccess</strong> files in any subfolders, it is more secure to move these rules to the webserver\'s Virtual Host entry.</li>\n<li>If you\'ve made any changes to the rules as provided by Dropinbase, thoroughly test that web users cannot access restricted files/folders.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Firewalls</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Implement ModSecurity / Fortigate etc.</li>\n<li>Register the site with a Cloudflare account. The paid version is preferable.</li>\n<li>Implement Fail2Ban</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>File &amp; Folder Permissions</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>âPre-generate all&nbsp;<strong>dibCode&nbsp;</strong>files on the Staging server using ~nav(dibRelease)~ before copying over to Production.\n<ul>\n<li>Note, to generate all files, Dropinbase requires a login record for each possible permgroup.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Set folder permissions on Production to read-only on all<strong>&nbsp;</strong>folders except <strong>/runtime</strong>, and where users store files (eg the DIB::$USERPATH) if applicable.</li>\n<li>Set $CODEUSE in&nbsp;<strong>Dib.php</strong>&nbsp;to 3.\n<ul>\n<li>Alternatively (less secure) set $CODEUSE in&nbsp;<strong>Dib.php</strong>&nbsp;to 2 on the Production server which will cause any missing code files to be generated on the fly, but this requires write permissions to&nbsp;<strong>dibCode&nbsp;</strong>folders and to the active permission tables.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>See ~navdocs(File System Settings)~ for more info.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Database Security</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>~navdocs(Move the Login and Other Tables)~ (<em>pef_login,</em> <em>pef_login_group</em>, <em>pef_perm_group</em>, <em>pef_security_policy, pef_twofactor)&nbsp;</em>to a separate database (normally the user/data database), and configure $$LOGINDB in <strong>Dib.php</strong> accordingly.<br>Once moved, mark the Ignore-field under Database Tasks-&gt;Table Tasks so that they are never imported, an no editable user-interfaces are built for them.</li>\n<li>Move <em>pef_audit_trail ($AUDITDB, </em><em>pef_error_log ($ERRORLOGDB) and pef_sqllog ($SQLLOGDB) </em>to separate database(s) (may be the user/data database), and configure the following the indicated variables in&nbsp;<strong>Dib.php</strong> accordingly.</li>\n<li>Allow all database-server users to connect from localhost only.â</li>\n<li>Use the&nbsp;<strong>utf8mb4&nbsp;</strong>character set for all tables and fields so that comms between the browser, PHP and the database is consistent.</li>\n<li>Do not specify database users in <strong>Conn.php</strong> that have administrative rights, eg&nbsp;<strong>root&nbsp;</strong>(MySQL) or&nbsp;<strong>sa&nbsp;</strong>(SQL Server).\n<ul>\n<li>Create database users for the various databases, each having only the rights that are absolutely necessary.</li>\n<li>Once active permission records are generated and the tables in the first two steps above are moved, the Dropinbase database user requires no more than read-only rights.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Network and Server Security</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Always run the latest stable LTS versions of all software as far as possible, and keep operating systems updated with patches.</li>\n<li>Do not expose your servers to remote users unnecessarily. Use firewall settings to secure access, and block all unnecessary users, ports (eg database ports) and external IP\'s.</li>\n<li>âBy using the same server for your databases and the Apache web-server, you need not expose your databases to remote users. Everything can run from 127.0.0.1 (localhost) which is the simplest solution. Alternatively, separate virtual or physical servers on the same machine or network can be protected by a firewall from external users.</li>\n<li>Do not install unnecessary applications that could contain security flaws on your servers.</li>\n<li>Strong passwords should be used for all logins and for all applications used by developers.\n<ul>\n<li>Keep credentials safe, and change them periodically - especially when you suspect hacking attempts.</li>\n<li>Each user should have access to only the necessary and user-maintenance and accountability mechanisms must be in place.</li>\n<li>Use a service such as LastPass and/or store credentials with one or two characters changed/removed/added</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Authentication</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Implement two-factor authentication.</li>\n<li>âIf you have highly sensitive information on your production server, you could disable logins for admin users (users where <em>pef_login.admin_user</em> = 1 and perm_group = x1x), or any other user that has privileges to custom administrative containers. If you need one or more admin users, then ensure they have secure passwords and implement two-factor authentication for them.</li>\n<li>Use the settings available in the ~navdocs(pef_security_policy, docs, Security Policy Table)~ to tighten your security as far as possible.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Link logins to the correct Permission Groups and Security Policy records.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Container Permissions</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Review permissions granted to permission groups, especially the <strong>system_public </strong>login. See ~navdocs(Permissions Overview)~</li>\n<li>Check Login and Login Group expiry dates, and rebuild all active permissions.</li>\n<li>Do not give users access to edit Eleutheria templates. Eleutheria contains functions that can be used to read files and execute database queries.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>DIB and Example Containers and PHP</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>âUse the <strong>Remove/Secure DIB Containers</strong> facility on ~nav(dibRelease)~ to remove all DIB Admin and Example Containers</li>\n<ul>\n<li>Ensure that all containers are removed (check the <em>pef_container </em>table) except tmpl(ate) containers which are needed for creating new containers.</li>\n</ul>\n<li>Remove or rename the <strong>/dropins/dibExamples</strong> folder.</li>\n<li>Double check the list of all containers that the Public permission group has access to - is the access to all of them intended?</li>\n<ul>\n<li>Use a filter on ~nav(dibPermContainerGrid)~</li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<h3>Passwords, Keys and Other Sensitive Info</h3>\n<p>Never store any sensitive information in unsafe places like a repository or text files on your local pc. <br>Repositories get checked-out on various machines and once info is committed to it, it is not simple to remove the info from the history.<br>If your code requires passwords or keys, store them in files on the server (preferably outside the www folder) which are not comitted to the repository. Let your PHP read the file contents to obtain the information.<br>Also watch out for information in documentation that is shared or stored in the repository.<br>All developers must have their own secure passwords, and use password vaults, eg Bitwarden or LastPass. Passwords must be changed periodically.<br>Do not store passwords in applications, unless you store them with extra or removed characters.</p>\n<h3>PHP</h3>\n<p>The two most common security holes introduced in a Dropinbase application are the following:</p>\n<p><strong>Code Injection</strong></p>\n<p>Occurs when untrusted data is evaluated by an interpreter (like PHP, MySQL or JavaScript) as part of a command or query. <br>Properly sanitize all user-supplied input based on the context in which it is injected.</p>\n<p>For eg. SQL injection occurs when insecure PHP code injects information submitted by users directly into SQL statements.</p>\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Example:</span></p>\n<pre>$sql = "SELECT first_name FROM client WHERE id = " . $clientData[\'alias_self\'][\'id\'];</pre>\n<p>If <strong>$clientData[\'alias_self\'][\'id\'] </strong>contains the following, this code could be catastrophic:</p>\n<pre>3; DELETE FROM client;</pre>\n<p>Always validate values being used against a whitelist of secure types or characters, eg:</p>\n<pre>if(empty($clientData[\'alias_self\'][\'id\']) || !is_numeric($clientData[\'alias_self\'][\'id\'])<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; return $this-&gt;invalidResult("Please select an existing client and try gain");</pre>\n<p><strong>XSS Attacks</strong></p>\n<p>If information submitted by users is displayed to other users in iframes without any sanitizing, an hacker has the opportunity to inject malicious scripts.&nbsp;<br>Properly escape all user-supplied input based on the context in which it is displayed (e.g., HTML, JavaScript, CSS, URL, etc.).<br>Note that Dropinbase and Angular sanitizes/encodes text being injected into generated code by default (except \'unsafe\' components). Eleutheria HTML-encodes text injected through merge fields into HTML templates by default.</p>\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Example:</span></p>\n<p>The following code generates HTML that is displayed in an iframe container:</p>\n<pre>$sql = "SELECT first_name FROM person WHERE id = :id";<br>$rst = Database::fetch($sql, [\':id\'=&gt;3]);\n$html = \'&lt;span&gt;\' . $rst[\'first_name\'] . \'&lt;/span&gt;\';\nreturn $html;\n</pre>\n<p>A hacker could store the following in first_name:</p>\n<pre>&lt;a href="http://malicioussite.com/maliciouscode.js"&gt;Click Here&lt;/a&gt;</pre>\n<p>Any information that originates from users must be escaped or sanitized before displaying it to users in the browser. Angular escapes values automatically, so this vulnerability is specifically for iframe containers where data is not parsed by Angular.</p>\n<p>Note, Eleutheria escapes values in merge fields in iframes using the <strong>htmlspecialchars</strong> function. This is safe as long as merge fields are not used inside HTML tags, JavaScript or in CSS etc. <br>For example, the following is unsafe:</p>\n<pre>&lt;span ~mergefield~&gt;Hello&lt;/span&gt;</pre>\n<p><strong>General PHP Rules</strong></p>\n<p>It is impossible to block users from sending malicious engineered content to the server, since hackers can quite easily send ANY information or request. The code must ensure that potentially malicious content is handled in a secure fashion, given each context where it is consumed or injected. A golden rule to keep in mind is not to trust any information received from the client. The server-side code must treat everything as potentially malicious content and protect what must be protected. This often includes using a whitelist approach to ensure content falls within an expected scope that is safe, given how and where it is used.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>âNote, public functions in PHP controller classes, that do not have <strong>$containerName</strong> parameters will be publicly available! The parameter must not have a default value (eg <strong>$containerName=NULL</strong> is wrong!)\n<ul>\n<li>If you require finer security on event level, then also include the <strong>$itemEventId</strong> (for item-events) or <strong>$containerEventId</strong> (for container-events) parameters (without defaults).&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Validate all user-input. Ensure integer parameters do not contain text values and that text values are not used insecurely (eg made part of SQL statements). Ensure that other submitted values fall within permitted scopes.</li>\n<li>All information / documents sent between the client and server, and the server and the database must be encoded using UTF-8 (utf8mb4). This protocol should be used consistently to prohibit attacks (see http://htmlpurifier.org/docs/enduser-utf8.html). Use a modern utf8 (eg. utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci) character set for all tables and the database itself.</li>\n<!--StartFragment-->\n<li>Use whitelist methods to validate input where possible. Blacklists are more than often insecure.</li>\n<li>Avoid including unsanitized user-input in HTML in iframes (see above), or even in messages displayed by Angular. For eg rather say "The submitted value is invalid" than "The following value is invalid: xxx".&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Tools such as HTMLPurifier can be used to sanitize text before making it available to clients.</li>\n<li>Use the PHP <strong>extends </strong>functionality to extend Controller classes with caution, since all non-private functions in extended classes will become available through URL calls!</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Dib.php</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>$CLIENT_DEBUG_LEVEL = 0</li>\n<li>$ELEUTHERIA_DEBUG_LEVEL = 0</li>\n<li>$LOGPERMISSUES = 1 (helps with finding possible hacking attempts). Remember to backup/clear the log file periodically.</li>\n<li>$CODEUSE = 2 or 3 (ensures that design changes don\'t affect the application)</li>\n<li>Set&nbsp;$USERSPATH to a secure path outside your www folder. The webserver-user (eg www-data) user must have the desired permissions to it.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>$DESIGNER_CAN_READ_ERRORS = FALSE (for extra protection, to ensure hackers can\'t find sensitive info. You will need to read errors in the database/file)</li>\n<li>$DESIGNER_CAN_READ_DEBUG = FALSE (for extra protection, to ensure hackers can\'t find sensitive info. You will need to read debug info from the file)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>php.ini</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>session.cookie_secure: ensures that the browser only sends the session cookie in secure HTTPS requests (eg. when users type http://example.com instead of https://example.com).</li>\n<li>session.cookie_httponly: stops JavaScript from accessing the session cookie, preventing common XSS attacks.</li>\n<li>session.use_only_cookies: enabling this protects against Session Fixation attacks.</li>\n<li>session.use_trans_sid: disabling this also helps protect against Session Fixation attacks.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Phishing / Spoofing / Impersonation</h3>\n<p>Hackers often use phishing, spoofing or related methods. For example a hacker can adjust email headers to send an e-mail to you where the from-address is any address, for eg. the address of a trusted end-user or your team leader. So doing, they could request one of your team members via email to change passwords or expose secrets. Notify your team to always verify requests like these using another communication medium (eg a text message, if the request came through an e-mail). These methods have become very common and service providers are incorporating ways of blocking such attempts, but they are not all fail-safe. If your team members have access to sensitive information they must remain competent to discern these attacks, and be extra vigilent. With AI being able to impersonate voice and video, these attacks are becoming more difficult to discern.</p>\n<h3>Files</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>âSet the <strong>allowed_file_extensions </strong>and <strong>max_file_size </strong>values in the ~nav(dibFileSettingGrid)~ table, and link these to appropriate item records where file or image components are used.</li>\n<li>Limit the extensions that can be sent with <strong>/files/files</strong> or <strong>/files/dropins/</strong> requests in <strong>/configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>iframe</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>HTML documents must contain the following line in the &lt;head&gt; as the first line, to remain consistent with UTF8 encoding throughout:\n<ul>\n<li>\n<div>\n<div><code>&lt;meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=UTF-8" /&gt;</code></div>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Eleutheria HTML encodes merged fields in HTML templates by default using the <strong>htmlspecialchars </strong>function.&nbsp;The context where the fields are used may necessitate a different type of encoding. See the Eleutheria <strong>encode </strong>function for more info.</li>\n<li>If you are unsure, then rather create a Container Setting<em>&nbsp;</em>record (linked to the iframe container) where the name is \'HTMLPurifier\'. This will sanitize the whole document before outputting it, but may slow down performance and remove certain code or styling by mistake.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Links</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://www.owasp.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.owasp.org/</a></li>\n<li><a href="http://phpsecurity.readthedocs.io/en/latest/Input-Validation.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http://phpsecurity.readthedocs.io/en/latest/Input-Validation.html</a></li>\n<li><a href="http://htmlpurifier.org/docs/enduser-utf8.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http://htmlpurifier.org/docs/enduser-utf8.html</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://angular.io/guide/security" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://angular.io/guide/security</a></li>\n<li><a href="http://excess-xss.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http://excess-xss.com/</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.cyberciti.biz/tips/php-security-best-practices-tutorial.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.cyberciti.biz/tips/php-security-best-practices-tutorial.html</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>Dropinbase Security Features</h2>\n<h3><em>(This is not an extensive list)</em></h3>\n<h3>Authentication</h3>\n<p>Use two-factor authentication, especially for your admin users / developers.</p>\n<p>Allowed and required characters in usernames and passwords can be set in the configuration file (Dib.php) and the <em>pef_security_policy </em>table. Passwords are masked on entry.</p>\n<p>Many other related security policies can be set in <em>pef_security_policy</em>.</p>\n<p>Users are blocked progressively after various levels of unsuccessful authentication attempts.</p>\n<p>Changing of passwords / forgot password facility uses registered email addresses to confirm identity.</p>\n<p>Passwords can be set to expire.</p>\n<p>Allowed IP address ranges can be set (note, there is no fail-safe way of blocking hackers based on IP address).</p>\n<p>Passwords are stored as secure hashes (in the database), using the most secure available algorithm on the system (see help on the <strong>password_hash </strong>function in PHP).</p>\n<h3>User Privileges</h3>\n<p>Permission Groups are assigned specific permissions to containers(pages), items, events, records and fields.</p>\n<p>A users\' access to a Permission Group can be set to expire on a certain date/time, as well as the privileges of the Permission Group itself.</p>\n<p>Only users with \'<em>admin_user</em>\' rights in the <em>pef_login </em>table can perform certain restricted functions such as set permissions.</p>\n<h3>General</h3>\n<p>A user\'s IP address, browser details (User Agent) and a security token are stored at the time of login, and can (optionally) be checked with each subsequent request. <br>Any failed match will log them out. Note, certain request types such as GET does not allow for the security token to be checked. Note, the IP and User Agent checks an often lead to false-positives because of load-balancers and dynamic IP addresses etc, and can be disabled in Dib.php. The check for the security token is highly recommended, and can be disabled for a particular PHP function, by adding a parameter named <strong>$REQUEST_TYPE</strong> with default <strong>\'GET,POST,ignoretoken\'</strong>.</p>\n<p>Logins on the same account from different browsers can optionally cause all sessions to expire.</p>\n<p>Any change in a user\'s privileges prompts their PHP session to be regenerated.</p>\n<p>The request type (eg POST or GET) is checked with each request and can be blocked per function by editing the <strong>$REQUEST_TYPE</strong> defaults (see above).</p>\n<p>The system will attempt to find a matching controller function for any non-files request. If not found, an error is logged.</p>\n<p>All function calls are subject to container and event permissions, unless specifically disabled by including \'<strong>ignorecontainerperms</strong>\' in the <strong>$REQUEST_TYPE</strong> parameter defaults (see above).</p>\n<p>The structure of URL\'s need to follow strict rules else they are rejected.</p>\n<p>The Angular framework has built-in functions to prevent XSS and other client-side hacking attempts.</p>\n<p>PDO parameters are used consistently in all generated and system code to avoid any SQL injection.</p>\n<p>Any parameters or data that is passed to Dropinbase\'s generated CRUD classes are validated according to type and other configured rules. Note, text fields could be protected by using regular expressions for validation.</p>\n<p>HTTP headers are set to handle cache properly, allow only certain methods and avoid cross-origin requests (see Dib.php).</p>\n<p>Cryptographically secure random numbers are generated as reset keys for passwords etc.</p>\n<p>The PHP autoloader is restricted to a list of known classes.</p>\n<p>Static, public files are restriced to a whitelist of folders, file extensions and allowed characters.</p>\n<p>User file uploads and downloads are restricted to specific sizes and types (mime-type and extension type checking is done).</p>\n<p>User file uploads can be stored in folders outside the /www folder.</p>\n<p>Design functions are restricted by setting the $ENVIRONMENT variable in Dib.php to \'production\'.</p>\n<p>Viewing of error logs can be blocked on the production server, and errors can be logged to text files only.</p>\n<p>Debug messages are restricted by setting the various _DEBUG_LEVEL variables in Dib.php.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase can notify an admin user of any critical errors / attacks by setting $INFORM_ADMIN_ERRORLEVEL and $ADMIN_EMAIL in Dib.php appropriately and configuring /configs/Mail.php.</p>\n<p>The use of cached generated files can be forced in (set CODEUSE = 3) in Dib.php to prevent Dropinbase from ever generating files.</p>\n<p>Webserver and software versions and details are not exposed to hackers.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc58-dib'),
    (59, 'Permissions Overview', 23, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Permissions can be configured in Dropinbase to a very specific degree for both public and logged-in users on containers, items, records and events. The flexibility of the permission system is often used to implement business rules.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase strives to be secure by default, but it must be noted that developers can introduce vulnerabilities through custom code and configurations. For more information about securing your Dropinbase site properly, see ~navdocs(Security)~.</p>\n<h2>How Dropinbase Permissions Work</h2>\n<p>Administrators create Permission Groups and Login Accounts (Users) and link them together. See ~navdocs(Users and Permission Groups)~ for more info.</p>\n<p>Administrators assign ~navdocs(Container Permissions)~, ~navdocs(Item Permissions)~ and ~navdocs(Event Permissions)~ to these Permission Groups.<br>Note, if a certain user requires special permissions, then a new Permission Group must be created for them.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase combines the Permission Groups that each user belongs to into a ~navdocs(Permgroups, Permgroup)~. <br>For example if a user belongs to Permission Groups 4, 5 and 6 then their permgroup is x4x5x6x (id\'s in ascending order and enclosed by \'x\').<br>A user\'s permgroup is stored in the Login (<em>pef_login</em>) record, and also in their PHP user session when they authenticate.</p>\n<p>Based on this information, Dropinbase "compiles" the permissions that the distinct permgroups have into Active Permission Tables, using fast, fine-tuned SQL queries.<br>These records are stored using container-name and permgroup as search index, and contain all the information that Dropinbase requires at runtime to check permissions and perform other functions.<br>The contents of these records for a particular container is available in the Designer under Container Details -&gt; Active Permissions.</p>\n<p>Based on the information in the Active Permission Tables, Dropinbase generates user interface and server-side code specifically for each permgroup.&nbsp;<br>The files are stored in the dropin /dibCode folders, are suffixed with the permgroup name, and only contain code that the users of each&nbsp; permgroup may execute.</p>\n<p>At runtime, when a user loads a container or executes a function, the request always contains a $containerName parameter. <br>This name and the user\'s permgroup (and for events, also the request itself) is used to find the relevant stored Active Permission record.&nbsp;<br>The record contains the data to verify the request and for eg the path to the function that performs the request. <br>If it targets generated code that does not exist, the code is then generated on the fly.</p>\n<p>See ~navdocs(Permission Checks)~ for important details regarding what controls the permission checks.</p>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>It is simpler and cleaner to design your application with fixed roles where each role has certain rights and consists of perferably one permission group. <br>Allowing users to belong to a random collection of many permission groups leads to many permutations of Permgroups, and code is generated for each permutation used.</li>\n<li>Dropinbase allows one to share modules of code and design records with other installations. <br>This includes the ability to open containers from other suppliers of which the design records (and therefore permission records) are not available.<br>See ~navdocs(Distributing Module Dropins)~ for more info.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Record Renewal</h2>\n<p>When administrators make design changes, the information stored in the Active Permission Tables and the generated code may be outdated, leading to bugs or unexpected behaviour.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase manages the renewal process with certain rules, but it can also be manually done. See ~navdocs(Generating and Clearing Generated Code)~ for more info.</p>\n<p>The following actions are used to maintain the active permission records:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If the <em>pef_dropin.clear_code</em> field of a container\'s module dropin record is set, then Designer changes to a container causes these records (and <strong>/dibCode</strong> files) to be removed.</li>\n<li>If the the user is a developer (<em>pef_login.admin_user</em>=1), then the records are automatically created when the permission checks determine that they don\'t exist.</li>\n<li>They can be manually removed and recreated via the various buttons on the Designer.</li>\n<li>The records are all recreated, and other initialization tasks are performed, upon the first request after either the&nbsp;<strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> or <strong>/runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt</strong> file is removed.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Other Means of Securing Data</h2>\n<p>Instead of Dropinbase permissions for read operations, grids can be based on SQL statements with criteria in the WHERE-clauses such as:</p>\n<p><code>:dibUser_position IN (\'manager\', \'supervisor\') AND company_id&nbsp; = :dibUser_company_id</code></p>\n<p>Using SQL to limit data also applies to dropdown lists. See ~nav(dibexSqlParams, SQL Parameters)~ for more info.</p>\n<p>Complex business logic can be accomplished by using ~nav(dibexSqlParamsPhp, PHP Parameters)~. <br>This is useful and and convenient to maintain where the same logic needs to be applied to multiple SQL statements/grids.</p>\n<p>Other methods include using servers-side ~nav(dibexEventBasics, Table and Container Events)~.</p>\n<p>Note, criteria specified in ~navdocs(Filters on Containers and Dropdowns)~ is not secure, since the filter is activated from the client-side.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, '', 'doc59-dib'),
    (61, 'Permgroups', 23, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Although used internally only, it is important to understand the concept of Permgroups as all processes are executed against them. <br>A user\'s Permgroup consists of the collection of unique permission groups that they belong to.&nbsp;<br>Eg should a user belong to permission groups with id\'s 2, 4 and 7 then the user\'s Permgroup would be x2x4x7x (id\'s in ascending order and enclosed by \'x\').</p>\n<p>Dropinbase "compiles" the permissions specified in the Designer (and other data) and stores the information in Active Permission Tables (see ~navdocs(Permissions Overview)~.<br>Dropinbase generates client- and server-side code (on the fly when it is requested) that is specific (custom) and optimized for each Permgroup, based on this information.<br>The files are stored in the /dibCode folder and file names are suffixed with the permgroup.</p>\n<p>When any request is sent to the server, the Active Permission Tables are queried to verify the request, all based on the Permgroup.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>When permissions change, then the information in the permission temp tables and affected cached files need to be manually regenerated to activate the new permissions. If permissions expire, the affected information and files will automatically be regenerated. This design greatly improves system performance, but also provides a means of delaying activation while configuring permissions.</p>\n<p>Let\'s use an example. Say</p>\n<ul>\n<li>login A belongs to 3 permission groups with id\'s (primary key values) 1, 2, 3 and 4</li>\n<li>login B belongs to 2 and 3</li>\n<li>login C belongs to 1 and 3</li>\n<li>login D belongs to 3 only</li>\n<li>login E belongs to the same groups as login B</li>\n<li>login F belongs to the same groups as login A</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If all the records are still active (the current server time is within the start and expiry dates) the following distinct permgroups will exist:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>x1x2x3x4x</li>\n<li>x2x3x</li>\n<li>x1x3x</li>\n<li>x3x</li>\n</ul>\n<p>And given that:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Permission group 1 can open a container when criteria X is true</li>\n<li>Permission group 3 can open it when criteria Y is true</li>\n<li>Permission group 2 can always open it</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Then the <em>pef_perm_active </em>table will have the following 4 entries against this container in the "Open" column:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>x1x3x : X or Y <em>(ie test whether condition X or Y is true before allowing the container to be opened)</em></li>\n<li>x3x : Y</li>\n<li>x1x2x3x4x: &nbsp;*&nbsp;<em>(indication that it is always true, since permission group 2 is part of the group and can always open it)</em></li>\n<li>x2x3x: *</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If permission group 2 expires, then if any user logs in that belongs to this permission group, the Active Permission records will automatically be updated to the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>x1x3x : X or Y</li>\n<li>x3x : Y</li>\n<li>x1x3x4x : X or Y</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>More Information:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>~navdocs(pef_perm_active, table)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(pef_perm_field_active, table)~</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc61-dib'),
    (62, 'Auto-generated Files', 324, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>While developing, set $CODEUSE=0 in the /configs/Dib.php file, to force /cache/*.* files to be recreated with every request. A value of 1 recreates only those files that are affected by design changes, which increases performance but some changes may slip through the auto-generator. Files in /crud folders are not recreated with every request. See ~navdocs(Permissions Overview)~ for more info about cached permission files and the need to recreate them.</p><p>The following files are created against each Permgroup.</p><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><strong>File Type</strong></td><td><strong>Folder</strong></td><td><strong>Notes</strong></td><td><strong>Examples</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Client-side files</td><td>/<strong>cache</strong></td><td>Client-side user-interface files, controllers, models, stores, etc.</td><td>dibItemForm_cxx1xx.txt <em>(the \'controller\' file for Permgroup x1x)</em></td></tr><tr><td>Lazy-loaded tabs</td><td>/<strong>cache</strong></td><td>Client-side tab components that host containers that are loaded.</td><td><p>lazyLoad_ci_dibDesigner21958xx1xx.txt<br/><em>(the tab for item 21958 for Permgroup x1x)</em></p></td></tr><tr><td>Other client-side info</td><td>/<strong>cache</strong></td><td>Client-side information used in certain Dropins types, eg. charts</td><td>JIUAXDD.txt</td></tr><tr><td>Container permission files</td><td>/<strong>permFiles</strong></td><td><p>List of permitted containers and related info frequently needed by the system.</p></td><td>_Containersxx1xx.php</td></tr><tr><td>Dropdown and other list permission files</td><td>/<strong>permFiles</strong></td><td><p>List of permitted dropdown items.</p></td><td>_Listsxx1xx.php</td></tr><tr><td>Container and item event permission files</td><td>/<strong>permFiles</strong></td><td>List of permitted container and item events</td><td>_ContainerEventsxx1xx.php<br/>_ItemEventsxx1xx.php</td></tr><tr><td>Table CRUD files</td><td>/<strong>crud</strong></td><td>CRUD actions for a table-based grid/form container.</td><td>Tablexx1xxtestCompanyForm.phpÂ <em>(file reading data from a table for container named \'testCompanyForm\' and Permgroup x1x)</em></td></tr><tr><td>SQL read file</td><td>/<strong>crud</strong></td><td>Reading of records for a sql-based grid container eg reports. The sql statement is defined in theÂ ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Sql,pef_sql)~ table.</td><td>Sqlxx1xxaaaf.phpÂ <em>(file reading data from a SQL statement for container named \'aaaf\' and Permgroup x1x)</em></td></tr><tr><td>Table component lists</td><td>/<strong>crud</strong></td><td>Reading lists based on tables. Used in eg dropdown lists. Each file is for a specific table and returns only that table\'s list.Â </td><td>Lxx1xxTable1442.php <em>(the list file for Permgroup x1x for table with id 1442)</em></td></tr><tr><td>SQL component lists</td><td>/<strong>crud</strong></td><td>Reading lists based on records in the ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Sql,pef_sql)~ table. Used in eg dropdown-lists. Each file is for a specific query and returns only that query\'s list.</td><td>Lxx1xxSql_qsItems.phpÂ <em>(the list file for Permgroup x1x for the query named qsItems)</em></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc62-dib'),
    (65, 'Relationships - Foreign Keys', 324, 110, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The relationships between tables that maintain referential integrity between primary key and foreign key values, are stored in the ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Table Foreign Keys (pef_table_fk),pef_table_fk)~ andÂ ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Foreign Keys (pef_fk),pef_fk)~ tables.Â </p><p>The information in these tables are frequently used when generating code and Item records, eg:</p><ul><li>Master-child relationships in ~navdocs(Filters)~</li><li>Navigation buttons next to dropdowns on forms and grids</li><li>Creating SQL joins to obtain display field values for dropdowns based on foreign keys</li></ul><p>Whenever actions on the ~nav(dibDatabaseForm,Databases)~ form are used that affect the relationships, the relevant records are re-created.</p><p>Future versions of Dropinbase will be capable of maintaining the referential integrity in code, without the need for configuring foreign keys in the database.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc65-dib'),
    (67, 'Containers', 52, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>As mentioned in ~navdocs(Basic Building Blocks)~ (it is recommended to read this article before continuing), a Dropinbase application is basically constructed from different types of containers (eg. forms, grids, charts, HTML templates, etc) stored in the ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Container Table,pef_container)~. An application always has one or more &#34;base containers&#34; that have menus or search facilities etc from where other containers can be loaded. Containers can be based on tables or queries from various databases. The menus, fields, buttons, tabpanels, etc. on containers are items stored in the pef_item table.</p><p>Other containers are added to the system by one of the following means:</p><ol><li>~navdocs(Generating Containers using Design Templates,Importing Tables)~ using the ~nav(dibDatabaseGrid,Databases container)~</li><li>Duplicating and changing existing containers and their items by using the Tools, Duplicate menu option on the ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~.</li><li>Creating records manually in pef_container, pef_item, pef_item_settings, etc.</li><li>Activating module Dropins (feature not yet available - coming soon).</li></ol><p>See ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Container Table,pef_container)~ for more information about fields in pef_container.</p><h2>Container Types</h2><p>The various types of containers are defined in the pef_dropin table, where the dropin_type field is \'container\', \'form container\' or \'grid container\'.Â </p><h3><strong>Default Types</strong></h3><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Name</strong></td><td><strong>Type</strong></td><td><strong>Description</strong></td></tr><tr><td>dibForm</td><td>form container</td><td>The default dropin used for Form containers when tables are imported into the application. Used mostly for a container based on a table (ie the <em>pef_table_id </em>field in pef_container is filled in) for CRUD (create, read, update, delete) purposes of records in a form layout.</td></tr><tr><td>dibContainer</td><td>form container</td><td>A \'light-weight\', form-type container used for any purpose and most often when CRUD actions of records are not required, although its child-containers can have CRUD actions and be filtered based on values of its items.</td></tr><tr><td>dibGrid</td><td>grid container</td><td>The default dropin used for Grid containersÂ when tables are imported into the application. Used mostly for a container based on a table (ie theÂ <em>pef_table_idÂ </em>field in pef_container is filled in) for CRUD purposes of records in a grid layout.</td></tr><tr><td>dibGridTree</td><td>gridÂ container</td><td>Displays records from a table or sql statement in a editable gridtree layout. Dropinbase generates a CRUD class that reads and maintains (if a table is used) records.</td></tr><tr><td>dibPage</td><td>container</td><td>Displays a webpage defined by the URL in the <em>template </em>field of pef_container.</td></tr><tr><td>dibGoogleMap</td><td>container</td><td>Displays a Google map with markers from a sql statement that returns longitude, lattitude and other information.</td></tr><tr><td>dibHighChart (ExtJs)</td><td>container</td><td>Display various types of charts using HighCharts (www.highcharts.com).Â </td></tr><tr><td>dibHTMLTemplate</td><td>container</td><td>Builds an HTML document using an Eleutheria template.</td></tr><tr><td>dibTree</td><td>container</td><td>Displays information in a tree. Note, a developer needs to create code to read and/or maintain records (can copy and change existing code). Unlike dibGridTree, Dropinbase does not generate the code since implementations vary greatly.</td></tr><tr><td>dibHelp (ExtJs - Angular uses dibContainer)</td><td>container</td><td>The dropin used by Dropinbase Docs. It can be used for any other purpose as well.</td></tr></tbody></table><h2>Container Settings</h2><p>The ~navdocs(Tables Reference,Container Settings Table,pef_container_setting)~ is used by the certain container dropins to provide additional information that is not stored in pef_container fields.</p><p>For more information about the available settings for each dropin, see eg ~navdocs(dibForm)~.</p><h2>Child Containers</h2><p>The subcontainer component is used to host other containers that are loaded with the primary/parent container. Any type of container can be hosted in subcontainers. The documention refers to the hosted containers as &#34;child containers&#34;.Â </p><p>Most container types also support filters. By adding a ~navdocs(Filters,Filter)~ and ~navdocs(Submission Data)~ to the subcontainer-component the information displayed in the child container can be filtered based on values from the parent or other container. Filters are often used to implement a typical master-child form scenario, eg a Client form with a child-grid displaying Sales. The data in a child container is automically refreshed whenever the user navigates to another record on the parent form.</p><h2>More Info</h2><p>~navdocs(Filters)~<br/>~navdocs(Permissions Overview)~<br/>~navdocs(Container Dropins)~</p><p>Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc67-dib'),
    (68, 'Items', 52, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Container dropins (eg dibForm) can make use of the items table for various purposes, but mostly it is to configure the components and layout of a the containers. Each item has a certain ~navdocs(Components,component type)~, which determines its characteristics.Â Â </p><p>The fields in the pef_item table cover the most common configurations (eg is_visible, caption, etc). The <i>configs </i>andÂ <em>layout_configs</em>Â fields are used generically and differ slightly in use between ExtJs and Angular implementations (see below).</p><p>The pef_item_setting table is often used by dropins to provide additional funtionality. Refer to the the relevant Dropin\'s documentation for more detail.</p><p>The items table has the following fields:</p><p>~docstable(pef_item)~</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc68-dib'),
    (71, 'Base Containers', 28, 5, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>"Base containers" in Dropinbase refer to containers that load first, and which can possibly contain or "host" other containers. An application can have multiple base containers, and if loaded in the same browser tab, they will replace one another.</p>\n<p>Any container can be a "base container" - it simply needs a Port record where the&nbsp;<em>pef_item_id</em> field is blank. Whenever such a Port is activated (for eg via a URL or click events), the system will reload the contents of the browser-tab. <br>Other containers are loaded into the base container using Port records where the <em>pef_item_id</em> field references items (eg tabs) in the base container, or one another.</p>\n<p>An application\'s base container normally has a logo, a menu, a logout button etc. It also has one or more tab-panels or layout items that act as port items to host containers. <br>Dropinbase ships with templates for base containers (eg tmplBase1 and tmplBase2). You can edit their design but note that certain items and names are required to make the Application Wizard work.</p>\n<p>The pef_login table has a&nbsp;<em>default_url</em> field which determines the first container that is loaded when a user logs in successfully. This need not be a base container. Dropinbase will automatically load all parent containers up to the base container as needed.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc71-dib'),
    (72, 'Ports', 28, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Ports are records attached to containers which define where containers are attached in the user-interface when they are dynamicaly loaded (~navdocs(Ports and Subcontainers, docs, more info in examples)~).&nbsp;<br>Port records have a&nbsp;<em>pef_container_id </em>identifying the container, a <em>pef_item_id </em>that references the<em> port item</em> (eg a <em>div</em>) that will host the container, and a <em>port_alias </em>field that is used in the URL to identify secondary ports.&nbsp;<br>A port\'s&nbsp;<em>pef_item_id&nbsp;</em>field can point to any item that can accept child items, eg. <strong>div</strong>, <strong>row</strong>, <strong>column</strong>, <strong>card</strong>, <strong>section </strong>etc. <br>If the container that is loaded is used as the tab, the container\'s&nbsp;<em>caption </em>replaces the tab\'s <em>caption.&nbsp;</em>If the Port record\'s <em>caption </em>field is not empty, it will override this value.</p>\n<p>A container can have more than one port record, linking it to various port items. In other words, a specific container can be re-used. It can be attached to more than one place in the user interface, even at the same time, and each instance will function independantly.</p>\n<p>The <em>port_alias&nbsp;</em>field is used in the URL to distinguish which port to implement. Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>/nav/dibexEventBasics/own</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;- opens the dibexEventBasics container using the port record where the <em>port_alias</em> field is \'own\'. Here dibexEventBasics is loaded as its own base container.</li>\n<li><strong>/nav/dibDesigner or /nav/dibDesigner/main</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;- opens the dibDesigner container using the default/main port record where the <em>port_alias</em> field is \'main\'. Here dibexEventBasics is loaded inside another container (dibAdmin).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Since base containers are not loaded in other containers, the <em>pef_item_id </em>field of a least one of a base container\'s port records must be \'main\'.<br>When this port is used to open the base container, it loads directly into the browser tab instead of in another parent container.&nbsp;<br>Another means (for developers) of forcing a container to open as a base container is to use the <strong>?loadAsViewPort=1 </strong>parameter in the url, eg <strong>/nav/dibDatabaseForm?loadAsViewPort=1</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Note, the&nbsp;<em>pef_item_id&nbsp;</em>field in a port record need not point to an item on a base container, it can point to a port item on <strong>any </strong>container.</p>\n<p>Use the&nbsp;<strong>Add Port&nbsp;</strong>link under Container Details on ~nav(dibDesigner)~ to create port records.</p>\n<h2>How Containers are Loaded</h2>\n<p>When a user refreshes the application, or clicks a button etc., the browser\'s URL or the port record linked to the button identifies which port record to activate.&nbsp;<br>For eg. <strong>/nav/myContainer/myAlias</strong> loads the <strong>myContainer </strong>container using this container\'s port record identified by&nbsp;<strong>myAlias</strong>.</p>\n<p>First a <strong>/peff/Container/getPortInfo </strong>request is made to verify if the user may open the container, and to fetch the name of the parent container (referenced by the <strong>Port Item</strong>) and other information like the caption etc.</p>\n<p>If the parent container is not loaded already, another <strong>/peff/Container/getPortInfo</strong> request is made using the \'<strong>main</strong>\' Port Alias. This implies that parent containers must always have a \'main\' port record. <br>This request is repeated until a parent container is found which is already loaded, or a base container which has no Port Item is found.</p>\n<p>The UI code for parent containers is then loaded in order, and finally the requested container is loaded.</p>\n<h2>Override Port Info</h2>\n<p>The information returned by port records can also be dynamicaly updated. This means a container\'s position and configuration can be determined at runtime.<br>For more info, see the help linked to the <em>port_override </em>field in the Designer.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc72-dib'),
    (76, 'Tooltips', 52, 70, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><b>ExtJs only. </b>Note, this feature is still in Beta. Tooltips are popup notices that appear when a container is loaded or the mouse moves over certain items. The main ~nav(dashboard)~ has tooltips that track the mouse\'s movement over icons. Tooltips are always anchored to items, and useful for providing more information or help about the items or their hosting container. Use the link on the Item Overview on ~nav(dibDesigner)~, or the ~nav(dibTooltipGrid)~ to configure a tooltip for a particular item.</p><p>Another useful feature about tooltips is the ability to configure a &#34;Next&#34; button that will display the next tooltip and load its container if necessary. Using the button a &#34;walk through&#34; presentation can be configured for users.</p><p>The tooltip table has the following fields:</p><p>~docstable(pef_tooltip)~</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc76-dib'),
    (77, 'dibContainer', 4, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>dibContainer lacks the events to view, save, add and delete records, but can contain components that have their own controllers eg dropdowns.</p>\n\n<p>To avoid unexpected behaviour, it is important to specify a layout for the container using pef_container_setting, eg layout = &#39;border&#39; or &#39;vbox&#39;.</p>\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc77-dib'),
    (78, 'Navigation and Menus', 28, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Navigation</h2>\n<h4>Using Ports</h4>\n<p>An items <em>Port </em>field (<em>pef_item.pef_port_id)</em> can be set on dropdowns, layout components that are used as tabs (eg row, section, div), and the various "navigation" components (eg button, icon or menu components). <br>When the user clicks the item it will open the container using the specified port. Use the <em>expression</em> field to optionally specify query parameters, eg <strong>?record=first</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Ports are often set on tabs to load containers inside them. <br>When ports are configured on dropdowns (in grids or forms) that are based on fields with a foreign-key relationship, a navigation button is added which opens a blank record when the dropdown is empty, or the specific record when it has a value.</p>\n<h4>Using the Expression field</h4>\n<p>A URL can be specified in the&nbsp;<em>pef_item.expression</em> field of button components to target a container. Note this implies maintenance issues when container names change, which makes ports preferable. The URL can contain query parameters, eg <strong>/nav/dibItemForm?primary_id=10</strong>.</p>\n\n<h4>Notes</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>To open a container in a new browser tab, provide a value for&nbsp;<em>pef_item.pef_port_id </em>and make the <em>expression </em>field = \'_blank;\' (exclude the single quotes), OR use an expression of the following form: \'_blank;http://www.space.com\'</li>\n<li>The <em>largeIcon</em> component is useful for creating dashboards (see eg ~nav(dibDashboard)~).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>See ~nav(dibexNavigation)~ for more info.</p>\n\n<h2>Menus</h2>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexSideNavMenu)~ and ~nav(dibexComponentsButtons)~</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc78-dib'),
    (79, 'dibMenu', 80, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Configuration</h2><h4>Angular</h4><p>Add a <i>sideNavMenu</i> item anywhere on the container. Add a <i>contentFor</i> item to it as child and name it <b>menuItems</b>. Build the menu\'s tree structure below <b>menuItems</b> using <i>SideNavMenuNode</i> components.</p><h4>ExtJs</h4><p>Add the <i>menu</i> component as child item of the <i>tabpanel</i> component. Then use the <i>menunode</i> component as child-items thereof to create a tree-structure resembling your menu.</p><p>---</p><p>Use the node\'s <i>caption</i> fields to set captions.</p><p>Navigation is configured on each node item by</p><ul><li>setting the <i>pef_item.pef_port_id</i> field with optional query parameters in the <i>expression</i> field (eg ?record=last)</li><li>setting the <i>expression</i> field, eg<b> /nav/dibItemForm?record=first</b></li><li>attaching an event in <i>pef_item_event</i></li></ul><p>See ~navdocs(Navigation and Menus)~ for more info.</p><h2>Customizing Menus for Permgroups</h2><p>The root of the visible menu is by default set to the <i>contentFor</i> (Angular) orÂ <i>menu</i>Â (ExtJs) item\'s id. It can be changed to any of the child node<em> </em>components per permgroup, by adding records to the <i>pef_item_setting</i> table as follows:</p><ul><li><i>setting_type</i> = rootMenuId</li><li><i>pef_item_id</i> = must reference the <i>sideNavMenu</i> (Angular) or <i>menu</i> (ExtJs) item.</li><li><i>name</i> = [name of the menu nodeÂ item, eg <b>mnuFruit</b>]</li><li><i>value</i> Â = [set to % for all, or provide a permgroup, eg x2x. The latter option will force this root menu only for the specified permgroup]</li><ul><li>Note, <i>value</i>Â is used with the SQL LIKE operator, and can therefore use the <b>%</b> and <b>_</b> wild-card characters to specify eligible permgroups, eg <b>x2x%x</b> or <b>x_x3x%</b> etc.</li></ul></ul><p>If <i>value</i>Â in any of the records (where <i>setting_type</i> is rootMenuId) does not match the current permgroup, then the default root is used.</p><p>Be careful to construct criteria in such a way that each permgroup returns only one possibility. For eg, if <i>value</i> is set to <b>%</b>, then you should only have one record since this covers all possibilities.</p><p>Alternatively, addÂ item permissions to menu node items.</p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc79-dib'),
    (80, 'Component Dropins', 42, 30, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc80-dib'),
    (81, 'dibGlobalSearch', 4, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><b>(ExtJs only)</b><span id="selectionBoundary_1500006116850_6894130336210624" class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span></p><p><span id="selectionBoundary_1500006116849_2517707322856362" class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span>Every entry must have a port and port2 and user must have open permissions to both containers.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc81-dib'),
    (82, 'iframe', 4, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>A container dropin most often used for reporting or dashboard displays. Either the contents of a specified HTML template can be merged and returned to the client, using the powerful Eleutheria engine, or a PHP class can be called to handle the request.Â </p><p>Drill down reports / pages can be built, and the HTML can contain special functions that enable Dropinbase features like lazyloading or the execution of server-side events. See ~nav(dibexContainerDropins)~ for examples.</p><p>Use the <i>pef_container.template</i> field to specify the operation:</p><h2>PHP Class</h2><p>If the path to a .php class is specified (eg /dropins/myDropin/components/myClass.php) then the <i>merge </i>function in the class is called statically. The function should be declared as follows:</p><pre>/**<br/>* Performs operations and echo\'s HTML content to the client<br/>* @param string $containerName<br/>* @param array $submissionData<br/>* @param string $activeFilter name of the activeFilter to apply (only applicable if the container is based on a table or SQL statement)<br/>* @param boolean $echoContent - whether content must be echo\'d to client or not<br/>* @return values depend on class...<br/>*/<br/>public static function merge ($containerName, $submissionData=null, $activeFilter=null, $echoContent=TRUE)<br/></pre><p>The dibHTMLTemplate TemplateController will call the /dropinbase/components/ContainerTemplate.php class which in turn will find the value in the containersÂ <i>templateÂ </i>field and call the above class. The parameters passed are exactly the same parameters as was sent to the ContainerTemplate.php class. Parameters are not processed as in the case of a .html file. If the container has any record sources (eg pef_table_id or pef_sql) etc, or if any filters apply, the developer\'s code should handle it.</p><h2>HTML Template</h2><p>In all other cases, the file is assumed to be a Eleutheria HTML template and the result of the merge is echo\'d to the client.Â </p><p>The<em> pef_container.pef_table_id</em> or <em>pef_container.pef_sql_id</em> field can be used to specify a main record source (on level 1) of the Eleutheria template, which will then also enable the use of ~navdocs(Filters)~ to be added to the main and/or child container. In this case the records can be processed in a loop in Eleutheria by means of the ~$delimdb~rsarr1;records~$delimdb~ domain directive (dibHtmlTemplate stores the rows from the record source in an array named \'records\' which it then passes on to Eleutheria for use in the template). In most cases it is simpler to specify a record source in the template itself using the conventional ~$delimdb~rssql1;...~$delimdb~ domain directive, and then filtering it with ~navdocs(Submission Data)~ from the client.</p><h3>Important: Security andÂ Submission Data</h3><h4>Valid Parameters</h4><p>As with any other programming language, inputs from the user must be handled with special care to avoid hacking.Â User data should always be treated as unsafe.Â Hackers can submit data containing executable code designed to exploit vulnerabilities in programs. Html templates is certainly an ideal place to insert harmful code since JavaScript, SQL and Eleutheria functions can be inserted maliciously. By default Dropinbase and Eleutheria takes many precautions to prevent harmful insertions, but there are certain loop holes that can only be avoided by being aware of the necessary measures.</p><p>Firstly, the Submission Data variables that must be passed on to the template must be explicitly identified. These variables are used as global variables that are replaced before any other template parsing is performed and can therefore contain Eleutheria functions. By allowing only certain global variables, the potential threats from Submission Data are isolated to where these variables are used. dibHtmlTemplate employs Eleutheria\'s globalsReplaceList to specify a regular expression defining a white list of allowed characters in global variables. The default expression isÂ &#34;#[^a-zA-Z0-9_ \\r\\n\\t]*#&#34; whichÂ will result in all characters being removed from global variables, except a-z, A-Z, underscore and space. The default can be overrided by specify a container setting record where name = globalsReplaceList and value is the regular expression. Eg. a value ofÂ #[~$delimdb~~$delim~]*# will act as blacklist to replace the default Eleutheria delim characters ~$delimdb~ and ~$delim~.</p><p>Specify the allowed Submission Data variables in <em>pef_container.valid_params</em>. Each variable must have a default (eg &#34;5&#34; or &#34;&#34;), or the value &#34;*required*&#34; which will prevent the template from being merged, unless Submission Data contains a value for the variable. Â If any required parameter is missing dibHtmlTemplate will return &#34;No content - check that required parameters have values.&#34; and if the current user has admin privileges the name of the parameter will be included.Â </p><p>The contents of <em>valid_params</em> must be provided as a list of json variables, eg</p><p>&#34;submitItemAlias_parent_InvoiceID&#34;:&#34;*required*&#34;, &#34;print&#34;:&#34;false&#34;</p><p>The other entry point for user data into Eleutheria templates is data stored in user tables that is used in merge variables. Eleutheria will always HTML encode any variables (globals, table data, session variables, etc) when merging them with a HTML template, which removes this risk.Â </p><p>Note, depending on the context (HTML, JavaScript, URLs, etc), text should be encoded appropriately. See the Eleutheria <i>encode </i>function for details.</p><p>In certain cases designers of templates need to include snippets of HTML in Eleutheria functions (eg an If-statement that conditionally displays one of two urls), in which case the encoding can be turned off by enclosing the text with [% ... %]. Â Always use these delimiters with care, making sure no user data is included. In other cases blocks of HTML (eg notes stored by users in HTML wysiwyg editors) need to be merged, in which case Html Purifier can be used (see section below).</p><h4>Avoiding SQL Injection</h4><p>Eleutheria has a special function namedÂ <em>param</em> that converts values to PDO parameters when running SQL statements.Â </p><p>See ~navdocs(param)~ for more information.</p><h4>Html Purifier</h4><p>Dropinbase contains the robust Html Purifier engine as an extension to ensure that the HTML sent to users is completely safe. Note, it does slow down performance, and should be used with the Eleutheria <b>encode </b>function to purify only specific user fields that may contain HTML (eg user notes stored in HTML).</p><p>Alternatively, HTMLPurifier can be used to purify the entire result before it is returned. To enable this, use a <i>pef_container_setting</i> with \'HtmlPurifier\' in <i>name </i>and \'true\' inÂ <i>value</i>.</p><p>Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc82-dib'),
    (83, 'Authentication', 28, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>With the first request made to a Dropinbase application, the user is automatically logged-in as the <strong>system_public </strong>user. As with any other user, the <strong>system_public\'s </strong>permissions are restricted to the permission groups it is linked to.</p>\n<p>After authentication via the login page, the user is redirected to the URL specified in the&nbsp;<em>pef_login.default_url </em>field, related to their account.</p>\n<p>If the <strong>system_public</strong>, or any other user, at any time navigates to a container that does not exist, or which is not permitted, they are also redirected to the URL specified in their <em>pef_login.default_url </em>field. By default, this url is set to <strong>/login</strong> which will open the login form. To specify a container, use <strong>/nav/CONTAINERNAME</strong> eg <strong>/nav/dashboard</strong>. Ensure that the user has rights to the container specified in this field. For the <strong>system_public </strong>user, this must be a publicly available container (eg <strong>/login</strong>).</p>\n<p>Ensure that all logins are linked to ~navdocs(pef_security_policy, table)~ records that are properly configured.</p>\n<p>See ~navdocs(pef_login,table)~ for more info.&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Changing Passwords</h3>\n<p>Users can use the Forget Password link on the login page to change their passwords.</p>\n<p><strong>Note</strong>, this facility sends emails which requires <strong>/configs/Mail.php</strong> settings, and that any firewalls allow the sending of mails on the relevant port.</p>\n<p>Administrators can also set passwords on ~nav(dibLoginForm)~ (icon is also on the Designer).</p>\n<p>Note, programmers with access to the <em>pef_login </em>table can copy-paste hash values in the <em>password </em>field.</p>\n<h3>Customizations and User Parameters</h3>\n<p>Any custom authentication logic can be added to the <strong>/configs/DibUserParams.php</strong> file. <br>This file has two purposes. It acts as the last layer of authentication checks before a user is allowed to sign in. It also defines an array of user session values that can be utilized in SQL code as parameters (eg. <code>payment.company_id = :dibUser_company_id</code>), filter and permission criteria (same as SQL criteria), and in PHP using eg.&nbsp; <code>DIB::$USER[\'company_id\']</code>.</p>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexSqlParams)~ for more info.</p>\n<p>The dibAuthenticate dropin contains user-interface and server-side code for authentication. To adjust the user-interface of the authentication pages (login, forgotmypassword, etc.) copy this dropin to <strong>/projectFolder/dropins/</strong> and alter the code in the <strong>/views</strong> subfolder.<br>Changes to the basic Dropinbase authentication logic can be made in <strong>/controllers/SiteController.php</strong> and <strong>/components/dibAuthenticate.php</strong>. Note, changes to the logic should be made by a security expert only.</p>\n<p>See ~navdocs(Customize Login and Authentication)~ for more info.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc83-dib'),
    (85, 'Origins of Dropinbase', 9, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The name \'Dropinbase\' was derived from the concepts of&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>a \'dropin\' replacement for legacy apps,</li>\n<li>the ability to \'drop\' the system on an existing database and have a functional application within minutes,</li>\n<li>plug-and-play shareable modules or "dropins".</li>\n</ul>\n<p>---</p>\n\n<p>The foundational architecture of Dropinbase is the result of over three decades dedicated to the development and deployment of database applications across a diverse spectrum of organizations and objectives. The strategic deployment of well-architected relational databases plays a pivotal role in structuring data and enhancing business operations, underscoring the essential nature of ERP/CRM systems within the core of thriving enterprises.</p>\n\n<p>However, a significant challenge presents itself in the implementation of these systems. According to <a href="https://www2.deloitte.com/mt/en/pages/technology/articles/erp-critical-factors-for-implementations.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">studies by Gartner and Deloitte</a>, there is an alarming failure rate of up to 90% in ERP/CRM system implementations. This underscores a critical gap in the realization of successful system integration and utilization within organizations.</p>\n\n<p>In response to this challenge, Dropinbase offers bespoke, leading-edge application solutions that facilitate substantial customizations with minimal effort. This approach is designed to markedly reduce the likelihood of your project aligning with the daunting statistics of failed implementations, ensuring a more successful integration and utilization of ERP/CRM systems.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc85-dib'),
    (86, 'Parameters', 324, 85, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>2b deprecated ???</h2>\n<p>The ~nav(dibParamGrid,Parameter table)~ provides a powerful, centralised and secure method to define and obtain values from a PHP function, SQL Statement, or directly from the Parameter table (in case of constant values). These values can then be used in the following contexts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>~navdocs(Filters )~</li>\n<li>Wherever the EvalCriteria function is used to evaluate criteria (see the Method column in ~navdocs(Criteria Evaluation)~)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Notes</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>To increase performance, parameter values are cached in /runtime/cache/params_DIB.dtxt. <strong>Remember to delete this file when changing parameter definitions.</strong></li>\n<li>SQL statements can contain parameter values themselves (constant, SQL or PHP). Ie they are resolved recursively and to any level. This is particularly useful if you have SQL statements that obtain values from other SQL statements.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Parameter Table (pef_param)</h2>\n<p>The Parameter table can be used to define values for parameters obtained from 3 different sources: SQL statements, PHP functions or constants. These parameters can be used in ~navdocs(Filters)~, and any criteria that makes use of the EvalCriteria class. See ~navdocs(Parameters)~ for more info.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>SQL Statements</h3>\n<p>The SQL statements can return more than one field, and can themselves use parameters returned by other SQL statements in the <em>pef_param</em> table. The parameters can be resolved in SQL statements to any recursive level, although recursive calls do slightly&nbsp;impede performance. Each field is prefixed with the parameter name using \'__\' as delimiter. Eg if the name field is \'testvar1\' and the SQL statement is:</p>\n<p>SELECT id, name, value FROM pef_setting WHERE setting_type=\'admin\' AND id &lt; :testvar4__lower;</p>\n<p>then the parameters that are exposed will be :testvar1__id, :testvar1__name and :testvar1__value. Note, if the SQL statement returns more than one record, only the first record will be used (the rest are ignored).&nbsp;</p>\n<p>~navtag(Criteria Evaluation Contexts)~</p>\n<h3>Constants</h3>\n<p>Single value constants that are replaced "as is" and are treated as strings. Note string values must not be enclosed in quotes.</p>\n<h3>PHP Functions</h3>\n<p>The&nbsp;<em>value&nbsp;</em>field in <em>pef_param</em> must contain the path to a PHP Controller class and function in a Dropin folder. Example:</p>\n<p>/dropins/test/run/testGetValue</p>\n<p>executes the function named testGetValue in the following PHP file: /dropins/test/controllers/RunController.php.</p>\n<p>The PHP function must be public and have one parameter which will contain the values of parameters resolved so far (use the order_no field to ensure dependant parameters are resolved last). The function must return an associative array if successful, and a numeric array if not of the following form: array(\'error\', \'The message to be displayed to the user...\'). &nbsp;The keys and values will be added to the other available parameters, after first prefixing the keys with the&nbsp;<em>pef_param.name</em>&nbsp;field using \'__\' as delimiter. If the&nbsp;<em>name&nbsp;</em>field in <em>pef_param </em>is say \'testvar4\' then the function below will add the following parameters and their values:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>:testvar4__lower = 1000 &nbsp;</li>\n<li>:testvar4__upper = 4000</li>\n</ul>\n<p>public function testGetValue($args) {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;if($args[\'testvar3__id\'] &lt; 550)<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;return array(\'error\',\'Invalid parameter values. Please try again.\');<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; else<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;return array(\'lower\'=&gt;1000, \'upper\'=&gt;4000);<br>}</p>\n<h2>Parameter Table Fields</h2>\n<p>~docstable(pef_param)~<br>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc86-dib'),
    (87, 'Executing Client Api Functions From the Server', 324, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Dropinbase ships with various useful classes and functions that are available for execution on the client. Most of the classes are situated in the dibGlobals dropin under the /js/action[/server] subfolders.Â Refer to the <b>Client API Reference</b>Â in Docs for more information about the available functions provided by Dropinbase, and the <b>Dropins Reference</b>Â of 3d-party providers for information about their classes and functions.</p><p>See ~nav(dibexEvents)~ for live examples of the following.</p><p>All client item and container events send requests to server controllers which can respond with an array of actions.Â </p><p>There are three types of client events, depending on the value of the <font face="inherit"><span style="font-size: 12px;"><i>response_type </i></span></font>field in the <i>pef_item_event </i>and <i>pef_container_event </i>tables:<br/></p><ul><li>\'actions\' - the client API will expect an array of actions, which is sent to the client only AFTER all PHP server-side code has been executed.</li><li>\'redirect\' - the client API expects <strong>no response</strong>. Any reponse is handled by the browser (useful if echo\'ing HTML or posting files to be downloaded etc).</li><li>an integer value (n) - the Queue is initiated to poll the server every n milliseconds. Any actions waiting in the Queue (for the particular user) is fetched and executed.</li></ul><p>Note, when \'redirect\' is used, the client API is disengaged and actions will not be executed.</p><p>The server controllers should all extend the Controller.php file. This class contains the ValidResult and InvalidResult functions which &#34;packages&#34; the array of actions in a response for delivery to the client.</p><p><!--StartFragment--><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">The ClientFunctionsÂ class provides wrapper functions to aid with executing client actions.Â </span>As an example the following code will add an action to an array to disable the Textfield1 item on the current container, another to hide the Textfield2 item on the dibTest container, and the last action refreshes the data in the \'myTest\' container. See the PHP code behind ~nav(dibexEvents)~ for practical examples.</p><pre>// addMethod&#10;ClientFunctions::addMethod($actionList, array(\'view.Textfield1.disabled\'=&gt;TRUE));&#10;ClientFunctions::addMethod($actionList, array(\'view.Textfield2.visible\'=&gt;FALSE), \'dibTest\');</pre><pre>// addAction&#10;ClientFunctions::addAction($actionList, \'RefreshContainer\', array(\'value\'=&gt;\'myTest\'));&#10;return $this-&gt;validResult($actionList);</pre><p><b>Notes</b></p><ul><li>Targeted items <b>must have aliases</b>. Any item (including layout components) can be targeted.</li><li>The last parameter ($containerName) is optional. It indicates where searching starts to find the item referenced by its Alias.Â </li><li>If $containerName is not provided, the current container is used. This will only work if $containerName is a parameter in the PHP controller function that was called.</li><li>If the target container is loaded in a port with an alias (not the default port), then $containerName should use the following format: CONTAINERNAME/PORTALIAS<br/></li><li>Use Queues or NodeJs to send actions while server-side PHP code is executing.</li></ul><h2>Using NodeJs</h2><p>Where Apache responds to requests from the client, NodeJs pushes content at will (during PHP execution) to any targeted client (end user). The Dropinbase NodeJs class has various wrapper functions to facilitate sending actions to the client. Note, the NodeJs::action function utilizes the same array structure as the validResult function in Controller.php which is generally used.Â </p><p>See ~navdocs(Setup and Start NodeJs)~ and ~nav(dibexEvents)~ (NodeJs-tab) for details about how NodeJs works.</p><p><b>Example</b></p><pre>NodeJs::msgHeader(&#34;Hello World&#34;, &#34;Hey :) We greet... and then wait 2 seconds before dismissing this message&#34;, 2000, \'notice\');<br/>ClientFunctions::addMethod($actionList, array(\'view.Textfield1.disabled\'=&gt;FALSE));<br/>NodeJs::action($actionList, $containerName);<br/>// Return something valid to stop client waiting for response and causing exception<br/>return $this-&gt;validResult(TRUE);</pre><h3><br/></h3><h2>Actions ArrayÂ </h2><p>The actions array sent to the client has the following structure (some ClientFunctions or NodeJs functions omit keys that are not required):Â </p><pre>$myAction_1 = array(<br/>Â  Â  Â \'actionClass\' =&gt; $actionClass, // name of the JavaScript class (excluding the .js extension), eg \'dibGlobals.action.itemHandler\'<br/>Â  Â  Â \'functionName\' =&gt; $functionName, // name of the function to execute in the .js file, eg \'init\'<br/>Â  Â  Â \'dropinName\' =&gt; $dropinName, // name of the dropin containing the JavaScript class, eg \'dibGlobals\'<br/>Â  Â  Â \'containerName\' =&gt; $containerName,Â // indicates the position in the DOM where searching starts when looking for items referenced by aliases<br/>Â  Â  Â \'params\' =&gt; $paramsArray // array of action parameters)</pre><p><br/></p><p>Multiple actions can be executed in order by appending them in the required order to an array, using the key \'actions\', eg:</p><pre>$actionList[0] = $myAction_1;<br/>$actionList[1] = $myAction_2;<br/>$actionList[2] = $myAction_3;</pre><h2>Follow-up Action</h2><p>The following action can be used to set the next client-side or server-side action to be called.Â </p><p>It is often used to export files to the client (see eg.Â /dropinbase/dropins/dibExcel/components/DibExcelExport.php).</p><pre>ClientFunctions::addSubmitUrl($actionList, &#34;/dropins/dibExamples/Events/textfield_changed/$containerName/dib*hy-1pnfq3?itemAlias=Textfield1&#34;);<br/>&#10;return $this-&gt;validResult($actionList);</pre><p></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc87-dib'),
    (89, 'Executing Server Functions From the Server', 324, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Container CRUD Events</h2><p>The ~navdocs(Container Events)~ article provides details about configuring the event trigger by using the <i>submit_url </i>and <i>trigger </i>fields in <i>pef_container_event</i>.Â </p><p>Depending on the trigger that was used for a Container Crud event, different parameter values are available for the corresponding PHP function that is called. See the &#34;Available Parameters&#34; column in the <b>Dropinbase Custom Events</b> table in ~navdocs(Container Events)~.</p><p>Note we can override default messages, and send actions to the client for execution by using the DibApp:setClientMsg function, and DibApp::$clientActions array. See the example below.</p><p>As an example we\'ll look at the <b>after readmany</b> event configured on the <b>dibtestConsultantEventsGrid </b>container. See <b>Container Crud Events</b> on ~nav(dibexEvents)~.</p><p><b>pef_container_event:</b></p><p>trigger: after readmany</p><p>submit_url: /dropins/dibExamples/ContainerEvents/afterReadMany</p><p><b>PHP:</b></p><p><i>See: /dropins/dibExamples/components/ContainerEvents.php</i></p><pre>public function afterReadMany($containerName, &amp;$attributes, $trigger, $filterParams) {        <br/>Â Â Â Â // NOTE, since we configured $attributes to be sent by reference,<br/>Â Â Â Â // we can (conditionally) modify the contents of $attributes, which would then change the values that are sent to the client      <br/>Â Â Â Â if(isset($attributes[3]))<br/>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â $attributes[0][\'name\'] = &#34;Container Events classified this info, if &gt;3 records ;-)&#34;;<br/>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â <br/>Â Â Â Â // We\'ll include a notice for the user. <br/>Â Â Â Â // By setting DibApp::$clientMsg we override any other message that may have been configured using validResult(...)<br/>Â Â Â Â DibApp::setClientMsg(&#34;Container Events triggered to change values in the \'name\' field&#34;, \'notice\', 4000);<br/>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â <br/>Â Â Â Â // We can also add any other client actions ... <br/>Â Â Â Â ClientFunctions::addAction(DibApp::$clientActions, \'AppendValue\', array(\'dibexEvents.containerEvents\'=&gt;&#34;$containerName: $trigger (fired from Container Crud Events); &#34;));<br/>}<br/></pre><h2>Table Events</h2><p>Table events occur when users perform create, update, or delete operations on a specified table. This excludes custom code that executes SQL statements with Database::execute.</p><p>Configuring Table Events is discussed in detail under ~navdocs(Table Events)~.</p><p>Also see ~nav(dibexEvents)~ and the associated /dropins/dibExamples/components/TableEvents.php class.Â </p><h2>Load Dropin Classes</h2><p>The DibApp class contains functions which makes locating and loading dropin classes convenient.</p><p>See ~navdocs(Loading Dropin Classes)~ and the PHP code behind ~nav(dibexPhp)~ for more info.</p><h2>Add Files to the Autoloader</h2><p>The /runtime/Components.php file can be edited to add files that must be available for auto-loading.</p><p>Alternatively, use the following function to add files at runtime:</p><h4>DibApp::registerFiles</h4><p>/**<br/>Â Â Â Â * Adds all the files in $path with a \'.php\' extension to the autoloader\'s list of files<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param string $path - Absolute folder path.<br/>Â Â Â Â * <br/>Â Â Â Â */<br/>Â Â Â Â public static function registerFiles($path)</p><p><b>Example</b></p><pre>DibApp::registerFiles(DIB::$BASEPATH . \'dropins\' . DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR . \'dibExcel\'Â . DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR . \'components\');&#10;// functions in DibExcelExport can now be called<br/>$dibEx = new DibExcelExport();&#10;$result = $dibEx-&gt;exportContainer($containerName, $templateFile, $submissionData, $filters, $start, $batchSize, $captions);&#10;</pre><h2>Using System Classes</h2><p>The /dropinbase/components folder contains classes that are used by the system but are also available for use in applications.Â </p><p>The system automatically creates a file named Components.php in theÂ /projectFolder/runtime/ folder with an array indexed by class name and pointing to the files in /dropinbase/components. The auto-loader uses this file to find and instantiate classes that are referenced the first time (require_once is used).Â </p><p>See <b>System Classes</b> below for a list of available classes. The useful functions in each class is well documented.</p><p><b>Example - Static function calls:</b></p><pre>$rst = Database::execute(\'SELECT * FROM pef_table\');<br/>$newId = Crud::create ($containerName, $newValues);</pre><p><b>Example - Non-static function calls:</b></p><pre>$tmpl = New ContainerTemplate();<br/>$tmpl-&gt;merge($containerName, $submissionData);<br/>$tmpl = NULL; // release memory</pre><h2>System Classes</h2><p>Note the following system classes are loaded (with require) automatically with every request.Â </p><ul><li>DibApp.php Â  - main application</li><li>Dib.php Â  Â - static global variables</li><li>Components.php Â  - autoloader\'s filesÂ </li><li>Conn.php Â  - database connection details</li><li>Authenticator.php Â  - authenticates users</li><li>Url.php Â  - analysis a url</li><li>Controller.php Â  - base controller functions</li><li>ControllerFactory.php Â  - calls controllers via reflection</li><li>Cache.php Â  - reads and maintains cache</li><li>Log.php Â  - logs errors and debugging text</li></ul><h3>Eleutheria</h3><p>Eleutheria is automatically added to the autoloader\'s class with every request. It can be called non-statically as follows:</p><p>Â  Â $e = New Eleutheria ();<br/>Â  Â $e-&gt;mergeTmpl (...);</p><p>Or statically as follows which saves memory when it is called multiple times:</p><p>Â  Â Template::generate($templateName, $params, $cacheKey);</p><h2>Â </h2>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc89-dib'),
    (90, 'Structuring Applications', 324, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Dropins</h2><p>A fundamental design goal of Dropinbase is facilitating the process of building a library of modules (&#34;dropins&#34;) that can be reused and distributed easily among developers and projects. When designing your application, think which portions can be re-used, and include them in a &#34;dropin&#34;. Functions that are related or similar should be grouped together in one dropin. Eg the dibCSV dropin contains all the controllers and other PHP files used to import and export CSV files.Â </p><p>To create a dropin simply create a new folder with a unique dropin name under the /projectFolder/dropins/ folder. If you plan to distribute the dropin to other Dropinbase developers, ensure the name is unique by prefixing it with your unique company DIB Code.</p><p>The following subfolders in a dropin have special purposes</p><ul><li><b>/controllers</b> Â - Â Contains classes with functions handling client requests and responses to the client. The controller functions mostly handle validation of the input variables, calling of other classes to process the request, and returning the processed result to the client (or a applicable error message).Â </li><li><b>/components</b> - Contains classes with functions that perform the actual &#34;work&#34; of the dropin, eg producing the csv file that will be exported. All classes in the components folder of the current dropin are auto-loaded when needed (no need to &#34;require&#34; them in PHP code).</li><li><b>/templates </b>- Contains any templates that are typically merged with metadata in the database to produce crud or user-interface files, eg dibHtmlTemplate template files. Requests of the form /files/dropins/DROPINNAME/templates/*.* are always denied.</li><li><b>/crud</b> - Automatically created. Stores the generated CRUD code used to interact with the database when a container or data-component (eg a dropdown) within the dropin is used.</li><li><b>/cache</b> - Automatically created. Stores the generated cache files that define the user-interfaces related to the dropin.</li><li><b>/permFiles</b> - Automatically created. Stores the generated permission file content for the containers linked to the dropin.</li></ul><p>Other folders frequently used are:</p><ul><li><b>â/js</b> - Contains JavaScript functions that are used in the user-interface.</li><li><b>/images</b> - Contains any image files used by containers within the dropin.</li></ul><p>Apart from the automatically created folders, and theÂ <b>/controllers</b> folder which is required for client requests, the above structure is not enforced. It does aid developers though when everyone follows the same general guidelines. Any of these folders may have their own subfolders.</p><p><b>Note</b>, if you are developing a container dropin such as dibGrid, then the controller that returns the view must be named TemplateController.php, and its public functions must have $containerName as a parameter. This restriction enables permissions.</p><p>Any dropin can be overridden by copying it from the /dropinbase/dropins/ folder to the /projectFolder/dropins folder, and then modifying them. It is only necessary to create copies of the specific controller files you wish to override, and their related component files (if any).</p><h2>Dropinbase Components</h2><p>The system classes stored in the subfolders of /dropinbase/components are automatically required by the auto loader, using the paths stored in the /runtime/Components.php class. This file is automatically created if deleted. To override one of the system component classes, make a copy of it and adjust the path to it in the Components.php file.Â </p><p></p><p>See ~navdocs(Loading Dropin Classes)~ for more info about utilizing code from other dropins.<br/></p><p></p><h2>Global Variables</h2><p>Variables stored in the Dib.php class is available globally for every request. Variables can be added to the file and their values set using the DIB::$SETUPSCRIPT to point to a script that will be loaded (using require) just before the call to the controller is setup. An example is setting a database id value that is used for certain queries, and dependent on the user that logs in. Note, that if the Dib.php file doesn\'t exist, it will be created based on the /projectFolder/configs/DibTmpl.php file.</p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc90-dib'),
    (92, 'How Dropinbase Works', 324, 5, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The following discussion outlines the structure and workings of the Dropinbase system. It provides enough background to successfully build nearly any system with Dropinbase.</p><p>(Strongly) recommended reading before continuing:</p><ul><li>~navdocs(Dropinbase Overview)~</li><li>~navdocs(Basic Building Blocks)~</li><li>~navdocs(Processes)~</li><li>~navdocs(Dropins Overview)~</li><li>~navdocs(Activating and Using Dropins)~</li><li>~navdocs(Permission Files)~</li><li>~navdocs(Submission Data)~</li><li>~navdocs(General Troubleshooting Tips)~</li></ul><h2>Tools</h2><p>Below is list of free and useful tools that can assist programmers starting out :-)Â </p><ul><li>WAMP Â - quick &amp; easy way to setup-up and maintain a Apache-MySQL-PHP environment.</li><li>CodeLobster / NetBeans - two common PHP editors &amp; debuggers</li><li>Heidisql &amp;Â MySQL BrowserÂ - creating &amp; maintaining databases in MySQL.Â </li><li>SQL Server Management Studio -Â creating &amp; maintaining databases in SQL Server.</li><li>Notepadd++ - text file editor recognising syntaxes for a wide variety of files including PHP, JavaScript and json.</li></ul><h2>Metadata and Merging</h2><p>Upon import of tables, Dropinbase collects and stores metadata of the table design (in <i>pef_table </i>and <i>pef_field</i>), it\'s relationships (in <i>pef_table_fk</i> and <i>pef_fk</i>) and indexes (in <i>pef_table_option </i>and <i>pef_table_option_field</i>). During the import process (or thereafter) the user has the option to let Dropinbase build grid and form containers. The design of the new containers is based on the selected design templates. The process generates metadata which is stored in mostly the <i>pef_container</i>, <i>pef_item </i>and <i>pef_port </i>tables. Storing the design in metadata tables makes it convenient to generate, change, debug, and distribute features through various database functions.Â </p><p>As mentioned in the ~navdocs(Dropinbase Overview)~ the metadata is merged with file templates to produce both server-side PHP code for crud classes stored in theÂ /runtime/crud Â or /dropins/xxx/crud folders, and client-side Json (ExtJs) or HTML (Angular) code stored Â in the /runtime/cache or /dropins/xxx/cache folders. The code that is produced is very specific to that container and can be easily adjusted using fields in <i>pef_item </i>and <i>pef_container</i>. When the $CODEUSE variable in /configs/Dib.php is set to 0, cache files are recreated with each request, but crud files and permission files are not. This implies that changes to metadata is only reflected once the related files are recreated, which the system attempts to do automatically for module dropins where the <i>pef_dropin.manage_files</i> field is set. Files can be manuallly cleared by using the Clear Files menu options on the Designer. The system automatically creates files if they do not exist, so all that is needed is to delete them.</p><p>There are merge templates for each type of container, eg forms and grids, and each type of component, eg textfields, checkboxes and toolbars. New templates for containers and components can be added by programmers and referenced in the ~navdocs(Tables Reference,pef_dropin,pef_dropin)~Â and ~navdocs(Tables Reference,pef_component,pef_component)~Â tables (see ~navdocs(Adding New Components)~ and ~navdocs(Adding New Dropins)~). Dropinbase uses Eleutheria, a very fast and powerful templating engine that has been optimized for Dropinbase. The /controllers/TemplateController.php script of each container dropin is responsible for merging controller, view, store and model template files for the user interface as required.Â </p><h2>Permgroups and Permission Files</h2><p>Dropinbase permissions are also stored in tables and can be very specific down to field and record level. The permissions in these tables are combined and stored in the <i>pef_perm_active </i>and <i>pef_perm_field_active </i>tables. User permissions are based on permgroups - the unique combinations of permission groups that users have current rights to. Each permgroup is assigned a name, eg if x1x14x exists, it means there is at least one user that has rights to permission groups with id values of 1 and 14. Containers\' crud and cache files are specifically generated for and named after permgroups, based on the information stored in the two pef_perm_XXX_temp tables. The SQL statements in the template files are crafted by Eleutheria to fetch metadata that is allowed for each permgroup. Note, Admin users can make changes to records in the permission tables but only &#34;activate&#34; them when ready by using the permgroup dropdown and Clear Files button on the ~nav(dibDesigner)~.</p><p>Whenever a user requests a protected resource (eg a container or dropdownlist) or triggers a serverside event, Dropinbase consults certain files, named permission files, in the /runtime/permFiles folder. These files are based on info from the <i>pef_perm_active,</i>Â <i>pef_perm_field_active</i> and otherÂ tables and store containers that permgroups have access to, as well as some other meta-data needed at runtime (see the PermFile link under Designer-&gt;Configuration). Eg _Containersxx1xx.php lists the containers that the x1x permgroup has access to. These files therefore need to be recreated to activate new changes to info stored in them, for eg when permissions, or a container\'s record source is changed, or a new container is added. Â As mentioned, certain actions prompts Dropinbase to automatically remove these files. They are also automatically recreated when specifically theÂ _Containersxx...xx.php file does not exist.</p><h2>Deploying an Application</h2><p>The /cache, /crud and /permFiles folders store everything needed to deploy an application. If you have made changes to your application locally and need to update your production server, then only copy these files across, and recreate the permission files - there is no need to update the dropinbase database on the server.Â </p><p>To force the server to use and never overwrite the /cache files for a particular dropin, add the name of the dropin to the /runtime/IncludePermFiles.php file and then recreate the permission files. Dropinbase will then include the content of this dropin\'s own permission files (generated with the ~nav(dibFiles)~ utility) in the main permission files, which will effectively then bypass any attempt to read the design of these containers from the database.</p><h2>Url Requests From the Client</h2><p>The system works (apart from NodeJs) by issueing requests from the client to the server, which in turn generates responses. The list of requests and their responses can be viewed in the browser\'s Console and Network tabs (press F12). Press Ctrl-f under Console to find specific requests (eg type \'controller\') or use the filter under Network. A few common requests are:</p><ul><li>Static file requests, egÂ http://dev.peff.net/files/dropins/setSencha/dibGlobals/js/ux/callout/resource/prettify/prettify.css</li><li>A container\'s template/controller request returns the whole design (controller, store, model and view) of the container, egÂ http://dev.peff.net/dropins/setNgMaterial/dibGrid/template/controller/test_company_grid</li><li>The crud/read request returns data for container or dropdownlist, egÂ http://dev.peff.net/peff/crud/read/test_company_grid</li><li>Item events have the form /dropins/DROPINNAME/CONTROLLERNAME/FUNCTIONNAME. Eg http://dev.peff.net/dropins/dibExamples/Run/helloWorld?containerName=test_company_form&amp;itemId=123073&amp;containerId=3401&amp;triggerType=click&amp;actionId=&amp;itemEventId=407</li></ul><p>There are two types of requests, file requests and API requests. The .htaccess file directs file requests to a single script named files.php in the root folder, while API requests are handled by index.php which invokes the rest of the framework starting with DibApp.php.</p><p>File requests involve no merging and basic permission checking. In otherwords, these requests are used to return static files that should be accessible to anyone in the world. The URLs for file requests are of the form: domain/files/files/... OR domain/files/dropins/... Â  eg www.myDIB.com/files/dropins/dibGlobals/js/ux/TabReorderer.js.Â </p><p>For both file request types, the file extension must be in  the /configs/MimeTypeWhiteList.php file.Â For domain/files/files/... requests, files.php serves files from the /projectFolder/files/Â folder. For domain/files/dropins/... requests, the code serves anyÂ file in a dropin folder, that has its extension listed in MimeTypeWhiteList, and is not in the \'/templates/\' subfolder of the dropin.</p><p>API requests are used for tasks such as fetching user interface definitions, data, and executing events. The following basic types of API requests exist:</p><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Url</strong></td><td><strong>Description</strong></td><td><strong>Examples</strong></td></tr><tr><td>/nav/CONTAINER</td><td>/nav/ requests are used to open containers (CONTAINER). Note these requests are handled by the client side framework - the server never handles them.</td><td><ul><li>/nav/ngexComponents?primary_id=1 - instructs the client side framework to issue server requests to load files needed to open theÂ ngexComponents container and to load the record where the primary key (named id) has a value of 1.</li></ul></td></tr><tr><td>/peff/CONTROLLER/FUNCTION</td><td>/peff/ requests execute functions in the core PHP libraries of Dropinbase. The function named FUNCTION in controller named CONTROLLERController.php in the /dropinbase/controllers/ folder is executed.</td><td><ul><li>/peff/Container/getPortInfo?containerName=ngexComponents - a request issued by the client side framework directly after a /nav/ request to load port-related information of the container being opened.</li><li>/peff/site/login - loads the login page.</li><li>/peff/crud/read/test_company_grid?primary_id=1 - reads data for a specified record</li></ul></td></tr><tr><td>/dropins/DROPIN/CONTROLLER/FUNCTION</td><td>/dropins/ requests execute functions under the /dropins folders. It firstly attempts to find the Controller.php file in /projectFolder/dropins/DROPIN/controllers/CONTROLLERController.php and if not found, it triesÂ /dropinbase/dropins/DROPIN/controllers/CONTROLLERController.php. This allows developers to override system dropin controllers (store a copy of the existing one under /projectFolder/dropins/DROPIN/controllers/ and adjust as needed). If a function named FUNCTION is not found in the Controller.php file an error will occur.</td><td><ul><li>/dropins/setNgMaterial/dibForm/Template/view/ngexComponents.html - loads the user interface file for the ngexComponents container in an Angular application</li><li>http://ng.peff.net/peff/DibTasks/dibDesignerCopy?containerName=dibDesignerItemTree&amp;itemId=60399&amp;containerId=2106&amp;triggerType=click&amp;actionId=&amp;itemEventId=231 - executes the copy function on the Designer\'s Item tree (note SubmissionData has been omitted from the url).</li></ul></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br/></p><p>See ~navdocs(Server Api Call Stack)~Â for more information about processes that are executed on the server with each request.</p><p>Programmers will find it useful to study the headers and responses of requests in browsers under Developer Tools (eg press F12 in Chrome).</p><h2>Landing and Login Pages and the system_public User</h2><p>By default all users are logged-in as the \'system_public\' user (a hard-coded user that will be recreated automatically if deleted from the <i>pef_login </i>table) before logging in. The system_public user may be assigned to any permission groups, which allows the general public to access any part of the sytem without logging in. If a request accesses a proteced resource, and the user is system_public, the system automatically redirects to the login page. After a successful login, the user is directed to the URL specified in his<em> pef_login.default_url</em> field.</p><p>Dropinbase ships with a default login.php page under /dropinbase/dropins/dibAuthenticate/views/. Developers can override it by copying the /dibAuthenticate folder (with all subfolders) to /projectFolder/dropins/ and modifying the files to suit their requirements. Alternatively, include the necessary HTML code therein in your own pages. Note the \'email1\' hidden fields that are used for security reasons to detect robots and must be included.</p><h2>Environment and Global Variables</h2><p>The /projectFolder/configs/Dib.php file is automatically generated if it doesn\'t exist, using the /projectFolder/configs/DibTmpl.php file as a template. The file contains useful constants and variables that are available globally using DIB:: eg DIB::$BASEURL.</p><p>The DIB::$ENVIRONMENT and DIB:$CODEUSE variables deserve special mention. DIB::$CODEUSE can have a value between 0 and 3 and affects whether cache files generated by /Template/ requests are regenerated with every request, automatically deleted when affected by design changes, or assumed existing and read from cache. This allows developers to make design changes without needing to empty the cache with every change, and forces production servers to only use generated files.Â Note the .php files in the /runtime/crud folder are not regenerated with every request as it affects performance unnecessarily while developing.Â When DIB::$CODEUSE is set to read from cache the system performance increases substantially.Â Â </p><p>The DIB::$ENVIRONMENT variable can be set to either \'development\' (all operations allowed and HTML is beautified) or \'production\' (some admin functions are prohibited to increase security, PHP errors are not sent to the browser</p><p>For more information see the comments within the DibTmpl.phpÂ file itself. Also note that dropins listed in the /runtime/IncludePermFiles.php file are forced to use cache files irrespective of the value of DIB::$CODEUSE.</p><h2>Error Reporting and Debugging Issues</h2><p>If an exception occurs anywhere in the call stack below DibApp.php, it will be hanlded by a global Try... Catch, unless the exception occurs within another Try... Catch lower down in the call stack. IfÂ DibApp.php handles it, the client will receive a message sayingÂ \'System error. Please check log for details\', and the details of the error will be appended to the /runtime/logs/error.log file. Any other Dropinbase specific system errors are also logged in the same file. Depending on settings in php.ini and httpd.conf, certain errors are sent to the browser Â (unless DIB::$ENVIRONMENT is set to \'production\') and logged in the php_error.log and apache_error.log file. Requests denied by the permission system are logged in the /runtime/logs/Permissions.log file (dependent on the $LOGPERMISSUES variable in Dib.php).</p><p>If any error or unexpected behaviour occurs, use the steps under ~navdocs(General Troubleshooting Steps)~ to resolve it. Also see ~navdocs(Productivity and Debugging Tips)~ for more helpful information.</p><p>Â </p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc92-dib'),
    (93, 'Common API Requests', 28, 80, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The list of requests and their responses can be viewed in the browser\'s Console and Network tabs (press F12).</p>\n<p>Find specific requests under the Network-tab by using the Filter, or the Search (Ctrl-F).</p>\n<p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/requests.png" alt=""></p>\n<p>Note, the <strong>View Code</strong> button under Container Details in the Designer will run the requests that return the uncompiled UI (Ctrl-u to view code) and TypeScript for a particular container. Ensure the resulting popup is not blocked by the browser for this request.</p>\n<h3>Request types (roughly in order of execution)</h3>\n<p>Note, see ~navdocs(Permission Checks)~ about handling request permissions.</p>\n<table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100.028%; height: 201.6px;" border="1"><colgroup><col style="width: 21.9516%;"><col style="width: 78.0347%;"></colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr style="background-color: rgb(194, 224, 244); height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Request</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Notes</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>/login</strong> <br>or <strong>/dropins/dibAuthenticate/Site/login<br></strong>or <strong>/logout</strong></td>\n<td>Returns the results of the <strong>/dropins/dibAuthenticate/views/login.php</strong> page.<br>This folder also contains scripts for <strong>forgotpassword,</strong>&nbsp;<strong>resetpassword,</strong>&nbsp;<strong>sitemaintenance,</strong>&nbsp;<strong>twofactor </strong>etc.<br><span style="text-decoration: underline;">NOTE</span>, the next request after a successful login, is defined by the <em>pef_login.default_url </em>field.&nbsp;<br>If a user opens the site on a valid container (eg /nav/myPage) but their session has expired, then they will be redirected to the login page. After successful authentication they will be redirected back to the container.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Any <strong>/nav/...</strong> request</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Returns the cached version of the <strong>/dropins/setNgxMaterial/angular/src/index.html</strong> page, after merging with settings.<br>Use the <strong>beforeBodyJs </strong>and <strong>afterBodyJs </strong>settings in <em>pef_setting </em>to insert JavaScript for chatbots etc.<br>Delete the <strong>/runtime/cache/index.dtxt</strong> file to force a recreate of the cache. Alternatively the Designer\'s various buttons to delete cache all also clears it.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<p>Any <strong>/files/...</strong> request<br>Eg. <strong>/files/dropins/dibAuthenticate/css/main.css</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Loads a static file like an image or .css file.<br>Is handled by the <strong>/dropinbase/files.php</strong> script. All other requests are handled by <strong>/dropinbase/index.php</strong>.<br><span style="text-decoration: underline;">NOTE</span>, add allowed file extensions and folders to the lists in <strong>/configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php&nbsp;</strong>else the requests will raise 401 exceptions.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>/peff/Template/environment.js</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Loads the result of the <strong>/configs/Environment.php</strong> file.<br>It returns the DIB object which contains variables for various functions in the UI framework.<br><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Add your own</span> variables or code. The values are accessible in the UI using <strong>getValue(\'xxx\')</strong> and <strong>env_xxx </strong>... <br>See ~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices)~ and ~navdocs(Conditional Directives)~ for more info.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>/peff/Container/getPortInfo</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<p>Checks user rights to open a specific container and fetches port information.<br>This is the first request that executes when a container is opened.<br>If the UI finds that this container\'s parent is not loaded yet, then that parent\'s port request will be issued and so on, until the base container is loaded.<br>Thereafter requests are made for the HTML &amp; JavaScript of the particular container (see next row).<br>Note, the JSON result is cached client-side, so it will only run once per container port.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>/dropins/setNgxMaterial/plain/Template/controller/dibDocsForm.js</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Loads the compiled HTML &amp; Javascript for a particular container, in this case <strong>dibDocsForm</strong>.<br>The <strong>View Code</strong> button under Container Details in the Designer will run the requests that return the uncompiled HTML (Ctrl-u to view code) and TypeScript for a particular container. Ensure the resulting popup is not blocked by the browser.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>/peff/Template/component/dibDocsForm?componentPath=pager&amp;dropin=setNgxMaterial.form</strong><strong><br></strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Fetches the compiled JavaScript for a particular Angular component, in this case the <strong>pager </strong>in the <strong>setNgxMaterial/form</strong> dropin.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>/peff/Crud/toolbarinfo/dibDocsForm</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Fetches primary key values for the current/first/last/next/prev record in a form, used by the <strong>pager </strong>component.<br>This is normally the first data request made on a form - if it fails, nothing else loads.<br>Calls the generated PHP code in the <strong>/dibCode</strong> for this container, in this case <strong>dibDocsForm.</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>/peff/Crud/view/dibDocsForm</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<p>Fetches a single record identified by primary key value(s) from generated code for the container, in this case <strong>dibDocsForm.</strong><br>The request is handled by <strong>/dropinbase/controllers/CrudController.php</strong> which calls the generated PHP code in <strong>/dibCode</strong> for this container.<br>Similar requets exist for <strong>read </strong>(many records on grids), <strong>create</strong>, <strong>update</strong>, <strong>delete</strong>, <strong>getDefaults</strong>, <strong>etc </strong>(see controller code for details).</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>/dropins/dibExamples/Events/countClients</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Calls server-side PHP code that can return JSON/HTML or a file etc., depending on the event\'s <strong>Response Type</strong>.<br>In this case executes the <strong>countClients </strong>function in the <strong>EventsController.php</strong> file in the <strong>dibExamples </strong>dropin folder.<br>First checks if the .php file exists in <strong>/dropins/dibExamples/controllers</strong>. If not, it checks <strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase//dropins/dibExamples/controllers</strong>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>/dropins/setMainDropin/dibExamples/Events/countClients</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Same as the above, but now the .php controller file is expected in the <strong>/setMainDropin/dibExamples</strong> dropin folder.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>/peff/File/upload</strong></td>\n<td>\n<p>Uploads a file. There are various other file requests: download/getFileSettings/deletefile/checkfile/getItemMaxFileSize</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc93-dib'),
    (94, 'Database Functions', 39, 60, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc94-dib'),
    (95, 'Client API Reference', 324, 150, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc95-dib'),
    (97, 'SQL Overview', 94, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The <strong>Database </strong>class (/dropinbase/components/database/Database.php) provides powerful wrapper functions around PHP\'s PDO functions to execute SQL queries in a secure way.</p>\n<p>Below is a summary of the available functions and variables with links to more info. Note all the functions are called statically, eg. Database::fetch($sql, null, DIB::$LOGINDB);</p>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexPhpDatabase)~ for examples.</p>\n<table style="width: 99.9925%; height: 748.8px;" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3">\n<tbody>\n<tr style="background-color: rgb(194, 224, 244); height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 22.4px;"><strong>Function</strong></td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 22.4px;"><strong>Description</strong></td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 22.4px;"><strong>Return</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 99.2px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 99.2px;">execute(...)</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 99.2px;">\n<p>Execute a SELECT statements that returns many records in a 3-dimensional array (note, the first 6 characters of the statement must be \'SELECT\' case-insensitive)<br>Execute any action queries (eg. UPDATE or DELETE etc)<br>~navdocs(Database - execute,docs,More Info on Database::execute)~</p>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 99.2px;">For SELECT statements it will return an array of records.<br>For INSERT statements it will return the new primary key value.<br>For other action queries, it will return TRUE (unless it fails).<br>If any error occurs it will return FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 67.2px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 67.2px;">fetch(...)</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 67.2px;">Calls the <strong>execute()</strong> function but then returns only the first record in the result in a 2-dimensional array. <br>Works only with \'SELECT \' statements, and typically used where the SELECT statement returns one record only. &nbsp;<br>Uses the same parameters as the <strong>execute()</strong> function.<br>~navdocs(Database - execute,docs,Refer to the documentation for Database::execute for more info)~</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 67.2px;">An array of records (arrays).<br>If any error occurs it will return FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 67.2px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 67.2px;">executeBatch(...)</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 67.2px;">\n<div>Executes a batch of SQL statements separated with semicolons</div>\n<div>- If the first 7 characters of a statement is \'SELECT \' (case-insensitive),&nbsp;then a single return value is expected which is available as parameter with same name for subsequent statements.</div>\n<div>- If the first 7 characters is \'INSERT \' (case-insensitive) then the new primary key value is stored in a parameter named by the preceding -- comment, or \'lastInserted\'</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 67.2px;">TRUE on success, otherwise FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 44.8px;">count()</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 44.8px;">Returns the count of records fetched by the last call to the execute() or fetch() functions. If an error occurred then it will contain 0.<br>Eg. $count = Database::count();</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 44.8px;">Integer count of records.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>create($tableName, $params, $container_database, $auditTrail=null, $notes=null)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 44.8px;">Creates a single record in $tableName where $params is an array of field values in the table.<br>See ~navdocs(Database - update create delete)~ for more info.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 44.8px;">primary key value on success, otherwise FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>update($tableName, $params, $container_database, $where=NULL, $auditTrail=null, $notes=null)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 44.8px;">Updates one or more records in $tableName identified by (optional) criteria, where $params is an array of field values in the table or used as PDO criteria parameters.<br>See ~navdocs(Database - update create delete)~ for more info.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 44.8px;">TRUE on success, otherwise FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>delete($tableName, $params, $container_database, $where=NULL, $auditTrail=null, $notes=null)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 44.8px;">Deletes one or more records from $tableName identified by (optional) criteria, where $params is used as PDO criteria parameters<br>See ~navdocs(Database - update create delete)~ for more info.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 44.8px;">TRUE on success, otherwise FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 44.8px;">transactionBegin($container_database=\'\')</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 44.8px;">Begins a database transaction. Typically any queries that follow that make changes to the database will only be visible to other users once the transaction has been committed. <br>The function also locks the database for changes to other users until either a Commit or Rollback has been issued. <br>Refer to the documentation for the applicable database engine for more information.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 44.8px;">TRUE on success, otherwise FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 22.4px;">transactionCommit($container_database=\'\')</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 22.4px;">Commits a database transaction.&nbsp;Refer to&nbsp;the documentation for the applicable database engine for more information.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 22.4px;">TRUE on success, otherwise FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 22.4px;">transactionRollback($container_database=\'\')</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 22.4px;">Performs a rollback on a database transaction.&nbsp;Refer to&nbsp;the documentation for the applicable database engine for more information.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 22.4px;">TRUE on success, otherwise FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>hasTransaction($container_database=DIB::$DIBDB)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>Returns whether a transaction has been started on given database</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 22.4px;">TRUE/FALSE</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 67.2px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 67.2px;">stmt()</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 67.2px;">If either the execute() or fetch() functions have been called with the $prepare parameter set to TRUE, the Database::stmt() function returns the prepared statement. <br>This is useful when the same statement must be executed many times with different parameter values.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 67.2px;">The last prepared PDO statement or NULL.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 22.4px;">fetchNext($style = PDO::FETCH_ASSOC)</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 22.4px;">Fetches the next row of an already prepared &amp; executed PDO statement. See stmt() above.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 22.4px;">Format dependant on $style.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 67.2px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 67.2px;">\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>setParamsType($paramsType, $container_database=DIB::$DIBDB, $keepInMemory=FALSE)</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 67.2px;">\n<div>\n<div>Specify types to use in PDO parameter binding <br>Eg array(\':id\'=&gt;PDO::PARAM_STR, \':good\'=&gt;PDO::PARAM_BOOL) &nbsp;</div>\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;array(0=&gt;PDO::PARAM_STR, 1=&gt;PDO::PARAM_BOOL)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 67.2px;">TRUE on success, otherwise FALSE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 22.4px;">lastErrorUserMsg()</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 22.4px;">If any error occurs, Database::$lastErrorUserMsg will contain a generic message with enough details to guide the user, without revealing sensitive information.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 22.4px;">The error message in a string.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 15.2114%; height: 22.4px;">lastErrorAdminMsg()</td>\n<td style="width: 67.2951%; height: 22.4px;">If any error occurs, Database::$lastErrorAdminMsg will contain details useful for debugging.</td>\n<td style="width: 17.486%; height: 22.4px;">The error message in a string.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc97-dib'),
    (98, 'Database - execute', 94, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Executes any SQL statement.</p>\n<div>\n<div>Note, if the first 6 characters of $sql is \'SELECT\' (case-insensitive), or $style is specified, then&nbsp;records are returned using the $style format (by default a 3-dim associative array).</div>\n<div>If these characters is \'INSERT\' (case-insensitive) then the new primary key value is returned.</div>\n<div>Else the query is merely executed and TRUE or FALSE is returned.</div>\n</div>\n<p><strong><span id="selectionBoundary_1533212858533_15421119761729862" class="rangySelectionBoundary"></span>Examples:<span id="selectionBoundary_1533212858533_5923791786836379" class="rangySelectionBoundary"></span></strong></p>\n<pre>$sql = "SELECT id, name FROM test_company WHERE notes LIKE :myString";<br>$params = [\':myString\'=&gt;\'%hello%\'];<br>$result = Database::execute($sql, $params, DIB::$LOGINDB);<br>if($result === false)<br>   return $this-&gt;invalidResult("Could not query the database. The following error (for administrators only) was returned:&lt;br&gt;" . Database::lastAdminErrorMsg());<br>}<br><br>Log::w(Database::count()); // prints the count of records returned to /runtime/logs/debug.log<br><br>foreach($result as $r) {<br>   Log::w($r[\'name\']); // prints the name field\'s value of this record to debug.log<br>}<br><br>$result = Database::execute("UPDATE test_company SET notes = :notes WHERE id = 1", array(\':notes\'=&gt;\'hello\'), DIB::$LOGINDB);\n</pre>\n<h2>Database::fetch</h2>\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Database::fetch</strong> command works exactly the same as <strong>Database::execute() </strong>except that it works only for SELECT statements and will return only 1 record. The <strong>Database::count()</strong> function will always either be 1 or 0 (0 in case of no records or an error).</p>\n<pre>$result = Database::fetch("SELECT id, name FROM test_company WHERE id = 5", null, DIB::$$LOGINDB)<br><br>Log::w($result[\'name\']);<br><br>if($result === false)<br>  &nbsp;return $this-&gt;invalidResult("Could not query the database. The following error (for administrators only) was returned:&lt;br&gt;" . Database::lastAdminErrorMsg());<br>}\n</pre>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexPhp)~ and the associated /dropins/dibExamples/controllers/PhpController.php file for many useful examples.</p>\n<h2>Syntax</h2>\n<p>public static function execute($sql, $params=array(), $container_database=DIB::$DIBDB, $style=null, $prepare=TRUE, $fetch=TRUE, $cacheKey=null, $addToSqlLog=TRUE)</p>\n<div>\n<table style="width: 99.9925%; height: 339.2px;" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3">\n<tbody>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 7.61785%; height: 22.4px;">Parameter</td>\n<td style="width: 83.8431%; height: 22.4px;">Description</td>\n<td style="width: 7.75624%; height: 22.4px;">Example</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 67.2px;">\n<td style="width: 7.61785%; height: 67.2px;">$sql (string)</td>\n<td style="width: 83.8431%; height: 67.2px;">The sql statement to execute. May contain PDO parameters as in the examples above.</td>\n<td style="width: 7.75624%; height: 67.2px;">UPDATE person SET `execute`=:value<br>WHERE id=:id</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="width: 7.61785%; height: 44.8px;">$params (array of mixed)</td>\n<td style="width: 83.8431%; height: 44.8px;">Associative array of parameter values, eg <code>[\':name\'=&gt;\'John\', \':id\'=&gt;4]</code></td>\n<td style="width: 7.75624%; height: 44.8px;">array(\':value\'=&gt;NULL, \':id\'=&gt;5);</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 115.2px;">\n<td style="width: 7.61785%; height: 115.2px;">$container_database (string/integer)</td>\n<td style="width: 83.8431%; height: 115.2px;">\n<p>The target database. If omitted it implies the main Dropinbase database.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>If it is an integer value it points to the \'id\' value in <em>pef_database</em>. &nbsp;<span style="background-color: transparent;">Otherwise it is assumed to be the name of a container, in which case the user\'s permissions to Open the container is first checked (criteria may apply). If the user has no permissions, FALSE will be returned and the error messages (see \'Notes\' below) will be set. If the user has&nbsp;permissions but the container is not linked to a table (<em>pef_container.pef_table_id</em> is null) FALSE will be returned and the error messages will be set.</span></p>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 7.75624%; height: 115.2px;">&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 7.61785%; height: 22.4px;">$style (integer)</td>\n<td style="width: 83.8431%; height: 22.4px;">PDO style for fetching records. See&nbsp;<a href="http://php.net/manual/en/pdo.constants.php">http://php.net/manual/en/pdo.constants.php</a>.<br><strong>Used to execute stored procedures and other statements. See notes below.</strong></td>\n<td style="width: 7.75624%; height: 22.4px;">&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 7.61785%; height: 22.4px;">$prepare (boolean)</td>\n<td style="width: 83.8431%; height: 22.4px;">Whether the PDO statement must be "prepared" or not.</td>\n<td style="width: 7.75624%; height: 22.4px;">&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 7.61785%; height: 22.4px;">$fetch</td>\n<td style="width: 83.8431%; height: 22.4px;">Whether a SELECT statement\'s results must be fetched or not (use together with $prepare in order to prepare a statement but not fetch any results yet).</td>\n<td style="width: 7.75624%; height: 22.4px;">&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="width: 7.61785%; height: 22.4px;">$cacheKey</td>\n<td style="width: 83.8431%; height: 22.4px;">&nbsp;If present, and $sql starts with \'SELECT\', the results of the query will be cached, using the Dropinbase Cache class.</td>\n<td style="width: 7.75624%; height: 22.4px;">&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 7.61785%;">\n<div>\n<div>$addToSqlLog</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 83.8431%;">\n<div>\n<div>Whether to log this SQL to <em>pef_sqllog </em>(<strong>DIB::$SQLLOGDB </strong>must also be set). Note, SELECT statements are never logged.</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 7.75624%;">&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>Notes</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>The ` character can be used to delimit table and field names. It will automatically be replaced by the applicable database engine\'s equivalent if not MySQL.</li>\n<li>Parameters are binded using the PDO bindValue function.</li>\n<li>A SELECT statement\'s SQL query must start with \'SELECT\' (case-insensitive) in order for the results to be fetched (using $pdoStmt-&gt;fetchAll()).</li>\n<li>A INSERT statement\'s SQL query must start with \'INSERT\' (case-insensitive) in order for the primary key value of the last inserted record to be returned.</li>\n<li>If the statement is not a SELECT or INSERT statement and executed successfully, TRUE is returned to the function call.</li>\n<li>Using the container name for the $container_database parameter&nbsp;is especially useful if the application needs to be distributed (since primary key values of databases will differ). It also the only option that checks permissions.</li>\n<li>The PDO functions execute within a Try ... Catch statement. If an error occurs the following steps are taken:\n<ol>\n<li>$lastAdminMsg is set to the PDOException\'s message, along with the database\'s id, the SQL statement and the $params used. Obtainable using <strong>Database::lastErrorAdminMsg()</strong></li>\n<li>If the PDOException\'s message contains the string \'duplicate entry\', an attempt is made to extract the value from the error message that is causing the unique index error, and $lastErrorUserMsg is set to contain "Unique value error! The following value already exists in another record: \'$value\'".</li>\n<li>Else if the PDOException\'s message contains the string \'foreign key constraint\' &nbsp;an attempt is made to extract the name of the table that contains restricting relationship, and $lastUserMsg is set, obtainable with <strong>Database::lastErrorUserMsg()</strong>.</li>\n<li>Else $lastUserMsg is set to a generic message. The error is logged in /runtime/logs/error.log.</li>\n<li>FALSE is returned to the function call.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc98-dib'),
    (102, 'Database Server Independency', 94, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>If your application needs compatibility between database engines (like MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQL Server), use the following principles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Use ` (backtick) as delimiter for names/identifiers. Dropinbase wil replace them appropriately for each engine.</li>\n<li>The Database::update/create/delete functions are compatible.</li>\n<li>The code generated by Dropinbase can be regenerated for each database engine to obtain compatibility.\n<ul>\n<li>Once generated the various Crud:: functions will also be compatible.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>SQL used with Database::execute and Database::fetch can use the ^^ delimiters as indicators of code that must be translated (see Code Translation below).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To switch, simply change the connection properties in <strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong> to a different database. Alternatively update the&nbsp;<em>pef_table.pef_database_id</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>pef_sql.pef_database_id</em>&nbsp;fields where needed.</p>\n<h2>Code Translation</h2>\n<p>As mentioned in ~navdocs(Why Not an ORM)~, the basic syntax and functions of the various database engines is the same.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase provides a way of translating basic incompatible syntax and functions, but where it differs significantly, code must be written to handle each engine separately.</p>\n<p>The principle is to use MySQL syntax for everything and enclose portions that contain incompatible syntax or functions with ^^.</p>\n<p>Eg <code>SELECT id, ^^CONCAT(\'hello\', `first name`, CAST(id AS char)^^) FROM myTable</code></p>\n<p>Dropinbase will translate it to compatible syntax for the target database.</p>\n<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Nested functions are handled. Eg. the CAST function is also incompatible, but since it is already part of the portion enclosed by ^^, it will be parsed.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Do not nest ^^ delimiters.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Note the use of the backticks to delimit identifiers.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;As of the time of this writing, only a few main functions are included. More will follow soon. If you would like to contribute, look into the <strong>/dropinbase/components/database/DSqlConvert.php</strong> class.</p>\n<h3>Identifier Delimiters</h3>\n<p>Each database engine\'s delimitters are defined in <em>pef_dropin.database_delim.&nbsp;</em> When generating code, Dropinbase uses this delimiter where needed.</p>\n<p>The database class for each engine (eg /setData/dibPgSqlPdo/components/dibPgSqlPdo.php) has code that replaces ` (backtick) with the engine\'s own delimitter in any SQL that is executed.</p>\n<h3>Concat</h3>\n<p>Concatenate strings, eg&nbsp;</p>\n<pre>SELECT id, `company name`, ^^CONCAT(\'hello\', `first name`, \' - \', CAST(id AS char))^^ AS greeting<br>FROM `company table`</pre>\n<p>Note, versions of SQL Server since 2012 support the CONCAT function, with a small difference: NULL values do not cause the whole expression to become null.</p>\n<h3>Cast As Char</h3>\n<p>Casts a value to a string type. Note, casting to other types is not supported. This function checks whether the last 8 characters is <strong>\' as char\'</strong> (case insensitive).</p>\n<p>See the example above under Concat.</p>\n<h3>Length</h3>\n<p>Returns the length of a string, eg</p>\n<pre>SELECT ^^Length(first_name)^^ as name_length<br>FROM individual</pre>\n<h3>Now</h3>\n<p>Returns the current date and time, eg</p>\n<pre>SELECT ^^Now()^^ AS this_time&nbsp;</pre>\n<h3>Ifnull</h3>\n<p>Returns a specified value if the expression provided is null, eg</p>\n<pre>SELECT ifnull(first_name, \'no name given\') AS name<br>FROM individual</pre>\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc102-dib'),
    (103, 'Technical Look at Creating Applications', 10, 90, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>This is a more technical look at what happens behind the scenes when applications are generated so that greater control can be exercised if needed.</p>\n<p>To work with a database, Dropinbase requires an entry in <strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong> and an associated record (with the same <em>id </em>value as the index used in <strong>Conn.php</strong>) in the <em>pef_database </em>table.</p>\n<p>When the user saves a new database connection using the <em><strong>Database Connections</strong></em>&nbsp;page, Dropinbase performs the following steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>creates the <em>pef_database </em>record using values from the \'template record\' in the same table (never delete the database record with name \'template record\'!)</li>\n<li>creates the associated <strong>Conn.php</strong> entry</li>\n<li>adds the list of tables in the database to <em>pef_table </em>and updates the <em>field_count </em>field for each</li>\n</ol>\n<p>When a base container is created, the <em>pef_port_item_id </em>and <em>pef_menu_item_id </em>(items on the base container)&nbsp;fields in <em>pef_database </em>and <em>pef_table</em> are updated. These fields are used as default values for new table records. Containers are generated based on field values in <em>pef_table</em>.</p>\n<p>When the <strong><em>Detect Outstanding Tasks</em></strong> button on <em>/nav/dibDatabaseForm </em>is clicked, Dropinbase uses SQL code from the <strong>setData </strong>dropin to inspect the design of tables and their relationships and then populates <em>pef_table </em>with suggested actions in the tasks fields.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>New tables at this point will only have a record in <em>pef_table</em> (not <em>pef_field)</em>.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Under Database Tasks (<em>/nav/dibDatabaseTasks</em>) the user has the chance to select a different base container template. Dropinbase will exchange the base container as requested.</p>\n<p>If the user selects a base container template that has an item named&nbsp;<strong>dashboardHolder</strong>, then a dashboard is automatically added to the application. The template for the dashboard container is named&nbsp;<strong>tmplDashboard.</strong></p>\n<p>New containers are generated by first copying template containers and then executing a list of follow-up actions as defined in the related pef_design, <em>pef_design_feature and pef_design_value </em>tables. The default "designs" to use for grids, forms and SQL grids can be set on the database record. These defaults carry over to new&nbsp;<em>pef_table </em>records (see the <em>pef_form_design_id </em>and <em>pef_grid_design_id </em>fields), and can be updated&nbsp;individually&nbsp;before containers are created.</p>\n<p>The names and captions of containers and items are obtained by applying a set of regular expressions to the names of tables and their fields. These expressions are stored only in the database record.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc103-dib'),
    (105, 'Setup Dropinbase', NULL, 20, 1, 'eleutheria', '', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc105-dib'),
    (107, 'Apache Settings', 105, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><strong>Please note that changing settings may cause malfunctioning (or damage!), especially if they are not set correctly. <br>Keep a backup of your old settings files, and proceed at your own risk.</strong></p>\n<p><em>Note, remember to save files and restart Apache for changes to take effect!&nbsp;</em></p>\n<h2>Apache Modules</h2>\n<p>The following Apache modules must be enabled:&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>mod_rewrite</li>\n<li>mod_headers</li>\n<li>mod_mime (normally enabled)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If you are enabling the /vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/installer/configs/<strong>.htaccess.for.production</strong> file, the following modules must be enabled which allows cache files to be zipped:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>mod_deflate</li>\n<li>mod_filters</li>\n<li>mod_expires</li>\n<li>mod_setenvif</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Virtual Host</h2>\n<p>Adding entries to the virtual host file allows you to host multiple installations of Dropinbase applications on a machine, using a separate URL for each.</p>\n<p>Example:</p>\n<p>You have two Dropinbase projects, stored in the following two folders:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>/www/project1/ &nbsp;</strong>- we want to use <strong>http://dib.net</strong> to access it.</li>\n<li><strong>/www/project2/</strong> &nbsp;- we want to use <strong>http://project2.dib.net</strong> to access it.</li>\n</ul>\n<ol>\n<li>In the main Apache .conf file (eg <strong>httpd.conf</strong>), the virtual hosts file must be included by ensuring the following line is uncommented/exists:<br>(note, the file location and even the name will differ between installations):<br>\n<ul>\n<li>Windows:\n<ul>\n<li>Include conf/extra/httpd-vhosts.conf&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Linux:\n<ul>\n<li>IncludeOptional sites-enabled/*.conf</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Create a Virtual Host section in the file referenced above for each application. See the examples below...</li>\n<li>Note the <strong>Allow, Deny</strong> and <strong>Order</strong> directives in older versions of Apache are deprecated and should be avoided. See&nbsp;<a href="https://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/howto/access.html">here&nbsp;</a>for more info.</li>\n<li>Port 80 is being used. This setting must correspond with the port configured in httpd.conf</li>\n<li>See&nbsp;<a href="https://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/howto/access.html">https://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/howto/access.html</a> for more info about allowing and disallowing connections.</li>\n<li><strong>AllowOverride all </strong>ensures that .htaccess can redirect URLs to the correct PHP files.</li>\n<li>Edit your hosts file if needed.\n<ul>\n<li>On Windows it is normally the following file C:\\Windows\\System32\\drivers\\etc\\hosts. (Note: open Notepad with "Run as Administrator" in order to save this file).</li>\n<li>Add lines that correspond with the URLs above, eg:\n<ul>\n<li>127.0.0.1&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;dib.net</li>\n<li>127.0.0.1&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;project2.dib.net</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Again, ensure that <strong>mod_rewrite </strong>is enabled in Apache\'s extensions.</li>\n</ol>\n<h4>Virtual Host File Entry Examples</h4>\n<pre>&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;<br>  &nbsp; DocumentRoot "C:/wamp/www/project1"<br>  &nbsp; ServerName dib.net<br> &nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;directory "C:/wamp/www/project1"&gt;<br> &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Options -Indexes +FollowSymLinks<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;AllowOverride all<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Require all granted<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;/directory&gt;<br>&lt;/VirtualHost&gt;<br><br>&lt;VirtualHost *:80&gt;<br>  &nbsp; DocumentRoot "C:/wamp/www/project2"<br>  &nbsp; ServerName project2.dib.net<br> &nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;directory "C:/wamp/www/project2"&gt;<br> &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Options -Indexes +FollowSymLinks<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;AllowOverride all<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Require all granted<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&lt;/directory&gt;<br>&lt;/VirtualHost&gt;\n</pre>\n<h2>Error Log</h2>\n<p>To enable error logging for Apache, ensure the following line is uncommented/exists in httpd.conf (replace the path with your own):</p>\n<p><code>ErrorLog "c:/wamp/logs/apache_error.log"</code></p>\n<p>It may be useful to log errors in Apache\'s log file for debugging purposes, but this file can become very large depending on the LogLevel parameter (see comments in httpd.conf).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc107-dib'),
    (108, 'PHP Settings', 105, 45, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><strong>Please note that changing settings may cause malfunctioning (or damage!), especially if they are not set correctly. <br>Keep a backup of your old settings files, and proceed at your own risk.</strong></p>\n<p><em>Note, remember to save files and restart the webserver for changes to take effect!</em></p>\n<h2>PHP Extensions</h2>\n<p>Extensions in <em>php.ini</em> that must be enabled:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>required:\n<ul>\n<li>pdo_sqlite and pdo_mysql&nbsp;</li>\n<li>curl</li>\n<li>mbstring</li>\n<li>openssl</li>\n<li>zip</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>relevant database pdo extensions (pdo_pgsql, php_pdo_sqlsrv_55_ts, etc.)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Note, to view installed modules, uncomment <code>//phpinfo(); die(); </code>in the <strong>/index.php</strong> file. Remember to comment this line again.</p>\n<p>The ZipArchive (used mainly for Excel related functions) should already be available. On certain Linux installations it is not always installed though. Use the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>sudo apt-get install php8.1-zip &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(<em>change 8.1 to your version of PHP)</em></li>\n<li>sudo service apache2 restart &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;(<em>restart Apache)&nbsp;</em></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Open_basedir Setting</h2>\n<p>Ensure that PHP can use the <strong>exec()</strong> command to run <strong>npm </strong>and also its own binary (eg <strong>php.exe</strong> (Windows) or <strong>php </strong>(Linux) etc):</p>\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Add</strong></span><strong> </strong>the following to the <strong>open_basedir </strong>setting in <strong>php.ini</strong>:</p>\n<p><em>(note, separate paths in Linux/Mac with a colon(:), and with a semicolon(;) in Windows)</em></p>\n<p><code><strong>:</strong>/root/.nvm/versions/node/v20.17.0/bin</code></p>\n<h2>Database Engines</h2>\n<p>See the ~navdocs(Connecting to Databases)~ section on how to configure PHP for various database engines.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc108-dib'),
    (111, 'Connecting to Databases', 105, 60, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Use the ~nav(dibConfigs, Database Connection Facility)~ to setup and test database connections.<br>Alternatively, edit the /configs/Conn.php file and/or test connection details using a third party application eg.&nbsp;<a href="https://www.heidisql.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HeidiSQL</a>&nbsp;or <a href="https://dbeaver.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DBeaver</a>..</p>\n<p>The following all needs to be in place for a successful connection with a secondary database (other than the main Dropinbase database):</p>\n<ol>\n<li>A compatible and running relational database server (eg MySQL / SQL Server / SQLite / PostgreSQL) containing a database.</li>\n<li>A username and password that has permissions to access both the database server and the database.</li>\n<li>The relevant PHP extentions to enable the connection.</li>\n<li>Connectivity to the database server (eg check firewall settings, internet access, etc).</li>\n<li>A record must be added to the Database table (pef_database).&nbsp;</li>\n<li>The connection details with an index value referencing the <strong>id </strong>of the database record above must be stored in the&nbsp;<strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong> file.</li>\n<li>The $DBINDEX, $LOGINDB constants and other database variables/constants in Dib.php must also match the entries in&nbsp;<strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong>.</li>\n<li>Also check the server specific settings below.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Specific Settings for Various Servers</h2>\n<p>Dropinbase makes use of PHP\'s PDO library to interface with databases.</p>\n<h3>MySQL / MariaDb / AuroraDb / etc.</h3>\n<p>Ensure that the PHP extension&nbsp;<strong>pdo_mysql </strong>is enabled.</p>\n<p>If the MySQL server is on a different machine than the webserver, ensure the firewall allows communication on the MySQL port (3306 by default).</p>\n<p>The collation of the dropinbase database is by default set to \'<strong>utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci</strong>\'. Ensure the <strong>collation </strong>property is set in the <strong>Conn.php</strong> file, and that your server\'s <strong>my.ini</strong> file is configured accordingly.<br>If you do not have access to the my.ini file, you can also change the collation for all tables - HeidiSQL has a useful bulk-tool to accomplish this.</p>\n<h3>SQLite</h3>\n<p>Ensure that the PHP extensions&nbsp;<strong>pdo_sqlite </strong>and <strong>php_sqlite3 </strong>are enabled.</p>\n<p>Ensure the webserver service has read/write rights on the SQLite database files.</p>\n<h3>PostgreSQL</h3>\n<p>Ensure that the PHP extension <strong>pdo_pgsql </strong>is&nbsp;enabled.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>PostgreSQL objects like tables and views are stored in schema\'s. One database can have many schemas.&nbsp;<br>A connection in Dropinbase sets the PostgreSQL <strong>search_path </strong>property to the schema(s) specified in the \'<strong>schema</strong>\' property of the <strong>Conn.php</strong> entry.<br>For eg. a value of \'<strong>my_schema, public</strong>\' will first look for a table in <strong>my_schema</strong>, and then the <strong>public </strong>schema.<br>If this value is empty, then this connection cannot be used for importing tables or synchronizing the design of tables with Dropinbase. Note, you can setup multiple connections to a particular database/schema for various purposes.</p>\n<h3>SQL Server</h3>\n<p>Dropinbase is compatible with all versions of SQL Server from 2005 onwards.</p>\n<p>SQL Server like tables and views are stored in schema\'s. One database can have many schemas. The \'dbo\' schema is the default.<br>If your tables, views, etc. are stored in a custom schema, then set the default schema for the user that is used in the connection:</p>\n<pre><span class="hljs-comment">-- Create a login</span> <br><span class="hljs-keyword">CREATE</span> LOGIN my_login <span class="hljs-keyword">WITH</span> PASSWORD <span class="hljs-operator">=</span> <span class="hljs-string">\'password\'</span>; <br><br><span class="hljs-comment">-- Create a user for the login and set the default schema</span> <br><span class="hljs-keyword">CREATE</span> <span class="hljs-keyword">USER</span> my_user <span class="hljs-keyword">FOR</span> LOGIN my_login <span class="hljs-keyword">WITH</span> DEFAULT_SCHEMA <span class="hljs-operator">=</span> my_schema;</pre>\n<p>Configuring the Database Connection:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Use SQL Server Configuration Manager to ensure:\n<ol>\n<li>SQL Server and SQL Server Browser services are running</li>\n<li>TCP/IP is enabled under SQL Native Client Configuration, Client Protocols and SQL Server Network Configuration, Protocols for xxx.</li>\n<li>Restart the database server for any changes to become active</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>If the webserver (eg Apache) is running on a different machine, add rules to the Windows Firewall on the machine that hosts SQL Server for the following:\n<ol>\n<li>If SQL Server is running as a named instance it will use dynamic ports. The client (the machine running the webserver) will obtain the port number from SQL Server Browser (listening on port 1434), and therefore the firewall must have a rule to allow incoming connections on port 1434 for the UTP protocol. Another rule is also needed to allow connections to the sqlserver.exe program in the /MsSql/Binn folder.</li>\n<li>Note if a static/fixed port no is configured then SQL Server Browser does not need to be running and this rule is not required either. The port that SQL Server is listening on (by default port 1433) must be opened on the firewall to accept incoming connections for the TCP protocol.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Use SQL Server Management Studio to ensure:\n<ol>\n<li>A database exists</li>\n<li>A username and password exists with permissions to access the database server and database remotely.\n<ol>\n<li>If the webserver is running on a different machine than SQL Server, check "Allow remote connections to the server" under SQL Server Properties, Connections.</li>\n<li>Check "SQL Server and Windows Authentication mode" under SQL Server Properties, Security</li>\n<li>A login exists for the user under Security, Logins. Under Login Properties, check:\n<ol>\n<li>"SQL Server Authentication" is used under General.</li>\n<li>"Default database" is the the particular database under General.</li>\n<li>"db_owner" is ticked under User Mapping, Role Membership for the particular database.</li>\n<li>"Grant" is ticked under Securables, Connect SQL.</li>\n<li>"Permission to connect to the database engine" is granted under Status.</li>\n<li>"Login" is enabled under Status.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Test that the connection works by using&nbsp;a third party app (eg Heidisql.com) or create a ODBC connection (Windows Control Panel, Administrative Tools, Data Sources (ODBC)).</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>The PHP PDO extentions for SQL Server must be enabled. Note that both 32 and 64 bit versions are available - install the one that matches your version of PHP:&nbsp;\n<ol>\n<li>Check compatibility of <strong>ALL </strong>the following in the different tables provided here:&nbsp;<br><a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/connect/php/microsoft-php-drivers-for-sql-server-support-matrix?view=sql-server-ver15#sql-server-version-certified-compatibility" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/connect/php/microsoft-php-drivers-for-sql-server-support-matrix?view=sql-server-ver15#sql-server-version-certified-compatibility</a><br>&nbsp; - Operating system version&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; - PHP version&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; - SQL Server version</li>\n<li>Then download the correct driver file and copy files to the in PHP extension folder\n<ol>\n<li><a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/connect/php/download-drivers-php-sql-server" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/connect/php/download-drivers-php-sql-server</a></li>\n<li>If you need older drivers then get them here:&nbsp;<a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/connect/php/release-notes-php-sql-driver?view=sql-server-ver15#previous-releases">https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/connect/php/release-notes-php-sql-driver?view=sql-server-ver15#previous-releases</a></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Check the PHP .dll file name you are using in the PHP bin folder, eg <strong>php7ts.dll</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>Here <strong>7ts&nbsp;</strong>means PHP Version 7 and Thread Safe</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Rename the driver files copied to the extension folder depending on PHP 86/64 version.\n<ol>\n<li>Find the matching PHP .dll file under Driver Versions here: <a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/connect/php/system-requirements-for-the-php-sql-driver?view=sql-server-ver15" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/sql/connect/php/system-requirements-for-the-php-sql-driver?view=sql-server-ver15</a></li>\n<li>Now rename the corresponding driver files,&nbsp;remove <strong>_x86</strong> &nbsp;or <strong>_x64</strong> so it says for eg. <strong>php_pdo_sqlsrv_74_ts.dll</strong></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Edit <strong>php.ini</strong>, add lines:<strong><br></strong>extension=php_pdo_sqlsrv_74_ts.dll<br>extension=php_sqlsrv_74_ts.dll</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>The relevant Microsoft SQL Server Feature Pack must be installed on the server depending on your version of Windows. Install the highest version of the Feature Pack.&nbsp;<br>The Feature Pack will install the Native Client drivers required by the PHP drivers for connecting to SQL Server. As at Sep 2023, the 2012 version works for all future releases:<br>\n<ol>\n<li><a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=50402" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=50402</a></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Restart the webserver</li>\n<li>Edit /index.php and enable the <code>phpinfo(); die;</code> line.\n<ol>\n<li>Check under PDO section. You are looking for <strong>pdo_sqlsrv</strong></li>\n<li>If it does not appear, the PHP extension for SQL Server has not been installed correctly.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Make sure your connection string in /configs/Conn.php is properly configured (see Example_Conn.php).</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Issues on Older SQL Servers</strong></p>\n<p>The mssql-odbc option\'s driver (SQL Server Native Client) has for many years had a bug which expects PDO parameters in subqueries to all be of type text. The workaround implemented is to replace parameters, eg :id, with code that casts them to varchar and then to their respective type, eg. CAST(CAST(:id AS varchar) AS integer). See&nbsp;<a href="https://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=44643">https://bugs.php.net/bug.php?id=44643</a>. MARS also needs to be enabled on the connection allowing multiple queries to execute concurrently. See&nbsp;<a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2701992/turning-on-multiple-result-sets-in-an-odbc-connection-to-sql-server">https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2701992/turning-on-multiple-result-sets-in-an-odbc-connection-to-sql-server</a>.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>SQL Server on Linux</strong></p>\n<p>This has not been tested but is possible since SQL Server 2017.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc111-dib'),
    (112, 'ExtJs Layout Tips', 324, 150, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3>Layout Basics</h3>\n\n<p>This topic is in no way an exhaustive explanation of managing layout in ExtJs, but is useful for most common scenario&#39;s. For more information consult the ExtJs documentation and other references provided below.</p>\n\n<p>In ExtJs the hbox and vbox layout, implemented in Dropinbase by layouthbox and layoutvbox, are commonly used. Their purpose is to cause their child items to be arranged horizontally next to or vertically below one another. Layout configs can be applied to further cause items to stretch accross available space or be positioned in specific places (eg top, left, center, etc.)</p>\n\n<p>For more information, see&nbsp;http://training.figleaf.com/tutorials/senchacomplete/chapter2/lesson4/4.cfm</p>\n\n<p>Another useful layout is &#39;column&#39; (or layoutcolumn). It is similar to hbox, but implements a float-left behaviour that will cause items to drop to the next level if space is restricted horizontally.</p>\n\n<p>See&nbsp;http://stackoverflow.com/questions/18311024/what-is-difference-beetween-layouthbox-and-layoutcolumn</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2>Useful tips</h2>\n\n<ol>\n	<li>If you use layoutvbox, make sure to set the width property of child panels (eg containers, layouthbox, layoutfit, panel, etc), or use layout configs (eg align : &#39;stretch&#39;). The default width is 0 which will cause these panels to be hidden. Same applies to layouthbox and height, although one difference is that you can set the width to &#39;100%&#39; (include single quotes) which will cause it to fill available space horizontally (any other percentage will proportionally fill available space).</li>\n	<li>Use the flex config to proportionally assign widths and heights to child items of layouthbox and layoutvbox respectfully. Eg, if an item has a flex value of 2 and the sum of flex values of all items is 5, then the item will fill two-fifths of available space.</li>\n	<li>&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Often the best way to learn is by example, and will be our approach here.</p>\n\n<p>Scenario 1</p>\n\n<p>You want a dibContainer with 2 grids and one textareabox, all vertically below one another that fills the available screen size.</p>\n\n<p>Add the 2 grids and the textareabox as child items to a layoutvbox (a panel which causes its child items to be vertically arranged within). Set the &#39;layout configs&#39; of the layoutvbox as follows:</p>\n\n<p>align : &#39;stretch&#39;, pack: &#39;start&#39;</p>\n\n<p>These layout configs will cause the items to stretch and fill the available screen size horizontally</p>\n\n<p>For non-programmers it is useful to understand a bit about JavaScript frameworks (like ExtJs) that consist of &quot;objects&quot;, eg textfields and buttons, before we go further. Objects have:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Configs (eg width, height, hidden),</li>\n	<li>Properties (eg frameSize),</li>\n	<li>Methods (eg setHidden, collapse, getValue), and</li>\n	<li>Events (eg click, activate, change).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>They mostly inherrit these from an ancestory of parent objects. Eg a textfield has a <em>width </em>config and a <em>setHidden</em>&nbsp;method, but so does a datefield since they both inherrit from the base object/class Ext.Component.</p>\n\n<p>By pre-configuring the values of <strong>configs </strong>an initial layout/state/behaviour can be obtained. By calling <strong>methods </strong>the objects can change dynamically and perform certain functions, eg a textfield&#39;s width can be adjusted and its value can be set. &quot;<strong>Properties</strong>&quot; are shared configs between all objects of the same type and are rarely set - they are mostly for internal use by the ExtJs framework. <strong>Events </strong>are triggers that are activated on certain actions/&quot;events&quot;, eg &#39;n button has a &quot;click&quot; event and a textfield has a &quot;change&quot; event. These events can be utilized in JavaScript to execute code.</p>\n\n<p>All objects in ExtJs inherrit their type from the base object/class Ext.Component. Certain components can contain other components, eg Fieldsets can contain textfields and datefields etc. These components inherrit from Ext.Container, which in turn inherrits from (ie extends) Ext.Component. It is useful to study the configs of Ext.Component and Ext.Container as they are commonly used. Components of type Ext.Container have default layout managers configured - see <a href="http://localhost/extjs51/5.1.0-apidocs/#!/api/Ext.enums.Layout">Ext.enums.Layout</a>. ExtJs utilizes &quot;layout managers&quot; to automatically configure the sizing and positioning of items within them. The following Ext.Container components are often used:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>vbox - positions child components vertically below one another</li>\n	<li>hbox&nbsp;- positions child components horizontally next to one another</li>\n	<li>column - positions&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\n\n<h3>Container Height and Width</h3>\n\n<p>Typically you&rsquo;ll specify at least one of the following:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li><a href="http://extjs.com/deploy/dev/docs/?class=Ext.grid.GridPanel&amp;member=height">height</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://extjs.com/deploy/dev/docs/?class=Ext.grid.GridPanel&amp;member=autoHeight">autoHeight</a></li>\n	<li>or within a container with a size-managing&nbsp;<a href="http://extjs.com/deploy/dev/docs/?class=Ext.Container&amp;member=layout">layout</a>, eg &#39;fit&#39;, &#39;border&#39; or &#39;anchor&#39;</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Fit, Hbox, Vbox</h3>\n\n<p>See&nbsp;http://training.figleaf.com/tutorials/senchacomplete/chapter2/lesson4/4.cfm</p>\n\n<p>layoutfit - only makes sense if there is one child item, whereas layouthbox and layoutvbox makes no sense if there is only one child item.</p>\n\n<h3>Flex</h3>\n\n<p>This config is only used when this Component is rendered by a Container which has been configured to use a&nbsp;<strong><a href="http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/3.4.0/#!/api/Ext.layout.BoxLayout">BoxLayout</a>.</strong>&nbsp;Each child Component with a&nbsp;<code>flex</code>&nbsp;property will be flexed either vertically (by a VBoxLayout) or horizontally (by an HBoxLayout) according to the item&#39;s&nbsp;<strong>relative</strong>&nbsp;<code>flex</code>&nbsp;value compared to the sum of all Components with&nbsp;<code>flex</code>&nbsp;value specified. Any child items that have either a&nbsp;<code>flex = 0</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>flex = undefined</code>&nbsp;will not be &#39;flexed&#39; (the initial size will not be changed).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3><a href="http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/3.4.0/#!/api/Ext.Panel-cfg-autoHeight">autoHeight</a>&nbsp;: Boolean</h3>\n\n<p><code>true</code>&nbsp;to use height:&#39;auto&#39;,&nbsp;<code>false</code>&nbsp;to use fixed height (defaults to&nbsp;<code>false</code>).&nbsp;<strong>Note</strong>: Setting&nbsp;<code>autoHeight: true</code>&nbsp;means that the browser will manage the panel&#39;s height based on its contents, and that Ext will not manage it at all. If the panel is within a layout that manages dimensions (<code>fit</code>,&nbsp;<code>border</code>, etc.) then setting&nbsp;<code>autoHeight: true</code>&nbsp;can cause issues with scrolling and will not generally work as expected since the panel will take on the height of its contents rather than the height required by the Ext layout.</p>\n\n<h2>More Information</h2>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Using Layout Managers: <a href="http://www.manning.com/garcia3/ExtJSinAction2E_CH05.pdf">http://www.manning.com/garcia3/ExtJSinAction2E_CH05.pdf</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc112-dib'),
    (113, 'Migrating from Other Applications', NULL, 200, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc113-dib'),
    (115, 'Microsoft Access', 113, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Steps</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Create an empty database in MariaDb/MySQL (HeidiSql is a very capable interface to MySQL, SQL Server and PostgresSQL).</li>\n<li>Use ODBC to export the tables to the database (see steps below)</li>\n<li>Ensure table structure and relationships are created before importing to Dropinbase (see steps below).</li>\n<li>Import tables to Dropinbase</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Export tables using ODBC</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Download and install ODBC drivers for MySQL.</li>\n<li>Go to ODBC Connections in Windows -&gt; System DSN. Create a ODBC connection to the MySQL database and test it.</li>\n<li>Name and save this connection</li>\n<li>Open the Access database that contains the Access tables (note, not <span style="text-decoration: underline;">links</span> to the tables, but the actual tables) and go to Tables.</li>\n<li>Repeat the following for each of the tables you want to export:</li>\n<li>Right-click on the table, click Export and choose ODBC under the "Save as type" dropdown. Confirm the table name...</li>\n<li>Click on the Machine Data Source tab, and double-click the DSN name created above.</li>\n<li>The table should be migrated now. You can use a tool such as HeidiSql to design and maintain data in MySQL tables.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Correct table structure before importing to Dropinbase</h3>\n<p>It is important to check and correct the following in mysql tables to guide the Dropinbase import process:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Primary keys are defined</li>\n<li>Foreign keys are defined</li>\n<li>Unique indexes on relevant fields (this will cause Dropinbase to identify these fields as search fields).</li>\n<li>Required fields - set the "Allow Null" columns</li>\n<li>Field and table names must not have spaces or non-alphanumeric characters.</li>\n<li>Change BIT fields to tinyint (also set default to 0 and make them required fields that don\'t allow Nulls).</li>\n<li>Choose either date or datetime for date fields as required.</li>\n<li>Use Decimal for currency fields.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc115-dib'),
    (116, 'Troubleshooting and Debugging', NULL, 100, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc116-dib'),
    (117, 'Dropdownlists where Foreign Keys Point to Non-Primary Keys', 310, 70, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The auto-generated PHP CRUD files for dropdown-lists return primary key values as the "binding" value for fields by default. This causes an error or invalid data being captured when a field\'s relationship references a field in another table that is not the primary key. <br>There are a few ways to resolve the problem:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Create a query for the dropdown where the primary field is not the primary key but the other field being referenced. Then reference this query for the dropdown in the Designer for that item. Clear the permission files in the Designer and refresh the relevant page in the browser that contains the dropdown. A new SQL based CRUD file will automatically be created next time the dropdown list is required.</li>\n<li>Find the relevant PHP CRUD file in the <strong>dibCode </strong>folder (eg LTable_client_2663_x1x.php) and change the primary key field in it to the other field being referenced. To prohibit the file from being recreated, move it to a /static/crud folder and edit the <strong>Crud Store Controller</strong> field for this dropdown accordingly (eg /static/crud/LTable_client_2663_x1x.php). Remember you can change the PHP CRUD file\'s name, but then you should also rename the class inside the .php file accordingly. Clear the permission files in the Designer and refresh the relevant page in the browser that contains the dropdown.</li>\n<li>Change the relationship in the database to reference the primary key instead. You will need to change the related entries in the <em>pef_fk&nbsp; table </em>as well. Clear the related PHP CRUD files in the Designer, and refresh the relevant page in the browser that contains the dropdown..</li>\n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc117-dib'),
    (119, 'Eleutheria', NULL, 90, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc119-dib'),
    (120, 'Domains', 119, 10, 0, 'none', '<p>Eleutheria only processes content within eleutheria domains, similar to php&#39;s &lt;?php  ?&gt; tags. Each Eleutheria domain typically defines a recordset,</p>\n\n<p>that is retreived from a database or other datasource, and as such, a domain will loop for each row in the recordset. Thisallows the construction of self populating tables etc.</p>\n\n<p>For Example: </p>\n\n<p>  |rssql1;SELECT * FROM users|</p>\n\n<p> |End1|</p>\n\n<p>will loop once for each row returned from the table &#39;users&#39;.</p>\n\n<p></p>\n\n<p>There are two ways to define an Eleutheria domain:</p>\n\n<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="width:986px">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n			<p>Function</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Description</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Details</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Example</p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n			<p><strong>|rs#;</strong><em><strong>recordsource</strong></em>[<em>;row/cell</em>][<em>;sql criteria</em>][<em>;sql sort order</em>][<em>;sql limit</em>][<em>;database id</em>]<strong>|</strong></p>\n\n			<p></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Used to define the start of an eleutheria domain.</p>\n\n			<p>The # notates a domain number. This number is used to distinguish one domain from another(especially if nested).</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p><strong>#</strong> - domain number(can be any integer)<br />\n			<em>recordsource</em> - named sql statement in report table<br />\n			row - duplicate whole table row (used in tables only)<br />\n			cell - duplicate whole cell (used in tables only)<br />\n			<em>sql criteria</em> - valid sql criteria<br />\n			<em>sql sort order</em> - valid sql sorting clause<br />\n			<em>sql limit</em> - valid sql limit clause<br />\n			<em>database id</em> - identifier of database in database table</p>\n\n			<p>Notes: No spaces between &#39;|&#39; and &#39;rs&#39;, &#39;| rs... |&#39; is invalid. &#39;|rs...|&#39; is valid.<br />\n			Merge fields/expressions inside domain definitions are replaced from the enclosing (current) domain.</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>|rs1;Individuals|<br />\n			|rs2;Individuals;;name &gt; &#39;M&#39;;city desc, `last name`;5|<br />\n			|rs3;Individuals;row;;city, `last name`;;2|<br />\n			|rs4;Individuals;cell;name &gt; &#39;M&#39;;;5;2|<br />\n			|rs5;Individual;;organisation_id = ~org_id~|</p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n			<p><strong>|rssql#;</strong><em><strong>sql statement</strong></em>[<em>;row/cell</em>][<em>;database id</em>]<strong>|</strong></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Alternative way to define the start a domain.</p>\n\n			<p>With this definition, you can use a sql-statement to retrieve a set of records.</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p><strong>#</strong> - domain number<br />\n			row - duplicate whole table row (used in tables only)<br />\n			cell - duplicate whole cell (used in tables only)<em>sql statement</em> - valid sql statement<br />\n			<em>database id</em> - identifier of database in database table</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>|rssql6;SELECT * FROM individual|<br />\n			|rssql7;SELECT name, `last name` FROM individual;2|</p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n			<p><strong>|End#|</strong></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Used to define the end of a domain.</p>\n\n			<p>Note: each sub-domain needs to be &#39;Ended&#39; before its superior domain is &#39;Ended&#39;:</p>\n\n			<p><strong>|rs1;</strong>Individual<strong>|</strong><br />\n			    <strong>|rs2;</strong>ItemsOrdered<strong>|</strong><br />\n			    <strong>|End2|<br />\n			|End1|</strong></p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p># - must match the number of the domain it is closing</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>|End1|<br />\n			|End7|</p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Domains can be nested, as seen above, however parent domains remain isolated from their child domains. To access a variable from a parent domain see (link to globalising variable)</p>\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc120-dib'),
    (121, 'Eleutheria Functions', 119, 20, 1, 'eleutheria', '/dropinbase/extensions/eleutheria/eleutheria.class.php', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc121-dib'),
    (124, 'Eleutheria Fields', 119, 10, 0, 'none', '<p>Eleutheria fields are used to place values from the current row of the domains recordsource.</p>\n\n<p>There are two methods for placing values:</p>\n\n<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="width:956px">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n			<p>Function</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Description</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Details</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Example</p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n			<p>~fieldname~</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Used to place a value from a recordsourcerow</p>\n\n			<p>Note: cannot be used inside functions</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>fieldname - the name of field that exists as a column in the recordsource of its enclosing domain</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>&lt;table&gt;<br />\n			&lt;tr&gt;<br />\n			&lt;td&gt;No&lt;/td&gt;<br />\n			&lt;td&gt;ID&lt;/td&gt;<br />\n			&lt;td&gt;Name&lt;td/&gt;<br />\n			&lt;td&gt;Email&lt;td/&gt;<br />\n			&lt;/tr&gt;<br />\n			|rssql1; select id, name, email from users|<br />\n			&lt;tr&gt;<br />\n			&lt;td&gt; ~#~ &lt;/td&gt;<br />\n			&lt;td&gt; ~id~ &lt;/td&gt;<br />\n			&lt;td&gt; ~name~ &lt;td/&gt;<br />\n			&lt;td&gt; ~email~ &lt;td/&gt;<br />\n			&lt;/tr&gt;<br />\n			|End1|<br />\n			&lt;/table&gt;</p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n			<p>~fld(fieldname)~</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Serves the same purpose as above, however can be used inside functions unlike the method above</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>fieldname - the name of field that exists as a column in the recordsource of its enclosing domain</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>~if(fld(bob)==&#39;bob&#39;, &#39;echo true&#39;)~</p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p></p>\n\n<p>You may have noticed the special field ~#~ above:</p>\n\n<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="width:956px">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Function</td>\n			<td>Description</td>\n			<td>Example</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>\n			<p>~#~</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>Returns the current record number within current domain</p>\n			</td>\n			<td>\n			<p>~#~</p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc124-dib'),
    (126, 'ET*if', 121, 15, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">Classic if-function. If the CONDITION is TRUE then PART1 is processed, else if present, PART2 is processed</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">Note, as with all eleutheria functions, if-functions can be nested</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> if(CONDITION, PART1[, PART2])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> CONDITION</b> - the condition to evaluate using EvalCriteria that must result in either TRUE or FALSE.\r\n</li><li><b> PART1</b> - an Eleutheria expression to process in case CONDITION is TRUE\r\n</li><li><b> PART2</b> - an optional Eleutheria expression to process in case CONDITION is FALSE\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li><b> The CONDITION can be built up with other expressions</b> - be careful of including field values without wrapping them in single-quotes (see examples)\r\n</li><li> Use single quotes, eg ~if(&apos;fld(notes)&apos;&gt;&apos;This my expresson: 2&gt;=1&apos;, ..., ...)~, to prohibit the following symbols from interfering with conditional expressions:\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">&lt; &gt; &lt;= &gt;= &lt;&gt; != or and ( ) like isnull</span>\r\n</li><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*exists" title="Dropinbase Features">exists</dib-nav>, <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*nv" title="Dropinbase Features">nv</dib-nav> and <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*fld" title="Dropinbase Features">fld</dib-nav> functions.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> if(fld(something),smaller,greater)</code> - indeterminate: fld(something) could contain an expression like &apos;1 &lt; 4 or 3 &gt; 4&apos; (the &apos;or&apos; will be evaluated as part of the condition!)\r\n</li><li><code> if(&apos;fld(something)&apos;&lt;3,smaller,greater)</code> - the single quotes prevents any &apos;and&apos;, &apos;or&apos; or &apos;&lt;&apos; etc in fld(something) to be evaluated. Prints &apos;smaller&apos; if fld(something) contains eg &apos;apple&apos;\r\n</li><li><code> if(&apos;fld(bob)&apos;=, Bob is gone, This is Bob)</code> - prints &apos;Bob is gone&apos; if fld(bob) retuns nothing\r\n</li><li><code> if(2&gt;1, hello, bye)</code> - prints &apos;hello&apos;\r\n</li><li><code> if(1&gt;2, hello)</code> - prints nothing\r\n</li><li><code> if(1&gt;2, if(2&gt;1, hello, bye), if(3&gt;4, really, yup))</code> - prints &apos;yup&apos;\r\n</li><li><code> if(2 fld(condition) 1, hello, bye)</code> - prints &apos;bye&apos; if fld(condition) contains eg &apos;&lt;&apos; and &apos;hello&apos; if it contains eg &apos;&gt;=&apos;\r\n</li><li><code> if(&apos;a&apos;&lt;&apos;b&apos;AND&apos;ef&apos;=&apos;ef&apos; and (5 &gt;= 6OR(&apos;aa&apos; &lt; &apos;ab&apos;)), yup, nope)</code> - prints &apos;yup&apos;&apos;\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc126-dib'),
    (127, 'ET*fld', 121, 10, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Prints a value. First checks if it is a special system defined value, then checks overrideArray,</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">then checks the current domain&apos;s recordset, and if still not found, prints an empty string.</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">Will html/xml encode values in html/xml documents by default (if not prevented by the encode() function)</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> fld(FIELDNAME or SYSTEM_FIELD[, VALUE_IF_EMPTY][, DIRECTIVE])</span></div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">FIELDNAME - name of a field in the current record domain</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">SYSTEM_FIELD - one of the following:</span>\r\n<ul><li><b>	#</b> - returns current record number\r\n</li><li><b>	*</b> - returns count of records in current domain\r\n</li><li><b>	$delim</b> - returns Delim character\r\n</li><li><b>	$delimDb</b> - returns DelimDb character\r\n</li><li><b>	$etGlobal</b> - returns etGlobal character\r\n</li><li><b>	$now;format</b> - the current date&amp;time;formatted with a PHP format (eg Y-m-d H:i:s)\r\n</li><li><b>	$start</b> - sets the merge index to the beginning of the expression causing the expression to be processed from the start again. WARNING!! use with care since merged user data can contain expressions!\r\n</ul><span class="et-section-line">VALUE_IF_EMPTY - value to return if FIELDNAME is an empty string or spaces. Leave blank to ignore. Not applicable if a SYSTEM_FIELD is specified.</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">DIRECTIVE - one or more of the following (semicolon delimitted):</span>\r\n<ul><li><b>	squote</b> - escape a single quote (&apos;) with a \\ eg \\&apos;\r\n</li><li><b>	dquote</b> - escape a double quote (&quot;) with a \\ eg \\&quot;\r\n</li><li><b>	bslash</b> - escape a backslash (\\) with a \\ eg \\\\\r\n</li><li><b>	html</b> - html encode the content (is done by default in html documents)\r\n</li><li><b>	xml</b> - xml encode the content (is done by default in xml documents)\r\n</li><li><b>	js</b> - escape javascript\r\n</li><li><b>	css</b> - escape css\r\n</li><li><b>	attr</b> - escape html attributes\r\n</li><li><b>	url</b> - escape portions injected into an url with rawurlencode\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Fields are replaced first from the overrideArray to facilitate overiding, and then from the current domain.\r\n</li><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*setval" title="Dropinbase Features">setval</dib-nav> and <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*getval" title="Dropinbase Features">getval</dib-nav> that is used to set and access values in globalArray.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code>	fld(#)</code> - prints eg 13\r\n</li><li><code>	fld($delim)</code> - prints ~\r\n</li><li><code>	fld($delimDb)</code> - prints |\r\n</li><li><code>	fld($now;Ym)</code> - prints 201607\r\n</li><li><code>	fld(first_name)</code> - prints eg Paul\r\n</li><li><code>	fld(notes,,dquote)</code> - prints eg There is meaning in \\&quot;Gahndi&apos;s memoirs\\&quot;\r\n</li><li><code>	fld(notes,,squote;dquote;html)</code> - prints eg There is meaning in \\&quot;Gahndi\\&apos;s memoirs\\&quot;\r\n</li><li><code>	fld(table_id,-999)</code> - will return -999 if table_id is null or &apos;&apos;\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc127-dib'),
    (129, 'ET*getdb', 121, 11, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> returns a value, or a list of values from the result of a SQL SELECT statement</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> getdb(SELECT_CLAUSE, FROM_CLAUSE[, WHERE_CLAUSE=&apos;&apos;][, SEPARATOR=&apos;,&apos;][, DATABASE=(maindb)][, TEMPLATESTRING=&apos;&apos;])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> SELECT_CLAUSE</b> - A SQL expression, eg first_name, or [*CONCAT(age, &apos; years&apos;)*]\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">Common Table Expressions (CTE&apos;s) can be included, eg [* CTE: WITH aaa AS (SELECT name From myTable) CTEEND CONCAT(age, &apos; years&apos;)*]</span>\r\n</li><li><b> FROM_CLAUSE</b> - the SQL From clause, eg tbIndividual, or tbIndividual i LEFT JOIN tbSales s ON s.individualId = s.id\r\n</li><li><b> WHERE_CLAUSE</b> - the SQL Where clause, eg last_name&gt;&apos;S&apos; AND [*length(first_name)*] &gt; 4\r\n</li><li><b> SEPARATOR</b> - if more than one record is returned, values are delimited with SEPARATOR. The default is a comma (,).\r\n</li><li><b> DATABASE</b> - index of database other than the MAIN database set with setMainDb(). Can also be the name of a container that is linked to a table or SQL query (which so doing identifies the database to use)\r\n</li><li><b> TEMPLATESTRING</b> - a template to use for each record returned.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">When TEMPLATESTRING is specified, SELECT_CLAUSE can return multiple fields.</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">* is used as field delimiter, eg *name*-*id*[*age*]</span>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> # in the output is replaced with a running number\r\n</li><li> If SEPARTOR=first_1, only the first record will be used (even if query returns multiple records)\r\n</li><li> WARNING! SQL injection risk if merge-fields are used without <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*param" title="Dropinbase Features">param</dib-nav>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li> getdb(vatperc,admin,year = &apos;2010&apos;)\r\n</li><li><code> getdb(name, person, id = param(id) OR id = param(getval(otherId)) )</code> - use of the param() function to avoid SQL injection\r\n</li><li><code> getdb(concat(&apos;#. &apos;, name), person)</code> - # is replaced with no.\r\n</li><li><code> getdb(name, person,,[*, *])</code> - records are separated with &apos;, &apos; (default is &apos;,&apos;)\r\n</li><li><code> getdb(vatperc,admin,year = &apos;2010&apos;,:,2)</code> - use &apos;: as separator and specify database id=2 (can be containername).\r\n</li><li><code> getdb([*id, name, age*], person,,/,,*name*-*id*[*age*])</code> - use &apos;name - id [age]&apos; as a template for each record, and &apos;/&apos; as record separator\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc129-dib'),
    (130, 'ET*getval', 121, 14, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> returns the value in the global array (globalArray) referenced by key NAME</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> getval(KEY[, PART1][, PART2])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> KEY</b> - the key/identifier name\r\n</li><li><b> PART1</b> - if KEY does not reference an array and the value returned is &apos;&apos; or null, then return PART1\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">if KEY references an array, then PART1 is a delimitter to include between values, where \\r, \\n and \\t can used for new line and tab characters</span>\r\n</li><li><b> PART2</b> - Provides basic escaping:\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">if present, any \\ in the value is replaced with \\\\</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">Additionally:</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">if dquote - will replace any &quot; with \\&quot;</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">if squote - will replace any &apos; with \\&apos;</span>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> If KEY does not exist in the global array, an empty string is returned.\r\n</li><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*setval" title="Dropinbase Features">setval</dib-nav> and <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*getparams" title="Dropinbase Features">getparams</dib-nav> which adds values to the global array (and optionally prints them)\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> getval(a)</code> - will print hello, assuming global array(&apos;a&apos;=&gt;&apos;hello&apos;, &apos;b&apos;=&gt;&apos;&apos;)\r\n</li><li><code> getval(b)</code> - will print an empty string, assuming global array(&apos;a&apos;=&gt;&apos;hello&apos;, &apos;b&apos;=&gt;&apos;&apos;)\r\n</li><li><code> getval(d)</code> - will print an empty string, assuming global array(&apos;a&apos;=&gt;&apos;hello&apos;, &apos;b&apos;=&gt;&apos;&apos;)\r\n</li><li><code> getval(b, joe)</code> - will print joe, assuming global array(&apos;a&apos;=&gt;&apos;hello&apos;, &apos;b&apos;=&gt;&apos;&apos;)\r\n</li><li><code> getval(f,,squote)</code> - will print O\\&apos;Reilly, assuming global array(&apos;f&apos;=&gt;&quot;O&apos;Reilly&quot;)\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc130-dib'),
    (131, 'ET*setval', 121, 37, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> updates a field name value in the current recordset (if it exists), else sets a value in the global array</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> setval(KEY, VALUE[, CRITERIA])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> KEY</b> - the key/identifier name\r\n</li><li><b> VALUE</b> - the value to be assigned\r\n</li><li><b> CRITERIA</b> - an optional condition to be checked. If present and TRUE, the VALUE is set. If present and FALSE, the VALUE is not set.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> If KEY already exists in the global array, the new VALUE is assigned\r\n</li><li> Names are case sensitive\r\n</li><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*getval" title="Dropinbase Features">getval</dib-nav> which returns values from the global array, and <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*getparams" title="Dropinbase Features">getparams</dib-nav> which adds values to the global array (and optionally prints them)\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> setval(A, 123)</code> - will assign the value 123 to A\r\n</li><li><code> setval(name, john)</code> - will change the value of fld(name) to &apos;john&apos; (if &apos;name&apos; is a field name in the current record scope)\r\n</li><li><code> setval(a, getval(A))</code> - will assign the contents of the global variable A to a\r\n</li><li><code> setval(A,)</code> - will assign an empty string to A\r\n</li><li><code> setval(A, 123, &apos;fld(b)&apos;&gt;m)</code> - will assign 123 to A only if fld(b) contains something like &apos;o&apos; (which is greater than &apos;m&apos;)\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc131-dib'),
    (132, 'ET*inclfile', 121, 19, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> includes the content of an Eleutheria template, and parses optional global variables</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> inclfile(FOLDER, FILENAME[,PARAMETER1, PARAMETER2, etc.)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> FOLDER</b> - if &apos;templatefolder&apos; then the folder of the main template is used\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">if the first 8 characters is &apos;/dropins&apos; then the file is searched first in the main /dropins folder, and if not found, then in the core API /dropins folder</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">else the path as provided is used</span>\r\n</li><li><b> FILENAME</b> -  a semicolon delimited list of file names; the first one found is used. Eg textFile.et.txt;textFile2.txt\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">a &apos;&gt;&apos; character is used to indicate minification type. Eg textFile.et.html&gt;html;textFile2.txt</span>\r\n</li><li><b> PARAMETER1</b> - A name, value pair using the format NAME:VALUE. ^NAME^ is replaced in FILENAME with VALUE, before any other action occurs.\r\n</li><li><b> PARAMETER2/3/4/etc</b> - same as PARAMETER1\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">The following steps are executed in order:</span>\r\n<ul><li> The file contents is read into a temporary variable\r\n</li><li> PARAMETER values are replaced first using ^ as delimiter for variables,\r\n</li><li> Values in the globalArray array are replaced, also using ^ as delimiter for variables.\r\n</li><li> Sections (eg |Section A| ... |End A|) and Subdomains (eg |rssql2;...| ... |End2|) are removed from the text, and replaced with placed holders.\r\n</li><li> The text is included in the document\r\n</li><li> The file pointer is placed at the beginning of the included text in order to process any merge fields and expressions.\r\n</ul><span class="et-section-line">Other Notes:</span>\r\n<ul><li> the string after NAME: in each PARAMETER is not trimmed! Ie. spaces are included.\r\n</li><li> Keep FOLDER and FILENAME case sensitive, to avoid issues on Linux with not finding files.\r\n</li><li> Warning: Allowing user values to determine any portion of FOLDER or FILENAME is a security risk!\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li> inclfile(/dropins/main/templates/, HelpSection.txt)\r\n</li><li><code> inclfile(&apos;templatefolder&apos;, fld(myTemplate);useMeAsLastOption.txt)</code> - if fld(myTemplate) is not found, then use useMeAsLastOption.txt\r\n</li><li><code> inclfile(&apos;templatefolder&apos;, containerModelInit.et.js, crit1:ABC, crit2:[*^sentence^*])</code> - Note how [* *] is used to ensure that the contents of ^sentence^ (which is replaced before anything else) does not break the template syntax.\r\n</li><li><code> inclfile(&apos;templatefolder&apos;, containerModelInit.et.js, crit1:)</code> - this will replace ^crit^ with an empty string\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc132-dib'),
    (133, 'ET*incl', 121, 18, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> includes the content of a section placed in memory, and parses optional global parameters</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> incl(SECTIONNAME[, PARAMETER1, PARAMETER2, etc.])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> SECTIONNAME</b> -  the name of a section in the current file, or in an file already included using <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*inclfile" title="Dropinbase Features">inclfile</dib-nav>\r\n</li><li><b> PARAMETER1</b> - A name, value pair using the format NAME:VALUE. ~NAME~ is replaced with VALUE, before any other action occurs.\r\n</li><li><b> PARAMETER2/3/4/etc</b> - same as PARAMETER1\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">The following steps are executed in order:</span>\r\n<ul><li> The section contents is read into a temporary variable\r\n</li><li> PARAMETER values are replaced first using ~ as delimiter for variables,\r\n</li><li> Sections (eg |Section A| ... |End A|) and Subdomains (eg |rssql2;...| ... |End2|) are removed from the text, and replaced with placed holders.\r\n</li><li> The text is included in the document\r\n</li><li> The file pointer is placed at the beginning of the included text in order to process any merge fields and expressions.\r\n</ul><span class="et-section-line">Other Notes:</span>\r\n<ul><li> the string after NAME: in each PARAMETER is not trimmed! Ie. spaces are included.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li> incl(A)\r\n</li><li><code> incl(A, fk_id:5, crit:8)</code> - replaces all occurances globally of ~fk_id~ in section A with 5, and ~crit~ with 8 before any other processing occurs.\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc133-dib'),
    (134, 'ET*left', 121, 21, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Returns the start or the end of a string, using either an integer number of characters, or the characters that precede any of a list of strings.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> left(PARAM1, PARAM2[, PARAM3, PARAM4, etc])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> PARAM1</b> - The complete string\r\n</li><li><b> PARAM2</b> - If numeric and positive then return PARAM2 count of characters from the left of the search string.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">If numeric and negative then return PARAM2 count of characters from the end of the search string.</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">If not numeric, then return everything before this parameter (case-insensitive match).</span>\r\n</li><li><b> PARAM3 (etc)</b> - If PARAM2 is not numeric and not found, then use PARAM3 in the place of PARAM2, and so on (for PARAM4, PARAM5, etc).\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> If PARAM2 is empty, then return PARAM1.\r\n</li><li> Any numeric value for PARAM2, PARAM3, etc. will immediately cause an answer to be returned and the rest of the parameters to be ignored.\r\n</li><li> Uses the PHP substr function under the hood.\r\n</li><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*mid" title="Dropinbase Features">mid</dib-nav> and <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*substr" title="Dropinbase Features">substr</dib-nav>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> left(abcdefg,e)</code> - returns abcd\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcd,2)</code> - returns ab\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcdefg,)</code> - returns abcdefg\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcde, cy, bc)</code> - returns a\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcde,tt,,ee)</code> - returns abcde\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcde,tt,2)</code> - returns ab\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc134-dib'),
    (135, 'ET*mid', 121, 24, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Returns the end characters of a string starting from the middle somewhere, using either an integer start, or the characters that start with any of a list of strings.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> mid(PARAM1, PARAM2[, PARAM3, PARAM4, etc])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> PARAM1</b> - The complete string\r\n</li><li><b> PARAM2</b> - If numeric and positive then return everything from PARAM1 starting at position PARAM2 (0-indexed).\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">If numeric and negative then return the last PARAM2 count of characters from the end of PARAM1.</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">If not numeric, then return everything from PARAM1, from the first occurance of PARAM2 onwards inclusive (case-insensitive match).</span>\r\n</li><li><b> PARAM3 (etc)</b> - If PARAM2 is not numeric and not found OR empty, then use PARAM3 in the place of PARAM2, and so on (for PARAM4, PARAM5, etc).\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Any numeric value for PARAM2, PARAM3, etc. will immediately cause an answer to be returned and the rest of the parameters to be ignored.\r\n</li><li> Uses the PHP stripos and substr functions under the hood.\r\n</li><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*left" title="Dropinbase Features">left</dib-nav> and <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*substr" title="Dropinbase Features">substr</dib-nav>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> mid(abcdefg,e)</code> - returns efg\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcd,2)</code> - returns cd\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcdefg,)</code> - returns an empty string\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcde,cy,,bc)</code> - returns bcde\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcde,tt,,ee)</code> - returns an empty string\r\n</li><li><code> left(abcde,tt,2)</code> - returns cde\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc135-dib'),
    (136, 'ET*substr', 121, 43, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">  Implements the PHP substr function to return a portion of a string. Where the substr function returns FALSE, it will result in a -1.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> substr(PARAM1, OFFSET[, LENGTH])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> PARAM1</b> - the string to return a part of\r\n</li><li><b> OFFSET</b> - where to start in the string.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">If positive number, start at the OFFSET-character (0-indexed).</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">If negative number, start OFFSET-characters from the end of the string</span>\r\n</li><li><b> LENGTH</b> - the length of the string to return. Default is to the end of the string.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> If PARAM1 is less than OFFSET characters long, an empty string will be returned.\r\n</li><li> From &gt;PHP 8 an empty string is returned instead of false(-1) where for eg. PARAM1 is less than OFFSET characters long,\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> substr(abcdef, 2, 3)</code> - prints cde\r\n</li><li><code> substr(abcde,8)</code> - prints -1 or an empty string (see notes above)\r\n</li><li><code> substr(abcdef,0)</code> - prints abcdef\r\n</li><li><code> substr(abcdef, -5, 2)</code> - prints bc\r\n</li><li><code> substr(abcdef, -5)</code> - prints bcdef\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc136-dib'),
    (137, 'ET*strlen', 121, 41, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Implements the PHP strlen function - returns the number of characters(bytes) in the given string</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> strlen(PARAM1)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> PARAM1</b> - a string of characters\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> returns the number of bytes rather than the number of characters in a string.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> strlen(abcdefg)</code> -  return 7\r\n</li><li><code> strlen()</code> -  return 0\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc137-dib'),
    (139, 'ET*displayfields', 121, 4, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (Dropinbase specific function). Takes table_id and pef_table.display_expression as input and adds table name to fields within</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> displayfields(DISPLAY_EXPRESSION, TABLE_NAME, DELIM_CHAR, TABLE_ID)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> DISPLAY_EXPRESSION</b> - typical display expression stored in pef_table.display_expression\r\n</li><li><b> TABLE_NAME</b> - name of table to add as prefix\r\n</li><li><b> DELIM_CHAR</b> - character used in DISPLAY_EXPRESSION to delimit fields\r\n</li><li><b> TABLE_ID</b> - pef_table.id value\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Used in TableList.php\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> displayfields([*CONCAT(`id`, &apos;(&apos;, `name`, &apos;)&apos;)*], client, `, 123)</code> - results in CONCAT(`client`.`id`, &apos;(&apos;, `client`.`name`, &apos;)&apos;)\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc139-dib'),
    (140, 'ET*nv', 121, 29, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (nullvalue) returns 2nd part if 1st part is an empty string or null</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> nv(EXPR1,EXPR2)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> EXPR1</b> - an eleutheria expression of which the result is returned by default\r\n</li><li><b> EXPR2</b> - an eleutheria expression of which the result is returned if EXPR1 is an empty string or null\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*exists" title="Dropinbase Features">exists</dib-nav> and <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*if" title="Dropinbase Features">if</dib-nav>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> nv(fld(amount),0)</code> - returns 0 if fld(amount) returns nothing\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc140-dib'),
    (141, 'ET*strpos', 121, 42, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Implements the php strpos function. Returns the character position of NEEDLE within HAYSTACK, with optional OFFSET where search must start</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> strpos(HAYSTACK, NEEDLE[, OFFSET=0])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> HAYSTACK</b> - string to search in\r\n</li><li><b> NEEDLE</b> - string to find\r\n</li><li><b> OFFSET</b> - numeric OFFSET where search starts. Default is 0.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> returns -1 if not found\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> strpos(abcdefg,c)</code> - returns 2\r\n</li><li><code> strpos(abcdefg,h)</code> - returns -1\r\n</li><li><code> strpos(abcdefg,c,3)</code> - returns -1\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc141-dib'),
    (142, 'ET*sqlconvert', 121, 39, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Uses the sqlconvert class to convert mysql SQL to the given syntax</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> sqlconvert(TARGET_SYNTAX, SQL_STATEMENT[, PRIMARY_KEYS])</span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Uses the Dropinbase DSqlConvert::convert() function under the hood\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li> sqlconvert(mssql, [*CONCAT(field1, field2, &apos;-hello&apos;)*])\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc142-dib'),
    (143, 'ET*getparams', 121, 13, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Adds a value, or an array of values to the globalArray array, and optionally prints the values.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> getparams(NEW_PARAM_NAME, SOURCE, PRINTLIST) OR getparams(NEW_PARAM_NAME, SOURCE, SESSION_VAR_NAME, PRINTLIST)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> NEW_PARAM_NAME</b> - the name of the new parameter in the $globalArray array.\r\n</li><li><b> SOURCE</b> - if &apos;$_SESSION&apos; then values are extracted from the PHP session, else this is a string containing pdo-style parameter names.\r\n</li><li><b> SESSION_VAR_NAME</b> - the name of the PHP $_SESSION variable to extract values from. Only applicaple if SOURCE = &apos;$_SESSION&apos;.\r\n</li><li><b> PRINTLIST</b> - whether to print the added list of values as a comma separated list\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Values in globalArray can be accessed in future included domains using ^KEY^, or by using getval(KEY).\r\n</li><li> if an array is added, it can be used as the source for a domain, eg |rsarr2;myArray| (like other arrays in globalArray)\r\n</li><li> if SOURCE is not &apos;$_SESSION&apos; then the pdo-style parameter names are identified by using &apos;:&apos; as the start and any character other than [0-9][a-z][A-Z][_] as the end (or the end of the string)\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> getparams(myArray, name=:name1 OR name = :name_2)</code> - $globalArray[&apos;myArray&apos;] = [&apos;name1&apos;, &apos;name_2&apos;] is set\r\n</li><li><code> getparams(myArray, name=:name1 OR name=:name2, anythinggoeshere)</code> - $globalArray[&apos;myArray&apos;] = [&apos;name1&apos;, &apos;name2&apos;] is set, and &apos;name1, name2&apos; is printed\r\n</li><li><code> getparams(myVal, $_SESSION, &apos;mySessVal&apos;)</code> - $globalArray[&apos;myVal&apos;] = $_SESSION[&apos;mySessVal&apos;] is set and can be retrieved using getval(myVal)\r\n</li><li><code> getparams(myArray, $_SESSION, &apos;mySessArray&apos;)</code> - $globalArray[&apos;myArray&apos;] = $_SESSION[&apos;mySessArray&apos;] is set\r\n</li><li><code> getparams(myArray, $_SESSION, &apos;mySessArray&apos;, printit)</code> - $globalArray[&apos;myArray&apos;] = $_SESSION[&apos;mySessArray&apos;] is set, and &apos;name1, name2&apos; is printed\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc143-dib'),
    (145, 'ET*param', 121, 30, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Replaces a value with a PDO parameter and adds the value to the parameter array which is used for any SQL statements executed hereafter.</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">*** IMPORTANT - the param function offers critical security to prevent SQL injection attacks where values originate from potentially insecure sources.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> param (VALUE[,PARAMETERNAME][,DONT_PRINT])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> VALUE</b> - the value to pass to the database server using PDO parameters\r\n</li><li><b> PARAMETERNAME</b> - an optional explicit name (alpha-numeric and underscore allowed) to use for the PDO parameter. If not specified a parameter name is auto-generated, eg. :etp0\r\n</li><li><b> DONT_PRINT</b> - the presence of a value here means that the name of the PDO parameter is not printed, but the value is remembered for a following statement\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*sql" title="Dropinbase Features">sql</dib-nav> and <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*getdb" title="Dropinbase Features">getdb</dib-nav> and the workings of domains.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> sql(SELECT name FROM client WHERE date_joined = param(getval(joined)) AND name &gt; param(fld(firstLetter)) )</code> - this assumes getval(joined) is something like &apos;2024-01-01&apos;, and fld(firstLetter) something like &apos;M&apos;\r\n</li><li><code> setval(zzz, getdb(name, test_client, [*notes like concat(&apos;%&apos;,*] param(fld(search_str)), [*, &apos;%&apos;)*]))</code> - embedding of Eleutheria functions like param() in SQL functions like concat() requires the use of [*...*] to avoid issues.\r\n</li><li><code> |rssql1;SELECT id, name FROM test_client WHERE notes = ~param(fld(xxx))~| ~name~ |End1|</code> - demonstrates how to use PDO parameters in domains\r\n</li><li><code> param(fld(id), myId, dontPrint) sql(SELECT name FROM client WHERE id = :myId)</code> - the param() function is used to store the fld(id) value with a name (myId), which is then used in the sql() function\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc145-dib'),
    (146, 'ET*replace', 121, 35, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> case-insensitive text replace of NEEDLE with NEWVALUE in SUBJECT, with some special features added.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> replace(NEEDLE, NEWVALUE, SUBJECT)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> NEEDLE</b> - the text to find. Note, &apos;\\r&apos; and &apos;\\n&apos; in NEEDLE means carriage-return &quot;\\r&quot; and line-feed &quot;\\n&quot; respectively.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">If NEEDLE is &apos;*an*&apos; then strip all non-alphanumeric characters from SUBJECT, except characters listed in NEWVALUE.</span>\r\n</li><li><b> NEWVALUE</b> - the string that replaces all occurances of NEEDLE in SUBJECT. Note, &apos;\\r&apos; and &apos;\\n&apos; in NEWVALUE means carriage-return &quot;\\r&quot; and line-feed &quot;\\n&quot; respectively.\r\n</li><li><b> SUBJECT</b> - the string to be searched and changed.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> All searching is done case-insensitively.\r\n</li><li> Uses the PHP str_ireplace() and stripos() functions under the hood.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> replace(b, abcdeABCDE, x)</code> - will print &apos;axcdeAxCDE&apos;\r\n</li><li><code> replace(\\n, X, replace(\\n, X, replace(\\r\\n,X,fld(myField))))</code> - will replace all Linux-, Windows-, Mac-style linebreaks with X in fld(myField)\r\n</li><li><code> replace(&lt;br&gt;, \\r\\n, fld(myField))</code> - will replace all &lt;br&gt; tags in fld(myField) with Windows-style linebreaks\r\n</li><li><code> replace(*an*, _$, $_abc_ABC_012_#%^&amp;)</code> - will print $_abc_ABC_012_\r\n</li><li><code> replace(b,,abcde)</code> - will print acde\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc146-dib'),
    (147, 'ET*jsonlist', 121, 20, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (Dropinbase specific function) Transform a list of quoted items separated by a comma to a JSON object that can be used in Angular.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> jsonlist (LIST)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> LIST</b> - the single-quoted list of items, eg &apos;a&apos;, &apos;b&apos;,&apos;c&apos;\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> does not handle multiple spaces between list items\r\n</li><li> &quot; is replaced with &apos; to be useful in Angular\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> jsonlist([*&apos;a&apos;, &apos;b&apos;,&apos;c&apos;*])</code> - prints {&apos;a&apos;,&apos;b&apos;,&apos;c&apos;}\r\n</li><li><code> jsonlist(getdb(value_list,pef_item,value_list IS NOT NULL)</code> - gets the first record with contents in value_list from pef_item and returns a JSON object containing the list of items\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc147-dib'),
    (148, 'ET*clipends', 121, 3, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> removes the first and last characters from a given string. if 2nd parameter (LENGTH) is present then remove first LENGTH and last LENGTH characters from string</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> clipends (PARAM1[, LENGTH=1])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> PARAM1</b> - the string\r\n</li><li><b> LENGTH</b> - the count of characters to clip from both ends\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Uses the substr and strlen PHP functions under the hood\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> clipends(abcdef)</code> - prints bcde\r\n</li><li><code> clipends(abcdef, 2)</code> - prints cd\r\n</li><li><code> clipends(ab)</code> - prints empty string\r\n</li><li><code> clipends(a)</code> - prints empty string\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc148-dib'),
    (149, 'ET*nav', 121, 25, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (Dropinbase specific function) Creates a DIB Docs specific navigation button</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> nav(CONTAINERNAME[, TITLE])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> CONTAINERNAME</b> - Dropinbase container name. May contain ? and query parameters (see example)\r\n</li><li><b> TITLE</b> - if not specified, then CONTAINERNAME will be used instead\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li><b> *** WARNING</b> - unsafe function if mergefields are used somewhere in the same expression!\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> nav(dibDesigner?containerId=1, Designer])</code> - converts to &lt;dib-nav class=&quot;helpNavigation&quot; data-container=&quot;dibDesigner&quot; data-query=&quot;?containerId=1&quot;&gt;Designer&lt;/dib-nav&gt;\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc149-dib'),
    (150, 'ET*navdocs', 121, 26, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (Dropinbase specific function) Converts to a DIB Docs specific navigation link that opens a named document in dibDocs.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> navdocs (DOCS_ID[,AREA][,TITLE])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> DOCS_ID</b> - id or name of the pef_docs record\r\n</li><li><b> AREA</b> - docs/table/component\r\n</li><li><b> TITLE</b> - display title\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Last two parameteres not implemented yet ([navToTagName], [containerName])\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> navdocs(Dropinbase Features,docs,Developers)</code> - converts to &lt;dib-nav class=&quot;helpNavigation&quot; data-container=&quot;dibDocs&quot; data-query=&quot;?area=docs&amp;doc=Dropinbase-Features&quot; title=&apos;Dropinbase Features&apos;&gt;Developers&lt;/dib-nav&gt;\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc150-dib'),
    (151, 'ET*navtag', 121, 27, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (Dropinbase specific function) Creates a Dropinbase HTML navigation tag that can be navigated to in Dropinbase docs</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> navtag(TAG, TITLE)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> TAG</b> - tag name\r\n</li><li><b> TITLE</b> - user caption\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li><b> *** WARNING</b> - unsafe function if mergefields are used somewhere in the same expression!\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> navtag(tagname,Edit document)</code> - converts to: &lt;span name=&apos;tagname&apos;&gt;Edit document&lt;/span&gt;\r\n</li><li><code> navtag(Edit document)</code> - converts to: &lt;span name=&apos;Edit document&apos;&gt;Edit document&lt;/span&gt;\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc151-dib'),
    (152, 'ET*math', 121, 23, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> performs complex math operations using the PHP EvalMath class</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> math(MATH_EXPRESSION[, ROUND_TO_DECIMALS][, PADDING])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> MATH_EXPRESSION</b> - a mathematical expression\r\n</li><li><b> ROUND_TO_DECIMALS</b> - rounds result to specified precision\r\n</li><li><b> PADDING</b> - presence of this parameter indicates that result is padded with zero&apos;s at right\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> math([*1 + 2</code> - (6 / 3)*]) - prints 1\r\n</li><li><code> math(2/3, 2)</code> - prints 0.66\r\n</li><li><code> math(2/3, 4, true)</code> - prints 0.6600\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc152-dib'),
    (156, 'ET*sql', 121, 38, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Executes a SQL statement. If values are returned, then print the first record&apos;s field values using DELIMITTER to separate values.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> sql(SQL_STATEMENT[, DATABASE][, DELIMITTER=&apos;,&apos;])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> SQL_STATEMENT</b> - any valid SQL statement (note, only the first record returned is used)\r\n</li><li><b> DATABASE</b> - index of database other than the MAIN database set with setMainDb(). Can also be the name of a container that is linked to a table or SQL query (which so doing identifies the database to use)\r\n</li><li><b> DELIMITTER</b> - string to use as record delimiter\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li><b> Queries should only return a single record</b> - returning more than that is wasted performance\r\n</li><li> Use PDO parameters in SQL statements to avoid SQL injection attacks (see examples below).\r\n</li><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*param" title="Dropinbase Features">param</dib-nav> and <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*getdb" title="Dropinbase Features">getdb</dib-nav>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> sql(UPDATE client SET name=param(getval(clientName))[*,*] date_joined=&apos;fld(join_date)&apos; WHERE id = fld(id))</code> - executes the query.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">Note the use of PDO parameters where needed (&apos;join_date&apos; and &apos;id&apos; is assumed here to always be safe) to avoid SQL injection, and [*...*] to avoid conflicts with Eleutheria&apos;s understanding of commas.</span>\r\n</li><li><code> sql(SELECT vatperc FROM admin WHERE year = param(getval(year)))</code> - executes SQL statement using PDO parameter for whatever is stored in getval(year).\r\n</li><li><code> sql(SELECT vatperc FROM admin WHERE year = &apos;2010&apos;, 2)</code> - execute sql on database id=2 (can use container name). Default is main Dropinbase db.\r\n</li><li><code> param(fld(id), myId, dontprint)sql(SELECT name FROM admin WHERE id = :myId)</code> - executes SQL statement using PDO parameter for whatever is stored in getval(year).\r\n</li><li><code> sql(Exec MyStoredProcedure [*34, True*], 1)</code> - execute stored procedure on database id=1 using parameter values: 34, True\r\n</li><li><code> sql(SELECT id FROM person, 2, ---)</code> - execute sql on database id=2 and delimits records returned with &apos;---&apos;\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc156-dib'),
    (158, 'ET*docstable', 121, 5, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (Dropinbase specific function). Produces an HTML table with info about table fields for a particular Dropinbase Table</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> docstable(TABLE_NAME[,FIELD_LIST])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> TABLE_NAME</b> - the name of the table\r\n</li><li><b> FIELD_LIST</b> - only list specific fields. Fields must be wrapped in $-characters, eg $field1$field2$field3$\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> *** WARNING this function causes the expression to be re-evaluated a 2nd time after the first merge takes place which constitutes a security hole should pef_field&apos;s records be compromised.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">It is also potentially unsafe since output is NOT htmlencoded.</span>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> docstable(pef_item)</code> - table containing all fields\r\n</li><li><code> docstable(table_name,$field1$field2$field3$)</code> - only show field1, field2 and field3 fields\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc158-dib'),
    (159, 'ET*img', 121, 17, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Adds images to .docx, and html files (.xslx still outstanding)</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> img(FULLPATHTOIMAGEFILE[, WIDTH=0][, HEIGHT=0][, FILEOPERATION=copy])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> FULLPATHTOIMAGEFILE</b> - full physical path to the image file to be included\r\n</li><li><b> WIDTH</b> - Default = 0. If width is 0, it is calculated by aspect ratio of the height.\r\n</li><li><b> HEIGHT</b> - Default = 0. If height is 0, it is calculated by aspect ratio of the width. If both are 0, the original dimensions are used.\r\n</li><li><b> FILEOPERATION</b> - If it is NOT &apos;move&apos;, then the source file is left intact, and a copy made in the temporary folder used to create the new file.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">If it is &apos;move&apos; then the source file is moved from its original positoin to the temporary folder used to create the new file.</span>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> If both WIDTH and HEIGHT are 0, the original dimensions are used. If the original dimensions can&apos;t be determined, then 200px x 200px is used.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code>	img(c:\\temp\\myImg.png)</code> - use image&apos;s original dimensions for both width and height\r\n</li><li><code>   img(c:\\temp\\myImg.png, 200, 0)</code> - set width = 200px, and calculate the height using aspect ratio\r\n</li><li><code>   img(c:\\temp\\myImg.png, 0, 250, move)</code> - set height = 250px, and calculate the width using aspect ratio\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc159-dib'),
    (165, 'ET*makelist', 121, 22, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Creates a comma-separated list of quoted values, useful for generating lists in SQL for eg the IN operator</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> makelist(LIST)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> LIST</b> - list of comma separated values\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> If LIST has less than 3 characters, then the word &apos;null&apos; is returned.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li> makelist(fld(viewlist)) where viewlist = ,a&apos;aa,bbb,c,   will result in &apos;a\\&apos;aa&apos;,&apos;bbb&apos;,&apos;c&apos;\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc165-dib'),
    (167, 'ET*parseselect', 121, 31, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (Dropinbase specific function). Parses the SELECT clause of a SQL statement and returns an array linking item names with columns&apos; SQL expressions</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> parseselect(SELECT_CLAUSE, CONTAINER_ID)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> SELECT_CLAUSE</b> - eg venue as name, concat(id, &apos; - &apos;, suburb) as map, t.id\r\n</li><li><b> CONTAINER_ID</b> - pef_container.id value\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">Output format: $itemName =&gt; array($expression, $contentType, $columnAlias), ..., ...</span>\r\n<ul><li> &apos;myVenueItem&apos; =&gt; array(&apos;venue&apos;, &apos;text&apos;, &apos;name),\r\n</li><li><b> &apos;myMapItem&apos; =&gt; array(concat(id, &apos;</b> - &apos;, suburb), &apos;text&apos;, &apos;map&apos;),\r\n</li><li> &apos;id&apos; =&gt; array(&apos;t.id&apos;, &apos;integer&apos;, &apos;id&apos;)\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li> parseselect(fld(select_clause), 123)\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc167-dib'),
    (168, 'ET*setmaindb', 121, 36, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Sets the mainDatabaseId&apos;s index, which indicates the default database to use for all database queries going forward.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> setmaindb(DATABASE)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> DATABASE</b> - either integer index in pef_database/Conn.php or name of a container that is linked to either a table or SQL record.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> The default DATABASE value is the main Dropinbase database index.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> setmaindb(3)</code> - use database index 3 in pef_database/Conn.php for all future queries\r\n</li><li><code> setmaindb(myContainerName)</code> - use database linked to container myContainerName (via table/sql) for all future queries\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc168-dib'),
    (171, 'ET*adddbval', 121, 0, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Adds values to overrideArray from 1 or many records returned from a SQL query. Field values can be referenced using fld()</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> adddbval(SQL_STATEMENT[, DATABASE])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> SQL_STATEMENT</b> - SQL statement to execute.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">OPTION 1: return many records and two columns. The first field is taken as the key, and the second as the value to be stored</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">OPTION 2: return one record and any number of columns where each column has an alias (eg name as name0). The alias is taken as the key, and the field value as the value to be stored</span>\r\n</li><li><b> DATABASE</b> - index of database other than the MAIN database set with setMainDb(). Can also be the name of a container that is linked to a table or SQL query (which so doing identifies the database to use)\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Use [*...*] around SQL that contains commas or brackets () to avoid collisions with Eleutheria syntax.\r\n</li><li> Nothing is printed to the document.\r\n</li><li> Also see <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*fld" title="Dropinbase Features">fld</dib-nav>. To add values to globalArray instead use <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*getparams" title="Dropinbase Features">getparams</dib-nav>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> adddbval([*SELECT name, id FROM individual WHERE name&gt;&apos;m&apos;*])</code> - eg fld(John) returns 1, and fld(Mary) returns 2, etc.\r\n</li><li><code> adddbval([*SELECT name AS name0, birth_date AS dob, notes AS notes FROM individual WHERE name&gt;&apos;m&apos;*])</code> - eg fld(name0) returns John, and fld(dob) returns &apos;2000-02-01&apos;, etc.\r\n</li><li><code> adddbval([*SELECT name, id FROM individual WHERE name&gt;&apos;m&apos;*],peopleForm)</code> - same as previous example, but runs against the database linked to the table of the peopleForm container\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc171-dib'),
    (175, 'Optimize Performance', 105, 120, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Running concurrent and complex queries against large amounts of data (eg &gt;1m records in a table) causes notable performance penalties.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase is optimized in many ways to avoid performance issues, but there are still other important factors one should be aware of to increase performance on the database server. <br>Note, apart from the general tips, each application is unique and increasing performance is a matter of investigating where the particular bottlenecks are and eliminating or tuning them.</p>\n<p>Here are some suggestions to improve performance of your application:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Recognize where the bottlenecks are\n<ul>\n<li>The principle of debugging is systematically isolating the problem area(s).</li>\n<li>Generally, querying large amounts of data (large records (many text/blob/varchar fields), large fields, and many records), and many concurrent users (ie queries) reduce speed. Queries need to be designed carefully in these cases.</li>\n<li>Investigate performance variables, eg <a href="http://www.techrepublic.com/blog/linux-and-open-source/10-mysql-variables-that-you-should-monitor/">http://www.techrepublic.com/blog/linux-and-open-source/10-mysql-variables-that-you-should-monitor/</a></li>\n<li>Investigate the time that specific queries take.</li>\n<li>Ensure there are enough database connections possible for sites with many concurrent users.</li>\n<li>Use EXPLAIN, SHOW STATUS, and SHOW PROCESSLIST to investigate the query plan for eg the use of indexes, and to find slow queries etc.</li>\n<li>Check the Task Manager (Windows) / top (Linux) to investigate CPU, memory and swap file usage.</li>\n<li>Your application design can often be improved to allow for archiving of records.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Optimize table design\n<ul>\n<li>Poor design (on all levels of the stack) is a main reason for poor performance.</li>\n<li>Add indexes (especially unique indexes where possible) to fields that are joined (in relationships), sorted, searched or grouped in queries. Optimal design requires a database expert.\n<ul>\n<li>See Optimize Indexes below</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Your tables should be normalized appropriately (requires research / a database expert).</li>\n<li>Use the smallest data types that can correctly store your data.</li>\n<li>Avoid text/blob fields unless absolutely necessary, especially on fields that are joined/sorted/searched/grouped.</li>\n<li>Large amounts of data influences network speed. Consider partitioning tables, separate database servers, or using one-to-one relationships to isolate large fields or sets of data queried less frequently.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Optimize queries\n<ul>\n<li>Often complex queries can be rewritten to produce the same result but many times faster.</li>\n<li>Use AI, preferably a recognized model for optimizing SQL.</li>\n<li>Large, complex queries can be implemented with subqueries that each solve a small part of the problem efficiently.</li>\n<li>Dropinbase queries can make use of temporary tables that are created and dropped before and after the main query executes.&nbsp;Consider moving the output of slow sub-queries to a temporary table using a child-query\'s sql_execute_before and sql_execute_after fields.</li>\n<li>Use bench marking and profiling tools (requires research / a database expert).</li>\n<li>Avoid using slow criteria, eg LIKE \'%xxx%\' (filter_any_part in Dropinbase), instead of LIKE \'xxx%\'.</li>\n<li>Avoid RIGHT JOINS - they are normally slower than LEFT JOINS.</li>\n<li>Avoid ORDER BY if possible.</li>\n<li>Avoid correlated subqueries. Correlated subqueries are run once for each row processed by the outer query penalising performance significantly. Move them to the FROM-clause and use joins to obtain the values.</li>\n<li>Implement a custom SQL statement that can be used to get the total count of records - stored in pef_sql.total_count_sql. Investigate the generated CRUD .php file in /dibCode/CONTAINERNAME.</li>\n<li>Consider using an in-memory table for derived data that is accessed often.</li>\n<li>There are many tips which are outside of the scope of this article and can be researched further. See &nbsp;resources below.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Optimize software\n<ul>\n<li>Use the latest, stable versions of database server software. There are huge performance gains in later versions.</li>\n<li>There are many variables that can be set to cater for special scenarios, eg large databases or servers dedicated to your database. See eg:\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://www.percona.com/blog/2014/01/28/10-mysql-performance-tuning-settings-after-installation/">https://www.percona.com/blog/2014/01/28/10-mysql-performance-tuning-settings-after-installation/</a></li>\n<li><a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/9195139/mysql-performance-variables-tweaking">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/9195139/mysql-performance-variables-tweaking</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>If you are a programmer and running many queries to perform certain tasks, consider different ways of doing them. Eg use temporary tables for data frequently accessed by your queries.</li>\n<li>Consider caching data which does not change often. Use the&nbsp;<em>Data Cache Lifetime</em><strong>&nbsp;</strong>field on Pg2 in the Designer.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Choice of Database Server and Cloud Considerations\n<ul>\n<li>MySQL/MariaDb is a good choice for its speed and simplicity, but really complex queries and demanding applications will benefit from a more advanced server like SkySQL (MySQL compatible), PostgreSQL or SQL Server.</li>\n<li>Your webserver and database engine should be on the same machine or server cluster to avoid network latency.</li>\n<li>Alternatively, host your entire application on AWS or Azure and implement scaling</li>\n<li>Or make use of AuroraDb, though first investigate the constraints.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Optimize storage devices.&nbsp;Note, this often provides considerable gains!\n<ul>\n<li>Check Windows Task Manager / Linux top to determine if cpu / memory / disks are under strain.</li>\n<li>Use fast SSD disks (some are much faster than others) that have a notable guarantee.</li>\n<li>Place disks&nbsp;in an appropriate RAID which allows the database server to read information concurrently (speeds up SELECT\'s).&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Ensure sufficient disk space for temporary caching tables etc.</li>\n<li>Configure the database server or file-system to store tables/databases that are used concurrently on separate disks (note physically separate disks - not partitioned drives)&nbsp;</li>\n<li>If possible (eg MsSql), configure the database server to store log files and data files on separate disks</li>\n<li>Research storage engine (eg InnoDb) specific optimizations</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Optimize memory and cpu performance\n<ul>\n<li>Type of memory</li>\n<li>Type of cpu (eg server-grade Intel or AMD processors)</li>\n<li>Add memory</li>\n<li>Add cpu\'s</li>\n<li>Add SSD\'s in a RAID configuration</li>\n<li>If you are using virtual servers, ensure your setup recognizes all available hardware.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>MySQL</p>\n<p><em>(TODO: update list)</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>https://www.percona.com/blog/2014/01/28/10-mysql-performance-tuning-settings-after-installation/</li>\n<li>http://www.askapache.com/mysql/mysql-performance-tuning.html</li>\n<li>http://20bits.com/article/10-tips-for-optimizing-mysql-queries-that-dont-suck</li>\n<li>http://www.sitepoint.com/using-explain-to-write-better-mysql-queries</li>\n<li>http://www.askapache.com/mysql/mysql-performance-tuning.html</li>\n<li>http://stackoverflow.com/questions/9195139/mysql-performance-variables-tweaking</li>\n<li>https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/5.5/en/optimizing-innodb-configuration-variables.html</li>\n<li>https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/documentation/articles/virtual-machines-linux-optimize-mysql-perf/</li>\n<li>https://www.percona.com/blog/2007/11/03/choosing-innodb_buffer_pool_size/</li>\n<li>https://www.percona.com/blog/2011/07/09/how-to-change-innodb_log_file_size-safely/</li>\n<li>https://www.oreilly.com/<wbr>library/view/mysql-reference-<wbr>manual/0596002653/ch05s02.html (older article for MyISAM tables but well written).</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Optimize Indexes</h2>\n<p>The database server constructs a query plan that uses available indexes to join tables, sort and filter records. If for eg data is sorted on name and then age, a composite index that contains these two fields would be the optimal choice. Note, while indexes lead to faster read operations, the more indexes a table has, the longer it takes to run large updates against it, and the more space it occupies in memory and on disk.</p>\n<p>1. Add indexes to fields in tables that are joined in relationships, sorted, searched or grouped on.</p>\n<p>2. Composite indexes (a,b) can be more effective than simple indexes, if the order of the columns match the order of how the database server requires them. If the order is different, they are not used at all, or only the usable part from the left is used (order matters). The following query will result in all records being read even though a, b and c each have their own index.</p>\n<p>SELECT a, b, c, count(*)&nbsp;<br>FROM table1<br>GROUP BY a, b, c</p>\n<p>Adding a composite index (a, b, c) will solve this issue. Note if the order of the fields in the GROUP BY clause differs (eg b,c, a) from the order of the fields in the index (a, b, c) the index will not be utilized fully.</p>\n<p>3. Indexes that are a left-prefix of another index are unnecessary and should be removed.</p>\n<p>4. Use a limited index on large varchar or blob/text fields that must be searched in reading order: ALTER TABLE myTable ADD KEY(Notes(20))</p>\n<p><strong>Resources</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/myxplain/mysql-indexing-best-practices-for-mysql">http://www.slideshare.net/myxplain/mysql-indexing-best-practices-for-mysql</a></li>\n<li><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/billkarwin/how-to-design-indexes-really">http://www.slideshare.net/billkarwin/how-to-design-indexes-really</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc175-dib'),
    (178, 'Installation Steps', 105, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><strong>Please note that installing software and changing settings may cause malfunctioning (or damage!), especially if it is not done correctly. <br>Keep backups where needed, and proceed at your own risk.</strong></p>\n<p>There are two main options for installing Dropinbase. Use Docker, or&nbsp;<a href="#manualInstall">install it manually</a>. <br>Note, Dropinbase also runs on ~navdocs(Shared Hosting Servers)~.</p>\n<p>There is also a convenient<strong> ~navdocs(Installation Checklist)~</strong>.</p>\n<h2>Ready-made Docker Container</h2>\n<p><a href="https://www.docker.com/what-docker" target="">Docker</a> is similar to a virtual machine, but is more efficient regarding resource use. Windows, Linux and macOS are supported.&nbsp;<br>Using Docker has the advantage of a pre-configured Dropinbase setup that works "out of the box" and does not conflict with any existing applications.</p>\n<p><strong>Note for Windows users:</strong> Docker is supported for&nbsp;<a href="https://docs.docker.com/desktop/install/windows-install/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">only specific versions of Windows</a>.</p>\n<h3>Steps:</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Install Node.js and NPM if you haven\'t done so already:<br>\n<ol>\n<li>See the "<strong>Install Node.js &amp; NPM and optionally NVM</strong>" section under ~navdocs(Install Angular)~</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Install Docker Desktop if you haven\'t done so already:\n<ol>\n<li><a href="https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/</a> <br><u>Note:</u> when prompted, authorize the Docker Desktop Installer with your system password during the install process. Privileged access is needed to install networking components, links to the Docker apps, and manage the Hyper-V VMs.</li>\n<li>On <strong>Apple Mac</strong>, you may need to resolve and issue with \'go\'. Please see this thread:<a href="https://github.com/webdevops/Dockerfile/issues/395" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://github.com/webdevops/Dockerfile/issues/395</a></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Restart your machine.</li>\n<li>Open the Docker console and go to&nbsp;<strong>Settings </strong>-&gt; <strong>General </strong>and enable WSL2 ("use the WSL2 based engine").\n<ol>\n<li>(<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Windows</span>&nbsp;only). If Docker does not run, you may need to install Hyper-V: <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/quick-start/enable-hyper-v" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/virtualization/hyper-v-on-windows/quick-start/enable-hyper-v</a></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Open a terminal window (eg PowerShell in Windows), and run the following commands:</li>\n<li><code>npm install dropinbase -g [Enter]</code>&nbsp;- this installs the Dropinbase package globally</li>\n<li><code>cd c:/www/projects/</code> - change to the directory of where the project must be installed</li>\n<li><code>dropinbase init myProject</code> - create a new Dropinbase Client project with a name of your choice\n<ol>\n<li>If PowerShell/Windows responds saying that running scripts is disabled on the system, first run the following:</li>\n<li><code>Set-ExecutionPolicy -ExecutionPolicy Unrestricted -Scope Process</code></li>\n<li>More options here: <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.core/about/about_execution_policies?view=powershell-7.3" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.core/about/about_execution_policies?view=powershell-7.3</a></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><code>cd myProject</code> -<strong> </strong>change to the directory of the project you just created</li>\n<li>Edit the <strong>docker-compose.yml</strong> file.\n<ol>\n<li>Change the <strong>container_name </strong>property to the name of your project, eg myProject.</li>\n<li>Save and close the file.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><code>npm start</code> - connect to the Dropinbase Docker container and start the services\n<ol>\n<li>If any security messages appear, accept them</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Open your web browser and visit <code>https://localhost</code>.</li>\n<li>If the system does not work, see the ~navdocs(Troubleshooting Installation)~ page.</li>\n<li>The Dropinbase <strong>Installer </strong>should open. Follow the on-screen installation steps.\n<ol>\n<li>These steps will guide you through installing a Dropinbase database that stores the design of your application.</li>\n<li>If you are connecting to a database server on your local machine, use the following as host instead of localhost: <strong>host.docker.internal</strong></li>\n<li>The last step will configure the <strong>/index.php</strong> file to open your new Dropinbase installation instead of the <strong>Installer</strong>.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>To login, the default username is <strong>admin</strong>&nbsp;and the password is <strong>test.</strong></li>\n<li>Update the <strong>admin </strong>password here: <code>https://localhost/nav/dibLoginForm?primary_id=1</code></li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Creating a Second Project with Docker</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Open the Docker Desktop and stop all project containers (if any) except the angular/dropinbase container.</li>\n<li>Follow the steps above from point 8 (<code>dropinbase init myProject</code>) onwards, but choose a different project name, eg <code>dropinbase init myOtherProject</code>.</li>\n<li>To run a particular project, simply stop and start the relevant container in Docker Desktop...&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Access Files within Docker</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><code>cd /www/projects/myProject</code></li>\n<li><code>docker exec -it myProject</code></li>\n<li>The Dropinbase core is installed in <strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/</strong></li>\n<li>Use <strong>vi</strong> to view/edit any file</li>\n</ol>\n<h2 id="manualInstall">Manual Setup</h2>\n<p>The following steps should lead to a stable system. If any errors occur, see ~navdocs(Troubleshooting Installation)~.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Ensure all the necessary ~navdocs(Technology and Requirements)~ are in place.\n<ol>\n<li>On Windows you can install&nbsp;<a href="http://www.wampserver.com/en/">WAMP</a> which is easy to manage, and installs some of the prequisites: MariaDb/PHP/Apache.</li>\n<li>WAMP installation steps (link my be outdated): <a href="http://forum.wampserver.com/read.php?2,138295" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http://forum.wampserver.com/read.php?2,138295</a></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Configure a custom URL / Virtual Host for the application (eg <code>http://myapp.dib</code>)\n<ol>\n<li>~navdocs(Apache Settings)~. Remember to restart the webserver.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Install&nbsp;<a href="https://getcomposer.org/download/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Composer</a>.</li>\n<li>Pull a copy of the <a href="https://github.com/Dropinbase/dibclient" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Dropinbase Client</a> from Github (or copy the files from a working system) to a folder under <strong>/www/</strong>, eg into<strong> /www/myProject/</strong>.</li>\n<li>Install the Dropinbase Core Framework and other default Composer packages under /vendor/:\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Option A (Composer):</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>Open a terminal window (eg Powershell)</li>\n<li>cd to the <strong>/www/myProject </strong>folder</li>\n<li>type: <code>composer install -vvv[Enter]</code> (the -vvv option prints detailed debugging information should you need it).</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Option B (Git):</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>Use Git to clone the Dropinbase Core Framework repository to <strong>/www/myProject/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase</strong>: <a href="https://github.com/Dropinbase/framework" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://github.com/Dropinbase/framework</a></li>\n<li>Note, certain features like converting HTML to PDF documents, single-signon using SAML and sending emails etc. relies on other Composer libraries. See the <strong>/composer.json</strong> file for details.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Option C (Multi-Tenant):</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>This is convenient if you already have the Dropinbase Core Framework on your machine</li>\n<li>see ~navdocs(Multi-Tenant Setup)~</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Install Angular:<br>\n<ol>\n<li>Note, this only affects the ability to create new containers. Dropinbase should start up without it.</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Install Angular)~</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Install a copy of the Dropinbase database:\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Option A (Installer):</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>Ensure the following line in the /www/myProject/index.php file is uncommented (this is the default):\n<div><code>include_once("./installer.php"); die();</code></div>\n</li>\n<li>Open a browser and enter your custom url configured above: eg <code>http://myapp.dib/</code></li>\n<li>Ensure you have a database user with permissions to create a database (if not already created).</li>\n<li>Use the Installer to complete the rest of the installation...</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Option B (Manual):</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>Create a database and a user with permissions to read/write records in all its tables, eg:\n<ol>\n<li><code>CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS `<strong>my_new_dib_database</strong>` DEFAULT CHARACTER SET = \'utf8mb4\' DEFAULT COLLATE \'utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci\';</code></li>\n<li><code>CREATE USER \'<strong>my_dib_user</strong>\'@\'localhost\' IDENTIFIED BY \'<strong>my_password</strong>\';</code></li>\n<li><code><span class="hljs-keyword">GRANT</span> SELECT, ALTER, CREATE, CREATE TEMPORARY TABLES, DELETE, INDEX, INSERT, UPDATE&nbsp;<span class="hljs-keyword">ON</span> `<strong>my_new_dib_database`</strong>.<span class="hljs-operator">*</span> <span class="hljs-keyword">TO</span> <span class="hljs-string">\'<strong>my_dib_user</strong>\'</span>@<span class="hljs-string">\'localhost\'</span>;</code></li>\n<li><code>FLUSH PRIVILEGES;</code></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Edit the following SQL script, adding <strong><code>use my_new_dib_database;</code></strong> at the top:&nbsp; <strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/installer/dropinbase.sql</strong>.</li>\n<li>Run the script.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Create/edit all the necessary configuration files in the <strong>/configs</strong> folder. See ~navdocs(System Configuration Files)~ for more info.</li>\n<li>Delete the <strong>/runtime</strong> folder (it is recreated when the core framework receives any request).</li>\n<li>Navigate to your chosen url, eg <code>http://myapp.dib</code></li>\n<li>To login, the default username is <strong>admin</strong>&nbsp;and the password is <strong>test.</strong></li>\n<li>Update the <strong>admin </strong>password here: <code>http://myapp.dib/nav/dibLoginForm?primary_id=1</code></li>\n<li>See ~navdocs(Troubleshooting Installation)~ if needed.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc178-dib'),
    (179, 'Goals of the Dropinbase Project', 9, 5, 0, 'eleutheria', '<ul><li>Simplicity. Power. Ease. Flexibility. Fun</li><li><span><span>Build cutting edge, responsible, secure systems with as little effort as possible</span></span><br></li><li>Facilitate a community to contribute towards common goals</li><li>Share and Connect</li><li>Do the right thing and make the world a better place</li></ul><h3>How</h3><p>Facilitate the learning, development and debugging process.</p><p>Allow developers to spend their time on interesting, custom things - let Dropinbase and AI handle slog and hassle.</p><p>Commonly used features should be quick and easy to create, while not limiting the custom development of the rest.</p><p>Harness and develop cutting-edge technological power.</p><p>If something of value can be improved, let\'s seriously consider doing it.</p><p>Keep an open ear to the community\'s needs.</p><p>Recognize common goals and create a focus to achieve them.</p><p>Facilitate platforms for support and sharing.</p><p><span>Connect, respect, share, uplift, inspire and believe in others.</span><br></p><p>&#160;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc179-dib'),
    (180, 'Server Functions Reference', NULL, 120, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc180-dib'),
    (181, 'EvalCriteria', 180, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The <strong>EvalCriteria </strong>class has three public functions.</p>\n<h2>evalCrit</h2>\n<p>Evaluates a criteria string containing parameters that reference values in a passed array, and other parameters (see ~navdocs(Criteria Evaluation)~.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Parameters</strong></p>\n<p>string $str - criteria expression which can containing parameters delimited by a colon (:)<br>associative array $params - parameter names and their values that can be replaced in criteria</p>\n<p><strong>Return</strong></p>\n<p>Boolean TRUE if the criteria resolves to TRUE, FALSE if not, and a array of the form arrary(\'error\', $msg) if not.</p>\n<p><strong>Notes</strong></p>\n<p>Parameter names must be delimited by {:...} OR prefixed with a colon (:), eg {:my parameter}&gt;15 &nbsp; AND &nbsp; :last_name &gt; \'don\\\'t parse the \\\' . Also don\\\'t parse OR\' &nbsp; AND :first_name &lt; `name`<br>NOTE: using {:...} is safer, since one parameter name can be a prefix to another.</p>\n<p>To avoid strings inside $str to be parsed as keywords (eg and/or), enclose them with single quotes (\'). The \' character can be escaped by using \\\'. &nbsp;See the example above.</p>\n<p>Parameters are evaluated by searching for their names (and finding the associated value) in the following places in the following order:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>the $params array</li>\n<li>User and Dropinbase Parameters (see ~navdocs(Criteria Evaluation)~</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>getParams</h2>\n<p>Returns an array containing the parameters delimited with : (or specified character $paramChar) in a string ($str).</p>\n<p><strong>Parameters</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>string $str - eg "person.name = :name AND person.name2 = :name AND (person.lastname = :lastname OR person.lastname = :lastname2)"</li>\n<li>boolean $allowDoubleUnderscore - allow __ to be part of parameter names (used to resolve pef_param sql fields). Default = FALSE.</li>\n<li>string $paramChar - character indicating the start of a parameter name. Default = \':\'.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Return</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>array - in our example, it will return array(\':name\',\':lastname\',\':lastname2\')</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Notes</strong></p>\n<p>The algorythm identifies parameters using $paramChar as the start and any character other than [0-9][a-z][A-Z][_] as the end (or the end of the string). If&nbsp;$allowDoubleUnderscore = TRUE then __ will be accepted as part of the string.</p>\n<h2>evalParam</h2>\n<p>Evaluates constant / SQL / PHP expressions stored in pef_param (<span style="text-decoration: underline;">may be deprecated soon!</span>), and referenced by parameter names in $str.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Parameters</strong></p>\n<p>string $str - expression containing parameters delimited by :<br>associative&nbsp;array &amp;$params - array containing parameters that can be passed to PHP functions, or with pdo for sql expressions<br>boolean $replaceInStr - Whether a parameter must be replaced with its "value", a in memory "placeholder" (used with evalCrit), or "not" replaced with anything</p>\n<p><strong>Return</strong></p>\n<p>string with placeholders or values in place of parameters. If a parameter in $str is not found in pef_param, it is left unchanged in $str.</p>\n<p><strong>Notes</strong></p>\n<p>Note that sql expressions in pef_param may recursively contain references to other parameters in pef_param. evalParam is called by evalCrit to resolve any unresolved parameters after&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc181-dib'),
    (183, 'File System Settings', 105, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><strong>Warning: changing settings may cause malfunctioning or damage, especially if they are not set correctly.<br>Keep a backup of your old settings files, and proceed at your own risk.</strong></p>\n<p>NOTE: The Dropinbase Installer requires <strong>write </strong>permissions on the /projectFolder itself to overwrite the <strong>index.php</strong> file to comment out the line that runs the Installer.php file. If it fails it must be manually done.</p>\n<p>On development machines, the webserver user (eg&nbsp;<strong>www-data</strong>) needs <strong>read/write</strong> permissions to files in the following folders, and all their subfolders:</p>\n<ol>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>/runtime</strong></li>\n<li>The various dropin <strong>/dibCode</strong> folders where files are created</li>\n<li>The folders that Angular uses for compiling files</li>\n<li>Ensure that the <strong>/configs</strong> folder is writable if the <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> file still needs to be created from the <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> file. Remove write permissions on this folder afterwards.</li>\n<li>The folder identified by <strong>DIB::$USERSPATH</strong> in <strong>Dib.php</strong> - where user\'s store uploaded files. And any other custom folders in your project like this.</li>\n<li>If you intend using the "<strong>Add Event &amp; PHP</strong>" link on the Designer, the webserver user will need rights to make changes to&nbsp;<strong>.php</strong> files in the <strong>/dropins/xxx/controllers/ </strong>folders.&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n<p><span style="color: #e03e2d;">On production servers all folders should be set to read-only, except the <strong>/runtime</strong> and user folders (eg <strong>DIB::$USERSPATH</strong>). See ~navdocs(Security)~ for more info.</span></p>\n<h3>Steps:</h3>\n<p>Change to your project folder:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>cd <code>/path/to/project</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Use the&nbsp;<strong>chown&nbsp;</strong>command to set user and group ownership:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>chown -R yourlinuxuser:webservergroup ./</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Folders: assign <strong>read </strong>and <strong>execute </strong>permissions on all folders to the owner (yourlinuxuser) and the group (webserver user). <strong>Execute </strong>permissions are needed to enter folders. Ensure these permissions are set on <strong>all folders</strong>, including the <strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase </strong>sub-folders:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>find ./ -type d -exec chmod 750 {} \\;</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Files: assign <strong>read </strong>and <strong>write </strong>to the owner (yourlinuxuser), and just <strong>read </strong>to the group (webserver user)</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>find ./ -type f -exec chmod 640 {} \\;</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Assign <strong>read/write</strong> permissions to the following folders (-R sets it recursively for subfolders):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>chmod -R 770 ./runtime</code></li>\n<li><code>chmod -R 770 ./dropins/<strong>myDropin1</strong>/dibCode</code>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (must be set to 750 on <strong>production server</strong> if all dibCode files exist)</li>\n<li><code>chmod -R 770 ./dropins/<strong>myDropin2</strong>/dibCode</code>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (must be set to 750 on <strong>production server</strong> if all dibCode files exist)</li>\n<li>etc</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Assign <strong>read/write</strong> permissions to folders where Angular generates code (must be set to 750 on <strong>production server</strong> if all dibCode files exist)</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>cd ./vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/setNgxMaterial/angular</code></li>\n<li><code>chmod -R 770 ./projects/plugins/src</code></li>\n<li><code>mkdir ./src/assets/plugins</code>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong><em>(if it does not yet exist)</em></strong></li>\n<li><code>chmod -R 770 ./src/assets/plugins</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Assign <strong>read/write</strong> permissions to folders where users upload files. Ensure that the webserver user can read&amp;write to this folder and all child folders:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>chmod -R 770 /path/to/user/folder</code></li>\n<li><code>chown -R yourlinuxuser:webservergroup /path/to/user/folder</code>&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc183-dib'),
    (184, 'Referencing Protocol', 324, 85, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Below are protocol rules used when specifying ~navdocs(Submission Data)~ configs to obtain values from the client, or when targeting items with client-side actions, eg <i>SetValue</i>. See additional syntax that applies for ~navdocs(Filters, filter criteria parameters)~ below.</p><p>Examples are available on ~nav(dibexEvents)~ and ~nav(dibexSubContainers)~.Â </p><h3>Rules</h3><p>ALIAS below refers to an item named ALIAS where the item_alias field is set.</p><p>When specifying Submission Data configs, ALIAS can only refer to a subcontainer component, and the primary key values of the current record in the child container will be returned.</p><ul><li>parent - references the parent container of the current container (the container from where the request originated). A popup(window) container\'s parent is always the base container.</li><li>CONTAINERNAME - references the named container</li><li>ALIAS - references an item with alias on the current container</li><li>parent.ALIAS - references an item with alias on the parent container</li><li>CONTAINERNAME.ALIAS - references an item with alias on the named container</li><li>CONTAINERNAME.ALIAS1.ALIAS2 - references item (ALIAS2) on the child-container where the subcontainer component has alias ALIAS1 on container CONTAINERNAME</li><li>ALIAS1.ALIAS2 - references item (ALIAS2) on the child-container where the subcontainer component has alias ALIAS1 on the current container</li><li>parent.ALIAS1.ALIAS2 - references item (ALIAS2) on the child-container where the subcontainer component has alias ALIAS1 on the parent container</li><li>self.grideditor.ALIAS or CONTAINERNAME.grideditor.ALIAS or CONTAINERNAME.ALIAS.grideditor.ALIAS - references the value of an item in a grid\'s editor from an event outside the grid row. If the event is triggered from an item in the grid row, then using ALIAS would suffice.</li></ul><p>NOTE: If the last ALIAS in the expression refers to a subcontainer component then the child-container inside the subcontainer component is targeted. Eg for submitItemAlias, the primary key values of the current record of the child-container are returned in an array (this includes eg parent.ALIAS and CONTAINERNAME.ALIAS). Eg containerUserGrid or testCompanyForm.containerUserGrid.</p><h3>Filter Parameters</h3><p>In order to evaluate parameters in ~navdocs(Filters, filter criteria)~, the server flattens the return values of Submission Data using the underscore (_) character.Â For example, if the Submission Data array contains:</p><p>Â  Â [submitItemAlias.self][SUBCONTAINER_NAME][PKEY_NAME]</p><p>it can be referenced in filter criteria as:Â </p><p>Â  Â submitItemAlias_self_SUBCONTAINER_NAME_PKEY_NAME</p><p></p><p>Example:</p><p>Â  Â submitItemAlias_self_Items_id</p><p></p><p>If checked items are involved, then the Submission Data includes a numbered array, which is also flattened as in the following example:</p><p>Â  Â submitCheckedItem_subCompanyConsult_0_id<br/>Â  Â submitCheckedItem_subCompanyConsult_1_id<br/>Â  Â submitCheckedItem_subCompanyConsult_2_idÂ </p><p><br/></p><p>NEW</p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><!--StartFragment--><table border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0" style="font-size: 12px;"><tbody><tr><td><strong><span style="font-size: 12px;text-align: left;float: none;">Context</span><br/></strong></td><td><strong><span style="font-size: 12px;text-align: left;float: none;">Example</span><br/></strong></td><td><strong>Notes</strong></td></tr><tr><td>SQL Params</td><td>Â  :submitItemAlias_self_id<br/>Â  :submitItemAlias_dibDesigner_container_id<br/><br/></td><td><br/></td></tr><tr><td><br/></td><td><br/></td><td><br/></td></tr><tr><td><br/></td><td><br/></td><td><br/></td></tr></tbody></table><!--EndFragment--><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, '', 'doc184-dib'),
    (192, 'dibTree', 4, 60, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>By default nodes are not removed from trees when dragged to another tree. To force their removal in this case, add a property to the nodes named canRemove which must be set to TRUE.</p><p>To disable the placing of a search box at the top of the tree, add a record to the pef_container_setting table, where <i>name </i>= \'searchTree\' and <i>valueÂ </i>= \'false\'. If it becomes required, change the value to \'true\', or remove the record.</p><p>The position where the tree nodes will appear can be altered by placing a contentFor component, named \'tree\', anywhere in the design.</p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc192-dib'),
    (194, 'System Configuration Files', 105, 70, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>/configs/Conn.php</h2>\n<p>Database connection details. Edit this file when you need to add new database connections or if existing connections must change. Note, Dropinbase applications can be based on multiple databases.</p>\n<p>All entries must have unique indexes (positive and integer). Note, these index values must match the id values of records added in the ~nav(dibDatabaseForm,Database Table)~. Since <strong>id </strong>values are auto-generated, it is recommended to add these records and then use the generated values as index values for the entries in Conn.php.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The primary "dropinbase" database\'s index must relate to the <strong>DBINDEX </strong>constant in <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> (and <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> for convenience - see Dib.php below).<br>The database containing the following tables must relate to the <strong>$LOGINDB </strong>constant. These tables are normally copied to the database containing the user data.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>pef_login</li>\n<li>pef_login_group</li>\n<li>pef_perm_group</li>\n<li>pef_security_policy</li>\n<li>pef_two_factor</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For more information see ~navdocs(Move the Login and Other Tables)~, and also the examples provided in the <strong>/configs/Example_Conn.php</strong> file.</p>\n\n<h2>/configs/DibTmpl.php and /configs/Dib.php</h2>\n<p>The main Dropinbase configuration file is <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong>.</p>\n<p>If it does not exist, it is automatically created based on the <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> file. This also triggers the Dropinbase initialization process that resets all permission records etc.<br>To enable new configurations, edit the&nbsp;<strong>DibTmpl.php</strong> file and delete the <strong>Dib.php</strong> file.</p>\n<p>Open <strong>DibTmpl.php </strong>and set values such Site Name, Logo, and others. Each value is described in the file.</p>\n<p>This file contains constants and variables that are used by the system and developers, eg database indexes, file paths to folders in the system, variables that control the use of cache and debugging etc. <br>Values can be accessed throughout your PHP code using eg DIB::$RUNTIMEPATH or DIB::$CODEUSE&nbsp; or DIB::$DIBDB.</p>\n<p>This file is executed with every request that targets the core framework (ie all non-<strong>/files/</strong> requests which are handled by <strong>/files.php</strong>).<br>You can add any "startup" code, or "global" variables or constants that you may need in your own PHP. A good example is constants for various databases.</p>\n\n<h2>/configs/DibUserParams.php</h2>\n<p>Sets values related to the current user that is used by the framework, and can be used throughout all code on the server.\n<br>Any additional authentication logic can also be added to this file.</p>\n<p>In Dropinbase installations, the SQL in this file is modified to return additional values related to the current user. The additional values can first be added as fields to the pef_login table, or pulled via a JOIN from another table.\n<br>These values can be accessed in PHP as <code>DIB::$USER[\'variable_name\']</code> and in SQL queries and other places as<code> :dibUser_variable_name</code>.</p>\n<p>This file contains a function which returns an array to the <strong>/dropins/dibAuthenticate/componets/Authenticator.php </strong>script.&nbsp;<br>All values in the array are stored in the PHP user session.</p>\n<p>Note, all values in the original script (except staff_id) are required by the Dropinbase framework. Do not alter or remove them, rather add others.</p>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexSqlParams, Server-side User Parameters)~ under the Configuration-tab for more info about User Parameters.</p>\n\n<h2>/configs/Environment.php</h2>\n<p>Sets custom values that are sent to the client-side framework when the first base container loads.</p>\n<p>These values are used by the client-side framework, but can also be utilized in your own client-side code in eg. *ngIf directives to conditionally hide items.</p>\n<p>Use it to specify additional values related to the current user or environment.<br>See the examples for more info about how to use these values, eg ~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices)~.</p>\n<p>This file contains an array which is stored in a global variable named DIB. <br>Open the Developer Tools (press F12 in Chrome) and type DIB [Enter] in the Console to view its contents.</p>\n<p>This file can also contain other JavaScript to be executed, although it is better to use the <strong>beforeBodyJs </strong>and <strong>afterBodyJs </strong>records in pef_setting.</p>\n<h2>/configs/FileLocations.php</h2>\n<p>Stores the locations of system files required by certain functions, eg the path to system error logs for displaying in the Designer, and the location of the PHP executable file for executing scripts asynchronously.</p>\n<p>See the notes in this file for more details.</p>\n<h2>/configs/Mail.php</h2>\n<p>Stores settings required for sending emails (eg mails to handle \'forgot my password\') using PHPMailer.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>See the examples provided in the /configs/Example_Mail.php file.</p>\n<h2>/configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</h2>\n<p>The webserver redirects all requests that start with /files/ to /files.php. These requests are for static and publicly available files <strong>only</strong>.<br>All other requests are handled by /index.php which starts the core framework.</p>\n<p>The AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php file acts as a whitelist to ensure that files.php cannot return sensitive information in files to public users.</p>\n<p>It has an array for configuring which folders are accessible by files.php, and another array specifying which file extensions are allowed and what the corresponding mimetypes are of the file extensions.</p>\n<p>A particular file will therefore only be accessible if:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Its folder is in the first array mentioned above</li>\n<li>Its file extension is in the second array mentioned above</li>\n<li>Its file contents matches the mimetype specified in the second array, related to its file extension.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Note, file extensions listed here must be in lower case, though the files themselves can have extensions in any case.</p>\n<p><strong>DO:</strong> create a small number of folders that are made for hosting publicly available files and put all such files there.<br>These folders must not contain files with any sensitive information.</p>\n<p><strong>DO NOT ADD</strong> the following file extensions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>âphp &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (server-side code)</li>\n<li>dtxt &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (used for cache files)</li>\n<li>et.html &nbsp; &nbsp;(certain Eleutheria templates)</li>\n<li>et.ts &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (certain Eleutheria templates)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc194-dib'),
    (195, 'Install Angular', 105, 80, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3>Install Node.js &amp; NPM and optionally NVM</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Angular works with specific versions only</strong>. If you have already installed Node.js, check the version using&nbsp;<code>node -v</code>&nbsp;in a terminal window.</li>\n<li>Check the Dropinbase repository <a href="https://github.com/Dropinbase/framework/blob/master/README.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener">README</a> for the current version of Node.js and Angular used in Dropinbase.</li>\n<li>Then download the latest <strong>specific version</strong> of Node.js that is compatible with this version of Angular:\n<ul>\n<li>Check version: <a href="https://angular.dev/reference/versions" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://angular.dev/reference/version</a>s</li>\n<li>Download Node.js: <a href="https://nodejs.org/en/download/releases" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://nodejs.org/en/download/releases</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>(Window only) The installation of NVM helps to install and switch between versions of Node.js when needed:\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://github.com/coreybutler/nvm-windows" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://github.com/coreybutler/nvm-windows</a></li>\n<li>Note that on <strong>Linux</strong>, NVM does not make Node.js available system wide, which is required for a secure setup of Dropinbase.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>&nbsp;</li>\n<li>NOTE: Node.js also installs npm. Npm must be accessible and executable by PHP, under the account that runs the webserver.\n<ul>\n<li>You may need to adjust the <strong>open_basedir </strong>setting in the <strong>php.ini</strong> configuration file.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Install Angular (after installing Dropinbase)</h3>\n<p>Note, this only affects the ability to create/change containers. Dropinbase should start up without Angular being installed.<br>This step is not necessary if you are installing the Dropinbase Docker container.<br>NPM (above) is required to install Angular.<br>Run the following commands in a terminal window (eg PowerShell on Windows):</p>\n<ol>\n<li><code>cd /www/myProject/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/setNgxMaterial/angular</code></li>\n<li><code>ls</code> (or <code>dir</code> on Windows) on to list files and folders. If the <strong>node_modules </strong>folder or the <strong>package-lock.json</strong> file exists, delete them:\n<ol>\n<li><code>rm -rf ./node_modules</code> (or <code>rmdir /s /q node_modules</code> on Windows)</li>\n<li><code>rm -rf ./package-lock.json</code></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><code>npm install</code></li>\n<li>If there are any errors: <code>npm audit fix --force</code></li>\n<li><code>npm install -g @angular/cli@17.3.9</code> - replace 17.3.9 with the specific version declared in&nbsp;<a href="https://github.com/Dropinbase/framework/blob/master/README.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener">README</a>.</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Start&nbsp; the Angular Compiler Watcher</h3>\n<p>This setp is not necessary if you are installing the Dropinbase Docker container.<br>The Watcher is a Dropinbase script that runs in the background and watches for any Dropinbase containers to compile.<br>It speeds up the compilation process by avoiding the boostrapping process which runs otherwise each time.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Watcher <span style="text-decoration: underline;">should start automatically</span>, but if it doesn\'t, run the following commands in a terminal window:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>cd /www/myProject/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/setNgxMaterial/angular</code> - replace /www/myProject with your own.</li>\n<li><code>npm run watch:modules</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc195-dib'),
    (196, 'Create Docs for Apps', 324, 150, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>In-app documentation is easy to add :-) Â !</p><h2>Popup Help (F1-key)</h2><p>If theÂ <i>help_html </i>field of Item records is not empty, popup help appears by default at the bottom of the page displaying the HTML. If the contents of <i>help_html </i>is \'field\' and the item\'s pef_field_id record is not empty, then the contents of theÂ related Field table record (<i>pef_field.help_html</i>) is used. This is the recommended approach for bound items so that the documentation can be maintained in only in place where the same field is used on multiple containers.</p><p>The HTML stored in the help_html fields can contain Eleutheria functions and ~$delim~nav(...)~$delim~ and ~$delim~navdocs(...)~$delim~ links etc (see &#34;Specific to Docs&#34; below).</p><p>The user can disable the help from popping-up with the \'Disable help\' tick. To make it popup again, press the F1-key.</p><h2>Create a Docs Container for Detailed Help</h2><ul><li>Duplicate the dibDocs and dibDocsTree containers and name them eg myAppDocs and myAppDocsTree respectively.</li><li>Change the Port record of myAppDocs to point to your application\'s base container, or make it its own base container (empty the <i>pef_port.pef_item_id</i> field).</li><li>Open myAppDocs in the Designer and find the dibDocsTree subcontainer component. Change the Child Container field to point to myAppDocsTree.</li><li>Use ~nav(dibDocsForm)~ to add records to the Docs (pef_docs) table. The container (<i>pef_container_id</i>) field must be linked to myAppDocsTree.</li><li>Navigate to /nav/myAppDocs. Use the Edit Document icon on each article to make changes. Use the HTML editor, or click the editor\'s Source button to edit the HTML directly.</li></ul><p><b>Notes:</b></p><p>Each document page must have a unique name. Names may only have the the following characters: alphanumerical, space, and any of _-@*</p><p>Many powerful features are made available by the Eleutheria templating engine.Â <span>If errors occur, use the Source button of the HTML editor to check that the source has not got HTML embedded in Eleutheria functions.</span></p><h2>Specific to Docs</h2><table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Feature</strong></td><td><strong>Syntax &amp; Notes</strong></td><td><strong>Examples</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Navigate to other documentation pages</td><td><ul><li>~$delim~navdocs(targetPageName[, title][, tagName][, containerName])~$delim~</li><li>If title is empty it will be set to the targetPageName.</li><li>The last 3 parameters don\'t need to be specified. Use commas to skip parameters (see last example).</li></ul></td><td><p>~navdocs(Item 1)~<br/>~navdocs(Item 1, Alternative caption for page Item 1)~<br/>~navdocs(Item 1, Jumping to tag1 on page Item 1, tag1)~<br/>â~navdocs(Basic Steps and Troubleshooting Setup,Navigating to another container docs,,myAppDocs)~</p><p>Â </p></td></tr><tr><td>Navigate to containers</td><td><ul><li>~$delim~nav(containerName with any parameters, title)~$delim~</li></ul></td><td>~nav(test_company_grid,Test Companies)~<br/>~nav(test_company_grid?filter_name=&gt;H,Test Companies filtered on name)~</td></tr><tr><td>Create a navigation tag</td><td><ul><li>~$delim~navtag(tagName[, title])~$delim~</li><li>Generates a tag as a target for the navdocs function</li></ul></td><td>~navtag(tag1)~<br/>~navtag(tag2, Tag with a title)~</td></tr><tr><td>Generate a table listing help in pef_field</td><td><ul><li>~$delim~docstable(tableName[, dollar($) delimitted list of fields])~$delim~</li><li>If the the 2nd parameter is omitted then all fields are displayed</li></ul></td><td>~docstable(test_company,$parent_company_id$website$)~</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Â </p><p>Â </p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc196-dib'),
