    (200, 'General Troubleshooting Tips', 116, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The general principle of troubleshooting/debugging is to<strong> isolate your problem</strong>.</p>\n<p>Start with a working configuration, and increase the scope of certainty incrementally (testing all the time) towards where the error lies. Alternatively one could remove portions that are not certain until the error goes away. This can be accomplished in many ways. Eg use the <strong>UI Include</strong> and <strong>CRUD Include</strong> fields in the Designer or comment out sections of PHP code. If you\'ve added a new feature and it is not working, is there a similar example that is working? If so, then change it incrementally until it resembles what you\'re after or the error is pinpointed.</p>\n<p>The cause of most problems can be found with the following steps. If not, either request help on the community forum, or contact official support.&nbsp;</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Check the list of ~navdocs(Common Error List, docs, Common Errors)~.</li>\n<li>Check the error logs for clues (set the logging levels in <strong>Dib.php</strong>):\n<ol>\n<li>The Dropinbase Error log in the Designer (stored in the <em>pef_error_log </em>table) - pay attention to the main error message, the Stack Trace and Client Data.\n<ol>\n<li>Note, whenever "<strong>Contact the System Administrator</strong>" is displayed, a message is normally logged here.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>/runtime/logs/error.log - if Dropinbase cannot write to the table above, it will write to this file.</li>\n<li>/runtime/logs/Permissions.log - logs users and URLs that attempt to access content that is blocked.</li>\n<li>The PHP error log</li>\n<li>The webserver error log</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Check the browser Console for clues:\n<ol>\n<li>In the browser press F12 (Chrome) or use the menu to open the Console under Developer Tools.</li>\n<li>If any errors are listed, see if the request that caused the error is listed and then find and click on this request under the Network-tab. View the response for details.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>If the error is in custom JavaScript you can "drill-down" into the error to view more info or set a breakpoint in your JavaScript.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Clear any geneated code and active permission records involved\n<ol>\n<li>See ~navdocs(Generating and Clearing Generated Code)~ for details.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>If there is a bug in custom PHP code, use <strong>Log::w(&lt;<em>comma separated list of variables&gt;</em>)</strong> to print values to <strong>/runtime/logs/Debug.txt</strong> (file can be viewed in the Designer), or use a debugger to step through code (eg. Visual Studio Code, Code Lobster, PHPStorm, etc).</li>\n<li>If you are facing a layout issue, use the <strong>UI Include</strong> and <strong>CRUD Include</strong> fields as mentioned in the opening paragraph of this section.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc200-dib'),
    (201, 'Dropinbase Overview', 324, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The following points cover all the main concepts of Dropinbase, allowing savvy developers to get going quickly.Â </p><p>We recommend working through the example pages available from ~nav(dibDashboard)~ and watching the first video in the Dropinbase training series.</p><ol><li>To add a connection to a secondary database, first add a record to ~nav(dibDatabaseGrid)~, and then add the connection details for the database to the /projectFolder/configs/Conn.php file. The index used in Conn.php must match the \'id\' field value of the record. See ~navdocs(Database Connections)~.</li>    <li>A Dropinbase application consists of a base container (eg /nav/dibBase1 or /nav/dibAdmin) that has one or more panels (Port Items) that act as docking positions for other containers to be added to. Port Items can be any component that accepts child panels. They are normally layout components that act as tabs. A container\'s port records identify the Port Items where a specific container can dock. Dropinbase automatically loads nested parent containers/items as they are needed. See ~navdocs(Ports)~ for more info.</li>    <li>New containers can be added to an application in many ways:<ol><li>Import Tables icon (Dashboard): Import one or more new tables and specify whether grid or form containers (or both) must be created. Some default settings can be altered (eg whether forms must have links to Related Records and Audit Trails etc), and design templates can be configured (see ~nav(dibDesignGrid)~.</li><li>For an existing (already imported) table, new containers can be created by using the Create Containers-tab on /nav/dibTableForm.</li><li>(<i>coming soon</i>) Tables and queries can also be dragged and dropped on the Overview section of the Designer to create containers. This is the only method available to automatically create containers based on SQL statements. These SQL grids are useful for reporting purposes as users can filter and sort records, and use navigation links to navigate to existing records.</li><li>(<i>coming soon</i>) Import files icon (Dashboard): Import .xlsx, .xls, .txt, .csv files which will automatically create tables in the database and optionally create form/grid containers based on them (still in Alpha development phase).Â </li><li>Duplicate existing containers using the ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~.</li><li>Manually create containers from scratch. Either use the Add button on theÂ ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~ which is easiest, or create a new record in the <i>pef_container</i> table in some other way (eg using dibContainerForm or another tool to edit database tables).</li></ol></li><li>When $CODEUSE=0 (see theÂ /configs/Dib.php file) the user interface files (stored in /runtime/cache or /dropins/DROPINNAME/cache) are recreated (on the fly) each time they are requested, while the server side crud files (stored in /runtime/crud) are created only if they don\'t exist yet. When DIB::$CODEUSE=2, user interface files are created for the first request only, and then read from cache thereafter. The crud and cache files and folders can be deleted at any time, which will cause them to be generated again when needed.</li>    <li>Dropinbase generates code on the fly for both the client interface and server-side functions of pages using data stored in the Dropinbase tables merged with templates. The templating engine, Eleutheria, is flexible, fast and easy to use to add new templates. Depending on the value ofÂ <em></em>$DEFAULTFRAMEWORK in /configs/Dib.php, either ExtJs or Angular (Ng Material) is used on the client side.</li><li>The Admininstration pages of Dropinbase, eg dibDesigner, make it easier to populate the Dropinbase tables with configuration data. There are many tools, eg<ol><li>Import tables from databases and text/.docx files and automatically create containers (pages) based on them</li><li>Duplicate containers</li><li>Automatically create grids based on SQL statements for eg reporting purposes</li><li>Drag-and-drop components, containers, tables and queries to and between containers</li><li>Copy-paste multiple items between containers and even between Designers in different browser tabs</li><li>Synchronize changes in tables (eg addition or removal of fields - but not changes in field properties eg size).</li><li>Build and maintain menu\'s</li><li>etc.</li></ol></li><li>Note, table records can be updated in bulk using sql statements or the Dropinbase\' Find-and-Replace tool (currently on certain grids, but with the ~nav(dibDesigner)~ it can be drag-and-dropped as a Reusable or copy-pasted, to any grid).</li><li>The administration pages include grids and forms for all Dropinbase tables. The most common tables are:<ol><li><i>pef_table</i> &amp; <i>pef_field</i> Â - the main tables that store the definitions of the database tables - each table has many fields.</li><li><i>pef_container</i> &amp; <i>pef_item</i> Â - based on <i>pef_table</i> and <i>pef_field</i> data, containers (pages) are created. Each container has many items. Each item is of a certain component type (eg inputText or mdButton). Certain component types are used for layout purposes (eg. layoutColumn which arranges its direct child items in vertical fashion). Items are based on HTML, CSS, and ExtJs xtypes or Angular directives which allows designers great flexibility to add configs to items that Angular or ExtJs recognises (see theÂ <i>layout_configs, configs, css</i> fields in pef_item). The easiest way to add new items to containers is by using the drag-and-drop interface of the ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~. See ~nav(dibexComponents)~ for examples.</li><li><i>pef_port</i> - each container can have one or more &#34;ports&#34; which define where in the application this container can be positioned when loaded. Port records have referrences to the container being loaded, and the parent Item (the &#34;Port Item&#34;) that will contain it.Â To open a container by means of eg a button or menuitem, specify a value in the <em>pef_item.pef_port_id </em>field. Ports can be added to containers easily by using the &#34;Add Port&#34; / &#34;Add Port Item and Port&#34; links on the Container Overview in theÂ ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~. See the ~nav(dibexPorts, examples for Ports)~ for more info.</li><li><i>pef_item_event</i> - defines triggers/listeners on items that invoke either server-side (egÂ /dropins/test/Run/helloWorld) or client-side (eg Dropins.dibAdmin.js.app.hideShowHelp) actions. Special actions include ablility to refresh containers/items and lazyload/replace items.</li><li><i>pef_login_xxx</i> &amp;Â <i>pef_perm_xxx</i> tables - defines logins, login groups, and permissions on containers, events, items, records, etc. Permissions can be used to define business rules. For example, a permission group can update certain records in a container, and view certain others, but not delete any. Menus will also automatically adjust to display items that are available to permission groups. Permissions are compiled into &#34;permFiles&#34; files and the <i>pef_perm_xxx_temp</i> tables, based on combinations of permission groups that users belong to, which affect the actual live permissions. Whenever changes are made to permission tables, or new containers or events or dropdownlists are added etc, these files and the <i>pef_perm_xxx_temp</i> tables need to be re-populated (use dibDesigner\'s Clear Files icon) else the live permission system will not recognise the changes. The system automatically replaces these files in many cases.</li><li><i>pef_dropin</i> - stores basic info about the following:<ol><li>Modules - containers can be linked to module dropins causing their crud and cache files to be generated in the associated dropin folders. Modules can be distributed to other developers or deployed to servers.</li><li>Features - one or more items, with their related records such as item events and settings, can be grouped together in a &#34;feature&#34; which can then be dragged-and-dropped to other containers or distributed.</li><li>Container dropins - each container is based on a container dropin (eg dibForm or dibGrid) which determines layout and functionality available for the container (more info in the next main point below).</li><li>Component dropins - each item is linked to a component which determines functionality of the item. Component dropins can be distributed.</li></ol></li></ol></li><li>More about container dropins. Especially in ExtJs, it is important to use the correct set of components for each container dropin type, eg. a gridtextfield cannot be added to dibForm. The Designer helps to a certain extent to display the available components (note that eg. a textfield, which is normally used on forms, can be added to a grid\'s toolbar). Client-side (/runtime/cache) and server-side (/runtime/crud) code for containers is automatically generated as needed. The most common container dropins are:<ol><li>dibGrid - provides a grid layout of records with the ablity to filter and sort them. If the grid is based on a table (pef_container.pef_table_id has a value) then a PHP Crud class is generated and records can also be editted, or added inline. If p<em>ef_container.pef_sql_id</em> has a value, it overrides the value of <em>pef_container.pef_table_id</em> - a PHP file will be generated only to view, filter and sort records.</li><li>dibForm - provides a form layout of components useful for data-entry and viewing related information. Can also contain child containers (eg grids or HTML containers). Must always be based on a table.</li><li>dibHtmlTemplate - uses the powerful Eleutheria engine to merge data from user\'s tables to create HTML reports / dashboards /etc. The HTML is not cached but generated from scratch for every request.</li><li>dibContainer - similar to dibForm, except that it is not bound to a table. It is used for ad hoc / functional forms, eg where users choose options and then execute certain functions (eg dibFiles). It can contain dropdowns or child containers that interact with data.</li><li>There are many other types that provide functions such as pivot grids, Google maps, High Charts, etc.</li></ol></li><li>To add child-containers to a container, use the &#34;subcontainer&#34; component and set its <em>pef_item.pef_child_container_id</em> field. Child container\'s records can be filtered to show eg related child records by using ~navdocs(Filters)~.</li><li>Items or groups of items can be lazy-loaded into an existing container and even replace previously lazy-loaded items. See the ~nav(dibexLazyLoad)~ examples and ~navdocs(Lazy Loading Items)~ for more details.</li><li>Menus can be created in many ways. Navigation is configured by providing values in <em>pef_item.pef_port_id</em> or <em>pef_item.expression</em>Â (eg /nav/dibItemGrid) or adding an event that performs a client- or server-side action. See ~navdocs(Navigation and Menus)~.</li><li>Items with their related records, which may include functionality like exporting records to .xlsx files, can be copy-pasted between containers using the Item tree in theÂ ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~.Â </li><li>Developers can easily add various types of events to items and containers using the available Dropinbase and Angular or ExtJs event triggers. See eg ~navdocs(Item Events)~ for more information.</li><li>By default the generated views for Containers is stored in the /runtime/cache folder, while crud classes are stored in /runtime/crud. Containers can be grouped together in modules using the <i>pef_container.pef_dropin_id </i>(Module Dropin) field. The crud and cache files of containers linked to Module Dropins are created in the respective dropins folders. Module Dropins (which can contain whole applications) can be deployed to servers without the accompanying Dropinbase table (meta data) recordsÂ that define the containers. See ~navdocs(Generating Files)~ and ~navdocs(Deploying Dropins and Applications)~.</li><li>Various tools are available for Debugging applications<ol><li>The ~nav(dibLog,Error Log Files)~ stored in /runtime/logs/. Any errors picked up by server-side code will be reported here.</li><li>Press F12 to view the browser\'s Developer Tools. Check the Console for client-side errors and click links provided for details. Step-by-step execution of client-side code and other features are available.</li><li>Programmers can use the Log::w(var1, var2, var3, ...) function to print information to Error Log\'s Print tab while code is executed.</li><li>Check PHP and Apache error logs. Configure the path to these files in /projectFolder/configs/FileLocations.php in order to view them on the Error Logs.</li></ol></li><li>For more information other than Docs, use the following sources of help<ol><li>Watch the training videos.</li><li>Work through the examples, eg ~nav(dibexComponents)~ and ~nav(dibexContainerDropins)~.Â Use the Â ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~ to investigate workings.Â Â Also note that the entire Administration system was built using Dropinbase and is a valuable source of examples.</li><li>Context sensitive help is available for each field by clicking on them in all Dropinbase\'s administration pages. To view context sensitive help, first open the help-panel on /nav/dibAdmin using the <img src="/files/dropins/setSencha/dibSencha/css/pef_help.png"/> button (ExtJs) or the F1-key (Angular).</li><li>For configuring the user interface, learn more about ~navdocs(Containers)~, ~navdocs(Items)~ and ~navdocs(Components)~. For more in-depth knowledge, see the documentation for either ExtJs or Angular:<ol><li><strong>ExtJs:Â </strong><a href="http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/4.2.2">http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/4.2.2</a></li><li><a href="http://docs.sencha.com/extjs/4.2.2"><strong>Angular (Ng Material):</strong>Â </a><a href="https://material.angularjs.org/latest">https://material.angularjs.org/latest</a>Â (see Demos and Directive), <a href="https://docs.angularjs.org/api">https://docs.angularjs.org/api</a></li><li><a href="https://docs.angularjs.org/api"><strong>Material Design:</strong>Â </a><a href="https://material.google.com/">https://material.google.com/</a>Â (also helpful for designing pages)</li></ol></li><li>For programmers, work through the documentation under Developer Topics, starting with ~navdocs(How Dropinbase Works)~.</li></ol></li></ol><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc201-dib'),
    (202, 'Basic Steps after Importing Tables', 10, 60, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3>Basic Application Settings</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Open the /configs/DibTmpl.php file</li>\n<li>Basic variables:&nbsp;$TIMEZONE,&nbsp;$SITENAME,&nbsp;$SITELOGO,&nbsp;$USERNAME_REGEX</li>\n<li>Delete the /configs/Dib.php file so that it can be regenerated based on DibTmpl.php</li>\n</ul>\n<!--EndFragment-->\n<h3>Adjust Dropdown Display Expressions</h3>\n<p>In some cases you may want to adjust the display expression in dropdowns that Dropinbase configured for foreign key values.</p>\n<p>See ~navdocs(Dropdown Display Expressions)~ for more info.</p>\n<h3>Bulk and Base Container Design Changes</h3>\n<p>Use the ~nav(dibContainerFeature)~ tool to adjust features on the Base Container, as well as make bulk changes to other containers.</p>\n<p>Features are stored under Categories and Sub-categories, and can be applied to specific containers, or containers linked to tables, depending on how the script is configured (see help for more info).</p>\n<p>This tool is based on the <em>pef_script</em> table which stores SQL scripts that makes changes. You can create and distribute your own scripts, or import scripts from other suppliers.</p>\n<h3>Customize the Menu</h3>\n<p>See ~navdocs(Navigation and Menus)~ in docs for more info.</p>\n<h3>Customize Your Application Design</h3>\n<p>Use the ~nav(dibDesigner)~ to make detailed design changes to the application. Learn from the examples provided, starting with ~nav(dibexOverview)~.</p>\n<p>Also see the various help topics under ~navdocs(Administering Dropinbase)~ like the various ways of ~navdocs(Create New Containers, docs, creating new containers)~ or how to ~navdocs(Customize Containers, customize containers)~ etc.</p>\n<h3>Create Login Accounts and set Security Policies</h3>\n<p>Create login account records in the <em>pef_login </em>table, or use ~nav(dibLoginGrid)~.</p>\n<p>Create permission groups in <em>pef_perm_group,</em> or use ~nav(dibPermGroupGrid)~</p>\n<p>Link accounts to permission groups using <em>pef_login_group</em> (see 2nd tab on dibLoginForm, accessible from dibLoginGrid).</p>\n<p>The <em>pef_security_policy </em>table defines various policies regarding signing-in and password expiry. Add records and adjust as needed and link login accounts to them using the <em>pef_login.pef_security_policy_id</em><strong> </strong>field.</p>\n<h3>Move the Login and Other Tables</h3>\n<p>It is recommended to ~navdocs(Move the Login and Other Tables)~ to your "user" database, if you have not already done that.</p>\n<p>Affected tables:</p>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>pef_login, pef_login_group, pef_perm_group, pef_two_factor and pef_security_policy</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>&nbsp;These tables store information that is related to your users, and you may want to add fields to them, or configure relationships with your other tables.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc202-dib'),
    (204, 'TroubleShooting Setup', 116, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>See ~navdocs(Troubleshooting Installation)~ for more info.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc204-dib'),
    (205, 'Dropdown Display Expressions', 28, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Dropdown fields display values that are more useful/understandable to users than the integer foreign key values they are based on.</p>\n<p><strong>Skip this paragraph if you are familiar with foreign keys.</strong> <br>Relational databases store information in tables that are related to one another through a set of primary and foreign keys. The <strong>primary key</strong> field stores a unique value for each record in the table (this field is often an auto-incrementing integer). A <strong>foreign key</strong> field in a related table has values that link the records to this <strong>primay key</strong>. Eg a table named <em>client</em>&nbsp;can contain a record where the <strong>primary key</strong> field named <em>id </em>has a value of 30 and the <em>name </em>field contains \'MIT\'. The&nbsp;<em>client_staff</em> table may have a record where the <em>name</em> field contains \'Noam Chomsky\' and the <strong>foreign key</strong> field named <em>client_id </em>has a value of 30 which links it to the \'MIT\' record. Since we don\'t want users to see the value of <em>client_id </em>in dropdowns, but rather the name of the client (\'MIT\'), we configure a display value.</p>\n<p>To prevent confusing users, display values should always be unique. Display values can be configured as a SQL expression in the <em>Display Expression</em> field of the parent/primary table record. Here they often consist of a single field name eg <strong>client_name</strong>, but can also be an expression eg <strong>CONCAT(`first_name`, \' \', `last_name`) </strong><span style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">(see rule below)</span>. &nbsp;For more flexible values a dropdown-list query can be defined under SQL Queries (in <em>pef_sql)</em>, and referenced by the dropdown item\'s SQL (<em>pef_sql_id)</em> field - this will override the value of <em>pef_table.display_expression</em>.</p>\n<p>On importing tables, Dropinbase automatically builds display expressions based on certain rules (see below).</p>\n<h2>Display Expression (pef_table.display_expression)</h2>\n<p>The expression must be valid in a SQL statement and consist of a singe field or combination of fields in the parent table.</p>\n<p><strong><span style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">RULE: Table field names must be enclosed by backticks (`) and not be prefixed with the parent table name.</span></strong></p>\n<p>Dropinbase automatically prefixes fields with table name aliases when building SQL statements in PHP Crud classes. The ` character helps to identify the field names that need prefixing.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>`name`</li>\n<li>CONCAT(`first_name`, \' \', `last_name`)</li>\n<li>CONCAT(`name`, \' (\', CAST(`id` AS CHAR), \')\')</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Dropdown List Queries (pef_sql)</h2>\n<p>The SQL statement must return two values: a primary key value which will be stored in the dropdown\'s foreign key field, and a display value.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The <em>pef_sql </em>record must conform to certain rules to allow Dropinbase to incorporate the SQL in SELECT statements that return data for eg grids.</p>\n<p><strong><span style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">RULES:</span></strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Set the <em>Query Type</em> field of the SQL record to \'dropdown list\'</li>\n<li>The expression that stores the primary key value must be in<em> Primary Field. </em>Examples:\n<ol>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>pef_component.id</strong></li>\n<li><strong>tableAlias.id</strong> - where tableAlias refers to an alias used in the <em>From Clause</em> field</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>The expression that stores the display value must be in D<em>isplay Field</em>. Examples:\n<ol>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>pef_page.`name`</strong></li>\n<li><strong>tableAlias.`name`</strong>&nbsp;- where tableAlias refers to an alias used in the&nbsp;<em>From Clause</em>&nbsp;field</li>\n<li><strong>CONCAT(c1.`name`, \'.\', ci1.`name`,\'(\', CAST(ci1.id AS CHAR),\')\')</strong> - where c1 and ci1 refers to aliases used in the <em>From Clause</em>&nbsp;field</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>The parent/primary table\'s name must be the first word in the <em>From Clause</em><em>.</em>&nbsp;</li>\n<li>If other tables are joined to the parent table, then the parent table&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration: underline;">must be followed by LEFT JOIN</span>. Examples:\n<ol>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>`test_company` t LEFT JOIN `test_company` `parentCompany` ON `t`.`parent_company_id` = `parentCompany`.`id`</strong></li>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>pef_component cp LEFT JOIN pef_dropin d8 ON cp.pef_material_dropin_id = d8.pef_material_dropin_id LEFT JOIN pef_container c8 ON c8.pef_display_dropin_id = d8.id</strong></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>If more than one dropdown on the same container is linked to the same <em>pef_sql </em>record, an error will occur stating that the same table alias is reused.<br>Since the FROM clauses of the various dropdown\'s will be incorporated into one query, the aliases need to be unique.<br>The solution is to create duplicates of the <em>pef_sql </em>record and changing the table name aliases for each to unique values, and then linking each of the various dropdowns to its own <em>pef_sql</em> record.</li>\n<li>The <em>Where Clause </em>and<em> Order By Clause</em> fields may be used.</li>\n<li>The <em>Select Clause</em> is used only to specify modifiers that will be placed after the \'SELECT\', eg<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"> <span class="token keyword">ALL</span> ~$delimDb~ <span class="token keyword">DISTINCT</span> ~$delimDb~ <span class="token keyword">DISTINCTROW</span> ~$delimDb~ <span class="token keyword">HIGH_PRIORITY<span style="color: #999999;"> <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">~$delimDb~</span> </span></span><span class="token keyword">STRAIGHT_JOIN etc.</span></span></li>\n<li>The <em>Group By Clause</em>, <em>Having Clause</em>&nbsp;and <em>Limit Clause </em>fields may not be used.<br>Use nested SELECT queries in the From-clause if these clauses are necessary.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>How Dropinbase Constructs Table Display Expressions</h2>\n<p>On importing the designs of tables, Dropinbase finds the parent tables that foreign keys reference and then automatically builds the values for&nbsp;<em>pef_table.display_expression.</em>&nbsp;<br>The rules for creating the expression are below.&nbsp;</p>\n<ol>\n<li>In all cases below:\n<ol>\n<li>unique indexes that contain fields where the content_type is&nbsp;\'image\',\'multilinetext\',\'tick\' or \'html\' are ignorred</li>\n<li>the first valid rule found below (from top to bottom) is used.</li>\n<li>the fields involved are concattenated using \'-\'. CAST is used to convert non-text fields to CHAR. IFNULL/ISNULL is used to convert NULLS to \'\' in order for concatenation to work.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>First look for a&nbsp;unique indexes containing only one field that is&nbsp;required and the content_type is text/date/datetime.</li>\n<li>If not found,&nbsp;look for a unique index where all fields are&nbsp;required and their content_type is text/date/datetime.</li>\n<li>If not found,&nbsp;look for a unique index where all fields are&nbsp;required and at least one field\'s content_type is text/date/datetime.</li>\n<li>If not found,&nbsp;look for a&nbsp;unique indexes containing only one field that is not required and the content_type is text/date/datetime. Ensure the contents of the field is unique (***).</li>\n<li>If not found,&nbsp;look for a unique index where fields are not all required and their content_type is text/date/datetime.&nbsp;Ensure the combined contents of the fields is unique&nbsp;(***).</li>\n<li>If not found,&nbsp;look for a unique index where fields are not all required and at least one field\'s content_type is text/date/datetime.&nbsp;Ensure the combined contents of the fields is unique&nbsp;(***).</li>\n<li>If not found, look for the first maximum of 2 fields that are required and their content_type is&nbsp;&nbsp;text/date/datetime.&nbsp;Ensure the combined contents of the fields is unique&nbsp;(***).</li>\n<li>If still not found,&nbsp;use the primary key</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;*** Note: MySql by default allows unique indexes to contain NULLS in more than one record. Dropinbase ensures this is not the case when building a display expression. <br>Where more than one field is involved in a unique index, the combination of fields is used.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc205-dib'),
    (206, 'Activating and Using Dropins', 3, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>General Requirements for all Types</h2>\n<p>The following needs to be in place:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The dropin folder that contains the server- and client-side code must be a subfolder of the /dropins folder, eg /dropins/fastMail</li>\n<li>The ~navdocs(Tables Reference,pef_dropin,pef_dropin)~&nbsp;table record that references the dropin. To create it automatically:\n<ul>\n<li>Delete the&nbsp;/runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt file.</li>\n<li>Next time any server-side call is made, any new dropins will be added to <em>pef_dropin</em> as \'module dropins\'.</li>\n<li>Select the correct <em>dropin_type</em>, in case it has not been set automatically.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>If containers are included with the dropin (containing eg source records for features, or examples), then those containers can be activated by following the steps under Modules below.</li>\n<li>See further requirements specific to each type of dropin below.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Components</h2>\n<p>The following needs to be in place:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <em>pef_component </em>table records that reference the components. See ~navdocs(Components)~ for more info.</li>\n<li>Items in <em>pef_item </em>where the <em>pef_component_id </em>field references the component(s).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The new components will appear in the Designer\'s Components tree under the section defined in <em>pef_component.category</em>, ready to for drag-and-drop actions.</p>\n<h2>Reusables</h2>\n<p>The following needs to be in place:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The container and item records that define the reusables\' source records.</li>\n<li>The <em>pef_dropin </em>table record where <em>dropin_type </em>= \'reusable\'.</li>\n<li>If there are specialized components involved, see the Components section above.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The reusable will appear in the Designer\'s Components tree <span style="float: none;">under the Reusables section, ready to for drag-and-drop actions.</span></span></p>\n<p>See ~navdocs(Reusables)~ for more info.</p>\n<h2>Modifiers</h2>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The following needs to be in place:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li style="font-size: 12pt;"><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The dropin folder that contains the server-side code must be a subfolder of the /dropins/setModifiers folder, eg /dropins/setModifiers/dibAddItem</span></li>\n<li>The <em>pef_dropin </em>table record where <em>dropin_type </em>= \'modifier\'.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-size: 12pt;">The modifier will appear in the Designer\'s Components tree under the Modifiers section, </span><span style="font-size: 16px;">ready&nbsp;</span><span style="float: none;">for drag-and-drop actions.</span></p>\n<div>\n<h2>Container Dropins</h2>\n<p>The following needs to be in place:</p>\n<ul>\n<li style="font-size: 12pt;">If there are specialized components involved, see the Components section above.</li>\n<li>The <em>pef_dropin </em>table record where <em>dropin_type </em>= container/grid container/form container.\n<ul>\n<li style="font-size: 12pt;">Ensure the <em>pef_material_dropin_id </em>field points to setNgxMaterial (or other?).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li style="font-size: 12pt;">Container records where the <em>pef_display_dropin_id </em>(Container Dropin) field links to the dropin record.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Module Dropins</h2>\n<p>The following needs to be in place:</p>\n<ul>\n<li style="font-size: 12pt;">If there are other specialized dropin types involved, see the relevant sections above.</li>\n<li>The <em>pef_dropin </em>table record where <em>dropin_type </em>= \'module\'.</li>\n<li style="font-size: 12pt;">If the containers\' original design (eg&nbsp;<em>pef_container</em>, <em>pef_item)</em> records are included, developers have the ability to adjust the design of the containers.</li>\n<li style="font-size: 12pt;">If they are not included, but their dibCode files are, then the pef_dropin.pef_dropin_cache_db_id field must be set to reference the database that this dropin interacts with (set to Dropinbase database index if none).\n<ul>\n<li style="font-size: 12pt;">See ~nav(Distributing Module Dropins)~ for more info.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc206-dib'),
    (207, 'Generating Files', 326, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The ~nav(dibRelease)~ tool is used to bulk generate code. If all code is generated, Dropinbase no longer relies on design records, and the folder permissions on a production server\'s dibCode folders can be set to read-only.&nbsp;<br>Also see ~navdocs(Deploying Applications)~ for more info.</p>\n<p>~nav(dibRelease)~ provides the following options:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Module Dropin</strong> - choose the module dropin (or \'(all)\') to generate files for.\n<ul>\n<li>The dropdown list contains all Module Dropins that have containers linked to them</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Permgroup </strong>- choose the permgroup to generate files for. Alternatively chooose (all) to generate files for all permgroups.\n<ul>\n<li>The dropdown lists all distinct permgroups in the Login (<em>pef_login</em>) table.</li>\n<li style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);"><span style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">See notes below about Login Accounts required!</span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Display Dropins</strong> - choose which Display Dropins to generate files for, or leave this blank to generate code for all.</li>\n<li><strong>Max Concurrent Threads</strong> - choose how many concurrent threads may be used to generate files. Note that higher values may cause problems with multiple Angular compiling threads. As \'n general rule, don\'t use more threads than you have CPU\'s available (minus 1).</li>\n<li><strong>Changed Containers Only</strong> - this option only generates code for containers of which the dibCode files have been cleared since the last time generation was done. It works by logging those tables in the <em>pef_generate </em>table.</li>\n<li><strong>Skip Existing Files</strong> - this option only generates code for files that don\'t already exist. It does not check the file contents to see whether they are outdated or not.</li>\n<li>Select the other checkboxes to indicate what must be generated. Select all of them if you are not sure what has not been generated.</li>\n<li><strong>List Specific Containers</strong> - ability to generate files for only the selected containers. Note, the green button under Container Details on the Designer can also be used.</li>\n<li><strong>Additional SQL Criteria</strong> - can be used to further restrict which containers are generated. This is often used to isolate problematic containers. See "Additional SQL Criteria" below.</li>\n<li><strong>Generate</strong>-button - perform the generation of files</li>\n<li><strong>Cancel Generation</strong>-button - this creates a file in the /runtime/tmp folder as an indication to the main loop and all active threads that they should stop generation.&nbsp;Note, it takes a little while for them to "see" the file - they typically first complete their immediate action.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Important Notes</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>The process loops through the selected permgroups. With each loop, crud files are generated synchronously, while other (mostly UI) files generate asynchronously using a different thread for each distinct combination of permgroup, module dropin and container type.</li>\n<li style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Dropinbase <span style="text-decoration: underline;">will only generate dibCode files for permgroups that exist in the Login table (<em>pef_login</em>)</span>. It literrally signs-in as one of these accounts while generating. Ensure there is at least one Login record for each permgroup required.</span></li>\n<li>Messages are placed in the Queue to notify the user of progress. If the browser is refreshed while generation is in progress, <span style="text-decoration: underline;">the PHP threads will not be cancelled</span>&nbsp;and carry on generating files. The queue on the server will "overflow" at 50 messages and an error will be logged. To terminate the threads, use the <strong>Cancel Generation</strong> button.</li>\n<li>Each thread first generates all the Angular/TypeScript code, and then compiles all the generated code together. If there are any misconfigured containers the compiling of all containers in the particular permgroup &amp; container type (eg x1x-form) combination will fail. See Troubleshooting below.</li>\n<li>All files required by the containers are generated.\n<ul>\n<li>This implies that the <strong>dibCode </strong>folder on production servers can be set to read-only.</li>\n<li>If the dropin is distributed to other Dropinbase applications, they don\'t need the original design records, unless the permgroups that access the containers differ. If the design records are not available to add more permgroups, then the <strong>dibCode </strong>file names can be altered and active permission records created for the new permgroups to access these containers.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>To verify whether the whole operation has completed, monitor the<strong> /runtime/tmp/</strong> folder to see when last files here were modified.</li>\n<li>It is important to monitor the <strong>/runtime/logs</strong> folder for errors and resolve them.</li>\n<li>Do not start generating code while previously started threads are still running.&nbsp;Users generating files for the same module dropin at the same time could cause conflicts. Use the <strong>Cancel Generation</strong> button to terminate threads, and wait a minute (see notes above).</li>\n<li>After generation for deployment purposes, ensure that developers do not make changes to containers, without also manually regenerating code for these containers. Note, if a container\'s&nbsp;related dropin module\'s <em>pef_dropin.clear_code </em>field is checked, any design change causes the container\'s <strong>dibCode </strong>files to be removed automatically.</li>\n<li>To regenerate all the required files for a single container (all permgroups), use the <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/generateCodeButton.png" alt="" width="40" height="27">-button in the Designer (under Container Details).<br>This is useful when production must be hotfixed, <span style="text-decoration: underline;">but note</span> that if permissions have changed, then the active permission records must be updated/regenerated on production too, since active permission records are checked at runtime.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Additional SQL Criteria</h3>\n<div>\n<div>The main loop that determines which containers to include uses the following FROM-clause. Any "<strong>Additional SQL Criteria</strong>" can reference any of the table aliases herein.</div>\n<pre>(pef_container c INNER JOIN pef_dropin displaydropin ON c.pef_display_dropin_id = displaydropin.id)<br>LEFT JOIN pef_dropin moduledropin ON c.pef_dropin_id = moduledropin.id<br>LEFT JOIN pef_dropin moduleParentDropin ON moduledropin.pef_parent_dropin_id = moduleParentDropin.id<br>LEFT JOIN pef_dropin parentDisplaydropin ON displaydropin.pef_parent_dropin_id = parentDisplaydropin.id<br>LEFT JOIN pef_dropin materialdropin ON displaydropin.pef_material_dropin_id = materialdropin.id<br>LEFT JOIN pef_perm_active prt ON c.id = prt.pef_container_id<br>LEFT JOIN pef_table t ON c.pef_table_id = t.id<br>LEFT JOIN pef_sql q ON c.pef_sql_id = q.id</pre>\n<div>Use single-quotes for text (double-quotes will break the code).</div>\n<div>If using both OR and AND operators, remember to use brackets to clarify the criteria.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><strong>Examples:</strong></div>\n<ul>\n<li>c.name &lt; \'m\'</li>\n<li>c.name &gt; \'h\' AND c.name &lt; \'m\'</li>\n<li>t.name IN (\'client\', \'invoice\', \'product\')</li>\n<li>(c.name &gt; \'h\' AND c.name &lt; \'m\') OR t.name IN (\'client\', \'invoice\', \'product\')</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Troubleshooting</h3>\n</div>\n<div><strong>dibRelease thread error logs</strong></div>\n<div>When Dropinbase starts a thread to generate UI cache files, it creates error log files in the <strong>/runtime/logs</strong> folder. If these files are not empty (0Kb) they will contain PHP error information.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><strong>No UI cache files are generated</strong></div>\n<div>The UI files are generated with asynchronous threads. Dropinbase may fail to find the <strong>php.exe</strong> file to use on your server, or may use the wrong version, or load the wrong version of the&nbsp;<strong>php.ini</strong> configuration file. These errors may be logged in the Dropinbase error log, or the log files mentioned above.<br>Use the <strong>/configs/FileLocations.php</strong> file to configure the path to the <strong>php.exe</strong> file to use. Preferably specify the same <strong>php.exe</strong> file that your webserver uses.&nbsp;</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><strong>Compiling fails</strong></div>\n<div>As mentioned above, when Angular finds an error with a particular container\'s configuration, then all containers in the permgroup/container type combination are affected since all these containers are compiled together.&nbsp;<br>The Dropinbase error log will contain the output of the Angular compiler (and any other errors that may occur), but it may be difficult to spot the exact container and/or item that contains the problem. <br>Follow a process of isolating the problem container(s):</div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>Start by investigating the error reported in the error log and look for ci-numbers (item id values) or container names. The Designer\'s item tree can be searched for an item id value.</li>\n<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">The most common error</span> is attributes or custom HTML with unclosed tags or quotes.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>If the error contains too little info, use "<strong>Additional SQL Criteria</strong>" above to isolate the problematic container(s). For eg. first generate all containers of the type that fails where&nbsp;<code>c.name &lt; \'N\'</code>. If the problem dissappears, use&nbsp;<code>c.name &gt; \'N\' AND c.name &lt; \'S\'</code> etc. to narrow the search to find the container with the problem.</li>\n<li>Manually open the container(s) as a user to generate them, preferably logged in as the particular permgroup. The Error Log should then contain more details of what caused the error.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>If the problem within the container is still unclear, use the&nbsp;<em>UI Include</em> field in the Designer under Item Details to progressively exclude sections of items until the problem disappears when testing.</li>\n<li>Once fixed, make sure it is not a more general problem. When ready, bulk generate and compile all the code again.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\nAlso monitor the <strong>/runtime/logs/error.log</strong> file for errors. Remember, if Dropinbase cannot write to the&nbsp;<em>pef_error_log table</em>, errors are logged here.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc207-dib'),
    (208, 'Reusables', 3, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Reusables are basically collections of items and their related events, filters and settings, that can be dragged-and-dropped from the Components tree in ~nav(dibDesigner)~ as a set. The feature may have related server or client-side code stored in a dropin. Dropinbase ships with the Export button as an example of a feature that can be added to grids. Features can be easily defined, and shared with other installations.</p>\n<p>While developing applications, developers often find repeating sections of the design in containers. These are ideal to define as Reusables. If sections repeat on all containers of a certain type, it may be easier to include these sections in a ~nav(dibDesigner?dibDesigner.groupId=2, Design Template)~, eg <strong>tmplGridTable</strong>.</p>\n<h2>Steps to Define a Reusable</h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Select one or more items in the Item tree in the ~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~.</li>\n<li>On the Tree\'s menu, click the Menu-icon and then "Create New Reusable from Selected Items".</li>\n<li>Provide a unique name for the new Reusable (the name must be unique within the <em>pef_dropin </em>table) and click OK.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Table Fields</h2>\n<p>~docstable(pef_item,$pef_reusable_dropin_id$reusable_source$)~</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc208-dib'),
    (211, 'appendtoField', 95, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', 'appendtoField and button that uses Expression as URL has ability to merge any itemAlias of current Container e.g. /nav/test_company_form?set_companyId={itemAlias}  ', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc211-dib'),
    (212, 'DTable Events', 32, 25, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Table events for CRUD actions are specified in theÂ <em>pef_table.table_events</em>Â field. All containers that are based on a table that have table events configured are affected.Â The event types that must be triggered per table are specified using abbreviations in a comma separated list. The following event types are available:</p><p>Â  Â bc(before create), ac(after create), bu(before update), au(after update), bd(before delete), ad(after delete)</p><p>Eg. theÂ <em>test_child </em>table has the following value in the pef_table.<em>table_events</em> field (use the ~nav(dibTableGrid)~ to view/edit):</p><p>Â  Â bu,bd</p><p>The code targeted by the event must be defined in a class named TableEvents.php with a function named trigger, stored in the container\'s dropin folder, or the components subfolder thereof. If the container is not linked to a module dropin, then TableEvents.php must be in the /projectFolder/runtime folder.Â </p><p>Eg see the /dropins/dibExamples/components/TableEvents.php class.</p><p>The return value of the event must be TRUE if code is to carry on executing normally, or array(\'error\', \'Message to be displayed for user\') if the operation must be cancelled. Obviously cancelling an \'after xxx\' event has little value.</p><p>See the example below for parameters that are available.Â </p><p>Also see Table Events on ~nav(dibexEvents)~ for more info.</p><h3><strong>Example definition of a trigger function</strong></h3><pre><p>/**<br/>Â  Â  Â * Processes any table-level crud event directed to it<br/>Â  Â  Â * Note the parameters sent by reference that can be updated<br/>Â  Â  Â *Â <br/>Â  Â  Â * @param string $containerName name of the containerName involved<br/>Â  Â  Â * @param string $trigger one of: before create, after create, before update, after update, before delete, after delete<br/>Â  Â  Â * @param string $source the record source of the container: table name, or id of pef_sql record involved<br/>Â  Â  Â * @param array $attributes record field names and values<br/>Â  Â  Â * @param array $primaryKeyData primary key names and values<br/>Â  Â  Â * @param int $databaseId id of database involved - useful for calls to Database class<br/>Â  Â  Â * @param object $crudClass object pointing to container\'s crud class<br/>Â  Â  Â * @param mixed $crudResult result of crud operation (note, could be array(\'error\', $msg) in case crud operation failed)<br/>Â  Â  Â *Â <br/>Â  Â  Â * @return mixed TRUE on success, or array(\'error\', $msg) to return a message to the user, and cancel any further operations.<br/>Â  Â  Â */</p>&#10;<p><br/>Â  Â  public static function trigger($containerName, $trigger, $source, &amp;$attributes, &amp;$primaryKeyData, $databaseId, &amp;$crudClass, &amp;$crudResult) {</p>&#10;<p>Â  Â  Â  Â  ...</p>&#10;<p>Â  Â  }</p>&#10;</pre><p>Â </p><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc212-dib'),
