    (215, 'Dropins Overview', 3, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Dropins are shareable folders and/or sets of design records that store code used to build applications and execute functions in them. Dropin folders can in-fact store anything and is therefore flexible in terms of purpose. <span style="text-decoration: underline; color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">Note</span>, since they are commited to repositories and backed up, they should never store user data.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>main&nbsp;</strong>is the default Module Dropin where you can store your application\'s custom code. The generated code for containers will be stored here in a <strong>/dibCode</strong> subfolder.</li>\n<li><strong>setNgxMaterial/grid</strong> is a Grid Container dropin that contains templates and code used to build and facilitate grids.&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>dibExcel </strong>is a core Module Dropin that contains code for reading and write .xlsx files.&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>dibExamples </strong>is a core Module Dropin that contains design records and server-side code for learning purposes. You can copy this folder to your application\'s /dropins folder to override it.</li>\n<li><strong>Grid Export File Menu</strong> is a Reusable dropin that consists of design records that provides a menu to export grid data in various ways.</li>\n<li><strong>calendar </strong>is a component dropin that enables an editable calendar view.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Dropins can be packaged and shared with other Dropinbase Installations. This implies:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Team members that work offline on the same application can exchange their work with one another (as long as they work on different sections)</li>\n<li>Modules can be exchanged between installations</li>\n<li>Developers can share their reusable creations with the community or sell them in the Store (coming soon)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To create dropins, start by investigating or copying an existing one. Also include documentation and examples.</p>\n<p>Create packages to share dropins with ~nav(dibShareExport)~ and import packages with ~nav(dibShareImport)~.</p>\n<p>There are 5 main types of dropins:</p>\n<h2>Dropin Types</h2>\n<p>A dropin can consist of nearly any part of the system, eg tables, containers, items, components, functions, events, PHP code, images, etc. or any combination thereof. Depending on their purpose and what they contain, they are classified by the <em>dropin_type </em>field into the following categories:</p>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Contents</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>component (HTML)</td>\n<td>A component dropin folder stores templates (eg inputText.et.html) and code for one or more components (eg a textfield or image component) that can be used as items in containers.&nbsp;<br>The <em>pef_component </em>table will have corresponding entries referencing the individual component files. The <em>pef_component_id </em>field in the <em>pef_item </em>table is set to use a particular component.</td>\n<td>Record(s) in the <em>pef_component </em>table identified by the <em>pef_component_dropin_id </em>field.<br>Template files (eg inputText.et.html).<br>Any useful or required server- or client-side code (eg controllers).&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<p>component (TypeScript)</p>\n</td>\n<td>A <strong>/ts/components</strong> folder stores the .html, .ts and .scss files required for a particular component. Developers implement the component by referencing it in Item Settings.<br>See ~navdocs(Custom Components)~ for more info.</td>\n<td>A <strong>/ts/components</strong> folder withthe .html, .ts and .scss files.<br>Any useful or required server-side code.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>reusable</td>\n<td>One or more items and their child items with related events, item settings, tooltips and code. Eg a Excel Export button.</td>\n<td>Records for the items, item settings, events etc. and all related client- and server-side code.&nbsp;Can also include components that are specific to the dropin.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>modifier</td>\n<td>PHP code that makes a tool available in the Designer to accomplish a certain design task. The code is stored in a dropin under /dropins/setModifiers/components/xxx.php where xxx is also the name of the dropin. <br>See the modifiers provided in the above folder for examples of how to create your own. <br>Please share useful modifiers with the community.</td>\n<td>PHP code.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>grid&nbsp;container</td>\n<td>A container-type that can be selected in the <em>pef_display_dropin_id</em> field of <em>pef_container</em>, displaying data from a table or sql statement in rows and columns (grid layout). Eg <strong>grid.</strong></td>\n<td>Templates and controllers and other code used by implementations of the container dropin. Can also include components that are specific to the dropin.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>form&nbsp;container</td>\n<td>A container-type that can be selected in the&nbsp;<em>pef_display_dropin_id</em>&nbsp;field of <em>pef_container</em>, displaying data from a table or SQL statement in a form layout. Eg <strong>form</strong>.</td>\n<td>Templates and controllers and other code used by implementations of the container dropin. Can also include components that are specific to the dropin.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>container</td>\n<td>Any other container-type (not a typical grid- or form-container)&nbsp;&nbsp;that can be selected in the&nbsp;<em>pef_display_dropin_id</em> field of pef_container. Eg <strong>plain </strong>and <strong>iframe</strong>.</td>\n<td>Templates and controllers and other code used by implementations of the container dropin. Can also include components that are specific to the dropin.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>module</td>\n<td>\n<p>Containers can be grouped together in modules by linking them to dropins by using the <em>Module Dropin</em> (<em>pef_container.pef_dropin_id)</em> field. <br>Their ./dibCode files will be generated under the dropin\'s folder.</p>\n<p>Module dropins consist of the code (dibCode, controllers, components, etc) and optionally the design records defining a part of an application that can be re-used in other applications, or even an whole application. Modules are functional units eg a stock or invoicing system. Another example is the Dropinbase Administration pages that are stored in <strong>/dropins/setNgxMaterial/dibAdmin</strong>. Modules can be distributed without the database design records that define their containers, but then end-users would not be able to make adjustments, integrate it with links to their own containers, and will need to copy and rename files and permission records when using it with permgroups that differ from the original. Modules can make use of new components, though these new components should be in a separate dropin unless they are dependent both ways.</p>\n</td>\n<td>The dropin folder with all the required code (at the very least the /dibCode files).</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc215-dib'),
    (216, 'Dropin Sets', 3, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Dropins can be stored under a \'parent\' dropin to help arrange files in a set, and provide structure to complex dropins. A dropin may only have a direct parent and not a "grandparent" dropin (ie one level of parent dropins). A parent dropin\'s name must start with \'set\' eg <strong>setData</strong>. The child dropin folders must be stored directly under the set folder. Material dropins (eg <strong>setNgxMaterial</strong>) must make use of sets in order to contain required dropins such as <strong>form </strong>and <strong>grid</strong>.</p>\n<p>Requests targeting child dropins will be of the form <strong>/dropins/setParent/ChildDropin/...</strong> eg <strong>/dropins/setNgxMaterial/iframe/Template/controller</strong>.</p>\n<p>Here is another (hypothetical) example - a button\'s click event targetting a child dropin:</p>\n<p><strong>/dropins/setExample/Export/Excel/write</strong> where \'<strong>setExample</strong>\' is the parent dropin, \'<strong>Export</strong>\' is the child dropin, \'<strong>Excel</strong>\' points to the <strong>ExcelController.php</strong> file, and \'<strong>write</strong>\' is the function name being called.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc216-dib'),
    (217, 'Generating Containers using Design Templates', 324, 33, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Apart from manually creating containers from scratch, they can be generated automatically by the system using any of the following means:</p><ul><li>Import one or more tables from a database (see ~navdocs(Creating Applications and Importing Tables)~ under Getting Started)</li><li>Drag-and-drop a table, query or container from the Components tree on the Layout-tab on ~nav(dibDesigner)~.</li><li>Import a text or .xlsx file (still in beta development phase)</li></ul><p>All the above methods make use of other containers that act as templates that define the general features of the new containers.Â </p><p>The relevant database record (in <i>pef_database</i>) stores references to which designs to use for Forms, Grids and SQL Grids. The design records (see ~nav(dibDesignGrid)~) each have a reference to a container that is used as a base template. Each time a specific type of container is created (eg a grid), a copy is made of the associated template container, specified in <i>pef_design</i>, and then a list of actions are performed, specified in <i>pef_design_featureÂ </i>and <i>pef_design_values</i>, to round it off.</p><p>Dropinbase ships with default designs for grid, form and sql grid containers. Use these as examples when adding your own.</p><p>The field values of the following tables related to the template containers are used when creating new containers:</p><ul><li>pef_container</li><li>pef_container_setting</li><li>pef_container_event</li><li>pef_container_filter</li><li>pef_perm_container</li><li>pef_perm_active</li><li>pef_item</li><li>pef_item_setting</li><li>pef_item_event</li><li>pef_item_filter</li></ul><h2>Table fields</h2><h3>pef_design - stores a link to the container used as design template</h3><p>~docstable(pef_design)~</p><h3>pef_design_feature - contains features (eg fields or dropin features) that are added to the container</h3><p>~docstable(pef_design_feature)~</p><h3>pef_design_values - defines field values that are updated after creating new containers</h3><p>~docstable(pef_design_values)~</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc217-dib'),
    (218, 'Permission Checks', 23, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Active Permission Record Checks</h2>\n<p>Please review ~navdocs(Permissions Overview)~ for essential background info.</p>\n<h3>How it works</h3>\n<p>If the targetted PHP function of any request contains <strong>$containerName </strong>as function parameter, the container permissions are checked for the specified container from the active permission record tables.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>In addition, if it contains&nbsp;<strong>$itemEventId</strong>, a further check is made against the <strong>Submit Url</strong> and <strong>dibuid </strong>value of the specific item event record, and if it contains&nbsp;<strong>$containerEventId</strong>, a check is made against the <strong>Submit Url</strong> and <strong>dibuid </strong>value of the specific container event record.</p>\n<p>Note, t<span style="color: #000000;">he Dropinbase generated client-side code automatically submits <strong>$containerName</strong>, and the&nbsp;<strong>containerEventId=[dibuid] </strong>parameter values for all container events, and&nbsp;<strong>itemEventId=[dibuid] </strong>for all item events.&nbsp;</span>Your custom JavaScript or other code that targets the Dropinbase framework, may need to add these parameter values.</p>\n<p><strong><span style="color: #e03e2d;">IMPORTANT:</span></strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="color: #000000;">If <strong>$containerName </strong>is absent in function parameters, then the permissions of the container specified in the </span><strong>$DEFAULTPERMSCONTAINER</strong> variable in <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> is checked. If <strong>$DEFAULTPERMSCONTAINER</strong> is empty or does not exist, then a container named \'<strong>noDefaultPermsContainerSpecified</strong>\' is assumed.</li>\n<li>If a container or item event record has no <strong>dibuid</strong> value, then its primary key (<strong>id</strong>) value is used instead for the check.</li>\n<li>If the PHP controller function definition assigns a default value to the <strong>$containerName </strong>parameter, any request that calls it without specifying a value will require that the user has permissions on that container. The <strong>$itemEventId</strong> and <strong>$containerEventId</strong> function parameters should never have defaults, but they can be omitted from the parameters to avoid that level of permission checking.</li>\n<li><span style="color: #000000;">If <strong>$containerName </strong>is absent and a <strong>$REQUEST_TYPE</strong> parameter is added to the function parameters which contains for eg <code>\'POST,ignorecontainerperms\'</code>, then this function is effectively public - no container or event permission checks are made.</span></li>\n<li><span style="color: #000000;">Note, the above rules also imply that if a container is created with the name specified in <strong>$DEFAULTPERMSCONTAINER</strong>, and the Public Users permission group is linked to it, then all events specified (on for eg. hidden buttons) on this container will be publicly available.</span></li>\n<li><span style="color: #000000;">Certain other parameter names and request types (like CRUD requests) lead to further checks against active permission records (see table below).</span></li>\n<li><span style="color: #000000;">As a general rule, functions should always have a <strong>$containerName</strong> variable without a default value, and then either <strong>$itemEventId</strong> or <strong>$containerEventId</strong> (depending on whether a item or container event is involved).</span></li>\n</ul>\n<table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 52.8101%; height: 179.2px;" border="1"><colgroup><col style="width: 10.1411%;"><col style="width: 6.86377%;"><col style="width: 11.8725%;"><col style="width: 71.1111%;"></colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr style="background-color: #c2e0f4; height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Parameter Name</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Request</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Table</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Check against Active Permission Record</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">$containerName</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">(any)</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">pef_perm_active</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">record for this container and permgroup must exist where <em>open_criteria </em>IS NOT NULL<br>If there is <em>open_criteria</em>, this is also verified.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">$containerName</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">/peff/Crud</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">pef_perm_active</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">the related crud criteria field (<em>create_criteria</em>, <em>read_criteria</em>, <em>update_criteria</em>,&nbsp; <em>delete_criteria</em>) must not be NULL.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>$containerItemId</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">(any)</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>pef_perm_item_list_active</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">record for this container and permgroup must exist</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>$itemEventId</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">(any)</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>pef_perm_active</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">record for this container and permgroup must exist where <em>item_event_detail </em>contains the request.<br>A specific search string is constructed to find the right match eg. "<strong>;/dropins/myDropin/MyActions/myFunction#FH4WR3PF-dib;</strong>" where the <strong>dibuid </strong>(or <strong>id</strong>) value follows the <strong>#</strong>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>$containerEventId</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">(any)</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>pef_perm_active</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">record for this container and permgroup must exist where <em>container_event_detail </em>contains the request.<br>A specific search string is constructed to find the right match eg. "<strong>;/dropins/myDropin/MyActions/myFunction;#RG4T5X6U-dib;</strong>" where the <strong>dibuid </strong>(or <strong>id</strong>) value follows the <strong>#</strong>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>(requests that do <span style="text-decoration: underline;">not</span> have $itemEventId or $containerEventId)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">/dropins/</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>pef_perm_active</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">record for this container and permgroup must exist where either <em>item_event_detail OR</em>&nbsp;<em>container_event_detail </em>contains the request.<br>A specific search string is constructed to find the right match eg. "<strong>;/dropins/myDropin/MyActions/myFunction#</strong>". Note the <strong>dibud</strong> (or <strong>id</strong>) value is omitted from the criteria.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Any violations are logged in the Dropinbase error log (<em>pef_error_log</em>) with <em>err_type </em>= \'perms\'.</p>\n<h2>Login Group Expiry</h2>\n<p>With each request, the system checks the user\'s <em>permgroup</em>, <em>login_expiry </em>and&nbsp;<em>login_group_expiry </em>dates in <em>pef_login</em>. <br>If the <em>permgroup </em>is empty or <em>login_group_expiry&nbsp;</em>date has expired, it will result in a recalculation of the user\'s permgroup. <span style="color: #e03e2d;">This will require <strong>write </strong>rights on the <em>pef_login </em>table. To avoid this situation set the expiry dates to far in the future.</span><br>If the <em>login_expiry </em>date is reached, or the recalculation result returns no active permgroup, the user is logged in as the <em>system_public </em>user.</p>\n<h2>Additional Checks</h2>\n<p>The following checks are done on all requests, irrespective of the existence of the <strong>$containerName, $itemEvent and $containerEvent</strong> parameters:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Any \'.\' character in the URL is replaced with underscore (_).</li>\n<li>Thereafter, the URL must be alpha-numeric, except for the following characters: /_*-</li>\n<li>The URL must be one of the Dropinbase accepted forms else the user is redirected to the login page.</li>\n<li>The user\'s PHP session must still be active and both his <em>pef_login.login_expiry</em> and <em>pef_login._login_group_expiry</em> dates must be in the future.</li>\n<li>If&nbsp;$VERIFY_IP is set in Dib.php then their public IP address must match the given pattern (note hackers can spoof this).</li>\n<li>If $VERIFY_USER_AGENT is set in Dib.php then the USER_AGENT submitted by the browser must match the value when the user signed in (note some ISP\'s/router-technology causes these values to change periodically, but generally it is not problematic).</li>\n<li>If $VERIFY_AUTH_TOKEN is set in Dib.php then this value must match the secure token value generated when the user signed in.</li>\n<li>\n<div>\n<div>If $CHECKUSERSESSIONS is set - block session hijacking. Affects users where pef_login.check_user_session==1. These users can have only one active session. Note, pef_login.session_version is compared with value stored in PHP session with every request, which affects performance.</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li>The request\'s type must be POST, unless the PHP function specifies a valid set using the following parameter name, eg&nbsp;<strong>$REQUEST_TYPE="GET,POST"</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Furthermore, the generated server (and client) code only contains code that the permgroup may execute.</p>\n<h2>.htaccess / Virtual Host Entry</h2>\n<p>This <strong>.htaccess</strong> file is used to redirect all <strong>/files/</strong> requests to the <strong>/files.php </strong>file, and all other requests to <strong>/index.php</strong>. Any requests for other .php files are blocked.</p>\n<p>Note, Dropinbase installations do not use <strong>.htaccess</strong> files in any subfolders. For improved security the rules in the <strong>.htaccess</strong> file can therefore be moved to the website\'s Virtual Host entry.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc218-dib'),
    (219, 'dibGrid - Sql', 2, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3>Configuration</h3><p>Create a record in ~nav(dibSqlForm)~. Provide values for at least the <i>select_clauseÂ </i>and <i>from_clauseÂ </i>fields<i>. </i>Use any of the other fields too, except <i>primary_field, extra_list_rows and total_count_sql</i> - these are used for specifying SQL for dropdown lists. The <i>display_field </i>field can be used for directives such as DISTINCT or STRAIGHT_JOIN. The <i>database </i>field identifies which database the SQL statement is executed against.</p><p>Use the Designer to set a container\'s <i>model</i> field on Pg1 to \'Sql\' and select the record created above in the Sql dropdown. Save the record, and ensure that the relevant permgroup\'s permission files are deleted (/runtime/permFiles) as well as any CRUD class that was created for this container.</p><p></p><p><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">From Component Tree, drag the contentFor component</span><span class="Apple-converted-space" style="font-size: 12px;">Â to the Item Tree, placing it anywhere you require the grid\'s columns to be positioned. Ie you can specify any design that incorporates various nested components, as long as (only one) contentFor component is placed somewhere within. Rename the contentFor component to \'columns\'.</span><br/></p><p>The Component Tree\'s Field List in the Designer will display all column aliases in the SQL statement, except those with the <i>_display_value </i>suffix (see below). Drag-and-drop columns to the Item Tree. Note, no parent item (eg layout-row or layout-column) is required for bound fields.</p><p>All fields in the item table are applicable, the primary ones being:</p><ul><li>caption - specify the column heading</li><li>expression - specify the column alias from the SQL statement</li><li>expression_type - must be \'sql\'</li><li>pef_component _id - specify the component type. Use grid-text-sql for fields that have a corresponding display_value column and must have a navigation link (see below), and input_text for the rest.</li></ul><p>When the client issues the first CRUD request for this container (eg /peff/Crud/read/dibtestCompanySqlRptGrid?page=1&amp;start=0&amp;limit=10), Dropinbase will create the relevant PHP class, eg Â Sqlxx1xxdibtestCompanySqlRptGrid.php.Â <font face="inherit">Therefore, </font><u>if any changes are made to the SQL statement in future</u><font face="inherit">, ensure that the container\'s CRUD class is deleted. By default the Designer attempts to automatically delete the CRUD class when </font>necessary<font face="inherit">.</font></p><p><font face="inherit">NOTE permission for permgroups can only be set for rights to open the container. More advanced permissions will probably be added later.</font></p><p><font face="inherit">Users can filter data in grids based on SQL in exactly the same manner as grids based on tables.</font></p><h3><font face="inherit">Adding Navigation Links to Columns</font></h3><p>If your SQL statement returns a foreign key value (which is normally an integer), you can make it display the value it references, along with a navigation link to open the related record in its container. Notice the following SQL statement:</p><p>SELECT sale.product_name, sale.client_id as client, client.name as client<b>_display_value</b>, sale.cost<br/>FROM sale LEFT JOIN client ON sale.client_id = client.id</p><p>If we add an item to the container where</p><ul><li>expression = client</li><li>expression_type = grid-text-sql</li><li>port = {port that points to the client container}</li></ul><p>The the client grid column will display the client\'s name (instead of the client_id) and a navigation link will be available to navigate to the specific client.</p><h3>Submission Data</h3><p>By default, all field values of items with aliases, of the record that last had the focus are submitted under submitItemAlias. Use the submitCheckedItems config to submit selected records.<br/></p><p></p><p></p><h3>Custom Field Data</h3><p>Change the SQL statement customize the data sent to the client. The client binds with the value in the expression field, which must therefore be the same as the column name/alias.</p><h3>Include Other Components<br/></h3><p>Columns can contain components such as comment and layout-column (see eg ~nav(dibexContainerDropins, Container Dropin Examples)~). Certain components will break the layout and need some coding adjustments before they can be used.</p><p><br/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc219-dib'),
    (222, 'Server API Call Stack', 39, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>(See also ~navdocs(Common API Requests)~)</p>\n<h2>File Requests</h2>\n<p>The following steps are processed with each API request that starts with&nbsp;<strong>/files/</strong> (eg&nbsp;<strong>/files/files/images/my.pdf&nbsp; </strong>&nbsp;or<strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;/files/dropins/main/Test/docs/hello.xlsx)</strong></p>\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Note, these are requests for static files that are publicly available (eg images and .css files).</span></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Break the URL into parts: file-name, file-extension, file-path</li>\n<li>Load the <strong>/configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</strong> file</li>\n<li>Perform following checks:\n<ol>\n<li>the file-path is alphanumeric (allow the following characters: /_-).</li>\n<li>the file-name is alphanumeric (allow the following characters: ._ -).</li>\n<li>the specific file path is listed in the array specified in the checkFile function of the <strong>AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</strong> file.</li>\n<li>the file-extension is listed in the array specified in the getMimeType function of the <strong>AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</strong> file.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>A violation of anything under point 3 above returns a 401 hedaer, and the error is logged in&nbsp;<strong>/runtime/logs/AllowedFileExtAndFoldersErrorLog.log</strong>.</li>\n<li>Check if the file exists\n<ol>\n<li>If not, 404 headers are returned.</li>\n<li>Note, URL\'s that start with&nbsp;<strong>/files/dropins/</strong>&nbsp; are checked under both the system and developer dropin folders.</li>\n<li>Files not found in <strong>/files/dropins/</strong>... folders are logged in <strong>/runtime/logs/InvalidDropinFileRequestLog.log</strong>.</li>\n<li>Files not found in other folders like /files/files/images are <span style="text-decoration: underline;">not</span> logged.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Main API Requests</h2>\n<p>The following steps are processed with each non-<strong>/files/</strong> API request (eg <strong>/nav/dashboard</strong>&nbsp; or&nbsp; <strong>/dropins/main/Test/myFunc</strong>)</p>\n<ol>\n<li>(Apache only) The <strong>.htaccess </strong>file directs any non-<strong>/files/</strong> request to <strong>/index.php</strong>, which in turn calls <strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/index.php</strong>.</li>\n<li>An error handler is configured to catch and log fatal errors, and then&nbsp;<strong>DibApp.php</strong> -&gt; <strong>setup() </strong>is called to initialize the framework.</li>\n<li>Initializes the autoloader for .php scripts in <strong>/component</strong> folders</li>\n<li>If <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> or <strong>/runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt</strong> does not exist, an initialization function is called which\n<ol>\n<li>creates <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> based on <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong></li>\n<li>creates any missing <strong>/runtime</strong> folders</li>\n<li>checks if new dropin folders have been added</li>\n<li>creates the <strong>/runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt</strong> file</li>\n<li>recreates all records in the Active Permission Tables\n<ol>\n<li>It obtains records for the <strong>dibAdmin/setNgxMaterial</strong> dropin (the Dropinbase admin pages, like dibDesigner) and other dropins where <em>pef_dropin.pef_dropin_cache_db_id</em> is set, from the dropins\' <strong>/dibCode/_perms</strong> folder.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>runs outstanding Migration Scripts in <strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/Migration Scripts.dtxt</strong> depending on the value of <strong>dibDatabaseVersion </strong>in the <em>pef_setting </em>table</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Loads core classes, including the global DIB:: variables in&nbsp;<strong>Dib.php</strong> and the database connection file <strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong>.</li>\n<li>Open a <strong>Try... Catch</strong> - any further unhandled errors in the application will be caught and logged.</li>\n<li>Analyze the URL.\n<ol>\n<li>Isolate and store the URL query parameters.</li>\n<li>Ensure the URL has valid characters.</li>\n<li>If <strong>/nav/...</strong> then serve the <strong>index.html</strong> page from cache stored in <strong>/runtime/cache/index.dtxt</strong>. First create the cache file if neccessary by merging <strong>pef_setting</strong> merge fields with the file identified in DIB::$INDEXPATH.</li>\n<li>If <strong>/login</strong> then call the <strong>/dropins/dibAuthenticate/Site/login</strong> function which serves the login page.</li>\n<li>Otherwise, if the URL contains less than 4 parts, call the <strong>/dropins/dibAuthenticate/Site/logout</strong> function which will sign the user out, and redirect to the login page.</li>\n<li>If <strong>/dropins/...</strong> or <strong>/peff/...</strong> ensure the URL is correctly formed, and store the URL parts.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Authenticate the user request.\n<ol>\n<li>If not logged in:\n<ol>\n<li>if <strong>DIB::$ENABLE_REMEMBERME</strong> is set check Remember Me cookies and authenticate, else assign as the <em>system_public </em>user &amp; redirect to login page.&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>If logged in:\n<ol>\n<li>if <strong>DIB::$VERIFY_IP</strong> is set check if IP address changed -&gt; assign as&nbsp;the <em>system_public </em>user if changed.</li>\n<li>if <strong>DIB::$VERIFY_USER_AGENT</strong>&nbsp;is set check if User Agent has changed -&gt; assign as the <em>system_public </em>user if changed</li>\n<li>if <strong>DIB::$CHECKUSERSESSIONS</strong>&nbsp;is set check if the <strong>pef_login.session_version</strong> value equals the value stored in the user\'s session -&gt; increment the value if not, which in effect will invalidate all sessions linked to this user.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Check if user\'s permgroup is empty\n<ol>\n<li>rebuild if so. If still empty,&nbsp;assign as the <em>system_public </em>user.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Check for permission expiry dates (<em>login_expiry</em>, <em>login_group_expiry </em>in <em>pef_login</em>)\n<ol>\n<li>if <em>login_group_expiry </em>reached&nbsp;rebuild permgroup. If still empty, assign as the <em>system_public </em>user.</li>\n<li>if <em>login_expiry </em>reached then&nbsp;assign as the <em>system_public </em>user.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Set <strong>DIB::$PERMGROUP</strong>, <strong>DIB::$USER</strong></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Construct the path to the relevant PHP controller file, based on the URL parts.</li>\n<li>Call the <strong>ControllerFactory.php</strong> file.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>The <strong>ControllerFactory.php</strong> file steps through the following actions:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Uses reflection methods to obtain the parameters declared in the targetted controller function</li>\n<li>Finds values for these parameters using the following order:\n<ol>\n<li>Check if extra values(words) exist in the URL before the \'?\' - assign them in order to the controller function\'s parameters</li>\n<li>Check parameter values from the query string (after the \'?\') - assign them according to name</li>\n<li>If the parameter name is \'clientData\' then get values from posted data</li>\n<li>Check if default values exist in the function declaration - assign them if the above has failed to assign values</li>\n<li>If nothing has been assigned yet for a particular required parameter, throw an exception.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Foreach of the following parameter names that occur in the PHP function, call functions that validation permissions based on Active Permission Table entries.\n<ol>\n<li>\'containerName\',\'containerItemId\',\'itemEventId\',\'containerEventId\'</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>If DIB::$VERIFY_AUTH_TOKEN is set, and the targetted function does not have \'ignoretoken\' as option in the $REQUEST_TYPE parameter, then check the request type against allowed values (POST by default).</li>\n<li>If DIB::$CATCHALLEVENT specified, call it.</li>\n<li>Call the function.</li>\n<li>If a non-empty result is returned, send (echo) it to the client.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc222-dib'),
    (223, 'User Help', NULL, 70, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc223-dib'),
    (224, 'Filtering Grid Records', 223, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>A user can filter data (remove unwanted records temporarily) from grids by applying filters.</p><p>Provide criteria in the filter boxes for each column/field that must be filtered. Eg if a certain grid displays information about companies and only records where the <em>Name </em>field is greater than \'M\', and the <em>Notes </em>field isÂ \'New\' must be displayed, the following criteria must be typed in the filter box just below the column caption \'Name\':</p><p><strong>&gt;M</strong></p><p>And the filter box for the Notes field must be:</p><p><strong>=New</strong></p><p>To apply the filter, click the Apply Filter button. To remove the filter, click the Clear Filter button. Click the Refresh button to re-apply the current filter (eg if data has been removed/changed since it was last refreshed).Â </p><p>Filter criteria can be composite, eg the following criteria in the <em>Name </em>field filters data where Name is greater than M and smaller than or equal to \'Peter\'</p><p><strong>&gt;M&amp;&lt;=Peter</strong></p><p>To find records where Name is smaller than M or greater than Peter use the ~$delimdb~Â operator, eg</p><p><strong>&lt;M~$delimdb~&gt;Peter</strong></p><p>If no comparison operator is supplied (eg &lt;) then the LIKE operator is implied to find values starting with the search term. Eg specifying:</p><p><strong>hello</strong></p><p>is the same as specifying:</p><p><strong>LIKE hello*</strong></p><p>To find records where a field contains (as opposed to starts with) the word \'hello\', use</p><p><strong>*hello</strong></p><p>To find records where a field does not start with \'aa\', or those that contain \'bb\' use</p><p><b>&lt;&gt;LIKE aa* ~$delimdb~ LIKE *bb*</b></p><h2>Notes</h2><ul><li>Mixing &amp; andÂ ~$delimdb~ operators in the same expression can have unexpected results, eg <b>&gt;3&amp;&lt;5~$delimdb~&gt;1</b> can effectually mean all numbers greater than 3, or all numbers greater 1. In practice expressions are normally evaluated from left to right which means in this case all numbers greater than 1 will apply.</li><li>When an operator (eg &lt; or &gt;=) is not present (as in our example of New in <em>Notes </em>above) then the Like operator is implied. Ie the following is equivalent:<ul><li>New</li><li>like New*</li></ul></li><li>Using upper or lower case makes no difference. Eg the following is equivalent:<ul><li>like m~$delimdb~&lt;sally</li><li>LIKE M~$delimdb~&lt;Sally</li></ul></li><li>The or operator (~$delimdb~) always results in more records being returned than using the and opeartor (&amp;).</li><li>When using for eg<b> &gt;J</b>, note that <em>Jam </em>is greater than <em>J</em> (follows alphabetically)</li><li>Spaces in criteria are ignored. Ie the following two sets of criteria is identical<ul><li>&gt;M&amp;&lt;=Peter</li><li>&gt;M &amp; &lt;=Peter</li></ul></li><li>The current filter reflects in the browser url. Users can copy urls containing filters and eg email them to other users.</li><li>Using Like<ul><li>Remember that the Like operator is implied (see note above)</li><li><b>like Paul</b> will find: Paul, Pauline, Paul in the pool, etc</li><li><b>Paul</b> will find the same result</li><li><b>=Paul</b> will only find: Paul</li><li><b>&lt;&gt;like</b> is used to exclude records</li><li>* is used with Like to indicate any string of characters (or nothing). Examples:<ul><li><b>*Paul</b> will find: Paul, Jane and Paul, Paul in the pool, abcPauldef, abcpaulDEF, etc</li><li><b>Paul*Jane</b> will find Paul and Jane, PaulJane, PaulabcJane, PAULabcjaneDEF, etc</li><li><b>A*B*C</b> will find abc, ABC, axxxbxxxcxxx, abxxxxcxxxx, etc</li></ul></li><li>_ (underscore) is used with Like to indicate any single character, eg<ul><li><b>_Paul</b> will find: aPaul, xPaul, 1Paul, aPaulbcd, aPaul and Jane, etc. Note it will not find Paul or Paulbcd.</li><li><b>_a_</b> will find: xax, xaxxx, xax bcde, 1azzz www rrr, etc</li><li><b>a__bc_d</b> will find axxbccxd, axxbcxdeeee fff ggg, a12bc defg, a Â bc d fegfhxx fd, etc</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><p>Following is a table with comprehensive filter options.</p><h2>Filter Operators</h2><table border="1" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" style="text-align: left;"><thead><tr><th scope="col"><strong>Operator</strong></th><th scope="col"><strong>Notes</strong></th><th scope="col"><strong>Example 1</strong></th><th scope="col"><strong>Example 2</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>&amp;</td><td>And-operator<br/>Used to specify more than one criteria that must apply.Â </td><td>&gt;Paul&amp;&lt;=U</td><td>&lt;&gt;empty&amp;&lt;P</td></tr><tr><td>~$delimdb~</td><td>Or-operator<br/>Used to specify that either one of many criterias must apply.</td><td>&gt;P~$delimdb~&lt;B</td><td>null~$delimdb~empty</td></tr><tr><td>&gt;</td><td>Greater than</td><td>&gt;J</td><td>&gt;234</td></tr><tr><td>&gt;=</td><td>Greater than or equal</td><td>&gt;=Paul</td><td>&gt;=-945</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;</td><td>Smaller than</td><td>&lt;Q</td><td>&lt;1</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;=</td><td>Smaller than equal</td><td>&lt;=w</td><td>&lt;=75</td></tr><tr><td>=</td><td>Equal to</td><td>=Paul</td><td>=54</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;&gt;</td><td>Not equal to</td><td>&lt;&gt;Paul</td><td>&lt;&gt;123</td></tr><tr><td>!=</td><td>Not equal to (same as &lt;&gt;)</td><td>!=Paul</td><td>!=123</td></tr><tr><td>like</td><td>Like<br/>See &#34;Using Like&#34; in Notes above for more info</td><td>like Paul</td><td>like 54</td></tr><tr><td>null</td><td>Whole field equals to NULL (no value), but text fields can be empty (see below).<br/>In text fields NULL means never given a value,<br/>as opposed to had a value which was removed by a user (empty) but beware, depending on<br/>the configuration of default values and custom code that may set values to NULL,<br/>it may not be the case. In Sql it uses IS NULL.</td><td>null</td><td>NULL</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;&gt;null</td><td>Field value is not NULL (but can text fields can be empty - see below). In Sql it uses IS NOT NULL.</td><td>&lt;&gt;null</td><td>&lt;&gt;NULL</td></tr><tr><td>empty</td><td><p>Whole field is empty (and not null). In Sql it uses =\'\'. Applicable to text fields only.</p></td><td>empty</td><td>EMPTY</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;&gt;empty</td><td>Whole fied is not empty and not NULL.Â In Sql it uses &lt;&gt;\'\'. Applicable to text fields only.</td><td>&lt;&gt;empty</td><td>&lt;&gt;EMPTY</td></tr><tr><td>&lt;&gt;like</td><td>The opposite of like. It is used to exclude records that are like a certain expression. See &#34;Using Like&#34; in Notes above for more info</td><td>&lt;&gt;like *aa</td><td>&lt;&gt;LIKE a__b*</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Â </p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc224-dib'),
    (225, 'dibGrid - Table', 2, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3>Table Model</h3><p><b>Configuration</b></p><p>Use the Designer to set the container\'s <i>model</i> field on Pg1 to \'table\' and select a table in the Table dropdown. Save the record, and ensure that the relevant permgroup\'s permission files are deleted (/runtime/permFiles) as well as any CRUD class that was created for this container.</p><p><!--StartFragment--><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">From Component Tree, drag the <i>contentFor </i>component to the Item Tree, placing it anywhere you require the grid\'s columns to be positioned. Ie you can specify any design that incorporates various nested components, as long as (only one) <i>contentFor </i>component is placed somewhere within. Rename the <i>contentFor </i>component to \'columns\'.</span><br/><br/>The Component Tree\'s Field List in the Designer will display all fields in the selected table, as well as fields from parent tables linked via foreign keys. Drag-and-drop fields under the <i>contentFor</i>(columns) component. Note, fields from the Parent Field list can also be used, though parent fields that themselves are foreign keys are not supported.</p><p>All fields in the item table are applicable, the main ones being:</p><ul><li>caption - specify the column heading</li><li>pef_field_id Â - specify the table field</li><li>pef_component _id - specify the component type to use (must correspond with the data type of the field).</li></ul><p>When the client issues the first CRUD request for this container (eg /peff/Crud/read/dibDatabaseGrid?page=1&amp;start=0&amp;limit=10), Dropinbase will create the relevant PHP class. The code will contain only fields that were included, and that the current permgroup has rights to.Â <font face="inherit">Therefore, </font><u>if any changes are made to fields in future</u><font face="inherit">, ensure that the container\'s CRUD class is deleted. By default the Designer attempts to automatically delete the CRUD class when </font>necessary<font face="inherit">.</font></p><h3><font face="inherit">Submission Data</font></h3><p><font face="inherit">By default, all field values of items with aliases, of the record that last had the focus </font><b>and is open forÂ </b><b>editing</b><font face="inherit">Â are submitted under submitItemAlias.Â </font></p><p>Use the submitCheckedItems config to submit the primary key values of selected records.</p><p><font face="inherit">Use the submitLastRecord config to submit the primary key values of the last selected record.</font></p><p><font face="inherit">If buttons are included as part of the rows, any value in the row where a button is clicked can be passed to the server by using the following syntax in the button\'s URL:</font></p><p><font face="inherit"><i>/dropins/dibExamples/Events/btnHot_click<b>/{{row.id}}/{{row.name}}Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â -Â </b></i></font>Note,Â <b>id</b> and <b>name</b> need not have aliases.</p><p></p><h3>Custom Field Data</h3><p>Dropinbase generates a SQL statement that is stored in the container\'s PHP class which is used for read requests. The FROM-clause of the SQL statement will contain the main table (which is not aliased), and any parent tables that are referenced by foreign keys in the main table. The parent tables are aliased, eg staff1001. These aliases can be viewed either in the PHP, or on the Designer under the container\'s Configuration-tab (View SQL-tick). If you know the alias, you can create any custom SQL expression to specify a column\'s data, eg <b>CONCAT(staff1001.first_name, \'-\', company.code)</b>.</p><p>Store the SQL expression in the Item\'s <i>expression</i> field, and set the <i>expression_type</i> field to <i>sql insert.</i></p><p>Note, fields from parent tables are a special case. If the expression is merely of the form <b>tableAlias.parentFieldName</b>, eg staff1001.first_name, and the pef_field_id references the first_name in the staff table in this case, then the field is fully editable; otherwise it will be read-only. Using drag-and-drop from the Field List in the Designer, will automatically configure parent fields correctly for you.</p><h3>Include Other Tables\' Fields</h3><p>Use the extra_table_join field in pef_container to extend the FROM clause to other tables.Â </p><p>The contents of this field must start with LEFT JOIN, and to avoid conflicts table names must have unique aliases, egÂ </p><p>LEFT JOIN pef_login lg ON staff1001.pef_login_id = lg.id</p><p>The above will allow you to add eg <b>lg.username</b> as an expression for another column in the grid (see Custom Field Data above).</p><h3>Include Other Components<br/></h3><p>Columns can contain components such as <i>comment </i>and <i>layoutColumn </i>(see eg ~nav(dibexContainerDropins, Container Dropin Examples)~). Certain components will break the layout and need some coding adjustments before they can be used.</p><p><br/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc225-dib'),
    (227, 'Updating Dropinbase', 105, 110, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>\r\nDropinbase is updated in three steps:\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>1. Update the core framework</h2>\r\n<p>This step depends on <u>how</u> the Dropinbase core framework was installed. \r\n<br>Open a Terminal window, and run the <u>relevant</u> commands:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><b>With Docker:</b></li>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Ensure the Docker Desktop is running\r\n        <li><code>cd /www/myProject</code>\r\n        <li><code>npm run docker:rebuild</code>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <li><b>With Composer:</b></li>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><code>cd /www/myProject</code>\r\n        <li><code>composer update</code>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <li><b>With Git:</b></li>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li><code>cd /www/myProject/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase</code>\r\n        <li><code>git pull</code>\r\n    </ul>\r\n </ul>\r\n \r\n<h2>2. Run any oustanding Migration Scripts on your database(s)</h2>\r\n<p>Certain releases require changes to the dropinbase tables. \r\n<br>NOTE, if you have moved the Login tables (eg. pef_login, pef_perm_group, etc) to another database then run the appropriate SQL statements against the correct database.\r\n</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Open the <b>pef_setting</b> table in your dropinbase database</li>\r\n    <li>View your current Build No. value where name = <b>dibDatabaseVersion</b></li>\r\n    <li>Open the <b>/www/myProject/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/Migration Scripts.txt</b> file</li>\r\n    <li>Scroll down to the section for the next Build No (Build No. + 1)</li>\r\n    <li>Run all SQL commands (against the correct database) from here onwards until the end of the file</li>\r\n    <li>Update the <b>dibDatabaseVersion</b> value in the <b>pef_setting</b> table to the last value in the file</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>3. Apply any required PHP changes</h2>\r\n<p>Certain releases require changes to your custom PHP. \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>View any comments related to the outstanding Builds in the <b>/www/myProject/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/Migration Scripts.txt</b> file</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc227-dib'),
    (230, 'Deploying Applications', 326, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Deploying a Dropinbase application to another machine is as simple as reproducing the environment and copying the files and databases across.</p>\n<h3>Step 1 - Generate Cache, Crud and Permission Files</h3>\n<p><strong>Are containers in your application linked to the correct Module Dropins?</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Module Dropins group containers together for code generation and distribution. A good choice is to link containers that load within the same base container to the same Module Dropin.&nbsp;<br>It is normally best to have only one or a few Module Dropins linked to containers, since it avoids duplicating certain steps below for each dropin.</li>\n<li>To create a new Module Dropin, create the a record in&nbsp;<em>pef_dropin </em>where the&nbsp;<em>dropin_type</em> field is \'module\', and <em>show_in_designer </em>= 1 and <em>clear_code </em>= 1.&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Have you linked containers to the necessary permission groups yet?</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>By default, all new containers are added to the permission group of the admin user that created them.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Create one or more ~nav(dibPermGroupGrid, Permission Groups)~ and link the necessary containers to each. Choose a name for each Permission Group that reflects the role of the users that belong to it. Note, users can be linked to multilple Permission Groups.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Is at least one user linked to each combination of Permission Groups that will exist?</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The system generates dibCode files for each combination of Permission Groups that users belong to. This combination is called a ~navdocs(Permgroups, docs, Permgroup)~<em>. </em>If a certain user belongs to Permission Groups 1, 3, and 5, then their permgroup will be <strong>x1x3x5x </strong>which will be stored in their login record in the <em>perm_group</em> field.</li>\n<li>When generating files, the system actually logs itself in as one of the existing users of each permgroup and then creates the files as that user. The names of the files that are generated will contain the name of the permgroup.</li>\n<li>Use the ~nav(dibLoginForm?record=first)~ to create users and link them to Permission Groups.</li>\n<li>Note, admin/developer users should all belong to the <strong>x1x&nbsp;</strong>~navdocs(Permgroups, docs, Permgroup)~. Ie. they must only be linked to the <strong>System Admin </strong>permission group, and no other permission groups, else they will not be able to open the Designer pages.&nbsp;<br>End-users should not be linked to the <strong>System Admin</strong> permission group. If they should be able to make design changes or alter permissions, either create developer accounts for them, or duplicate the dibLoginGrid etc. containers and assign ports and permissions as needed to the new containers.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Generate application files</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>For more information about this topic see ~navdocs(Generating Files)~.</em></li>\n<li>Inform your team not to make any changes until deployment is complete, or ~navdocs(Enable Maintenance Mode)~ and allow only your IP (remember to disable MM afterwards).</li>\n<li>Open the ~nav(dibRelease)~ container and select the combination of Module Dropins and permgroups that you wish to generate files for.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Select all the following ticks: <strong>Actions</strong>, <strong>Components</strong>, <strong>CRUD/PHP</strong>, <strong>UI/Cache</strong>.</li>\n<li>The <strong>Max Concurrent Threads</strong>-field is set to 4 by default. You can increase this value dependant on the count of CPU cores of the machine generating the code, although a count &gt; 6 may lead to concurrency issues and the queued status messages overflowing the buffer limit of 50.</li>\n<li>Click the Generate button. The system will display progress messages while it is busy generating files for each permgroup. CRUD files are generated synchroneously, while the generation of UI/cache files make use of an asynchronous thread for each module dropin, container type and permgroup combination.</li>\n<li>Wait until all threads are completed, or until there is no activity for more than 2 minutes.\n<ul>\n<li>If any errors occured, they will be logged in the Dropinbase error log.</li>\n<li>Note, code for each combination of module dropin, container type and permgroup is compiled together in a batch by Angular. If any container within this batch has an error, the whole batch fails.</li>\n<li>Finding the container that caused the problem could be difficult. Start by investigating the error reported in the error log and look for ci-numbers (item id values) or container names. The Designer\'s item tree can be searched for an item id value. If the error gives no indications, then use the <em>Additional SQL Criteria</em>-field to isolate the problematic container. Eg specify <code>c.name &lt; \'N\'</code> and click the Generate button again. If the problem persists then use <code>c.name &lt; \'H\'</code> etc. to narrow the search for the container with the problem.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Remove redundant containers</strong></p>\n<p>Any non-essential containers that are available to non-developer users should be secured by removing these permissions, or deleting them if they are redundant.</p>\n<p>You could go as far as removing all admin permissions to all containers, in addition to removing the design records of example and admin containers. <br>Note, while these precautions limit what hackers may attempt, if they can hack into admin functions, then they will be able to hack into any others as well.<br><br>Note, the admin and example containers can (optionally) function without their design records. See ~navdocs(Remove Unneeded Design Records)~ for more info.</p>\n<h3>Step 2 - Install Dropinbase on Production Server</h3>\n<p>Since we want to duplicate our existing setup, follow the steps under Manual Setup on ~navdocs(Installation Steps)~ with the following exceptions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Instead of pulling the files from Github, copy the /projectFolder with all files from your staging/development machine to the production server\'s www folder.\n<ul>\n<li>More experienced users can pull the files from a repository.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Delete the /runtime folder.</li>\n<li>Instead of installing a fresh dropinbase database, make a copy of your development dropinbase database and install it on the production server.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Ensure the<strong> .htaccess</strong> file is in the root folder (it may be hidden by the operating system).</li>\n<li>Review the ~navdocs(Security, docs, security checklist)~.</li>\n<li>Ensure folder permissions are set. Follow the special instructions for <strong>production server</strong> under ~navdocs(File System Settings)~.</li>\n<!--StartFragment-->\n<li>Login with the same user credentials.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Step 3 - Production Settings in DibTmpl.php</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>âOpen the /<strong>projectFolder/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> file on the production server.</li>\n<li>Set $ENVIRONMENT to \'production\' which will ensure any generated JavaScript is compressed and sensitive admin functions are blocked.</li>\n<li>Set $CODEUSE to to 3 which expects all generated code to be in place. You must ensure all required code exists to prevent any errors. A setting of 3 gives a slight performance increase since no file checking is done, but be warned that fatal errors will result if files do not exist.\n<ul>\n<li>An alternative is 2, which will generate the code if it does not exist. This setting requires write permissions on the necessary folders as discussed in ~navdocs(File System Settings)~ which is less secure.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Review the ~navdocs(Security, docs, security checklist)~ for security related settings like DEBUG_LEVEL variables.</li>\n<li>Save the file, and then delete the <strong>/projectFolder/configs/Dib.php</strong> file so that it can be regenerated based on the <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> file.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Step 4 - Test and Make Live</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>âBefore removing Maintenance Mode, run some spot-checks on critical code and areas that have been recently updated.</li>\n<li>Add comments around the Maintenance Mode array in Dib.php and save it.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc230-dib'),
    (231, 'Support and Help', NULL, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<ul>\n<li>Extensive live examples and code, eg ~nav(dibexOverview)~.</li>\n<li>Use the <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/helpButton.png" alt="">-button in the Designer for contextual help with fields.</li>\n<li>Use the various wizzard buttons in the Designer to add attributes, container and item settings, or to set configs.</li>\n<li>Documentation (~nav(dibDocs)~).</li>\n<li>Community Forum - visit <a href="https://www.dropinbase.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.dropinbase.com.</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Official support and development&nbsp;</h3>\n<p>Visit <a href="https://www.dropinbase.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.dropinbase.com</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc231-dib'),
    (232, 'Loading Dropin Classes', 39, 90, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Whenever a client request targets a controller function from a certain dropin, the classes within the /components subfolder of that dropin become available to the system\'s auto-loader. These classes can therefore be referenced without requiring them.Â </p><p>Eg if the request is /dropins/myDropin/myController/myFunction/1/2?containerName=myGrid</p><p>Then the myFunction function in the myController.php class will be called. The first two parameters (if present) of the myFunction function will be assigned the string values \'1\' and \'2\' respectively, and the containerName parameter (if present), it will be assigned the value of \'myGrid\'.</p><p>Any PHP class within the /dropins/myDropin/components can then be instantiated as follows:</p><pre><p>// Note the auto-loader will use require_once to load the /dropins/myDropin/components/MyClass.php file automatically.</p><p>$class = New MyClass();</p><p>$class-&gt;myClassFunction(...);</p></pre><p><br/></p><p>Since a class within the /projectFolder/dropins folders overrides a class with the same path (/DROPINNAME/CLASSNAME) in the /dropinbase/dropins folder, the following functions are made available to easily instantiate and optionally require any other PHP classes. Note, the DibApp::load function is also used at times to resolve only the physical path to the class, without instantiating it.</p><h3>DibApp::load</h3><p>/**<br/>Â Â Â Â * Searches for a file named $fileName, first in the developer and then in the system dropin folders<br/>Â Â Â Â * If found the physical path is returned.<br/>Â Â Â Â * <br/>Â Â Â Â * @param string $dropinName name of Dropin folder. If a child dropin, then use parentName/name<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param string $fileName name of file (must include file extension), eg \'MyClass.php\'<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param string $subfolder subfolder(s) - must exclude trailing /, eg. \'components/actions\'<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param string $require whether to use require_once to load a php file (default is TRUE and non php files are excluded)<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param boolean $dontReportError in case of not finding file, whether only to return array(\'error\', $errMsg), or log error and return false.<br/>Â Â Â Â * @return mixed path to file on success, see $dontReportError above for return value on failure<br/>Â Â Â Â */Â Â Â Â <br/>Â Â Â Â public static function load($dropinName, $fileName, $subfolder=\'\', $require=TRUE, $dontReportError=FALSE)Â </p><p><b>Example:</b></p><pre><p>DibApp::load(\'myFirstDropin\', \'FirstClass.php\', \'components\');</p><p>$result = FirstClass::helloWorld(\'Peter\');</p><p>$filePath = DibApp::load(\'myOtherDropin\', \'OtherClass.php\', \'components/reports\', FALSE);</p></pre><h3><br/>DibApp::loadPath</h3><p>/**<br/>Â Â Â Â * Resolves physical path to file referenced by $dibUri (must use and start with / as separator). <br/>Â Â Â Â * If $dibUri starts with \'/dropins/\' then first look in /projectFolder/dropins, if not found try /dropinbase/dropins<br/>Â Â Â Â *    Else use system root as base<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param string $dibUri eg /dropins/testDropin/myClass or /dropins/setSencha/dibAdmin/FindReplaceFindList/selectList<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param boolean $require whether require_once must be used<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param boolean $functionNameRequired whether functionName should be in $dibUri (results in error if TRUE and not in $dibUri)<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param string $fileExtension file extension to use (default = \'.php\')<br/>Â Â Â Â * @param boolean $inComponents whether /dropins uri\'s must resolve to a class in the components folder (else look in the specified dropin subfolder (nested allowed))<br/>Â Â Â Â * @return array If a function name is present: array(filePath, className, functionName). Else array(filePath, className).  array(\'error\', $errMsg) on error<br/>Â Â Â Â */<br/>Â Â Â Â public static function loadPath($dibUri, $require=TRUE, $functionNameRequired=FALSE, $fileExtension=\'.php\', $inComponents=TRUE)Â <br/></p><p><b>Example:</b></p><pre><p>// Instantiate the same class as in the DibApp::load example above</p><p>DibApp::loadPath(\'/dropins/myFirstDropin/FirstClass\');</p><p>$result = FirstClass::helloWorld(\'Peter\');</p><p>list($filePath, $className, $functionName) = DibApp::loadPath(\'/dropins/myOtherDropin/components/reports/OtherClass\', FALSE, FALSE, \'.php\', FALSE);</p></pre><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc232-dib'),
    (233, 'Naming and URL Conventions', 28, 35, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3>Containers and Items</h3>\n<p>Due to restrictions in Angular, <strong>container names</strong> must adhere to the following rules:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lower camel case (eg myFirstContainer or myContainer or my).&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Only alpha-numeric characters allowed (underscore (_) and spaces are not allowed). Note, the first character must be alphabetical (a-z) and lower case.</li>\n<li>Using \'Form\' and \'Grid\' as suffix, is optional but helpful.</li>\n<li>Examples: dibItemForm, mySubContainerGrid</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Item names</strong> are a bit more relaxed</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Only alpha-numeric and underscore (_) characters allowed. Spaces are not allowed.</li>\n<li>Prefixes such as \'btn\', \'fs\' and \'row\' helps to read layouts.</li>\n<li>Examples: my_item, myItem, btnExecuteFast</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Files, Folders and Functions</h3>\n<p><strong><em>Note: This section applies mostly to programmers.</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Dropins</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Only alpha-numeric and underscore (_) charcters allowed. Spaces are not allowed.</li>\n<li>Must be unique within its parent folder, and the folder name must be identical to the name in the <em>pef_dropin </em>table.</li>\n<li>Strongly suggested: use lower camel case.</li>\n<li>If the dropin contains child dropins, the name must be prefixed with \'set\'.</li>\n<li>Examples: dibForm, ktgGridList</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>PHP Controller Classes</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>âAlpha-numeric and no spaces.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Must end in \'Controller.php\'.</li>\n<li>The name of the class inside the file must be identical to the file name (without the \'.php\' extension).</li>\n<li>Strongly suggested: capitalize individual words, eg MyController.php.</li>\n<li>Examples: ContactController.php, MyControllerController.php</li>\n<li>Note: the URI\'s used to reference the controller functions excludes the \'Controller\' part, <br>eg <strong>/dropins/myDropin/Contact/doSomething</strong> instead of <strong>/dropins/myDropin/ContactController/doSomething</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Angular / HTML Components</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Alpha-numeric and no spaces.</li>\n<li>Must be unique within the selected Material Dropin. The file name must use the .et.html file extension and the name (without the extension) must be identical to the name in the <em>pef_component</em> table.</li>\n<li>Strongly suggested: use lower camel case.</li>\n<li>Using prefixes such as \'btn\' is optional but helpful</li>\n<li>Examples: myFirstComponent.et.html, myComponent.et.html, my.et.html</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Other PHP Classes and Files</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>âAlpha-numeric and no spaces.</li>\n<li>The name of the class inside the file must be identical to the file name (without the \'.php\' extension).</li>\n<li>Strongly suggested: capitalize individual words, eg MyContacts.php</li>\n<li>Examples: Contact.php, MyFirstClass.php</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Other Folders</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>âAlpha-numeric and no spaces.</li>\n<li>Strongly suggest using lower camel case.</li>\n<li>Examples: mail, myMail, myFirstMail</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>PHP Functions and Variables</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>âAlpha-numeric and no spaces.</li>\n<li>Strongly suggest using lower camel case.</li>\n<li>Function name examples: send, sendMail, sendFirstMail</li>\n<li>Variable name examples: $mail, $myMail, $myFirstMail</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>NOTE</strong></p>\n<p>Avoiding plural forms in naming objects solves the problem of remembering if the plural form was used or not.</p>\n<h3>URL\'s</h3>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Type</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Form</strong></td>\n<td><strong>Notes</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Navigation</td>\n<td>/nav/CONTAINERNAME</td>\n<td>Reloads the whole application and opens the CONTAINERNAME container. <br>If the user\'s permgroup is restricted or the container name is spelled incorrectly (case-sensitive), <br>the user will be notified and then redirected to the login page (the user will not be logged out though).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dropin Controller Function</td>\n<td>/dropins/DROPINNAME/CONTROLLERNAME/FUNCTIONNAME<br>Note: DROPINAME can be a single name, or include a parent dropin name eg (setNgxMaterial/form).</td>\n<td>Calls a PHP controller function in a dropin to process the request. See ~navdocs(Item Events)~ and ~navdocs(Container Events)~ for more info.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>System Controller Function</td>\n<td>/peff/CONTROLLERNAME/FUNCTIONNAME</td>\n<td>Calls a PHP controller function in the /dropinbase/controllers folder to process the request.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>General Static File</td>\n<td>/files/xxx/yyy/FILENAME.EXT</td>\n<td>Returns the file named FILENAME.EXT stored in the /projectFolder/files/ folder (or any nested child folder as indicated by xxx/yyy). <br><strong>NOTE:</strong> The file\'s extension and folder must be listed in the /configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php file.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Dropin Static File</td>\n<td>/files/dropins/DROPINNAME/xxx/yyy/FILENAME.EXT<br>Note: DROPINAME can be a single name, or include a parent dropin name eg (setNgxMaterial/form).</td>\n<td>Returns the file named FILENAME.EXT stored in the /projectFolder/dropins/DROPINNAME/ folder (or any nested child folder as indicated by xxx/yyy). <br><strong>NOTE:</strong> The file\'s extension and folder must be listed in the /configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php file.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>â</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc233-dib'),
