    (235, 'Dropinbase Folder Structure', 28, 70, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The following folder structure assumes the default installation.</p>\n<p>The vendor and/or dropinbase folders can be moved to any location on a machine by using symbolic links or editing the index.php file. See ~navdocs(Multi-Tenant Setup)~ for more info.</p>\n<p><strong>/www</strong><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>/projectFolder</strong><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>/configs</strong> - stores all the configuration files. The <strong>DibTmpl.php</strong> file acts as a template for creating the main configuration file stored as <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong>.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="text-decoration: underline;">xxx.xxx</span> - see ~navdocs(System Configuration Files)~ for details about files.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>/dropins</strong> - the main folder to host your custom application code.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>/dibCustom</strong> - dropin that allows developers to add or customize features of certain Dropinbase core libraries eg Eleutheria.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>/main </strong>- default dropin for application development - if renamed, then rename in pef_dropin table as well.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>/files</strong> - place for images/icons/etc. and overrides to css. Files are loaded with urls starting with /files/files/. Note, only folders listed in /configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php can be loaded and are publicly available.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>/runtime</strong> - all files and folders here are automatically created when <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> or <b>/runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt</b>does not exist. Delete at any time to reset Dropinbase (see <strong>**3</strong> below).<strong><br></strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>/cache</strong> - some user cache files, most notably the index.html file\'s contents is cached here after merging with <em>pef_setting</em>. Delete it if for eg. beforeBodyJs setting is changed.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>/logs</strong> - stores error en debugging logs. If Dropinbase cannot write to the pef_error_log table for any reason, errors will be logged here regardless of settings in Dib.php.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>/tmp</strong> - files generated at runtime for temporary operations - can be cleared at any time.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="text-decoration: underline;">FilesCache.php</span> - workaround for case-sensitive file systems and mismatching URL\'s (note, this feature will be deprecated soon).<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>/vendor</strong> - Composer modules.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>/composer</strong> - created and maintained by Composer.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>/dropinbase</strong> - Dropinbase vendor folder.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>/dropinbase</strong> - Dropinbase core API/framework.<br><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">.htaccess </span>- Apache redirect settings (see<strong> **1</strong> below).<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="text-decoration: underline;">composer.json</span> - Composer file indentifying project dependencies to load. Alter to add your own 3d party libraries.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="text-decoration: underline;">files.php</span> - Redirect to core /files.php. Used to process requests that require public static files, eg images and certain JavaScript libraries. Requests all start with /files/.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="text-decoration: underline;">index.php</span> - Redirect to core /index.php. Bootstraps the core framework and handles all other requests (see&nbsp;<strong>**2 </strong>below).<br><strong>Notes:</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>**1 - .htaccess</strong> (Apache only) redirects all requests that start with /files (eg <strong>http://localhost/files/dropins/images/a.png</strong>) to the <strong>files.php</strong> file, and all other requests to <strong>index.php</strong> (the core framework).\n<br>For improved security, move the rules in the .htaccess file to the website\'s Virtual Host entry.\n</p>\n\n<p><strong>**2 -&nbsp;</strong>after the initial setup, the&nbsp;<strong>index.php</strong> file directs all requests to <strong>installer.php</strong>. The installer can update this file to run the core framework instead (or it can be changed manually quite easily).</p>\n<p><strong>**3</strong> - ~navdocs(Reset Dropinbase)~ - ensures core configurations for the framework are in place.</p>\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc235-dib'),
    (236, 'Excluding Items', 28, 60, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Items can be excluded from user-interfaces using the following methods:&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Angular Directives (dynamic exclusion with criteria)</h3>\n<p>Dynamically hide/show items (which can have nested items) based on conditions using an Angular expression.</p>\n<p>See the examples under<strong> </strong>~nav(Dropinbase Services and Angular Directives)~&nbsp;and use the ~nav(dibDesigner)~ to study the expressions used in the Item Details -&gt; <em>Attributes</em>&nbsp;field.</p>\n<p>More information available here:</p>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://angular.io/guide/structural-directives" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://angular.io/guide/structural-directives</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>User Interface (static exclusion)</h3>\n<p>When the user-interface for a container is generated, a SQL statement is used (recursively) to fetch the items.&nbsp;The WHERE clause is used to exclude the following items:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>where <em>pef_item.ui_include</em>&nbsp;= 1â</li>\n<li>where the Port field references a restricted container (ie, the current&nbsp;<strong>permgroup </strong>does not have any rights on the container). This is very useful - it causes for eg. menu items and buttons not to be generated for users that don\'t have the permissions to the referenced containers.</li>\n<li>restricted by item permissions (the user must have at least <strong>create </strong>or <strong>read </strong>permissions (you can\'t update what you can\'t read)). See ~navdocs(Permissions Overview)~ - Item Level Permissions for details.</li>\n<li>linked to components restricted by the <em>pef_component.permissions</em> field (eg delete buttons where the current permgroup lacks delete permissions). See ~navdocs(Tables Reference, pef_component, pef_component)~ for details.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc236-dib'),
    (237, 'Essential Concepts', 324, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h4 style="text-align: center;">So you don\'t know what you don\'t know, and everything is new :)Â </h4><h4 style="text-align: center;">We\'re aware of that, and will try our best to facilitate the learning process! Let us know how we\'re doing.</h4><h4 style="text-align: center;">The following discussion introduces the basic and essential concepts needed to customize applications in Dropinbase.</h4><h4 style="text-align: center;">You should work through it AFTER creating your first application (see ~navdocs(Building and Rebuilding Apps)~).</h4><h4 style="text-align: center;">For any further queries, first refer to the HowTo articles in Docs or use the F1-key in the Designer.<br/></h4><h4 style="text-align: center;">You should soon be on your way to super-hero status!</h4><hr/><ol><li>Given connection strings to one or more databases, the system can read and store an analysis of the structure and data of the tables and their relationships.<br/>It then has the ability to build application pages and menus etc based on this information..<br/><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/introBasic.png"/><br/></li><li>The complete design of your application is stored in the Dropinbase database tables. The data is merged with templates (on the fly) to produce server-side and user-interface code required.~htmlitem(showHide, code, View more)~<ul><li>For example, info about tables and fields is stored in <i>pef_table </i>and <i>pef_field</i>, info about pages (containers) and items on containers is stored in <i>pef_container </i>and <i>pef_item </i>etc.Â </li><li>The templates for grid user-interfaces is stored in /dropinbase/dropins/setNgMaterial/dibGrid/templates/js while the templates for server-side code performing data (CRUD) actions is in /dropinbase/dropins/setData/templates/crud.</li><li>Note, all the administration pages of Dropinbase, like this very Documentation page, was built using Dropinbase. The associated design records is distributed with Dropinbase as examples to learn from and copy or modify.</li><li>When the CACHEUSE property in /configs/Dib.php (the main configuration file) is set to 0, the required user-interface code is regenerated with every request while server-side code is automatically regenerated only when affected. This is useful while designing applications since changes are made all the time. Fortunately code generation happens very quickly.</li><li>On production servers performance can be optimized by treating the generated code as static (nothing is regenerated) by setting CACHEUSE to 2 or 3 (see comments in Dib.php for details).</li></ul>~htmlitem(divEnd)~</li><li>Different types of pages (named <b>containers</b> in Dropinbase) are available, eg grids, forms, trees, html pages, etc.</li><li>Certain container types can be linked to various data source types (eg tables, SQL statements and custom PHP scripts). A form container can be linked to any database table, while a grid can be linked to either a table or SQL statement. The <i>dibContainer</i> container type is not linked to any data source - it is useful when building pages that should not fetch and display data from the server.</li><li>Each container has items, eg buttons, layout components, fields or images etc.</li><li>Each item has at least a name (eg. <i>rowToolbar </i>or <i>btnSave</i>) which must be unique per container, and a component type (eg. <i>layoutRow </i>or <i>mdButton </i>respectively). The component type determines an item\'s features and behavior. See the image below for examples of how layoutRow and layoutFieldset were used to arrange their child (contained) items.</li><li>The Dropinbase Designer presents these items in a tree structure from where it is easy to modify the container\'s design, by using drag-and-drop, cut-copy-paste, and changing/adding/deleting items and their properties.<br/><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/introItems.png"/><br/></li><li>The initial design of containers as generated by the system is based on the design of template containers. The design of these template containers can be modified the same way any other container is modified, and new template containers can be created. See ~navdocs(Generating Containers using Design Templates)~ for more info.<br/></li><li>An application consists of containers that are nested in one another. The first container that is loaded is named the <b>base container</b>. It normally contains the application logo, menu, logout buttons etc, and provides a basic structure for the application. Any other container that is loaded from eg a button/menu is attached to the base container, or another previously loaded container.<br/><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/introNestedContainers.png"/><br/></li><li>To navigate to the &#34;live&#34; version of a container use <b>http://yourdomain/nav/CONTAINERNAME</b> (eg http://myApp.dib/nav/clients). To open the design of the container, use the blueÂ <b>Design Menu</b>Â gear button at the bottom-left of the view (see image above). Note, the <b>base containerÂ </b>is named after your database by default.<br/></li><li>Any container can be nested in another, either via <b>subcontainer components</b>,<b>Â </b>or <b>ports</b>.</li><li>Containers nested via subcontainers are loaded along with their parent containers. A parent container that has many &#34;child&#34; containers in subcontainer components will therefore take relatively long to fully load.</li><li>Containers targeted by ports are loaded dynamically when the user clicks on eg a tab, button or menu-item on the main container. The browser URL can optionally change when a container is opened via a port. The loading of the other containers targeted by ports is therefore delayed until (or if ever) needed, and the main container will load much quicker.</li><li>A port record specifies the tab or other layout component item that a container is attached to when loaded. </li><li>A container can have multiple port records, or in other words, a container can be loaded/reused in multiple places. Each port record has a port alias field which is a name/label used to unique identify each port record. So why the name port? A boat can dock at various ports, and a gadget can dock in various usb-ports of your laptop. <i>The difference though with Dropinbase is that the same container can dock in various ports at the same time :)</i>.</li><li>The application illustrated above could be designed in many different ways. For eg, the dashboard could be loaded via a port (same as Products and Clients) or a subcontainer. Alternatively the dashboard icons could be part of the base container\'s design. There are no hard &#34;rules&#34; - the best design often depends on what is the most maintainable, given the set of features and permissions required.</li><li>Filters can be used to limit the records returned in containers and dropdowns, and to facilitate typical master-child relationships between them and the value(s) of other item(s).<br/><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/introFilters.png"/><br/>~htmlitem(showHide, filters, View more)~<ul><li>Filters are implemented by specifying SQL criteria on dropdowns, subcontainer components, or directly on containers that must be filtered.</li><li>The SQL criteria can contain references to items on the user-interface that have aliases (their <i>Alias</i> field is checked).</li><li>In the above example, the name of the item linked to the <i>id</i> field is <b>project_pk</b> (we could name it anything as long as it is unique within the container). The <i>Alias</i> field is checked.</li><li>The SQL criteria (that references this value) used on the subcontainer hosting the grid is: <br/><b>staff_project.project_id = :submitItemAlias_parent_project_pk</b></li></ul>~htmlitem(divEnd)~</li><li>The example above also illustrates the ability to configure default values for fields (see red text).~htmlitem(showHide, defaults, View more)~<ul><li>Default values can be configured on either the user-interface (form-default) or server (crud-default).</li><li>Form-defaults can reference other items that have aliases (Alias-field is checked). In the example above a form-default of <b>=parent.project_pk</b> was used on the project dropdown in the grid.</li><li>Crud-defaults are values fetched from the server whenever a new record is opened for editing. Crud defaults are values the server is aware of, eg date/time and values in the Login record.</li><li>Both Form or Crud defaults can be used to specify constants like 56, -7 or apple, though Crud defaults will only work if the form/grid is based on a table.</li></ul>~htmlitem(divEnd)~</li><li>Dropdowns and tabs are often used to facilitate relationships with other tables. See the image below. Currently the &#34;fishing&#34; record is displayed from the project table. The project table has a &#34;foreign key&#34; field <i>client_idÂ </i>pointing to the <i>client </i>table. If you click on the associated field below (with caption &#34;Client&#34;) a dropdown list of clients will appear from which the user can select the relevant client for the project. The project table has another foreign key named &#34;project_leader_id&#34; referencing the staff table. This is also a dropdown, with caption &#34;Project Leader&#34;. Both dropdowns are configured with &#34;navigation buttons&#34; which can be used to navigate to the selected client or staff records.<br/><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/introDropdownsTabs.png"/><br/> </li><li>Containers, items and tables can also have custom events linked to them. ~htmlitem(showHide, events, View more)~<ul><li>Depending on the container type (eg dibForm, dibGrid, etc.) various <b>container events</b> can be configured on both the user-interface and server.</li><li>Whenever create, update or delete actions affect table data, <b>table events</b> can call server-side code to block the change, alter the data or perform some other action.</li><li>Events configured on items (eg click or change) and containers (eg reloadContainer or postLink) can call either client- (JavaScript) or server-side code.</li><li>Whenever server-side code is called, actions can be returned to the client for execution, which in turn can call server-side code again...</li><li>Calls to server-side code is always accompanied with values gathered from the current and parent containers. These values are posted to the server in a parameter named submissionData. To include a value in submissionData, set the Alias tick on the specific item. Values outside the current or parent container can also be included by setting configs (see ~navdocs(Submission Data)~ for more info).</li><li>By using Queues or NodeJs,  actions can be &#34;pulled&#34; or &#34;pushed&#34; to the client for asynchronous execution which is useful for long-running server-side code.<br/></li></ul>~htmlitem(divEnd)~</li><li>Containers must have permissions linked to them. Permissions are assigned to groups (roles). Logins (users) are linked to one or more groups. Permissions cannot be assigned directly to logins.<br/><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/introPerms.png"/><br/>~htmlitem(showHide, perms, View more)~<ul><li>The <b>system_public</b> Login record is created automatically if it does not exist. Any un-authenticated user assumes the rights of the groups that the <i>system_public </i>user is linked to. By default this user is not linked to any groups.</li><li>Use the Designer to configure permissions on containers, items and events.</li><li>In the example above:</li><ul><li><b>Managers</b> can create, read, update and delete all records in the <b>clientGrid</b> container.</li><li><b>Data Clerks</b> can read all records, but only update those where the <i>client_status</i> field of the underlying table has a value of \'active\'.</li><li><b>Clients</b> can read can read and update only their own record. Values of any fields added to the <i>pef_login</i> table are available as parameters in criteria. In this case it is assumed that a <i>client_id</i> field exists in pef_login.</li><li><b>Data Clerks</b> and <b>Clients</b> can not create or delete records.</li></ul><li>Note: a login (user) can be linked to more than one permission group.Â </li><li>Permissions on items and events are inherited from the container, but can be configured specifically.</li><li>Each permission group has an <i>id </i>value, for eg <i>System Administrators</i> is always 1, <i>Managers </i>may be 5 and <i>Data Clerks </i>may be 6 etc. The unique combinations of permission groups that users belong to form what is known as a &#34;<b>permgroup</b>&#34;. For eg, if user <i>paul </i>is linked to both the <i>Manager </i>and <i>Data Clerk</i> group, a permgroup named <b>x5x6x </b>will be created. This permgroup name is used by Dropinbase extensively to name for eg container designs or code facilitating CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) actions for this permgroup.</li><li>Dropinbase automatically assigns full permissions for the System Administrators group (x1x) when generating containers.</li><li>Permissions are stored in &#34;compiled&#34; format in the <i>pef_perm_active</i> and <i>pef_perm_field_active</i> tables, as well as in files in the <i>/runtime/permFiles</i> folder. Dropinbase attempts to recreate these records and files automatically whenever affected by permission or design changes. Certain actions may require forced regeneration by using the <b>Clear</b> menu on the Designer (top-right).</li><li>The active permissions for each permgroup are displayed on the Designer by clicking the Configuration -&gt; PermFiles link.</li></ul>~htmlitem(divEnd)~</li><li>Dropins facilitate the modular, share-plug-and-play concepts of Dropinbase. A dropin always has a folder containing files, and a record in the pef_dropin table. Dropins can contain only PHP code providing certain functionality (eg. dibExcel can read/write .xlsx files). Other dropins contain the generated HTML, Javascript and PHP code of containers, and the PHP code (added by programmers) behind their buttons etc. that make up a specific application.</li><li>By default, the generated server-side CRUD (PHP) code for containers is stored in /runtime/crud, while the generated user-interface-code (HTML and Javascript) is stored in /runtime/cache. As mentioned, the associated permgroup name is used to name these files. Since each permgroup may has specific rights related to fields they can see or update etc., the design of a specific container can vary per permgroup, and therefore each permgroup will have its own copy of a container\'s CRUD and user-interface files - the code therein will be specific to what is allowed.</li><li>Multiple containers can be linked to the same module Dropin in which case the related code is stored in the selected Dropinâs folders instead of the default (/runtime) folders.</li><li>Any PHP code that is linked to container or item events must be placed in dropin folders, although their containers need not be linked to dropins, or the same dropins.</li><li>The /configs/Dib.php file is the main configuration file and is automatically generated (if it does not exist) based on the /configs/DibTmpl.php file. The /configs folder contains other configuration files, eg Conn.php which specifies the database connection details, and Mail.php which specifies email configurations.</li><li>The Logs-tab (/nav/dibLog) is used to report any server-side errors.Â </li><li>Use your browserâs Developer Tools (press F12 in Chrome) to view client-side errors in the Console. Click on a particular request to view more info.</li></ol><p><b>NEXT STEP: work through the HowTo articles which contain many tips and tricks ...</b><br/></p><h3><br/></h3><h3>Main Tools used in Dropinbase</h3><p>~nav(dibConfigs, Connections &amp; Configs)~ â Configure database connection strings.</p><p>~nav(wizBuildApp, App Wizard)~ â Build new applications based on a selected database, and base container template.</p><p>~nav(dibDatabaseForm?record=last, Import Tables)~ â Import tables and build containers. Apply changes to the underlying tables to containers (add/remove fields etc).</p><p>~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ â Alter the design of your application (containers).</p><p>~nav(dibSqlGrid, SQL Queries)~ â Configure SQL statements as record sources for containers or dropdowns. Also bulk import SQL statements and create grids based on them.</p><p>~nav(dibLoginGroupGrid, Permissions)~ â Follow the links to configure permission groups, logins and permissions.</p><p>~nav(dibLog, Logs)~ â View the system error logs. The \'Print\'-tab is used by PHP developers to debug applications.</p><p><br/></p><h3>Where Else to Find Help</h3><p>The <b>HowTo </b>articlesÂ provide a very good introduction, and tips &amp; tricks, to building applications. Work through them in the order they are presented.</p><p>Watch the first <b>training video</b>. <i>Warning,</i> first play around a bit with the Designer to familiarize yourself, based on the info above. The video moves fast (and is already a bit outdated) but illustrates many essentials.</p><p>Work through the ~nav(dibDashboard,Tutorial Examples)~ available through the dashboard. Use the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ to view the configuration of examples provided.</p><p>The <b>F1-key</b> provides help for the current field of any of the Dropinbase forms/grids. </p><p>The official ~nav(dibDocs, Documentation)~ contains detailed explanations and reference guides.</p><p>Participate on the online <b>Community Forum</b>.</p><p>Make use of <b>Paid Support</b> by contacting us at info@dropinbase.com.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc237-dib'),
