    (239, 'How to create a grid based on a SQL statement', 238, 110, 0, 'eleutheria', '<ol><li>âOn the Dashboard, click on <b>SQL Queries</b>. The <i>dibSqlGrid </i>container will open displaying all the SQL queries stored in the system.</li><li>Click on the <b>CREATE FROM SQL</b> button.Â Â </li><ul><li>Alternatively you could also click one of the Add buttons and populate the fields yourself, but theÂ <i>dibCreateFromSql </i>container that opens does a lot of the work for you.</li></ul><li>Populate the fields:</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateSqlGrid.png"/><ul><li><b>Name:</b>Â Provide a unique name for the new SQL record. Only alpha-numeric characters and spaces are allowed.</li><li><b>Database:</b>Â Select the database that the SQL is executed against.</li><li><b>SQL:</b>Â Provide the full SQL statement. It must start with the word SELECT and contain at least a FROM clause.</li></ul><li>Note, if a grid is to be created based on this query, ensure that the query returns at least one record.</li><li>Click on the <b>Create Record</b> button.</li><ul><li>The <i>dibSqlGridÂ </i>container should open displaying the new record as the first record in the grid.</li></ul><ul><li>If any errors are reported, check your SQL and try again. Also use third-party tools such as <i>HeidiSql </i>to run your queries.</li></ul><li>Select the record and click the <b>CREATE GRID(S)</b> button.</li><ul><li>Note, if more than one record is selected then a grid will be created for each of them. There will be less options available though as to where the grid will be located.</li></ul><li>Populate the fields:</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateSqlGrid_Container.png"/><ol><li><b>Choose Action:</b>Â </li><ol><li><b>Option 1:</b> A port record will be created, linking the new grid to the selected <b>Item</b>. If you navigate to <b>/nav/myfirstqueryGrid</b> the grid will be loaded in the specified <b>Item </b>(the MainHolder tab of the dibdemo (base) container). You probably need to add a menu item too... This is the only option available when creating multiple grids, by selecting more than one SQL statement in dibSqlGrid.</li><li><b>Option 2:</b> This is the same as the first option, except that the selected Item (eg a tab) will be linked to the port record. If the user clicks the Item, the grid is loaded dynamically. Note, the Item must be &#34;clickable&#34; in order to trigger the loading, eg a tab.<br/></li><li><b>Option 3:</b> A subcontainer component will be created under the specified <b>Item</b> to host the new container. Note, any container hosted in a subcontainer is always loaded when the parent container (dibdemo) is loaded.Â </li></ol><li><b>Caption: </b>Choose a caption for the container.</li><li><b>Item: </b>If a subcontainer is involved (option 3) this refers to the parent Item of the new subcontainer. Otherwise it refers to the Port Item (ie, where the new grid will be attached to when loaded).</li><li><b>Create Grid:</b> This is required if the data source is a SQL query.</li><li><b>Name: </b>Provide a name for the new grid container.Â </li><li><b>Design:</b> Select the Design Template to use for the new grid container. Note, certain templates are specific to certain types of queries (eg UNION SELECT).</li><li><b>Add Menu Item:</b> Select this checkbox in case a menu item must be added to open the new grid. Note, if option 3 (subcontainer) is selected,Â  a port record will be created linked to the default Port Item specified in the database record.</li><li><b>Parent Menu Item:</b> Select the parent menu node of the new menu item. Any root or child node of any menu within Dropinbase is available as Parent Menu Item.</li></ol><li>Click <b>CREATE </b>to create the new grid(s), or <b>CANCEL </b>to exit.</li></ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc239-dib'),
    (240, 'How to switch between different base container templates', 238, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Switching a base container template provides a different basic layout for your application. The process takes only a few seconds.<span id="selectionBoundary_1556969937084_7378664669915636" class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span></p><p>If the base container of your application is based on one of the official base container templates (and you haven\'t changed the names of certain items eg MainHolder), you can switch your application to another.</p><ol><li>Open the ~nav(dibDatabaseGrid, Database Grid)~ and use the pencil icon to open your database record in the form.Â </li><li>Click the <b>CHANGE BASE CONTAINER</b> button.</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToChangeBaseContainer.png"/><br/><li>Choose a new template</li><ul><li>Descriptions will appear upon selection. Avoid choosing the active one :).</li></ul><li>Click the REPLACE BASE CONTAINER (or CANCEL) button.</li><ul><li>Dropinbase creates a new base container and then moves any menu items across to the new one.Â </li><li>It also updates any ports referencing the old base container.Â </li><li>Finally, it deletes the old base container and renames the new one with the old name.</li></ul><ol></ol><li>You can repeat this process with another base container template...</li></ol><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc240-dib'),
    (241, 'How to modify the application menu', 238, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><br/></p><ol><li>Open the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and select your base container (named after your database by default) in the dropdown.Â </li><li>Open the node named <b>menu</b> in the tree under the <b>Layout</b>-tab</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToModifyMenu_Tree.png"/><br/><li><b>Remove menu items:</b></li><ul><li>Hold down the Ctrl-key while clicking on the nodes you wish to delete.</li><li>Click <b>delete</b> on the Fab menu.</li><li>Confirm or cancel the operation.</li></ul><li><b>Change order of menu items:</b></li><ul><li>Use drag-and-drop to position the menu nodes under the menuItems node.</li><li>All nodes must remain child items of the <b>menuItems</b> node.</li></ul><li><b>Create menu categories:</b></li><ul><li>From the Components Tree, drag-and-drop a sidenavMenuNode component to the tree, making it a child of the menuItems node.Â </li><li>Click on the new component (it will be named <b>sidenavMenuNode</b> by default).</li><li>Use the Editor to change the <i>Name</i> to eg <b>mnStaff</b>, and the <i>Caption</i> to <b>Staff.</b></li><li>Use drag-and-drop to relocate mnstaff, mnstaffproject and mnstaffskill as child nodes under the new mnStaff component.</li><li>Alternatively, hold down the Ctrl-key while clicking on all three these nodes to select them (the Shift-key selects all between two nodes). Use the Cut and Paste commands to paste them to the mnStaff node.</li><li>Any amount of categories can be created, but menu categories can be only one level deep.</li></ul><ol></ol><li><b>Create a menu item that opens a specific container:</b></li><ul><li>Create another new sidenavMenuNode item as child of either menuItems or another sidenavMenuNode.</li><li>Use the Editor to change the <i>Name</i> and set the <i>Caption</i>.</li><li>Set the <i>Port</i> field to the desired port record of the container you wish to open.</li><li>Note you may first need to create the port record for this container (select the container in the Designer, click on Ports, and add a record).</li><li>You can also set the Port fields of buttons and tabs to make them open containers.</li></ul></ol><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc241-dib'),
    (242, 'How to change the display values of dropdowns', 238, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Overview Facts:</h5><ul><li>To specify a display expression, a dropdown can be linked to a table field and/or a SQL record.</li><br/><li>When linked to a <b>table field only </b>(the default), it is assumed that the selected field is also a foreign key that references a primary table.Â </li><ul><li>For eg, in the image below, the <i>client_id </i>field in the <i>client_contact </i>table references the <i>client </i>table.</li><li>The dropdown then obtains the display expression from the primary table\'s <i>display_expression </i>field. In our case the client table\'s <i>display_expression </i>field is set to <b>`name`</b>.</li><li>Dropdowns on dibContainer forms (ie forms not bound to tables or queries) can also be linked to foreign key fields to enable their associated lists.</li><li>Some rules apply:</li><ul><li>A single field (eg <b>`name`)</b> can be used, or any valid SQL expression that references only fields in the primary table (eg CONCAT(`name`, \' - \', `start_date`))</li><li>Do not prefix fields with the table name (eg. use <b>`name`</b> instead of <b>`client`.`name`</b>) and delimit fields with <b>`</b> (eg <b>`name`</b> instead of <b>name</b>). (The <b>`</b> character is used for identification purposes when Dropinbase automatically prefixes the fields with the particular aliases used in the generated CRUD classes).<br/></li><li><b>Warning: </b>If the field is not stored as a foreign key in Dropinbase, it will result in errors. If a foreign key has newly been configured in the underlying database, use the ~nav(dibDatabaseForm?record=last, Execute Tasks-&gt;Refresh Relationships)~ command to update Dropinbase, or add records for the foreign key in <i>Table Foreign Keys</i> and <i>Foreign Keys</i> (see main menu under <i>Tables &amp; Fields</i>).</li></ul></ul><br/><li>When linked to a <b>SQL record</b>, it obtains the display expression from the SQL record\'s <i>display_field </i>field.Â </li><ul><li>Using SQL, the display expression can be far more versatile AND the list can be limited by the SQL Where Clause.</li><li>View the SQL record for an existing dropdown as an example (eg dibqsTestCompanyWithParent).</li><li>A few rules apply here too... Press the F1-key to activate help for the following fields on ~nav(dibSqlForm)~: <i>Primary Field, Display Field, From Clause.</i></li></ul><li>Filters and refresh events can added to dropdowns ...Â </li><li>See <b>Warnings &amp; Troubleshooting </b>belowÂ </li></ul><p><br/></p><h5>Steps:</h5><ol><li>Open the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and select the container that has the dropdown.Â </li><li>Click on dropdown item in the tree under the <b>Layout</b>-tab.</li><li>Click on the Details tab that reveals more properties for the selected item in the tree.</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToDisplayExpr.png"/><br/><li><b>Change the existing display expression:</b></li><ul><li>Click the <b>CHANGE DISPLAY EXPRESSION</b> button.</li><ul><li>If the dropdown component is linked to a SQL record (marked in red above), the details of the SQL record will be opened. Change the <i>Display Field</i> field.</li><li>Otherwise the primary table record referenced by the foreign key field is opened. Change the <i>Display Expression</i> field.</li><li>Save any changes you make to records, and test it out.</li></ul></ul><li><b>Create a SQL record to specify the display expression:</b></li><ul><li>Open ~nav(dibSqlForm)~.</li><ul><li>Add a new record and give it a unique (and practical) name, eg. <b>qsClientsWithPhoneNos</b>.</li><li>Set the <i>Query Type</i> field to \'dropdown list\'.</li><li>Provide values for at least the following fields: <i>Primary Field, Display Field, From Clause. </i>See an existing dropdown list query for guidance, eg dibqsTestCompanyWithParent.</li><li>There are very specific rules that apply. Press the F1-key to toggle help for each of the above fields for more info.</li><li>Save the new record.</li></ul><li>Return to the Designer and to your dropdown item\'s properties under the Details-tab.</li><ul><li>Select the name of your new query in the SQL field (indicated in red above).</li><li>Save the changes to this record, and test it out.</li></ul></ul></ol><p><br/></p><h5>Warnings &amp; Troubleshooting:</h5><p>When Dropinbase generates CRUD code to read data for grids or forms, the display expressions are merged into the queries. This is why the following rules must be adhered to:</p><p>The From Clause of SQL statements for dropdown lists must always use LEFT JOIN\'s exclusively.<br/></p><p>Any errors will be listed under Logs. They will probably be SQL errors. Study the details of the error to pinpoint any invalid syntax or rules that were not adhered to.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc242-dib'),
    (243, 'How to apply changes in the underlying database to your application', 238, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Scenario:</h5><ul><li>You have added new fields, tables, indexes and/or foreign key relationships to the underlying database, and/or</li><li>You have removed one or more of the above from the underlying database</li><li>You want to update the affected containers to reflect these changes</li></ul><h5><br/></h5><h5>Side Notes:</h5><p>Some powerful database design tools are available free of charge... See:</p><ul><li>HeidiSql</li><li>SQL Server Management Studio (download the version that corresponds to your SQL Server installation)</li><li>MySQL Workbench</li><li>And many more ...</li></ul><p>Dropinbase stores the structure of underlying databases in the following tables:</p><ul><li>â<b>pef_table </b>- tables</li><li><b>pef_field </b>- fields and primary keys</li><li><b>pef_table_fk </b>- foreignkey relationships</li><li><b>pef_fk </b>- fields used in a foreign key relationship</li><li><b>pef_table_option </b>- indexes</li><li><b>pef_table_option_field </b>- fields used in an index</li></ul><h5>Steps:</h5><ol><li>Open ~nav(dibDatabaseGrid)~ and use the pencil icon (in the grid) to navigate to the record of the database that contains the changes.</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToApplyDbChanges.png"/><br/><li>Click the <b>REFRESH TASKS</b> button</li><ul><li>Dropinbase (DIB) analysis the structure of all tables in the underlying database and lists any differences with its own version thereof in the <i>Notice </i>column.</li><li>The following fields are used to specify actions to execute (you can update them):</li><ul><li><b>New Database Fields:</b> What to do with new fields found in tables. Double-click the grid row, and use the dropdown to choose either to <b>add to DIB</b> (Dropinbase) or <b>leave outside DIB</b>. Remember to save your changes to the row.</li><li><b>Extra DIB Fields:</b>Â What to do with fields found in Dropinbase\'s definitions, but not in the underlying database. Choose either to <b>remove from DIB</b> or to <b>IGNOREÂ </b>(not recommended if this field is linked to any items!).</li><li><b>Create Grid:</b> A new grid container will be created, based on the table. Use the other fields to specify options (eg <i>Caption, New Grid Name, Grid Design</i>, etc).</li><li><b>Create Form:</b> A new form container will be created, based on the table. Again, use the other fields to specify options...</li></ul><li>NOTE: The <b>New Database Fields</b> and <b>Extra DIB Fields</b> actions affect all items and containers linked to these table fields. Items will be either removed from, or added to these containers (depending on the actions specified).</li></ul><li>Use the <i><b>Ignore </b></i>tick to excluded certain tables from any actions specified.</li><li>Click on the <b>EXECUTE TASKS </b>menu. The following options are available:</li><ul><li><b>Execute Selected Tasks</b> - only tasks specified to selected rows in the grid are executed, except where <i>Ignore </i>is checked (in our example the product and staff rows are selected).</li><li><b>Execute All Tasks</b> - all tasks specified in the grid are executed, except where <i>Ignore </i>is checked.</li><li><b>Refresh Relationships (All/Selected)</b> - the foreign key relationship definitions stored in Dropinbase will be updated. If any records are filtered or selected, then only those apply, else relationships for all tables apply.</li><li><b>Refresh Indexes (All/Selected)</b> - the definitions for indexes stored in Dropinbase are updated. Again, either selected/filtered or all...</li><li><b>Remove from DIB </b>- completely remove all related records (eg containers with their items, events, settings etc.) of the tables in question. Again, either selected/filtered or all...Â </li><ul><li>A dialog will prompt you to confirm your action</li><li>If no records are selected, the dialog will prompt you to specify whether to also remove the related dashboard. The database record will remain intact. To remove EVERYTHING use the big red button on the same form.</li></ul></ul><li>The system will provide feedback via popup messages as it executes actions. It also updates the SYNC LOG-tab at the end with a log of all actions taken. A more detailed log is stored in the /runtime/logs folder.</li></ol><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc243-dib'),
    (244, 'How to force the width and height of grid columns and rows', 238, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Scenario:</h5><ul><li>Certain fields in the underlying table of a grid contain lots of data, causing excessive height of grid rows. We\'d like to set a maximum or fixed height.</li><li>Dropinbase assigns equal widths by default to a grid\'s columns. It is often desirable to force certain columns\' widths.</li></ul><h5><br/></h5><h5>Steps:</h5><ol><li>Open the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and select the grid container.Â </li><li>Select a column in the tree under the <b>Layout</b>-tab.</li><li>The following Editor appears:</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToGridHeightWidth.png"/><br/><li><b>Set row height:</b></li><ul><li>use css styling to apply a max-height attribute in the <i>Css </i>field (often the best option since not all rows have lots of data), eg <b>max-height : 80px;</b>Â  Â </li><li>or, set a fixed height in the <i>Height </i>field, eg <b>90px</b></li></ul><li><b>Set column width:</b></li><ul><li>To set a fixed width, set the <i>Flex </i>field to none and the <i>Width </i>field to the desired width, eg<b> 300px</b></li><li>Alternatively choose percentage values for all the columns in the <i>Flex </i>field, eg <b>10 </b>or <b>33 </b>etc (a value of <b>flex </b>will fill the remaining space)</li></ul><li><b>Other properties:</b></li><ul><li>Use <i>Margin </i>to set the margin around the field contents</li><li>Use <i>Padding </i>to set the padding around content within the field</li><li>SeeÂ <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/css/css_margin.asp" target="">https://www.w3schools.com/css/css_margin.asp</a> andÂ <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/css/css_padding.asp" target="">https://www.w3schools.com/css/css_padding.asp</a> for more info.</li></ul></ol><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc244-dib'),
    (245, 'How to nest a container inside a subcontainer component', 238, 60, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Overview Facts:</h5><ul><li>The subcontainer component is used to load child containers along with their parent/hosting containers.</li><li>Any type of container (eg dibGrid, dibForm, dibHtmlTemplate) can be set as child container this way.</li><li>Filters are often set on subcontainers to facilitate master-child relationships. See the relevant ~nav(How to set a filter on a dropdown or subcontainer or Port Item, HowTo topic)~ for more info.</li></ul><h5><br/></h5><h5>Steps (Automatic option - also has ability to add a filter)</h5><ol><li>âOpen the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and select the parent container that must contain the child container.</li><li>On the Component Tree and click on <b>Containers.</b></li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToSubcontainerEasy.png"/><li>Click on a category to select a container from:</li><ul><li><b>Related Containers:</b> containers based on tables that have foreign key relationships with the current container<br/></li><li><b>Other Containers:</b> containers not based on any tables/queries<br/></li></ul><ul><li><b>dibdemo/dropinbase/etc: </b>all containers based on tables/queries linked to the selected database</li></ul><li>Drag-and-drop one of the container names to the tree.</li><ul><li>If it is a Related Container, a filter will automatically be configured to facilitate a master-child relationship.</li></ul><li><b>Tips:Â </b></li><ol><li>Use the Seach box in the Components Tree to filter container names. Eg an entry of \'<b>client</b>\' will list only the <b>clientContactForm </b>and <b>clientContactGrid </b>in our example above.</li><li>the Databases node in the Components Tree lists tables and queries. Use drag-and-drop to create containers from them...</li></ol></ol><p><br/></p><h5>Steps (Manual option):</h5><ol><li>Open the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and select the parent container that must contain the child container.Â </li><li>Drag-and-drop a subcontainer component from the Component Tree to the desired location.</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToSubcontainer.png"/><li>Click on the new subcontainer component in the tree.</li><ol><li>If it is positioned as the child of mdTabs it will present as a tab. The subcontainer\'s caption will become the tab\'s caption.</li><li>If it is positioned inside another layout component, eg. layoutRow or div, then you may want to either set <i>Flex </i>to <b>flex </b>(or a fixed number eg <b>30</b>), or <i>Flex </i>to <b>none </b>and <i>Width </i>to a fixed number (eg <b>500px</b>). Also set a height, eg <b>400px</b>.</li></ol><li>Click on the Details tab to reveal more properties of the subcontainer.</li><li>Select the desired child container in the Child Container field.</li><li>Setting a filter is not required, but if you need to set one, then see the ~nav(How to set a filter on a dropdown or subcontainer or Port Item, HowTo topic about filters)~.</li></ol><p><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc245-dib'),
    (246, 'How to set a filter on a dropdown or subcontainer or Port Item', 238, 80, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Overview Facts:</h5><ul><li>Filters are expressions that Dropinbase includes in the WHERE clause of the container/dropdown\'s underlying SQL statement.</li><ul><li>The underlying SQL statement of a container can be viewed on the Configuration-tab on the Designer by ticking the <i>View SQL</i> checkbox.</li><li>Any field in any table used in the FROM clause of the SQL statement can be used in the filter expression. Use the <i>Extra Table Join</i> field to include more tables.</li></ul><li>The expression can contain parameters that reference item values on the user-interface.Â </li><ul><li>Eg <b>`client_contact`.`client_id` = :submitItemAlias_parent_client_pk</b></li><li>The items referenced must have their <i>Alias </i>field checked.</li><li>Use <b>:submitItemAlias_self_ITEMNAME</b> (eg <b>:submitItemAlias_self_categoryId</b>) to reference an item on the current container.</li><li>Use<b> :submitItemAlias_parent_ITEMNAME</b> (eg <b>:submitItemAlias_parent_id</b>) to reference an item on the parent container.</li><li>See ~navdocs(Filters)~ for more info about referencing item values.</li></ul><li>The child container\'s <b>view/read </b>request, or the component\'s <b>componentlist </b>request, (sent by the user-interface code) will contain parameters named <b>activeFilter </b>and <b>submissionData </b>that are used to process the filter on the server.</li><ul><li>Use the browser\'s Developer Tools to view requests under the Network-tab.</li></ul><li>Filters can be placed on:</li><ul><li>dropdowns: mdAutocomplete, mdSelect,Â mdMultiSelect,Â mdSelectSearch</li><li>subcontainer</li><li>And any layout component that is also a Port Item (ie a container is attached to it when loaded via a port)</li><li><b>NOTE: for subcontainer and Port Items, the <i>Child Container</i> field must link to the container being filtered for the filter to work.</b></li></ul></ul><h5><br/></h5><h5>Examples:</h5><ul><li>See ~nav(dibexSubContainers)~.</li></ul><ul><li>Dropinbase automatically adds filters to Port Item-tabs when generating applications that have foreign key relationships.</li></ul><p><br/></p><h5>Steps:</h5><ol><li><b>(NOTE:</b> see ~navdocs(How to nest a container inside a subcontainer component)~ for an automatic way of adding a subcontainer with a filter).</li><li>Open the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and select the container that has the dropdown, subcontainer or Port Item.Â </li><li>Click on this item in the tree under the <b>Layout</b>-tab.</li><li>Click on the Details tab that reveals more properties for the selected item in the tree.</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToFilters.png"/><br/><li>Put the expression in the <i>Filter </i>field.</li><li>If this is a subcontainer or Port Item, ensure that the <i>Child Container</i> field is linked to the container being filtered.</li><li>If this is a dropdown component that is filtered by the value of another dropdown (ie dependant dropdown scenario), you may want to add a Refresh Item event on the first dropdown to refresh the list of the dropdown with the filter when the value of the first dropdown changes. See the <b>parentCompanyId </b>andÂ <b>parentCompanyContactId </b>dropdowns on ~nav(dibexSubContainers)~ as an example. Note, the target of the Refresh Item event (the dropdown with the filter) must have its <i>Alias </i>field set.</li><li>NOTE: any items referenced by parameters in the filter expression must have their <i>Alias </i>field set.</li></ol><p><br/></p><h5>Troubleshooting:</h5><ul><li>Check the <b>view/read</b> request for the container, or the <b>componentlist </b>request for the dropdown using the browser\'s Developer Tools (Network-tab).</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToFilters_debug.png"/><ul><li>If there is no <b>activeFilter </b>parameter under <b>Query String Parameters</b>, it means the <i>Filter </i>field was not set, or the browser page needs to be refreshed to include the new code.</li><li>If the submissionData parameter under Request Payload does not contain the item value used in the filter expression, ensure that the item has an Alias. If the item is not on the current or parent containers, you will need to set ~navdocs(Submission Data)~ configs to include it.</li></ul><li>Any SQL errors will be listed under Logs. Study the details of the error to pinpoint any invalid syntax in the filter expression.<br/></li></ul>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc246-dib'),
    (248, 'How to load a container via a port', 238, 70, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Overview Facts:</h5><ul><li>Containers targeted by <b>ports </b>are loaded dynamically when the user clicks on eg a tab, button or menu-item.Â </li><li>The <b>URL </b>can (optionally) be set to change when a container is opened via a port.</li><li>A port record specifies the tab or other layout component item, named the <b>Port Item</b>, that a container is attached to when loaded.</li><li>A container can have multiple port records, or in other words, a container can be loaded/reused in multiple places.Â </li><ul><li>The default port record\'s Port Alias field is \'main\'. The associated URL contains only the container name, eg. /nav/clientContactGrid.</li><li>Secondary port records have other unique Port Alias values(eg <b>clientForm</b>), which are also used in URLs, eg /nav/clientContactGrid/<b>clientForm.</b></li></ul><li>So why the name <b>port</b>? A boat can dock at various ports, and a gadget can dock in various usb-ports of your laptop.</li><li>Filters can be set on Port Items to facilitate master-child relationships. See the relevant ~nav(How to set a filter on a dropdown or subcontainer or Port Item, HowTo topic)~ for more info.<br/></li></ul><h5><br/></h5><h5>Steps</h5><ol><li>âOpen the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and select the target container (the container that must be opened).</li><li>On the Ports-tab, ensure that a record exists to attach the container to the desired Port Item. If it does not exist, use one of the Add buttons to create a new record (see field descriptions in the next point).</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToPorts.png"/><li>Port record field descriptions:</li><ul><li><b>Container:</b> the container that must be loaded.<br/></li><li><b>Port Item:</b> where the container is attached to.<br/></li></ul><ul><li><b>Port Alias: </b>unique identifier used in URL to identify the port records<li><li><b>Caption:</b> optional caption to be used when the container is loaded via this port. The caption is used on eg tabs and will replace any existing caption.</li><li><b>Window Mode:</b> whether the container is loaded as a floating window or not. Note, in Angular Material, the window will close the moment it loses focus.</li><li><b>Change URL: </b>whether the URL must be updated when the port record is activated.Â </li><li><b>Remember Query String:</b> parameters such as primary key values are added to URLs and kept in memory for the next time the same URL is activated. When this is unchecked, the last used parameters are not kept in and fetched from memory.</li></ul><li>Next, we need to link a button, tab or menu item etc. to this port record. When the user clicks on it, the container will load using the settings specified above for the specific port. If it does not yet exist, you will need to create it. The following components are often used with ports:</li><ul><li>mdButton<br/></li><li>mdMenuItem (will be a child of mdMenu)</li><li>sidenavMenuNode (will be a child of contentFor(menuItems) or another sidenavMenuNode)</li></ul><ul><li>various layout components that are used as tabs under mdTabs (eg div, layoutRow, layoutColumn)</li></ul><li>Click on the item, and select the desired port record in the Port field (note the distinguishing Port Alias follows the dash(-) in the dropdown list).</li><ul><li>In the example below, a div component is used as a tab. When the user clicks on the tab, the target container is loaded using the specified port settings.</li></ul></ol><p><br/></p><p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToPorts_setItem.png"/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc248-dib'),
    (249, 'How to implement a custom theme or style for your appllication', 238, 90, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Overview Facts:</h5><ul><li>Dropinbase implements AngularJS Material which follows a Material Design approach to theming. You can read more about it here:</li><ul><li><a href="https://material.angularjs.org/latest/Theming/01_introduction" target="">https://material.angularjs.org/latest/Theming/01_introduction</a></li></ul><li>Basically, theming is based on four palettes, or &#34;color intentions&#34;:</li><ul><li>Primary</li><li>Accent</li><li>Warn</li><li>Background</li></ul><li>Dropinbase ships with two methods to define a theme:</li><ul><li>A general facility to choose a palette for each of the above color intentions, from all the options defined in the Material Design specification.</li><li>For applications that require a very specific theme (eg implement corporate colors), the palettes can be configured manually (not too difficult).</li></ul></ul><h5><br/></h5><h5>Steps (Material Design themes):</h5><ol><li>âOpen the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and click on the Palette icon.</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToTheme_Pallete.png"/><li>Choose a palette for each of the four color intentions:</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToTheme_DIB.png"/><li>Click Save to implement the new theme.</li><ul><li>the chosen theme palettes are stored in the ~nav(dibSettingGrid, Settings table)~.</li></ul></ol><p><br/></p><h5>Steps (specific theme):</h5><ol><li>Browse to the following online facility:Â <a href="http://mcg.mbitson.com/" target="">http://mcg.mbitson.com/</a></li><p><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToTheme_Custom.png"/></p><li>Use the Add button to add three more themes and name them as illustrated below.</li><ul><li>Note, we\'ll update these names again later on since the facility does not allow capital letters.</li></ul><li>Also specify main and secondary colors for each palette.</li><p><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToTheme_Custom4.png"/></p><li>Click the Export button.</li><li><b>Click on AngularJS Material in the sidebar.</b></li><li>Select and copy all the text, except the last part indicated in red below:</li><p><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToTheme_Copy.png"/></p><li>Open the following file in a text editor (eg NotePad++):Â <b>/files/themes/overrides/setNgMaterial/dibAngular/dibCustomTheme.js</b></li><li>Replace ONLY the corresponding sections in the <b>dibCustomTheme.js</b> file</li><ul><li>Note, be careful NOT to replace anything that is not a duplicate of what is being pasted (the top part is different).</li></ul><li>Now we need to update the names again... Each palette section\'s name needs a capital letter after \'custom\':</li><p><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToTheme_Rename.png"/></p><ul><li>customprimary -&gt; customPrimary</li><li>customaccent -&gt; customAccent</li><li>customwarn -&gt; customWarn</li></ul><ul><li>custombackground -&gt; customBackground</li></ul><li>Save the file and reload your application.</li></ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc249-dib'),
    (250, 'How to create a new container and table from scratch', 238, 120, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>There are many different types of containers. We will discuss creating a dibContainer, used for functional purposes such as base containers or wizards, and then how to create a new database table based on its fields, to create a functional form.<br/></p><h5>Or perhaps:</h5><ul><li>To create <b>grids and forms</b>, the easiest (automated) methods are described here:Â </li><ul><li>~navdocs(How to create a grid or form based on an existing table)~</li><li>~navdocs(How to create a grid based on a SQL statement)~Â Â </li></ul><li>If your new container should look and function very similar to an existing container, then rather <b>make a copy of the existing one</b>:</li><ul><li>Click the <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/duplicateButton.png"/> button under Configuration on the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and follow the instructions...</li></ul></ul><h5>Notes</h5><ul><li>âCreating a new database table based on a container\'s fields, currently works only for MySQL, and is still in Alpha development phase.</li></ul><h5><br/></h5><h5>Steps - Part 1 (Create new container):</h5><ol><li>âOpen the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~.</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateNewContainer.png"/><li>Under <b>CONFIGURATION</b>, click the <b>Add New Container</b> button.</li><li>Fields:</li><ul><li><b>Name:</b> provide a unique name for the container. Due to restrictions with Angular:Â </li><ul><li>only alpha-numeric characters are allowed</li><li>first letter must be lowercase and alphabetic</li><li>no spaces allowed and capital letters may not follow one another</li><li>eg aaaHelloThere</li></ul><li><b>Caption:</b> provide a caption for the container that will used when it is loaded in eg tabs.<br/></li></ul><ul><li><b>Container Dropin: </b>select the type of container (eg dibGrid, dibForm, etc). We\'re using dibContainer as explained above.</li><li><b>Module Dropin: </b>this field is used to group containers together in a <b>Module Dropin</b>Â and to cause the container\'s generated code to be stored in the dropin\'s folder. If left empty, files are stored in the /runtime/ folder. To create a Module Dropin:</li><ul><li>Create a new folder under the /dropins/ folder (alpha-numeric characters and no spaces).</li><li>Delete the /runtime/permFiles folder (this will cause DIB to check for new Module Dropins).</li><li>The new Module Dropin should now be available on the dropdown list.</li></ul><li><b>Model:</b> select the data source type. dibContainer has no data source and should therefore always be \'None\'.</li><ul><li>If for eg <b>Table</b>, is chosen, then the <i>Table </i>dropdown would become visible to select a table.</li></ul></ul><li>Click the save button to save the new container record.</li><ul><li>Dropinbase will automatically navigate the Designer to the new record.</li><li>You will notice that Permission records were added automatically for the admin user.</li></ul><li>Click <b>Add Port</b> to automatically add a Port record.</li><ul><li>The field defaults are obtained from the ~nav(dibDatabaseGrid, Database record)~ if available, or else from ~nav(dibSettings, Settings records)~ (Default Base Container and Default Port Item).Â </li><li>Click on the <b>Ports </b>tab to modify Port records.</li></ul></ol><h5><br/></h5><h5>Steps - Part 2 (Create new table based on the container\'s fields):</h5><ol><li>Click on the <b>LAYOUT</b>-tab.</li><br/><p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateNewContainer_Table.png"/></p><li>Add components (the form components will be used to identify table fields)<br/></li><ul><li>Use drag-and-drop to add components from the Components Tree.</li><li>Start with a layout component, eg. layoutColumn or layoutFieldset</li><li>Add form components/fields (eg inputText, inputEmail, mdCheckbox, etc.) as child components of the layout component. Give each of them a unique name (which will also become table field names), eg <i>first_name</i>, <i>mobile</i>, etc.</li></ul><li>Return to the <b>CONFIGURATION</b>-tab.</li><br/><p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateNewContainer_Create.png"/></p><li>Click on the<b> Create table and/or fields for all new editable container items</b> menu item, under <b>TABLE AND FIELD TASKS</b>.</li><li>The <b>Table Designer</b> will open on the newly created table record with its fields.</li><br/><p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateNewContainer_TableDesign.png"/></p><li>You can modify field values before creating the actual table in the underlying database:</li><ol><li>the table\'s <i>Name</i></li><li>the <i>Database </i>it will be created in (must be MySQL)</li><li>the <i>Display Expression </i>(for foreign keys that will reference this table)</li><li>field <i>Names, Field Types, Lengths</i>, etc.</li></ol><li>Click on the <b>DATABASE TASK</b>S-tab.</li><li>Click on the <b>GENERATE SQL</b> button.</li><ul><li>You should not alter any SQL that does not correspond with the table fields; ie rather change the values in the Dropinbase tables and then click <b>GENERATE SQL</b> again.</li></ul><li>Click on <b>EXECUTE SQL </b>to create the new table.</li><li>Return to the Designer.</li><ul><li>You will notice that the form fields have all been linked to their table fields.</li></ul><li>Click on the <b>CONFIGURATION</b>-tab.</li><li>Change the<i> Container Dropin</i> field now to <b>dibForm.</b></li><ul><li>You will notice the <i>Model </i>has been changed to <b>Table </b>and the <i>Table </i>field references the new table record.</li></ul><li>Click the save button.</li><li>The last few steps adds the toolbar buttons to our new form. We\'ll simply copy-paste them from another form...</li><ul><li>Open the clientForm (or any other form container with the necessary buttons)</li><br/><p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateNewContainer_ToolbarCopy.png"/></p><li>Under the LAYOUT-tab, select the toolbar item in the Items tree</li><li>On the Fab-menu, click Copy</li><li>Return to the new container (eg myTest)</li><li>Click anywhere in the Items tree, and click Paste</li><li>Use drag-and-drop to position the toolbar in the top-most position of the tree</li></ul><li>You can use the &#34;Play&#34; button at the top of the Designer, next to the container dropdown, to open the new container in another tab.</li></ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc250-dib'),
    (251, 'How to create a grid or form based on an existing table', 238, 100, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Overview Facts:</h5><ul><li>Grid and form containers can be created automatically either by:</li><ul><li>Checking <b>Create Grid</b> and/or <b>Create Form</b> on ~nav(dibDatabaseForm?record=last)~ and using the EXECUTE TASKS-button.</li><li>Dragging tables, queries or containers from the Components Tree</li></ul><li>To manually create containers, see ~navdocs(How to create a new container and table from scratch)~</li></ul><h5><br/></h5><h5>Steps (Using dibDatabaseForm):</h5><ol><li>Open ~nav(dibDatabaseGrid)~ and use the pencil icon (in the grid) to navigate to the database containing the tables for which new containers must be created.</li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateGridForm.png"/><br/><li>Configure the following fields in the table:</li><ul><li><b>Create Grid:</b> a new grid container will be created, based on the table.</li><li><b>Create Form:</b> a new form container will be created, based on the table.</li><li><b>Related Records:</b> specifies whether related grids, forms or both must be included on tabs on new <b>form containers</b>Â that are created.</li><li><b>Caption:</b> the caption to use in eg tabs when the container is loaded.</li><li><b>New Grid Name:</b> the name of the new grid container (if applicable). Will be used in URLs, eg /nav/CONTAINERNAME.</li><li><b>New Form Name:</b> the name of the new form container (if applicable). Will be used in URLs, eg /nav/CONTAINERNAME.</li><li><b>Grid Design:</b> the design template to use when creating a grid container for this table.</li><li><b>Form Design:</b> the design template to use when creating a form container for this table.</li><li><b>Menu Item:</b> the parent menu item. If left blank, then no menu item will be created.</li></ul><li>Click on the <b>EXECUTE TASKS </b>menu. The following options are available:</li><ul><li><b>Execute Selected Tasks</b> - only tasks specified in selected rows are executed, except where <i>Ignore </i>is checked (in our example the client and myTest rows are selected).</li><li><b>Execute All Tasks</b> - all tasks specified in the grid are executed, except where <i>Ignore </i>is checked.</li></ul><li>The system will provide feedback via popup messages as it executes actions. It also updates the SYNC LOG-tab at the end with a log of all actions taken. A more detailed log is stored in the /runtime/logs folder.</li></ol><p><br/></p><h5><br/></h5><h5>Steps (Using dibDatabaseForm):</h5><ol><li>Open the ~nav(dibDesigner, Designer)~ and navigate to the parent container where the new container must be added/attached.</li><br/><li>On the Components Tree, click on Databases</li><li>Select one of the following</li><ul><li><b>New Tables:</b> new tables in the database that are not yet imported/indexed in Dropinbase</li><li><b>Existing Tables:</b>Â tables that are already imported/indexed</li><li><b>Queries:</b>Â SQL statements defined in Dropinbase</li></ul><li>Drag-and-drop one of the listed tables (or queries) to where the new container must be attached.</li><p><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateFromTableQuery.png"/></p><li>The Create Container page will open with various options:</li><p><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToCreateFromTableQuery_Options.png"/></p><li>Choose one of the Actions:</li><ol><li><b>Option 1:</b> A port record will be created, linking the new grid to the selected <b>Item</b>. If you navigate to <b>/nav/clientContactGridÂ </b>the grid will be loaded in the specified <b>Item </b>(divClientContacts on clientForm) which in this case is a tab.</li><li><b>Option 2:</b> This is the same as the first option, except that the selected Item (the tab) will be linked to the port record. If the user clicks the Item (tab), the grid is loaded dynamically. Note, the Item must be &#34;clickable&#34; in order to trigger the loading, eg a tab.<br/></li><li><b>Option 3:</b> A subcontainer component will be created under the specified <b>Item</b> to host the new container. Note, any container hosted in a subcontainer is always loaded when the parent container (clientForm) is loaded.Â </li></ol><li><b>Caption: </b>Choose a caption for the new container(s).</li><li><b>Item: </b>If a subcontainer is involved (option 3) this refers to the parent Item of the new subcontainer. Otherwise it refers to the Port Item (ie, where the new grid will be attached to when loaded).</li><li><b>Create Grid:</b>Â whether to create grid container. This is required if the data source is a SQL query.</li><li><b>Create Form:</b> whether to create a form container.</li><li><b>Name: </b>Provide a name for the new grid/form container.Â </li><li><b>Design:</b> Select the Design Template to use for the new grid/form container. Note, certain templates are specific to tables, or certain types of queries (eg UNION SELECT).</li><li><b>Add Menu Item:</b> Select this checkbox in case a menu item must be added to open the new container. Note, if option 3 (subcontainer) is selected,Â  a port record will be created linked to the default Port Item specified in the database record.</li><li><b>Parent Menu Item:</b> Select the parent menu node of the new menu item. Any root or child node of any menu within Dropinbase is available as Parent Menu Item.</li></ol><p></p><p></p><p><li>Click <b>CREATE </b>to create the new grid(s), or <b>CANCEL </b>to exit.</li></p><p></p><p></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc251-dib'),
    (252, 'How to call client-side JavaScript or server-side PHP code', 238, 130, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Overview Facts:</h5><ul><li>When an item or container event is specified (stored in <i>pef_item_event</i> and <i>pef_container_event</i> respectively) Dropinbase generates code in the design of the container to handle the event.Â </li><li>In the case of executing JavaScript, the code loads a JavaScript file for execution. In the case of a server-side call, the Dropinbase server-side API is invoked to redirect the request to a PHP controller function.</li><li>The syntax for defining the URL differs for the above two cases. See ~navdocs(Item Events)~ for more info.</li><li>The alternative is to use the wizards to build the url.</li></ul><h5><br/></h5><h5>Steps:</h5><ol><li><br/></li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToFiltersx.png"/><br/><li><br/></li></ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc252-dib'),
    (253, 'How to add an Excel Export menu to a grid', 238, 140, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h5>Overview Facts:</h5><ul><li></li></ul><h5>http://mcg.mbitson.com/<br/></h5><p><br/></p><h5>Steps:</h5><ol><li><br/></li><br/><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howToFiltersx.png"/><br/><li><br/></li></ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc253-dib'),
    (254, 'Development Phase', 324, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><br/></p><p>Principles</p><p>It is best to implement a project in phases, where each phase encompasses parts of the system that the client actually needs and can cope with. Keep phases as small and simple as possible.</p><p>Move from general to detail. At the beginning focus on gathering and clarifying foundational facts and build a prototype that encapsulates them and provides a high-level answer. Move on to a MVP (minimal viable product) by delving into and implementing more levels of detail. Round off the project by implementing details not yet attended to.</p><p>Prototyping, which is a strength of Dropinbase, helps to put everyone on the same page and provides a practical platform for further planning and implementation. Prototypes need to contain only basic user-interface features to be useful.</p><p>Recognize areas in the project which are grey ito scope and/or resources required as early as possible. They may greatly affect deadlines and budget and are a primary cause of disappointment. Advise the client in these cases that more research (which may require funding) is necessary before commitments can be made. It is preferable to arrange for payment by time &amp; material for these areas.</p><p>There is nothing more important thanÂ sufficient information gathering followed byÂ thoughtful planning and a creative consideration of the best options.</p><p>Projects with complex business rules, processes or permissions will require an experienced architect and an eye for detail.</p><p><br/></p><p>Team Members</p><p>The following roles can be shared or combined among people. Note, that where roles are not clear however, you may end up with egg on the floor :)</p><p>Project Leader</p><p>Each project must have someone who owns the overall responsibility for ensuring its success. Their primary task is to ensure the best route at each turn, and managing resources, eg time, budget and staff, to accomplish tasks. A project leader must therefore have good management skills, especially of the most important resource, namely people. They need to be informed and understand whatever is necessary to fit the available resources into a plan and actualize it. Another important task is to get absolute clarity of the end-client\'s expectations, and manage it when necessary.</p><p><br/></p><p><b>Information gathering</b></p><p>In most cases the client already has some idea of the purpose of the proposed system, but since they are not system experts, it is beneficial to make them aware of possibilities.</p><p>Â A business application is much more than a mere data repository. A well-designed application becomes an indispensable tool that plays a primary role in facilitating:</p><p>the business processes (task flows)</p><p>communication (between departments and with clients and/or suppliers)</p><p>Â  Â Eg it will no longer be necessary to phone Paul to determine if stock has arrived - just look on the system.</p><p>services to clients, suppliers, etc.</p><p>automation of repetitive tasks</p><p>record keeping and auditing, and</p><p>business intelligence (eg stats)</p><p><br/></p><p><b>The following questions need to be asked:</b></p><p><b>Executive summary.</b> What does the company do and what main purposes must and can the proposed system fulfill?Â </p><p>This should be a short description of why the new system is needed and what is at the heart of the solution.</p><p><b>Current situation.</b> What existing systems are in place? What are the strengths and weaknesses thereof. Are there files or a paper trail from the existing system that can help to understand the business and build the new system.</p><p>Role players (entities) and their relationships. Who and what is involved. Products, services, staff, quotes, stock systems, clients, etc... and the type of relationship between them, ie 1 to 1, 1 to many, or many many. This information will surface during the discussion, but is important to identify especially for constructing the ER diagram.</p><p><b>Business rules.</b> Certain applications facilitate many sets of rules (if A = 1 and user role = \'staff\' then X must be visible). A detailed description is needed. List them in such a way that the client can easily sign them off and programmers can understand them easily for the purpose of implementation. Spreadsheet tables are often used.</p><p><b>Processes.</b>Â Information or physical objects move between users, suppliers, clients and other systems and gets processed or changes status on the way. Flow charts can be used to describe this movement and transformation and any conditions that are involved, but don\'t document it unless it really serves a purpose of understanding or building the system.Â </p><p><b>Outputs. </b>The proposed solution normally involves essential reports or some other form of output. Often clients already have a manual example they have in use that has been carefully crafted over years. By studying it, some key information can become clear. Also, the output points to the required input and processes to get there.</p><p><b>Project phases.</b>Â How can the project be divided into phasesÂ </p><p><b>Environment.</b> How will the proposed system fit and integrate with existing systems and processes?</p><p><b>Users</b>. Who are the users and what are their roles, tasks and existing computer skills related to the proposed system? What devices will they use, when?</p><p><b>Security</b>. What are the system security and permission constraints, and how will it be implemented from the user\'s point of view.</p><p><b>Technology and design requirements. </b>How many new records are envisaged per year for which entities, and how many concurrent users will be active at peak periods and doing what? What type of devices will be used for which functions?Â </p><p>Hosting requirements.Â </p><p><b>Maintenance and dependencies.</b> What contingencies</p><p><span style="font-size: 12px;float: none;">Implementation</span><br/><br/><br/><b>Projest Phases and Approach</b><br/><br/>Dividing a project into major and minor phases makes it manageable (and affordable) for both your client and your team. The first phase must focus on foundations that can\'t be replaced later, and essential features that the client needs most urgently. Refrain from adding features that do not have any great need or will not be used soon - most of them are never used!</p><p>Note, Gartner reports that 75% of ERP system implementations fail. Dropinbase takes aim at this horrific statistic by realizing a truly Agile approach to developing systems at a greatly reduced cost and time frame. Instead of delivering a huge end-product which may become a white elephant since the end-users don\'t adopt it for whatever reason, the project makes use of a &#34;discover-the-best-solution-together&#34; approach, as follows:</p><p>Obtain enough information to establish the foundations</p><p>Create an ER diagram and get a second opinion from an expertÂ (see guidelines below).</p><p>Build the database</p><p>Obtain enough information to build a prototype of a specific key feature</p><p>Deliberate with key players about the best possible solution</p><p>Use DIB to build a simple user-interface that reflects the solution. Don\'t be bogged down with details or functionality that requires coding.</p><p>Do a demo and get the client\'s input. Establish how it can be refined (or perhaps completely replaced) towards a more fitting solution.</p><p>Repeat the process until the prototype is fully accepted as the best solution.</p><p>Create a MVP (minimal viable product) by adding essential functionality</p><p>Perform in-house tests (often best to use someone that is not familiar with the project) and refine.</p><p>Let the client test it and obtain input.Â </p><p>Refine towards a fully functional feature or system.</p><p><br/></p><p><b>Risk Awareness &amp; Management</b></p><p><br/></p><p><b>Technical setup</b></p><p>Three implementations: development, client testing, live.</p><p>Trello, Slack, Google Docs,Â </p><p>Documents must capture the planning but act as a bridge for developers.<br/><br/><b>Closing the deal</b></p><p>During the very first visit to a potential client, your main aim is to instill a sense of viability, trust and a bit of excitement. This can be accomplished by:</p><p></p><ul><li>Be confident, pleasant, and take a team member with you (going as a team projects your commitment and there is someone that can take notes).</li><li>Provide a background of your company and clients.</li><li>Enlighten the client about the many benefits of Dropinbase and the longterm support environment that goes with it.</li><li>Do a demo of Dropinbase to give them a feel of what they can expect (most other providers can\'t and this gives them something more tangible)</li><li>Suggest a phased approach with frequent prototypes which are accessible an any time on the internet.</li><li>Throw something they like in for free.</li><li>Remove their pains. You may get some extra business by offering to do things they neither the capacity or skills for.</li></ul><p>However some basic insights are gathered about the project, or a part of it, that should be enough to build a simple prototype with DIB. The best way to close the deal is to push them a bit by saying they will not find a better deal vs quality, andÂ suggesting that you take a copy of any required files with you and return in a day or two with a functional solution that will not break the bank.</p><p>Another tip is not be shy and ask them what their budget and deadlines are, saying that DIB allows you to provide them with either the Mercedes Benz or the Toyota version, and you need a feel for what is within their reach. It is often necessary to come up with creative solution that makes the project affordable, which is difficult if you do not know what the client\'s limitations are.</p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc254-dib'),
    (255, 'Kickstart a Career in System Development', 333, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>All organizations make use of database systems in some form, whether they are handwritten lists, Excel spreadsheets or enterprise systems such as SAP.</p>\n<p>A well designed database system plays a core role in facilitating the processes and business rules of successful and growing organizations, from small NPO\'s to multi-national institutions. Designing and building these systems is a rewarding career involving a wide range of skills including social, analytical, creative, and logic skills.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>A business application is far more than a data-repository: It is a powerful tool for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Streamlining business processes and task flows</li>\n<li>Enhancing communication within departments and with external entities like clients and suppliers</li>\n<li>Automating repetitive tasks</li>\n<li>Managing resources</li>\n<li>Facilitating growth</li>\n<li>Controlling quality and compliance</li>\n<li>Simplifying record keeping and auditing</li>\n<li>Providing business intelligence (eg. statistics)</li>\n<li>Enhancing staff experience</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If building these computer systems and offering these solutions to clients thrills you, it will be a very rewarding journey.</p>\n<p>Below is a list of technical skills to explore.&nbsp; You do not need them to start using Dropinbase productively, but in-depth knowledge of them is required for the road ahead to complex systems.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Client Server Model - how cloud-based business applications function from a technical point of view.</li>\n<li>Relational Database Theory, and Relational Database Management System (RDBMS)</li>\n<li>Structured Query Language (SQL)</li>\n<li>Entity Relationship Diagrams (ERD)</li>\n<li>Hypertext Markup Language (HTML)</li>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Also see https://www.w3schools.com/html/</em></li>\n</ul>\n<li>Cascading Style Sheets (CSS)</li>\n<li>Sassy Cascading Style Sheets (SCSS)</li>\n<li>PHP&nbsp;<em>(recursive acronym for PHP: Hypertext Preprocessor)</em></li>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Also see http://php.net/manual/en/intro-whatis.php</em></li>\n</ul>\n<li>JavaScript</li>\n<li>TypeScript</li>\n<li>Angular</li>\n<li>Angular Material</li>\n<li>AI chatbots and agents, used both for coding and integrated into solutions</li>\n</ul>\n<p><br><br></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc255-dib'),
    (256, 'Relational Database Theory', 333, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Relational Database Theory was formalized in 1970 by Dr EF Codd. It revolutionized database design and resulted in the development of various RDBMS (relational database management systems) such as MySQL, PostgreSql and SQL Server. Prior to these technologies, data was mostly stored in Excel-like tables with no relationships and was prone to frustrating data duplication issues and was difficult to query. Many organizations start out with storing their data in various Excel sheets, but then soon face the inherent short-comings of this system.</p>\n<p>Under Relational Database Theory, the data fields are divided into distinct entities, where the fields belonging to each entity directly relate to it in a one-to-one fashion. Eg, in a given set of data, an <em>Individual </em>has one <strong>first name</strong>, one <strong>last name</strong>, one <strong>educational institution</strong>&nbsp;etc, and a <em>Organisation </em>has a <strong>name </strong>and <strong>physical address</strong>. In case the data or business rules provides for a maximum of two <strong>educational institutions</strong> per person, we can simply add an <strong>educational_inst2&nbsp;</strong>field to the individual table. This strategy is fine for two or three institutions, but thereafter many of these fields would mostly be empty and waste space in displays in reports. The solution is to create another table to store any amount of institutions per individual. The two tables are linked with a system of primary and foreign keys. But let\'s first look at how different entities relate.</p>\n<p>An&nbsp;<em>Organisation </em>could have one or many <em>Individuals </em>linked to them as for eg <strong>staff</strong>. Similarly an <em>Individual </em>could be linked to one or many <em>Organisations </em>as for eg <strong>directors</strong>. The relationships between entities (one-to-one, one-to-many, or many-to-many) are facilitated by a system of primary and foreign keys.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>For each table, a field (or combination of fields) that has an unique value for each record is assigned as the primary key. This means that if I refer to Organisation 79 in a given table, then I will find one and only one record where the primary key field has a value of 79. I can now add foreign key fields to other tables to relate their records to the primary table\'s records. In the <em>Individual </em>table we add a <strong>organisation_id</strong> field and can then add two or more records where the value here is 79 to indicate that these individuals are all linked to a specific organisation in a one-to-many relationship.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Should an individual also be linked to many organisations, we need to facilitate the many-to-many relationship with an intermediate table that links the two primary tables (Individual and Organisation). The intermediate table will contain one foreign key for each primary table that is linked in the relationship.</p>\n<p>If a few of the individuals are VIP\'s for which we need to store values in many additional fields (eg next visit date, spouse name, award level, etc.) we can create a <em>VIP&nbsp;</em>table with an <strong>individual_id </strong>foreign key field. Each record will have a unique value in the <strong>individual_id </strong>field, meaning that each individual relates to zero or one records in the <em>VIP&nbsp;</em>table. This one-to-one relationship is not often used, but useful if there are many fields that need to be isolated or hidden by permissions, or if other entities (eg Donations From VIP\'s) need to relate to it only. In Dropinbase we can then add a button to the Individual Form container which opens the VIP Form container. Only certain users could have rights to open the container, or view and/or edit these records.</p>\n<p>There are no perfect designs for table structures. There are however good and bad designs. A good design:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>reflects the real world situation of entities and relationships between them accurately</li>\n<li>is&nbsp;<strong>normalized ***</strong>, but only as far as it serves the practical purpose of being normalized.</li>\n<li>reflects the practical user scenario, ie. the eventual user-interface design that facilitates working with and viewing the data</li>\n<li>eliminates the need to capture or maintain the same data in more than one place</li>\n<li>implements good naming and other design protocols consistently that makes the design easy to understand and work with</li>\n<li>takes future (potential) phases of the system, or integrations with other systems, into account</li>\n</ul>\n<p>*** Normalization refers to a set of steps one can follow to eliminate redundancy (the <strong>educational institution</strong> problem above) and to ensure that data dependencies make sense.</p>\n<p>Entity Relationship Diagrams are used to design the structure of database systems.</p>\n<h3>SQL</h3>\n<p>To create the tables, and query and modify the data that is stored in the related entities, Structured Query Language (SQL) was developed as part of Relational Database Theory. SQL is an english-like language that can draw very specific information from all the related tables. It is amazingly powerful, and is easy to get into. We encourage you to explore it further.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc256-dib'),
    (257, 'Database - update create delete', 94, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3>Database::create</h3>\n<pre>/**<br>* Inserts values specified in $params in $tableName (NOTE spaces and non-alphanumeric characters in field names may cause errors)<br>*<br>* @param string <strong>$tableName</strong> name of table to add records to<br>* @param array <strong>$params</strong> associative array of fieldName=&gt;value<br>* @param mixed<strong> $container_database</strong> the target pef_database_id (must also match value in /config/Conn.php) OR the name of a container linked to a database via pef_table_id or pef_sql_id<br>* @param string <strong>$auditTrail&nbsp;</strong>(optional) level of detail to store in audit trail table, detail/summary/basic or NULL<br>* @param string&nbsp;<strong>$notes </strong>(optional) are stored in pef_audit_trail record<br>*<br>* @return mixed boolean FALSE on error, primary key value on success<br>*/<br><strong>public static function create($tableName, $params, $container_database, $auditTrail=null, $notes=null)</strong></pre>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<pre><em>// Create a new company record providing values for all required fields</em><br>$params = [\'name\'=&gt;\'Test Pty (Ltd)\', \'notes\'=&gt;\'testing 123\'];<br><br>$newId = Database::create(\'test_company\', $params, DIB::$LOGINDB, \'detail\');<br><br>if($newId === false) $return $this-&gt;invalidResult("Could not create record");</pre>\n<h3>Database::update</h3>\n<pre>/**<br>* Updates fields specified in $params in $tableName (NOTE spaces and non-alphanumeric characters in field names may cause errors)<br>*<br>* @param string <strong>$tableName</strong> name of table to add records to<br>* @param array <strong>$params</strong> associative array of fieldName=&gt;value<br>* @param mixed <strong>$container_database</strong> the target pef_database_id (must also match value in /config/Conn.php) OR the name of a container linked to a database via pef_table_id or pef_sql_id<br>* @param string <strong>$where</strong>&nbsp;(optional) SQL criteria string without the WHERE keyword<br>* @param string <strong>$auditTrail</strong>&nbsp;(optional) level of detail to store in audit trail table, detail/summary/basic or NULL<br>* @param string&nbsp;<strong>$notes </strong>(optional) are stored in pef_audit_trail record<br>* <br>* @return mixed boolean TRUE on success, or FALSE on error<br>*/<br><br><strong>public static function update($tableName, $params, $container_database, $where=NULL, $auditTrail=null, $notes=null)</strong></pre>\n<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>If a field name in the $params array is prefixed with a <code>#</code>, then the associated value in the array is treated as a SQL expression and not a string value.&nbsp; Example:\n<ul>\n<li>$params = array(\'#notes\' =&gt; "CONCAT(notes, \' hello \', name)");</li>\n<li>$params = array(\'#id\' =&gt; "(SELECT max(id) FROM test_company) + 2");</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>If a field name in the $params array is prefixed with a <code>!</code>, then the associated value in the array is used only in the criteria, and will be excluded from the fields being updated.\n<ul>\n<li>Example, if you have a statement, <strong><code>Database::update(\'test_company\', $params, \'id = :id\');</code>&nbsp; </strong>with $params like this:</li>\n<li>$params = array(\'!id\'=&gt;45, \'notes\'=&gt;\'hello\')&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;\n<ul>\n<li>the SQL that is executed will look like this:</li>\n<li>UPDATE test_company SET notes=:notes WHERE id=:id&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\n<li>using PDO parameters array(\':id\'=&gt;45, \':notes\'=&gt;\'hello\')</li>\n<li>note, id was excluded from the SET clause because of the <code>!</code></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>$params = array(\'id\'=&gt;45, \'notes\'=&gt;\'hello\');&nbsp; // note the ! was removed\n<ul>\n<li>will result in SQL that looks like this:</li>\n<li>UPDATE test_company SET id=:id, notes=:notes WHERE id=:id</li>\n<li>using the same parameters ... note it will have the same effect, but is a bit messy. The <code>!</code> forces the value to be used in criteria only.<span id="selectionBoundary_1535989351303_1715627677329885" class="rangySelectionBoundary"></span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n<pre><em>// Change all notes to a certain fixed value</em><br>$result = Database::update(\'test_company\', array(\'notes\'=&gt;123), \'myForm\');<br><br><em>// Change the name and notes field values for record where id = 1, and log one record in audit trail</em><br><em>// Note the ! used for the id field</em><br>$params = array(\'!id\'=&gt;1, \'name\'=&gt;\'Test\', \'notes\'=&gt;\'testing 123 456\');<br>$result = Database::update(\'test_company\', $params, DIB::$LOGINDB, \'id = :id\', \'summary\');<br><br><em>// Use a SQL expression to change the name values where notes contains \'hello\', and log detailed records in audit trail<br>// Note the # used for the name field</em><br>$params = array(\'#name\'=&gt;"CONCAT(name, \'123\')", \'!notes\'=&gt;\'%hello%\');<br>$result = Database::update(\'test_company\', $params, DIB::$LOGINDB, \'detail\');</pre>\n<h3>Database::delete</h3>\n<pre>/**<br>* Deletes records identified by params and/or a SQL where clause from $tableName (NOTE spaces and non-alphanumeric&nbsp;characters in field names may cause errors)<br>*<br>* @param string <strong>$tableName</strong> name of table to add records to<br>* @param array <strong>$params </strong>null, OR an associative array of PrimaryKeyFieldName=&gt;value that identifies a specific record to be deleted<br>* @param mixed <strong>$container_database</strong> the target pef_database_id (must also match value in /config/Conn.php) OR the name of a container linked to a database via pef_table_id or pef_sql_id<br>* @param string <strong>$where</strong> (optional) SQL criteria string without the WHERE keyword; can make use of params<br>* @param string <strong>$auditTrail</strong>&nbsp;(optional) level of detail to store in audit trail table, detail/summary/basic or NULL<br>* @param string&nbsp;<strong>$notes </strong>(optional) are stored in pef_audit_trail record<br>*<br>* @return mixed boolean TRUE on success, or FALSE on error<br>*/<br><strong>public static function delete($tableName, $params, $container_database, $where=NULL, $auditTrail=null, $notes=null)</strong></pre>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<pre><em>// Delete record where id = 4</em><br>$params = array(\'id\'=&gt;4);<br>$result = Database::delete(\'test_company\', $params, DIB::$LOGINDB);<br><br><em>// Delete the latest record inserted and store detailed records in the audit trail</em><br>$criteria = "id = (SELECT LAST_INSERT_ID())";<br>$result = Database::delete(\'test_company\', null, DIB::$LOGINDB, $criteria, \'detail\');<br><br><em>// Delete all records</em><br>$result = Database::delete(\'test_company\', null, DIB::$LOGINDB);</pre>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc257-dib'),
    (259, 'incl_configsTable', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<table class="dib_table" border="1" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="0"><tbody><tr><th>Name</th><th>Description</th><th>Example in Filter / SQL</th></tr><tr><td><b>alias</b></td><td>Values of items that have an alias (pef_item.alias=1).<br/>For <b>subcontainer </b>components, the primary key values of the record in the child container (if present) is returned.</td><td>:alias_parent_company_id</td></tr><tr><td><b>checked</b></td><td>All the primary key values of records that are checked in either a grid or tree.</td><td><p>:checked_self_0_myPkField<br/>:checked_self_1_myPkField</p></td></tr><tr><td><b>selected</b></td><td>Values of all fields of the last selected record in the target grid or tree.</td><td>:selected_myTreeContainer_id<br/>:selected_myTreeContainer_company_id<br/>:selected_self_name</td></tr><tr><td><b>formData</b></td><td>Values of all fields on a form container.</td><td>:formData_parent_name</td></tr><tr><td><b>pkey</b></td><td>Primary key values of the current record.<br/>Available for container dropin types that have a single current record (eg dibForm).<br/></td><td>:pkey_myContainer_myPk<br/>:pkey_self_id<br/>Â </td></tr><tr><td><b>gridFilter</b></td><td>The filter values as provided by the user in a particular grid\'s filter boxes.</td><td>:gridFilter_self_name<br/>:gridFilter_myContainer_company_id</td></tr><tr><td><b>urlFilter</b></td><td>The filter parameters present in the current URL, eg /nav/myGrid?<b>filter_name=jack&amp;last_name=sprat</b></td><td>:urlFilter_last_name<br/>:urlFilter_age</td></tr><tr><td><b>activeFilter</b></td><td>Name of the active filter on a particular container or subcontainer component. <br/>This name can be used as eg a parameter in <b>Crud::read</b> requests and functions to determine filtering criteria on grids. The Excel Export button requires the config if the export is done from a grid with a filter.</td><td>:activeFilter_myContainer</td></tr><tr><td><b>prompt</b></td><td>The user\'s last reply to the prompt function.</td><td>:prompt</td></tr><tr><td><b>custom</b></td><td>(***due soon) custom value set by developer, eg SetCustomData?xxx=:alias_parent_id&amp;yyy=123 </td><td>:custom_xxx<br/>:custom_yyy</td></tr></tbody></table>', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc259-dib'),
    (260, 'incl_portWorkings', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<p><b>How do Ports work?</b></p><p>A port record defines both which container to open and where to load it, ie to which item to attach it.<br/><br/>A port record must be created for each item where a container can be attached. Each container must have a default port record which has no alias.<br/>It is activated by a URL of the form: /nav/[containerName].<br/>Secondary port records are distinguished by their aliases and are activated by: /nav/[containerName]/[alias].<br/><br/>A port can also be activated by any event, eg a click event on a button that loads a container in a certain part of the app.<br/>Another frequently used example is a click event on a tab that loads a container within the same tab.<br/>When the &#34;Activate Port Record&#34; field of an item is linked to a port record, this item\'s click event will activate the port.<br/>To enlist other triggers (eg. \'blur\') use Item- or Container Events.<br/><br/><i><span id="selectionBoundary_1583508416407_5524250523028749" class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span>Why the term \'Port\'?<span id="selectionBoundary_1583508416407_1986605851311669" class="rangySelectionBoundary">&#65279;</span></i><br/>A boat (container) can dock at many ports, or a USB device can plug into many ports. <br/>The difference though is that a container can &#34;dock&#34; in many items at the same time, and function independently in each.<br/></p>', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc260-dib'),
