    (289, 'incl_validParams', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<h2>Valid Params</h2>\r\n<p>This is <strong>JSON </strong>object (without the surrounding curly braces {}) specifying the allowed parameters, their default values and the validation to apply to them when iframe templates are merged with the Eleutheria templating engine. Parameters must reference Client Data, URL query parameters, User Parameters or specify constants. For reports, the \'dibSqlPerms\' parameter has a special meaning (see ~nav(dibexReportBasics)~ for details.</p>\r\n<p>Apart from providing default values, Valid Params provides an important security layer acting as a whitelist ensuring that not all parameters are passed on to merge fields in the template. For eg if a hacker were to add <strong>?first_name=someevilcode</strong> to the URL request that generates the template, and <strong>~$delim~fld(first_name)~$delim~</strong> appears in the template as part of JavaScript or HTML attributes, <strong>Valid Params</strong> will block it unless any value is specifically allowed for <strong>first_name</strong>. Furthermore, values are sanitized allowing only certain characters (see below for details).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Specify as JSON encoded "<strong>FIELDNAME" : DEFAULTVALUE </strong>pairs, where:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>FIELDNAME </strong>refers to User Parameters, a (flattened) index name in Client Data, or any other name for hard-coded values</li>\r\n<li><strong>DEFAULTVALUE</strong>&nbsp;is a single value, or an array of the form [DEFAULTVALUE, VALIDATIONTYPE, VALIDATIONMESSAGE] (VALIDATIONMESSAGE is optional).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Valid Params Example</h3>\r\n<pre>\r\n<p>"dibUser_id" : -999,<br>"alias_self_clientId" : -999,<br>"print" : "false",<br>"anotherHardCodedValue" : 5,<br>"alias_self_managerId" : "*required*",<br>"query_params_staffId" : [null, "int"],<br>"alias_self_company_id" : [-999, "int", "Invalid Company. Please try again"],<br>"alias_myContainer_name" : [null, "text", "Only the following characters are allowed in \'Name\': [a-z, A-Z, 0-9, _ .-]"],<br>"alias_parent_name" : ["", "text"],<br>"clickedLast_parent_code" : ["*required*", "/^[a-d0-9]{4,8}$/i", "Code must between 4 and 8 characters long, consisting only of characters [a-d, 0-9]"]</p>\r\n</pre>\r\n<h3>Examples of [FIELDNAME]</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>"alias_self_id"</strong> - the value of the item named \'id\' on the current container (which will be the iframe container).</li>\r\n<li><strong>"alias_parent_company_id"</strong> - the value of the company_id item on the parent container (which contains the iframe via a subcontainer or port).</li>\r\n<li><strong>"clickedLast_parent_id"</strong>&nbsp;- the value of the id field in the last clicked row of the parent grid.</li>\r\n<li>"<strong>alias_myContainer_id" </strong>- the value of the id field on the myContainer container. NOTE, include myContainer in the Configs field of the iframe container so that the Client Data becomes available. See ~nav(dibexClientData)~ or the Configs field help for more info.</li>\r\n<li><strong>"dibUser_company_id"</strong>&nbsp;- the company_id of the currently logged in user. Note, any field in the PHP session is available. See ~nav(dibexPermSegmentDataByUser)~ for more info about adding custom values.</li>\r\n<li><strong>"dib_containerName"</strong> - the name of the current iframe container.</li>\r\n<li><strong>"urlContainerName"</strong> - the name of the container in the current URL, eg xxx in&nbsp; /nav/xxx</li>\r\n<li><strong>"dib_sessionId"</strong> - the user\'s PHP session identifier (do not expose this to other users).</li>\r\n<li><strong>"anyName" : "Peter"</strong> - any hardcoded value can be passed this way, in this case ^anyName^=Peter.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Examples of [DEFAULTVALUE]</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>"John"</strong> - a hardcoded value is passed if no value is supplied.</li>\r\n<li><strong>5</strong> - a hardcoded integer value is passed if no value is supplied.</li>\r\n<li><strong>-999</strong> - a commonly used value. <br>In Eleutheria one can use an if-statement to test for this value to catch values that are not provided.<br>Note, if a number is provided as default and the user provides a non-alpha-numeric value, the default number will be forced as a value.<br><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>This if often used to ensure malicious values are not passed.</strong></span></li>\r\n<li><strong>"*required*"</strong> - a special indicator that if the value is not provided, an error message stating that required values are not provided must always be displayed instead of the processed template. NOTE: passing default values may lead to a better user experience.</li>\r\n<li><strong>null </strong>-&nbsp; a null-value is passed if no value is provided.</li>\r\n<li><strong>"" </strong>-&nbsp; (also) a null-value is passed if no value is provided.</li>\r\n<li><strong>[null, "int"]</strong> - if a value is provided, a generic validation message is displayed if it is not integer instead of the processed template. Else a null-value is passed.</li>\r\n<li><strong>[-999, "dec", "Invalid Amount. Please try again"]</strong> - if a value is provided, the specified validation message is displayed if it is not decimal instead of the processed template. Else -999 is passed.</li>\r\n<li><strong>["", "text"]</strong> - if a value is provided, a generic validation message is displayed if it does not adhere to the following regular expression: <br>/^[a-zA-Z0-9_\\- \\.]/<br>Else null is passed.</li>\r\n<li><strong>["*required*", "/^[a-d0-9]{4,8}$/i", "Code must between 4 and 8 characters long, consisting only of characters [a-d, 0-9]"]</strong> <br>If a value is provided, the specified validation message is displayed if it does not adhere to the specified regular expression.<br>Else an error message is displayed stating that required values are not provided.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<b>Notes:</b>\r\n<li>Back-slashesÂ (\\) in regular expressions must be escaped using a second backslash, eg. "/^\\\\d*\\\\\\\\book$/" matches 2348\\book.</li>\r\n<li>A handy tool to create reqular expression patterns:Â https://regex101.com/</li>\r\n<li>The validation specified above has no effect on sanitization - see notes about <b>GlobalsReplaceList</b> below.\r\n\r\n<h3>Important Security Notes</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The parameter values can be used in Eleutheria templates using the global delimiter ^. Eg <b>^alias_self_staffId^</b>.\r\n<li>Eleutheria will HTML encode these values before they are inserted in the template.\r\n<li>In addition, Eleutheria will strip any but the following characters: [a-zA-Z0-9_-: ] using the regular expression #[^a-zA-Z0-9_\\-\\: ]*#. To overide this, specify your own regular expression value using the <b>GlobalsReplaceList</b> Container Setting record. Characters that have meaning in Eleutheria to avoid are: ^~$delimdb~~$delim~&lt;()\r\n<li>Using merge values in the following contexts could be dangerous if the above stripping is disabled, and proper validation does not block them or ensure they are safe values (eg numbers or restricted text characters):\r\n        <ul>\r\n        <li>As part of JavaScript or outside the HTML body tags</li>\r\n        <li>As part of an HTML element&apos;s attributes</li>\r\n        <li>As part of Eleutheria code or SQL statements (SQL injection)</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Use the Eleutheria <b>param</b> function to mitigate SQL injection.</li>\r\n </ul>\r\nSee ~navdocs(iframe)~ and ~nav(dibexiFrameEleutheria)~ for more info.', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc289-dib'),
    (290, 'incl_aboutPorts', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<p>A port record defines the&nbsp;container to open and where to load it (ie to which item to attach it). <br><br>A container can have multiple port records, ie multiple items it can attach to, even at the same time.</p>\r\n<p>Each container must have a port record where the&nbsp;<strong>alias </strong>field is blank - the default port record.&nbsp;<br>It is activated by a URL of the form: <strong>/nav/[containerName]</strong>. Secondary port records are identified by their aliases and are activated by:&nbsp;<strong>/nav/[containerName]/[alias]</strong>.<br>If a container is loaded via a URL and it is nested in a parent container via a port, the default port record (where the alias is empty) of the parent container is used to load it (and its parent container, etc).</p>\r\n<p>Port records also define how a container is opened, eg as a popup window or not, and whether the URL must change.&nbsp;<br><br>Port records can be activated by an <strong>event</strong>, eg a click event on a button that loads a container in a certain part of the app. <br>A frequently used scenario is the click event on a tab that loads a container within the same tab.<br>When the&nbsp;<strong>"Open Container / Port"</strong> field of an item is linked to a port record, this item\'s click event will activate the port.<br>To enlist other triggers (eg. \'blur\') use Port field (pef_port_id) in Item or Container Events.<br><br><strong>Why the term \'Port\'?</strong><br>A boat (container) can dock at many ports, or a USB device can plug into many ports. <br>The difference though is that a container can "dock" in many items at the same time, and function independently in each.<br><br><br></p>', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc290-dib'),
    (291, 'incl_responseType', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<p>Response Type informs the browser how it must handle the response it gets from the server.<br><strong>Note</strong>, this is only applicable when the client calls server-side code.</p>\r\n<table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 90%;" border="1"><colgroup><col style="width: 18.5808%;"><col style="width: 81.3929%;"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Response Type</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>Description</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>actions</td>\r\n<td>Most common. Used for calling client-side actions like set-value, or server-side code that returns a JSON object that may contain messages or actions.\r\n<br>If no response is received after 60 seconds, a client exception occurs - make use of ~nav(dibexQueues)~ then for long-running code.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>(integer) eg 1500</td>\r\n<td>Used with ~nav(dibexQueue,Queues)~. Instructs the browser to "poll" the server with requests every 1500 milliseconds for any pending actions, like updating a progress bar or displaying a progress message. <br><strong>Submit Url </strong>must contain a call to a server-side controller function that returns actions, and eventually stops the queue.\r\n<br>Note the queue will terminate itself after 10 requests that do not receive any actions. This is adjustable - see the examples for more info.\r\n<br>Also, if a list of actions is sent to the client to execute, any action that is of type \'redirect\' will cause the actions following it to not be executed.\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>redirect</td>\r\n<td>Used for calls to the server that must replace the app in the current tab/window with HTML or another site. Can also be used for downloads, but if an error occurs and the file cannot be returned, the whole app will be replaced with an error message.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>new-tab</td>\r\n<td>Often used for calls to the server that returns a file for downloading since a new tab/browser window opens briefly and then closes when the file is received. Any error message/HTML is displayed in the new tab which circumvents the problem with <strong>redirect </strong>above.<br>Is also used to display HTML in a new tab/browser window.\r\n<br>Note, the server-side programming should respond with the appropriate HTTP headers, which Dropinbase handles if you use eg. <b>DibFunctions::exportFileToClient()</b> for downloads.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>window</td>\r\n<td>Same as new-tab, but content is displayed in popup window instead. Useful for HTML content. The following settings are applied to the window:<br><strong>scrollbars=yes, resizable=yes, status=yes, location=no, toolbar=yes, menubar=no, width=900, height=800</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>basic-window</td>\r\n<td>Same as window, but content is displayed in a more basic popup window with only a close-button. The following settings are applied:<br><strong>scrollbars=no, resizable=no, status=no, location=no, toolbar=no, menubar=no, width=600, height=300, left=100, top=100</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc291-dib'),
    (292, 'incl_sqlPerformance', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<ol>\r\n<li>Ensure best practices are followed in the table design, especially with normalization and indexes.</li>\r\n<li>Consider how your application design can be improved to optimize performance.</li>\r\n<li>Use the latest stable versions of your database engine - they are often significantly faster.</li>\r\n<li>Server architecture\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Enough RAM and CPU\'s allocated to the database engine. Fast SSD drives.</li>\r\n<li>Database engine should be on same physical machine than the webserver (can be in different virtual machines).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>MySQL has many derivatives (eg MariaDb, SkySQL, AuroraDb). Some are significantly faster than others.</li>\r\n<li>Ensure there are enough database connections possible for sites with many concurrent users.</li>\r\n<li>Ensure relevant indexes exist and are utilized by your SQL for joins, where-clauses, group by, ordering, etc.</li>\r\n<li>Use Explain to investigate the query plan and find bottlenecks.</li>\r\n<li>Use AI, eg ChatGPT\'s latest version, to optimize your SQL.</li>\r\n<li>Avoid using slow criteria, eg LIKE \'%xxx%\' (filter_any_part in Dropinbase), instead of LIKE \'xxx%\'.</li>\r\n<li>Avoid RIGHT JOINS - they are normally slower than LEFT JOINS.</li>\r\n<li>Avoid ORDER BY if possible.</li>\r\n<li>Avoid correlated subqueries. Correlated subqueries are run once for each row processed by the outer query penalising performance significantly. Move them to the FROM-clause and use joins to obtain the values.</li>\r\n<li>Use the smallest data types that can correctly store your data.</li>\r\n<li>Consider an archiving strategy for old records where possible.</li>\r\n<li>Implement a custom SQL statement that can be used to get the total count of records - stored in pef_sql.total_count_sql. Investigate the generated CRUD .php file in /dibCode/CONTAINERNAME.</li>\r\n<li>Consider caching data which does not change often. Use the <em>Data Cache Lifetime</em><strong> </strong>field on Pg2 in the Designer.</li>\r\n<li>Identify slow sub-queries in a query with many sub-queries and optimize them.</li>\r\n<li>Consider partitioning tables based on values that are used in criteria. Queries that match certain partitioning criteria can run faster because they need to scan less data.</li>\r\n<li>Consider moving the output of slow sub-queries to a temporary table using a child-query\'s sql_execute_before and sql_execute_after fields.</li>\r\n<li>Consider using an in-memory table for derived data that is accessed often.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>More Info:</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/mysql-reference-manual/0596002653/ch05s02.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/mysql-reference-manual/0596002653/ch05s02.html&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1689250533998000&amp;usg=AOvVaw2cmcFw7U5nGaQ3qkUlGKmZ">https://www.oreilly.com/<wbr>library/view/mysql-reference-<wbr>manual/0596002653/ch05s02.html</a> (older article for MyISAM tables but well written).</p>', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc292-dib'),
    (293, 'incl_fillHeight', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<p><strong>The following settings can be used in any combination with one another, except [forcedSpace].</strong></p>\r\n<p>[additionalSpace]=200</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Will subtract 200px in when it calculates the remaining height of the screen. The effect is that 200px is available for something else below the grid.</li>\r\n<li>Eg. Set&nbsp;<strong>attributes3</strong> to:&nbsp; <code>fill-height [additionalSpace]=200</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>[footerElement]="XXX"</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Add [footerElement]=\'XXX\' to the attributes of another item below the grid, where XXX is any unique name.</li>\r\n<li>Set&nbsp;<strong>attributes3</strong>&nbsp;to:&nbsp; <code>fill-height [footerElement]="XXX"</code></li>\r\n<li>The height of this other item will then be subtracted when it calculates the height. The effect is that other item will have enough space to fully display below the grid (provided there is enough space for both).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>[setProperty]="min-height"</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Instead of setting "height" it will set "min-height", allowing for grids with only a few rows to take less space.</li>\r\n<li>Any valid CSS property can be inserted, eg. "margin-bottom".</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div>[forcedSpace]=250</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Instead of calculating the remaining&nbsp;height, it will set "max-height:250px". Note this will cause the [additionalSpace] and [footerElement] settings to be ignored.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div>[debug]="true"</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Print debug information to the browser Console.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div><strong>Example</strong></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div><strong>&nbsp;</strong></div>\r\n<div>Set&nbsp;<strong>attributes3</strong>&nbsp;to:&nbsp; <code>fill-height [additionalSpace]=200 [setProperty]="min-height" [debug]=true</code></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Will calculate the remaining height left on the screen, subtract 200px from it, and then set min-height to this value. Debug info will be printed to the browser\'s Console.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc293-dib'),
    (294, 'Validation', 261, 45, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc294-dib'),
    (295, 'incl_parentAndSqlInsertFieldsConfiguration', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Important: first ensure the container is based on a table, and the <strong>Model </strong>field is set to \'Table\'.&nbsp;<br></span>After any changes, clear the container\'s generated code.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Notes:&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>use the&nbsp;<strong>View SQL</strong> button under Container Details to view a grid\'s (or form\'s) underlying SQL.</li>\r\n<li>on grids, bound fields must be child-items of the contentFor/columns item.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Table Fields</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Drag-and-drop a field from the <strong>Field List </strong>in the Components Tree. The <strong>Field </strong>field must contain a field in the container\'s table.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Important: the item name and field name must be the same! This restriction enables the working of Table Events.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Parent Fields</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Drag-and-drop a field from the <strong>Parent Fields</strong> List in the Components Tree. The <strong>Field </strong>field must contain a field in one of the parent tables.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">The <strong>Parent Table Link</strong> field will contain the name of the foreign key field that links the two tables. <br>See the help in the Designer related to this field for more info.<br>(Remember to update it if you manually make breaking changes).</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">This <strong>Parent Table Link</strong> field(belonging to the container\'s table) must be included as an item, even if it is hidden, else errors will occur when users update fields.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">LIMITATIONS</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">the item name of parent fields must differ from any field (not item) name in the container&apos;s table. Errors will occur otherwise.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">the <strong>Field</strong>-field must reference a field in a direct parent table of the form\'s table.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>SQL Insert Fields</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Set the&nbsp;<strong>Expr Type</strong> field to \'<strong>sql insert</strong>\' which is used by the framework to identify these fields.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Set the <strong>Expression</strong> field to any valid SQL. Note, t</span><span style="font-family: Arial;">he container\'s underlying SQL statement can be viewed in the Designer (View SQL button) and extended using the <strong>Extra Table Join</strong>&nbsp;field under&nbsp;<strong>Container Details</strong>.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Remember that for forms and editable grids, any joins should still result in only one record being returned per main table primary key value. If not, the first record will be used.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">These fields are not updateable. Use the <strong>sqlText </strong>Data Component to display their values.</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><span style="font-family: Arial;">Troubleshooting</span></h2>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">If a table, field or parent field is not visible, it may not be imported into Dropinbase yet. Use the App Wizard or /nav/dibDatabaseGrid -&gt; form to import new tables / fields.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">If the field is imported, refresh the Components Tree and try again.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">&nbsp;</span></p>', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc295-dib'),
    (296, 'Basic', 338, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<ul>\n<li>~navdocs(Setup Dropinbase, docs, Install and Configure Dropinbase)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Create a Development Environment)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Build a Database, docs, Build a Database - if you don\'t already have one)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Build My Apps, docs, Generate an Application and Make Basic Adjustments)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Customize Containers, docs, Customize Containers in Detail)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Base Containers, docs, Learn about Base Containers)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Ports, docs, Learn about Port Records)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Create New Containers)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Handle Changes to Table and Query Designs)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Permissions Overview, docs, Configure Permissions)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Troubleshooting and Debugging, docs, Troubleshooting)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Deploying Applications, docs, Deploy to Production)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Hotfixing Production)~</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Not required for this level, but you may also want to learn about:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Styling the Application and Login Pages</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Security, docs, Tightening Security)~</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Test</h2>\n<p>Build a fully production-ready web-application with Dropinbase. The following are minimal requirements. <br><strong>Note, do not present copies of the existing examples - all work must be original and your own.</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Install Dropinbase on a public webserver</li>\n<li>Create a user database with 5 tables (or more) which includes one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships.</li>\n<li>Build a Dropinbase web application to view and edit records in all these tables. The following features must be present:</li>\n<ol>\n<li>A collapsible "slide-in" menu.</li>\n<li>Forms which contain grids displaying related records (with filters) using both subcontainers and ports.</li>\n<li>Grid(s) based on a SQL statement, and which is loaded with a port, and also displaying related records using a filter.</li>\n<li>Certain, not all, grids that have related (filtered) data must be editable. Their foreign-key values must be filled in by default.</li>\n<li>Certain, not all, grids and forms must have a parent field.</li>\n<li>At least one window/popup form used for editing records.</li>\n<li>Some dropdowns must be based on SQL queries.</li>\n<li>Ability to upload and store files against records.</li>\n<li>A date field on a form must have a default date of today on new records.</li>\n<li>Server- and client-side validation on certain fields.</li>\n</ol>\n<li>Create at least two new permission groups, with at least one new user linked to each.\n<ol>\n<li>The first new user must not have Dropinbase design rights, but must otherwise have full permissions on the web application.</li>\n<li>The second new user must have view rights on most containers, and update and create rights on certain containers, and delete rights on only a few.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Demonstrate your understanding of the following used for styling, positioning and sizing elements:\n<ol>\n<li>The grey fields in the Designer under Item details.</li>\n<li>The green fields in the Designer under Item details.</li>\n<li>Responsiveness of forms (not grids) to work on mobile devices too.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Other features:\n<ol>\n<li>Create a button that calls a client-side action to set the value of an item on a different container</li>\n<li>Demonstrate your understanding of the basic use of *ngIf, [dibDisabled] and [hidden]</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc296-dib'),
    (297, 'Reset Dropinbase', 116, 10, 0, 'none', '<p>"Resetting" Dropinbase often helps to restore functionality since it ensures core configurations for the framework are in place.</p>\n<p>Simply delete the&nbsp;<strong>/runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt</strong> file, or even the whole <strong>/runtime </strong>folder, and then reload the site, or execute any action that calls the core framework.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase will perform the following actions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>create the /runtime folder and any of its sub-folders that should exist</li>\n<li>create /configs/Dib.php if it does not exist (using the <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> file as template)</li>\n<li>recreate all active permission records in the <em>pef_perm_active </em>tables</li>\n<li>run any outstanding Migration Scripts (stored in <strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/Migration Scripts.dtxt</strong>) <br>and update <strong>pef_setting </strong>-&gt; dibDatabaseVersion record</li>\n<li>scan for new dropin folders and add missing records to the <strong>pef_dropin</strong> table</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc297-dib'),
    (298, 'Multi-Tenant Setup', 105, 100, 0, 'none', '<p>A multi-tenant setup is where one Dropinbase core is used by many client apps.</p>\n<h3><strong>Option A</strong></h3>\n<p>The easiest and most maintainable method is using symbolic links / virtual folders:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Store the /vendor folder anywhere that the webserver has access to\n<ul>\n<li>the /vendor folder contains the third-party projects (of which Dropinbase is one) installed with Composer.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Create the www/projectFolder/vendor folder as a symbolic link (see below) that points to the /vendor folder mentioned in the first step.</li>\n<li>Repeat for www/projectFolder2/vendor, www/projectFolder3/vendor etc.</li>\n<li>Delete the various project\'s /runtime folders so that they are recreated</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Creating Symbolic Links:</strong></p>\n<p>For&nbsp;<strong>Windows</strong>, the following Windows Explorer extension works well:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://schinagl.priv.at/nt/hardlinkshellext/linkshellextension.html">https://schinagl.priv.at/nt/hardlinkshellext/linkshellextension.html</a></li>\n<li>Right-click -&gt; <strong>Pick Link Source</strong> on the (source) vendor folder</li>\n<li>Right-click -&gt; <strong>Drop As</strong> -&gt; <strong>Symbolic Link</strong> on all the project folders (eg www/myDibProject)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>On <strong>Linux </strong>use the command:</p>\n<p><code>ln -s SOURCEFOLDER NEWVIRTUALFOLDER</code></p>\n<h3>Option B</h3>\n<p>Alternatively edit the following files, forcing them to use the new location of the Dropinbase core:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>/index.php - reference to the /vendor folder</li>\n<li>/configs/DibTmpl.php - remove the merge fields and hard-code all references to the /vendor folder</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Then delete the various project\'s /runtime folders so that they are recreated.</p>\n<p>This option can be used in conjunction with a \'currentVendorFolder\' Symbolic Link if the /vendor folder\'s location is updated periodically, eg. with each new release.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc298-dib'),
    (299, 'Shared Hosting Servers', 105, 90, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Dropinbase works well on shared hosts :).</p>\n<p>The steps are basically to get the whole system working on your local machine where you have root access.</p>\n<p>Then:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Create the website folder on the shared host.</li>\n<li>Copy your project folder, which includes the <strong>/vendor</strong> folder, across to the new website\'s root folder.\n<ol>\n<li>The <strong>/vendor</strong> folder can be in any location, as long at the webserver can access it and the <strong>include_once()</strong> statement in the <strong>/index.php </strong>file references the new location.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Create the dropinbase database, and any other databases you\'ve installed locally, on the shared host.</li>\n<li>Edit the <strong>Conn.php</strong> file. Ensure connection details are correct and that the array indexes in the <strong>Conn.php</strong> file match the values of the \'<strong>id</strong>\' fields in the&nbsp;<em>pef_database </em>table.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Some more notes</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Follow the ~navdocs(Troubleshooting Installation)~ steps if there are any errors. Particularly check the contents of error logs and responses from network requests in the browser console.</li>\n<li>It may be necessary to set $CODEUSE&lt;=2 in&nbsp;<strong>Dib.php</strong> initially to ensure all /dibCode files are created.</li>\n<li>Ensure folder permissions are set (see ~navdocs(File System Settings)~ for more info).</li>\n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc299-dib'),
    (300, 'Troubleshooting Installation', 105, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Note, after applying a fix below, delete the&nbsp;<strong>/www/projectFolder/runtime</strong> folder before testing further.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Review the ~navdocs(Installation Checklist)~ for anything you may have missed.</li>\n<li><strong>Delete the /www/projectFolder/runtime folder</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>When either of the <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> or <strong>/runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt</strong> files do not exist, Dropinbase goes through an initialization process where it creates the Dib.php file and any missing folders under <strong>/runtime</strong> and recreates all active permission entries in the above tables (for more info, see the point below for Permission log entries).</li>\n<li>Refresh the website. If there are still problems, continue working through these steps.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Check error logs</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>Dropinbase stores errors in the&nbsp;<em>pef_error_log </em>table by default. If it cannot write to the table, errors are written to the <strong>/runtime/logs/error.log </strong>file instead.</li>\n<li>Also check the webserver, PHP and operating system error logs (eg <strong>/var/log/apache2/</strong>...)</li>\n<li>If no errors are displaying, set the <code>display_errors</code>&nbsp;setting in <strong>php.ini</strong> temporarily (security risk!).</li>\n<li><strong>Note</strong>: normally the first error listed is also the source of other errors.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>The webserver is not starting</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>Check whether another service on the current machine uses the same port (eg Skype could be using port 8080).\n<ol>\n<li>Check the webserver and the operating system\'s error/event logs for any indications.</li>\n<li>Terminate any suspect service and try again.</li>\n<li>If your webserver uses a custom port, eg 81, then edit the virtual host file entry to match this port. Remember to use the port in URL\'s, eg http://myapp.dib:81</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>The webserver configuration file has an error (eg httpd.conf for Apache and nginx.conf for Nginx)\n<ol>\n<li>Check the webserver and the operating system\'s error/event logs for any indications.</li>\n<li>Attempt to restart the webserver with each change made.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>A webserver module or PHP extension may not be properly configured or they may reference a file (eg a .dll) that does not match the operating system.&nbsp;\n<ol>\n<li>Remove any references to suspect modules or extensions one-by-one and try starting the webserver again until the problem is found.</li>\n<li>Consult search engines from there for your specific version of PHP and webserver.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Can Dropinbase connect to the database server?</strong>&nbsp;\n<ol>\n<li>The <strong>/runtime/logs/error.log</strong> file will list the error.</li>\n<li>Check that the values of <strong>$DBINDEX</strong> and <strong>$LOGINDB</strong> in the <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> file correspond with the <em>id </em>values in the <em>pef_database </em>table and with the index values in the <strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong> file.</li>\n<li>See <strong>/configs/Example_Conn.php</strong> to check whether the syntax of entries in <strong>Conn.php</strong> are correct.</li>\n<li>Check that the database server is running. Use a tool like HeidiSql to connect (<a href="https://www.heidisql.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">www.heidisql.com</a>) using the same credentials as setup in the <strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong> file.</li>\n<li>Establish if the credentials used in <strong>/configs/Conn.php </strong>has rights to read/write the dropinbase database tables.</li>\n<li>See ~navdocs(Connecting to Databases)~ for more info.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>There are errors in /runtime/logs/Permissions.log (also available in the Designer).</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>You may have been logged out&nbsp; - log in again.</li>\n<li>A request was made that violates the permission rules. Most requests have a containerName parameter. <br>If this container does not exist in the active permission tables <em>(pef_perm_active </em>and <em>pef_perm_active_list)</em>, a permission error will result.&nbsp;\n<ol>\n<li>Has the container been deleted?&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Rebuild all permissions (use the green button in the Designer) and try again.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>If the above does not resolve the issue, this is normally an indication that Dropinbase could not populate the active permission tables<em>.</em>\n<ol>\n<li>Delete the <strong>/www/projectFolder/runtime </strong>folder (see the first main point above). This will recreate permission records for all containers, including containers in dropins of which&nbsp;the <strong>dibCode </strong>files exist, but not the original design records. Dropinbase ships with the <strong>dibCode </strong>files of the Designer and other admin pages, but not with their design records.</li>\n<li>To identify the dropins that have these <strong>dibCode </strong>files (but not the design records) the <strong>pef_dropin_cache_db_id </strong>field in <strong>pef_dropin&nbsp;</strong>must be set. It references the database which these containers must be linked to (note, for the admin pages it is the main Dropinbase database).&nbsp;</li>\n<li>By default <strong>dibAdmin (setNgxMaterial)</strong> is listed, which means the permission records stored in the following file are incorporated: <strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/setNgxMaterial/dibAdmin/dibCode/_permFiles/setNgxMaterial_dibAdmin.dtxt</strong></li>\n<li>Ensure this file (and others listed) exists, and contains all the necessary records.</li>\n<li>Ensure the <strong>pef_dropin_cache_db_id&nbsp;</strong>field points to the main Dropinbase database record for the <strong>dibAdmin (setNgxMaterial)</strong> dropin record, and any other suppliers\' records are also set.</li>\n<li>Delete the <strong>/runtime</strong> folder and refresh the website and check again for errors in all the logs.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Check the browser Developer Tools for any errors</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>In the browser, open the Developer Tools (press F12 on Chrome)</li>\n<li>Refresh the website.</li>\n<li>Check the Console-tab for errors.</li>\n<li>Click on the Network-tab, and then on all the requests. For each, check the Preview-tab (under the Network-tab) for errors.</li>\n<li>Except for errors, any missing requests may also indicate a problem.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>The website is not working properly</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>(Linux/Mac only): ensure the webserver has the necessary permissions to read/write files where needed (see ~navdocs(File System Settings)~ for more info).</li>\n<li>Ensure that the virtual host file entry for dropinbase specifies the same port number (eg 80 or 81) that your webserver is using.</li>\n<li>Restart the webserver.</li>\n<li>Run the Dropinbase intialization process:\n<ol>\n<li>Ensure your <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> file configuration is correct.</li>\n<li>Delete the <strong>/www/myProject/runtime</strong> folder and refresh the website.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Check all the error logs (see above) for any clues.</li>\n<li>Check that the necessary webserver and PHP settings are enabled and working:\n<ol>\n<li>If you have Composer installed, run the following in a terminal window (eg Powershell on Windows) to view installed PHP extensions:&nbsp;\n<ol>\n<li><code>cd /www/myProject</code></li>\n<li><code>composer show --platform</code></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Alternatively:\n<ol>\n<li>Uncomment the following line in <strong>/www/myProject/index.php</strong>:&nbsp;<code>phpinfo(); die();</code></li>\n<li>Navigate to your site\'s url, eg <strong>http://myapp.dib/</strong> or <strong>http://localhost/projectFolderName</strong>.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Review&nbsp;~navdocs(Apache Settings)~ and ~navdocs(PHP Settings)~</li>\n<li>Remember to undo any changes to index.php before commencing.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Check that<strong> .htaccess</strong> file (in the root folder), and the webserver\'s virtual host file settings are in place and are correct.</li>\n<li>(PHP &lt;7.1): On Windows, <strong>libeay32.dll</strong> and <strong>ssleay32.dll</strong> needs to be accessible through the PATH environment variable for <strong>php_curl.dll</strong> to work. Add <strong>c:/php</strong> (your PHP folder) and restart Windows.</li>\n<li>Use the latest long term stable releases of PHP and your webserver.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>The system fails to load after the Installer executed the installation steps:</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>Check that the dropinbase database has been created successfully. If not, you can manually create the database using the manual steps above.</li>\n<li>Open /www/myProject/index.php\n<ol>\n<li><code>include_once("./installer.php"); die();</code> - line must be commented out</li>\n<li>\n<div>\n<div><code>include_once("./vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/index.php"); die();</code>&nbsp; - line must be active</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Navigate to the application, eg http://myapp.dib&nbsp; - if it does not work, continue with the troubleshooting procedure below.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>The webserver/Dropinbase cant read/write files or execute PHP scripts:</strong>\n<ol>\n<li>Certain folders don\'t have the necessary read/write permissions. Normally not a problem on Windows.</li>\n<li>See ~navdocs(File System Settings)~ for more info.&nbsp;</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Further help: </strong>if the problem is still unresolved, please make use of the Community Forum or official support on <a href="https://www.dropinbase.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.dropinbase.com</a>.</li>\n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc300-dib'),
    (301, 'Build a Database', 333, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>If <strong>you are an experienced database designer</strong>, you can skip this topic.</p>\n<p>Web applications have three basic layers:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>the user-interface</strong> - what the user works with</li>\n<li><strong>the server-side code / "logic layer"</strong> - eg the PHP-code that executes user requests</li>\n<li><strong>a database</strong> - that stores data and executes queries</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The structure of the underlying database of an application is like the foundations and walls of a house. A good design facilitates an efficient and maintainable system, while the converse is true for a bad design.</p>\n<p>In its simplest form, a database contains one or more tables (eg <strong>tbClient</strong>), each containing fields (eg <strong>first_name</strong>, <strong>last_name</strong>, etc). If you learn about creating tables with primary keys, foreign-keys (relationships) and indexes you can be well on your way to build databases for functional web applications.</p>\n<p><strong>Basic Steps to Get Going:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Read these topics: ~navdocs(Relational Database Theory)~ and ~navdocs(Strict Naming Conventions)~ and ~navdocs(Prime the Database Design)~</li>\n<li>Install a local database like <a href="https://www.mariadbtutorial.com/getting-started/install-mariadb/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MariaDb</a> (or rather a full stack install, <a href="http://www.wampserver.com/en/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WAMP</a>/LAMP, if you are not using the Docker install of Dropinbase).</li>\n<li>Use an application like <a href="https://www.heidisql.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HeidiSQL </a>&nbsp;or <a href="https://dbeaver.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">DBeaver </a>to interface with it. By default, use \'localhost\' as host, \'root\' as username and a blank password to connect.</li>\n<li>Create a new database and execute the <strong>/installer/dropinbase.sql</strong> script that is distributed with Dropinbase.</li>\n<li>Study the <strong>test_</strong> example tables. Start a discussion with an AI chatbot about primary keys, foreign-keys (relationships) and indexes.</li>\n<li>Now create your own database with tables and relationships. NOTE: use the InnoDb table engine in MySQL, else you will not be able to create foreign key constraints (relationships) between tables.</li>\n<li>Learn about basic SQL statements, like SELECT, UPDATE, INSERT, DELETE at <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/sql/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.w3schools.com/sql/</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Building a well-structured relational database for large applications requires experience, and in-depth understanding of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Relational Database Theory</li>\n<li>Normalization</li>\n<li>Entity Relationship Diagrams</li>\n<li>SQL (Structured Query Language)</li>\n<li>Full Stack Development</li>\n</ul>\n<p>There are many online courses teaching professional database design for free:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/office/database-design-basics-eb2159cf-1e30-401a-8084-bd4f9c9ca1f5</li>\n<li>https://www.classcentral.com/course/relational-database-12430</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc301-dib'),
    (302, 'Customize Login and Authentication', 39, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3>Override dibAuthenticate</h3>\n<p>If you need to alter business rules for authentication then override the <strong>dibAuthenticate </strong>dropin.</p>\n<p>Simply copy the&nbsp;<strong>dibAuthenticate </strong>folder with all its contents to your project\'s own <strong>dropins </strong>folder:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>cd /www/myProject</code></li>\n<li><code>cp /vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/dibAuthenticate ./dropins</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Now that it is part of your own project, any changes overides any of Dropinbase\'s default code, and is stored along with your other code.\n<br>Note, you can override any Dropinbase core dropin in the same way.\n</p>\n<h3>Customize the Login Pages</h3>\n<p>The pages used to facilitate login (eg. login, forgot my password, reset password, etc) are all common HTML / PHP pages.</p>\n<p>The user-interface design is stored in the following sub-folders of <strong>/dropins/dibAuthenticate</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>/views</strong> - the HTML / PHP</li>\n<li><strong>/css</strong> - the styling</li>\n<li><strong>/images</strong> - any images</li>\n</ul>\n<p>But you can alter it anyway you wish.</p>\n<p>You could include the necessary fields in the design of other applications so that users can login from there.</p>\n<h3>Security Policies</h3>\n<p>Every user\'s login record is linked to a <em>pef_security_policy </em>record where various field values determine the level of security.<br>See ~navdocs(pef_security_policy,table,Security Policy Table)~ for more info.</p>\n<h3>Change Authentication Business Logic</h3>\n<p>All requests are routed to the <strong>/controllers/SiteController.php </strong>script. This script in turns calls functions in the <strong>/components/Authenticator.php</strong> script.</p>\n<p><strong>IMPORTANT:</strong> any changes to these files must not compromise security. If in doubt, consult an expert.<br>What may not be obvious is that error messages returned by the script to the user are purposefully made the same.<br>For eg. if a user gets their username or password incorrect the wording of the response in both cases is the same.<br>This way hackers never know if they are making progress.</p>\n<p>The login function in the <strong>Authenticator.php </strong>file is where the business logic for authentication resides.</p>\n<p>Alter this where necessary but, again, be very careful with changes.</p>\n<p>If the user passes all authentication tests, the <code>logUserIn()</code> function is called.<br>This function creates a PHP session containing parameter values for the user.<br>These parameter values are very useful in your custom Dropinbase PHP code and SQL queries. The available parameter values can be customized by editing the <strong>/configs/DibUserParams.php</strong> file.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc302-dib'),
    (303, 'Customize Containers', 21, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Apply Bulk Customizations</h2>\n<p>The ~nav(dibContainerFeature)~ tool is useful to apply bulk changes to selected containers. When you first open a Dropinbase generated app there will be a link to open this tool which will also automatically select your base container.</p>\n<p>Features are stored under Categories and Sub-categories, and can be applied to specific containers, or containers linked to tables, depending on how the script is configured (see help for more info).</p>\n<p>The tool uses pre-defined SQL scripts stored in the <i>pef_script</i> table. Developers can add their own scripts for users.</p>\n<h2>Use the Designer</h2>\n<p>The Designer is the main tool used to design applications. It has many features to facilitate development and reduce slog-work. Keep it handy in a separate browser tab/window.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>A container\'s layout is reflected in a tree structure of items. By using drag-and-drop, items of various component-types can be added, and containers can be nested with optional filters. Container and item-properties can be set and other configuration-changes can be made, such as adding events and permissions on container or item level.</p>\n<p>The Designer is intuitive to learn by experimentation. The following images provides some basic guidance of the mean features. Also note the Help slider (under More Help) which displays inline help.</p>\n<p><img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/DesignerHelp.png" alt=""></p>\n<p>Learning Dropinbase is best done through studying ~navdocs(Learn By Example, docs, examples)~ and experimentation, with the assistance of the available context-sensitive help.&nbsp;<br>Click the Help-toggle in the Designer and hover over buttons and Item Tree headings. <br>Also click on fields in the Designer and then the help-icon (see <strong>Last-clicked Field Help</strong> above) to view detailed information.</p>\n<p>Changes to Designer fields are automatically stored, unlike in other Admin pages eg <strong>/nav/dibSqlForm</strong>. <br>The Audit Trail-buttons show the history of changes and provides the ability to revert if necessary. Note, reverting is only available for updates - deletes and inserts will follow shortly.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Dropinbase also automatically clears a container\'s generated code and active permission records after each change and notifies the user via a \'toast\'-message. <br>Some changes, like name changes or linking buttons to ports, may affect other containers and then manual clearning is required. See ~navdocs(Generating and Clearing Generated Code)~.</p>\n<p>Note, each container type (eg grid/form/plain) and feature (eg servers-side actions or item permissions) requires certain attributes to be in place with the correct syntax to be functional.<br>Dropinbase builds containers/pages by merging the contents of fields "as-is" into templates. Incorrect syntax will lead to compile errors or bugs, in either the generated client-side or server-side code. <br>View the Error log for details, and refer to the examples for the correct syntax. Also view the Trouble-shooting guide to help find the source of bugs.</p>\n<p>On drag-and-drop actions, Dropinbase assists with populating attributes, but with manual updates it is best to make smaller incremental changes with testing inbetween, until you have gained experience. <br>Remember to use the <b>UI-Include</b> and <b>CRUD-Include</b> fields to temporarily remove items to isolate the source of bugs.</p>\n<p>View the examples under ~navdocs(Container Types)~ for detailed information.</p>\n<h2>Updating Design Tables Directly</h2>\n<p>The design of a Dropinbase application is stored in a well-structured database that is fairly straight-forward to understand.&nbsp;<br>Container attributes are stored in <strong>pef_container</strong>, item attributes are stored in <strong>pef_item </strong>etc. Foreign-key fields are generally named after the primary table they reference.<br>By editing these tables directly or with SQL, developers can quickly and easily make design changes to applications.<br>Remember to ~navdocs(Generating and Clearing Generated Code, docs, clear generated code)~ before testing changes.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc303-dib'),
    (304, 'Create New Containers', 21, 10, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc304-dib'),
    (305, 'Create New Grids', 304, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3>Requirements for all grids</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Container Type = \'grid\'</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Model = Table/Sql. Also select a Table or SQL record accordingly.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Grid containers must have a <strong>contentFor</strong> component named \'<strong>columns</strong>\'. Any grid column fields can only be child items of this item. Other than this, grid containers can have any layout.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Grids based on tables must have a primary key, </span><span style="font-family: Arial;">and the primary key must be an item under <strong>columns </strong>in the grid (even if it is hidden). <br>If selecting records is required for a grid based on SQL, it must have a field with name/alias \'id\', or the Primary Field in the record must indicate the name/alias of the column that uniquely identifies each record.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">If the grid is used to update records, it must contain all required fields under <strong>columns </strong>(even if they are hidden).</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Ways to create grids</span></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Create grids (and forms) </span>&nbsp;for all or a selection of your tables is by using the&nbsp;<strong>~nav(wizBuildApp,App Wizard)~</strong>.</li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">~nav(dibDatabaseGrid,Database Tasks)~ - similar to the App Wizard, but has more options (eg. refresh indexes/relationships and remove specific tables and related containers).</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Using the <strong>+Container</strong>&nbsp;button in the Components tree in the Designer and dragging the grid chip onto an existing container,&nbsp;<br></span>where the new grid must be attached via a button or tab.</li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Dragging a query or table under the Components tree -&gt; Databases in the&nbsp;</span><strong>~nav(dibDesigner,Designer)~</strong>.</li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">(SQL Grids) Using the&nbsp;<strong>Tools -&gt; Create Grid</strong> button under&nbsp;</span><strong>~nav(dibSqlGrid)~&nbsp;-&gt; form</strong>.</li>\n<li>(SQL Grids) Queries can be imported in bulk. First export a list of (filtered) queries to see the required format, then import your queries using the same format under&nbsp;<strong>~nav(dibSqlGrid)~&nbsp;-&gt; Tools-menu.</strong></li>\n<li>Using the<strong>&nbsp;+&nbsp;</strong>button under<strong>&nbsp;Container Details</strong>&nbsp;in the Designer to create one from scratch.<br><span style="font-family: Arial;">Then d</span>rag-and-drop the relevant&nbsp; <strong>Grid&nbsp;Layout&nbsp;</strong>under&nbsp;<strong>Reusables&nbsp;</strong>in the Components tree to insert common items used on grids.</li>\n<li>Duplicating an existing grid and modifying it - not recommended if the grid is linked to a different table<br>since it\'s easy to miss a relic bound field belonging to the source grid which will cause errors.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>General notes</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Ensure that at least one Port record for your new container exists and correctly defines where it must be loaded. Note, port records are not needed if the container is only ever loaded in a subcontainer.</li>\n<li>Both the<strong>&nbsp;App Wizard</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>+Container</strong>&nbsp;button creates containers based on predefined templates,<br>which can be configured under&nbsp;<strong>~nav(dibDesignGrid)~&nbsp;-&gt; form</strong> -&gt; click&nbsp;<strong>Design Container</strong>.</li>\n<li>Remember to ~navdocs(Generating and Clearing Generated Code, docs, clear the container dibCode files)~ before testing changes to it.</li>\n<li>Bulk changes can be applied to containers by using ~nav(dibContainerFeature)~.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc305-dib'),
    (306, 'Create New Forms', 304, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Requirements for all forms</span></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Container Type = form</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Model = Table. Also select a Table.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">The table must have a primary key and the primary key must be an item on the form (even if it is hidden).</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">If the form is used to update records, it must contain all required fields (even if they are hidden).</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Ways to create forms</span></h3>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Create forms (and grids)&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;for all or a selection of your tables is by using the&nbsp;<strong>~nav(wizBuildApp,App Wizard)~</strong>.\n<ul>\n<li>The same functionality (and more) is under ~nav(dibDatabaseGrid, Database Tasks)~</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Using the&nbsp;<strong>+Container</strong> button in the Components tree in the Designer and dragging the form chip onto an existing container,&nbsp;<br></span>where the new form must be attached via a button or tab.</li>\n<li>Using the<strong> + </strong>button under<strong> Container Details</strong> in the Designer to create one from scratch. <br><span style="font-family: Arial;">Then d</span>rag-and-drop the <strong>Form Layout&nbsp;</strong>under <strong>Reusables </strong>in the Components tree to insert common items used on forms.</li>\n<li>Duplicating an existing form and modifying it - not recommended if the form is linked to a different table<br>since it\'s easy to miss a relic bound field belonging to the source&nbsp;form which will cause errors.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>General notes</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Ensure that at least one Port record for your new container exists and correctly defines where it must be loaded. Note, port records are not needed if the container is only ever loaded in a subcontainer.</li>\n<li>Both the<strong>&nbsp;App Wizard</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>+Container</strong>&nbsp;button creates containers based on predefined templates,<br>which can be configured under&nbsp;<strong>~nav(dibDesignGrid)~&nbsp;-&gt; form</strong> -&gt; click&nbsp;<strong>Design Container</strong>.</li>\n<li>Remember to ~navdocs(Generating and Clearing Generated Code, docs, clear the container dibCode files)~ before testing changes to it.</li>\n<li>Bulk changes can be applied to containers by using ~nav(dibContainerFeature)~.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc306-dib'),
    (307, 'Generating and Clearing Generated Code', 21, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Code Generation</h2>\n<p>Dropinbase generates code and ~navdocs(Permissions Overview, docs, active permission records)~ on the fly when it does not exist. <br>Alternatively, all code ~navdocs(Generating Files, docs, can be generated in bulk)~ which is useful for deployment to production servers where write-permissions are limitted.</p>\n<p>Generated code for each container is stored in <strong>/dropins/[MODULE-DROPIN]/dibCode/[CONTAINERNAME]</strong> where [MODULE-DROPIN] is the Module Dropin a container is linked to. <br>Shared code, such as dropdown lists, actions and components is stored in specific <strong>dibCode </strong>sub-folders, eg <strong>/_lists</strong>, <strong>/_components</strong> and <strong>/_actions</strong>.</p>\n<p>Code is generated very specifically for each user <strong>~navdocs(Permgroups, docs, permgroup)~ </strong>(the unique combinations of permission groups that users belong to). For example, if a <strong>permgroup </strong>has no update rights on a certain field, then the code to update the field is not generated.</p>\n<h2>Clear Generated Code and Active Permission Records</h2>\n<p>If changes are made in the Designer, Dropinbase mostly automatically removes the generated code and active permission records of the current container and informs you of the fact.&nbsp;<br>However, sometimes changes affect other containers linked with ports etc. and then manual removal of the code of those containers may be needed to reflect changes.</p>\n<p>Clearing generated code can be done manually by:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>deleting the generated files or folders (for example <strong>/dropins/main/dibCode</strong>), OR</li>\n<li>by using the <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/remove_files.svg"> button in the Item Tree or under Container Details, OR</li>\n<li>by using the menu-button in the top-right corner of the Designer</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To clear active permission records manually, delete the relevant records in the following tables: <em>pef_perm_active, pef_perm_item_list_active, pef_perm_field_active,</em> or delete <strong>/runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt</strong> file to regenerate all permissions and run other initialization functions.</p>\n<p>Alternatively use the green <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/settings_backup_restore.svg"> button under Container Details to recreate a specific container\'s dibCode files for ALL related permgroups (this takes longer).&nbsp;<br>These two buttons also clear the related active permission records.</p>\n<p>Also see ~navdocs(Remove Unneeded Design Records)~</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc307-dib'),
    (308, 'Handle Changes to Table and Query Designs', 21, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Handle Table Design Changes</h2>\n<p>If the design of a container\'s underlying table (fields, indexes and relationships) changes, then use the&nbsp;<strong>Detect Outstanding Tasks</strong>&nbsp;button under&nbsp;<strong>/nav/dibDatabaseGrid -&gt; Tasks</strong>&nbsp;-&gt;&nbsp;<strong>Table Tasks</strong>-tab to view changes, and set options how to handle them in Dropinbase.</p>\n<p>Choose a Task for each change detected. If a new table was added, check/uncheck the Create Grid and Create Form tasks.</p>\n<p>If fields were added or removed, the available options are:</p>\n<p><strong>New Database Fields Tasks</strong></p>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>leave new fields outside DIB</td>\n<td>Do not import the new table fields that are listed in the Notice column.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>import new fields to DIB</td>\n<td>Add the new fields listed in the Notice column to the Dropinbase tables (only).&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>import new fields &amp; add to Containers</td>\n<td>Add the new fields listed in the Notice column to the Dropinbase tables. <strong>Also add items, linked to these fields, to all containers that are based on the current table.</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><strong>Missing (Removed) Database Fields Tasks</strong>&nbsp;</p>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>IGNORE!</td>\n<td>Ignore fields found in Dropinbase tables that are not in the current table.<strong> Warning - will probably cause errors!</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>remove fields from DIB</td>\n<td>Remove the missing/extra fields completely from Dropinbase tables and containers etc.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Then use the <strong>Tasks Menu</strong> to execute tasks for Fields, Relationships or Indexes (depending on what has changed).</p>\n<p>Dropinbase will automatically clear the related generated code.</p>\n<h3>Field Attribute Changes</h3>\n<p>Note, Dropinbase does not yet detect changes to field attributes, eg a change from <strong>int </strong>to <strong>varchar, </strong>or <strong>required </strong>to <strong>non-required</strong>. If there is such a change follow these steps:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Find the field record using the filter/search facility on ~nav(dibFieldGrid)~.</li>\n<li>Edit the record to reflect the actual table-design and save it.</li>\n<li>Click the <strong>Items-</strong>tab and notice if any changes are needed to items. Edit these records if needed.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Handle Query Design Changes</h2>\n<p>Columns can be automatically added and removed from containers after their underlying SQL has been edited.</p>\n<p>Both the ~nav(dibSqlGrid, SQL Grid)~ and the ~nav(dibSqlForm, SQL Form)~ has the same <strong>Tools</strong>-menu with options to add and remove columns in related containers.<br>Note, new columns are added to the end of the existing list of columns. Use the Designer to position them or to nest them in column-headers etc.</p>\n<p>Alternatively, manually delete the columns that are no longer supported, and drag-and-drop new columns from the <strong>Components Tree</strong>. Note, the configuration of columns based on SQL is quite specific, which is why duplicating a different type of component (eg a button) and altering it is not advisable.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc308-dib'),
    (309, 'Basics For Any Container', 304, 5, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>To create a container from scratch, use the <strong>+</strong> button in the toolbar under&nbsp;<strong>Container Details</strong>&nbsp;in the Designer.</p>\n<p>All containers must have the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Name</strong> - protocol: alphanumeric (no spaces). First letter must be alphabetic and lower-case. Capital letters cannot follow one another, eg myFirstGrid.</li>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>Caption</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Container Type</strong> - eg grid/form/plain</li>\n<li><strong>Model </strong>- eg None/Table/Sql. Identify the type of record source (if none, choose \'None\'). Allowed values depend on the Container Type.</li>\n<li><strong>Module Dropin</strong> - the subfolder where the code for this container lives. Dropinbase stores generated code in for eg /dropins/<strong>myDropin</strong>/dibCode/myFirstGrid. -&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>Port Record(s)</strong> - all containers must have at least one port record, unless they are only ever embedded using a subcontainer component.</li>\n<li><strong>Permission Record(s) </strong>- list which permission groups can open/edit this container</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Certain fields are conditionally required:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Table / SQL / Crud Store Controller </strong>- relates to the Model above. Select a table or SQL record to link the container if applicable.</li>\n<li><strong>Template </strong>- if the Container Type is iframe, then provide the path to the HTML template file.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Useful Tips:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>After making changes to a container\'s design, remove the generated code (see ~navdocs(Generating and Clearing Generated Code)~.</li>\n<li>Click on the container\'s title under Container Details to open it in its default port, or click on one of the "play" button under Ports .</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc309-dib'),
    (310, 'Common Error List', 116, 40, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc310-dib'),
    (311, 'Container Compile Error', 310, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Symptom(s)</h2>\n<p>The container doesn\'t load and the user sees the following error message:&nbsp;</p>\n<pre>\n<p id="mat-mdc-dialog-title-0"><strong>Unable to load page</strong></p>\n<p><strong>This could be due to a template error or our system could be under severe load and cannot serve the page correctly at present.</strong></p>\n</pre>\n<p>The response to the Network request for the container\'s .js file either contains an error, or code with one or more bugs.</p>\n<p>The Console normally states the cause of the error.</p>\n<p>The Dropinbase error log contains details of the error.</p>\n<h2>Cause and Solution</h2>\n<p>The error is caused when either faulty JavaScript or HTML was generated which could not be compiled by Angular.<br>(Note, the container\'s .js file contains both the JavaScript and HTML in one file).</p>\n<p>In most cases the faulty code is caused by errors like missing quotes (" or \') or broken HTML (eg unclosded tags) in the Attributes or Expression fields of the Designer.</p>\n<p>View the error in the Dropinbase error log and in the Console for clues. Attempt to find the item containing the invalid code. <br>If not sure, use the <strong>UI Include</strong> field to isolate the problem by excluding batches of items until the problem dissapears.</p>\n<p>Fix the faulty configuration, regenerate the container\'s code, and test again.</p>\n<p>Avoid errors like this by following official examples, and making and testing changes in small batches, rather than everything at once.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc311-dib'),
    (312, 'Enable Maintenance Mode', 21, 60, 0, 'none', '<h2>Configure the Maintenance Mode Page</h2>\n<p>The following file contains the design of the Maintenance Mode page:</p>\n<p><strong>/projectFolder/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/dibAuthenticate/views/sitemaintenance.php</strong></p>\n<p>If you wish to change it, override the dropin by saving a copy of the whole /dibAuthenticate dropin folder under <strong>/projectFolder/dropins/</strong>. <br>Changes to any of these files will now take precedence over the official Dropinbase dibAuthenticate dropin.</p>\n<h2>Enable Maintenance Mode</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Open the /configs/Dib.php file.</li>\n<li>Uncomment the $SITEMAINTENANCE array.</li>\n<li>Make any changes to the contents as necessary.\n<ul>\n<li>Note the \'warningMsg\' which is displayed to users from 10 minutes before the site enters Maintenance Mode onwards. Users see the message once.</li>\n<li>To enter Maintenace Mode immediately, set the \'startTime\' to a date in the past.</li>\n<li>Note the convenient \'allowedIps\', which enables developers to use/test the system during Maintenance Mode. \n   <br>To obtain your public IP address, go to Google and enter \'What is my ip\'.\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Save the file to activate the changes.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Alternative Method</h2>\nTo completely and immediately block the site from all access, edit the /index.php file of your project.\n<br>Here is an example of code. Update or remove the URL pointing to a cover image below. \n<br>This code must be added to the top of the /index.php file. Comment it out for future use:\n\n<pre>\nif(array_key_exists(\'HTTP_REQUESTVERIFICATIONTOKEN\', $_SERVER)) {\n   echo \'{"success":false,"message":"System is under maintenance, we will be back soon.","showType":"dialog","messageDelay":null,"records":null,"total":0,"auth_id":null}\';\n} else {\n   echo "&lt;html&gt;&lt;head&gt;&lt;title&gt;Under Maintenance&lt;/title&gt;&lt;/head&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;img width=\'100%\' src=\'/files/files/themes/overrides/images/under-maintenance.jpg\'&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;";\n}\n    \ndie();\n</pre>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc312-dib'),
    (313, 'Create a Development Environment', 39, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Dev and Team Tools</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Trello / Kanbanize</strong> - kanban board for planning and creating tickets</li>\n<li><strong>Discord / Slack / Google Chat / Teams</strong> - create a space for each project wherein to communicate with team members</li>\n<li><strong>Github / Bitbucket</strong> - code repository</li>\n<li><strong>Visual Studio Code with CoPilot</strong>- coding environment with built-in debugger, AI and Git tools</li>\n<li><strong>Zoom / Microsoft Teams / Chrome Remote Desktop</strong> - online meeting with remote control</li>\n<li><strong>ShareX </strong>- screen capturing</li>\n<li><strong>FileZilla / WinSCP</strong> - SFTP file management</li>\n<li><strong>HeidiSQL / DBeaver / SQL Server Management Studio / pgAdmin </strong>- database management</li>\n<li><strong>Notepad++</strong> - text file editing and comparison tools etc.</li>\n<li><strong>NordPass / LastPass</strong> - password management and sharing</li>\n<li><strong>Claude / ChatGpt / Gemini / Bard</strong> - chatbot with coding ability</li>\n<li><strong>Google Drive</strong> - file sharing, documentation and policies etc.</li>\n<li><strong>Clockify</strong> - time tracking</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Team Members</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Project Manager\n<ul>\n<li>Assumes overall responsibility for the project success. Main client-liason and planner.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Technical Architect(s) /&nbsp;Senior Developer(s)\n<ul>\n<li>Assumes responsibility for application design and implementation. Facilitates continual growth of developers.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Server Technician\n<ul>\n<li>Assumes responsibility for server installation and maintenance.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Developer(s)\n<ul>\n<li>Develops application and fixes bugs with guidance from Senior Developers.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Junior Developer(s)\n<ul>\n<li>Works on non-critical / easier features and repetitive work.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>QA Tester(s)\n<ul>\n<li>Responsible for ensuring application works to the satisfaction of the client.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Support User(s)\n<ul>\n<li>Provides user support and informs the rest of the team of client issues.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Succession planning plays a vital role in projects to ensure the transfer of accumulated knowledge among developers and to facilitate their progression into new roles.&nbsp;<br>If not managed properly, replacing senior developers on projects with extensive custom codebases can be costly and potentially disastrous.</p>\n<p>Developers must always priotize the maintainability of their code.</p>\n<h2>Kanban Board Structure</h2>\n<table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 94.9985%;" border="1"><colgroup><col style="width: 6.00427%;"><col style="width: 5.69032%;"><col style="width: 6.27897%;"><col style="width: 4.78772%;"><col style="width: 7.18158%;"><col style="width: 4.27755%;"><col style="width: 6.23973%;"><col style="width: 8.12342%;"><col style="width: 8.00569%;"><col style="width: 5.18015%;"><col style="width: 9.10451%;"><col style="width: 9.73241%;"><col style="width: 6.23973%;"><col style="width: 13.1466%;"></colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="3">Requested</td>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="5">Development</td>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="3">Staging</td>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="3">Production</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Backlog</td>\n<td>To Do: Feeder</td>\n<td>To Do: Priority</td>\n<td>Coding</td>\n<td>Ready for Dev Testing</td>\n<td>Dev Testing</td>\n<td>Post Testing Issues</td>\n<td>Ready for Staging Deploy</td>\n<td>Ready for Staging Testing</td>\n<td>Staging Testing</td>\n<td>Ready for Production Deploy</td>\n<td>Ready for Production Testing</td>\n<td>Production Testing</td>\n<td>Done</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="14"><strong>Expedite</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="14"><strong>Support Issues / Client Requests (Small) / Discussion Required</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="14"><strong>Internal Bugs / Security Matters / Error Logs</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="14"><strong>Existing Feature Enhancements / Technical Debt / Core System Updates</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="14"><strong>New Features / Client Requests (Large) / System Integrations</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="text-align: center;" colspan="14"><strong>UX Improvements / Styling / Miscellaneous</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>New tickets are entered under one of the first three columns and under the relevant \'swimlane\' (<strong>Expedite </strong>to <strong>UX Improvements</strong>). Team members move tickets from left to right as they progress.<br>The higher swimlanes generally have higher importance. Anything under <strong>Expedite</strong> needs immediate attention.</p>\n<h2>Project Machines</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Dev Server - where all UI development and developer testing is done. Data is test data.</li>\n<li>Developer Machines - most PHP coding takes place here, and uploaded to the Dev Server when ready. Data is test data.</li>\n<li>Staging Server - where code for a new release is thoroughly tested before copied to the Production Server. It is an exact copy of the Production Server environment and code. Data is real user data.</li>\n<li>Production Server - where the live client site resides.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Notes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>for less critical and single-developer projects, the environment may consist of only a Developer Machine and a Producion Server. Client data could be copied to the Developer Machine (and obfuscated) for thorough testing.</li>\n<li>to improve security, do not create DNS entries for the Dev and Staging servers. Configure the hosts file (eg C:/windows/system32/drivers/etc/hosts) on team member\'s machines to access the sites.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Dib.php Settings:</h3>\n<table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 99.9925%; height: 246.4px;" border="1"><colgroup><col style="width: 33.3211%;"><col style="width: 33.3211%;"><col style="width: 16.6605%;"><col style="width: 16.6605%;"></colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Setting</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Dev Server and Developer Machines</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Staging Server&nbsp;</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Production Server</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 89.6px;">\n<td style="height: 89.6px;">\n<div>\n<div><strong>$ENVIRONMENT</strong> (disable echo of PHP error messages to browser, and admin functions like code generation)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 89.6px;">\'development\'</td>\n<td style="height: 89.6px;">\'production\'<br>(To generate code or prepare hotfixes on Staging, set temporarily to \'development\' and ~navdocs(Enable Maintenance Mode)~.</td>\n<td style="height: 89.6px;">\'production\'</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div><strong>$CODEUSE</strong> (when dibCode files are generated)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">1</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">2</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">3</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>$CLIENT_DEBUG_LEVEL</strong> (printing of JavaScript error &amp; debug messages in browser Console)</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">1</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">0</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div><strong>$ELEUTHERIA_DEBUG_LEVEL</strong> (displaying of Eleutheria code error messages in iframe, and generation of debugging info)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">1<br>(Can temporarily set to 2 or 3 for detailed debugging information)</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">1</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">0</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div><strong>$DEBUG_LEVEL</strong> (logging of PHP errors to Dropinbase error logs)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">2</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">2</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div><strong>$LOGPERMISSUES</strong> (logging of permissions and authentication issues)</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">2</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">1 or 2</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">1 or 2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>$DESIGNER_CAN_READ_ERRORS</strong></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>TRUE</td>\n<td>TRUE (only if no DNS entry)</td>\n<td>FALSE</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>$DESIGNER_CAN_READ_DEBUG</strong></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>TRUE</td>\n<td>TRUE</td>\n<td>FALSE</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>$CHECKUSERSESSIONS</strong></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>FALSE</td>\n<td>TRUE</td>\n<td>TRUE</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>$VERIFY_AUTH_TOKEN</strong></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>TRUE</td>\n<td>TRUE</td>\n<td>TRUE</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div><strong>$WRITE_ERRORS_TO</strong></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\'db\'</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\'db\'</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td>\n<div>\n<div>\'file\'</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>Also see ~navdocs(File System Settings)~ for file system rights for each environment.</p>\n<h2>Git Repository</h2>\n<p>A code-repository allows a team to work concurrently on files and merge and track their updates.</p>\n<p>The Dropinbase core can be cloned from the master branch at&nbsp;<a href="https://github.com/Dropinbase/framework" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://github.com/Dropinbase/framework</a> and pulled when you wish to upgrade to the latest version.</p>\n<p>A copy of the Dropinbase client can be downloaded from <a href="https://github.com/Dropinbase/dibclient" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://github.com/Dropinbase/dibclient</a>. Once downloaded, upload it to your own repository in GitHub/Bitbucket from where it can be shared with others. <br>The client is where all your custom code additions and configurations will be made. The client and core are linked via the index.php file in the client.</p>\n<p>Here is a suggested structure for a code repository:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>develop </strong>- the branch that is checed-out on the Dev Server</li>\n<li><strong>tickets&nbsp;</strong>- relates to tickets on kanban board. Name contains developer initials and kanban ticket number.\n<ul>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>DB#123_newsletter email</strong></li>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>CL#128_bulk importer</strong></li>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>DB#90_fix_image viewer</strong></li>\n<li>etc.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>releases&nbsp;</strong>- create a release branch for each staging deployment date\n<ul>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>20240101</strong></li>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>20240108</strong></li>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>20240115</strong></li>\n<li>etc.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>master&nbsp;</strong>- the branch that is checked-out on the Staging and Production Servers</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For each new feature or bug tackled on the kanban board, a developer creates a ticket branch off&nbsp;<strong>master </strong>on his local machine and makes changes within this branch. When it is ready for testing on the Dev Server, the ticket is merged into <strong>develop</strong> and pulled on the Dev Server.<br>If the ticket passes testing, it can be merged into the latest pending <strong>release </strong>folder.</p>\n<p>When the pending release folder date arrives and there are enough tickets ready, merge the release folder into master, and create a new release folder for the next week.<br>The <strong>master </strong>branch is then pulled on the Staging Server and thorough testing is conducted, focussing especially on the lastest tickets introduced and critical features.<br>Also merge <strong>master </strong>into <strong>develop </strong>to ensure it is up to date.</p>\n<p>Note, the <strong>develop </strong>branch is never merged into any other branch as it may contain tickets that are not ready for deployment.</p>\n<h2>Channels / Spaces on Slack(etc)</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>general\n<ul>\n<li>All team members. Anything that affects the whole team.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>development\n<ul>\n<li>Developers only. Things that affect development.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>support\n<ul>\n<li>Support users only. Things that affect client support.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>repository\n<ul>\n<li>Used to avoid merge issues into specifically the <strong>release </strong>and <strong>development </strong>branches that can occur when developers merge at the same time. Each developer announces when they are merging and when they are done. No-one else merges while someone is busy.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>deployment\n<ul>\n<li>All team members. Anything that affects the state of deployments.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>random\n<ul>\n<li>All teams benefit from fun and meaning. Post anything of interest.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>keep\n<ul>\n<li>Place to store details that are often used.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc313-dib'),
    (314, 'Hotfixing Production', 21, 70, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Bugs are not always discovered during testing, and when a resolution cannot wait for the next deployment, a "hotfix" needs to be applied.</p>\n<p>The fixes are normally applied on the Staging server since it is an exact copy of the Production Server, and does not include unwanted changes on the Dev Server.</p>\n<p>Once the new code has been tested on Staging, it is normally best to first ~navdocs(Enable Maintenance Mode)~ on the Production Server. This allows you to apply the relevant patches and test them on Production while users are forced to wait. Users will also be forced to load the corrected User Interface files when Maintenance Mode is disabled.</p>\n<p>Also remember to apply the same fixes to the Dev Server.</p>\n<p>Depending on where the bug lies, different approaches are required.</p>\n<p><strong>PHP File Changes</strong></p>\n<p>Apply the fix to the .php file and copy it to the Staging server. Test thoroughly before copying it to the Production and Dev Servers.<br>Remember to commit the file to the repository.</p>\n<p><strong>User Interface Changes</strong></p>\n<p>Set the <strong>$ENVIRONMENT</strong> variable to \'development\' in <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> on the Staging server to allow admin actions.<br>Open the Designer on Staging and apply the fix to the necessary containers. For each of the affected containers regenerate the dibCode and permission records&nbsp; by using the green <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/generateCodeButton.png" alt="" width="50px" height="34px">-button. This button will generate code for all ~navdocs(Permgroups)~.</p>\n<p>Once everything has been thoroughly tested, the affected files must be copied to Production.&nbsp;<br>Each container\'s files are stored in its own subfolder under <strong>/dropins/DROPIN/dibCode/</strong>. Copy the relevent folders accross.<br>If changes have been made to dropdown-lists, actions or components, also copy the&nbsp;<strong>/_lists</strong>, <strong>/_actions</strong> and <strong>/_components</strong> subfolders of <strong>/dibCode</strong> accross.</p>\n<p>No changes are needed in the Designer on Production, unless there were changes to Permissions (see below).</p>\n<p><strong>Permissions Changes</strong></p>\n<p>Permissions are stored in the active permissions tables (eg. <em>pef_perm_active</em>), and affects the design of containers. For eg. buttons and tabs with ports that reference non-permitted containers are not generated for affected ~navdocs(Permgroups)~.</p>\n<p>If permissions have changed then the dibCode files for the affected containers must be regenerated. This normally includes the base-container where other containers are injected into tabs/ports.</p>\n<p>Follow the steps above for User Interface Changes. Then also apply the changes to permissions in the Designer on the <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Production</span> Server and regenerate all active permission records by using the <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/generatePermsButton.png" alt="" width="50" height="33">-button.</p>\n<p>Test thoroughly before removing Maintenance Mode.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc314-dib'),
    (317, 'Configure Database Connections', 10, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h4>Steps:</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>âAfter logging in to Dropinbase as admin (the default password is \'test\'), the main dashboard will open and the URL will change to /nav/dibDashboard.</li>\n<li>Click on&nbsp;<em><strong>Database Connections</strong>.</em></li>\n<li>If your client database is not listed here, click the <em><strong>Add New</strong></em> button.</li>\n<li>Provide any suitable name for the database connection and provide the connection properties.</li>\n<li>Click <em><strong>Test</strong> </em>and make any adjustments as required until the connection succeeds.</li>\n<li>Click <em><strong>Save</strong>.</em></li>\n</ol>\n<p>If there are any issues, review ~navdocs(Connecting to Databases, docs, technical setup prerequisites here)~.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc317-dib'),
    (318, 'Use the App Wizard', 10, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h4>Steps:</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>âClick the&nbsp;<strong>App Wizard</strong> button/icon (on the <strong>Dashboard</strong>,&nbsp; <strong>Database Connections</strong> container, or in the <strong>Designer</strong>).\n<ol>\n<li>Note, finer control, and even more tasks are available on the <strong>Database Tasks</strong> page.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Choose your client database (if it is not listed, you have probably not saved it under the previous step).</li>\n<li>Choice of Base Container (the first container that loads and "hosts" others).\n<ol>\n<li>When creating a base container, you must also choose a template. The design of this template can be adjusted in the Designer. But also note that the Container Features-tool can be used to make useful adjustments after the base container is created.</li>\n<li>When choosing an existing base container, you also need to choose the Port Item where the new containers will be attached to when loaded.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>App Settings\n<ol>\n<li>This step contains a fair amount of help notices. Check the "View All Options"-slider for more options, and make changes as needed.</li>\n<li>Save the changes to the database record, or to the related table records. <strong>Note, containers are generated based on the settings stored on table-level. </strong>The regular expression that affects container names is worth highlighting here.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Select Tables to Import\n<ol>\n<li>Note, this grid is editable. Change names and options as needed.</li>\n<li>Reload the list of tables to see the active settings, and also any differences (stated in the Notices column) between the table design stored in Dropinbase compared to the actual design in the underlying database.</li>\n<li>If there are any differences, click the "Show Detail" button and scroll to the right in the grid to view the "New Database Fields Task" and "Missing Database Fields Task" columns. Any tasks selected here will be applied when the "Build Application" button is used.</li>\n<li>Note, to conform to Angular naming conventions, the first letter of container names is automatically converted to lowercase.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Build My App\n<ol>\n<li>This will start the generation process.</li>\n<li>If there were no errors, the dashboard of the new app will open.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Tasks &amp; Error Log\n<ol>\n<li>This will log the steps accomplished, and also provide more details about any errors that may have occured.</li>\n<li>Note, the error login in the Designer may also have more info about errors\n<ol>\n<li>If Dropinbase cannot write to the Designer\'s error log table (<em>pef_error_log</em>) in the database, it will write errors to <strong>/runtime/logs/error.log</strong></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Also check the <strong>/runtime/logs/DatabaseSync.log</strong> file</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc318-dib'),
    (319, 'Delete and Rebuild My App', 10, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><strong>Start from Scratch, Rebuild Your App</strong></p>\n<p>This step is useful if you decide many design changes are neccessary, or your cat steps on your laptop\'s power button while your app is generating :).</p>\n<ol>\n<li>âThe "Delete Database and/or Related Records" button is available in multipe places: Database Connections / App Wizzard (after selecting a database) / Database Tasks</li>\n<li>Alternatively you can remove only certain tables and their related containers, under Database Tasks -&gt; Tasks -&gt; Table Tasks. Select the tables and click the Tasks Menu -&gt; Remove Tables... button.</li>\n<li>Start again with Step 1.</li>\n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc319-dib'),
    (320, 'Prime the Database Design', 10, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Dropinbase utilizes the design of the database it is importing when building apps. The following are recommendations (not rules) that assist in producing a clean outcome.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong><em>Note: see ~navdocs(Delete and Rebuild My App)~ if needed</em></strong></p>\n\n<h2>The User/Login Table</h2>\nDropinbase ships with its own "user" table, named <b>pef_login</b>. It is essential in Dropinbase installations and cannot be replaced because of the session and authentication system. However, integration with your user table is possible, or you can move the required fields to <b>pef_login</b>.\n\n<h4>A. Integrate with your User Table</h4>\n<p>Create a foreign key field in <b>pef_login</b> that links to your user table, eg <i>user_id</i>. Then ignore the first_name, last_name, email and other fields that already exist in your user table. Instead, use the <b>/configs/DibUserParams.php</b> file to specify that these field values must originate from your own user table via the foreign key link.\n<br>When new users are added to your system, you will need to populate both these tables, and set the foreign key field to link the records.</p>\n\n<h4>B. Add Fields to pef_login</h4>\n<p>Add any outstanding fields to pef_login. If any of these fields must be added to the PHP session or be available as parameter values in queries, then also add them to the SQL in the <b>/configs/DibUserParams.php</b> file. Note, this option replaces your own user table.\n</p>\n<p><b>Warning</b>\n<br>For security reasons you should never create an editable form or grid based on <b>pef_login</b> which is accessible by users other than system administrators. If you have Registration or Personal Details pages, then it is best to implement option A above and base these pages on your own user table and completely exclude the foreign key field. Populate the <b>pef_login</b> record with eg. <b>after create</b> container events and PHP code, after validating all user data properly (using eg. <b>before create</b>).\n\n\n<h2>Naming Protocols</h2>\n<p>Dropinbase uses sets of regular expressions to convert table and field names into container and item captions and names. â<br>For this to function efficiently, it is vital that a naming protocol is followed for table and field names in your databases.</p>\n<p>If you need guidance, ~navdocs(Strict Naming Conventions, docs, follow the protocols implemented in Dropinbase)~&nbsp; which leads to a clean design.</p>\n<p>Generally speaking, implementing naming and other protocols is the "secret" to building bug free systems quickly.<br>Adjust the regular expressions (stored in the database table) in the Application Wizard to match your naming protocols.<br><br></p>\n<h2>Use UTF8</h2>\n<p>Tables should store data using the <em><strong>utf8/utf8mb4</strong></em> character set. Dropinbase will work with other character sets, but certain characters may not display correctly, and it can even lead to security issues.</p>\n<p>Tools like HeidiSQL have bulk operations that allow you to set the character set of all text fields in all tables, or for a specific table. Database systems like MySQL have SQL functions to convert character sets.</p>\n<p>Also configure the database character set in the database connection file&nbsp;<strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong>. Use \'<strong>utf8mb4</strong>\'<strong> </strong>unless you want to force a different character set.</p>\n<h2>Configure Foreign Keys (Relationships)</h2>\n<p>Dropinbase uses database relationships to automatically configure certain features:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>filters for related records (eg show all related invoice items on an invoice form)</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Dropdown Display Expressions, docs, display expressions of dropdown lists)~ based on foreign key fields</li>\n<li>"nav-buttons" next to dropdowns which facilitates application navigation</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Without them, Dropinbase will generate a non-relational database application and you will need to manually configure these features.</p>\n<h2>Configure Unique Indexes</h2>\n<p>Dropinbase generates display expressions for dropdown lists based on foreign key fields, based on info such as unique indexes and the order of fields in tables. See ~navdocs(Dropdown Display Expressions)~ for more info.<br>Eg the dropdown for the <em>client_id </em>field in the <em>quote</em><strong> </strong>table should display a list of client names. If the <em>name </em>field in the <em>client </em>table does not have a unique index or is not one of the first fields in the table, Dropinbase may constuct a less useful display expression.<br>Note, display expressions for dropdowns can be manually changed in the <em>pef_table </em>table, or by linking them to dropdown-list queries.</p>\n<h2>Set Primary Keys to Auto-Increment</h2>\n<p>This is not essential, but avoids the problem of users providing less than optimal or problematic values.<br>This design implies that foreign keys (that by definition reference the primary keys of other tables) are integers too.</p>\n<h2>Set Field Attributes Accurately</h2>\n<p>Required fields, data-types, field lengths, and defaults&nbsp;pull right through to the design of fields in grids and forms. <br>They restrict user input which keeps data clean and useful (you don\'t want names in date fields etc).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc320-dib'),
    (321, 'Applying Subsequent Database Changes', 10, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Dropinbase can detect which new fields/tables are added to the underlying database, and any redundant fields/tables that were removed, and apply the necessary changes to your application.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em>Note, at present changes to fields that retain their original name, eg <strong>datatype</strong>, <strong>field length</strong>, <strong>required</strong>, <strong>default value</strong> etc, are not detected and must be applied manually by editing the configuration for both the ~nav(dibFieldGrid, Fields)~ and ~nav(dibItemGrid, Items)~ linked to the Fields.</em></p>\n<h4>Steps:</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Click the <strong><em>Databases</em></strong><em>-tab</em></li>\n<li>Click the <strong>Tasks </strong>button next to your database record</li>\n<li>Before adding new tables, check that the defaults under the <strong><em>App Settings</em></strong>-tab are correct for the new containers that will be added.</li>\n<li>On the <strong><em>Table Tasks</em></strong>-tab, click the<strong><em> Detect Outstanding Tasks</em></strong>-button.&nbsp;</li>\n<ol>\n<li>Dropinbase will detect and list all changes, and suggest actions in the <strong>New Database Fields Task</strong> and <strong>Missing Database Fields Task</strong> columns.</li>\n<li>Also see ~navdocs(Handle Changes to Table and Query Designs)~</li>\n</ol>\n<li>Change the suggested actions (directly in the grid) where needed.&nbsp;</li>\n<ol>\n<li>Note, new fields can be added to all related containers, or only to the table itself. <br>With the latter option you can manually add items (fields) to containers where needed. <br>With the first option you can sort records descending on \'id\' on <strong>/nav/dibItemGrid</strong> to view newly added items, and then delete / edit them as required.</li>\n<li>The <strong>Ignore </strong>checkbox can be used to completely ignore a table or any changes to it. <br>Note, if other tables are related to a table, it should not be ignored before the table\'s design has been imported, else features like dropdown display expressions will not function correctly.</li>\n</ol>\n<li>Use one of the <strong>Execute Tasks</strong> menu options to apply the actions.</li>\n<ol>\n<li>Once completed, Dropinbase will list the actions applied to each table in the grid</li>\n</ol>\n<li>It is often helpful to view and edit newly added items on <strong>/nav/dibItemGrid</strong> (sort the grid descending on \'id\').</li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc321-dib'),
    (322, 'Settings Table', 105, 55, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h2>Global Settings</h2>\n<p>The <strong><em>pef_setting </em></strong>table (in the Dropinbase database) contains various values and settings that affect Dropinbase on a global level.</p>\n<p>Certain records contain system values that are dynamically updated by Dropinbase to keep track of things. Leave these values as is.<br>Certain values are linked to Module Dropins.</p>\n<p>The following are of note:</p>\n<table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 62.2363%; height: 313.6px;" border="1"><colgroup><col style="width: 21.2703%;"><col style="width: 78.7101%;"></colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr style="height: 179.2px;">\n<td style="height: 179.2px;">dibDatabaseVersion</td>\n<td style="height: 179.2px;">New versions of the Dropinbase core framework are periodically released which often neccessitate updates to the Dropinbase tables, or even your PHP code. The SQL scripts to perform the table updates, and the comments about PHP code updates, are stored in the /dropinbase/Migration Scripts.txt file. The scripts are linked to build numbers. <br>When the /runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt file is deleted, Dropinbase compares the dibDatabaseVersion value with the latest build number in the file, and attempts to run the outstanding scripts. <br>If any errors occur, they will be logged and then the outstanding scripts must be manaully executed and the dibDatabaseVersion value must be updated accordingly.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">defaultModuleDropinId</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">A foreign key pointer to a <em>pef_dropin table </em>record identifying the default Module Dropin for new containers. Dropinbase ships with a value of 1 which points to the \'main\' Module Dropin in&nbsp;<em>pef_dropin</em>. Alter it if needed.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">gridMultiselect</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">This is an example of a common global grid setting. There are others and all of them can be set in pef_setting as global values, and overriden in container settings. Use the Container Setting add-wizard in the Designer to see all.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">formFieldAppearance</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">This controls the appearance of all input/form fields that are generated. See <a href="https://material.angular.io/components/form-field/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/form-field/overview</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>validationTicks</td>\n<td>Site-wide disabling of validation ticks on inputs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">beforeBodyJs and afterBodyJs</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">These values are used to insert JavaScript in the index.html file that bootstraps the application. It is often blank, or contains the JavaScript that enables chatbots or other plugins.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc322-dib'),
    (323, 'Distributing Module Dropins', 3, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Module dropins can be distributed to other Droinbase installations with or without the original design records.</p>\n<p>The Dropinbase admin pages is a good example. The default installation of Dropinbase does not include the design records of the admin pages. Instead the <strong>dibAdmin (setNgxMaterial)</strong> dropin record in <em>pef_dropin </em>is linked to the main Dropinbase database record via the <em>pef_dropin_cache_db_id </em>field. This serves as an indication that the active permission records of all containers in this module dropin must be generated from files stored in this dropins\' <strong>dibCode/_permFiles</strong> folder, instead of the original design records (which may not exist). It also indicates the database that tables in this dropin are linked to. If all the other <strong>/dibCode</strong> files (PHP and JavaScript etc) in the dropin for the admin pages exist, then Dropinbase has everything it needs for the full functionality of the admin pages.</p>\n<p>If the design records are included, the end-user has a choice. If they don\'t set the&nbsp;<em>pef_dropin_cache_db_id </em>field, then Dropinbase will populate active permission records for these containers from the permission tables (<em>pef_perm_container</em>, <em>pef_perm_item_list</em>, etc). Dropinbase can also generate <strong>/dibCode</strong> files for these containers from the design records, which implies the end-user can alter the design. If the end-user imports a package update released by the supplier of the dropin, they can use settings on the package importer (/nav/dibShareImport) to control whether (all) updates or new records they\'ve added are lost or not.</p>\n<p>If the end-user populates the &nbsp;<em>pef_dropin_cache_db_id </em>field, then Dropinbase will expect the existence of all the <strong>/dibCode</strong> files, which includes the <strong>/dibCode/_permFiles </strong>files from which active permission records are populated.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc323-dib'),
    (324, 'Docs from Old Dropinbase Versions', NULL, 500, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc324-dib'),
    (325, 'Creating Ports for Dropin Modules', 324, 33, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>If another developer provides you with the cache files for a container (eg dibFindReplace) but not the records that define the container\'s design, you can still use this container. The main problem is that the new container\'s port cache file will be configured for a base container which you do not have. When a Dropinbase installation needs to open a container for which there is no definition records, in a different base container than the available port records specify, a port file that links the container with the new base container must be created. At present this is still a manual process and will be facilitated soon.</p>\r\n<h3>Steps:</h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Copy paste the existing port record, eg&nbsp;port_dibFindReplace____.txt, and rename it to contain a port aliias, eg&nbsp;port_dibFindReplace__myAlias__.txt</li>\r\n<li>Edit the contents of the new file\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>portItemId must&nbsp;point to the id of the port item that will host the container. If the container is a popup window, specify "", eg&nbsp;"portItemId":""</li>\r\n<li>portItemAlias must contain the new port alias, eg&nbsp;"portItemAlias":"myAlias"</li>\r\n<li>parentContainerName&nbsp;must contain the new parent container (which often would be the new base container), eg&nbsp;"parentContainerName":"newBase"</li>\r\n<li>If the parent container must open in a non-default port, then specify it in parentContainerPortAlias, else leave it blank, eg&nbsp;"parentContainerPortAlias":""</li>\r\n<li>preloadItemTargetId must point to the parent item id of the port item (portItemId), eg&nbsp;"preloadItemTargetId":"123553"</li>\r\n<li>baseContainer&nbsp;must contain&nbsp;the new base container, eg &nbsp;"baseContainer":"newBase"</li>\r\n<li>if the parent container is not the base container, then&nbsp;parentPortItemId must point to the id of the port item that the parent container links to, else specify null, eg&nbsp;"parentPortItemId":null</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>The file must be saved with the new name in the same folder as the original port file.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Below is an example of a port file using the settings discussed above for the dibFindReplace popup container:</p>\r\n<pre>{"success":true,"records":<br>{"type":"modal window","containerName":"dibFindReplace","containerTitle":"Find and Replace","containerType":"modal window","containerId":"C6657","label":"Find and Replace",<br>"portItemId":"","portItemAlias":"myAlias","parentContainerName":"newBase","parentContainerPortAlias":"base1","rememberIfOpened":"1","preloadItemTargetId":"123553","close_button":true,<br>"min_button":false,"max_button":false,"maximized":false,"collapsed":false,"dropinName":"dibContainer",<br>"defaultQuery":null,"baseContainer":"apros","baseDropin":"dibContainer","parentPortItemId":null},<br>"message":null,"showType":null,"summary":"Valid","total":0,"filtertotal":0}</pre>\r\n<h2>Port Table Fields</h2>\r\n<p>~docstable(pef_port)~</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc325-dib'),
    (326, 'Deploying Apps and Generating Files', 21, 45, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc326-dib'),
    (327, 'Remove Unneeded Design Records', 326, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Use the "Remove DIB Containers"-tab on ~nav(dibRelease)~ to clean up the Dropinbase tables of the design records for Examples and Admin pages, which also limits the scope of what hackers can attempt.&nbsp;<br>You will not be able to view the design of these containers, or make design changes to them. <br><br>Note, this will only remove the database design records of the containers and recreate active permission records. <br>The Designer and other Admin pages will still function since this facility will set the <strong>pef_dropin.pef_dropin_cache_db_id</strong>-field <br>of the <strong>setNgxMaterial/dibAdmin</strong> record to force the use of the dropin\'s stored cache and permission records. <br><br>The examples will also still function even though their design records are removed. <br>To disable Examples and/or Admin pages completely set the <strong>pef_dropin.pef_dropin_cache_db_id</strong>-field of their dropin records to null, and delete the /runtime/deleteMeToInitDIB.dtxt file to rebuild active permissions.<br>Also ensure that the database user configured in Conn.php does not have rights to update records in the active permission tables (eg <em>pef_perm_active</em>).</p>\n<h3>Restore the Design Records</h3>\n<p>Use the ~nav(dibShareImport)~ facility to obtain the design records again.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc327-dib'),
    (328, 'Users and Permission Groups', 28, 100, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Use the ~nav(dibLoginGrid)~ to create/edit <strong>Users (Logins) </strong>and <strong>Permission Groups</strong>, and to link them together using <strong>Login Groups</strong>.<br>Note the <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/icons/people.svg" alt="People" width="24" height="24">-icon in the Designer for quick access.</p>\n<p>To optimize server performance, permissions are specified on group level only. If you need to assign special permissions to a certain login, a permission group record must be created which can then be assigned permissions.</p>\n<h2>Permission Groups</h2>\n<p>Permission groups are created in ~nav(dibPermGroupGrid)~ or in the&nbsp;<em>pef_perm_group </em>table.<br>Names must be descriptive but not too long since they are used in dropdown lists.<br>Remember to set expiry dates far in the future for groups that will never expire.</p>\n<p><strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">NOTE</span>:</strong></p>\n<p>It is advisable to design your application with fixed roles where each role has certain rights and consists of preferably one permission group.&nbsp;<br>Allowing users to belong to a random collection of many permission groups leads to many permutations of Permgroups. Note, sets of code is generated for each permutation used.<br>Although the above scenario will work, having fixed roles is simpler and cleaner which avoids maintenance and support issues.</p>\n<h2>Login Accounts / Users</h2>\n<p>Create users by clicking the Add button on ~nav(dibLoginGrid)~ or in the <em>pef_login </em>table. The Designer also has an icon to access this page.</p>\n<p>Some fields of note:</p>\n<p>~docstable(pef_login,$username$admin_user$perm_group$test_user$default_url$pef_security_policy_id$dib_username$supplier_code$)~</p>\n<h2>Login Account Groups</h2>\n<p>Login accounts are linked to Permission groups on the 2nd-tab of ~nav(dibLoginForm)~, or in the <em>pef_login_group </em>table.<br>Remember to set expiry dates far in the future for links that will never expire.</p>\n<h2>Developer / Admin Users</h2>\n<p>Developer/Administrator accounts must be linked to the default System Admin group (only) where <strong>id </strong>= 1, and the <strong>admin_user</strong>-field must be checked. Their Permgroup is therefore <strong>x1x</strong>.</p>\n<h2>Public Users</h2>\n<p>Any un-authenticated user is automatically logged-in with the user name <strong>system_public</strong>. <br>If the default record for the&nbsp;<strong>system_public </strong>user was removed an error will be logged and further code execution will be terminated. <br>If you need to restore the record, remember to link it to an active <em>pef_perm_group</em> record (normally the Public Users record), using an entry in <em>pef_login_group</em>. <br>The <strong>system_public </strong>record can be linked to any permission groups and thus assigned permissions the normal way.</p>\n<p>Note, the&nbsp;<strong>default_url</strong>-field in the <em>pef_login </em>table<em> </em>for <strong>system_public </strong>is set to the login page. <br>This URL is activated whenever a user\'s PHP session expires. <br>It can be set to any container, but ensure that the user has the necessary rights to all containers being loaded.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc328-dib'),
    (329, 'Container Permissions', 23, 40, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Container permissions are specified under Container Details -&gt; Container Permissions in the Designer, or in the&nbsp;<em>pef_perm_container</em> table.</p>\n<p>For help with the various fields, click on a field in the Designer and then click the <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/helpButton.png" alt="" width="30" height="26">-icon.</p>\n<p>To allow a permission group the right to open a certain container, add a record referencing this permission group and container to the table, and tick the&nbsp;<em>open </em>field.</p>\n<p>If only the <em>open&nbsp;</em>field is ticked, the permission group will not be able to <strong>create, read, update&nbsp;</strong>or <strong>delete</strong><em> </em>any records in containers that are based on tables (eg. form and grid) - to allow these permissions, tick the appropriate ticks.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Note that user input items (eg inputText) that are bound to table fields are only displayed if the permission group has at least&nbsp;<strong>read </strong>or <strong>create </strong>rights. <strong>Update </strong>and <strong>delete </strong>rights only makes sense if the user can at least <strong>read </strong>the data.</p>\n<p>The system automatically disables/enables eg <strong>btnDelete </strong>and <strong>btnSave </strong>buttons etc. should the permgroup\'s <strong>update</strong>, <strong>create </strong>or <strong>delete </strong>permissions require it as the user navigates between creating and editing records. <br>This is based on the <em>pef_component.permissions</em>&nbsp;field.</p>\n<p>If the items or fields/columns in a container or record must be limited or hidden, then item level permissions must be specified in addition.</p>\n<h3>Criteria Fields</h3>\n<p>If certain conditions apply for opening the container, specify them in the <em>open_criteria </em>field. The criteria is evaluated using the ~navdocs(Criteria Evaluation, docs, EvalCriteria class)~ and User Parameter details of the current user.</p>\n<p>To limit the records that the permission group may <strong>read</strong>, <strong>update </strong>or <strong>delete</strong>, specify SQL&nbsp;criteria in the&nbsp;<em>criteria </em>field (the current record\'s existing values are available as parameters).<br>This SQL criteria will be added to the underlying container\'s SQL WHERE clause using the AND-operator.</p>\n<p>If values in new records, or new values in existing records (for update operations) must be limited, specify criteria in the&nbsp;<em>criteria_new </em>field (~navdocs(Criteria Evaluation, docs, EvalCriteria)~&nbsp;is used with the new values as parameters). <br>Note that the criteria will apply to all permissions that are ticked in that row (<em>criteria </em>for <strong>read</strong>, <strong>update&nbsp;</strong>and <strong>delete</strong>, and <em>criteria_new </em>for <strong>create </strong>and the new values in <strong>update</strong>).</p>\n<p>If for example&nbsp;<strong>`position` = \'staff\' </strong>should apply for viewing records, but<strong> `position` = \'manager\'</strong> should apply for changing, adding and deleting records, then two records must be added to the table for the specified container and permission group combination. <br>Any amount of records can be added with different criteria and combinations of permission fields ticked for a particular container and permission group.</p>\n<p>When the permissions are activated (moved to the "live"&nbsp;<em>pef_perm_active</em> table) the distinct criteria is combined as necessary for each permgroup.<br>The permissive OR operator is used to combine criteria of different rows, but the same container and permission type (eg <strong>read</strong>/<strong>create</strong>).</p>\n<p>The combined criteria can be viewed under Container Details -&gt; Active Permissions (the data may need to be refreshed).</p>\n<h3>More Info:</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>See the help available in the Designer for each field.</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexPermsContainer)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexPermSegmentDataByUser, Segment Data by User)~</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, '', 'doc329-dib'),
    (330, 'Item Permissions', 23, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Item permissions are specified under Item Details -&gt; Item Permissions in the Designer, or in the&nbsp;<em>pef_perm_item</em> table.<br>They specify permissions on items and fields/columns (as opposed to records/rows).</p>\n<p>For help with the various fields, click on a field in the Designer and then click the <img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/helpButton.png" alt="" width="30" height="26">-icon.</p>\n<p><strong>Note, also see ~nav(Dropinbase Services and Angular Directives)~ and ~navdocs(Excluding Items)~ to exclude/disable/hide items conditionally and dynamically at runtime.</strong></p>\n<p>By default a permission group has full item permissions.&nbsp;<strong>Read</strong>/<strong>update</strong>/<strong>delete </strong>permissions must be explicitly removed for each item.<br>This means Item permissions only have an effect where&nbsp;<strong>view/read, update </strong>or <strong>create</strong><em> </em>is <span style="text-decoration: underline;">unchecked</span>, BUT if criteria is involved, it must be&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration: underline;">checked</span>.</p>\n<p>For example, for <strong>view</strong>/<strong>read </strong>rights:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Items that are listed in the&nbsp;<em>pef_perm_item </em>table and <span style="text-decoration: underline;">unchecked</span> will not be visible.</li>\n<li>If&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration: underline;">checked</span> and criteria is involved, the criteria must evaluate to TRUE for the item to be visible.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The same logic applies for <strong>update </strong>and <strong>create</strong>.</p>\n<p>Also, setting item level permissions (eg <strong>update </strong>rights) has no effect if it has been revoked on container level. In other words, if container permissions does not allow an action, then it overrides item permissions that may permit it.</p>\n<div>\n<div>If any permission group of a user allows something, then that right is given. This means to remove a permission for a user, all their permission groups must agree about what&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration: underline;">cannot</span> be done.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Note: viewing an item (like a button) and reading data in an item (eg. <strong>first_name</strong> data in a textbox) both use&nbsp;<strong>read</strong> rights.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Items in the user-interface are displayed only if the permission group has at least <strong>read&nbsp;</strong>or&nbsp;<strong>create&nbsp;</strong>rights&nbsp;on a particular item (if a user does not have <strong>read </strong>rights, it makes no sense to give them <strong>update </strong>rights).</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Specifying Criteria</h3>\n<p>Item Permission Criteria only has an effect where containers are based on tables, items are bound to fields, and where <em>read</em>/<em>update</em>/<em>create</em> is checked.</p>\n<p>You will notice the table has two criteria fields, and both of them mention \'update\'.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The&nbsp;<em>Read/Create/Update Criteria</em> (<em>criteria) </em>field is evaluated with ~navdocs(Criteria Evaluation, EvalCriteria)~, and for updates, the criteria acts upon the new values that a user provides.</li>\n<li>The <em>Update Criteria</em> (<em>update_criteria) </em>field specifies a SQL condition which is added to the SQL WHERE-clause of the statement that does the update. It therefore acts upon existing values in the table.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>To allow a permission group to <strong>read,</strong>&nbsp;<strong>create or update </strong>data in certain fields under certain conditions, specify criteria in the <em>Read/Create/Update Criteria</em> (<em>criteria) </em>field and tick the appropiate field(s).<br>~navdocs(Criteria Evaluation, EvalCriteria)~ is used with the existing record values as parameters for <strong>read</strong>, and with the new values for <strong>create </strong>and<em> </em><strong>update</strong>. <br>Eg of criteria for&nbsp;<strong>create</strong>:&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; (<strong>:date_joined IS NULL AND :dibUser_user_type = \'admin\') OR :dibUser_user_level LIKE (1~$delimDb~3~$delimDb~5)</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>To allow rights to <strong>change </strong>data in certain fields under certain conditions, specify SQL criteria in the <em>Update Criteria</em> (<em>update_criteria) </em>field and tick the <em>update</em> field. <br>The SQL criteria is applied against the existing record\'s values.&nbsp;<br>Eg&nbsp;<strong>(person.date_joined &lt;&nbsp; DATE_ADD(CURDATE(),INTERVAL -10 day) AND :dibUser_permgroup = \'admin\') OR :dibUser_user_level IN (1,3,5)</strong>.</p>\n<p>As with container level permissions, multiple records can be used for the same item and permission group.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>For each item and permission type (eg <strong>read </strong>or <strong>update</strong>), the <em>criteria </em>/ <em>update_criteria </em>is combined using the permissive OR operator.<br>The combined criteria is then stored as an expression in the <em>pef_perm_field_active </em>table which can be viewed in the Designer under Container Details -&gt; Active Permissions.</p>\n<p><strong>Generated Code in the PHP Crud Class</strong></p>\n<p>For each of the fields that had <em>Read/Create/Update Criteria</em> (<em>criteria),&nbsp;</em>a call is made to EvalCriteria to evaluate the (combined) criteria expression for that field. <br>If the validation fails for a <strong>create </strong>or <strong>update</strong>, then the whole operation fails. If it fails for a read operation, the that record\'s field value is returned as NULL (the rest of the values are still returned).</p>\n<p>As mentioned, the <em>Update Criteria</em> (<em>update_criteria)</em> is evaluated using SQL. <br>A SQL WHERE clause is constructed by combining the (combined) criteria for each of the fields using the restrictive AND operator.<br>This also means that if the criteria for any of the fields fail the test, then the whole UPDATE statement fails.</p>\n<div><strong>Example:</strong></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>I\'m a manager and can see data in a field only if :<strong>status=\'manager\'</strong>. I\'m also a staff which can never see the data (<strong>item perm.read = 0</strong>).</div>\n<div>In this case the criteria for manager will be applied. If however staff can see the data when :<strong>status=\'staff\'</strong>,</div>\n<div>then the following must be true to SHOW the data:&nbsp;<strong>(:status=\'manager\') OR (:status=\'staff\')</strong>.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><strong>More Info:</strong></div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>See the help available in the Designer for each field.</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexPermsItem)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexPermSegmentDataByUser, Segment Data by User)~</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, '', 'doc330-dib'),
    (331, 'Overview of Permission Tables', 23, 70, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Permissions and security are managed using the following tables:</p>\n<table style="width: 100%;" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;"><strong>Table</strong></td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;"><strong>Notes</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">\n<p>~navdocs(pef_login,table)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibLoginGrid,Login)~</p>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">User logins and related settings. Also used to define a user\'s security policy (see next row), and the default URL that opens when the user logs-in.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">~navdocs(pef_security_policy,table)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibSecurityPolicyGrid,Security Policy)~</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">Stores settings for security policies that can be attached to logins for such things as password complexity and expiry.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">~nav(dibSqlForm,The where_clause field in pef_sql)~</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">Limit records returned by SQL statements for grids and dropdown lists. Can contain PDO parameters that are evaluated against the current user\'s login record.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">~navdocs(pef_perm_group,table)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibPermGroupGrid,Perm Group)~</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">Define permission groups, each with their start and expiry dates.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">~navdocs(pef_login_group,table)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibLoginGroupGrid,Login Group)~</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">\n<p>Associate logins to permission groups in a many-to-many relationship (a login can be in many permission groups, and each permission group can have many logins linked to it). Each association has a start and expiry date.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">\n<p>~navdocs(pef_perm_container,table)~<br>More Info: ~navdocs(Container Permissions)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibDesigner,Design Container Permissions)~</p>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">\n<p>Permissions on container and record level. Incorporates criteria on opening a container, and CRUD (create, read(view), update (change - permissions configurable on new and old values) and delete) actions. <br>Global permissions on container and item events can also be specified.<br>Note, permissions and criteria to open a container and execute events affects containers of any dropin type.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">~navdocs(pef_perm_item,table)~<br>More Info: ~navdocs(Item Permissions)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibDesigner,Design Item Permissions)~</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">Permissions on item level. Incorporates criteria on CRUD actions (only create, read and update (delete is not applicable)).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">~navdocs(pef_perm_container_event,table)~<br>More Info: ~navdocs(Event Permissions, Container Event Permissions)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibDesigner,Design Container Event Permissions)~</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">Permissions for events on container level. Note, the <em>container_events</em> field in the <em>pef_perm_container </em>table can be used as a global setting to allow/disallow all custom events on a container. <br>If it is set to 0 then no events will execute, even if permissions are assigned in the <em>pef_perm_container_event</em> table.&nbsp;<br>If it is set to 1, and there are no permissions specified in the Perm Container Event table, then all custom events will fire for this container. <br>If it is set to 1 and there are any permissions specified in the Perm Container Event table, then only those specified will fire.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">\n<p>~navdocs(pef_perm_item_event,table)~<br>More Info: ~navdocs(Event Permissions, Item Event Permissions)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibDesigner,Design Item Event Permissions)~</p>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">Permissions for events on item level. Note, the <em>item_events</em> field in the <em>pef_perm_container </em>table works exactly the same as specified above for the <em>container_events</em> field - just for item events...</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">~navdocs(pef_perm_active,table)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibDesigner,Active Permissions)~</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">Best viewed in the Designer (<strong>Active Permissions</strong>-button). A systems table that stores the "live" combined permissions against Permgroups and containers. <br>It is automatically maintained when permissions expire, but can also be manually updated by an Administrator.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">\n<p>~navdocs(pef_perm_field_active,table)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibDesigner,Item Active Permissions)~</p>\n</td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">A systems table that stores the "live" combined permissions that have criteria of the <em>pef_perm_item </em>table against Permgroups. It is automatically maintained when permissions expire, but can also be manually updated by an Administrator.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style="width: 21.3639%;">~navdocs(pef_perm_item_list_active,table)~<br>Configure: ~nav(dibDesigner,Item List Active Permissions)~<br><br></td>\n<td style="width: 78.6361%;">A systems table that stores the "live" combined permissions that Pergroups have to the data returned in dropdown lists. It is automatically maintained when permissions expire, but can also be manually updated by an Administrator.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, '', 'doc331-dib'),
    (333, 'System Development Basics', 39, 20, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc333-dib'),
    (334, 'Build a Winning Solution', 333, 10, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>System development is an art.</p>\n<p>There can be many different "solutions" to a problem. Some will succeed, but the reality is that most don\'t fair well.</p>\n<p>A modern system like Dropinbase affords a agile and structured approach to build and maintain a "winning" system, however it is important to implement the basic principles inherent to a successful project, some of which are:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Careful Planning:</strong> Invest time in research and planning where necessary, which will save effort and resources in the long run.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Expectation Management:</strong> Ensure that there is clarity and agreement regarding what the client (and the team) expects ito timelines, payments, quality and ongoing work.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Match System Design with Needs:</strong> Ensure that the system design closely aligns with the actual needs it\'s intended to address.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Eliminate Grey Areas AFAP:&nbsp;</strong>Most of a project\'s budget is often spent on areas that are not well defined or the expertise/know-how to do it is lacking, which can have severe results.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Phased Development Approach:</strong> Adopt a phased approach including requirement research, prototyping, and iterative development with user feedback.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Early and Continuous Feedback:</strong> Involve users early and often, allowing them to use the system even in its developmental stages for better feedback.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Minimum Viable Product (MVP):</strong>&nbsp;Focus on developing and implementing the most needed portion of the project first, and build it out from there.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>User-Centric Design:</strong> The end-user experience must be prioritized in design decisions.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Minimize Need for Comments with Structured Code:</strong> Write well-structured code that is self-explanatory, reducing the need for extensive comments.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Mentorship and AI:</strong> A good mentor and AI tools can save a lot of time.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Leverage Experience:</strong>&nbsp;Recognize the value of experience in system development.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Well-Structured Database Design:</strong> Place a high emphasis on a robust and efficient database design, which is the foundations of a system.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Focus on Maintainable Code:</strong>&nbsp;Prioritize writing maintainable code over "clever" or overly complex code.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Simplicity and Clarity:</strong>&nbsp;Simple and clean solutions are often more effective and easier to maintain.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Scalability and Flexibility:</strong> Design systems that can easily scale and adapt to future needs.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Strict Naming Conventions and Protocols:</strong> facilitates the development processes and team work.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Adherence to Standards and Best Practices:</strong>&nbsp;Follow industry standards and best practices to ensure quality and consistency.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Security and Privacy:</strong> Incorporate strong security measures and respect user privacy from the outset.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Performance Optimization:</strong>&nbsp;Continuously optimize for performance to enhance user experience.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Cross-Platform Compatibility:</strong> Ensure the system works seamlessly across various devices and platforms.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Continuous Integration and Deployment:</strong> Implement CI/CD practices for regular and automated testing and deployment.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Useful Documentation:</strong> This is important for onboarding, maintenance and succession management.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Collaboration and Communication:</strong> Foster an environment of open communication and teamwork.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Sustainable Development Practices:</strong> Consider the environmental impact and practice sustainable development.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Cultural and Ethical Considerations:</strong> Be mindful of cultural and ethical aspects in system design and implementation.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc334-dib'),
    (335, 'Strict Naming Conventions', 333, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Proper and strict naming conventions in especially the underlying databases greatly facilitates the development process. Conventions and protocols creates clean and workable structures, assists team work, and helps to avoid frustrating typos and the need to look up spellings of names.</p>\n<p>Investigate the designs of the Dropinbase database tables as examples.</p>\n<h4>Table and field name guidelines</h4>\n<ol>\n<li>Names must clearly state the use/purpose of fields and tables and exclude ambiguity</li>\n<li>Avoid abbreviations except if names become very long, or the abbreviation is more commonly used.</li>\n<li>Avoid plural forms of all names\n<ol>\n<li>Some names just don\'t work well in the plural form, and its not always easy to remember if the plural form was used).</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Avoid composite primary keys for tables.</li>\n<li>Avoid using fields that users edit as primary key values, since contrary to what clients may claim, these values do change, split or merge in future.</li>\n<li>Use an auto-increment integer named <strong>id</strong> as primary key name</li>\n<li>Names should use alpha-numeric characters and underscore (_) only.</li>\n<li>Use lowercase for all names.</li>\n<li>Use underscore (_) to separate words in names.</li>\n<li>Tables that relate to a "primary" table must include the primary table name as prefix, eg <strong>person_role</strong>.</li>\n<li>Foreign key names must consist of the table name they relate to and suffixed with \'<strong>_id</strong>\', eg&nbsp;<strong>person_id</strong> points to the <strong>person</strong> table.\n<ol>\n<li>If more than one field in the table relates to the same primary table, use descriptive names in this case suffixed with <strong>_id&nbsp;</strong>(eg <strong>advisor_id </strong>and <strong>manager_id</strong>).</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Preferably use \'<strong>name</strong>\' for the main display field in a table<strong>. </strong>Other protocol names for often used fields: <strong>code</strong>, <strong>short_name, notes, updated, created</strong></li>\n<li>Suffix date fields with _<strong>date </strong>(eg <strong>start_date</strong>), time fields with _<strong>time,</strong> and datetime fields with&nbsp;_<strong>dt</strong>.</li>\n<li>Use the MySQL enum field type where dropdown list options are fixed. However if there is a chance that users must edit these lists, then create a lookup table with the following basic structure:&nbsp;<strong>id</strong>, <strong>name </strong>(other fields can be added eg <strong>code</strong>, <strong>notes</strong>, etc).</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Note, if the same names are used in PHP, they are easier to remember and developers can conveniently copy-paste them which saves a lot of time and typos.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc335-dib'),
    (336, 'Why Not An ORM', 94, 60, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>Instead of implementing a classic ORM (Object Relational Mapping) class by default, Dropinbase opted for using native SQL for the following reasons (in no order of priority):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Developers don\'t need to learn another ORM\'s syntax. If they know SQL they can execute queries in Dropinbase.</li>\n<li>There are many ORM\'s. Implementing one will not satisfy everyone\'s preferences</li>\n<li>Learning SQL opens many doors (basics are simple).</li>\n<li>It is however easy to implement a favourite ORM as a Dropinbase dropin :-).</li>\n<li>ORM\'s are often large and complex libraries which execute slower than native SQL.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>ORM\'s are always limitted to a certain degree.</li>\n<li>The basic SQL syntax is already very compatible between the various database engines. Dropinbase stives to offers ways to automatically translate the syntax where needed.</li>\n<li>Documentation for ORM\'s is sometimes lacking, where there is exhaustive documentation and examples for SQL.</li>\n<li>ORM\'s syntax is forced to be complicated and clumsy to handle complicated SQL. Often one can write a few lines of SQL vs many lines of code and ORM calls.</li>\n<li>Most applications will never need to migrate to another database engine.</li>\n<li>ORM\'s are typically used to handle CRUD operations, where the Dropinbase Database and Crud classes facilitate it in an optimized manner.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc336-dib'),
    (337, 'Information Gathering', 333, 45, 0, 'none', '<p>Clients often request interviews with, and quotes from more than one supplier before they make a final choice. "Winning" the deal is made much easier with the benefits that Dropinbase brings, but remember that accepting the responsibility is engaging in a long-term relationship. For large and complex projects, it is important to establish if the partnership is a fit and be prepared to decline after consideration.</p>\n<p>Your first meeting sets the stage:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Be confident with a friendly demeanor, and take a team member with you.</li>\n<li>Provide a background of your company and past successes.</li>\n<li>Explain the important advantages of using Dropinbase and the long-term support environment that goes with it.</li>\n<li>Conduct a demo of Dropinbase, showcasing its capabilities which gives them a hand-on feel for what to expect.</li>\n<li>Listen very carefully and understand their specific challenges clearly, and how Dropinbase can assist. This is of utmost importance to gain their confidence.\n<ul>\n<li>If you listen carefully you may uncover more business than you expected.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Suggest a phased development approach with frequent, accessible online prototypes.</li>\n<li>Throw something of interest in for free.</li>\n<li>Establish their budget and deadlines for a Minimal Viable Product.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Here is a more elaborate list which focusses on Information Gathering. Recognize that not everyone\'s core skill is project management, but good project management is essential for success.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Clarify Purpose</strong>: Understand and elaborate on the client\'s initial idea of the system\'s purpose. Highlight potential possibilities they may not have considered.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Beyond Data Storage</strong>: Keep in mind the purpose of a properly designed bussiness application. It\'s a tool for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Streamlining business processes and task flows</li>\n<li>Enhancing communication within departments and with external entities like clients and suppliers</li>\n<li>Automating repetitive tasks</li>\n<li>Managing resources</li>\n<li>Facilitating growth</li>\n<li>Controlling quality and compliance</li>\n<li>Simplifying record keeping and auditing</li>\n<li>Providing business intelligence (eg. statistics)</li>\n<li>Enhancing staff experience</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Executive Summary</strong>: Gather information about the company&rsquo;s core functions and define the primary objectives of the new system.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-sourcepos="44:1-44:80"><strong>Active Listening:</strong>&nbsp;Be attentive to unspoken needs and implicit information.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Current Systems Analysis</strong>: Evaluate existing systems, identifying their strengths and weaknesses. Request any existing documentation to understand business operations.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Identify Stakeholders and Relationships</strong>: Determine all entities involved (e.g., staff, products, clients) and their relationships (e.g., 1-to-1, many-to-many) for creating an Entity-Relationship (ER) diagram. Identifying and listing entities is key to provide structure.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Business Rules Definition</strong>: Document business rules clearly for client approval and developer implementation. Use tools like diagrams or spreadsheet tables for easy understanding.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Process Mapping</strong>: Chart the flow of information or objects between stakeholders, noting any transformations or conditions. Use flowcharts where beneficial.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Output Requirements</strong>: Understand the required outputs of the system, including essential reports. Request examples (in eg. Excel) as a baseline.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Project Phasing</strong>: Break down the project into manageable phases for better control and tracking.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>SMART Objectives: </strong>define<strong> </strong>Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound objectives where possible<strong>.</strong> Provide clear benchmarks for success.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>System Integration and Environment</strong>: Assess how the new system will integrate with existing systems and processes.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>User Analysis</strong>: Identify the users, their roles, tasks, and existing computer skills. Determine the devices they will use and their usage patterns.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Security Considerations</strong>: Define system security and permission constraints, focusing on user perspectives and requirements.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Technology and Design Needs</strong>: Estimate the volume of data (records per year), number of concurrent users, peak usage periods, and device types for various functions.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Hosting Requirements</strong>: Determine hosting needs based on system size and expected traffic.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Maintenance and Dependencies</strong>: Plan for system maintenance and identify any dependencies or external factors that could impact the system.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Feedback Loops</strong>: Establish channels for ongoing client feedback throughout the development process to ensure alignment with business needs.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Client Buy-in:</strong> Establish key contacts at the client that will be responsible to ensure success of the project from the client\'s side. Your main allies. This may be per department/phase.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Risk Assessment</strong>: Identify potential risks and challenges, and develop mitigation strategies.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Training and Support</strong>: Plan for user training and post-deployment support to ensure smooth adoption and usage.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Cost Analysis</strong>: Provide a clear cost breakdown for development, deployment, and maintenance.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Legal and Compliance Checks</strong>: Ensure the system meets all relevant legal and regulatory requirements.</p>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Shared Platforms:&nbsp;</strong>Use collaborative tools and documentation platforms to share requirements and track progress with stakeholders.</li>\n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc337-dib'),
    (338, 'How to Do It', 264, 20, 1, 'eleutheria', '<p>The documentation and examples are categorised into courses, from basic to advanced.</p>\n<p>Since our capacity to offer support is limitted, the idea is to offer the opportunity to anyone who successfully completes the tests associated with the levels to become support personal, and offer development services.<br>Their service will be rated, and they will earn an hourly rate related to their level of expertise and experience with full-stack development.</p>\n<p>More information about the tests to follow soon.</p>\n<p>Also see ~navdocs(Support and Help, docs, Official Support and Help)~.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc338-dib'),
    (339, 'Trees', 265, 50, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc339-dib'),
    (340, 'Database Server Settings', 105, 47, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p><strong>Please note that changing settings may cause malfunctioning (or damage!), especially if they are not set correctly. <br>Keep a backup of your old settings files, and proceed at your own risk.</strong></p>\n<h3>MySQL / MariaDb</h3>\n<p>Locate the my.ini or my.cnf file for your MySQL/MariaDb server installation. <br>Save the file after editing it in a text editor, and then reboot the MySQL/MariaDb server. <br>The following are suggested settings from the community, although the character-set configurations are required. Depending on your requirements, you will need fine-tune them.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>max_allowed_packet=64M</li>\n<li>sort_buffer_size=4M</li>\n<li>read_buffer_size=4M</li>\n<li>group_concat_max_len=20000</li>\n<li>default_storage_engine=InnoDB</li>\n<li>innodb_file_format=Barracuda</li>\n<li>innodb_file_per_table=1</li>\n<li>innodb_buffer_pool_size = 256M</li>\n<li>innodb_log_buffer_size=64M</li>\n<li>innodb_log_file_size=64M</li>\n<li><strong>[mysql]</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>default_character_set=utf8mb4</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>[mysqld]</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>character-set-server=utf8mb4</li>\n<li>collation_server=utf8mb4_unicode_520_ci</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc340-dib'),
    (341, 'Navigation', 261, 55, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc341-dib'),
    (342, 'Client Data', 261, 65, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc342-dib'),
    (343, 'Dropinbase Services', 261, 75, 1, 'eleutheria', NULL, NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc343-dib'),
    (344, 'Intermediate', 338, 20, 0, 'eleutheria', '<ul>\n<li>Styling the Application and Login Pages</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexGridHeadersAndStyling, Add Headers and Styling to Grids)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexNgStyle, Conditional Styling)~</li>\n<li>Implement Custom Columns in ~nav(dibexGridCustomColumns, Table Grids)~ and ~nav(dibexGridSqlCustomColumns, SQL Grids)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Client Data, docs, Learn about Client Data)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Get and Set User Interface Values)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexSqlParams, Use Parameters in SQL)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexEventBasics, Learn about Client-side and Server-side Events)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexActionBasics, Learn about Client-side Actions)~ / ~nav(dibexActionPrompt, Prompts)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexPhpBasics, PHP Basics)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexPhpDatabase, Execute Database commands with PHP)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Dropinbase Services, docs, Use Dropinbase Services)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexPermSegmentDataByUser, Segment Data by User)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Reports, docs, Create Reports)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexiFrameEleutheria, Use Eleutheria to Build Custom Reports)~ / ~navdocs(Eleutheria, docs, Eleutheria Functions)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Permissions and Business Rules, docs, Deep Dive into the Permission System)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Security, docs, Tighten Security)~</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Test</h2>\n<p>Build a fully production-ready web-application with Dropinbase. The following are minimal requirements. <br><strong>Note, do not present copies of the existing examples - all work must be original and your own.</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Install Dropinbase on a public webserver.</li>\n<li>Create a user database with 5 tables (or more) which includes one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships.</li>\n<li>Build a Dropinbase web application to view and edit records in all these tables. The following features must be present:</li>\n<ol>\n<li>Styled authentication pages (including styled forgot-my-password page etc).</li>\n<li>Themed application styling using .scss.</li>\n<li>Grid(s) with multiple header levels and conditional styling.</li>\n<li>Custom columns in grids, including the use of an <strong>after readmany</strong> event that creates an extra column with sanitized HTML for display in a unsafe component in the grid</li>\n<li>Interpolation using conditions and getValue() (on form/plain)</li>\n<li>Use Dropinbase Fill In values on a button that opens popup form on a new record and sets a value.</li>\n<li>Implement an <strong>afterviewInit</strong> container event that calls a client-side action and sets a value.</li>\n<li>Implement a <strong>after delete</strong> container event that returns a client-side action presenting a prompt. The user\'s answer is written to the Debug Log.</li>\n<li>Pass Client Data to a PHP function, database commands with ::fetch() ::execute() and ::update() and return a client-side action that sets sanitized HTML in an unsafe HTML component.</li>\n<li>Introduce a new Environment variable value in /configs/Environment.php related to the current user, and reference it in an *ngIf.</li>\n<li>Set a global custom data variable and make use of it server-side in PHP.</li>\n<li>Implement client-side default values on a form using @{value_xxx_yyy)</li>\n<li>Implement server-side default values on a form using a custom :dibUser_ parameter set in /configs/DibUserParams.php.</li>\n<li>Implement permission criteria using parameters on grid rows.</li>\n<li>Implement item and item event permissions for only certain users (in a permission group).</li>\n<li>Create eg. a \'client_id\' value in pef_login and add it User Parameters. Use this to segment data per user with permission criteria.</li>\n<li>Create a report containing a chart and a grid, filtered on a selected user. The report must have a print button.</li>\n</ol>\n<li>Use an iframe to create a report with the following Eleutheria features:\n<ol>\n<li>A grid with conditional colors or features per row</li>\n<li>Make use of the following Eleutheria functions/features:</li>\n<ol>\n<li>setMainDb()</li>\n<li>nested domains</li>\n<li>nested if() statements</li>\n<li>incl()</li>\n<li>encode()</li>\n</ol>\n</ol>\n&gt;</li>\n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc344-dib'),
    (345, 'Advanced', 338, 30, 0, 'eleutheria', '<ul>\n\n<li>~navdocs(PHP, docs, Dropinbase PHP Functions)~</li>\n\n<li>~nav(dibexQueue, Long Running Server-side Code with Progress Updates)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexSqlParamsPhp, Alter SQL with PHP before it is Executed)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexiFramePhp, Display Custom HTML in an Iframe)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexDefaultValuesServer, PHP Powered Default Values)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexEventBasics, Table Events)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexGridDynamicColumns, Implement Dynamic Columns in Grids)~</li>\n<li>~navdocs(Trees, docs, Create Interactive Trees)~</li>\n<li>~nav(dibexCalendar, Create an Updatable Calendar)~</li>\n\n<li>~navdocs(Custom Components, docs, Create a Custom Angular Component)~</li>\n<li>Create a Custom Angular Action</li>\n\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Test</h2>\nBuild a fully production-ready web-application with Dropinbase. The following are minimal requirements.\n<br><b>Note, do not present copies of the existing examples or use the example test_ tables - all work must be original and your own.</b>\n<ol>\n<li>Install Dropinbase on a public webserver</li>\n<li>Create a user database with 5 tables (or more) which includes one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships.</li>\n<li>Build a Dropinbase web application to view and edit records in all these tables. \n<br>Read through the requirements below and plan your work. \n<br>The following features must be present:</li>\n<ol>\n    <li>A button that presents a Yes/No popup question. On \'No\', an action hides a card. On \'Yes\' a long-running script (5-10sec) is started which uses a Queue to update a progress bar and when completed, presents some answer.</li>\n    <li>A SQL Grid based a query where the from-clause is dynamically altered based on the user\'s permission group.</li>\n    <li>Create a PHP function that accepts a Client Data input, and creates the HTML for a table related to the input, and display it in an iframe.</li>\n    <li>Create a button that downloads the custom (filtered) table in the previous bullet point as a PDF document.</li>\n    <li>Create a button that writes the custom (filtered) table data in the previous bullet point to a .xlsx document.</li>\n    <li>A form that loads default values from custom PHP.</li>\n    <li>Use Table Events to do validation on certain tables before updating or deleting records. If validation fails, display a helpful message.</li>\n    <li>Build a grid displaying pivot-table style columns using Dynamic Columns.</li>\n    \n    <li>Create a Tree displaying hierarchial data. Implement the ability to drag-and-drop nodes, and change their display values.</li>\n    <li>Create your own updatable calendar for events listed in a table.</li>\n    \n    <li>Create a custom Angular component which displays data in a table, filtered by Client Data. Values in one column of the table must be editable, and automatically stored in the database table.</li>\n    \n    <li>Create a custom Angular action - surprise us!</li>\n    <li>Server- and client-side validation on certain fields.</li>\n\n</ol>\n<li>Make use of the following in your PHP:\n<ol>\n    <li>Database::execute()</li>\n    <li>Database::fetch()</li>\n    <li>Database::update() with the audit trail parameter</li>\n    <li>Database::delete()</li>\n    <li>Database::create()</li>\n    <li>Database::transactionBegin()</li>\n    <li>Database::transactionCommit()</li>\n    <li>Database::transactionRollback()</li>\n    <li>Crud::read()</li>\n    <li>Crud::update()</li>\n    <li>DibFunctions::getGridCritAndParams()</li>\n    <li>---</li>\n    <li>Log::err()</li>\n    <li>Log::w()</li>\n    \n</ol>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc345-dib'),
    (346, 'Move the Login and Other Tables', 105, 35, 0, 'none', '<p>The Dropinbase tables below need not be in the main Dropinbase database. It is advisable for backup and security reasons to move them to your "user" database, so that all the "user" tables can be managed together. Because of its potential size, you want to move the pef_audit_trail table to its own database.</p>\n<table class="dibTable">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Table(s)</th>\n<th>Variable to Update</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>pef_login <br>pef_login_group <br>pef_perm_group <br>pef_two_factor <br>pef_security_policy</td>\n<td>$LOGINDB</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>pef_audit_trail</td>\n<td>$AUDITDB</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>pef_error_log</td>\n<td>$ERRORLOGDB</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<h3>Steps</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Use HeidiSQL or DBeaver or the like to export them to the chosen database.</li>\n<li>Delete them from the Dropinbase database.</li>\n<li>Set the relevant variables in the&nbsp;<strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> and <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> files.</li>\n<li>Under Database Tasks -&gt; Table Tasks click the <strong>Detect Changes-</strong>button to detect the new tables. Then set the Ignore field on these tables so that they are not imported.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc346-dib'),
    (347, 'incl_serversideContainerEvents', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<p>Container Events like <b>after update</b> call your own functions from the generated CRUD code.\r\n<br>The code for triggering these Container Events is generated into these Crud classes.\r\n<br>The class targeted by a Container Event must be in a <strong>/components </strong>folder.</p>\r\n<p>Eg. <strong>/dropins/myDropin/ContainerEvent/afterUpdate</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;- URI specified on <strong>after update</strong> Container Event<br>will execute the following function:</p>\r\n<p>/dropins/myDropin/components/ContainerEvent.php -&gt; <code>public function afterUpdate($containerName, $attributes, $trigger, $recordOld, $validAttributes, $clientData)</code></p>\r\n<p>Each type of trigger, eg <strong>before update,</strong>&nbsp;assumes the function it is calling has a specific set of parameters.</p>\r\n<div>\r\n<div><strong>before readone</strong>, &nbsp;<strong>before readmany</strong>, <strong>before readoneinit</strong>, <strong>before readmanyinit</strong>:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <code>$containerName, &amp;$criteriaParams, $trigger, $gridFilter, &amp;$criteria, $sql</code></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>after readone</strong>, &nbsp;<strong>after readmany</strong>:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <code>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger, $filterParams</code></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>before update</strong>:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <code>$containerName, &amp;$attributes, $trigger, $recordOld, $clientData</code></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>after update</strong>:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <code>$containerName, $attributes, $trigger, $recordOld, $validAttributes, $clientData</code></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>get defaults</strong>, <strong>before create</strong>, <strong>after create</strong>, <strong>before delete</strong>, <strong>after delete</strong>:</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <code>$containerName, &amp;$attributes, $trigger, $clientData</code></div>\r\n<br>\r\n<div>Note that parameters such as <strong>$attributes</strong> and <strong>$validAttributes</strong> can be received by reference (eg <strong>&amp;$attributes</strong>) which is useful on the \'before\' and \'get defaults\' events. Values can be manipulated before storing them.</div>\r\n<br>\r\n<div>Return boolean TRUE if normal code execution should continue. To cancel execution of any further code in the calling Crud class:</div>\r\n<pre>return array(\'cancel\', $message);</pre>\r\n\r\n<div>where $message will be displayed to the user.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Consequently, to change audit trail info being captured for a specific container, set <strong>$attributes </strong>on \'after create\' or <strong>$validAttributes</strong> on \'after update\'.</div>\r\n<br>\r\n<div>Note, delete the generated Crud class after any change in <strong>pef_container_event</strong>, <strong>pef_container</strong>, <strong>pef_item, pef_perm_container </strong>etc. that may affect it. The&nbsp;Crud class code is regenerated on demand.</div>\r\n</div>', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc347-dib'),
