    (349, 'Event Execution', 39, 50, 0, 'eleutheria', '<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Event Triggers</span></h3>\n<p>There are various triggers in Dropinbase that can execute PHP:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Item Events\n<ul>\n<li>linked to an item (use the "<strong>ADD - PHP"</strong> or "<strong>ADD - CLIENT ACTION"</strong> wizard buttons in the Designer to quickly add)</li>\n<li>triggered client-side and calls a controller function</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Container Events\n<ul>\n<li>linked to a container (use the&nbsp;"<strong>ADD - PHP"</strong> or "<strong>ADD - CLIENT ACTION"</strong>&nbsp;wizard buttons&nbsp;in the Designer to quickly add)</li>\n<li>triggered client-side and calls a controller function, <strong>or</strong></li>\n<li>triggered server-side in generated CRUD files and calls a component function</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Table Events\n<ul>\n<li>linked to tables, using the Table Events field on a table record, or in the Designer under Container Details</li>\n<li>triggered server-side and calls the TableEvents.php component -&gt;<code> function trigger</code> in a dropin folder</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>See the ~nav(dibexEventBasics)~ and ~nav(dibexPhpBasics)~ for more info.</p>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Dropinbase URI\'s</span></h3>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Dropinbase exposes its functionality using the following 3 forms of URI\'s, in a REST API (although PHP sessions are used to maintain state).&nbsp;<br>These URI\'s are configured by a developer on Item and Container Events, or called from generated user-interface code to for eg. read a grid\'s records. The URI\'s always target controller functions.</span></p>\n<p><code>/peff/DROPINBASE_NATIVE_CONTROLLER/FUNCTION</code></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 40px;">Eg&nbsp;<strong>/peff/Crud/read</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li style="list-style-type: none;">\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Performs CRUD (create, read, update, delete) operations.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Mostly called from generated user-interface code, but developers can use these URI\'s in their own custom components or JavaScript code.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Executes the CRUD function (eg read or componentlist) in a PHP class named&nbsp;<strong>CrudController </strong>stored here: /vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/controllers/CrudController.php</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Always returns a JSON result</span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><code>/dropins/DROPIN/CONTROLLER/FUNCTION</code></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 40px;">Eg&nbsp;<strong>/dropins/myDropin/MyController/myFunction</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li style="list-style-type: none;">\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Executes the <strong>myFunction </strong>function&nbsp;</span>in a PHP class named&nbsp;<strong>MyController</strong> in a file named <strong>MyController.php </strong><span style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">(case-sensitive!)</span><br>(Note, class names are always the same as the file names, and the case is determined by the name of the controller in the URI).</li>\n<li>The type of result is determined by the event\'s <strong>Response Type</strong> field (see help for this field in the Designer)</li>\n<li>Custom dropins override Dropinbase core dropins. Upon receiving this URI, the Dropinbase core framework first looks for the <strong>MyController.php</strong> file under\n<ul>\n<li>&nbsp;/dropins/myDropin/controllers/</li>\n<li>If not found, look under /vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/myDropin/controllers/</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><code>/dropins/setPARENTDROPIN/DROPIN/CONTROLLER/FUNCTIONNAME</code></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 40px;">Eg&nbsp;<strong>/dropins/setUser/admin/Account/delete</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li style="list-style-type: none;">\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Sets assist in providing more structure to code files, by grouping related dropins together.&nbsp;</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">The PARENTDROPIN name must begin with \'<strong>set</strong>\'.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">eg <strong>/dropins/setTest/myDropin/MyController/myFunction</strong></span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Executes the&nbsp;<strong>myFunction&nbsp;</strong>function&nbsp;</span>in a PHP class named&nbsp;<strong>MyController</strong>&nbsp;in a file named&nbsp;<strong>MyController.php </strong><span style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">(case-sensitive!)</span>.</li>\n<li>Custom dropins override Dropinbase dropins:\n<ul>\n<li>First look for the&nbsp;<strong>MyController.php</strong>&nbsp;file under /dropins/setTest/myDropin/controllers/</li>\n<li>If not found, look for it under /vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/setTest/myDropin/controllers/</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">The various item and container events make use of the above URI\'s to issue requests. View these requests in the browser\'s Developer Tools (press F12 in Chrome) -&gt; Network-tab.</span></p>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Permission Checks, Cache Records and Files</span></h3>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">The permission system checks at runtime if the user executing the URI has the rights to do so. A cache of the allowed URI\'s is maintained in the <strong>pef_perm_active </strong>table (<em>item_event_detail</em>, <em>container_event_detail </em>fields) for use at runtime.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial; color: rgb(224, 62, 45);"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">See</span> the important note below about the <span style="text-decoration: underline;">function parameters</span> that must be present to enable permission checking.</span></span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Furthermore</span><span style="font-family: Arial;">, if the <strong>$VERIFY_AUTH_TOKEN</strong> variable in <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong> is TRUE, then requests must also include the <strong>RequestVerificationToken </strong>header value (generated at user login and sent to the client via \'<strong>auth_id</strong>\' in <strong>Environment.php</strong>). This is why simply copying the URI to a new browser window will not work. Note, the <strong>dibCurl</strong> dropin caters for this header and can be used to sign-in to and access another Dropinbase API programmatically using CURL.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">If a URI changes, use the Designer to remove the related container\'s <strong>pef_perm_active </strong>records and the generated UI files (which contains the URI\'s)&nbsp;so that they can be regenerated again, else the new URI will not be called and/or not be allowed.</span></p>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Function Parameters, Client Data and REQUEST_TYPE</span></h3>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Each of the above URI\'s call PHP functions (in PHP classes) with very specific function parameters.&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">For Item Events:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code><span style="font-family: Arial;">public function myFunction(<strong>$containerName, $itemEventId</strong>, $clientData=[], $itemAlias=null, $itemId=null, $triggerType=null)</span></code></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">For Container Events:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code><span style="font-family: Arial;">public function myFunction(<strong>$containerName, $containerEventId</strong>, $clientData=[], $itemAlias=null, $containerId=null, $triggerType=null)</span></code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>If&nbsp;<strong>$containerName</strong> is present, then a check is done to see whether the user may execute this URI on the specific container. This is the "normal" case, and all public controller functions should have <strong>$containerName</strong>.</p>\n<p>If it is not present then Dropinbase checks for permissions configured on the container specified in&nbsp;<strong>Dib.php</strong> in the <strong>$DEFAULTPERMSCONTAINER</strong> variable. If this variable is empty then a container named \'<strong>noDefaultPermsContainerSpecified</strong>\' is assumed. If this container does not exist, then Dropinbase will throw a permissions error.</p>\n<p>To avoid checking container-based permissions which makes a function open to the public, include the&nbsp;<strong>$REQUEST_TYPE</strong> function parameter with a default of <span style="font-family: Arial;">\'<strong>ignorecontainerperms</strong>\', eg.</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code><span style="font-family: Arial;">public function myPublicFunction($clientData=[], $itemAlias=null, $REQUEST_TYPE=\'POST,ignorecontainerperms\')</span></code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Note, the <strong>$REQUEST_TYPE</strong> parameter can also be used to avoid checking for the auth token (the <span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>RequestVerificationToken </strong></span>&nbsp;sent with each request) using \'<strong>ignoretoken</strong>\', and to specify which type of browser requests are allowed, eg GET and/or POST (by default only POST requests are allowed). Requests that return HTML content or file downloads will typically include GET. Eg:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code><span style="font-family: Arial;">$REQUEST_TYPE=\'GET,POST,ignoretoken\'</span></code></li>\n<li><code><span style="font-family: Arial;">$REQUEST_TYPE=\'POST,ignoretoken,ignorecontainerperms\'</span></code></li>\n<li>etc.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If&nbsp;<strong>$itemEventId</strong> is present, then a check is done to see if the user may call the specific implementation of the URI on the container. This is strictly only necessary if for instance two buttons on a container call the same URI with different parameter values, but it also enables another layer of permission checking which increases the security, and is therefore good protocol. The same mechanism applies for <strong>$containerEventId</strong>.</p>\n<p>Note, the Dropinbase client-side framework automatically adds the <strong>itemEventId</strong> and <strong>containerEventId </strong>POST parameter values for item and container events. If you have for eg. custom JavaScript in an iframe that targets a controller function that needs to be protected, create a hidden button on the specified container, linked to the same URI. Dropinbase will assign it with a dibuid value (eg <code>abc123def567</code>). Ensure your JavaScript then calls the URI specifying this value for <strong>itemEventId</strong>, eg <code>/dropins/myDropin/Actions/myFunc?$containerName=myContainer&amp;itemEventId=abc123def567</code>.</p>\n<p>The <strong>$clientData</strong> parameter contains any ~nav(dibexClientData,Client Data)~ configured to be submitted with requests from a certain container or dropdown.</p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">The values sent from the browser to the server and on to these functions, can be viewed in the Developer Console (press F12 in Chrome). It is very useful to inspect these values for debugging purposes:<br></span><em>(Press F12 -&gt; Network-tab -&gt; click the Greeting button -&gt; click on the request under \'Name\' -&gt; click Payload-tab)</em><span style="font-family: Arial;"><br></span></p>\n<p><img src="/files/dropins/dibExamples/img/ConsoleClientData.png"></p>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">How values are assigned to function parameters</span></h3>\n<p>The code loops through the function parameters from left to right, and assigns the first value found by checking the following sources in order:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>URI parts that follow after defined parts but precede the \'?\' character (see defined parts under Dropinbase API above). Eg /dropins/myDropin/My/myFunction/<strong>var1/var2</strong>?var3=1</li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">URI query parameters (ie what follows after the \'</span>?\')</li>\n<li>POST parameters</li>\n<li>Default values defined in function parameters</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Example. Given the following function parameter, and URI:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code><span style="font-family: Arial;">function helloWorld ($containerName, $id, $itemEventId, $age, $clientData, $itemAlias, $myValue=456, $status=\'new\')</span></code></li>\n<li><strong><span style="font-family: Arial;">/dropins/test/cont/helloWorld/individualForm/456</span><span style="font-family: Arial;">?age=23&amp;status=done</span></strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The function parameter values are assigned as follows:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>individualForm </strong>and <strong>456</strong> follows the defined parts (or more specifically, the FUNCTION part) and is therefore assigned to <strong>$containerName</strong> and <strong>$id</strong> respectively</li>\n<li><strong>$itemEventId</strong> is not provided as part of the URI or as a query parameter and therefore gets its value from POST parameters (added by Dropinbase). If it does not appear in POST parameters, an error is thrown, since firstly no default value was given. Default values for this parameter should not be set - but if a default was given which does not equal the cached value in <strong>pef_perm_active </strong>a permission error is raised.&nbsp;</li>\n<li><strong>$age</strong> gets its value from the query parameter, \'<strong>23</strong>\'</li>\n<li><strong>$clientData</strong> from POST parameters (added by Dropinbase)</li>\n<li><strong>$itemAlias</strong> from POST parameters (added by Dropinbase)</li>\n<li><strong>$myValue&nbsp;</strong>from function parameter defaults (since its not provided anywhere else), \'<strong>456</strong>\'</li>\n<li><strong>$status</strong> from the query parameter, \'<strong>done</strong>\' and not from the parameter default.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Responses</span></h3>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Each Container and Item Event is configured with a <strong>Response Type</strong> which determines what the client-side code will expect as return values.<br>If it is \'actions\', then actions and/or messages are returned in a JSON object with a very specific structure.&nbsp;<br>For this reason PHP controller classes extend the Dropinbase Controller class that has functions like <strong>validResult </strong>and <strong>invalidResult </strong>to package data correctly before returning it.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">See the help in the Designer for the <strong>Response Type</strong> field, for other available values.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">The JSON response can be viewed in the Developer Console under Response or Preview:<br></span><em>(Press F12 -&gt; Network-tab -&gt; click the Greeting button -&gt; click on the request under \'Name\' -&gt; click Response-tab)</em><span style="font-family: Arial;"><br></span></p>\n<p><img src="/files/dropins/dibExamples/img/ConsoleResponse.png"></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">See&nbsp;</span>the ~nav(dibexEventBasics)~ page for more info.</p>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Global Configs</span></h3>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Any global variables or constants that are required in your application can be added to the <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php </strong>file. <br>The<strong> /configs/Dib.php</strong> file is automatically created based on the <strong>DibTmpl.php </strong>file if it does not exist, and contains the DIB class which exposes Dropinbase settings.<br>For eg. the base path for where user files are uploaded and stored is configured in&nbsp;<strong>Dib.php</strong> and accessed with&nbsp;<code>DIB::$USERSPATH</code> anywhere in the PHP.</span></p>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Component PHP files</span></h3>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">As mentioned, Item and Container Event requests call dropin controller class functions (see <strong>Dropinbase API</strong> above), stored in the <strong>/dropin/DROPIN/controllers</strong> folder.<br>Store other classes that must not be accessible via URI\'s in the&nbsp;<strong>/dropin/DROPIN/components</strong> folder. The Dropinbase auto-loader will automatically require (load) classes in the <strong>components </strong>folder of the same DROPIN when they are referenced. Note, the file name must match the class name.<br>Classes (even controller classes) in other dropin folders can be required (loaded) using the <strong>DibApp::load()</strong> function.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">See the <strong>Load Classes</strong> button (below), and the code behind it for more info.</span></p>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Overiding System Dropins</span></h3>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">The Dropinbase framework has a <strong>/dropins </strong>folder that contains various non-core functionalities. By storing a copy of any of these dropin folders in your own project\'s <strong>/dropins</strong> folder, you can effectively overide the functionality. The <strong>dibAuthenticate </strong>dropin is often overridden in this way.&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">For any <strong>/dropins</strong> URI, Dropinbase first checks whether the targetted controller class exists in the project\'s<strong> /dropins</strong> folder. If it exists it will execute the targetted function in it, ignoring the same controller class in the <strong>/dropins</strong> folder of the framework. Note, if the targetted function does not exist in the controller class, an error will occur.</span></p>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Dropinbase Classes</span></h3>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Various native Dropinbase functions are available for use in PHP. The most commonly used are in the following classes:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>Database.php</strong> - functions to perform database actions (see&nbsp;</span>~nav(dibexPhpGridCrud)~)</li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>Crud.php</strong> - functions to call generated container CRUD class functions&nbsp;</span><span style="font-family: Arial;">(see&nbsp;</span>~nav(dibexPhpGridCrud)~)</li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>ClientFunctions.php</strong> - functions to prepare return values required for client-side actions</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>Queue.php</strong> - functions to add actions or messages to the queue (see </span>~nav(dibexQueue)~)</li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>DibFunctions.php</strong> - various utility functions eg exportFileToClient, zipDir</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>DValidate.php</strong> - functions to validate data</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>Escaper.php</strong> - functions to escape potentially malicious strings</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>DibApp.php</strong> - this file is the main core of Dropinbase, and contains some useful functions like <br>load() to load other PHP files, and clientData() to process Client Data.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">The functions in the above classes can be called without requiring the files. Dropinbase\' auto-loader will load them.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">The various native Dropinbase dropin classes need to be required. They provide extended functionality, such as:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>dibExcel </strong>- import and export data from and to .xlsx files</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>dibCsv </strong>- import and export data from and to .csv files</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>dibAuthenticate </strong>- provides code to handle user authentication</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>dibMail </strong>- send/receive emails</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>dibPdf </strong>- convert HTML to PDF files</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">As mentioned, use the <strong>DibApp::load()</strong> function to require them.<br></span>Note, you can override these dropins with your code and modifications (see above).</p>\n<h3><span style="font-family: Arial;">Third Party Libraries</span></h3>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">By using&nbsp;</span><a href="https://getcomposer.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Composer</a><span style="font-family: Arial;">&nbsp;(already incorporated), other 3d-party libraries can be loaded into the <strong>/vendor</strong> folder. <br>You will notice the Dropinbase core files here too, under<strong> /vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase</strong>.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Alternatively, they can be stored anywhere and required the normal way using native PHP functions.</span></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc349-dib'),
    (350, 'How the Internet Works', 333, 150, 0, 'none', '<h2><span lang="EN-GB">The Basics of the Internet</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The internet is a global network of interconnected computers and devices that communicate with each other using a physical infrastructure and communication and security protocols.</span><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;"> </span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB"><span style="mso-spacerun: yes;">&nbsp;</span>2. Servers and Webpages</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">A <strong>server</strong> is a special type of computer connected directly to the internet. Servers store and provide access to web pages, which are files on the server\'s hard drive. When you visit a website, you\'re accessing files stored on a server somewhere in the world.</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">3. IP Addresses</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Each device connected to the internet has a unique address, known as an <strong>IP (Internet Protocol) address.</strong> This address functions like a postal address, helping devices locate each other. An IP address might look like `67.205.46.248` or `72.14.205.100`. </span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">To make it easier for humans to navigate the internet, we use <strong>URLs (Uniform Resource Locators) </strong>instead of IP addresses. For instance, `www.example.com` or `google.com` are URLs that correspond to specific IP addresses. These URLs are also known as web addresses.</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">4. DNS (Domain Name System) Servers</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">DNS servers</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;"> act like the internet\'s phone book. They translate human-readable URLs into IP addresses. For example, when you type "www.example.com," a DNS server finds the corresponding IP address of the server hosting that website.</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">5. Connecting to the Internet: ISPs, Routers, and Modems</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l2 level1 lfo2;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Internet Service Providers (ISPs)</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: ISPs provide the infrastructure that connects your device to the internet. They supply the physical connection (like cables, fibre optics or radio-links) and offer services like DNS.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l2 level1 lfo2;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Routers</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: A router is a device that directs internet traffic between your home network and the broader internet. It connects to your modem and helps manage data transmission, ensuring that the correct data reaches the correct device in your network.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l2 level1 lfo2;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Modems</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: A modem (modulator-demodulator) is a device that converts digital data from your device into a format suitable for transmission over the physical medium of the internet (like phone lines or cable). It also converts incoming signals back into digital data.</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">6. Making a Request</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Once the DNS server provides the IP address, your browser sends a request to the server at that address. This request is called an <strong>HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol)</strong> request, or if it\'s a secure connection, an <strong>HTTPS (HTTP Secure)</strong> request.</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">7. Server Response</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The server that receives your request processes it and sends back the data you asked for, such as a web page, image, or video. This data is sent back to your device, which then displays it in your browser.</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">8. Security on the Internet</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l4 level1 lfo3;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">HTTPS and Encryption</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: HTTPS is the secure version of HTTP. It encrypts the data exchanged between your browser and the website, making it difficult for anyone else to read or tamper with the information. This is especially important for sensitive information, like online banking or shopping.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l4 level1 lfo3;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">SSL/TLS Certificates</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: Websites that use HTTPS have a digital certificate known as an <strong>SSL (Secure Sockets Layer)</strong> or <strong>TLS (Transport Layer Security)</strong> certificate. This certificate verifies that the website is legitimate and encrypts the data being transmitted.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l4 level1 lfo3;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Firewalls and Security Measures</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: To protect data and networks, many organizations use <strong>firewalls</strong>. Firewalls act as a barrier between a trusted internal network and untrusted external networks (like the internet). They monitor and control incoming and outgoing network traffic based on security rules.</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">9. Caching and Content Delivery Networks (CDNs)</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">To speed up the delivery of content, websites often use <strong>caching</strong> and <strong>Content Delivery Networks (CDNs). </strong>Caching stores copies of frequently accessed content closer to the user, reducing the time it takes to load. CDNs are networks of servers located around the world that cache content, ensuring faster delivery by serving it from a location near the user.</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">10. How Information Travels: Packets</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Data sent over the internet is broken into smaller pieces called <strong>packets</strong>. Each packet contains a piece of the data along with information about its origin, destination, and how to reassemble it with other packets. These packets travel independently across the network and are reassembled into the original data when they reach their destination.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Imagine packets like candy with wrappers. As each packet passes through different devices, it gets another layer of wrapper. For example, when a packet passes through a router, it gets one wrapper; through an ISP, it gets another wrapper, and so on. This wrapping helps protect and direct the packet to its destination.</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">11. IP Address Classes and Types</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l8 level1 lfo4;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Class A, B, and C IP Addresses</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: These classifications are based on the range of IPs they include and the number of devices they can support. Class A can support a large number of devices, while Class C supports fewer.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l8 level1 lfo4;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Public vs. Private IP Addresses</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: </span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 36.0pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">- Public IP addresses are assigned to devices that are directly accessible over the internet. These are unique across the entire internet.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-left: 36.0pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">- Private IP addresses are used within private networks (like a home or office network). They are not unique across the entire internet and cannot be accessed directly from outside the network. Private IP ranges include:</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style="margin-left: 72.0pt; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l12 level1 lfo5;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Wingdings; mso-fareast-font-family: Wingdings; mso-bidi-font-family: Wingdings;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&sect;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Class A: 10.0.0.0 - 10.255.255.255</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" style="margin-left: 72.0pt; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l12 level1 lfo5;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Wingdings; mso-fareast-font-family: Wingdings; mso-bidi-font-family: Wingdings;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&sect;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Class B: 172.16.0.0 - 172.31.255.255</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" style="margin-left: 72.0pt; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l12 level1 lfo5;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Wingdings; mso-fareast-font-family: Wingdings; mso-bidi-font-family: Wingdings;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&sect;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Class C: 192.168.0.0 - 192.168.255.255</span></p>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">12. Ports</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Ports are numerical identifiers used in networking to distinguish different types of services or applications running on the same device. Ports help the operating system know which application or service should handle incoming data.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">How Ports Work</span></strong></p>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="disc">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l9 level1 lfo9; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Port Numbers</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: Ports are identified by numbers ranging from 0 to 65535. Certain port numbers are designated for specific services (these are known as "well-known" ports). For example:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l9 level2 lfo9; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Port 80</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: Used for HTTP (web traffic).</span></li>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l9 level2 lfo9; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Port 443</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: Used for HTTPS (secure web traffic).</span></li>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l9 level2 lfo9; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Port 25</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: Used for SMTP (email).</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l9 level1 lfo9; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Source and Destination Ports</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l9 level2 lfo9; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Source Port</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: This is a randomly assigned port number for the client device\'s outgoing request.</span></li>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l9 level2 lfo9; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Destination Port</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: This is the port number on the server that corresponds to the service being requested (e.g., 80 for HTTP).</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ul>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Example of Ports in Action</span></strong></p>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="disc">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l3 level1 lfo10; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">When you visit a website, your computer sends a request from a source port (e.g., 56789) to the destination port on the server (e.g., 80 for HTTP). The server then responds to your computer\'s public IP and the source port (56789).</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">13. Network Address Translation (NAT)</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">NAT is a method used in networking to modify network address information in packet headers while in transit across a traffic routing device. The primary purpose of NAT is to map multiple private IP addresses to a single public IP address (or a few public IP addresses). This is especially useful for conserving the number of public IP addresses needed by a network.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraph" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l6 level1 lfo13;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-weight: bold;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">How NAT Works</span></strong></p>\n<ol style="margin-top: 0cm;" start="1" type="1">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l1 level1 lfo11; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Private IP Addresses</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: Devices within a local network (like your home network) typically use private IP addresses (e.g., 192.168.x.x or 10.x.x.x). These addresses are not routable on the public internet and are meant to be unique only within the local network.</span></li>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l1 level1 lfo11; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Public IP Address</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: When devices on the local network want to access the internet, they use a public IP address assigned by the ISP. NAT allows these devices to share a single public IP address for outbound traffic.</span></li>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l1 level1 lfo11; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">NAT Table</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: The router or NAT device maintains a NAT table, which keeps track of the mappings between private IP addresses and ports, and the corresponding public IP address and ports. This table helps the router to translate the private IP addresses to a public IP address and back.</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Example</span></strong></p>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="disc">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l10 level1 lfo12; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Outgoing Traffic</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: When a device inside the network (say, with a private IP 192.168.1.10) sends a request to a web server, the router replaces the private IP with the router\'s public IP (e.g., 203.0.113.5). It also assigns a unique port number to this connection (e.g., 54321) and records this mapping in the NAT table.</span></li>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l10 level1 lfo12; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Incoming Traffic</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: When the response from the web server arrives at the public IP (203.0.113.5) and the specific port (54321), the router uses the NAT table to map this back to the original private IP (192.168.1.10) and forwards the response to the correct device.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span lang="EN-GB">14. Mobile Devices and Internet Connectivity</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Mobile devices can connect to the internet in several ways:</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l11 level1 lfo6;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Cellular Networks</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: Mobile devices use cellular towers to connect to the internet. These towers communicate with your device using radio waves, providing internet access through a cellular network provider.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -18.0pt; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l11 level1 lfo6;"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: Symbol; mso-fareast-font-family: Symbol; mso-bidi-font-family: Symbol;"><span style="mso-list: Ignore;">&middot;<span style="font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span><!--[endif]--><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Wi-Fi</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">: Mobile devices can also connect to the internet using Wi-Fi. This involves connecting to a wireless router, which is connected to the internet via a modem. Wi-Fi networks use radio waves to transmit data over short distances, allowing devices to access the internet wirelessly.</span></p>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">&nbsp;<img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/howTheInternetWorksFig1.png" alt="Internet Connectivity Diagram" width="853" height="472"></span></p>\n<h2 class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><span lang="EN-GB">Summary</span></h2>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Flow from User to Web Server:</span></strong></p>\n<ol style="margin-top: 0cm;" start="1" type="1">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo7; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="FR" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-ansi-language: FR;">Client Device (e.g., Laptop)</span></strong><span lang="FR" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-ansi-language: FR;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level2 lfo7; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The user types a URL into the web browser and presses enter. This action initiates a request.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo7; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Router/Modem</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level2 lfo7; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The request is sent from the user\'s device to the router or modem, which manages the local network and connects to the Internet Service Provider (ISP). </span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo7; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">ISP (Client Side)</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level2 lfo7; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The router/modem forwards the request to the client\'s ISP. The ISP provides access to the internet and directs the request towards its destination.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo7; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">DNS (Domain Name System) Server</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level2 lfo7; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The request includes the URL, which needs to be translated into an IP address. The DNS server acts like the internet\'s phonebook, translating the human-readable URL into the corresponding IP address of the web server.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo7; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Internet</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level2 lfo7; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The request, now directed to the correct IP address, travels through the internet infrastructure. It may pass through various routers and networks to reach the destination ISP.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo7; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">ISP (Server Side)</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level2 lfo7; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The request arrives at the ISP that serves the web server hosting the requested website. This ISP routes the request to the specific web server.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo7; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Web Server</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l0 level2 lfo7; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The web server receives the request. It processes the request (e.g., fetching the web page or data) and prepares the response.</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ol>\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Flow from Web Server to User:</span></strong></p>\n<ol style="margin-top: 0cm;" start="8" type="1">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level1 lfo8; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Web Server</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level2 lfo8; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The server sends the requested data (e.g., web page, image, video) back to the client.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level1 lfo8; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">ISP (Server Side)</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level2 lfo8; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The response travels from the web server through the server-side ISP.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level1 lfo8; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Internet</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level2 lfo8; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The response traverses the internet, passing through various networks and routers, heading back towards the client\'s ISP.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level1 lfo8; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">ISP (Client Side)</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level2 lfo8; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The response reaches the client\'s ISP, which directs it towards the user\'s local network.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level1 lfo8; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">Router/Modem</span></strong><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level2 lfo8; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The response is received by the router or modem and forwarded to the user\'s device.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level1 lfo8; tab-stops: list 36.0pt;"><strong><span lang="FR" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-ansi-language: FR;">Client Device (e.g., Laptop)</span></strong><span lang="FR" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-ansi-language: FR;">:</span></li>\n<ul style="margin-top: 0cm;" type="circle">\n<li class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 150%; mso-list: l5 level2 lfo8; tab-stops: list 72.0pt;"><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 150%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif;">The user\'s device receives the response and displays the requested web page, image, or video in the web browser.</span></li>\n</ul>\n</ol>\n<p><span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size: 11.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: \'Arial\',sans-serif; mso-fareast-font-family: Aptos; mso-fareast-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-ansi-language: EN-GB; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;">This entire process happens very quickly, often in a fraction of a second, allowing users to access and interact with websites seamlessly</span></p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc350-dib'),
    (351, 'incl_clientDefaults', NULL, NULL, 0, 'none', '<p><strong>Examples</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><code>1234</code> - constant number</li>\r\n<li><code>hello world</code> - constant string</li>\r\n<li><code>my brother\\\'s keeper</code> - example of string with escaped quote (<span style="color: #e03e2d;">else a compile error will occur!</span>)</li>\r\n<li><code><b>first</b></code> - this is a special client default that works on dropdowns. The first item in the dropdown-list is automatically selected.</li>\r\n<li><code>@{value_parent_id}</code> - get value of item named \'<strong>id</strong>\' on the parent container (this is often used to populate foreignkey values)</li>\r\n<li><code>@{alias_myContainer_name} </code>- get value of item (where <strong>Alias </strong>is checked) named \'<strong>name</strong>\' on the <strong>myContainer</strong> container</li>\r\n<li><code>@{env_staff_id}</code> - get \'<strong>staff_id</strong>\' environment value defined in /configs/Environment.php and loaded into browser when project loads</li>\r\n<li><code>@{custom_global_xxx}</code> - get value of xxx stored in custom global client data. See ~nav(dibexActionSetCustomGlobal)~ and ~nav(dibexActionSetCustom)~</li>\r\n<li><code>@{dibDateTime}</code> - current date &amp; time returned by Dropinbase client-side framework. Other values:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><code>@{dibDate}</code> - current date</li>\r\n<li><code>@{yearStart}</code> - Jan 1 of current year</li>\r\n<li><code>@{yearEnd}</code> - Dec 31 of current year</li>\r\n<li><code>@{monthStart}</code> - 1st of current month (and year)</li>\r\n<li><code>@{monthEnd}</code> - last day of current month (and year)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><code>Good day @{env_user_fullname}. Today is @{dibDateTime}</code> - demonstrating that values can be combined and embedded in strings</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ensure that containers that are referenced are open (currently in the view)</li>\r\n<li>The value is wrapped in single-quotes but otherwise merged "as is" into the design of the container when it is first created. Therefore any single-quotes must be escaped using \\, eg <code>The Cat\\\'s Food</code></li>\r\n<li>Note, that <span style="color: #e03e2d;">client-side defaults are not secure!</span> Hackers can edit their values before they are sent to the server.<br>~nav(dibexDefaultValuesServer,Server-side Defaults)~ and Table/Container Events offer more security and flexibility on Table-bound containers.</li>\r\n<li>See&nbsp; ~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices, Dropinbase Services)~ for more info.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>When using <strong>alias_CONTAINERNAME_...</strong>&nbsp;the following are required, which makes using <strong>value_... </strong>the better choice:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>the container that is referenced must be included in the container\'s <strong>Client Data Configs</strong> field, eg <strong>"alias":"myContainer"</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>alias_parent_xxx </strong>and <strong>alias_self_xxx</strong> do not have this restriction</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>the field that is referenced must have its&nbsp;<strong>Alias </strong>field set</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', NULL, 1, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc351-dib'),
    (352, 'Get and Set User Interface Values', 28, 25, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The following values are generally available to display, or submit to the server, or use in conditional criteria:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Item values on visible containers, eg&nbsp;<strong>value_myContainer_myItem</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>alias_self_xxx</strong></li>\n<li>Dropinbase values, such as&nbsp;<strong>containerName</strong>, <strong>parentContainerName</strong>, <strong>dibDateTime</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>dibIP</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>monthStart</strong></li>\n<li>Custom Values that you set with actions, eg.&nbsp;<strong>custom_global_myValue</strong>,&nbsp;<strong>custom_myContainer_myContainerValue</strong></li>\n<li>Environment values\n<ul>\n<li>When the project loads into the browser, the <strong>/peff/Template/environment.js</strong> request fetches values that you define in the <strong>/configs/Environment.php</strong> file.</li>\n<li>You can configure these values (eg. the current user\'s team name or phone number or staff_id value etc.) and use them in the user-interface.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>These values are available for:</p>\n<h3>New Records</h3>\n<p>Set the default values for bound/unbound inputs on any type of container, using the&nbsp;<strong>Client Default </strong>field, for eg:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>@{dibDateTime}</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Note, there is a more secure and flexible&nbsp;<strong>Server Default</strong> field.<br>See ~nav(dibexDefaultValuesClient)~ and the help in the Designer associated with the <strong>Client Default</strong> field (click the ?-button)</p>\n<h3>Displaying Text</h3>\n<p>Angular interpolation can be used to display values in <strong>span </strong>components, for eg the <strong>Expression</strong> field contains:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>You typed: &lt;b&gt;{{resolve(\'value_self_yourText\')}}&lt;/b&gt;</code> - on any container</li>\n<li><code>Value of &lt;b&gt;staffOnly&lt;/b&gt; Environment Variable: {{getEnv(\'staffOnly\')}}</code>&nbsp;- on any container</li>\n<li><code>Conditional Greeting: {{( getEnv(\'staffOnly\') == 1 ~$delimDb~~$delimDb~ !!getValue(\'multi_select\') ) ? \'hello\' : \'bye\'}}</code> - on any container</li>\n<li><code>{{row.name + \' \' + (!!row.start_date ? (row.start_date ~$delimDb~ date:\'yyyy-MM-dd\') : \'\')}}</code> - in grid rows</li>\n</ul>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexComponentsOther)~,~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices)~, ~nav(dibexGridCustomColumns)~ and ~nav(dibexGridSqlCustomColumns)~</p>\n<h3>Incorporating in HTML Elements</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Expression</strong> field can be used with the <strong>html</strong> component to create complex elements that change dynamically:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>&lt;img style="max-width:750px"&nbsp;<br>[src]="\'/files/dropins/myDropin/images/img_\' + getValue(\'selectedImg\') + \'.jpg\'"&gt;</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Actions</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Submit Url </strong>field of item/container events can contain references to values, eg a button in the row of a grid submits the current row\'s id value, and the name of the parent container using:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>/dropins/myDropin/Action/doSomething?id=@{actionData.id}&amp;parent=@{parentContainerName}</code><br>(NOTE: the attributes of this button must have [actionData]="row")</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Technically you can include other Client Data values like <code>@{value_self_clientName} </code>in the URI as well, but these values are already (and better) submitted using Client Data POST parameters.<br>See the button in ~nav(dibexGridBasics)~</p>\n<h3>Conditional Styles/Disabled/Hidden/Removal</h3>\n<p>Angular comes with powerful directives to conditionally set styles, disable inputs, hide items (with their child items) and completely remove them from the DOM.<br>For eg. a button may have the following in the attributes field to remove it when the user has not yet provided a value in the <strong>yourName </strong>item:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>*ngIf="!!getValue(\'yourName\')"</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The conditional expression must be valid TypeScript expression that evaluates to boolean true/false. This includes the use of Dropinbase functions like <strong>getValue()</strong> and <strong>resolve()</strong>.<br>See ~navdocs(Conditional Directives)~ and ~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices)~</p>\n<h3>Navigation using Ports</h3>\n<p>When a button is linked to a Port, the <strong>Expression </strong>field can contain URL parameters to be set in the browser\'s URL.<br>There are various commonly used scenarios for working with records on forms, for eg:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>\'?primary_id=\'+row.client_id</code> - used on a button in a grid to open a form on a particular record</li>\n<li><code>\'?record=new\'</code> - used to open a new record in a form</li>\n<li><code>\'?record=first\'</code> - used to open the first record in a form</li>\n<li><code>\'?record=last\'</code> - used to open the last record in a form</li>\n</ul>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexNavigation)~</p>\n<h3>Setting Item Values</h3>\n<p>When a container is opened with a Port (can be via a button, or for eg the \'open-url\' action), values can be sent in URL query parameters to set values of items in the target container.<br>To add the URL parameters on a button we use the <strong>Expression </strong>field:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>\'?record=new&amp;myForm.clientId=@{value_self_clientId}&amp;myForm.name=@{value_myContainer_first_name}\'</code> - set bound field values (see Notes below)</li>\n<li><code>\'?myContainer.myDate=@{dibDate}\'</code> - set unbound field values</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Notes:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Setting the value of bound fields (items linked to table fields) via URL parameters, only works on new records. Setting values of unbound fields works on any record and any container type.</li>\n<li>The port record must be set to change the URL</li>\n<li>The targetted items must have their <strong>Alias</strong>-field set in the Designer.</li>\n<li>Item names in the URL must be prefixed with the target container name, eg <strong>myContainer.clientId=1 </strong>instead of&nbsp;<strong>clientId=1</strong>.</li>\n<li>To prevent phishing-type of attacks, the values will only be set if the URL is not used to load the project (ie. you can\'t paste the URL in the browser to set the values).</li>\n<li>It is often easier to set the values of fields on new records by using the <strong>Client Default</strong> field (see New Records above)</li>\n<li>An alternative way to set client-side values is with actions. See ~nav(dibexActionSetValue)~ and ~nav(dibexActionSetHtml)~</li>\n</ul>\n<p>See <strong>Setting Values </strong>on ~nav(dibexNavigation)~, and \'<strong>Fill In Values</strong>\'-tab on ~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices)~</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc352-dib'),
    (353, 'Workings of encode function', 119, 15, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>By default the output of all expressions in Eleutheria is HTML encoded to block hacking attempts. \n<br>To alter the encoding to allow your own safe HTML, use the encode() function.\n<br>Below we set xxx to "malicious" HTML code that runs the JavaScript alert() function. \n<br>and then we demonstrate how the <b>encode()</b> function works.\n<br><span style="color:red">Users can store any values in text fields. Disabling the default encoding should be done with caution.</span>\n<br>For more info, see the ~navdocs(ET*encode, docs, encode)~-function.\n<br><br>\n<strong>NOTE: This example contains live Eleutheria code</strong> <br>\n</p>\n<h3>Setup malicious code:</h3>\nWe start with using the <b>setval()</b> function to store malicious code in a variable.\n\n~setval(xxx, <a onclick="alert(\'you were hacked\')">if this link works then code was injected</a>)~\n<p><code>setval(xxx, &lt;a onclick="alert(\'you were hacked\')"&gt;if this link works then code was injected&lt;/a&gt;)</code></p>\n<h3>Attempts to escape malicious code:</h3>\n<p>The functions below display the contents of the variable - some with adequate encoding to block it, and some without.</p>\n<p>Malicious code injected successfully (for this function only): <br><code>encode(this, none, getval(xxx))</code>: ~encode(this, none, getval(xxx))~</p>\n<p>Here the encoding is returned to the default and blocks the malicious injection. <u>Instead of the code having any effect, the actual HTML is displayed</u>: \n<br><code>getval(xxx)</code>: ~getval(xxx)~</p>\n<p>Malicious code injected successfully (for this expression only): <br><code>encode(expr,none) getval(xxx)</code>: ~encode(expr,none) getval(xxx)~</p>\n<p>Here the encoding is returned to the default and blocks the malicious injection. <br><code>getval(xxx)</code>: ~getval(xxx)~</p>\n<p>Malicious code injected successfully (for this expression and all following!): <br><code>encode(all,none) getval(xxx)</code>: ~encode(all,none) getval(xxx)~</p>\n<p>The default encoding WAS CHANGED - the malicious injection is not blocked! <br><code>getval(xxx)</code>: ~getval(xxx)~</p>\n<p>Reset the encoding to \'html\' for this expression and all to follow: <br><code>encode(all,html) getval(xxx)</code>: ~encode(all,html) getval(xxx)~</p>\n<p>The html encoding blocks the malicious injection <br><code>getval(xxx)</code>: ~getval(xxx)~</p>\n<p>Note, if an expression contains <code>encode(this, none)</code> even once, then only the parts in the whole expression that is encoded specifically are encoded; the rest are NOT. <br><code>encode(this, none, getval(xxx)) NOT ENCONDED: getval(xxx) AND ENCODED: encode(this,html, getval(xxx) )</code>: ~encode(this, none, getval(xxx)) NOT ENCONDED: getval(xxx) AND ENCODED: encode(this,html, getval(xxx) )~</p>\n<p>Here the encoding is returned to the default and blocks the malicious injection <br><code>getval(xxx)</code>: ~getval(xxx)~</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc124-dib'),
    (354, 'ET*exists', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> If EXPRESSION is not empty and not 0 then returns PART1. Otherwise returns PART2 or an empty string if PART2 is not specified.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> exists(EXPRESSION, PART1[, PART2])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> EXPRESSION</b> - a string (or empty string)\r\n</li><li><b> PART1</b> - Value to return if EXPRESSION is not empty and not 0\r\n</li><li><b> PART2</b> - Optional value to return if EXPRESSION is empty or 0. If not specified, then an empty string is assumed.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Unlike if, PART1 and PART2 are always processed regardless, which makes if functions potentially faster to process</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> exists(fld(bob),jam,hungry)</code> - prints &apos;jam&apos; if fld(bob) is not empty else prints &apos;hungry&apos;\r\n</li><li><code> exists(,jam,hungry)</code> - prints hungry\r\n</li><li><code> exists(0, jam, hungry)</code> - prints hungry\r\n</li><li><code> exists(   ,jam)</code> - prints\r\n</li><li><code> exists(1, jam)</code> - prints jam\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc354-dib'),
    (355, 'ET*pathinfo', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> implements the PHP pathinfo function</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> pathinfo(PATH, PART1)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> PATH</b> - path to the file (exclude file name)\r\n</li><li><b> PART1</b> - dirname/basename/extension/filename\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> See <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.pathinfo.php" title="Dropinbase Features">https://www.php.net/manual/en/function.pathinfo.php</dib-nav>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li> pathinfo(/dropins/setSencha/dibGlobals/templates/textfield.js, basename)\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc355-dib'),
    (356, 'ET*dibtranslate', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> A Dropinbase specific function used in Angular templates to facilitate internationalization</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> dibtranslate(KEY, CAPTIONVALUE[, ADDBRACES=true])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> KEY</b> - the dictionary key used to locate a string\r\n</li><li><b> CAPTIONVALUE</b> - the string/caption in its default language\r\n</li><li><b> ADDBRACES</b> - true/false - whether the result is wraped in braces, {{ ... }}\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> ADDBRACES is true by default. Use false to avoid them.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> dibtranslate(^containerName^.fld(name),fld(caption)))</code> - generates for eg. {{dibtranslate(&apos;myKey&apos;, &quot;myCaptionValue&quot;)}}\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc356-dib'),
    (357, 'ET*getcomponentmodules', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> A Dropinbase specific function used in Angular templates to generate import statements</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> getcomponentmodules(PART1)</span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li> getcomponentmodules(getval(containerModules))\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc357-dib'),
    (358, 'ET*encode', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Sets the escaping / encoding that is applied to the specific scope of functions/expressions.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> ~encode(SCOPE, DIRECTIVES[, THIS_CONTENT_TO_ESCAPE])~</span></div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">SCOPE (one of the following values):</span>\r\n<ul><li><b> expr</b> - the end-result of all functions in the current expression is escaped with DIRECTIVES. The scope and directives only applies to the current expression.\r\n</li><li><b> this</b> - the value in THIS_CONTENT_TO_ESCAPE is escaped with DIRECTIVES. The scope and directives only apply to the value in the 3d parameter. Everything else in the expression is NOT encoded (unless encode() is used there too).\r\n</li><li><b> all</b> -  the current expression and all expressions that are evaluated hence are escaped with DIRECTIVES\r\n</ul><span class="et-section-line">DIRECTIVES (one of the following values):</span>\r\n<ul><li><b> none</b> - do not do any escaping/sanitization\r\n</li><li><b> bslash</b> - escape all backslashes with a backslash, eg \\ becomes \\\\\r\n</li><li><b> dquote</b> - escape all double quote characters (&quot;) with a backslash, eg. &quot; becomes \\&quot;\r\n</li><li><b> squote</b> - escape all single quote characters (&apos;) with a backslash, eg. &apos; becomes \\&apos;\r\n</li><li><b> apos</b> - replace all single quote characters (&apos;) with a &apos;\r\n</li><li><b> html</b> - all HTML special characters are replaced, using htmlspecialchars($string, ENT_QUOTES | ENT_SUBSTITUTE | ENT_HTML5, &apos;UTF-8&apos;, FALSE)\r\n</li><li><b> xml</b> - all XML special characters are replaced, using htmlspecialchars($value, ENT_QUOTES | ENT_SUBSTITUTE | ENT_XML1, &apos;UTF-8&apos;);\r\n</li><li><b> attr</b> - escape any characters that may cause security issues in an HTML element&apos;s attributes context\r\n</li><li><b> css</b> - escape a string for the CSS context. CSS escaping can be applied to any string being inserted into CSS and escapes everything except alphanumerics.\r\n</li><li><b> purify</b> - use the htmlPurifier class to sanitize HTML\r\n</li><li><b> js</b> - escape a string for the Javascript context\r\n</li><li><b> url</b> - encode a URL with the PHP rawurlencode() function\r\n</ul><span class="et-section-line">THIS_CONTENT_TO_ESCAPE</span>\r\n<ul><li> Any value to escape. Only applicable when SCOPE = &apos;this&apos;.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> The default escaping DIRECTIVES is set to &apos;html&apos;.\r\n</li><li> If SCOPE = &apos;this&apos; then (only) the THIS_CONTENT_TO_ESCAPE must be provided.\r\n</li><li> BEWARE of using &apos;this&apos; since all other functions in the same expression are not encoded, unless specifically encoded with encode(this, ..) too.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> ~encode(expr, none)fld(my_field)~</code> - often used to avoid HTML encoding of field values (use with great caution).\r\n</li><li><code> ~encode(expr, purify)getval(mySavedValue)~</code> - use htmlPurifier to sanitize HTML\r\n</li><li> ~encode(all, xml)~\r\n</li><li> ~encode(expr, none)dropin(/dropins/myDropin/myClass/myFunc, data, ^alias_self_individual_id^, ^alias_yyy_company_id^)~\r\n</li><li> ~if(&apos;fld(xxx)&apos;=&apos;hello&apos;, &lt;a href=&quot;/dropins/myDropin/iframe/Template/open/myContainer?filter=encode(this, url,{&quot;alias_self_tableName&quot;:&quot;^alias_self_tableName^&quot;[*,*]&quot;alias_xxx_individual_id&quot;:&quot;^alias_xxx_individual_id^&quot;[*,*]&quot;myId&quot;:&quot;fld(my_pkey)&quot;})&gt;click here&lt;/a&gt;)~\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc358-dib'),
    (359, 'ET*trim', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Implements the PHP trim function</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> trim(STRING[, CHARACTERS][, OPTIONS])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> STRING</b> - the string to trim\r\n</li><li><b> CHARACTERS</b> - the characters to trim. The default is all whitespace characters (same as in PHP)\r\n</li><li><b> OPTIONS</b> - which function to use: ltrim/rtrim (default is trim)\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> trim(fld(comments))</code> - trims all white-space characters on either side of the contents of fld(comments)\r\n</li><li><code> trim(fld(comments),,ltrim)</code> - trims all white-space characters on only the left side of the contents of fld(comments)\r\n</li><li><code> trim(abcdef, a)</code> - returns bcdef\r\n</li><li><code> trim(abcdef, a, rtrim)</code> - returns abcdef\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc359-dib'),
    (360, 'ET*dropin', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> executes specified dropin function, and inserts any text returned</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> dropin(PATH[, PARAM1][, PARAM2][,...])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> PATH</b> - the URI identifying the dropin function to execute, eg /dropins/myDropin/chart/getChartDef\r\n</li><li><b> PARAM1,2,3,...</b> - values to pass to function, as a single array of values\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Eleutheria resolves the physical path to the PHP class by using DibApp::loadPath()\r\n</li><li> Parameter values are passed in a single array to the first function parameter.\r\n</li><li> If the function has a second parameter, it will contain any parameter values used in the current SQL query.\r\n</li><li> Functions are called statically by default to ensure maximum performance in Eleutheria loops.\r\n</li><li> If the functionName is prefixed with *, it will be called non-statically, eg /dropins/test/ComponentsClass/*dibImporterDropdown\r\n</li><li> The class must be in the &apos;components&apos; subfolder of the dropin, and return a string on success or array(&apos;error&apos;, $errMsg) on failure.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> dropin(/dropins/test/ComponentsClass/dibImporterDropdown,1,2)</code> - calls the dibImporterDropdown function in ComponentsClass.php in the /dropins/test/components folder with array(&apos;1&apos;,&apos;2&apos;) as parameter\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc360-dib'),
    (361, 'ET*camelCaseToChar', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (Dropinbase specific function) converts camelCaseString to camel**Case**String (where parts[0] = &apos;camelCaseString&apos; and parts[1] = &apos;**&apos;)</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> camelCaseToChar(STRING, GLUE)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> STRING</b> - string to convert\r\n</li><li><b> GLUE</b> - characters to insert in between parts\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> used in Dropinbase Angular templates\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> camelCaseToChar(helloThereWorld, **)</code> - prints: hello**There**World\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc361-dib'),
    (362, 'ET*incldropintmpl', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> includes the content of an Eleutheria template obtained from a PHP dropin component, and parses optional global variables</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> incldropintmpl(PATH[,FUNCTION PARAMETERS][,TMPL_PARAM1, TMPL_PARAM2, TMPL_PARAM3, etc.]...)</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> PATH</b> - the URI identifying the dropin function to execute, eg /dropins/myDropin/templates/getTmpl\r\n</li><li><b> FUNCTION PARAMETERS</b> - a JSON array (where all commas are replaced with ;) of parameters to send to the dropin function (see Notes)\r\n</li><li><b> TMPL_PARAM1/2/3/etc</b> - A name, value pair using the format NAME:VALUE. ^NAME^ is replaced in FILENAME with VALUE, before any other action occurs.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Since this function is useful for user reports/forms etc. errors are printed to the error log instead of the document.\r\n</li><li> Eleutheria resolves the physical path to the PHP class by using DibApp::loadPath\r\n</li><li> Function Parameter values are passed in a single array to the first function parameter.\r\n</li><li> If the function has a second parameter, it will contain any parameter values used in the current SQL query.\r\n</li><li> Functions are called statically by default to ensure maximum performance in Eleutheria loops.\r\n</li><li> If the functionName is prefixed with *, it will be called non-statically, eg /dropins/test/ComponentsClass/*dibImporterDropdown\r\n</li><li> The class must be in the &apos;components&apos; subfolder of the dropin, and return a string on success or array(&apos;error&apos;, $errMsg) on failure.\r\n</li><li> Works otherwise exactly like inclfile function\r\n</li><li> *** NOTE: security risks mentioned in <dib-nav class="helpNavigation" data-container="dibDocs" data-query="?area=docs&doc=ET*inclfile" title="Dropinbase Features">inclfile</dib-nav> documentation\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> incldropintmpl(/dropins/test/ComponentsClass/dibImporterDropdown, {&quot;id&quot;:4 ; &quot;name&quot;:&quot;hello&quot;})</code> - calls the dibImporterDropdown function in ComponentsClass.php in the /dropins/test/components folder with array(&quot;id&quot;:4, &quot;name&quot;:&quot;hello&quot;) as parameter\r\n</li><li><code> incldropintmpl(/dropins/myDropin/templates/getTmpl,,crit1:ABC, crit2:[*^sentence^*])</code> - Note how [* *] is used to ensure that the contents of ^sentence^ (which is replaced before anything else) does not break the template syntax.\r\n</li><li><code> incldropintmpl(/dropins/myDropin/templates/getTmpl,,crit1:)</code> - this will replace ^crit^ with an empty string\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc362-dib'),
    (363, 'ET*incldocs', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> Inserts html stored in pef_docs.body</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> incldocs(DOCS_NAME[, DOCS_SET[, DOCS_SUBSET]])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> DOCS_NAME</b> - name of pef_docs record\r\n</li><li><b> DOCS_SET</b> - pef_docs set column value\r\n</li><li><b> DOCS_SUBSET</b> - pef_docs docs_subset column value\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> *** WARNING unsafe if pef_docs records are altered maliciously.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">This function causes the expression to be re-evaluated a 2nd time after the first merge takes place, which constitutes a security hole should pef_docs&apos;s records be compromised.</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">It is also potentially unsafe since output is NOT htmlencoded.</span>\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> incldocs(Domains)</code> - inserts HTML stored in `body` field of pef_docs where name = &apos;Domains&apos; and docs_set is the same as current context set (normally &apos;dib&apos;)\r\n</li><li><code> incldocs(Domains, myset)</code> - inserts &apos;Domains&apos; from the &apos;myset&apos; set.\r\n</li><li><code> incldocs(Domains, myset, mysubset)</code> - inserts &apos;Domains&apos; from the &apos;myset&apos; set, and &apos;mysubset&apos; subset.\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc363-dib'),
    (364, 'ET*dropinfn', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> (Dropinbase specific function) Returns PHP code that calls a dropin component class function (with parameters) defined in the reference</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> dropinfn(URI[, PARAM1, PARAM2, PARAM3, etc])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> URI</b> - eg. /dropins/test/run/button2Activate\r\n</li><li><b> PARAM1/2/3/etc</b> - are added as function parameters\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> dropinfn(/dropins/test/myClass/button2ActivateTab, &apos;test_company&apos;, null, null, &apos;on load&apos;)</code> - returns:\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">DibApp::load(&apos;test&apos;, &apos;myClass.php&apos;, &apos;components&apos;);</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">t = new $class();</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">$error = $t-&gt;button2ActivateTab(&apos;test_company&apos;, null, null, &apos;on load&apos;);</span>\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc364-dib'),
    (365, 'ET*inclfiletext', 121, 1000, 0, 'none', '<div class="et-function"><div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Description:</div>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line"> includes text from a file between start and end-delimiters. Otherwise works exactly the same as inclfile.</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Syntax: <span class="et-syntax-line"> inclfiletext(FOLDER, FILENAME, BEGINTEXT, ENDTEXT[, PARAM1, PARAM2, PARAM3, etc])</span></div>\r\n<ul><li><b> FOLDER</b> - if &apos;templatefolder&apos; then the folder of the main template is used\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">if the first 8 characters is &apos;/dropins&apos; then the file is searched first in the main /dropins folder, and if not found, then in the core API /dropins folder</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">else the path as provided is used</span>\r\n</li><li><b> FILENAME</b> -  a semicolon delimited list of file names; the first one found is used. Eg textFile.et.txt;textFile2.txt\r\n</li><li><b> BEGINTEXT</b> - string which indicates start position of text to include - is itself NOT included\r\n</li><li><b> ENDTEXT</b> - string which indicates end position of text to include - is itself NOT included\r\n</li><li><b> PARAM1/2/3/etc</b> - A name, value pair using the format NAME:VALUE. ^NAME^ is replaced in FILENAME with VALUE, before any other action occurs.\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Notes:</div>\r\n<ul><li> Once the file is found, the PARAM values are replaced first using ^ as delimiter for variables,\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">followed by values in the globalArray array also using ^ as delimiter for variables.</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">Then Sections (eg |Section A| ... |End A|) and Subdomains (eg |rssql2;...| ... |End2|) are replaced with placed holders</span>\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">The file pointer is then placed at the beginning of the included text in order to process any merge fields and expressions.</span>\r\n</li><li> Note, the string after NAME: is not trimmed! spaces are included...\r\n</li><li> Keep FOLDER and FILENAME case sensitive, to avoid issues on Linux with not finding files\r\n</li><li> Warning: Allowing user values to determine any portion of FOLDER or FILENAME is a security risk!\r\n</ul></div>\r\n<div class="et-section"><div class="et-section-head">Examples:</div>\r\n<ul><li><code> inclfiletext(/dropins/myDropin/templates, textfield.js, hello, bye)</code> - gets the file from $this-&gt;inclFileRoot/myDropin/templates/textfield.js but only fetches text between the first occurrence of &apos;hello&apos; and &apos;bye&apos;\r\n</li><li><code> inclfiletext(/dropins/myDropin/templates, textfield.js, hello, bye, crit:fld(name), crit2:[*^sentence^*])</code> - replaces ^crit^ in the content with the value of  fld(name)  (be careful of spaces after : which will also be included), and ^crit2^ with whatever is in ^sentence^.\r\n<br><span class="et-section-line">Note how [* *] is used to ensure that the contents of ^sentence^ (which is replaced before anything else) does not break the template syntax</span>\r\n</li><li><code> inclfiletext(templatefolder, textfield.js, hello, bye, crit:10)</code> - fetches file from the folder containing the current template\r\n', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc365-dib'),
    (366, 'Eleutheria Basics', 119, 5, 0, 'none', '<p>Eleutheria <strong>(eh-le-oo-the-ree-ah</strong>, meaning freedom in Greek<strong>) </strong>is a flexible and fast templating engine that merges record sources with templates. It can be used widely, eg to generate code, create reports, .docx and .xlsx documents.</p>\n<p>Eleutheria incorporates coding principles (eg loops and conditions), can be easily extended with your own functions, and can draw from any record source.</p>\n<h2>Security</h2>\n<p>Since Eleutheria if often used to generate HTML-reports or emails, a note about security here is important. The output of all expressions are HTML-encoded by default. This implies:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If all your expressions are embedded between HTML tags, eg <code>&lt;b&gt;~name~ ~getval(town)~&lt;/b&gt;</code> then the output is safe.</li>\n<li>If an expression is embedded in JavaScript or as part of an URL or HTML tag then its encoding needs to change or values must be sanitized.\n<ul>\n<li>Eg. consider&nbsp;<code>&lt;input type="text" value="~town~"&gt;</code> - it essential to ensure that <strong>town</strong> contains only for eg. alpha-numeric characters and spaces (a value like <code>Perth" onclick="..." title="</code> could be used to inject malicious scripts).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Always ensure that HTML documents have the necessary tags to enforce UTF-8 content.</li>\n<li>Eleutheria has functions to override or change the encoding. If in doubt always use the class from <a href="http://htmlpurifier.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http://htmlpurifier.org/</a> (built into Dropinbase) to sanitize the output.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Basic Principles</h2>\n<p>The main features of Eleutheria are explained below.</p>\n<pre>~$// This is a <strong>comment</strong> - comments are removed~</pre>\n<p>Below is&nbsp;<strong>global merge field</strong>. They are replaced in the template before anything else is merged.</p>\n<pre>&lt;h1&gt;^myHeading^&lt;/h1&gt;</pre>\n<p>Eleutheria <strong>expressions </strong>start and end with the tilde-character (~). This character can be changed.<br>Expressions consist of Eleutheria functions that can be nested.&nbsp;<br>Each function consists of a lowercase name followed by one or more parameters between round brackets.<br>Below the&nbsp;<strong>sql() </strong>function executes SQL against Dropinbase database index<strong> 3</strong>, to return a result. <br>Then the&nbsp;<strong>math()</strong> function is used to add 5 to that result.<br>Note, that&nbsp;<strong>count(id)</strong> is <strong>not</strong> an Eleutheria function, but SQL. <br>Since any round brackets or commas can interfere with Eleutheria syntax, we use [* ... *] to inform Eleutheria of text that must not be processed.</p>\n<pre>&lt;h3&gt;Total votes:&lt;/h2&gt;&nbsp;<br><br>&lt;b&gt;~math(5 + sql(SELECT [*count(id)*] FROM tb_votes, 3))~&lt;/b&gt;</pre>\n<p>Some functions return results, while other functions set values and configurations.<br>Below the&nbsp;<strong>setmaindb()</strong> function is used to change the default database index from the Dropinbase database to 3.<br>All database operations going forward will now use this database.<br>If we executed this function before the&nbsp;<strong>sql()</strong> function above, there would have been no need for the second parameter (<code>, 3</code>) part of the <strong>sql()</strong> function.<br>We also use the&nbsp;<strong>setval()</strong> function to define a variable value we will use later. Note functions can be nested, and also executed next to one another.<br>Any text (see&nbsp;<code>Oops, this shouldn\'t be here</code> below) appearing in expressions that has no meaning in Eleutheria is printed "as is", but is HTML encoded in HTML templates (more about that later).</p>\n<pre>~setmaindb(3)setval(priorityStatus, new)Oops, this shouldn\'t be here~</pre>\n<p>Looping through records and printing data is facilitated by&nbsp;<strong>recordsets</strong>.<br>The source of the records is either an array, denoted by&nbsp;<strong>rsarr</strong>, or a SQL statement, denoted by <strong>rssql</strong>.<br>Recordset definitions are wrapped in pipe-characters(|), and semicolons (;) are used to delimit parameters.<br>Each recordset must have a unique number, and the end of the recordset is denoted by&nbsp;<strong>End#</strong> where <strong>#</strong> is the same number.<br>Everything between the recordset definition and&nbsp;<strong>End#</strong> is processed and printed once for each record in the recordset</p>\n<pre>|rssql1;SELECT id, name, status, birthdate, city, join_date FROM person WHERE join_date &gt; \'2024-01-01\'|<br><br>~$// To print the contents of a field in the recordset, use an Eleutheria expression that equals the name of the field~<br><br>~name~ was born on ~birthdate~&lt;br&gt;<br><br>~$// <strong>Conditional statements</strong> are mainly facilitated by <strong>if(CONDITION, TRUE_EXPR, FALSE_EXPR)</strong> (certain other functions like <strong>exists()</strong> and <strong>nv() </strong>manage simple not-emtpy condtions).<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Note, depending on the outcome of the CONDITION, either TRUE_EXPR or FALSE_EXPR is evaluated, not both.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The CONDITION can consist of complex expressions using operators like and/or/=/&lt;&gt;/&lt;/&gt;/&lt;=/&gt;= and brackets ().<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The condition can contain Eleutheria functions that return values. Since these return values can contain operators (like and/or) that will be evaluated, <br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; wrap them in single quotes to inform Eleutheria to treat them as values.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Inside other functions, recordset field values are accessed using the <strong>fld()</strong> function.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Note the use of [*...*] to wrap text that contains commas or brackets that interferes with Eleutheria syntax.<br>~<br><br>~if(\'fld(status)\'=\'getval(priorityStatus)\', &lt;b&gt;A priority member from fld(city)&lt;/b&gt;, A fld(status) member[*,*] joined us on fld(join_date))~&lt;br&gt;<br><br>|End1|</pre>\n<p>Recordsets can be nested, and their definitions can contain expressions.<br>Below we use this to facilitate master-child relationships between sets of data.<br><span style="color: #e03e2d;">IMPORTANT</span>: we use the&nbsp;<strong>param()</strong> function to facilitate PDO parameters to prevent SQL injection where we insert user data in SQL statements.<br>As explained above,&nbsp;<code>^mainCountryId^</code> below was passed as a global parameter to Eleutheria.</p>\n<pre>|rssql2;SELECT id, name, status, birthdate, city, join_date FROM person WHERE position=\'manager\' AND country_id=~param(^mainCountryId^)~|<br><br>Manager: ~name~ from ~city~&lt;br&gt;<br><br>&lt;h3&gt;List of this manager\'s staff:&lt;/h3&gt;<br><br>~$// Here we have a nested recordset that returns the staff belonging to each manager. <br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The <strong>id</strong> field in <code>param(fld(id))</code> originates from the <strong>rssql2 </strong>recordset above~<br><br>|rssql3;SELECT first_name, last_name, diet FROM staff WHERE manager_id = ~param(fld(id))~|<br><br>~$// To print the record number, use #. To print the record number inside a function use fld(#)~<br><br>~#~. ~first_name~ ~last_name~&lt;br&gt;<br><br>~$// To replace the merge field in a template which is only printed if the merge field is not empty (0 is allowed)~<br><br>~diet, This staff member prefers $$ for lunch~&lt;br&gt;<br>~$// Note, the $$ is replaced with the value of the merge field~<br><br>~$// Templates can define sections of code that can be included anywhere.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;After inclusion they are processed, so it is important that their expressions work in the contexts where they are included.<br>~<br><br>~if(\'getval(priorityStatus)\'=\'new\', incl(newMembers))~<br><br>|End3|<br><br>|End2|<br><br><br>|Section newMembers|<br><br>&lt;img src="~fld(diet)~.jpg"&gt;<br><br>~$// The output of expressions in HTML templates are HTML encoded to prevent code-injection attacks.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;When you need to include HTML, set the encoding to allow it using the <strong>encode()</strong> function.<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;The getdb()<strong> </strong>function offers another way (with its own features) to retrieve data from a database.<br>~<br><br>~encode(expr, none)getdb(diet_description_html, tbDiet, diet=param(fld(diet)))~<br><br>|End newMembers|</pre>\n<p>Template code can also be included from files or PHP functions, using the&nbsp;<strong>inclfile()</strong> and <strong>incldropintmpl()</strong> functions.</p>\n<pre>~if(fld($now,n)&gt;6,&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; inclfile(/templates/, SecondSemester.html), <br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; inclfile(/templates/, FirstSemester.html)<br>)~</pre>\n<p>Alternatively, raw HTML/text containing no Eleutheria expressions can be included from PHP functions</p>\n<pre>~encode(expr,none)dropin(/dropins/test/ComponentsClass/myFunction, getval(priorityStatus))~</pre>\n<p>HTML inside expressions can also be excluded from being encoded by using [%...%]</p>\n<pre>~if(fld($now,Y)&gt;2045,<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;[%&lt;b&gt;Singularity ahoy!&lt;/b&gt;%], <br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;[%&lt;a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=The+Singularity"&gt;The Singularity&lt;/a&gt;%]<br>)~</pre>\n<h3>Merge Fields</h3>\n<p>Two types of merge fields exist</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>global merge fields</strong> (eg&nbsp;<strong>^individualId^</strong>) - they are replaced in the template (and any child-templates) before anything else is merged.\n<ul>\n<li>To prevent unexpected results, or hacking attempts, characters with special meaning in Eleutheria are removed from global merge fields: <strong>|[~^</strong></li>\n<li>Configure the public <strong>$globalsReplacelist</strong> variable with your own regular expression to define characters to remove. For strict security, define a whitelist rather than a blacklist.&nbsp;<br><br></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>domain fields</strong> (eg&nbsp;<strong>~first_name~ </strong>or<strong> ~fld(first_name)~</strong>) - accessible only within a recordset domain based on a SQL query or array.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Recordsets</h3>\n<p>Recordsets</p>\n<ul>\n<li>overrideArray - the fld(FIELDNAME) function first checks the overrideArray for FIELDNAME, before the current domain\'s recordset.\n<ul>\n<li>Use the setoverride() function to add values</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>globalArray - an array of values and arrays passed to Eleutheria when it is loaded. The arrays&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc366-dib'),
    (367, 'Installation Checklist', 178, 15, 0, 'eleutheria', '<p>The ~navdocs(Installation Steps)~ ensures that the following are all in place which generally leads to a working Dropinbase installation:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>An appropriate <strong>A-record</strong> exists in DNS configurations to point the domain to the server\'s IP address (and has resolved), or the local&nbsp;<strong>hosts&nbsp;</strong>file has been configured (Windows).</li>\n<li>If using <strong>https</strong> (instead of <strong>http</strong>), then a current SSL certificate is configured for the domain.</li>\n<li>The Dropinbase Client and Dropinbase Framework files are installed, and the file permissions have been configured correctly (Linux).</li>\n<li>The path to the&nbsp;<strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/index.php</strong>&nbsp;file in the&nbsp;<strong>/www/myProject/index.php</strong>&nbsp;file resolves correctly.</li>\n<li>The webserver\'s Virtual Host entry is configured correctly.</li>\n<li>The webserver (Apache/Nginx) is running with all the required modules. The webserver can execute PHP (&gt;= ver 5.3) scripts, and PHP has all the required modules.\n<ul>\n<li>Test both by changing&nbsp;<strong>/index.php</strong> to run <code>phpinfo(); die();</code> and look for the required modules and extensions in the output.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>If running Apache, then the <strong>/.htaccess</strong> file is in place (unless these directives have been moved to the Virtual Host configuration).</li>\n<li>The Dropinbase database is in a MySQL compatible database, and is accessible from the webserver with credentials.</li>\n<li>The <strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong> file contains an entry for the Dropinbase database, and is has the correct credentials, host, port, collation, etc.</li>\n<li>The <strong>/configs/DibTmpl.php</strong> file is configured correctly. Check the following:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>$DBINDEX</strong> matches the entry for the Dropinbase database in <strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong>, and also the \'<strong>id</strong>\' value in the <em>pef_database</em> table.</li>\n<li><strong>$LOGINDB</strong> matches&nbsp;the entry for the database containing all the login tables (see ) in <strong>/configs/Conn.php</strong>, and also the \'<strong>id</strong>\' value in the <em>pef_database</em> table.</li>\n<li><strong>$ERRORLOGDB</strong> matches the entry for the database containing the <em>pef_error_log </em>table.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The <strong>system_public</strong>, and <strong>admin </strong>users exist and their permgroups are <strong>x2x </strong>and <strong>x1x </strong>respectively, which matches the entries in the <em>pef_login_group </em>table for these <em>pef_login </em>records.</li>\n<li>The <strong>/configs/Environment.php </strong>file is in place and runs without errors\n<ul>\n<li>Check the response of <strong>/peff/Template/Environment.js</strong> in the browser Console\'s network requests.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The <strong>/configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</strong> file does not block any files required for the login pages (check the browser Console\'s network requests).</li>\n<li>The SQL and other code in the <strong>/configs/DibUserParams.php</strong> file runs without errors.</li>\n<li>Your browser\'s cache is cleared&nbsp; - add <code>?a=1</code> (some non-used number) to URL\'s to make sure (eg https://mydomain.com/?a=123)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>After checking the above, delete the <strong>/runtime</strong> folder and refresh the browser. One should be able to sign-in and view the Dashboard and Designer.<br>For compiling containers, the correct version of <strong>Node.js</strong>, <strong>npm</strong> and <strong>Angular </strong>need to be installed and accessible by the webserver user.</p>', NULL, 0, 'dib', NULL, NULL, 'doc367-dib');
