    (24, 272, 223, 15, 'eleutheria', 'Database.php', 'Crud.php', 'getGridCritAndParams', '<p>Dropinbase provides the following database functions:<br><em>(See /vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/components/database/Database.php for details)</em></p>\n<ul>\n<li>$rst = Database::fetch() - fetch one record from database</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::execute() - fetch many records from database, OR execute a query that changes data</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::create() - create a record in a specific database table, and provide audit trailing support</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::update() - update records in a specifc database table, and provide audit trailing support</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::delete() - delete records in a specifc database table, and provide audit trailing support</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::stmt() - returns the last statement prepared</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::fetchNext() - fetches the next row of an already prepared &amp; executed PDO statement</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::setParamsType() - specify types to use in PDO parameter binding</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::hasTransaction() - returns whether a transaction has been started on given database</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::transactionBegin() - start a transaction</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::transactionCommit() - commit a transaction</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::transactionRollback()- rollback a transaction</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::count() - returns the number of records affected by the previous command. Note, not all database engines support this for all actions</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::lastErrorAdminMsg() - returns the last error message generated for the administrator</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::lastErrorUserMsg() - returns the last error message generated for the user (certain contexts only)</li>\n<li>$rst = Database::lastErrorUserMsg() - sets the lastErrorAdminMsg and lastErrorUserMsg messages</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Click the Demo Database.php functions button below.</strong><br><strong><span style="color: #c92c2c;">NOTE: the actual PHP code that is executed contains many more notes!</span></strong></p>\n<h3>Audit Trails</h3>\n<p>The <strong>Database::create/update/delete</strong> functions have a parameter that allows for storing of audit trail information in various levels of detail. <br>Note, the <strong>pef_table.pef_audit_trail_field_id</strong> field, which identifies the field value to store in <strong>pef_audit_trail.entity_id</strong>, must have a value. <br>See the example code notes for more info.</p>\n<h3>SQL Log</h3>\n<p>If&nbsp;<strong>DIB::$SQLLOGDB</strong>&nbsp;is set in Dib.php then&nbsp;<strong>all&nbsp;</strong>SQL statements (except read statements) are logged in the&nbsp;<strong>pef_sqllog&nbsp;</strong>table by default (can be overridden).</p>\n<h3>Error handling</h3>\n<p>If the SQL fails due to a system or syntax error (eg database server is down or table does not exist etc, then&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The return value ($rst) would be FALSE and <strong>Database::count()</strong> would be 0.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>An error will be logged in the <strong>pef_error_log </strong>table (or <strong>/runtime/logs/error.log</strong> on failure).</li>\n<li><strong>Database::lastErrorAdminMsg()</strong> will contain technical details of the error.</li>\n<li>If the the error originates in core DIB classes such as the Crud class,&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;Database::lastErrorUserMsg()</strong> will often contain a useful message for display to the user.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If it succeeds but there are no records then <strong>$rst</strong> would be an empty array, and <strong>Database::count()</strong> would still be 0.</p>\n<p>Note that certain database engines do not reliably return the count of affected records. Use<strong> !empty($rst)</strong> or <strong>count($rst)&lt;1</strong> instead...</p>\n<p>WARNING. In case of an error, the Database class returns <strong>FALSE </strong>but does not cause the system to stop executing PHP code.&nbsp;<br>Developers must handle potential errors.&nbsp;<br>The details of the error can however be retrieved by using the <strong>Database::lastErrorAdminMsg()</strong> and <strong>Database::lastErrorUserMsg()</strong> functions.</p>\n<h3>Referential integrity (foreign key constraint) errors&nbsp;</h3>\n<p>SQL statements that fail because of referential integrity on relationships will return FALSE, but will not be logged in error.log.<br>Use the <strong>Database::lastErrorAdminMsg() </strong>function to obtain error details.<br>If a particular INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE statement could fail because of referential integrity,<br>either run another query prior to it to ensure conditions are met that will not cause referential integrity issues, OR<br>test the result of the database call and handle it.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>The <strong>Crud.php </strong>class provides CRUD functionality based on ContainerName (for containers) or ItemId (for eg dropdown lists).<br>It makes use of the same classes that is generated specifically (under dropins/DROPIN/dibCode) for the CRUD functionality of containers/dropdowns.<br>The files are generated automatically if they do not exist.</p>\n<p>All features available in CRUD classes are available through the use of <strong>Crud.php</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete)</li>\n<li>duplication of records</li>\n<li>container specific validation is done on Create and Update as defined on items in the Designer</li>\n<li>container and item specific permissions apply on all actions as defined in the Designer</li>\n<li>grid header filters and subcontainer/activefilters are available</li>\n<li>sorting can be applied</li>\n<li>audit trailing (if specified in <strong>pef_table</strong>) applies</li>\n<li>records can be retrieved as batches/pages</li>\n<li><strong>Server-side container events apply</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Table events apply </strong>(table events DO NOT apply with Database::fetch/execute/update/create/delete)</li>\n<li>get default values</li>\n<li>get captions, primary keys, field types, etc.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Crud.php</strong> class is stored in /vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/components/Database/</p>\n<p>Click the&nbsp;<strong>Demo Crud.php functions</strong>&nbsp;button below.<br><strong><span style="color: #c92c2c;">NOTE: the actual PHP code that is executed contains many more notes!</span></strong></p>\n<h3>Error Handling</h3>\n<p>If an error occurs on any of the functions, the result is an array, eg</p>\n<p>array(\'error\', "Useful error message to display to the user.");</p>\n<p>Performance is slightly slower when using CRUD class functions since validation, getting counts, audit trails, processing filters, etc. takes time.<br>For this reason Database::fetch/execute/update/create/delete are often preferred.<br>The details of the error can however be retrieved by using the Database::lastErrorAdminMsg() function.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>It is often necessary to process the data a user has filtered on in a grid, for eg to export it to a file.<br><span>The grid may be in a subcontainer with a filter linked to a parent container, <br>or&#160;</span><span>the user may have filtered records on the grid, or selected records,&#160;<br></span><span>or all three cases may apply simultanously - limiting the records you need to work with.</span></p><p>To obtain the records, the <b>DibFunctions::getGridCritAndParams</b> function can be used.</p><p>The function extracts the specified filter data from $clientData entries and builds a SQL criteria string.<br></p><p>Click the&#160;<b>Get Filter Criteria as SQL</b>&#160;button below.<br><b><font color="#c92c2c">NOTE: the actual PHP code that is executed contains many more notes!</font></b><br></p><p><br></p>', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce24-dib'),
    (25, 275, 222, 50, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>The Eleutheria class can merge (hierarchical) data from various data-sources with templates of the following type:</p><p></p><ul><li>.xlsx</li><li>.docx</li><li>.html</li><li>.xml</li><li>any text file (.txt, .csv, etc)</li></ul><p>Note,&#160;<b>Eleutheria&#160;</b>is also used by the&#160;<b>iframe&#160;</b>dropin to display the result of merged HTML templates directly in the application, and by Dropinbase to produce PHP and Angular code in&#160;<b>dibCode&#160;</b>folders.</p><p></p><p></p>', '<font face="Arial">Use either the \'<b>redirect</b>\' or \'<b>new-tab</b>\' Response Type on the Item Event, which stops the Angular client from waiting for a JSON response, and lets the browser handle the response natively.</font><p><font face="Arial">The \'<b>new-tab</b>\'&#160;</font><span>Response Type</span><font face="Arial">&#160;is often preferred since if there are error/validation messages, they will be displayed in a new window/tab that can be closed to return the user to the application, whereas the \'<b>redirect</b>\' option will replace the application with the message.</font></p><p><font face="Arial">The error/validation message itself can be any HTML.</font></p><p><font face="Arial">See the PHP code with comments behind the actions below for more info.</font></p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce25-dib'),
    (26, 275, 224, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<span>Convert HTML to a PDF file, and store the file and/or export it to the browser.</span>', '<p>For the downloading/exporting of files the following needs to be in place:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>Response Type</strong> on the button\'s event must be \'<strong>redirect</strong>\' or \'<strong>new-tab</strong>\' (not \'<strong>actions</strong>\' which expects a JSON result from the server).</li>\n<li>The PHP function parameters must include <code>$REQUEST_TYPE=\'GET,ignoretoken\'</code> to allow GET requests, and disable the security token which will not be sent.</li>\n<li>The PHP function parameters must have <code>$containerName</code>, and <code>$itemEventId</code> or <code>$containerEventId</code> to enforce permission checking.</li>\n<li>The PHP function must send the appropiate headers, and the file contents to the browser. Use for eg. the <code>DibFunctions::exportFileToClient()</code> function to handle this.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Error and Validation Messages</h3>\n<p>If the <strong>Response Type</strong> of the button is not set to \'<strong>actions</strong>\' it will print any JSON it receives from return <code>$this-&gt;invalidResult(\'Some error or validation message\') </code>as is on the screen.</p>\n<p>There are two ways of dealing with this.</p>\n<p>The simplest way is to return a nicely formatted HTML message which is presented to the user. This works best with the \'<strong>new-tab</strong>\' option which will print it on a new browser-tab.</p>\n<p>The other option is to have two buttons. The button the user clicks is set to \'<strong>actions</strong>\' and here you can use&nbsp;<code>$this-&gt;invalidResult(\'...\')</code> to return validation and/or error messages. If there are no messages to be returned, this button returns the client-side \'<strong>run</strong>\'&nbsp; (~nav(dibexActionRun)~) action which executes the click event of the other (hidden) button that is set to \'<strong>new-tab</strong>\' and calls the code to export the file. You can reuse the same PHP function and code by adding a function parameter, for eg.&nbsp;<code>$requestPhase=\'validation\'</code>. The second (hidden) button calls the same PHP function, but with <code>?requestPhase=download</code> added to the URL in the event\'s&nbsp;<strong>Submit URL </strong>field. In your PHP code you test the value of <code>$requestPhase</code> and accordingly execute the appropiate code (either validation or file export).</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce26-dib'),
    (27, 275, 225, 10, 'none', 'General', NULL, NULL, '<font face="Arial">The <b>dibExcel </b>dropin has native Dropinbase classes that were designed to handle very large .xlsx files while optimizing performance.<br></font><span>Instead of using a library that loads the entire document into objects in memory, it works with the raw strings.</span><p><font face="Arial">The <b>DibExcel.php</b> class handles amending&#160;of existing .xslx files or creating new files based on a template, while <b>DibExcelReader.php</b> handles reading.</font></p><p><font face="Arial">See the code behind the examples below for more info.</font></p><p><font face="Arial">More specific help can be viewed in the actual .php files.</font></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce27-dib'),
    (28, 343, 210, 70, 'none', 'General', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce28-dib'),
    (29, 276, 226, 290, 'none', 'General', NULL, NULL, '<p>Sets the value of specified items.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>itemName=value</strong> (repeated): Pairs of item names and their corresponding values. <code>itemName</code> is either the name of the item in the current container or <code>containerName.itemName</code> to reference an item in another container.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Examples:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.set-value?myContainer.myItem=hello world&amp;myForm.status=done</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce29-dib'),
    (30, 276, 227, 5, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Dropinbase Actions refer to JavaScript utilities&nbsp;(compiled from TypeScript) that perform specific functions (normally only one) in the client (browser application).<br>For eg. the <strong>set-value</strong> function in the example below is used to set the (model) values of items on the container.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Actions originate from one of two sources (see examples below):</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>client-side</strong> - an element (eg a button) has an action (eg. shared.action.set-value) configured on a trigger (eg click).</span></li>\n<li><strong>server-side</strong> - PHP returns a JSON array of one or more actions to be executed in the browser.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Actions can have parameters which are supplied by URL query parameters for the first case above, and as part of the JSON result for the latter case.</p>\n<p><strong>See the Configurations-tab for a detailed explanation of how actions work and can be debugged.</strong></p>', '<p>A client-side event action is configured in the submit_url field of an Item or Container Events as follows:</p>\n<p><strong>shared.action.set-value</strong><strong>?item1=hello world&amp;item2=123&nbsp;</strong><em><span style="font-family: Arial;">(items are on the same container)<br></span></em><strong>shared.action.set-value</strong><strong>?parent.item1=hello world&amp;parent.item2=123&nbsp;</strong><em><span style="font-family: Arial;">(items are on the parent container)<br></span></em><strong>shared.action.set-value</strong><strong>?myContainer.item1=hello world&amp;myOtherContainer.itemA=123</strong><em>&nbsp;(items are on other containers)</em></p>\n<p><em>(Note, certain actions like activate-tab provide a containerName parameter instead whereby a specific container can be targetted).</em></p>\n<p>The same actions are prepared for the JSON result in PHP as follows:</p>\n<p><strong>ClientFunctions::addAction($actionList, \'set-value\', [\'item1\'=&gt;\'hello world\', \'item2\'=&gt;123));<br>ClientFunctions::addAction($actionList, \'set-value\', [\'parent.item1\'=&gt;\'hello world\', \'parent.item2\'=&gt;123));<br>ClientFunctions::addAction($actionList, \'set-value\', [\'myContainer.item1\'=&gt;\'hello world\', \'myOtherContainer.item2\'=&gt;123));</strong></p>\n<p>The addAction function\'s 4th parameter is containerName whereby a specific container can be targetted:</p>\n<p><strong>ClientFunctions::addAction($actionList, \'set-value\', [\'item1\'=&gt;\'hello world\', \'item2\'=&gt;123), \'myContainer\');</strong></p>\n<p>The values are packaged in PHP as JSON and returned to the client as follows:</p>\n<p><strong>return $this-&gt;validResult($actionList);</strong></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">View network requests in Developer Console (press F12 in Chrome -&gt; Network):</span></p>\n<p><img src="/files/dropins/dibExamples/img/ConsoleActions.png" alt=""></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">The first time an action is used since the site was loaded, the JavaScript code for the action is fetched, using a request that looks like this:<br><strong>/peff/Template/action/dibexActionBasics?actionPath=shared.action.set-value</strong><br></span><em>(Note, the containerName is part of the URL; users that don\'t have any permissions to the container will not be able to load the code).</em><br>The JavaScript is not loaded again on subsequent calls.</p>\n<h3>Action URI\'s</h3>\n<div>\n<div>The action\'s .ts file location is resolved from the action URI (eg <strong>myDropin.action.myAction</strong>) as follows:</div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>if fist part = \'shared.\' or second part = \'.action.\' -&gt; looks in /dropins/setNgxMaterial, first in developer and then system folder</li>\n<li>else look in specified dropin folder, first in developer and then system folder</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n<div>\n<div>CHILDDROPIN.action.ACTION =&gt; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;/dropins/setNgxMaterial/CHILDDROPIN/ts/actions/ACTION.ts</div>\n<div>CHILDDROPIN.action.xxx.yyy.ACTION &nbsp;=&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; /dropins/setNgxMaterial/CHILDDROPIN/ts/actions/xxx/yyy/ACTION.ts</div>\n<div>DROPIN.ACTION &nbsp;=&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;/dropins/DROPIN/ts/actions/ACTION.ts</div>\n<div>DROPIN.CHILDDROPIN.ACTION =&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; /dropins/DROPIN/CHILDDROPIN/ts/actions/ACTION.ts &nbsp; &nbsp;(DROPIN name starts with \'set\')</div>\n<div>DROPIN.xxx.yyy.ACTION =&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; /dropins/DROPIN/ts/actions/xxx/yyy/ACTION.ts</div>\n<div>DROPIN.CHILDDROPIN.xxx.yyy.ACTION =&gt; &nbsp;/dropins/DROPIN/CHILDDROPIN/ts/actions/xxx/yyy/ACTION.ts &nbsp; &nbsp;(DROPIN name starts with \'set\')</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Dropinbase compiles the code to JavaScript on-demand, or using /nav/dibRelease, and then stores it in the same dropin\'s dibCode/</span>_actions/<span style="font-family: Arial;"> folder, eg:<br></span><strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/setNgxMaterial/shared/dibCode/_actions/shared.action.set-value__a.dtxt</strong></p>\n<h3>Adding Your Own Actions</h3>\n<p>Actions are written in TypeScript and compiled by Angular to JavaScript. The source code is found in dropin folders.<br>The native Dropinbase actions are mostly all found in the following folder:<br><strong>/vendor/dropinbase/dropinbase/dropins/setNgxMaterial/shared/ts/actions/</strong></p>\n<p>You can add your own actions. Copy-paste an existing one and alter it.</p>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<h3>Debugging Actions</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Open the Console and press Ctrl-P</li>\n<li>Search for the action, \'shared.action.set-value\'</li>\n<li>Add break-points in the margin - the <strong>handle</strong>-function is called first</li>\n<li>Execute the action to let the first break-point activate</li>\n<li>Use the debug-toolbar to step through execution. <br>All break-points can also be disabled, or execution can be paused.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce30-dib'),
    (31, 272, 228, 100, 'none', 'General', NULL, NULL, '<p><font face="Arial">Most server scripts execute within the time limit imposed by PHP and the browser\'s configurations, while preparing a response for the client.</font></p><p><font face="Arial">Normally scripts that potentially take more time are handled using one of the following strategies:</font></p><p></p><ol><li><font face="Arial">Increase both the client and server timeouts (normally not a good solution)</font></li><li><font face="Arial">Use Dropinbase Queues (most often the best solution)</font></li><li><font face="Arial">Execute the actual script asynchronously (and impose an acceptable timelimit), and either:</font></li><ol><li><span>inform the user that they can click a certain button to periodically check the status, OR&#160;</span></li><li><span>start a queue and service it with actions from within the asynchronous script</span></li></ol></ol><p></p><p><span>The example below uses the third method to run a very basic script asynchronously, and starts a queue for handling progress messages and actions to keep the user informed.</span><br></p><p><font face="Arial">Note, using Dropinbase Queues is easier to configure. See ~nav(dibexQueue)~ for more info.</font></p><p><span>A very valid use-case for asynchronous threads is if multiple threads must be executed simultaneously. This mechanism is used on /nav/dibRelease to create dibCode files.</span><br></p><h2><span>Error Log</span></h2><p><span>PHP creates a error log for each asynchronous thread. The log is stored in /runtime/logs and named according to the PHP file that is run.</span></p><p><span><b>See the code behind the button below for more info.</b></span></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce31-dib'),
    (32, 266, 230, 60, 'none', 'General & Configuration', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Enable editing of only one row at a time.</p>\n<p>Add a <strong>columnHeader </strong>component containing a <strong>btnGridInlineEdit </strong>button.<br>The button will become a \'save\' button as soon as editing is toggled.</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce32-dib'),
    (33, 266, 231, 50, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>The <strong>gridExcelEditingEnabled </strong>Container Setting enables inline editing of all rows in a grid, like editing an Excel file.</p>\n<p>Note, the design contains a <strong>btnGridInlineSave </strong>button in the first column, but it only appears when a new record is added, since the <strong>gridExcelEditingAutoSave </strong>Container Setting is true.<br>Set it to <strong>false </strong>to make the button appear and let the user manually save their changes to existing and new records.</p>\n<p>Check/uncheck the VIP field - note the conditional styling works the same as for non-editable grids.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Required:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>gridExcelEditingEnabled=true</strong> (Container Setting)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Required (to enable adding of records):</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>btnGridInlineAdd </strong>in toolbar above the columns</li>\n<li><strong>btnGridInlineSave </strong>in <strong>columnHeader </strong>under columns (required, irrespective of <strong>gridExcelEditingAutoSave </strong>setting below)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Optional:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>gridExcelEditingAutoSave=true</strong> (Container Setting) - to enable auto saving of changes to existing records</li>\n<li><strong>btnGridToggleEditing </strong>in toolbar above the columns - to toggle editing mode</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce33-dib'),
    (34, 272, 229, 100, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce34-dib'),
    (35, 265, 232, 30, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">"Plain" containers are not linked to data-sources.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Any items on them cannot be bound to fields.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">They can contain mostly any type of component, and can nest other containers in&nbsp;<strong>subcontainer</strong> components or via ~nav(dibexPorts, Ports)~.</span></p>', '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Required settings (Designer -&gt; Container Details -&gt; Pg1):</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Container Type = plain</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Model = None</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Table = (empty)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Sql = (empty)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Crud Store Controller = (empty)</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">&nbsp;</span></p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce35-dib'),
    (36, 277, 233, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', 'fill-height configs', '<p><strong>Iframes </strong>use Eleutheria to process and display the output of HTML templates at runtime. <strong>Eleutheria (eh-le-oo-the-ree-ah)&nbsp;</strong>is a powerful, fast and flexible templating engine that incorporates coding principles (eg loops and conditions) to merge field values and produce a document based on the template.</p>\n<p>Iframe containers are always linked to a&nbsp;<strong>Template </strong>(Pg 2 in the Designer).</p>\n<p>Templates have two types of Eleutheria merge fields:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>global merge fields (eg <strong>^individualId^</strong>) - filled from <strong>Client Data</strong> and <strong>User Parameters</strong> specified in the <strong>Valid Params </strong>field (Designer - Pg2).</li>\n<li>domain fields (eg <strong>~$delim~first_name~$delim~</strong>) - declared within a recordset defined by for eg a SQL query.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>NOTES:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The iframe container can (optionally) be linked to a Table, Sql or Custom Controller which will can be used as a record source for domain fields.</li>\n<li>Field values merged into HTML templates are HTML encoded for security reasons.</li>\n<li>When the <strong>Template </strong>field is used to reference a PHP component file instead, the latter must contain a class returning the complete HTML to be displayed in the iframe. See ~nav(dibexiFramePhp)~.</li>\n<li>The container\'s configuration is cached in dibCode. Remember to clear dibCode for the iframe container should any values change.</li>\n<li>You can comment out an Eleutheria expression but not a block of code. Ie using &lt;!-- ... --&gt; does NOT comment out the Eleutheria code - it will still be processed, and can cause errors if it is incorrect.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>More About Eleutheria</h2>\n<p>Dropinbase makes use of Eleutheria to generate the server- and client-side code for the entire application from the Dropinbase database entries. Client-side code is thereafter parsed with Angular.</p>\n<p>Eleutheria can also be called with PHP to process other types of templates, notably .xlsx, .docx, .txt, etc. <br>See ~navdocs(Eleutheria)~ and the PHP examples for more info.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><strong>Required (under Container Details of the iframe container):</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Container Type</strong> (pef_display_dropin_id) = iframe</li>\n<li><strong>Template </strong>(Pg2)\n<ul>\n<li>reference to .html template which must be in a /dropins/ folder,&nbsp;eg <strong>/dibExamples/templates/dibexiFrameEleutheria.html</strong></li>\n<li>OR reference to a .php file that contains a class returning the complete HTML to display. See ~nav(dibexiFramePhp)~.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Valid Params</strong> - specify allowed parameters (see below)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If the template itself has any references to images, css, or JavaScript files etc. that are stored in the project code folders, these folders and the file extensions must be added to the <strong>/configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</strong> file to make them accessible.</p>\n<p>Eg, for: <code>&lt;img src="/files/dropins/myDropin/images/test.png"&gt;</code></p>\n<p>Add <strong>\'files/dropins/myDropin/images\'</strong> and <strong>\'png\'</strong> to the relevant arrays in the <strong>AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</strong> file.<br>Note, files within these folders with matching file extensions will become publicly available.</p>\n<p>If the Model and related Table, Sql, or Custom Controller is specified, then Dropinbase fetches the data and passes it to Eleutheria. In the template it is accessible through an array named \'records\', eg</p>\n<pre>~$delimDb~rsarr1;records~$delimDb~\nHello ~$delim~first_name~$delim~ ~$delim~last_name~$delim~\n~$delimDb~End1~$delimDb~\n</pre>\n<div>~incldocs(incl_validParams)~</div>\n<h2>Iframe height</h2>\n<p>As with grids, Dropinbase uses the fill-height directive by default to vertically size iframe\'s to fill the remaining portion of the screen. This is a problem however should the remaining space not be enough which is the case on small screens or where the iframe is loaded in a space which is already low down on the screen.</p>\n<p>To override this, populate&nbsp;<strong>attributes3 </strong>on Pg2 of the iframe container.</p>\n<p>See the fill-height-tab for more info about&nbsp;<strong>fill-height</strong> properties and setting heights.</p>\n<h2>Executing Dropinbase Functions</h2>\n<p>By including the following reference in the HTML template, it is possible to access the Dropinbase framework:</p>\n<div>&lt;script type="text/javascript" src="/files/dropins/setNgxMaterial/dibAdmin/js/template/TemplateActions.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</div>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexiFrameDropinbaseFunctions)~ for more info.</p>\n<p><strong>Server-side function calls</strong></p>\n<p><strong>*** NOTE</strong>, if a server-side function is called that has the <strong>$containerName</strong> and/or <strong>$itemEventId</strong> parameters specified in the function definition, then values for these parameters must be sent to check permissions. This also implies that a event has been specified in Dropinbase on container <strong>$containerName</strong>, for item/container event that has a dibuid value of <strong>$itemEventId</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>If there is no existing event specified, then simply add a hidden button to the iframe container with an item event. Make sure the item event has a dibuid value (an unique identifying string for this event). Use the iframe container\'s name and the dibuid value specified for the dibCommon.startAction parameters.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>~incldocs(incl_fillHeight)~</p>', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce36-dib'),
    (37, 277, 234, 20, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>The source of the HTML can be a PHP component class function.</p>\n<p>In this example, the PHP returns the entire HTML document.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>To pull HTML for only certain parts of the document (from potentially different PHP components), rather use the <strong>dropin </strong>Eleutheria function in the HTML template, eg:</p>\n<div>\n<div><code>~$delim~encode(expr, none)dropin(/dropins/main/PhpComponent/functionReturningHtml, ^id^, ^alias_parent_tmplId^)~$delim~</code></div>\n</div>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexiFrameEleutheria)~ for more info about iframes.</p>', '<p>The Valid Params on Pg2 is not required. All Client Data is passed to the PHP function.<br>The path to the template must be the path to the PHP file.</p>\n<p>Eg <strong>/dibExamples/components/dibexiFramePhp.php&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>the class must contain the following static function: <code>public static function merge($containerName, $clientData, $activeFilter, $echoContent=true) {...}</code></li>\n<li>the function must echo the HTML string to the client.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If the content returned has any references to images, css, or JavaScript files etc. that are stored in the project code folders, these folders and the file extensions must be added to the <strong>/configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</strong>&nbsp;file to make them accessible.</p>\n<p>Eg, for:&nbsp;<code>&lt;img src="/files/dropins/myDropin/images/test.png"&gt;</code></p>\n<p>Add&nbsp;<strong>\'files/dropins/myDropin/images\'</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>\'png\'</strong> to the relevant arrays in the <strong>/configs/AllowedFileExtAndFolders.php</strong> file.</p>\n<p>Note, files within these folders with matching file extensions will become publicly available.</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce37-dib'),
    (38, 269, 237, 20, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<font face="Arial">This example shows how containers that are loaded with <b>ports </b>can be filtered.</font><p><font face="Arial">Note, when containers are on <b>tabs</b>, a <b>subcontainer </b>is normally used for the first container so that it is visible when the parent container is opened.</font></p>', '<p><font face="Arial">Required:</font></p><font face="Arial"><ul><li><font face="Arial">A div (or card or column, etc) is used for the second tab instead of a subcontainer component.</font></li><li><font face="Arial">The Child Container field must be populated.</font></li></ul></font><p><font face="Arial">If required, the filter field of the second tab is populated. In this case with:<br></font><span><font face="Arial"><b>test_project.client_id = :alias_parent_id</b></font></span></p><p><span><font face="Arial">Alternatively the filter could also be placed on the testProjectGrid container\'s filter field.<br></font></span><span>This implies though that this filter is applicable wherever the container is loaded.</span></p><p><font face="Arial">Note, if there is a filter on both the tab (the Port Item) and the container, the combination of their criteria will apply.</font></p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce38-dib'),
    (39, 278, 238, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>As mentioned, applications consist of containers that are nested in one-another. They can be nested:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>as a subcontainer (like the \'plain\' container above) meaning they are automatically loaded into the view after their parent container is loaded, OR</li>\n<li>via a port, meaning they are only loaded when and if requested.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Ports allow you to have 1000\'s of containers, and users will only load those they need and have access to. <br>A container\'s Port records define the items (eg a div/card) in which this container can be loaded.&nbsp;<br><br>Ports are very flexible:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Any layout item like a tab, card or div, can be designated as the target where a container must be loaded.</li>\n<li>Ports are activated by an event, eg. the click of a button. More often the event is the click of a tab that loads a container within the same tab.</li>\n<li>When a port is activated, the URL can optionally change. And if a user browses to that URL, then that port will be activated.</li>\n<li>Containers can be loaded as popup windows (either maximized or not), or inside other layout items.</li>\n<li>The same container can be loaded into different positions and each instance will function independently.</li>\n<li>Multiple containers can be loaded into the same port (eg. a tab), replacing one another. The tab\'s caption will be updated to the caption set on the port record, and if this is not set, the container\'s caption.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>More about Ports:</strong></p>\n<p>A port can be activated by a URL. URL\'s of the form <strong>/nav/[containerName] </strong>activates the default port record, where the Port Alias field = \'main\'.<br>Secondary port records for a particular container are activated by:&nbsp;<strong>/nav/[containerName]/[alias]</strong>.</p>\n<p>When a container is loaded via a URL, Dropinbase makes a <strong>/peff/Container/getPortInfo</strong> request to obtain details of the container\'s port and the Port Item on the parent container in which it is nested (filter for these requests in the Console). If the parent is not yet loaded, another <strong>getPortInfo </strong>request is made, and so on until the base container is reached. Then containers are loaded in reverse until the target container is loaded. Note, the getPortInfo requests always retrieve the details of the default/main Port record of parent containers.</p>\n<p>Note,&nbsp;<strong>tabs</strong>&nbsp;have a special relationship with Ports. A tab remembers which container was last loaded into it, and will display that container when clicked, even though the original Port configured on the tab loads a different container.<br>This improves the user experience where more than one container (eg a grid and a form based on the same table) loads into the same tab.<br>Examples of this is seen in the Dropinbase Admin application (eg. SQL, Tables, etc.).</p>\n<p><strong>Why the term \'Port\'?</strong><br>A boat (container) can dock at many ports, or a USB device can plug into many ports.<br>The difference though is that a container can "dock" in many items at the same time, and function independently in each.</p>\n<p><br><br></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>A port record must be created for each item which a specific container can be attached to.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>A container must always have a port record, unless it is only ever loaded via&nbsp;<strong>subcontainer&nbsp;</strong>components.</p>\n<p>The <strong>Port Alias</strong> field must be set to \'main\' for at least one of the container\'s port records - this identifies the <strong>default </strong>port record.<br>When a user navigates to /nav/CONTAINERNAME the default port record is activated.</p>\n<p>When the&nbsp;<strong>"Open Container / Port"</strong>&nbsp;field of an item is linked to a port record, this item\'s click event will activate the port.</p>\n<p>To enlist other triggers (eg. \'blur\') use ~nav(dibexEventBasics, Item or Container Events)~.</p>\n<p>When a developer adds a port record for a container using the Designer, Dropinbase sets the Port Item by default to the related database\'s Port Item field. If the container is not linked to a table or SQL statement whereby Dropinbase can derive the database record and therefore the Port Item, the main Settings table (<em>pef_setting</em>) is queried for \'Default Base Container\' and \'Default Port Item\' to obtain the Port Item. These values are set when Dropinbase creates a Base Container using the Application Wizard, but can be manually updated.</p>\n<p><strong>Port Record Attributes</strong></p>\n<p>The Port Record fields define various aspects, like whether a container opens as a popup window and whether the URL changes. <br>Use the&nbsp;<img src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/images/docs/helpButton.png" alt="" width="24px" height="24px">-button in the Designer to view detailed help for the various Port fields.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce39-dib'),
    (40, 278, 239, 20, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Windows give the user the user the ability to "drill down" into a certain feature, and when they close it, they\'ll be back at their original place.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Note, although Dropinbase provides stacking of windows, it can add complexity to the user\'s experience and must be implemented with discretion.</span></p>', '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Required (on the Port record):</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Ports that use URL query parameters to communicate information like&nbsp;</span><strong>?record=new</strong> or <strong>?primary_id=123</strong>&nbsp; must have the <strong>Change Url</strong> setting set.</li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Window Mode = window/dialog</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Window State = normal/maximized</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Keep History</h3>\n<p>This affects whether a popup window is kept open (in history) when another popup window is opened. If not set, opening another popup window will close the current one.</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce40-dib'),
    (41, 280, 240, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Permissions are highly configurable and are only partially demonstrated in the examples.<br>See ~navdocs(Permissions and Business Rules)~ for more info.</p>\n<p>On the <strong>form </strong>container <span style="font-family: Arial;">below,&nbsp;</span>the Admin user:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Can <strong>read all</strong> records, but <strong>create and update</strong> only where the existing values of records satisfy:</li>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>vip=1 AND name LIKE \'test%\'</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<li>New values for name must be <strong>LIKE \'test%\'</strong></li>\n<li>Cannot <strong>delete</strong> any records</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">On the <strong>grid </strong>container, the Admin user:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Can <strong>read</strong> all records where&nbsp;<strong>status&lt;&gt;\'complete\'</strong>.</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Can only <strong>delete </strong>records where&nbsp;<strong>vip=1 <em>in the related parent client record via an Extra Table Join.</em></strong></span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Automatic Removal of Items</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Permission settings cause items like menu items, buttons, subcontainers, and tabs to be removed depending on whether the user has the relevant rights, and access to target containers involved.</li>\n<li>Certain buttons are automatically removed based on rights.&nbsp;<strong>btnDelete </strong>was removed since Admin cannot delete records. No<strong>&nbsp;create&nbsp;</strong>rights<span style="font-family: Arial;">&nbsp;in the grid</span>&nbsp;caused <strong>btnAdd </strong>to be removed, etc.</li>\n<li><strong>btnOpenContainer</strong>&nbsp;on the <strong>form</strong>, and <strong>btnGridEdit</strong> in&nbsp;the <strong>grid</strong> was removed since it is linked to a container that the user does not have rights to.</li>\n<li>The second tab below was removed, since its&nbsp;<strong>Port </strong>references a <strong>form </strong>container that the Admin user has no rights to.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Filters, Client Data and Permissions</strong></p>\n<p>Note, although <strong>filters</strong> limit records, filters must not be used for permission purposes, since they rely on parameters and Client Data sent from the browser to the server.<br>Hackers can easily adjust any information sent from the browser to the server. <br><strong>Permissions must solely depend on code and data (eg ~nav(dibexSqlParams, Server-side SQL Parameters)~ stored on the server that users cannot ever access.</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce41-dib'),
    (42, 280, 243, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, 'Create, View/Read and Update permissions can be specified on items. Criteria can be added for data fields.<br>This example demonstrates only a subset of features. For more information, see ~navdocs(Item Permissions)~.<br><p><br></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce42-dib'),
    (43, 266, 245, 45, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>The&nbsp;<strong>gridMultiselect </strong>container setting enables users to select more than one row (on both Table and SQL grids).</p>\n<p>The Client Data -&gt; <strong>selected </strong>will contain the primary key values of the selected rows, while&nbsp;<strong>clickedLast</strong> will contain all values of items <span style="text-decoration: underline;">with aliases</span> of the last row clicked.</p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">There are various other grid settings that control selection. Use the +<img src="/files/dropins/setNgxMaterial/dibAdmin/images/wiz-24px.png"> button under Container Settings in the Designer to add them.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">It is also possible to submit any column value of the current row as part of the URL (see the <strong>Row Id</strong> button below).</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">&nbsp;</span></p>', '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">To enable multiselect, add <strong>gridMultiselect = true</strong> to Container Settings.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">SQL Grids must either have a column named <strong>\'id\'</strong>, or specify a column that has unique values in <strong>Primary Field</strong>. The column need not be present in the grid itself.<br>The primary key(s) of a Table Grid must be present in the grid itself.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">When multiselect is enabled, Client Data will return an array of objects, eg</span></p>\n<p><strong><span class="name" title="clientData.selected_self">selected_self :&nbsp;</span>[{"id":123, "id":"321"}]</strong></p>\n<p>When multiselect is disabled, Client Data will return a object, eg<br><strong><span class="name" title="clientData.selected_self">selected_self :&nbsp;</span></strong><strong>{"id":123}</strong></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">The Info button inside the grid uses the following client-side action:<br><strong>shared.action.message?messageText=Id:@{actionData.cc_id}&amp;messageTitle=Clicked</strong><br></span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Note, the button has the following attribute which enables the replace of the </span><strong>@{actionData.cc_id} </strong><span style="font-family: Arial;">reference:</span><br><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>[actionData]=row</strong></span></p>\n<p>This is also used on the <strong>Row Id</strong> button to submit a value to the server. Any column value can be submitted in the same way.</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce43-dib'),
    (45, 278, 246, 30, 'none', 'General', 'Resources / More Info', NULL, '<font face="Arial">Dialogs can be used to gather information from users that is then passed on via Client Data to the server with buttons.</font><p><font face="Arial">There are two special components available for dialogs only which helps to make a scrollable div while keeping the buttons visible.<br></font><font face="Arial"><b>dialogContent </b>and <b>dialogActions </b>which corresponds with the Angu</font><span>lar&#160;</span><b>&lt;mat-dialog-content&gt;</b><span> and&#160;</span><b>&lt;mat-dialog-actions&gt;</b><span> tags.</span></p><p></p><p><font face="Arial"><br></font></p><p></p>', '<a href="https://material.angular.io/components/dialog/overview" target="_blank">https://material.angular.io/components/dialog/overview</a><br><p><font face="Arial"><br></font></p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce45-dib'),
    (46, 281, 247, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Dropinbase makes ~nav(dibexClientData, Client Data)~, User, and certain other values available for use as parameters in SQL queries of dropdowns, grids and in Eleutheria Templates.</span></p>\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">SQL Parameters is the key to display related and permitted data in containers and dropdowns.</span></span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Note, permitted data must always be controlled by server-side parameter values. <span style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">Any limiting that is dependant on Client Data is not secure since hackers can easily manipulate the data submitted from the client (browser)</span>.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">See the <strong>Configurations</strong>-tab for parameter details.<br></span></p>\n<p>The parameters can be used in any of the following parts of the query:</p>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>select-clause</li>\n<li>from-clause</li>\n<li>where-clause</li>\n<li>having-clause</li>\n<li>sql-header</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Parameters are also available in the following Dropinbase features:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>Extra Table Joins</strong> (in Containers and Container Permissions)</span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>Filters</strong></span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>Permission SQL Criteria</strong></span></li>\n<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>Expression </strong>field for <strong>SQL Insert</strong> fields</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The values are bound as PHP&nbsp;<a href="https://www.php.net/manual/en/pdostatement.bindparam.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PDO parameters</a> in queries.</p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<h2>Client Data Parameters</h2>\n<p>Any values in <span style="font-family: Arial;">~nav(dibexClientData, Client Data)~</span> can be used as parameters in queries and filters.&nbsp;<br>Note, since they originate from the client, they are not safe for use as permission criteria.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>To view a particular request\'s available <strong>Client Data</strong> parameters, open the <strong>Console </strong>(press F12 in Chrome) and execute the request (eg refresh a grid\'s data).<br>Click on the <strong>Network</strong>-tab and find the request. Here are examples of what common requests look like:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>/peff/Crud/read/CONTAINERNAME</strong> - grid \'read\' request (replace \'read\' with update/create/delete for other requests)</li>\n<li><strong>/peff/Crud/view/CONTAINERNAME</strong> - form \'read\' request (replace \'read\' with update/create/delete/toolbarinfo for other requests)</li>\n<li><strong>/peff/Crud/componentlist/CONTAINERNAME/?containerItemId=123</strong> - dropdown-list request</li>\n<li><strong>/dropins/dibExamples/Event/helloWorld</strong> - custom button request</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Click on the <strong>Payload</strong>-tab, and open <strong>clientData</strong>:</p>\n<p><img src="/files/dropins/dibExamples/img/ConsoleClientData2.png" alt="" width="834" height="464"></p>\n<p>To use the <strong>id </strong>value of <strong>alias_parent</strong>, and the <strong>area</strong> value of <strong>query_params </strong>(note, <strong>query_params </strong>includes the browser\'s URL query parameters):</p>\n<p><code>SELECT id, name FROM test_client WHERE id = :alias_parent_id AND name LIKE (\'%\', :query_params_area, \'%\')</code></p>\n<p>When users select multiple records in grids, then <strong>selected </strong>will contain an array of values, eg:</p>\n<p><code>selected: [{id: 3}, {id: 5}]</code></p>\n<p>Although not often used in queries, they can be referenced using the array index of each value, starting with 0 for the first one (1 for the second, etc):</p>\n<p><code>SELECT id, name FROM test_client WHERE id = <strong>:selected_0_id</strong></code></p>\n<p>The <strong>clickedLast</strong> variable contains all values of the last row clicked in a grid:</p>\n<p><code>SELECT id, name FROM test_client WHERE id = <strong>:clickedLast_cliendContactFilterGrid_id</strong></code></p>\n<p>~incldocs(incl_sqlQueryParams)~</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce46-dib'),
    (47, 281, 248, 20, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>PHP Parameters offers full control over a SQL query. Any part or all of a SQL statement can be adjusted.</p>\n<p>This method is often used to insert portions of SQL that are required in multiple queries and to implement custom permissions.<br>The obvious advantages are&nbsp; that queries can be fully customized on the fly with the power of PHP, and that the code can be maintained in a single place.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<div>\n<div>References to PHP functions can be placed in the SQL, in any of the following parts:</div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>select-clause</li>\n<li>from-clause</li>\n<li>where-clause</li>\n<li>having-clause</li>\n<li>sql-header</li>\n<li>read-criteria (container permissions field)</li>\n<li>read-extra_join (container permissions field)</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div>The reference(s) must be of the form:</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div><code>{:/dropins/DROPIN/COMPONENTNAME/FUNCTIONNAME[, var]}</code></div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Example:</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p><code>{:/dropins/dibExamples/SqlPhpParams/replaceParams}</code></p>\n<p>or with a parameter:</p>\n<p><code>{:/dropins/dibExamples/SqlPhpParams/replaceParams, blue-fruit}</code></p>\n<p>The PHP function must have the following parameters (see the example referenced above for detailed parameter descriptions):</p>\n<div>\n<div><code>public static function replaceParams($containerName, &amp;$params=array(), $flatClientData=array(), &amp;$sql=\'\', $var=null)</code></div>\n</div>\n<p>The PHP has access to various inputs and values that inform the transformation of the SQL:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>$containerName - name of the container that made the request</li>\n<li>$flatClientData - <span style="font-family: Arial;">~nav(dibexClientData, Client Data)~</span> sent to the request, in flattened format.</li>\n<li>$var - parameter value (if any) sent with the reference</li>\n<li>DIB::$USER - User login variables. See help at ~nav(dibexSqlParams)~ on how to add/adjust these variables</li>\n<li>Other - the code can execute SQL statements to lookup values or create temporary tables etc.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The code can replace strings and/or return a string value. The end-goal of the PHP code is to populate the following fields:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>$sql </strong>- the SQL statement that returns records (passed by reference)</li>\n<li><strong>$params</strong> - any PDO parameters required by the SQL statement (passed by reference)</li>\n<li><strong>return value</strong> - a string value to replace the {:/dropins...} reference with - often just an empty string if the code replaces strings.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Alternatively the PHP can return an error that will be logged in the error log:</p>\n<p><code>return array(\'error\', $errorMessage);</code> <br>A generic error notice will be displayed to the user to contact the System Administrator.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce47-dib'),
    (48, 282, 252, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Client-side default values populate bound input fields (items linked to table fields) on new records, and unbound input fields when the container first opens.</p>\n<p>~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices, Dropinbase Services)~ are enabled in client-side defaults<br>Simply place any string with references to values (eg <strong>Hello @{env_user_fullname}</strong>) in the <strong>Client Default</strong> field. See the Configuration-tab for&nbsp; more examples.</p>\n<p>Client-side defaults are often used to populate foreign key values in new records, especially on editable child-grids (see Configurations-tab, and live example below).</p>\n<p>Although less flexible, it has the following advantages over server-side defaults:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Works on any type of container. Server-side defaults work only on forms and editable grids where the <strong>/peff/Crud/getDefaults</strong> call returns values.</li>\n<li>No call to the server is made</li>\n<li>A definition for a default value can contain a combination of references and hardcoded values (see <strong>Configuration</strong>-tab)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Order of Methods that Set Values on New Records:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Set values specified in client-side defaults</li>\n<li>Set values specified in server-side defaults</li>\n<li>Set values defined in the URL, eg /nav/myForm?record=new&amp;myForm.notes=xxxx</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Which means URL values override server-side defaults which override client-side defaults. Client-side defaults will always be replaced by the other two.</p>\n<p><strong>More Info:</strong></p>\n<p>~nav(dibexDefaultValuesServer, Server-Side Default Values)~ - especially note the advantages of Table and Container Events for setting values.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>~incldocs(incl_clientDefaults)~</p>\n<h2>Populating values in new records</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario 1</strong></p>\n<p>A form based on <strong>table A</strong> contains a grid based on <strong>table B</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Table B</strong> has a foreign key field referencing the primary key of <strong>table A</strong>.</p>\n<p>Place the following in <strong>Client Default </strong>of the foreign key field.</p>\n<p><code>@{value_parent_id}</code>&nbsp; <em>(where id is the name of the primary key field on the form)</em>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Note this field and the primary key field can be hidden but present, and not removed from the DOM with&nbsp;<strong>*ngIf</strong>.</p>\n<p>If the foreign key field is a hidden number field, it is best to use the <strong>inputNumber </strong>component rather than an <strong>autocomplete </strong>which is more resource intensive.</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario 2</strong></p>\n<p>A button on a container is used to open a popup form for adding new records.</p>\n<p>The new records have one or more fields that must be auto-populated. These fields can be hidden, but must be present.</p>\n<p>If for eg a <strong>company_id </strong>field on the popup must get its value from a dropdown named <strong>main_id </strong>on the base container named <strong>base</strong>,<br>place the following in&nbsp;<strong>Client Default</strong> of the <strong>company_id </strong>field.</p>\n<p><code>@{value_base_main_id}</code>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce48-dib'),
    (49, 282, 253, 20, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Server defaults are set on new records only.</p>\n<p>When Dropinbase makes a new record available for editing in both forms and grids, it sends a request to fetch any default values from the server.<br>The request is of the form:<br><strong>/peff/Crud/getDefaults/CONTAINERNAME</strong></p>\n<p>Any values entered in the CRUD Default field of both bound and unbound items are processed on the server, and an array is returned with values to be set.</p>\n<p><strong>Order of Methods that Set Values on New Records:</strong></p>\n<ol>\n<li>Set values specified in client-side defaults</li>\n<li>Set values specified in server-side defaults</li>\n<li>Set values defined in the URL, eg /nav/myForm?record=new&amp;myForm.notes=xxxx</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Which means URL values override server-side defaults which override client-side defaults. Values set by the URL will replace values set using server-side defaults.</p>\n<h2>Table and Container Events</h2>\n<p>The <strong>gd </strong>(get defaults) Table Event and&nbsp;<strong>get defaults</strong>&nbsp;Container Event is the most flexible method of constructing default values. Table Events ensure that values are set correctly for all containers linked to a particular table.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>If you need to force a value, use the&nbsp;<strong>bc </strong>(before create) and&nbsp;<strong>bu&nbsp;</strong>(before update) Table Events. If the values relate only to the current container and there are other containers linked to the same table, then the <strong>before update </strong>and <strong>before create </strong>Container Events can be used instead.</p>\n<p>Table and Container Events can prevent CRUD actions from occuring and optionally return custom error/validation messages to the user.</p>', '<h2>Dropinbase Values for the CRUD Default field</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>:dibDateTime </strong>- date(\'Y-m-d H:i:s\')</li>\n<li><strong>:dibDate</strong> -&nbsp;date(\'Y-m-d\')</li>\n<li><strong>:dibTime</strong> -&nbsp;date(\'H:i:s\')</li>\n<li><strong>:dibSessionIdMd5</strong> - md5(session_id()) - the md5 hash of the PHP session. ***</li>\n<li><strong>:dibIp</strong> - DibApp::getRealIpAddr(), eg 192.168.1.8</li>\n<li><strong>:dibUniqueId</strong> - cryptographic strong unique random number tied to a user session and set in Authenticator.php; never sent to the browser.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>User Parameter Values</h2>\nValues configured in <b>/configs/DibUserParams.php</b> that are tied to the user\'s session.\n<br>Eg :dibUser_username  or :dibUser_employee_id\n\n<h2>Client Data Values</h2>\n<p>To view the available <strong>Client Data</strong> parameters, open the <strong>Console </strong>(press F12 in Chrome) and then open a new record.<br>Click on the <strong>Network</strong>-tab and type \'getDefaults\' in the Filter to find the /peff/Crud/getDefaults/CONTAINERNAME request for this container.</p>\n<p>Click on the <strong>Payload</strong>-tab, and open <strong>clientData</strong>:</p>\n<p><img src="/files/dropins/dibExamples/img/ConsoleClientData2.png" alt="" width="834" height="464"></p>\n<p>To use the <strong>area </strong>value in <strong>query_params</strong> in the example above&nbsp;<strong> </strong>(note, <strong>query_params </strong>includes the browser\'s URL query parameters):</p>\n<p><code><strong>:query_params_area</strong></code></p>\n<p>When users select multiple records in grids, then <strong>selected </strong>will contain an array of values, eg:</p>\n<p><code>selected: [{id: 3}, {id: 5}]</code></p>\n<p>Although not often used in defaults, they can be referenced using the array index of each value, starting with 0 for the first one (1 for the second, etc):</p>\n<p><code><strong>:selected_1_id</strong></code>&nbsp;- will return 5 in this example.</p>\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>clickedLast</strong> variable contains all values of the last row clicked in a grid:</p>\n<p><code><strong>:clickedLast_cliendContactFilterGrid_id</strong></code></p>\n<h2>PHP Code or Hard Coded Values</h2>\n<p>If no match is found for any of the above (Dropinbase&nbsp; or Client Data Values) then the text is inserted "as is" in the PHP code. It is assumed to be something like this:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>\'some string here\'</strong>&nbsp; (include the quotes!)</li>\n<li><strong>"Greetings " . $attributes[\'name\']</strong></li>\n<li style="font-weight: bold;"><strong>"Stored on " . Date(\'Y-m-d\') . " by " . DIB::$USER[\'username\']</strong></li>\n<li><strong>123</strong>&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>While this provides tremendous flexibility, care should be taken!</p>\n<ul>\n<li>It can cause an error if the text is not executable.</li>\n<li>It can be a security concern but only if hackers can access your dropinbase database. Treat your dropinbase database like your source-code.&nbsp;<em><strong>Use a read-only database user for the dropinbase database on your production server</strong></em>, and<em><strong>control access for developers to any other server where this database is kept</strong></em>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Table Events</h2>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexTableEvents, Table Events)~ for more info.</p>\n<h2>Container Events</h2>\n<p>See ~nav(dibexContainerEvents, Container Events)~ for more info.</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce49-dib'),
    (50, 279, 266, 90, 'none', 'General', 'References', NULL, '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Buttons are used to perform actions.</span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">There are many ways to style and configure them using Dropinbase and Angular Material.</span></p>', '<font face="Arial">buttons:&#160;</font><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/button/overview" target="_blank">https://material.angular.io/components/button/overview</a><p>icons:&#160;<a href="https://material.angular.io/components/icon/overview" target="_blank">https://material.angular.io/components/icon/overview</a><br></p><p><font face="Arial">exhibitCard:&#160;</font></p>', '', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce50-dib'),
    (51, 279, 259, 10, 'none', 'General', 'References', NULL, '<p>These inputs are used to reflect boolean values, although additional attributes can change this behaviour.</p>\n<p>See the References-tab for more info.</p>', '<font face="Arial">checkbox:&#160;</font><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/checkbox/overview" target="_blank">https://material.angular.io/components/checkbox/overview</a><p><font face="Arial">slideToggle:&#160;</font><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/slide-toggle/overview" target="_blank">https://material.angular.io/components/slide-toggle/overview</a></p><p><font face="Arial">radioButton, radioGroup, inputRadio:&#160;</font><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/radio/overview" target="_blank">https://material.angular.io/components/radio/overview</a></p>', '', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce51-dib'),
    (52, 279, 261, 30, 'none', 'General', 'References', NULL, '<p>Angular Material provides a highly configurable <strong>datepicker </strong>component. See the References-tab for more info.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase also ships with templates for common date inputs.</p>\n<p>If you require a specific customization it is easy to add attributes, or even create your own template.</p>', '<p>datepicker: <a href="https://material.angular.io/components/datepicker/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/datepicker/overview</a></p>\n<p>HTML components:</p>\n<p><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/date">https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/date</a></p>\n<p><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/datetime-local">https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/datetime-local</a></p>\n<p><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/month">https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/month</a></p>\n<p><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/time">https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/time</a></p>\n<p><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/week">https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input/week</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce52-dib'),
    (53, 279, 262, 50, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>The <strong>fileUpload </strong>component allows for uploading of a single file to the server.<br>Optionally, uploaded images can be displayed.</p>\n<p>The <strong>File Setting</strong> field on Pg3 in the Designer must have a value. <br>It is linked to a <strong>File Setting</strong> record which defines various aspects of the uploaded file, eg the path where files are stored, and image size.</p>\n<h3>Security Notes</h3>\n<p>It is best to store files outside the <strong>www </strong>folder.</p>\n<p>File names may only contain a defined set of characters:<br><strong>alpha-numeric (A-Z,a-z,0-9), space( ), underscore(_), period(.) and dash(-)</strong><br>The user will receive a message stating the allowed characters and be requested to rename the file before uploading it again.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><strong>Required:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Specify a File Setting on Pg3 in the Designer. Click the arrow next to the field to edit details.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Optional:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>For images only: add an Item Setting record with imagePreview=true to enable a preview of uploaded images.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>File Path Expression field Help</h3>\n<p>Specifies the server path where users\' uploaded files are stored.<br>Various "merge fields" are used to construct a path (also see the examples below).&nbsp;<br>For bound fields, use the combination of the primary key value and folder names wisely to ensure the path to each file can be found again using the primary key value.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>~$delim~users_root~$delim~</strong> =&gt; DIB::$USERSPATH (see /configs/Dib.php)</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~app_root~$delim~</strong> =&gt; DIB::$BASEPATH (see /configs/Dib.php)</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~file_name~$delim~</strong>&nbsp;=&gt; the name of the file being uploaded</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~id~$delim~</strong>&nbsp;=&gt; the primary key value of the current record</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~field_id~$delim~</strong>&nbsp;=&gt; the primary key value of the pef_field record that is referenced by the fileuploader component/item used</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~unique_id~$delim~</strong>&nbsp;=&gt; a random string generated by the PHP uniqid function</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~unique2_id~$delim~</strong>&nbsp;=&gt; a random string generated by the PHP uniqid function using more entropy</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~ext~$delim~</strong>&nbsp;=&gt; the file name extension</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~session_id~$delim~</strong> =&gt; the current user\'s PHP session_id. Rather use the following secure_id if possible.</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~secure_id~$delim~</strong> =&gt; a cryptographically strong random code generated when the user logs in and stored against their session.<br>See Authenticator::logUserIn() function. 16 Characters in length by default.<br>In PHP the code is obtained by: DIB::$USER[\'secure_id\']</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~user_xxx~$delim~</strong> =&gt; the contents of the xxx field stored in the current user\'s PHP session.&nbsp;<br>By default the following fields in pef_login are specified in Authenticator.php:&nbsp;\n<div>\n<div>id, username, perm_group, admin_user, email, test_user, first_name, last_name, default_url, pef_security_policy_id, login_expiry, login_group_expiry, language, larger_font, dib_code, dib_username<br>Overide in&nbsp;/configs/DibUserParams.php -&gt; getUserParams().</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~id;<em>xxx</em>~$delim~</strong>&nbsp;=&gt; (where <em>xxx </em>is an integer, eg 100) specifies the modulus of the primary key value of the current record and xxx. <br>This ensures for eg that a certain folder will have only <em>xxx</em> files in before creating a new folder.</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~sql_expr;<em>xxx</em>~$delim~</strong>&nbsp;=&gt;where <em>xxx </em>is a valid field in the current table, or SQL expression. <br>Eg DATE_FORMAT(date_fld, \'%Y%m\'). <br>A SQL statement of the following form is created using the field or SQL expression: <br>SELECT&nbsp;<em>xxx </em>FROM current_table_name WHERE <em>Primarykey_Criteria</em>. <br><em>Primarykey_Criteria </em>will limit records returned to the current record. <br>If &nbsp;no record or value is returned then an empty string is returned. <br>Eg. the expression&nbsp;DATE_FORMAT(Now(), \'%Y%m\') can be used to ensure a new folder (eg 201512) &nbsp;is created every month,<br>while&nbsp;DATE_FORMAT(date_fld, \'%Y%m%d\')&nbsp;can cause a folder for every day based on the value stored in <em>date_fld</em>. <br>Note, a single file_path_expr can use&nbsp;~$delim~sql_expr;<em>xxx</em>~$delim~&nbsp;multiple times.</li>\n<li><strong>~$delim~sql;<em>xxx</em>~$delim~</strong>&nbsp;=&gt;where&nbsp;<em>xxx&nbsp;</em>is a SQL query that returns a single record and value.<br>Eg SELECT Max(^^CONCAT(id,\'_\',name)^^) AS A FROM table1. <br>Parameters are not available for critieria. <br>If no record or value is returned then an empty string is returned, otherwise the first value of the first record returned is used (other values and records are ignored). <br>Note, a single file_path_expr can use ~$delim~sql;<em>xxx</em>~$delim~&nbsp;multiple times.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>~$delim~users_root~$delim~/uploads/A~$delim~id;100~$delim~/A_~$delim~id~$delim~_~$delim~file_name~$delim~</li>\n<li>~$delim~users_root~$delim~/uploads/tmp/Xlsx_~$delim~session_id~$delim~.~$delim~ext~$delim~</li>\n<li>~$delim~users_root~$delim~/uploads/~$delim~sql;SELECT DATE_FORMAT(Now(), &amp;apos;%Y%m&amp;apos;) AS A~$delim~/A_~$delim~id~$delim~_~$delim~file_name~$delim~</li>\n</ul>', '', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce53-dib'),
    (54, 279, 263, 60, 'none', 'General', 'References', NULL, '<p>Input components can be customized with various attributes.&nbsp;See the References-tab for more info.</p>\n<p>On forms and grids that are based on tables, the components can be bound to fields in the underlying table.</p>\n<p>Pg2 in the Designer provides various fields for client- and server-side validation, and limiting values.</p>', '<p><strong>inputs:&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/input/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/input/overview</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input">https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/input</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.w3schools.com/tags/tag_input.asp">https://www.w3schools.com/tags/tag_input.asp</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>slider:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/slider/overview">https://material.angular.io/components/slider/overview</a></li>\n</ul>', '', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce54-dib'),
    (55, 279, 265, 80, 'none', 'General', 'References', NULL, '<p>These layout components are mostly used to position and size other components like input fields , buttons and other layout components, using the flex directives. However, they can be used anywhere, even inside grid columns.</p>\n<p>Note, normally cards and sections are essentially the same, except for their styling. Normally sections are used as sub-sections of cards, and cards are used on a more macro-level. It is important however to style tabs, cards and sections appropriately so that the look-and-feel "works" together, and with fields and buttons etc.</p>\n<p>These layout components are also often used as tabs.</p>', '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">card and section: https:</span><a href="http://material.angular.io/components/card/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> http://material.angular.io/components/card/overview</a></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">column:</span> <a href="https://material.angular.io/components/grid-list/overview#setting-the-number-of-columns" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/grid-list/overview#setting-the-number-of-columns</a></p>\n<p>row: <a href="https://material.angular.io/components/grid-list/overview#setting-the-row-height" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/grid-list/overview#setting-the-row-height</a></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">inputText:&nbsp;<a href="https://material.angular.io/components/input/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/input/overview</a></span></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">expansionPanel:&nbsp;</span><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/expansion/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/expansion/overview</a></p>\n<p>toolbar: <a href="https://material.angular.io/components/toolbar/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/toolbar/overview</a></p>', '', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce55-dib'),
    (56, 279, 264, 70, 'none', 'General', 'References', NULL, '<p>These components are commonly used to provide structure to an application, but can be used anywhere, even inside grids.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">accordion:&nbsp;</span><a href="https://material.angular.io/cdk/accordion/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/cdk/accordion/overview</a></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">tabs: </span><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/tabs/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/tabs/overview</a></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">tabStepper:</span><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/stepper/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">&nbsp;https://material.angular.io/components/stepper/overview</a></p>', '', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce56-dib'),
    (57, 279, 267, 100, 'none', 'General', 'References', NULL, '<p>Some odd but useful components :)</p>', '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">divider: </span><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/divider/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/divider/overview</a></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">progressBar:&nbsp;</span><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/progress-bar/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/progress-bar/overview</a></p>\n<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">progressSpinner:&nbsp;</span><a href="https://material.angular.io/components/progress-spinner/overview" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://material.angular.io/components/progress-spinner/overview</a></p>', '', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce57-dib'),
    (58, 279, 260, 20, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', 'References', '<p>Selects provide users with the ability to select a value from a dropdown list of items.</p>\n<p>The list can be hard-coded (selectEnum), but is mostly obtained from the server.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase uses selects to show the value of&nbsp;<em>foreign</em>-key fields.<br>A <em>foreign-key </em>field like <strong>client_id </strong>contains values that reference records in the <strong>client </strong>table.<br>When a dropdown is linked to a foreign-key field, Dropinbase constructs a dropdown list of values from the table being referenced. The table record\'s&nbsp;<strong>display_expression</strong> field defines what the display values look like. The list can be limited by applying a ~nav(dibexFilterDropdown, filter)~.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase attempts to configure a meaningful display value expression for each table, but you can alter it in the <strong>pef_table.display_expression</strong> field.<br>If a more complex display expression or custom list is desired, a SQL query or custom PHP class can be specified as data source for the list.<br><br></p>', '<p>The data-source for <strong>selectEnum</strong> is specified on Pg2 in the Designer in the <strong>Value List</strong>-field (see help (?-button) for this field for more info).</p>\n<p>The data-source for other dropdowns can be one of three options:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Select a foreign-key field in <strong>Field</strong>.\n<ol>\n<li>Even if this is a plain container, Dropinbase will obtain the list using the&nbsp;<strong>Display Expression</strong> of the parent table that the foreign-key field references.</li>\n<li>To edit this display expression, use the T-icon in the Designer next to the Field (note the T-icon only appears if the field is a recognized foreign-key within Dropinbase).</li>\n<li>If the container is based on a table, make sure to select a field only within the table (or parent tables) to prevent errors - use drag-and-drop from the Component-tree.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Select the name of a \'dropdown list\' query in the&nbsp;<strong>SQL</strong>-field. Requirements:\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Query Type</strong> must be \'dropdown list\'</li>\n<li>Specify a <strong>Primary Field</strong> (the value that will be stored)</li>\n<li>Specify a <strong>Display Field</strong> (the value the user sees).</li>\n<li>If the query must return distinct results, place the word \'DISTINCT\' in the SELECT-clause (leave this field blank otherwise).</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Specify a Crud Store Controller.\n<ol>\n<li>See the help linked to this field in the Designer (Pg3) - click the ?-button while in this field.</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Dropdown List Length</h3>\n<p>For the first two options, the max amount of items in the list can be configured by adding an Item Setting where&nbsp;<strong>name</strong>=<code>selectLimitMax </code>and <strong>value </strong>is an integer. Alternatively, a global limit can be set in the main Settings table (<strong>pef_setting</strong>), also using <strong>name</strong>=<code>selectLimitMax</code>. The limits are enforced in server-side code.</p>\n<h3>Add Extra Hardcoded Values</h3>\n<p>Note, hard-code values can be added to the top of lists defined by SQL statements, by using the <strong>Extra List Rows</strong> field.<br>The following will add two rows:</p>\n<p><code>-999;(none);-998;first</code></p>\n<p>The dropdown list will display "(none)" and "first" as the first two items in the list. If the user selects "(none)" then -999 is associated/stored/submitted, and if "first", then -998.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><span style="font-family: Arial;">Select, SelectEnum: <a href="https://material.angular.io/components/select/overview">https://material.angular.io/components/select/overview</a></span></p>\n<p>AutoComplete: <a href="https://material.angular.io/components/autocomplete/overview">https://material.angular.io/components/autocomplete/overview</a></p>', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce58-dib'),
    (60, 279, 268, 120, 'none', 'General', '', NULL, '<p>These are the common HTML h1 - h5 typography elements.</p>\n<p>Adjust .scss files to configure.</p>', '', '', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce60-dib'),
    (61, 284, 209, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', 'More Info', '<p><strong>*ngIf</strong> instantly removes HTML elements completely from the DOM whenever the condition tied to them evaluates to <em>truthy</em>/<em>falsy (see Configuration-tab)</em>.</p>\n<p>Even though items are removed from the DOM, item values are not removed from the JavaScript model.<br>This means that directives (like <strong>[hidden]</strong>) or functions (like <strong>getValue()</strong>) configured on other items that refer to removed items will still work, and removed items with aliases are still included in Client Data. This is also true for items on tabs.</p>\n<h3>Limitations</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>*ngIf</strong> is a built-in Angular \'*\'/structural directive which is limited by Angular to one only per element. In certain Dropinbase component templates&nbsp;<strong>*ngIf</strong> is used, which prevents a second <strong>*ngIf</strong>. To get around this you can use <strong>[hidden]</strong> which is often a good replacement, or wrap your item in a <strong>div </strong>or <strong>span </strong>and configure another structural directive there. <br><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Note, using&nbsp;<strong>*ngIf</strong> is preferred over <strong>[hidden]</strong> since collaboratively it saves memory and reduces processing (there are less items in the DOM).</span></li>\n<li>Angular activates the wrong content when <strong>*ngIf</strong> is on tabs, unless all those tabs with <strong>*ngIf</strong>\'s are the last tabs, and only one of them displays at a given time.<br>Use <strong>[hidden]</strong> as an alternative.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Add <strong>*ngIf="xxx"</strong> to an element\'s attributes where <strong>xxx</strong> is a conditional expression in TypeScript that evaluates to <em>truthy</em>/<em>falsy</em>.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<p><code>*ngIf="hello World"</code> - this expression is <em>truthy</em>.</p>\n<p><code>*ngIf="0"</code> - this expression is <em>falsy</em>. Also<strong> </strong>\'\' (empty string),&nbsp;<em>null </em>and <em>undefined</em>.</p>\n<p><code>*ngIf="getValue(\'selectEnum\') != \'A\'"</code></p>\n<p><code>*ngIf="!!getValue(\'datepicker\') || resolve(\'value_myContainer_age\') &gt; 2"</code></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><a href="https://blog.angular-university.io/angular-ngif/">https://blog.angular-university.io/angular-ngif/</a></p>\n<p><a href="https://angular.io/guide/built-in-directives#adding-or-removing-an-element-with-ngif">https://angular.io/guide/built-in-directives#adding-or-removing-an-element-with-ngif</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce61-dib'),
    (62, 284, 295, 20, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p><strong>[hidden] </strong>instantly hides HTML elements whenever the condition tied to them evaluates to&nbsp;<em>truthy</em>/<em>falsy (see Configuration-tab)</em>.</p>\n<p>Unlike <strong>*ngIf</strong>, elements are not removed from the DOM, but instead&nbsp;<strong><span class="webkit-css-property" aria-label="CSS property name: display">display</span><span class="styles-name-value-separator">: </span><span class="value" aria-label="CSS property value: none!important">none!important</span><span class="styles-semicolon">;</span></strong> is applied to their CSS.</p>\n<p>Note, using <strong>*ngIf</strong> is preferred over <strong>[hidden]</strong> since collaboratively it saves memory and reduces processing (there are less items in the DOM).</p>', '<p>Add <strong>[hidden]="xxx"</strong> to an element\'s attributes where <strong>xxx</strong> is a conditional expression in TypeScript that evaluates to <em>truthy</em>/<em>falsy</em>.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<p><code>[hidden]="hello World"</code> - this expression is <em>truthy</em>.</p>\n<p><code>[hidden]="0"</code> - this expression is <em>falsy</em>. Also<strong> </strong>\'\' (empty string),&nbsp;<em>null </em>and <em>undefined</em>.</p>\n<p><code>[hidden]="getValue(\'selectEnum\') != \'A\'"</code></p>\n<p><code>[hidden]="!!getValue(\'datepicker\') || resolve(\'value_myContainer_age\') &gt; 2"</code></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce62-dib'),
    (63, 284, 296, 30, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p><strong>[dibDisabled]&nbsp;</strong>instantly disables HTML elements whenever the condition tied to them evaluates to&nbsp;<em>truthy</em>/<em>falsy (see Configuration-tab)</em>.</p>\n<p>The following is applied to the CSS of the elements:&nbsp;</p>\n<ul class="tree-outline" role="tree">\n<li role="treeitem"><span class="webkit-css-property" aria-label="CSS property name: pointer-events">pointer-events</span><span class="styles-name-value-separator">: </span><span class="value" aria-label="CSS property value: none">none</span><span class="styles-semicolon">;</span></li>\n<li role="treeitem"><span class="webkit-css-property" aria-label="CSS property name: opacity">opacity</span><span class="styles-name-value-separator">: </span><span class="value" aria-label="CSS property value: .6">.6</span><span class="styles-semicolon">;</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Add <strong>[dibDisabled]="xxx"</strong> to an element\'s attributes where <strong>xxx</strong> is a conditional expression in TypeScript that evaluates to <em>truthy</em>/<em>falsy</em>.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<p><code>[dibDisabled]="hello World"</code> - this expression is <em>truthy</em>.</p>\n<p><code>[dibDisabled]="0"</code> - this expression is <em>falsy</em>. Also<strong> </strong>\'\' (empty string),&nbsp;<em>null </em>and <em>undefined</em>.</p>\n<p><code>[dibDisabled]="getValue(\'selectEnum\') != \'A\'"</code></p>\n<p><code>[dibDisabled]="!!getValue(\'datepicker\') || resolve(\'value_myContainer_age\') &gt; 2"</code></p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce63-dib'),
    (64, 284, 297, 40, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', 'References', '<p>[ngStyle] is mainly used to apply CSS styling to elements where the style to be applied is variable and the condition (if any) is relatively simple.<br>Conditions are implemented with TypeScript inside the style object.</p>\n<p>The use of [ngClass] is preferred where possible for more maintainable code.</p>', '<p>Add&nbsp;<strong>[ngStyle]="xxx"</strong>&nbsp;to an element\'s attributes where&nbsp;<strong>xxx</strong> is a style object.</p>\n<p>Examples:</p>\n<p><code>[ngStyle]="{\'color\': \'blue\', \'font-weight\': 600}"</code></p>\n<p><code>[ngStyle]="{\'color\':\'black\', \'background-color\': getValue(\'inputColor\')}"</code> - get a value from a user-input field.</p>\n<p><code>[ngStyle]="{\'background-color\': getValue(\'selectEnum\') == \'A\' ? \'green\' : (getValue(\'selectEnum\') == \'B\' ? \'yellow\' : \'red\')}"</code> - apply a condition.</p>\n<p><code>[ngStyle]="{\'background-color\': row.color}"</code> - get a value from a grid colom in the same row.</p>\n<p><code>[ngStyle]="{\'background-color\': row.position == \'Employee\' ? \'yellow\' : (row.position == \'Manager\' ? \'red\' : \'transparent\')}"</code> - apply a condition to a grid colom\'s style, based on a column value.</p>', '<p><a href="https://angular.io/api/common/NgStyle">https://angular.io/api/common/NgStyle</a></p>\n<p><a href="https://blog.angular-university.io/angular-ngclass-ngstyle/">https://blog.angular-university.io/angular-ngclass-ngstyle/</a></p>\n<p><a href="https://angular.io/guide/built-in-directives#setting-inline-styles-with-ngstyle">https://angular.io/guide/built-in-directives#setting-inline-styles-with-ngstyle</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce64-dib'),
    (65, 279, 299, 100, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', 'More Info', '<p>The calendar plots events based on various fields returned from a data source.</p>\n<p>Either an existing form\'s generated CRUD class (example below) or a custom controller can be used as the data source (see ~nav(dibexActionReloadCalendar)~).</p>\n<p>For updating/adding/deleting records, clicking an event will open a configured form container.</p>\n<p>Records can also be created and moved visually on the component itself.</p>', '<p>Set the \'Open Container in Port\' (pef_port_id) field to the container/port to activate for editing events (optional).</p>\n<p>Item Settings (with default values):</p>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>crudUrl</strong>&nbsp;(required setting)</li>\n<li><strong>crudContainerName </strong>(required setting)</li>\n<li><strong>primaryIds</strong> (\'id\')</li>\n<li><strong>titleColumnName</strong> (\'title\')</li>\n<li><strong>startDateColumnName </strong>(\'start_date\')</li>\n<li><strong>endDateColumnName</strong> (\'end_date\')</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Notes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>When crudUrl is set to \'/peff/Crud\' then crudContainerName identifies the container that is configured to act as data-source. This container should have the relevant CRUD permissions for users, and can have any model: Sql/Table/Custom.</li>\n<li>The \'ColumnName\' settings above identify the names of relevant columns in the source data.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>Additional Fields that can be returned by the data-source (with default values):</p>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>color</strong> (\'navy\')</li>\n<li><strong>allDay</strong> (true)</li>\n<li><strong>cssClass</strong> (null)</li>\n<li><strong>resizableLeft</strong> (true)</li>\n<li><strong>resizableRight </strong>(true)</li>\n<li><strong>draggable</strong> (true)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>', '<p>The following project was extended:</p>\n<p><a href="https://mattlewis92.github.io/angular-calendar/#/kitchen-sink">https://mattlewis92.github.io/angular-calendar/#/kitchen-sink</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce65-dib'),
    (66, 276, 269, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Activates a specified tab within a container. This function can target a tab either by its alias or by its index.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string): The name of the container holding the tabs. If not specified, the function will use the current container by default.</li>\n<li><strong>itemAlias</strong> (string): The name of the tab to activate if not using <code>tabIndex</code>. Alternatively, it can be the name of the parent tab-component if using <code>tabIndex</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>tabIndex</strong> (int): The index of the tab to activate, starting at 1.</li>\n<li>\n<div>\n<div><strong>portItemAlias </strong>(string): Used if container is open multiple times on different ports, to distinguish between them</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Either <code>itemAlias</code> or <code>tabIndex</code> must be provided.</li>\n<li>Known issue: If you use <code>*ngIf</code> to conditionally show or hide tabs, <code>activateTab</code> might activate the wrong tab. <br>Workaround: move tabs that use <code>*ngIf</code> to the end of the tabs list to avoid this issue.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce66-dib'),
    (67, 276, 270, 20, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Appends the value provided to the specified items\' model. This function can handle multiple item name-value pairs, allowing you to reference items within the current container or across different containers.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>itemName=value</strong> (repeated): Pairs of item names and their corresponding values. The item name can be either the name of an item in the current container or in the format <code>containerName.itemName</code> to reference an item in another container.</li>\n</ul>\n<div>\n<div><strong>Example: </strong></div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.append-value?myItem=123&amp;myContainer.myItem2=hello</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce67-dib'),
    (68, 276, 272, 30, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Executes the browser\'s back button functionality, navigating the user to the previous page in their browsing history.</p>\n<div>\n<div><strong>Example:&nbsp;</strong></div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.back</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce68-dib'),
    (69, 276, 271, 50, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Deletes the custom variables created with the <code>set-custom</code> and <code>set-custom-global</code> actions.&nbsp;<br>Note, if the user refreshes the browser, it will have the same effect since these are JavaScript variables.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string, optional): The name of the container. <br>If specified, only this container\'s values will be deleted. If set to \'ALL\', the values of all containers will be cleared.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.clear-custom?containerName=myContainer</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>See the examples for <code>set-custom</code> and <code>set-custom-global</code> for more info.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce69-dib'),
    (70, 276, 273, 60, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Closes a popup \'dialog\' style container.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string, optional): The name of the container. If not specified, the current dialog is closed.</li>\n<li><strong>portItemAlias</strong> (string, optional): Used if the container is open multiple times on different ports, to distinguish between them.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.close-dialog?containerName=myDialog</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce70-dib'),
    (71, 276, 274, 70, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Closes a popup \'window\' style container.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string, optional): The name of the container. If not specified, the current window container is closed.</li>\n<li><strong>portItemAlias</strong> (string, optional): Used if the container is open multiple times on different ports, to distinguish between them.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.close-window?containerName=myWindowContainer</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce71-dib'),
    (73, 276, 275, 90, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Enables setting the style, class, and disabled/visible attributes of items.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>value</strong> (object): An object containing name-value pairs of information to be sent.</li>\n<li><strong>itemName=object</strong> (repeated): Pairs of item names and their corresponding objects. Items must be in the current container.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Setting the style or class overwrites all existing styles or classes on the element.</li>\n<li>When sending as a client-side action, objects must be URL encoded\n<ul>\n<li>eg<code>"</code> to <code>%22</code>, <code>{</code> to <code>%7B</code>, <code>}</code> to <code>%7D</code>, <code>[</code> to <code>%5B</code>, <code>]</code> to <code>%5D</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.item-handler?btnShortCard={"visible":false}&amp;cardGrid={"style":{"height":"500px", "background":"blue"}}\n<ul>\n<li><strong>encoded as:</strong> shared.action.item-handler?btnShortCard=%7B%22visible%22:false%7D&amp;cardGrid=%7B%22style%22:%7B%22height%22:%22500px%22,%22background%22:%22bluepx%22%7D%7D</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n</div>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce73-dib'),
    (74, 276, 277, 100, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Redirects the browser to <code>/logout</code>, logging the user out of the application.</p>\n<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>It is advised to use the <code>shared.action.cache-action</code> action to pre-load the logout action, since if the user\'s session expires and they then click a logout button to go to the login page, they get a permission error.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.logout</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce74-dib'),
    (75, 276, 278, 110, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Displays a message to the user. The message can be a dialog or a toast-style notification with varying types and display durations.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>messageText</strong> (string): The (HTML) message to display.</li>\n<li><strong>messageType</strong> (string): The type of message. Options are <code>dialog</code>, <code>success</code>, <code>notice</code>, or <code>warning</code>. The latter three are \'toast\' style messages in different colors. Default is <code>dialog</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>messageTitle</strong> (string): The title of the message. Default is <code>Notice</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>messageDelay</strong> (string): The time in milliseconds to display a toast style message. Note, for <code>dialog</code>, the user must click \'OK\' to close it.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>If invoked by PHP, the <code>DIB::$ALLOWEDHTML</code> value (configure in /configs/Dib.php)&nbsp; controls how <strong>messageText </strong>is sanitized. To avoid sanitization, set <code>DIB::$ALLOWEDHTML</code> to null in your code.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.message?messageText=Hello &lt;b&gt;world!&lt;/b&gt;&amp;messageType=notice&amp;messageDelay=4000&amp;messageTitle=Greetings</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce75-dib'),
    (76, 276, 279, 120, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Loads or opens the specified container.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string): The name of the container.</li>\n<li><strong>portAlias</strong> (string): The alias of the port to activate. Default is <code>main</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>queryString</strong> (string): Any URL query parameters. It should be URL encoded if using <code>dibDesigner</code> submitUrl. Using an object is recommended if returning with PHP Action.</li>\n<li><strong>changeUrl</strong> (string): If present and not \'false\', then the URL will not be changed. This overrides the port setting field, <code>change_url</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A client-side action to open a container is often better facilitated by the <strong>Open Container in Port</strong> (pef_port_id) field.</li>\n<li>Another alternative is to use the <strong>open-url</strong> action.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.open-container?containerName=myContainer&amp;changeUrl=false&amp;portAlias=myAlias&amp;queryString=URLENCODEDQUERYSTRING</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce76-dib'),
    (77, 276, 280, 130, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Loads the specified URL.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>url</strong> (string): Either a DIB URL (e.g., <code>/nav/myForm/alias?record=first</code>) or an external site (e.g., <code>https://example.com</code>). When using a client-side action and query-parameters are present in the URL, the URL must be url-encoded (see examples below). <code>ClientFunctions::addAction</code> in PHP will handle this server-side.</li>\n<li><strong>target</strong> (string): If set to \'blank\', a new browser tab/window is used.</li>\n<li><strong>clientData</strong> (string): If present and not \'false\', <code>clientData</code> is included as query parameters.</li>\n<li><strong>changeUrl</strong> (string): If present and not \'false\', then the URL will not be changed.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A client-side action to open a container is often better facilitated by the <strong>Open Container in Port</strong> (pef_port_id) field.</li>\n<li>Another alternative is the <strong>open-container</strong> action.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Examples:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.open-url?url=/nav/myForm/alias</li>\n<li>with query parameters (url-encode):\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.open-url?url=%2Fnav%2FmyForm%2Falias%3Frecord%3Dfirst%26aaa%3D123%20</li>\n<li>Note, if sending the action from the server, the PHP framework will automatically url-encode the parameters.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce77-dib'),
    (78, 276, 281, 140, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Presents a Yes/Cancel prompt to the user. More buttons can be added and buttons are configurable. Each button can execute a different function. If no action is specified for the Cancel button, it will simply close the popup.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>messageButtons</strong> (object/array): An object or array defining the two popup buttons.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Example:\n<div class="dark bg-gray-950 rounded-md border-[0.5px] border-token-border-medium">\n<div class="overflow-y-auto p-4 text-left undefined" dir="ltr"><code class="!whitespace-pre hljs language-css"><span class="hljs-selector-attr">[  {<span class="hljs-string">\'buttonText\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'Yes\'</span>, <span class="hljs-string">\'actionType\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'submitUrl\'</span>, <span class="hljs-string">\'action\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'/dropins/dibExamples/Events/helloWorld\'</span>},  {<span class="hljs-string">\'buttonText\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'Cancel\'</span>}]</span>\n</code></div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li>Where <code>actionType</code> can be <code>submitUrl</code>, <code>action</code>, or <code>itemAlias</code>.</li>\n<li>And <code>action</code> is related to <code>actionType</code>:\n<ul>\n<li>For <code>submitUrl</code>: A URI, e.g., <code>/dropins/test/Msg/hello?containerName=aaa</code> or <code>shared.action.set-value?myItem=123</code>.\n<ul>\n<li>Optionally add \';\' followed by response type, e.g., <code>/dropins/test/Msg/hello?containerName=aaa;redirect</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>For <code>action</code>: An array/object, e.g.,\n<div class="dark bg-gray-950 rounded-md border-[0.5px] border-token-border-medium">\n<div class="overflow-y-auto p-4 text-left undefined" dir="ltr"><code class="!whitespace-pre hljs language-arduino">[ <span class="hljs-string">\'submitUrl\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'shared.action.set-value\'</span>,\n  <span class="hljs-string">\'params\'</span>: [<span class="hljs-string">\'first_name\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'Tom\']</span>,\n  <span class="hljs-string">\'responseType\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'actions\'</span> ]</code></div>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li><code>params</code> and <code>responseType</code> are optional and default to <code>[]</code> and <code>actions</code> respectively.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>For <code>itemAlias</code>: The alias of another item (normally an invisible button) whose click event will be fired, e.g., <code>btnHelloWorld</code>.\n<ul>\n<li>Optionally add \';\' followed by trigger, e.g., <code>downloadFile;redirect</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>messageText</strong> (string): The (HTML) message to display.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>messageTitle</strong> (string): The title of the message. Default is \'Notice\'.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>If invoked by PHP, the <code>DIB::$ALLOWEDHTML</code> value controls how <strong>messageText </strong>is sanitized. To avoid sanitization, set&nbsp;<code>DIB::$ALLOWEDHTML</code> to null in your code.</li>\n<li>For client-side events, the <code>messageText</code> and <code>messageTitle</code> strings, and the <code>messageButtons</code> object must be URL-encoded. &nbsp;\n<div>\n<div><code>ClientFunctions::addAction</code> in PHP will handle this server-side for you.</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Examples:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The following needs to url-encoded if activated client-side:\n<ul>\n<li><code>shared.action.popup?messageTitle=Please Confirm&amp;messageText=Delete the Record&amp;messageButtons={"buttons":[{"buttonText":"OK","actionType":"itemAlias","action":"btnDoSomething"}]}</code></li>\n<li>as follows:</li>\n<li><code>shared.action.popup?messageTitle=Please%20Confirm&amp;messageText=Delete%20the%20Record&amp;messageButtons=%7B%22buttons%22%3A%5B%7B%22buttonText%22%3A%22Yes%22%2C%22actionType%22%3A%22itemAlias%22%2C%22action%22%3A%22btnDoSomething%22%7D%5D%7D</code></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce78-dib'),
    (79, 276, 282, 150, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Presents a question with an input box for the user to provide an answer. A specified action is executed upon submission and optionally another action upon cancellation.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>text</strong> (string): The (HTML) message to display.</li>\n<li><strong>title</strong> (string): The title of the message. Default is \'Notice\'.</li>\n<li><strong>forceInput</strong> (boolean): Determines whether the user is required to provide a value.</li>\n<li><strong>confirm</strong> (object): Defines the action to be executed on the Confirm button.\n<ul>\n<li>Example: <code>{\'actionType\': \'submitUrl\', \'action\': \'shared.action.logout\'}</code></li>\n<li>Where <code>actionType</code> can be <code>submitUrl</code>, <code>action</code>, or <code>itemAlias</code>.</li>\n<li>And <code>action</code> is related to <code>actionType</code>:\n<ul>\n<li>For <code>submitUrl</code>: A URI, e.g., <code>/dropins/test/Msg/hello?containerName=aaa</code> or <code>shared.action.set-value?myItem=123</code>.\n<ul>\n<li>Optionally add \';\' followed by response type or queue polling time, e.g., <code>/dropins/test/Msg/hello?containerName=aaa;redirect</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>For <code>action</code>: An array, e.g.,\n<div class="dark bg-gray-950 rounded-md border-[0.5px] border-token-border-medium">\n<div class="overflow-y-auto p-4 text-left undefined" dir="ltr"><code class="!whitespace-pre hljs language-arduino"><span class="hljs-string">[\'submitUrl\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'shared.action.set-value\'</span>,\n  <span class="hljs-string">\'params\'</span>: [<span class="hljs-string">\'first_name\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'Tom\']</span>,\n  <span class="hljs-string">\'responseType\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'actions\']</span></code></div>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li><code>params</code> and <code>responseType</code> are optional and default to <code>[]</code> and \'actions\' respectively.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>For <code>itemAlias</code>: The alias of another item (normally an invisible button) whose click event will be fired, e.g., <code>btnHelloWorld</code>.\n<ul>\n<li>Optionally add \';\' followed by trigger, e.g., <code>downloadFile;redirect</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>cancel</strong> (object): Defines the action to be executed on the Cancel button (same definition as <code>confirm</code>).</li>\n<li><strong>regex</strong> (string): If not empty, the user input must match the regular expression before the Confirm button can be clicked.</li>\n<li><strong>errorMsg</strong> (string): The error message to be displayed when validation fails.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<p>Upon submission, the specified URL is called and the user\'s answer is included in Client Data under \'prompt\'.&nbsp;<br>It will not be included again in any other requests\' Client Data.</p>\n<p>A common pattern for server-side actions that return a prompt, is to call the same server-side function again with the answer.<br>The presence of the \'prompt\' index indicates that the user is submitting an answer, and can be catched as follows:</p>\n<pre>if (array_key_exists(\'prompt\', $clientData)) {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;$answer = $clientData[\'prompt\'];<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; // handle answer and return a message and/or actions to the user<br><br>} else {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;// code that returns the prompt<br>}<br><br></pre>\n<ul>\n<li>If invoked by PHP, the <code>DIB::$ALLOWEDHTML</code> value controls how <strong>text </strong>is sanitized. To avoid sanitization, set&nbsp;<code>DIB::$ALLOWEDHTML</code> to null in your code.</li>\n<li>For client-side events, objects and other parameter values must be URL-encoded (see example below)</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>client-side parameter values must be url-encoded:\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.prompt?text=What%20is%202%20%2B%203%3F&amp;title=Maths%20Test&amp;confirm=%7B%22actionType%22%3A%22submitUrl%22%2C%22action%22%3A%22%2Fdropins%2FdibExamples%2FAction%2Fprompt%2FdibexActionPrompt%2Fie354-dib%22%7D&amp;regex=%5E%5B0-9%5D%2B%24</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce79-dib'),
    (81, 276, 283, 170, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Reloads the browser window or tab.</p>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.reload</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce81-dib'),
    (82, 276, 285, 180, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Reloads the data or content of the specified container.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string): The name of the container to reload (e.g., <code>self</code>, <code>parent</code>, <code>containerName</code>).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.reload-container?containerName=myContainer</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce82-dib'),
    (83, 276, 286, 190, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Reloads the environment variables from the server.</p>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.reload-env</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce83-dib'),
    (84, 276, 284, 200, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Repaints the browser window contents by triggering a \'resize\' event internally.</p>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.repaint</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce84-dib'),
    (85, 276, 287, 210, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Executes an event linked to a specified item, typically of <code>itemAlias</code> type of action. It implements the same structure as&nbsp;<code>popup</code> and <code>prompt</code> actions for consistency.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>actionType</strong> (string): The type of action. Options are <code>itemAlias</code>, <code>submitUrl</code>, or <code>action</code>.</li>\n<li><strong>action</strong> (mixed): Related to the <code>actionType</code>:\n<ul>\n<li>For <code>itemAlias</code>: The alias of another item (normally an invisible button) whose click event will be fired, e.g., <code>btnHelloWorld</code>. Optionally add \';\' followed by a trigger, e.g., <code>downloadFile;redirect</code>.</li>\n<li>For <code>submitUrl</code>: A URI, e.g., <code>/dropins/test/Msg/hello?containerName=aaa</code> or <code>shared.action.set-value?myItem=123</code>. Optionally add \';\' followed by a response type or queue polling time, e.g., <code>/dropins/test/Msg/hello?containerName=aaa;redirect</code>.</li>\n<li>For <code>action</code>: An object, e.g.,\n<div class="dark bg-gray-950 rounded-md border-[0.5px] border-token-border-medium">\n<div class="overflow-y-auto p-4 text-left undefined" dir="ltr"><code class="!whitespace-pre hljs language-arduino">[&nbsp; <span class="hljs-string">\'submitUrl\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'shared.action.set-value\'</span>,\n  <span class="hljs-string">\'params\'</span>: [<span class="hljs-string">\'first_name\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'Tom\']</span>,\n  <span class="hljs-string">\'responseType\'</span>: <span class="hljs-string">\'actions\'</span> ]</code></div>\n</div>\n<code>params</code> and <code>responseType</code> are optional and default to <code>[]</code> and <code>actions</code> respectively.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>actionData</strong> (object, only for <code>itemAlias</code> actionType): Any values to be passed to the server function (to the <code>$actionData</code> parameter).</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>For client-side actions, <code>submitUrl</code> must be URL-encoded.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><code>shared.action.run?actionType=itemAlias&amp;action=myItem&amp;trigger=change&nbsp;&nbsp;</code></li>\n<li>\n<div>\n<div>(submitUrl must be url-encoded), eg</div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li><code>shared.action.run?actionType=submitUrl&amp;action=/dropins/myDropin/Contr/myFunc;change</code></li>\n<li>url-encoded to:</li>\n<li><code>shared.action.run?actionType=submitUrl&amp;action=%2Fdropins%2FmyDropin%2FContr%2FmyFunc%3Bchange</code></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce85-dib'),
    (86, 276, 288, 220, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Selects rows in a grid where the specified column is equal to the given value. <br>This function could be useful for interface automation testing.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string): The name of the grid container.</li>\n<li><strong>column</strong> (string): The column in which to search for the specified value.</li>\n<li><strong>value</strong> (string): The value to search for in the specified column.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.select-row?containerName=myContainer&amp;column=status&amp;value=done</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce86-dib'),
    (87, 276, 294, 230, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Creates or sets the value of a container-bound custom JavaScript variable. Values are only available as long as this container is in the view. Note that refreshing the browser clears these JavaScript values.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string, optional): The name of the container. If not specified, the current container (<code>self</code>) applies. Can be <code>self</code>, <code>parent</code>, or a specific container name.</li>\n<li><strong>variableName=value</strong> (repeated): Pairs of variable names and their corresponding values.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The value is accessible in <code>clientData</code> submitted to the server, and with <code>resolve(\'custom_CONTAINERNAME_xxx\')</code> or <code>@{custom_CONTAINERNAME_xxx}</code>.</li>\n<li>More info: See ~nav(dibexActionClearCustom)~, and the last tab on ~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices)~</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.set-custom?myVar=123&amp;myVar2=hello world</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce87-dib'),
    (88, 276, 289, 240, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Sets the dropdown list values of a <code>selectEnum</code> component.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>itemName=list</strong> (repeated): Pairs of item names and their corresponding lists of values. <code>itemName</code> is either the name of the item in the current container or <code>containerName.itemName</code> to reference an item in another container. The list is a comma-separated list of values.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.set-enum-list?mySelectEnum=Option1,Option2,Option3&amp;anotherContainer.anotherSelectEnum=ValueA,ValueB,ValueC</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce88-dib'),
    (90, 276, 290, 260, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Sets the inner HTML of components like htmlSettable and htmlSettableUnsfafe, that implement <code>[innerHtml]="getHtml(\'~name~\')"</code>.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>itemName=html</strong> (repeated): Pairs of item names and their corresponding HTML content. <code>itemName</code> is either the name of the item in the current container or <code>containerName.itemName</code> to reference an item in another container.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.set-html?myContainer.myItem=&lt;b&gt;hello%20world&lt;/b&gt;&amp;myForm.status=&lt;i&gt;done&lt;/i&gt;</li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style="color: #e03e2d;"><strong>IMPORTANT:</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The <strong>htmlSettable </strong>component will automatically sanitize potentially unsafe HTML, while the <strong>htmlSettableUnsafe </strong>component uses the Angular <code>safeHtml</code>&nbsp;pipe to allow any HTML. Use both these components with care, ensuring HTML that contains user data is sanitized&nbsp;<span style="text-decoration: underline;">server-side</span> using the code below, before setting their values with the <strong>set-html</strong> action:</li>\n<li>\n<div>\n<div><code>$safeHtml = htmlspecialchars($myHtmlContainingUserInputOrData, ENT_QUOTES ~$DelimDb~ ENT_HTML5, \'UTF-8\', FALSE);</code></div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><span style="color: #e03e2d; text-decoration: underline;">Bottom Line:</span></span> Use <strong>htmlSettableUnsafe </strong>(which Angular will not sanitize) instead of htmlSettable for complex HTML that does not contain any text that originates from a user. But if any user data is being incorporated in complex HTML, always use PHP to sanitize the user data as well.</li>\n<li>HTML can be sanitized using<code> DibApp::sanitizeHtml($myHtml)</code> which is based on the <code>DIB::$ALLOWEDHTML</code> configuration in <strong>/configs/Dib.php</strong>.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce90-dib'),
    (91, 276, 291, 270, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Sets the theme and activates or deactivates the \'darkness\' theme for a specified container.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string): The name of the container.</li>\n<li><strong>theme</strong> (string): The name of the theme to activate.</li>\n<li><strong>darkness</strong> (string): If set to \'true\', the darkness theme is activated. If set to any other value, the darkness theme is deactivated.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.set-theme?containerName=myContainer&amp;theme=myTheme&amp;darkness=true</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce91-dib'),
    (92, 276, 292, 280, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Activates or deactivates the \'darkness\' theme for a specified container.<br><strong>Note:</strong> use the <code>set-theme</code> action for other named themes.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string): The name of the container.</li>\n<li><strong>darkness</strong> (string): If set to \'true\', the darkness theme is activated. If set to any other value, the darkness theme is deactivated.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.set-theme?containerName=myContainer&amp;darkness=true</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce92-dib'),
    (93, 276, 293, 300, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Executes a URL request.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>submitUrl</strong> (string): The URL request to execute.</li>\n<li><strong>containerName</strong> (string): The name of the container to send with the request.</li>\n<li><strong>responseType</strong> (string): The event response type to use. Options include <code>actions</code>, <code>redirect</code>, <code>new tab</code>, <code>2000</code>, etc. Default is <code>actions</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.submit-url?containerName=myContainer&amp;responseType=actions&amp;submitUrl=/dropins/myDropin/Contr/myFunc</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce93-dib'),
    (97, 276, 300, 40, 'none', 'General', NULL, NULL, '<p>Sets the language for the translation service to the specified language code.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>lang</strong> (string): The code for the desired language, for example, <code>en-US</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.change-language</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce97-dib'),
    (98, 276, 301, 75, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Emits an event to a listener object in the browser, often used within an iframe\'s JavaScript.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>value</strong> (object): An object containing name-value pairs of information to be sent.</li>\n<li><strong>emitName</strong> (string, optional): The name the listener is attached to (defaults to \'eventAction\').</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.emit-event?emitName=myEvent&amp;action=explodeImage&amp;value=@{value_self_explodeRadius}</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>', '<p>Add the following to the iframe\'s JavaScript:</p>\n<pre>  &nbsp; if (!!parent.DIB.emitEventSubscription) {<br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; parent.DIB.emitEventSubscription.unsubscribe();<br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; parent.DIB.emitEventSubscription = null;  <br>&nbsp; &nbsp; }\n\n&nbsp; &nbsp; // Note, \'<strong>myEvent</strong>\' below should equal the <strong>emitName </strong>parameter value.<br>  &nbsp; parent.DIB.emitEventSubscription = parent.eventService.on(\'myEvent\').subscribe( (params) =&gt; {    <br><br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; if(params.action == \'xxx\') {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// your code accessing other params. values here ...&nbsp;<br><br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; } else if(params.action == \'yyy\') {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// your code accessing other params. values here ...&nbsp;<br><br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; });</pre>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce98-dib'),
    (99, 276, 302, 165, 'none', 'General', NULL, NULL, '<p>Sets the polling interval and count for an active queue, or stops it. <br>This is mostly used by users to restart a queue that has stopped due to a very long-running server-side script. <br>When the queue restarts, any pending actions (up to a maximum of 50) are retrieved.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>id</strong> (int): The queue identifier.</li>\n<li><strong>pollCount</strong> (int): The number of polling requests that may return empty results before polling is terminated.</li>\n<li><strong>intervalMs</strong> (int or string): Milliseconds to wait between polling requests, or the word \'stop\' to stop polling.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.refresh-queue?id=1234567&amp;pollCount=10&amp;intervalMs=1500</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce99-dib'),
    (100, 276, 303, 175, 'none', 'General', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce100-dib'),
    (101, 285, 305, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Developers can create custom and reusable Angular components and make them available for use in Dropinbase containers.</p>\n<p>An Angular developer would know that applications in Angular are built using a component-based architecture, where components are the fundamental building blocks. These components can be nested within each other to create complex user interfaces. Note, a&nbsp;component in Dropinbase is not the same as an Angular component. Dropinbase components are mere HTML that may or may not wrap more complex Angular components.</p>\n<p>In this example we have a SQL grid and use a custom component for the Start Date field. The custom component code is stored in <strong>/dropins/dibExamples/ts/components/date-change/</strong>. It contains logic to make the field editable, set the background-color based on <strong>colorName</strong>-column values, and disable the field based on <strong>VIP</strong>-column values. The <strong>/dropins/dibExamples/General/startDateChange</strong> server-side function is called to handle updates.</p>\n<p>Dropinbase will automatically create compiled code in the <strong>/dropins/DROPIN/dibCode/_components</strong> folder if it does not exist already. Delete this file manually or via the normal Designer buttons when the design of a component changes.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p><strong>Required:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Item record\n<ul>\n<li>component = [reference to the \'component\' component]</li>\n<li>caption = [grid column or form field caption]</li>\n<li>name = start_date (ie same as data column in SQL. Only because the custom component\'s TypeScript refers to the column using&nbsp;\n<div>\n<div>this.data[this.itemName] to make it reusable in other containers.)</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Item Setting record\n<ul>\n<li>name = <strong>component</strong></li>\n<li>value = [name of the component in camelCase]</li>\n<li>dropin = [reference to the Module Dropin folder containing the custom component]</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Component files\n<ul>\n<li>Create /dropins/DROPIN/ts/components/COMPONENTNAME folder\n<ul>\n<li>COMPONENTNAME must be <span style="text-decoration: underline;">camelCase</span>, eg <strong>dateChange </strong>and not <strong>date-change</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Create the following files using <span style="text-decoration: underline;">lower-case</span> for COMPONENTNAME\n<ul>\n<li>COMPONENTNAME.component.html</li>\n<li>COMPONENTNAME.component.ts</li>\n<li>COMPONENTNAME.component.scss</li>\n<li>eg <strong>date-change.component.html</strong> etc.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Hidden button with event\n<ul>\n<li>Dropinbase must &apos;know&apos; which requests to allow against which container/item for which permgroups.</li>\n<li>To inform Dropinbase of the custom component&apos;s request, we create a hidden button linked to the same event (see buttonHidden in the design).</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>\n<p>If any directives like<strong> *ngIf </strong>or <strong>[dibDisabled]</strong> etc. must be applied to the component, add it to <strong>attributes2 </strong>on the item. Alternatively add these to the design of the custom component itself (as in the example).</p>\n<p>Dropinbase will automatically create compiled code in the <strong>/dropins/DROPIN/dibCode/_components</strong> folder if it does not exist already. Delete this file manually or via the normal Designer buttons when the design of a component changes.</p>\n<h2>Accessing Container Data</h2>\n<h3>In Grids</h3>\n<p>Adding&nbsp;<strong>[dibData]="row" </strong>to <strong>attributes3 </strong>of the item makes it possible to access the values of columns in the grid in the TypeScript using <strong>this.data</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code><strong>this.data[\'first_name\']</strong></code> - access value of first_name column in current grid.</li>\n<li><code><strong>this.data[this.itemName]</strong></code> - access value of current custom component column in grid.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>In Forms</h3>\n<p>Add [dibData]="model" to attributes3 of the item. Accessing values requires a bit more code than with grids:</p>\n<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><code><strong>this.data.modelItems.first_name.formControl.value</strong></code> - access value of first_name on current container.</li>\n<li><code><strong>this.data.$formGroup.value&nbsp;</strong></code> - access all form values.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Note, any other value can be sent to<strong> this.data</strong>, eg. <strong>[dibData]="getValue(\'myField\')"</strong>.</p>\n<p>To access Client Data in the component, use&nbsp; <strong>this.container.clientData </strong>with a reference to <strong>ContainerService</strong>. See the example for more info.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce101-dib'),
    (102, 286, 306, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Instead of reinventing charts and reports, Dropinbase provides the tools to easily integrate with 100\'s of 3d party providers.</p>\n<p>The configuration is basically the same for all of them. See the Configurations-tab for more info.</p>\n<p>This example showcases Plotly which <strong>offers over 40 chart types, 3D charts, statistical graphs, and SVG maps</strong> with tons of customizations.<br><strong>See:</strong> <a href="https://plotly.com/javascript/" target="blank_">https://plotly.com/javascript/</a></p>\n<div>\n<div>Note the report on ~nav(dibexOverview)~ is far more elaborate.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n</div>', '<p>Required:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Container Type</strong> = iframe</li>\n<li>Pg2 -&gt; <strong>Template </strong>= URI referencing an .html template file, <strong>eg /dibExamples/templates/dibexReportBasics.html</strong></li>\n<li>Pg2 -&gt; <strong>Valid Params</strong> specifying values to pass to the template, and Chart configurations (see below)</li>\n<li>The template file must contain the necessary HTML and JavaScript (see examples)</li>\n<li>The default examples make use of a call to <strong>/dropins/dibAdmin/DData/getData</strong> to receive the data for the queries listed in the <strong>dibSqlPerms Valid Params</strong>. To enable permissions for this request, add a hidden button to the iframe container where <strong>Submit Url</strong> contains&nbsp;<strong>/dropins/dibAdmin/DData/getData</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Template File</h3>\n<p>The easiest way to build a template file is to base it on an existing example file.</p>\n<p>The iframe container type parses the template file with the Eleutheria templating engine, which gives the opportunity to dynamically build parts of it before its contents are sent to the browser. Eleutheria can loop through nested records filtered by values from Client Data, process conditional statements, and safely include values from records and build any HTML / JavaScript / CSS in the process. In our example we use it to merely lookup the Client\'s name.</p>\n<p>The template file must load the JavaScript libraries of the third party charting libraries being used:</p>\n<p>Eg for Plotly:</p>\n<pre>&lt;script type="text/javascript" src="/files/dropins/setCharts/dibPlotly/js/plotly-2.16.1.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\n<div>Also load Dropinbase libraries that facilitate charts and dynamic loading of data:</div>\n<pre>~$delim~$// Load iframe Js tools, and interface with Dropinbase~$delim~<br>&lt;script type="text/javascript" src="/files/dropins/setNgxMaterial/dibAdmin/js/template/TemplateActions.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;&nbsp;\n<br>~$delim~$// Load tools required to do Ajax calls and messages~$delim~<br>&lt;script type="text/javascript" src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/js/dibTools.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n<br>~$delim~$// Load chart tools~$delim~<br>&lt;script type="text/javascript" src="/files/dropins/dibAdmin/js/dibChartTools.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;\n</pre>\n<p>If you are using the printing feature:</p>\n<pre>~$delim~$// Ability to print~$delim~<br>&lt;script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/html2canvas/1.4.1/html2canvas.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\n<p>The template file must contain a JavaScript object with Chart definitions. The structure of the definition depends on the chart type.</p>\n<p>For eg. for a single Plotly chart that we name \'<strong>plotly_a</strong>\':&nbsp;</p>\n<pre>var dibCharts = {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; // Bar with line<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>plotly_a </strong>: {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>type : \'plotly\',<br></strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>data </strong>: [<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; type: \'bar\',<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; x: <strong>\'dibexPlotlyTest.names\'</strong>,<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; y: <strong>\'dibexPlotlyTest.sumExp\'</strong>,<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; name: \'Total Yrs of Experience\'<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }, {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; type: \'line\',<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; x: <strong>\'dibexPlotlyTest.names\'</strong>,<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; y: <strong>\'dibexPlotlyTest.maxRating\'</strong>,<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; name: \'Max Skill Rating\'<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; },<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ],<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>layout </strong>: {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; title: \'Staff Experience and Skill Rating\',<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; yaxis: {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; title: \'Years\'<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; },<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>config</strong>: {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; responsive: true<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }</pre>\n<div>\n<div>Note, the Plotly library requires the following function call to create a chart:</div>\n<pre>Plotly.newPlot(<span class="hljs-string">\'myDiv\'</span>, <span class="hljs-keyword">data</span>, layout, config);</pre>\n<div>The above&nbsp;<strong>plotly_a</strong> object contains the&nbsp;<strong>data</strong>, <strong>layout </strong>and <strong>config </strong>child-objects required by this Ploty function. All that was added was <strong>\'type\'</strong> to inform Dropinbase&nbsp; to use the Plotly function to process this object.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Also note that merge strings like&nbsp;<strong>\'dibexPlotlyTest.names\'</strong> appear in the object where normally there are arrays of data. The <strong>fetchAndRefresh </strong>JavaScript function scans the object (or specified parts of it) for strings that match <strong>[queryName].[fieldName] </strong>and replaces them with the actual data they refer to.</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>More charts can be added, eg <strong>plotly_b </strong>and <strong>google_a </strong>etc, each with their own type of definition (see chart configurations in ~nav(dibexOverview)~ and other examples).</div>\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\n<div>Add HTML elements with matching id\'s as used in the object, where the charts must appear:</div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<pre>&lt;div id="<strong>plotly_a</strong>" style="flex: auto;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div>The HTML document\'s&nbsp;<strong>body </strong>tag calls the <strong>loadData()</strong> function. This function calls the <strong>fetchAndRefresh </strong>function which replaces the above mentioned merge strings with data, and then calls another function (<strong>refreshCharts</strong>) to plot/refresh each of the charts.</div>\n</div>\n<h3>Valid Params</h3>\n<p>This is a JSON object specifying any parameter values passed to the Eleutheria template, the same as for any iframe container.</p>\n<p>The <strong>fetchAndRefresh </strong>function (see above), assumes that <strong>Valid Params</strong> contains <strong>"dibSqlPerms"</strong> which lists the named queries in Dropinbase (<em>pef_sql</em>) that must be executed to obtain the chart data. As mentioned, <strong>fetchAndRefresh </strong>makes the columns of data returned by the queries available as merge-fields in a given object.</p>\n<p><strong>Data-format:</strong></p>\n<p>Certain nodes require data in different formats. Where <strong>x</strong> and <strong>y</strong> in Plotly require simple arrays like <strong>[<span class="hljs-number">19</span>, <span class="hljs-number">26</span>, <span class="hljs-number">55</span>]</strong>, Google org and gantt charts require tables of data:</p>\n<pre>[<br>  &nbsp; [\'Research\', \'Find sources\',<br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; new Date(2015, 0, 1), new Date(2015, 0, 5), null, &nbsp;100, &nbsp;null],<br>  &nbsp; [\'Write\', \'Write paper\',<br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; null, new Date(2015, 0, 9), daysToMilliseconds(3), 25, \'Research,Outline\'],<br>  &nbsp; [\'Cite\', \'Create bibliography\',<br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; null, new Date(2015, 0, 7), daysToMilliseconds(1), 20, \'Research\'],<br>  &nbsp; [\'Complete\', \'Hand in paper\',<br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; null, new Date(2015, 0, 10), daysToMilliseconds(1), 0, \'Cite,Write\'],<br>  &nbsp; [\'Outline\', \'Outline paper\',<br>  &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; null, new Date(2015, 0, 6), daysToMilliseconds(1), 100, \'Research\']<br>]</pre>\n<p>Also, Open Streetmaps require markers of [Longitude, Lattiude] pairs.</p>\n<p>Use the pipe character (~$delimDb~) in Valid Params to indicate which data-sources will be used as tables or markers, instead of individual columns:</p>\n<pre>"dibSqlPerms" : "dibexPlotlyTest, dibexGantsTest<strong>~$delimDb~table</strong>, dibexOrgChartTest<strong>~$delimDb~table</strong>, dibexOpenStreetMapsMarkers<strong>~$delimDb~markers</strong>"</pre>\n<h3>Limiting data with parameters</h3>\n<p>To pass parameter (eg Client Data) values to the SQL, they need to be part of the&nbsp;<strong>serverParams.sqlParams </strong>object in the template file. As with other iframe containers, use <strong>Valid Params </strong>and Eleutheria to build this object.</p>\n<p>For eg. if <strong>Valid Params</strong> contains:</p>\n<pre>{"selectedClientId" : "alias_self_clientId"}</pre>\n<p>Then the template file would contain:</p>\n<pre>var serverParams = {<br>  &nbsp; \'containerName\' : \'^dib_containerName^\',<br>  &nbsp; \'itemEventId\' : 1,<br>  &nbsp; \'sqlParams\': {\'clientId\' : ^selectedClientId^}<br>};\n</pre>\n<p>And the named query\'s SQL could implement this parameter as follows:</p>\n<pre>SELECT name, min(age) as minAge<br>FROM client_contact<br>WHERE client_id = :clientId</pre>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce102-dib'),
    (103, 280, 307, 30, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Dropinbase can store any data in the PHP user session, which is made available with each request that the server receives.<br>By assigning for eg. a <strong>staff_id </strong>or <strong>client_id </strong>to a user, it enables staff and/or clients to log in as users.&nbsp;<br>This data can be used as parameters in permissions and other SQL queries so that staff/clients will only have access to their information.</p>\n<p>Furthermore, by adding a value to Environment.php, ~nav(dibexNgIf, conditional directives)~ can be used to hide certain buttons, fields or cards etc. that must be available only if a user is on their own record. Eg:</p>\n<p><code>*ngIf="getValue(\'staff_id\') === getEnv(\'staff_id\')"</code></p>\n<p>or for buttons etc in grids:</p>\n<p><code>[dibDisabled]="row.staff_id === getEnv(\'staff_id\')"</code></p>\n<p>Remember that while these buttons or fields may be invisible, hackers can still send any data to the server. Permission checks must also be done server-side.</p>\n<p>Note, for demo purposes, a <strong>staff_id</strong> field has been added to the user\'s PHP session in the <strong>/configs/DibUserParams.php </strong>file. See the notes in this file for more info. All users are now linked to a <strong>staff_id </strong>value of 1. Normally a field like <strong>staff_id</strong> would be added to the <strong>pef_login</strong> table and included in the SELECT statement in <strong>DibUserParams.php</strong> so that each user has different value.</p>\n<p>The form below has been restricted using Permission Criteria to only read records where <strong>test_staff.id = :dibUser_staff_id</strong>.<br>Additionally, to restrict users to selecting only valid Main Projects, the update criteria is:<br><strong>test_staff.id = :dibUser_staff_id AND test_staff.main_project_id IN (SELECT project_id FROM test_staff_project WHERE staff_id = :dibUser_staff_id)</strong></p>\n<p>Effectively they can only <strong>view </strong>and<strong> update </strong>their own record, and only select a Main Project from the pool they are linked to.<br>(The grid is restricted using much the same permissions on the <strong>test_staff_project </strong>table.)</p>\n<p>Although <strong>delete </strong>is not allowed, it could be. It makes little sense to allow <strong>create</strong> on the form if they can only view their own record.&nbsp; <strong>Create </strong>could be allowed in the grid, but then configure a default value for the <strong>staff_id </strong>field and ensure the <strong>Criteria New</strong> permission field restricts hackers for&nbsp;<strong>create </strong>to <strong>`staff_id` = :dibUser_staff_id.</strong> The implication is that another user with more rights needs to add/remove projects for this user.</p>\n<p>Furthermore, the <strong>Main Project</strong> dropdown in the form, and the <strong>Project </strong>dropdown in the grid has been linked to a SQL query with the following WHERE clause, which restricts users to view only their projects:<br><strong>tsp.staff_id = :dibUser_staff_id</strong></p>\n<p>The <strong>View My Report</strong> button has the following Conditional Directive on it. When users with more rights scroll through staff records, this button will only appear on their own record:</p>\n<p><strong>*ngIf="getEnv(\'staff_id\') == getValue(\'id\')"</strong></p>\n<p><em>(See the ~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices)~ and ~nav(dibexNgIf)~ for more info about Conditional Directives. In the Console type <strong>DIB </strong>and press <strong>[Enter]</strong> too see current Environment values).</em></p>\n<p>The PHP controller function linked to this button has the following to block hackers:</p>\n<pre>\n<p>If(empty($staffId) || DIB::$USER[\'staff_id\'] != $staffId)<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;return $this-&gt;invalidResult(\'Invalid request\');</p>\n</pre>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>~incldocs(incl_sqlQueryParams)~</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce103-dib'),
    (104, 288, 309, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Dropdowns can be filtered with Client Data.<br>This is especiallly useful if you have dependent dropdowns - where a dropdown\'s value filters a successive dropdown.<br>The criteria specified in the dropdown\'s Filter is added to the underlying SQL WHERE-clause, using the AND operator.</p>\n<p>A dropdown\'s list can also be limited with query parameters in the dropdown\'s SQL query, but this may impede the reusability of the SQL query.</p>\n<p>Note, the&nbsp;<strong>select</strong> component is easier to use than autocompletes, but it has no search ability.</p>\n<p><strong>Security</strong></p>\n<p>Although filters limit data, it is not a security feature. Hackers can remove the activeFilter parameter from requests rendering them useless. To securely limit data in a dropdown\'s list, base it on a SQL query and add criteria in the SQL query that references User Parameters, eg <code>team.member_id = :dibUser_member_id</code>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Add filter criteria to the dropdown item that references the dropdown\'s underlying SQL, eg</p>\n<p><strong>cc.client_id = :alias_self_clientId</strong></p>\n<p>The above criteria assumes the alias (cc) is used in the dropdown\'s underlying SQL where-clause.</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce104-dib'),
    (105, 294, 310, 10, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Client-side validation guides the user to input valid values before they click the Save button and the data is sent to the server.</p>\n<p>It is also useful to guide input on unbound fields or Plain containers.</p>\n<p><span style="color: rgb(224, 62, 45);">NOTE: The necessary server-side validation also needs to be in place since hackers can alter any value sent to the server.</span></p>', '<p>See Pg2 in the Designer for the various client-side validation fields.</p>\n<p>Specify additional attributes for input fields in <strong>Attributes2 </strong>on Pg3.</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce105-dib'),
    (106, 294, 311, 10, 'none', 'General', 'About Hacking', NULL, '<p>Server-side validation (and permission-checking) is the only way to gaurantee that an application stores allowed values in the database.</p>\n<p>The generated server-side code performs the following actions on <strong>create </strong>and <strong>update </strong>requests for values that are not empty string(\'\') or NULL.</p>\n<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>In some cases values are coerced into a valid format to provide for a range of input values (noted below).</li>\n<li>If an item is required but the value is an empty string(\'\') or NULL then a validation message is displayed.</li>\n<li><strong>TestLength </strong>below refers to Test Length field in Validation Type table (<em>pef_validation_type.test_length</em>).</li>\n<li><strong>TestSize&nbsp;</strong>below refers to Test Size field in Validation Type table (<em>pef_validation_type.test_size</em>).</li>\n<li><strong>MSG </strong>below means a validation message is displayed to the user.</li>\n<li><strong>INPUT </strong>refers to the value the user supplies.</li>\n<li><strong>ALLOW-NEGATIVE</strong> refers to whether the item\'s underlying field record\'s Allow Negative (<em>allow_negative</em>) is set (=1).</li>\n<li><strong>FIELD_LENGTH </strong>refers to the size/length of the underlying text field in the Field table (<em>pef_field.field_length</em>).</li>\n<li><strong>MAX_SIZE </strong>refers to the&nbsp;<em>max_size_signed </em>field in the&nbsp;underlying field record\'s data type definition in the Data Types (pef_data_type) table.</li>\n<li><strong>MAX_SIZE </strong>refers to the&nbsp;<em>max_size_signed </em>field in the&nbsp;underlying field record\'s data type definition in the Data Types (pef_data_type) table.</li>\n<li><strong>MAX_SIZE_UN&nbsp;</strong>refers to the&nbsp;<em>max_size_unsigned </em>field in the underlying field record\'s data type definition in the Data Types (pef_data_type) table.</li>\n</ul>\n<table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 883.2px;" border="1"><colgroup><col style="width: 16.1169%;"><col style="width: 10.3969%;"><col style="width: 73.4674%;"></colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px; background-color: rgb(194, 224, 244);">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Field</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Value</strong></td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;"><strong>Validation</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Min Length</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">N (integer)</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">If N&gt;0 and INPUT has &lt; N characters then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Max Length</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">N (integer)</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">If N&gt;0 and TestLength=1 and INPUT has &gt; N characters then MSG.<br>Note, Server Validation Type must be supplied for this rule to have effect.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">Min Value</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">N (float)</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">If N &gt;0 and TestSize=1 and and INPUT &lt; N then MSG.<br>Note, Server Validation Type must be supplied for this rule to have effect.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Max Value</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">N (float)</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">If N &gt;0 and TestSize=1 and and INPUT &gt; N then MSG.<br>Note, Server Validation Type must be supplied for this rule to have effect.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Server Validation Type</td>\n<td>(any numeric type)</td>\n<td>If TestLength=1 and INPUT has &gt; FIELD_LENGTH characters then MSG.<br>***Note: if Max Length is supplied, it takes precedence over this rule.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 67.2px;">\n<td style="height: 67.2px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 67.2px;">(any numeric type)</td>\n<td style="height: 67.2px;">If TestSize=1 and INPUT &lt; 0 then MSG.<br>Note, if ALLOW-NEGATIVE then the last part becomes: INPUT&lt; -MAX_SIZE (instead of 0).<br>***Note: if Min Value is supplied, it takes precedence over this rule.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">(any numeric type)</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">If TestSize=1 and INPUT &gt; MAX_SIZE then MSG.<br>Note, if not ALLOW-NEGATIVE then the last part becomes: INPUT &gt; MAX_SIZE_UN.<br>***Note: if Max Value is supplied, it takes precedence over this rule.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">boolean</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;"><strong>1 / \'1\' / \'True\' / True</strong> is converted to 1, and any other value to 0.<br>Thereafter, if the value is required and 0 then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>date</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">If INPUT cannot be converted to a date then MSG.<br>Value is then converted to standard date format before stored: yyyy-mm-dd<br>Note, date conversion is very forgiving, using PHP\'s strtotime function.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>datetime</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>&nbsp;If INPUT cannot be converted to a date-time then MSG.</div>\n</div>\nValue is then converted to standard date-time format before stored: yyyy-mm-dd hh:nn:ss<br>Note, date-time conversion is very forgiving, using PHP\'s strtotime function.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>time</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">If INPUT cannot be converted to a time then MSG.<br>Value is then converted to standard time format before stored: hh:nn:ss<br>Note, time conversion is very forgiving, using PHP\'s strtotime function.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 67.2px;">\n<td style="height: 67.2px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 67.2px;">\n<div>\n<div>decimal</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 67.2px;">If INPUT is not numeric then MSG.<br>INPUT is then converted to a double-precision float.<br>If the conversion fails for whatever reason then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>integer</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">INPUT is converted to a positive integer. <br>If not integer then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>email</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">If INPUT is not a valid email then MSG.<br>Note, uses PHP filter_var() function with FILTER_VALIDATE_EMAIL.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 44.8px;">\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">\n<div>\n<div>url</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 44.8px;">If INPUT is not a valid URL then MSG.<br>Note, uses Dropinbase DValidate::_url() function.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>enum/set</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">If INPUT is not one of the values supplied in the <strong>Value List </strong>(<em>value_list</em>) field then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>latitude</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">If INPUT is not a float or &gt;90 or &lt;-90 then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>longitude</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">If INPUT is not a float or &gt;90 or &lt;-90 then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>html</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">INPUT is purified using HTMLPurifier. <br>This is not strictly validation, but purification/stripping of potentially malicious code.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>alpha</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">If INPUT does is not only alphabetical then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>\n<div>alphanum_space</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">If INPUT is not alpha-numeric only (spaces allowed too) then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr style="height: 22.4px;">\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">Server Validation Type</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">(any one linked to a regex)</td>\n<td style="height: 22.4px;">If INPUT does not satisfy the regular expression in the <strong>regex</strong>-field of the Validation Type table then MSG.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '<p>Hacking commonly occurs when a hacker submits a request to the server containing values that the server does not check or escape before using it or displaying it to another user.</p>\n<p>Any value can be malicious, depending on the context in which the value is used or where it is returned to the browser.</p>\n<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\';DELETE FROM pef_login\' is malicious if this value is injected "as is" in a SQL statement.</li>\n<li>\'href="http://hackers.com/maliciouscode"\' is malicious if injected in the right place in the user-interface.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Dropinbase and Angular by default does the appropriate checking and escaping of all data in generated code and the client and server-side frameworks. (Developers of custom server- or client-side code should do the same).</p>\n<p>The above preventions however do not stop hackers from accessing information or files through Dropinbase\'s API. This is where the permission system must be configured to allow specific user groups access to specific info.</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce106-dib'),
    (107, 276, 318, 235, 'none', 'General', NULL, NULL, '<p>Creates or sets the value of a global custom JavaScript variable. <br><strong>Note: </strong>refreshing the browser clears these JavaScript values.</p>\n<h4>Parameters:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>variableName=value</strong> (repeated): Pairs of variable names and their corresponding values.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The value is accessible in <code>clientData</code> submitted to the server, and with <code>resolve(\'custom_global_xxx\')</code> or <code>@{custom_global_xxx}</code>.</li>\n<li>More info: See ~nav(dibexActionClearCustom)~, and the last tab on ~nav(dibexDropinbaseServices)~</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Example:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>shared.action.set-custom-global?myVar=123&amp;myVar2=hello world</li>\n</ul>', NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce107-dib'),
    (108, 279, 319, 95, 'none', 'General', 'Configuration', NULL, '<p>Data buttons facilitate various record actions on grids and forms.</p>\n<p>See the Configuration-tab for info about how to specify a custom audit trail grid.</p>', '<h2>Specify custom Audit Trail grid(s)</h2>\n<p>Note, if nothing is specified, the global option in&nbsp;<strong>/configs/Environment.php</strong> is set to \'dibAuditTrailGrid\' which opens as a maximized window.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Specify a global custom audit trail grid in <strong>/configs/Environment.php</strong> in the \'audit_trail_container\' key. Specify the port alias (if not \'main\') in \'audit_trail_port\'.<br>By default the code reads these values from the Settings table (<em>pef_setting</em>), where <em>name</em>=<strong>auditTrailContainerName </strong>and <em>name</em>=<strong>auditTrailPortAlias </strong>respectively.</li>\n<li>Specify a custom audit trail grid for each Module Dropin in the Settings table, using <em>name</em>=<strong>auditTrailContainerDropin, </strong><em>value</em>=<strong>CONTAINERNAME</strong>. and <em>dropin </em>is the module dropin.</li>\n<li>Specify a custom audit trail grid for a specific btnAuditTrail-button using the <strong>Open Container in Port</strong> field.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Create Your Own Audit Trail Grid</h3>\n<p>The default audit trail grid (dibAuditTrailGrid) displays columns like primary and foreign key values that may not be ideal for your users.<br>Do not customize this container as it used by Dropinbase admin containers.</p>\n<p>Alternatively, you can freely customize the auditTrailGrid container that is a copy of the dibAuditTrailGrid container, <br>or you can create your own grid, based on a SQL query that links the <em>pef_audit_trail </em>table to your own tables.</p>\n<p>Note, the audit records for specific containers or tables can be stored in their own copies of the pef_audit_trail table. <br>Use the <em>pef_table.pef_audit_trail_table_id</em> and <em>pef_container.pef_audit_trail_table_id</em> fields to identify the tables to use.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, 'dce108-dib'),
