    (4363, 'comment15', NULL, 173, 25, 4362, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Permissions in Dropinbase are based on the rights given to Permissions Groups.\n<br>A Permission Group can be seen as a Role, eg Staff, Supervisors, Managers, Sales Director, etc.\n<br>Each Permission Group / Role is then given certain permissions on containers, items, events and even certain records within a container using criteria.\n<br>In the example above:\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Managers</strong> can create, read, update and delete all records in the <strong>clientGrid</strong> container.</li>\n<li><strong>Data Clerks</strong> can read all records, but only update those where the <em>client_status</em> field of the underlying table has a value of \'active\'.</li>\n<li><strong>Clients</strong> can read can read and update only their own record.\n   <br>Values of specific database fields can be stored in a user\'s session, and made available as parameters in criteria.\n   <br>In this case it could be a <em>client_id</em> field in pef_login.</li>\n<li><strong>Data Clerks</strong> and <strong>Clients</strong> can not create or delete records.</li>\n</ul>\n\nUsers can be assigned to any combination of these Permission Groups, and their rights are determined by the combined rights of the groups they are linked to. \n<br>Each unique combination is called a Permgroup.\n<br>For eg. a user/login record that is linked to Permission Groups 3 and 5 has Permgroup x3x5x.\n<br>\n<br>Dropinbase generates and stores user-interface and server-side code specifically according to the rights of each Permgroup.\n<br>The code is generated on-the-fly when requested, and is stored in the relevant /dibCode subfolder if it has not been generated and stored already.\n<br>The file names are suffixed with the relevant permgroup.\n<br>Before deploying to a production server, all code can be generated. On the production server the  folder permissions can be set to read-only, except for the /runtime folder which stores temporary info.\n<br>\n<br>Dropinbase will not generate menu items, tabs, buttons, and subcontainers etc. linked to containers that Permgroups do not have rights to access. \n<br>This feature is highly convenient, as it ensures each user will automatically only see the elements they have the rights to access.', NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'mysql', NULL, NULL, 'fixed', 'standard', 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'CRUD', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, 'other', NULL, NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'nowrap', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 25, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, 'field', 0, 'david', '2024-01-06 15:04:11', ' ', 'i4363-dib'),
